<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIEBERMAN-CONN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIEBERMAN CAN RUN FOR SENATE WHILE RUNNING WITH GORE 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID M. HERSZENHORN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   STAMFORD, Conn. _ Joseph I. Lieberman's life will never be quite
the same now that Al Gore has tapped him to be his running mate,
but one thing seems likely to remain unchanged: Lieberman can
continue to run for re-election to the Senate, a race he is an
overwhelming favorite to win, while also running in the tougher
race for vice president.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing in Connecticut law prevents Lieberman from running for
both offices simultaneously. And, as news of his selection by Gore
swept across the country Monday, state Democratic Party officials
said that they expected Lieberman to be on the ballot for both
offices this November.
</P>
<P>
   The state Democratic Party chairman, Edward L. Marcus, said that
Lieberman ``was inclined'' to remain in the Senate race. Other
state party officials and aides to Lieberman said they also
believed he would stay on the ballot for the Senate, following
precedent set by two senators and vice-presidential nominees from
Texas, Lloyd Bentsen in 1988 and Lyndon B. Johnson in 1960.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman is immensely popular in Connecticut and has long been
viewed as a heavy favorite to win a third term in the Senate by
trouncing a little-known opponent, Mayor Philip A. Giordano of
Waterbury. But while Republicans and Democrats said Monday that
they still expected Lieberman to be re-elected, his decision to
seek two offices at once carries several political risks that could
alter the state and national political landscapes.
</P>
<P>
   The obvious benefit to Lieberman is that he can hedge his bet.
Should the Democrats fail to defeat George W. Bush, he could keep
his job in the Capitol. Predictably, Republicans in Connecticut and
elsewhere pounced quickly Monday, calling this evidence that
Lieberman lacks full confidence that the Democratic ticket will
prevail in November.
</P>
<P>
   And even Lieberman's best-case outcome, that the Democrats win
the White House and he also wins re-election to the Senate, has a
potential drawback for his party. Although he can run for both
offices, he cannot serve in both. If Lieberman is inaugurated as
vice president in January, Connecticut's Republican governor, John
G. Rowland, will pick someone to serve in the Senate until the next
statewide election, in November 2002.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear Monday night whether Gore or Democratic leaders
in Washington would pressure Lieberman to give up his Senate
re-election campaign. Under state election rules, Lieberman has
until Oct. 27 to quit the race and be replaced by a Democratic
nominee. But state party leaders said it was already too late to
hold a primary, and that if Lieberman dropped out, a replacement
would have to be chosen at a special convention.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland, during a news conference Monday afternoon at the state
Capitol, said that he had not yet considered whom he would appoint.
And although he praised Lieberman, he described the prospect of
appointing someone as far-fetched because, he said, he expects Bush
to win the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Still, if the seat comes open, it is virtually certain that
Rowland would appoint a fellow Republican, either one of the
state's two Republican members of Congress, Nancy Johnson of New
Britain or Christopher Shays of Stamford, or his lieutenant
governor, M. Jodi Rell. Rowland could select himself, but at
Monday's news conference he pledged not to do so.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the one definite I can give you,'' he said. ``I have no
interest in going to Washington, and I also think it would be
self-serving for any governor to appoint himself or herself to the
U.S. Senate. I want to finish this job.''
</P>
<P>
   Marcus, the state Democratic chairman, said his party was
researching whether the state Legislature had the authority to
enact a bill calling for a special election for the U.S. Senate
sooner than the November 2002 election.
</P>
<P>
   He said he believed Rowland would support such a bill and sign
it.
</P>
<P>
   One Republican whom officials in both parties said Rowland was
unlikely to choose as the interim senator was Giordano, the man who
is actually running against Lieberman this year. Giordano, whose
long-shot candidacy was initially opposed by the governor and state
Republican leaders, moved quickly Monday to take advantage of the
national spotlight on Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can't be a man of two countries, if you will,'' Tim
Longino, Giordano's campaign manager, said of Lieberman. ``That is
the issue of the campaign now. We don't believe he represented us
enough as U.S. senator, never mind as a vice president, and don't
think he should run for both seats at the same time.''
</P>
<P>
   He said Giordano was enjoying the newfound interest in his
candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are calling now to find out who Phil Giordano is,''
Longino said, adding that Giordano would hold a news conference in
Hartford on Tuesday to attack Lieberman's voting record in the
Senate. ``He has been on `CNN Live' today,'' Longino said. ``He'll
be on all of the nationwide networks this week. Most of the
Connecticut networks have picked him up already. So our job just
got a lot easier.''
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut's senior senator, Christopher J. Dodd, a Democrat,
said Monday that he had urged Lieberman to remain on the ballot for
the Senate and that he was confident that the Democrats would
eventually reclaim the seat in a special election. He also said it
would be difficult to find a replacement candidate for November.
``It's 12 weeks away,'' Dodd said. ``Joe is our strongest candidate
for re-election to the Senate.'' He added, ``I don't think it's
fair to deprive him of that.''
</P>
<P>
   As potential Democratic candidates to succeed Lieberman, Dodd
named two members of Congress, John B. Larson and Rosa DeLauro, and
the state attorney general, Richard Blumenthal.
</P>
<P>
   Blumenthal said that he was not sure whether Lieberman should
run for both offices, but he was confident that the law allowed it.
State law, he said, does not address the issue of dual candidacies
for federal office and, therefore, by not banning it, effectively
permits it.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Ward, a Republican state representative, said he believed
that Gore was trying to distance himself from President Clinton, to
no avail. ``There is no question that Joe Lieberman is an honorable
and trustworthy individual,'' he said. ``I think Joe Lieberman's
problem is that his running mate is Al Gore.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
