<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-TOURISM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOURIST RISE MAKES BIG APPLE NO. 2 U.S. SITE  
</HEADLINE>
  By ERIC LIPTON    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ New York City welcomed an estimated 36.7 million
visitors last year, an 11 percent rise from the previous year,
generating billions of dollars in sales for city businesses and
supporting several hundred thousand jobs, but also intensifying
congestion on city streets and sidewalks, officials said yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   The figures, compiled from federal surveys and a tourism
research concern, earned New York City a second-place ranking
nationwide as a destination for U.S. travelers, pushing Las Vegas
down to the No. 3 spot. Orlando, Fla., maintained its top ranking.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani pointed to the numbers on Monday as
further proof of the city's improved reputation within the United
States and around the globe as a safe, family-friendly place to
visit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The numbers are staggering,'' Giuliani said, adding that the
total number of visitors should hit 38.4 million this year, up from
28.5 million in 1995. ``This means a tremendous number of jobs and
tremendous benefits to citizens of the whole city.''
</P>
<P>
   The tourists, business travelers and others visiting the city
spent an estimated $15.6 billion last year at hotels, restaurants,
stores, cultural institutions and countless other locations,
according to the survey, released by NYC &AMP; Company, the city's
convention and visitors bureau.
</P>
<P>
   That spending generated an estimated $2.9 billion in local,
state and federal tax revenues, and supported about 275,000 jobs.
But even Giuliani acknowledged on Monday that the flood of tourists
had its costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bad side is we are very crowded,'' Giuliani said, speaking
at a Times Square news conference, while crowds of tourists pressed
up against a window to get a glimpse of the mayor. ``But the last
time I was in Los Angeles you could not move, on all of those, what
do they call them, `freeways,' `stopways,' . . . `parking lots.' So
I think we are in better shape than some other cities, even with
the tremendous amount of tourism we have.''
</P>
<P>
   Visitors from outside the United States made up about 20 percent
of the total last year, with tourists from Britain, Canada,
Germany, Japan and France topping the list of international
visitors. Overall international visits to the city rose to about
6.6 million last year, up 9 percent, according to data attributed
by NYC &AMP; Co. to the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   But the strongest growth has been from within the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, domestic travel increased by an estimated 3.2
percent last year, according to D.K. Shifflet &AMP; Associates of Falls
Church, Va., a company that collects travel information from about
100,000 households each year. In New York City, visits increased by
11.6 percent, a growth rate faster than at all but 3 of the
nation's top 10 tourist destinations, a spokesman for D.K. Shifflet
said.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Sweeney of Boston, who brought his wife and three children
to New York this week, said the trip was fascinating, but he is not
planning to move to the city. ``It is a great place to visit,'' he
said in Times Square. ``But I would not want to live here. The
stress level is a couple of notches higher than I can bear.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
