<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DB HOUSTON HAS MORE PROBLEMS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILLY WITZ  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Lovell Houston, who UCLA coaches had hoped would
start at free safety, will undergo reconstructive surgery on his
right shoulder and be lost for the season, the school announced
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Houston had offseason surgery on both shoulders to tighten up
the joints, but the right shoulder did not respond and a decision
was reached Friday to have him undergo more-extensive surgery, UCLA
sports information director Marc Dellins said. No date has been set
for the surgery.
</P>
<P>
   The loss of Houston leaves the position wide open. Jason Zdenek,
a fifth-year senior whose only action last season came against
Boise State, will be atop the depth chart Saturday when camp opens.
</P>
<P>
   It marks the latest in a series of physical setbacks for
Houston, a 6-foot-1, 187-pound sophomore who arrived from Denver as
one of the stalwarts of the Bruins 1998 recruiting class that was
ranked No. 1 in the country by some analysts.
</P>
<P>
   While others in that class _ running back DeShaun Foster,
defensive tackle Ken Kocher and linebacker Robert Thomas _ have
shined, Houston has rarely been healthy enough to live up to his
billing as one of the top defensive back prospects in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Houston, expected to contend for a starting cornerback position
two years ago, missed training camp with a thigh injury and was
redshirted. After offseason shoulder surgery to repair high school
injuries, Houston reinjured his left thigh in training camp last
year.
</P>
<P>
   The first time Houston touched the ball for the Bruins, he
returned a kickoff 95 yards for a touchdown against Stanford. He
moved from cornerback to strong safety and started three
consecutive games, but a concussion against Washington ended his
season. The Bruins planned on moving him to free safety this
season.
</P>
<P>
   __ Hoops update: The basketball team could get its first verbal
commitment from the 2001 recruiting class this week in Michael Fey,
a 6-foot-11, 235-pound center from Olympia (Wash.) Capital High.
</P>
<P>
   Fey, who said he was offered scholarships by Syracuse,
Connecticut and Washington, said he decided two weeks ago he didn't
want to leave the West Coast. He must earn a qualifying ACT score;
Fey said he scored 16 on the test last spring, one point below
qualifying.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now UCLA is on top of my list,'' Fey said Monday. ``When
I went down there for my unofficial visit (in June), I fell in love
with it. The only thing left to do is commit.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
