<HEADER>
A5462 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-COMPLAINTS-PUC-SFCHRO     08-08 1045
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPLAINTS-PUC-SFCHRON(W/LONGDISTANCE) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WRITTEN COMPLAINTS HAVE BEST CHANCES WITH PUC
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By TODD WALLACK 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  Filing a complaint about the phone company is a little like
playing craps in Reno:
<P>
   You're likely to do much better if you understand the odds.
</P>
<P>
   A Chronicle analysis of 125,000 complaints filed with the
California Public Utilities Commission found that consumers are 10
times more likely win a favorable decision if they send a letter to
the PUC, instead of trying to get a problem solved with a phone
call.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easier to analyze (a complaint) when you have it in
writing,'' said Linda Woods, manager of the PUC's consumer affairs
office. A letter, for instance, allows consumers to send along
documentation, such as copies of phone bills or ads promising a low
price.
</P>
<P>
   Some of that logic might seem obvious, of course. But the
differences in success rates even surprised PUC staff members.
</P>
<P>
   Woods, for instance, recommended that customers swing by the
PUC's offices in San Francisco to state their case. But The
Chronicle found that the odds are actually tilted in the utilities'
favor when consumers complain in person.
</P>
<P>
   You're likely to do somewhat better if you send an e-mail or
complain to a commissioner, who will then refer the complaint to
the PUC's consumer affairs office.
</P>
<P>
   But nothing matches a fax or letter. Consumers who mailed their
complaints to the PUC received a favorable decision 58 percent of
the time. Callers won just 5 percent of their cases. (Overall,
customers won 39 percent of the time.)
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, customers often receive help even without a clear
victory. Sometimes the PUC brokers a compromise. On other
occasions, the PUC refers a problem back to the utilities, which
can find ways to appease an angry customer.
</P>
<P>
   And overall, many consumers say the PUC worked wonders after
they complained.
</P>
<P>
   ``Within a month, the CPUC was able to resolve an issue that I
was unable to resolve in almost a year,'' one consumer wrote the
agency. Another gushed: ``I am glad there is such a thing as the
CPUC,'' the person wrote.
</P>
<P>
   But critics say the process often lets consumers down, not doing
enough to fix individual problems or warning consumers after
spotting a pattern.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, an internal PUC survey completed in January found
that 4 in 10 people who filed a written complaint said the PUC fell
short of their expectations. ``I was very disappointed,'' one
person wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Some consumers griped that the PUC sloughed off complaints with
only a cursory review. Other times, it took the PUC a month or more
to respond, according to the PUC survey, which The Chronicle
obtained under public records laws.
</P>
<P>
   Critics say the PUC probably would have found even more
frustrated consumers had it also contacted people who filed
complaints by telephone, because these complaints were far less
likely to receive a positive verdict.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd like to see a system where everyone gets attention,''
said Nettie Hoge, executive director of the Utility Reform Network,
a San Francisco consumer group.
</P>
<P>
   Hoge said she believes that the consumer affairs division is
understaffed and undertrained. The agency has about 40 people to
handle 500 calls, letters and other queries per day.
</P>
<P>
   But Woods, the PUC's consumer affairs manager, insists that some
consumers are bound to be unhappy _ especially if the PUC rules in
favor of the company.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Woods said consumers have recourse. If they don't
get satisfaction from a PUC staff member, they can appeal to a
supervisor ``who will give it a second look,'' Woods said.
</P>
<P>
   Or they can file a formal complaint with the commissioners. The
process is often slow and cumbersome, but it is the only way to ask
commissioners to penalize companies for misconduct.
</P>
<P>
   The PUC levied a $2,500 fine on Pacific Bell earlier this year,
after George Sawaya of Pollock Pines complained. He said that he
was overcharged and that key information was omitted from his
telephone bill. Sawaya, who is retired, said he filed a formal
complaint because it was the only way to make sure the company
would be sanctioned for the mistake.
</P>
<P>
   Still, critics say the agency rarely takes the initiative to
prosecute a company on its own after spotting a pattern of abuse.
</P>
<P>
   It took the agency years to finally file a lawsuit against
WorldCom. And although the PUC's enforcement arm initiated a formal
investigation last year of USP&AMP;C, a billing company that drew
hundreds of complaints, similar firms with just as many problems
have escaped scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are effectively letting the criminals do whatever they
want,'' said Charles Carbone, a San Francisco lawyer retained by
the Utility Consumers' Action Network, a San Diego watchdog group.
``One bad actor might get stung. But it sends a clear message ...
that 99 percent of the market can get away with it.''
</P>
<P>
   But William Schulte, who oversees the PUC's enforcement arm,
said the PUC does not have the staff to take on an entire industry
at once.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a matter of resources,'' he said. In addition, he said,
the PUC wanted to first test the waters with USP&AMP;C before
proceeding against other companies.
</P>
<P>
   Schulte said Monday he was being stripped of his position
because the PUC president wants to choose her own consumer services
chief.
</P>
<P>
   Watchdog groups also say they wish the PUC would do more with
the complaint data, such as creating a report card ranking the best
and worst companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could be a bully pulpit,'' said Utility Reform's director,
Hoge. The Federal Communications Commission already produces a
``score card'' for telecommunications firms nationwide, though a
state report might be more relevant for Californians, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The PUC has already corrected some problems. Two years ago,
roughly half the people who participated in the survey said they
had trouble getting through to the agency. But those complaints
declined after the PUC's consumer branch hired more people and
extended its hours in early 1998.
</P>
<P>
   PUC Commissioner Carl Wood, who has championed stronger consumer
rules to protect telephone customers, said the current complaint
process is under review. But he declined to give details.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-08-00 0019EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
