<DOCNO> NYT20000808.0006 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 00:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5463 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-LONG-DISTANCE-SFCHRON     08-08 1814
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LONG-DISTANCE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONG-DISTANCE CARRIERS ARE COMPANIES CALIFORNIA CONSUMERS LOVE
TO  HATE
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By TODD WALLACK 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MCI surprised Paul Harvey in San Francisco with a $2,000 phone
bill, after abruptly raising his rate to call England from 10 cents
per minute to $2.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T charged Howard Frohlich of Redwood City, Calif., $17 for
four short phone calls, totaling 8 minutes: 97 cents for the calls
and $16 in surcharges, taxes and other fees.
</P>
<P>
   And Cindy Taormino in San Jose haggled with Sprint for more than
a year, after she switched long-distance companies to AT&AMP;T, but
Sprint kept trying to charge her a $7 monthly fee.
</P>
<P>
   By the tens of thousands, angry telephone customers in
California are fuming that long-distance companies overcharged
them, switched their service without permission or kept them
waiting forever on hold when they called with a problem.
</P>
<P>
   Complaints against long-distance companies roughly doubled in
the state from 1997 to 1999, according to a Chronicle analysis of
more than 125,000 complaints filed with the California Public
Utilities Commission. The Chronicle obtained the records using
public records laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I wish I didn't have to have a telephone,'' said the
exasperated Taormino, a health care contract analyst. She said she
finally resolved her problem with Sprint after firing off a letter
to the PUC. But now she is upset about strange charges that have
popped up on her cellular phone bill.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, long-distance phone woes are not limited to the
Golden State. A national regulatory group found last month that
complaints in 28 states against AT&AMP;T and WorldCom nearly tripled in
two years as companies employed increasingly aggressive tactics to
recruit new subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say stiffer competition, coupled with looser regulation,
is pushing companies to promise ever more fantastic offers, and
then sock consumers with a litany of minimum fees and other hidden
charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``Customers are getting ripped off,'' said Regina Costa, a
telecommunications specialist with the Utility Reform Network, who
chides regulators for expecting the marketplace to eliminate any
problems. ``If nobody is watching, (long-distance companies) are
going to maximize profits.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past few months, however, state regulators around the
country have been cracking down on long-distance companies.
California Attorney General Bill Lockyer and the PUC last month
sued WorldCom, the second largest long-distance company, over a
laundry list of complaints, ranging from deceptive advertising to
shoddy customer service.
</P>
<P>
   Five other states also filed separate suits against WorldCom,
which merged with MCI in 1998, mainly for false advertising. And
several states attacked AT&AMP;T and Sprint for running similar ads.
Lockyer confirmed that California is gearing up to sue other
telecom firms.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, as in other states, the PUC is considering tougher
rules to protect consumers. Most of the current regulations were
designed to cover traditional local telephone monopolies, such as
Pacific Bell, not long-distance giants like WorldCom and AT&AMP;T. But
Commissioner Carl Wood has proposed a ``telecommunications bill of
rights'' that would apply to all telecom firms in California.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are playing catch-up,'' Wood said. ``There is an
unacceptably high level of complaints.''
</P>
<P>
   Although complaints are rising across the board, The Chronicle
found that a few companies were responsible for more than their
share of grief.
</P>
<P>
   WorldCom, which is better known to consumers as MCI, racked up
more than 3,500 complaints last year, several hundred more than
rival AT&AMP;T even though it has less than a quarter as many
customers. Several smaller firms, like NOS Communications, scored
even higher complaint rates.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, Pacific Bell is still the phone company many
Californians love to hate. The local company received 5,400
complaints last year, more than any other telecommunications
company in California. But complaints against Pac Bell tumbled 35
percent from 1997 to 1999, even as gripes against long-distance
giants soared. (Caveat: All the complaint figures against Pac Bell,
AT&AMP;T, WorldCom and Sprint in this story exclude their fast-growing
wireless businesses to better show the shift from local to
long-distance gripes. But the trend still holds even when those
figures are included.)
</P>
<P>
   Analysts cited several reasons for the turnabout:
</P>
<P>
   --Confusing promotions. Long-distance giants have rolled out a
plethora of complicated pricing plans, ranging from Sprint's
``Nickel Nights'' to AT&AMP;T's ``One Rate Seven Cents Plan.'' One Web
site,  &UR; www.abelltolls.com, &LR;  tracks 170 different long-distance
plans. And most of the plans are more complicated, said the site's
co-founder, Marc-David Seidel.
</P>
<P>
   --Minimum fees. Starting two years ago, AT&AMP;T, WorldCom (MCI) and
others slapped customers who rarely make long-distance calls with
minimum fees of at least $3 per month. The change affected 15
million low-volume AT&AMP;T callers alone, many of whom did not know
about the fee in advance. ``People really get ticked off when they
see a large charge on their bill they don't expect,'' said Linda
Sherry, a spokeswoman for Consumer Action in San Francisco. AT&AMP;T
dropped the minimum fee last month, but has raised other rates.
</P>
<P>
   --Slamming. Overly aggressive telemarketers are increasingly
switching customers' service without permission. Complaints have
soared. And in the past two months, federal regulators forced
WorldCom (MCI) and Qwest Communications to cough up a total of $5
million to settle slamming charges.
</P>
<P>
   --Hidden surcharges. Critics say companies are increasingly
disguising extra charges to look like mandatory taxes. California,
for instance, sued WorldCom (MCI) for levying a 7.2 percent
``federal'' universal service fee, even though the government does
not require companies to charge the fee or set the rate. ``It
appears to be a standard government tax or fee, ... but it's
different for every company,'' Seidel said. WorldCom has since
increased the fee to 8.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Seidel and other analysts agree many of the surcharges are
confusing. But some attorneys general say they are also illegal.
</P>
<P>
   WorldCom (MCI), for instance, pitches rates as low as 5 cents a
minute in television commercials featuring basketball star Michael
Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   Lockyer and others say the ads are misleading because customers
always pay more than 5 cents a minute. First, the rate applies only
to out-of-state calls on evenings and weekends. Then, WorldCom
tacks on a $5 monthly minimum, a $4.95 flat monthly fee, the 8.3
percent universal service charge and a $1.46 ``carrier line
charge,'' which also is not required.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint and AT&AMP;T's promotions have also come under fire. Sprint,
for instance, trumpets rates as low as 2 cents a minute. But Sprint
also tacks on more than $20 in monthly fees under the plan, so
customers always pay more than is advertised.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a lot more fine print consumers need to be aware
of,'' said Lesley Fair, a senior attorney with the Federal Trade
Commission.
</P>
<P>
   But while consumer watchdogs complain customers need a
magnifying glass to read all the pint-size catches, companies
sometimes do not tell customers about important details at all.
Under the Byzantine rules covering telecommunications firms,
companies are only legally required to spell out restrictions and
extra fees in thick government documents, called ``tariffs,'' filed
with the PUC or FCC.
</P>
<P>
   Commissioner Wood, for instance, has noticed cellular telephone
companies sometimes neglect to warn consumers about expensive
``termination fees,'' which kick in when customers cancel their
service early.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a real problem,'' Wood said. ``If it's in the tariff,
you're stuck with it.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, Wood said, tariffs may have made sense in the days
of Ma Bell, when regulators carefully scrutinized a single monopoly
phone company. But today, state regulators normally just
rubber-stamp tariffs unless someone files a formal protest.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, tariffs are generally available only in a handful of
government offices, like the PUC's office in San Francisco, putting
them out of reach of most consumers.
</P>
<P>
   To fix the problem, both federal and state regulators are trying
to dismantle much of the tariffing process. Under Wood's proposal,
for example, telecom companies would have to tell consumers about
all the key terms and fees.
</P>
<P>
   Wood also hopes to close another loophole: Cellular phone
companies are exempt from most state regulations.
</P>
<P>
   But complaints against wireless firms more than doubled from
1997 to 1999, in part because mobile phones are becoming nearly
ubiquitous. A trade group estimates that U.S. residents used 86
million cell phones last year, up from 55 million in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Complaints are rising even faster, though, especially involving
billing disputes. Gripes against Sprint PCS jumped 13-fold, and Pac
Bell's figures leaped nearly 500 percent. Only AT&AMP;T's held steady.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, none of the wireless carriers would say how many
subscribers it has in California, so it's unclear who receives the
most complaints per customer in the state.
</P>
<P>
   But The Chronicle found stark distinctions among long-distance
giants. Of the three largest carriers, WorldCom appeared to have
the worst record both in California and nationwide. Complaints
soared 132 percent from 1997 to 1999.
</P>
<P>
   WorldCom officials insist they are responding. One source said
the company fired 300 telemarketers suspected of slamming. And
through June 2000, complaints have fallen 20 percent in California.
``We are doing the right things,'' said WorldCom Vice President
Sally McMahon. ``We simply must continue.''
</P>
<P>
   Historically, AT&AMP;T has had the lowest number of complaints per
customer, although its luster is fading. Complaints against the New
York firm soared 69 percent over the past three years. Now, AT&AMP;T is
in the same ballpark as Sprint, whose complaints rose just 9
percent. But complaints are not surging against all telephone
companies.
</P>
<P>
   Pac Bell mostly fixed the problems it had installing new phone
lines in 1996 and 1997. The phone company was so understaffed in
1997 that it couldn't keep up with orders, inciting blistering news
articles and angering regulators.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Pac Bell's complaint rate is slightly lower than its
counterpart in Southern California, Verizon Communications, the
only other major local phone company in the state.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Pac Bell is now grappling with new installation
headaches _ keeping up with orders for high-speed Internet
connections, digital subscriber lines. The PUC has received
hundreds of complaints about DSL in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   But increasingly, Bay Area residents are pinning their
frustrations on long-distance and wireless companies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
