r s BC-BKN-DILBECK-COLUMN-LA     08-08 0862
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-DILBECK-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEST FINALLY EARNS BELOVED ANONYMITY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE DILBECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   He was forever in the spotlight, searching for shadows. There
might never have been a sports figure who accomplished more, and
seemed to enjoy it less, than Jerry West.
</P>
<P>
   One of the greatest players in NBA history. A successful and
completely miserable head coach. One of the greatest executives in
NBA history, if ultimately somehow still as miserable.
</P>
<P>
   So West finally went out Monday, a multiyear, on-and-off-again
production that only he could manage. Perhaps fittingly, he went
quietly. Without saying a word, save for the safe haven of a press
release.
</P>
<P>
   You would like to think he's not agonizing anymore. That he
won't have to be ducking into a tunnel at the Forum. Won't be
staying away from the Staples Center, tormented by those private
demons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would prefer to be anonymous,'' West once said. ``It's no
fun living your life in a fishbowl. Some people like it. Some
people promote it. I never liked it. . . . There is something about
my life, my personality, that I don't feel comfortable in the
limelight.''
</P>
<P>
   He kept trying to slip into the chorus line, only to be thrown
back into a starring role. He wanted to blend into some dark corner
of the theater, not be given billing above the title.
</P>
<P>
   But if never at ease with the adulation, West always craved the
competiton. He was probably happiest playing the games, happiest
winning.
</P>
<P>
   It was his own spectacular gifts matched with his unrelenting
drive to succeed that made West one of the finest guards in NBA
history.
</P>
<P>
   He had one of the smoothest jumpers ever seen. He was an
outstanding defensive player. During his 14-year playing career, he
averaged more than 30 points four different seasons. He once led
the league in assists.
</P>
<P>
   The complete player with a burning desire to win, he was dubbed
``Mr. Clutch'' long before anyone ever saw Michael Jordan hit a
game-winner. For his career, West averaged 27.0 points per game _
stepping it up to 29.1 in the playoffs, second in league history
only to Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   Yet for all his success, he could seem more tormented by the
team's failures. During his first 10 seasons, he led the Lakers to
the NBA Finals seven times. The Lakers lost each one _ four in a
painful seventh game.
</P>
<P>
   It was as if West had left those balloons hanging in the Forum
rafters in '70. Finally, with Wilt Chamberlian at center, West won
his lone title two years later, on what some consider the greatest
team in NBA history.
</P>
<P>
   Two years after retiring as a player, he returned as the Lakers
head coach. Maybe he was never so unhappy. A perfectionist as a
player, it pained him to receive less that full effort from his
team.
</P>
<P>
   His team failing to live up to his standards, the high-strung
West left after three seasons. The Lakers were a winning team each
season but never advanced beyond the second round of the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   The first year after he left as head coach, the Lakers drafted
Magic Johnson and won the first of five NBA titles in the '80s.
</P>
<P>
   He spent two years as a consultant before taking over the top
front-office spot. The first player he ever drafted was James
Worthy. With Worthy, Magic and Kareem Abdul-Jabbar, he had the core
of an elite team. Yet throughout his tenure, West was continually
complementing his big three with key additions _ a Bob McAdoo,
Mitch Kupchak, Maurice Lucas, Mychal Thompson, Orlando Woolridge or
Sam Perkins.
</P>
<P>
   As a talent evaluator he liked to say he ``trusted his
instincts,'' and few could claim to be his peer.
</P>
<P>
   Drafting low every year because of the team's continued success,
he found gems were others were left empty. He selected A.C. Green
with a 23rd pick, Vlade Divac 26th, Elden Campbell 27th, Nick Van
Exel 37th, Derek Fisher 24th.
</P>
<P>
   Not every selection proved a steal _ there was Earl Jones and
Ken Barlow taken with 23rd picks, and David Rivers with a 25th _
but more often, rival general managers were left lamenting when
West saw what they had not.
</P>
<P>
   His trades were normally winners, too, especially the early
ones. He essentially got Byron Scott for a fading Norm Nixon.
Traded change for Thompson. Second-round picks for Lucas. Later did
the same for Sedale Threatt.
</P>
<P>
   The Eddie Jones and Campbell deal for Glen Rice proved
disappointing. He has only Tyronn Lue and Travis Knight to show for
Van Exel. He traded away a first-round pick for George McCloud's
half-season stint.
</P>
<P>
   But his biggest, sweetest trade, was when he gambled by sending
Divac to Charlotte for a high school kid named Kobe Bryant. A week
later, he signed Shaquille O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   West had his new cornerstones. He had a new championship team
that he had built from scratch.
</P>
<P>
   And still, he couldn't recede far enough into the shadows of the
Staples Center. He stayed away when the Lakers won the title at
home last June.
</P>
<P>
   Now he has finally stepped away from the pressure, the wringing
of the hands, the anguish of games out of his control. He can be a
recluse if he wants. An anonymous NBA silhouette.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-08-00 0025EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
