<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 00:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5473 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-VEEPSTAKES-LIEBERMAN-     08-08 1337
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VEEPSTAKES-LIEBERMAN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 GORE PICKS CENTRIST JEWISH SENATOR AS RUNNING MATE  &HT;     By CARLA MARINUCCI 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Making history and a clear appeal to the political center, Vice
President Al Gore has chosen Sen. Joseph Lieberman, an Orthodox Jew
and an outspoken critic of President Clinton's sexual escapades, as
his running mate.
</P>
<P>
   Gore is expected to formally announce the selection of the
two-term senator from Connecticut at a Nashville rally Tuesday.
Lieberman officially received the call from Gore Monday and told
the vice president he was ``humbled'' by the opportunity and
``excited because I believe in you.''
</P>
<P>
   A deeply religious man who is the first Jew ever to run on a
major party presidential ticket, Lieberman was praised by Democrats
as a bold choice. Even normally combative Republicans in the
campaign of Texas Gov. George W. Bush lauded him as a man of honor.
</P>
<P>
   Gore ``has chosen a good man whom Governor Bush and Secretary
Cheney respect,'' said Bush spokesman Ari Fleischer in a statement
that praised Lieberman's ``intelligence'' and ``integrity.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman was the first Democrat to attack Clinton on the Senate
floor after the president admitted he did not tell the truth about
his relations with Monica Lewinsky. But Monday, Clinton also had
high praise for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's one of the most outstanding people in public
life,'' said Clinton, who was rumored to be considering Lieberman
as a running mate in 1992. ``He's a bold thinker. He is always full
of new ideas.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman, who appeared elated when word of his nomination
leaked out, wasted no time assuming his role as an aggressive
defender of Democratic policies _ and Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can tell you that he is without a doubt a more qualified,
more honorable, more intelligent, more progressive, more
hardworking candidate for this high office'' than Bush, Lieberman
told an AFL-CIO audience in Hartford Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line: When the working people of America look for a
helping hand from the other party and the other ticket, they too
often will receive the back of their hand,'' Lieberman said as the
audience cheered.
</P>
<P>
   With less than a week to go before the opening of the Democratic
National Convention in Washington, Gore's pick of Lieberman gives
his presidential campaign a much-needed shot of excitement.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's some potential upside in picking somebody who has a
real strong independent streak, who's going about doing things in
his own way and is a different kind of Democrat,'' said pollster
Mark Baldassare of the Public Policy Institute of California.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Lieberman is a centrist Democrat who voted for the North
American Free Trade Agreement against the wishes of major unions,
is pro-choice and has fought for campaign finance reform. But he
also has supported parental consent laws and an experimental
school-voucher program, and in a vote last year he asserted that
prayer in schools as part of memorial services is constitutional.
</P>
<P>
   The son of a liquor store owner who grew up in Stamford, Conn.,
and attended Yale College and Yale Law, Lieberman is widely admired
by colleagues precisely because, from time to time, he has broken
with his party to speak his mind.
</P>
<P>
   He earned national attention in 1998 when _ before others in
Washington began to speak out on the Monica Lewinsky affair _ he
issued a stern rebuke to Clinton for his ``immoral'' behavior.
</P>
<P>
   The two-term senator and former Connecticut attorney general has
also formed alliances with conservatives, such as Republican values
guru William Bennett. He is an honorary co-chairman of the Center
for the Study of Jewish and Christian Values, a group that boasts a
number of leaders of the Christian conservative movement, such as
former presidential candidate Gary Bauer, on its board.
</P>
<P>
   As a member of the Senate committee investigating campaign
fund-raising abuses, for instance, he said he was ``suspicious''
that Chinese money entered the 1996 election. In a position that,
no doubt, will be highlighted by the George W. Bush camp, Lieberman
chastised both Clinton and Republican Bob Dole for betraying the
public trust through ``issue ads'' and other ``back-door''
fund-raising devices that evaded spending limits. The ``mad
hatters'' from both parties, he said, ``hung a giant `For Sale'
sign on our government.''
</P>
<P>
   He also has been an outspoken critic of the movie and television
industries, frequently lamenting what he calls the ``increasingly
toxic popular culture.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the last year, Lieberman has called for the Federal
Communications Commission to consider the content of television
shows when renewing broadcasters' lucrative licenses. He has said
that if it were up to him, shows like ``Friends'' would be shown
only in movie theaters or late at night so children couldn't watch.
He has even asserted that Hollywood ``doesn't understand piety.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Lieberman and his wife, Hadassah, observe the Jewish
Sabbath from sundown Friday to sundown Saturday, the Connecticut
senator said he will vote on legislation and engage in important
meetings during the Sabbath, but only to promote ``the respect and
protection of human life and well-being.''
</P>
<P>
   Baldassare said Lieberman's resume may assist Gore in drawing
support from the all-important moderate swing voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Al Gore is going to need all the support he can get outside
the Democratic Party,'' Baldassare said. ``The fact that Lieberman
has this strong independent streak, has spoken out against Clinton
and seems to be a person with strong integrity and a strong
viewpoint will help those independent voters who might otherwise
feel uncomfortable about going with (Gore).''
</P>
<P>
   But Baldassare noted that vice-presidential picks do not
influence the vast majority of voters, and Lieberman's home state,
Connecticut, doesn't provide Gore with a geographic advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats argued that the choice carries important strategic
implications for the Gore campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``He neutralizes or diminishes (Green Party presidential
candidate Ralph) Nader in the Northeast and picks up the Jewish
Republican vote in the Midwest,'' said Bob Mulholland, campaign
adviser to the California Democratic Party. Mulholland said
Lieberman will attract the critical soccer-mom vote given his
outspoken concern about the effects on children of violence in
video games and on television.
</P>
<P>
   Some liberal Democrats _ irritated by last week's GOP convention
and its show of diversity _ said Lieberman will serve to underscore
that the Democrats are the truly inclusive party.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shows that diversity is not just something that is talked
about,'' said California Lt. Gov. Cruz Bustamante. ``It's
attempted.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a wonderful step for the country,'' said Rabbi Steven
Chester, a leader in the Reform Movement who heads Temple Sinai,
Oakland's largest congregation. ``It says a lot about the country
and the feeling of the candidate, that (Gore believes) the country
will not judge Lieberman by his religion.''
</P>
<P>
   While acknowledging that the vast majority of Jewish voters tend
to be Democrats, Chester said he doesn't believe anti-Semitism will
affect Gore's chances.
</P>
<P>
   Some Republicans _ even those with generous praise for Lieberman
_ also said Gore's choice could backfire.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a Jewish American, I can't help but be proud to see Senator
Lieberman on a national ticket,'' GOP political analyst Dan Schnur
said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Gore obviously sees Lieberman as willing to speak out
against Clinton, to distance himself from Clinton's ethical
lapses,'' Schnur said. ``Lieberman's courage and independence just
underscore that Gore wasn't willing or able to show either.''
</P>
<P>
   And, Schnur said, Gore cannot take much credit for boldness.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the difference between a campaign that's 10 points
ahead,`` he said, ``and one that's 10 points behind.''
</P>
<P>
   (Chronicle political writer Lynda Gledhill and Chronicle news
services contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
