<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 00:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5475 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r n BC-DWP-POWER-LADN     08-08 0801
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DWP-POWER-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POWER PLANT SELL_OFF ATTACKED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOMINIC BERBEO 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A Department of Water and Power plan to capitalize
on Los Angeles' power surplus by selling an old plant to help build
more efficient, cleaner plants faced a stepped-up attack Monday
just before it goes before the City Council.
</P>
<P>
   City Controller Rick Tuttle sent a letter to the council, which
is to consider the $1.7 &UR;  &LR; billion plan Tuesday, urging rejection of
the sale of the DWP's aging plant in Nevada.
</P>
<P>
   DWP General Manager S. David Freeman sees the plant sale as
critical to a 10-year plan to reduce rates, ensure a power surplus
to attract new business to the city and eliminate the rest of the
debt.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to expand now to meet growing demand, and the longer
we sit on this, the more expensive it's going to be for us,''
Freeman told Daily News editors and reporters. ``Things are hot
right now, and that's when you need to go to town.''
</P>
<P>
   But Tuttle said the city should reject the $265 million offer
for the Mojave plant and borrow instead to build new facilities. He
warned that the DWP cannot be certain it will get necessary permits
to replace existing power plants, including an energy inefficient
and polluting facility in Sun Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``The income from the Mojave sale represents only a fraction of
the total costs of these upgrades,'' he wrote, ``a fraction which
might better be financed through debt than through any measure
which puts the city's power supply at risk.''
</P>
<P>
   During Freeman's three years as head of the DWP, he has lowered
the agency's debt from more than $4 billion to $1.7 billion by
eliminating about 2,000 jobs and getting more than $130 million a
year in windfall profits selling excess power in the open market.
</P>
<P>
   The expansion would help lower customer rates by 5 percent in
2002 and 10 percent the next year, Freeman said.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Freeman is scheduled to outline his plan to the council.
</P>
<P>
   He needs 10 votes to get it on the agenda because it did not
pass through committee.
</P>
<P>
   Business community support for the plan is strong.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Kyser, chief economist at the county Economic Development
Corporation, said the DWP expansion plan would help retain local
businesses and bring new ones to the area by ensuring a cheap and
stable source of energy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The new economy is technology-driven and new businesses are
power hogs,'' he said. ``The rest of the state is going to be
facing power problems for the next few years, while L.A. can offer
a low-cost and stable alternative.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Ackerman, president and chief executive officer of the
Economic Alliance of the San Fernando Valley, said the DWP plan is
good for business if it would ensure affordable rates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some other parts of the state are now seeing that deregulation
didn't pay off they way they thought it would,'' he said. ``Also,
any time you can build with existing capital or resources instead
of borrowing, it usually makes good business sense.''
</P>
<P>
   Freeman said he wants to finance the 2000 Integrated Resource
Plan without borrowing, thereby avoiding huge debts that nearly
bankrupted the department over the past two decades.
</P>
<P>
   Selling the city's 20 percent share in the coal-burning Mojave
Generating Station in southern Nevada to private companies would
bring $190 million in cash and an additional $75 million in savings
by not having to implement government-imposed environmental
upgrades at the site.
</P>
<P>
   Freeman argues Los Angeles has more than enough power without
Mojave, and that the cash in hand would help pay off its entire
debt by 2003, freeing up revenues to increase production and lower
rates.
</P>
<P>
   If the city waits until after a Sept. 1 sale deadline, Freeman
says, the city's share value will decrease by 20 percent once the
new owner, the AES Co., goes through with its current plan to buy
out all the other major shareholders this year.
</P>
<P>
   The new local power plants would be natural-gas-burning and
built on the same sites as old, less efficient natural-gas-burning
plants in Sun Valley, Long Beach and Playa del Rey.
</P>
<P>
   In Sun Valley, Freeman said, a new 500-megawatt plant could be
constructed by 2004 and would produce up to 50 percent more energy
with less pollution than the old plant.
</P>
<P>
   The expansion plan was unanimously approved by the DWP Board of
Commissioners, but requires final approval from the council.
</P>
<P>
   Councilwoman Ruth Galanter, who chairs the Commerce, Energy and
Natural Resources Committee, said she supports the plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``The city of L.A. has an opportunity to get out of a dirty coal
contract, rely on local power generation instead of a faraway
plant, and create jobs here in our own communities,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
