<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 00:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5481 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f BC-HOME-SALES-LADN     08-08 0640
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-SALES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VALLEY HOME SALES SLUMP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREGORY J. WILCOX 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Sales of single-family homes plunged 19.5 &UR;  &LR; percent
in the San Fernando Valley during July as an unseasonable cold
front buffeted the market, a trade group said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The sales slowdown, the biggest annual percentage drop since a
20.1 &UR;  &LR; percent decline in December 1995, reflects rising prices and
a tight inventory, said the Van Nuys-based Southland Regional
Association of Realtors.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, escrow closed on 1,051 previously owned, detached
homes -- 255 fewer than in July.
</P>
<P>
   While the drop is significant, both the association and analysts
note that sales counts are being compared with one of the Valley's
best years ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a big drop, but we are coming off the second-strongest
year in San Fernando Valley residential real estate history, so we
have to keep it in perspective,'' said Jim Link, the association's
executive vice president.
</P>
<P>
   July's median price, the point at which half the homes sold for
more and half for less, increased 8.3 percent to $236,000. That's
$4,000 less than June's median but the highest for a July since
1989.
</P>
<P>
   The record median of $245,000 should be surpassed later this
year.
</P>
<P>
   While it is too early to say whether the sales slide is a trend
or a blip, prices will continue to rise.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the easy part of all this,'' John Karevoll, a market
analyst at DataQuick Information Systems Inc., said of predicting
the price curve. ``The strength of the economy and new job creation
is driving prices. The question is at what rate?''
</P>
<P>
   In January, the Realtors group predicted sales would fall about
5 percent from last year's level while prices would gain between 7
percent and 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way the numbers are tracking we're pretty much going to
hit that right on the head,'' Link said.
</P>
<P>
   Rising prices have been pushing buyers, especially first-timers,
into the condominium market.
</P>
<P>
   During July, Realtors sold 396 condominiums, an increase of 35,
or 9.7 percent, from the year-ago period.
</P>
<P>
   The median price of $138,000 was a gain of 8.7 percent over the
past 12 months, the highest for a July since 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the all-important single-family sector slumped last
month, agents remain upbeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a strong market with no signs of fundamental weakness
on the horizon. Indeed, this may represent the kind of activity
we'll see for several years to come -- very busy with just enough
restraint on resale prices to prevent them from rising into the
stratosphere,'' noted association President R.E. ``Mitch'' Davis.
</P>
<P>
   While sales took a hit last month, they still broke the 1,000
barrier for the fifth consecutive time this year.
</P>
<P>
   A bigger concern is the inventory.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of last month there were 5,040 active listings,
nearly 15 percent fewer than a year ago. That's less than a
four-month housing supply at the current sales pace.
</P>
<P>
   A market of the Valley's size should have about a six-month
supply.
</P>
<P>
   But analyst Karevoll said more homes could soon come on the
market as prices keep rising.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't make sense for some homeowners to sell right now
because they would not make enough money on the transaction for a
down payment on a nicer home. Rising prices will change that
thinking, though.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very close to a threshold as we speak we may be in the
process of crossing it -- where homeowners can walk away from the
sale with enough money to make it feasible. They couldn't do that
three or four months ago,'' Karevoll said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've seen this happen in other areas and once that line is
crossed, a huge amount of inventory goes on the market and we feel
certain it will happen sometime this fall.''
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
