<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 01:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5492 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-WEST-LADN-(SLANG)     08-08 1142
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEST-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A. ICON RETIRES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL SEGUNDO, Calif. _ There would be no buzzer- beating shots
this time, no timely last-minute maneuvers from a man who
personified the term ``clutch,'' no symbolic, halfcourt heave to
change the outcome of one dramatic, franchise-shaking decision.
</P>
<P>
   And in the end, not even a farewell appearance by Jerry West
either.
</P>
<P>
   West retired Monday as the Los Angeles Lakers' basketball
operations chief, ending a 40-year tenure and a legacy unmatched in
professional sports. It concluded not with a moving send-off, but
with a brief, simply worded, five-paragraph open letter to Laker
fans.
</P>
<P>
   And that was that. West, who helped bring seven NBA
championships to L.A. as a player and executive, was gone.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers held a press conference to announce the promotions of
general manager Mitch Kupchak to head of basketball operations and
Kurt Rambis to assistant general manager. But West himself was far
from the proceedings, having cleaned out his office weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Lakers spokesman John Black noted the absence was ``a little bit
awkward,'' but added, ``This is the way he wanted to go away.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision, reported by the Daily News last month, was not
made official until Monday morning, and members of the organization
had held out hope West would change his mind. But after suffering
an irregular heartbeat this past season, health concerns and a
desire to shred the stresses of the job won out.
</P>
<P>
   ``He feels the pressures are tearing him down physically as well
as mentally,'' said Lakers broadcaster Chick Hearn, West's close
friend for almost 40 years. ``I think he just said to himself,
`I've got to go now.' I commend him for that. . . . It's a sad day
for me.''
</P>
<P>
   If West's career is truly over, he departed on a winning note,
less than two months removed from the Lakers' seventh championship.
He helped win the first as a player, the other six as a member of
the front office.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a difficult yet happy time for me personally,'' wrote
West, 62, adding he looked forward to ``more freedom to enjoy my
friends and particularly my family, unburdened with the pressures
of the professional athletic business.''
</P>
<P>
   There are indications, however slight, that West could return.
He has a contract with owner Jerry Buss to act as a paid consultant
and will be in constant contact with Kupchak. This could turn out
to be just a break. But officially, West is retired, a fact with
which his loyal proteges were still coming to grips.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of me tends to look over at that door over there and
(expect to) see Jerry's face come out and (say), `I was only
kidding.' But I don't think he's only kidding today,'' said
Kupchak, who at 46 inherits one of the premier positions in sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got mixed emotions about today,'' he said. ``On one hand,
the Laker organization is losing a guiding light for over 40 years.
I no longer get to stand side by side with my mentor, my confidante
and my best friend on a daily basis. That part I will miss to no
end.''
</P>
<P>
   The West era included seven championships and an lengthy string
of NBA legends _ from Magic Johnson and Kareem Abdul-Jabbar in the
``Showtime'' 1980s to Shaquille O'Neal and Kobe Bryant today.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, Jerry West is irreplacable. What he's meant to the
Lakers franchise over the past 40 years is immeasurable,'' Buss
said in a prepared statement.
</P>
<P>
   West singled out only three individuals in his letter,
expressing thanks to Buss and ``gratitude'' to O'Neal and Bryant
``for their belief in the Lakers.''
</P>
<P>
   It was West's signing of O'Neal and trade for Bryant in a
one-week span in the summer of 1996 that catapulted the Lakers from
their post-``Showtime'' malaise _ including two losing seasons _
back to preeminence. And aside from the personal torment West
subjected himself to daily, it was the conclusion of the Lakers'
restoration that paved the way for his departure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was important for him for that (``Showtime'' era)
group to retire and for him to rebuild this team from scratch,''
Kupchak said, ``and get it from the very bottom, which is where we
were several years ago with a lottery pick (in 1994), to where it
is today.''
</P>
<P>
   West's tightly wound personality didn't allow him to enjoy the
march back to greatness. He didn't attend a single game after Game
2 of the Western Conference finals and didn't even watch the Finals
on television, saying it was too stressful.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Hearn, the team's broadcaster since 1961 _ and the one who
dubbed West ``Mr. Clutch'' for his play as a Lakers guard in the
'60s and '70s _ was surprised West decided to quit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never dreamed he'd succumb to this,'' Hearn said. ``I
thought he was strong enough to overcome it if there were anything
there. I think he feels for his family and himself it's time to
take a one-year sabbatical, so to speak. The door is open for him
to come back, he told me that himself. . . . I've got a funny
feeling he'll be back.''
</P>
<P>
   No one, apparently not even West, knows if he will come back. He
visited Kupchak at home on Sunday night to deliver some fish he
caught on his recent Alaska vacation, and Kupchak said West never
looked more relaxed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw it in his face that this is it, he's really gonna do
it,'' Kupchak said. ``Compared to where he was a month ago, he was
relaxed last night, oh yeah.''
</P>
<P>
   No one questioned the decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to wish him the best,'' said Lakers forward Rick Fox,
``and pray for those who run into him over at the Bel Air country
club. Now he has more time to tune his golf game up again.''
</P>
<P>
   Said O'Neal, on his Web site, Dunk.net, ``All good times must
come to an end. If it's not fun for him anymore, then it's time for
him to do something else.''
</P>
<P>
   Assistant coach Bill Bertka, who has spent 25 years in the
organization, including a stint in the late '60s when West was a
player, said he was ``extremely happy for him that he's made his
decision and he's at peace with himself. . . . The thing that
probably is best about it is he's leaving at the pinnacle, having
won another world championship.''
</P>
<P>
   Given West's Hall of Fame playing career and his four-decade
string of success, Bertka placed him among sport's all-time
greats.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They call them icons. He's certainly an icon of professional
basketball, as Lombardi was in football and John Wooden in college
basketball and Babe Ruth to baseball and Jim Thorpe to track and
field,'' Bertka said. ``He's one of the most significant, one of
the true superstars of the game. . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``He was not only one of the greatest of basketball players,
then he turns around and becomes one of the greatest of executives,
because of the goals he establishes for himself.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-08-00 0105EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
