r s BC-BBA-ANGNOTE-LADN-(SLA     08-08 0481
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGNOTE-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS RELEASE HILL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GORDON VERRELL  
 c.2000 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ The Anaheim Angels released veteran
right-hander Ken Hill Monday, citing his lack of consistency on the
mound.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some days I felt good, some days I didn't,'' Hill said. ``I've
had pain (from arthritis) in my elbow for three years and it ain't
going away.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Manager Mike Scioscia: ``We saw glimpses of what he could
do . . . but he couldn't maintain it.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he felt he could still pitch, Hill answered,
emphatically, ``Yeah, I can still pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   Hill was in the last year of a three-year $16.05 million
contract which paid him $5.6 million this season. The Angels must
eat just under $2 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a combination of a lot of things,'' general manager Bill
Stoneman said. ``I can't say enough about Ken's effort . . . but
the results just weren't there.''
</P>
<P>
   Hill was 5-7 with a 6.52 earned run average in 16 starts. He had
been scheduled to make start No. 17 tonight against the Boston Red
Sox and Pedro Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   Hill, who has a 117-107 record with eight shutouts in a 12-year,
five-team career, was 22-28 with the Angels. One of his wins was a
two-hitter against Texas in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   He also went on the disabled list eight times, including four
times since coming to Anaheim and once this season.
</P>
<P>
   Hill said he certainly would listen to a proposal from a
contending club, otherwise, he said, ``I'll just go home to
Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Baby-faced staff: The Angels' pitching suddenly has the look
of a young-boys choir. The 34-year-old Hill is now out of the
picture, along with Kent Bottenfield, 31, who was traded away last
month; Tim Belcher, 38, and Kent Mercker, 32, remain on the
disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   Jarrod Washburn, who started Monday night's game, is the oldest
of the new breed. He'll turn 27 Sunday. Scott Schoeneweiss is 26,
Ramon Ortiz 24 and Matt Wise 24. Brian Cooper, who was optioned
Monday to Triple-A Edmonton but will soon return, will be 27 Aug.
19.
</P>
<P>
   __ Odds and ends: Tim Salmon was selected AL player of the week
after batting .583 (14 for 24) with two homers, a triple and four
doubles. Salmon is the third Angel honored this season, joining
Darin Erstad (twice) and Mo Vaughn. . . . Left-hander Kent Mercker,
who suffered a life-threatening cerebral hemorrhage in mid-May,
will continue his comeback Wednesday night with a rehab start for
Triple-A Edmonton in a Pacific Coast League game at Tucson.
Scioscia said Mercker will throw between 75 and 80 pitches. If all
goes well, Mercker will rejoin the club this weekend and might even
be activated for the series against the New York Yankees. . . .
Disabled reliever Troy Percival underwent an MRI exam Monday, which
confirmed the original diagnosis of tendinitis in his right elbow.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-08-00 0107EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
