<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 01:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5497 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-KUPCHAK-LADN-(SLA     08-08 0840
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KUPCHAK-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S KUPCHAK'S TURN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL SEGUNDO, Calif. _ Mitch Kupchak is measured, soft-spoken and
deliberate. Methodical, and some will say even conservative. But
there are moments now and then when he gets passionate, maybe even
a bit frenetic, and his wife, Claire, sees another personality come
through.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lately, she has mentioned a couple times, that `You're
starting to act just like Jerry,' '' Kupchak relates with a smile.
</P>
<P>
   The comparison to his friend and mentor, Jerry West, is taken as
a compliment. And Kupchak is eager to continue earning such
comparisons _ presumably more for his bold and successful
management of the Los Angeles Lakers than for those occasional fits
of excitement.
</P>
<P>
   The 46-year-old Kupchak was elevated Monday to the head of
basketball operations, succeeding the retired West. If West's
departure sent waves through the organization and the league,
Kupchak's ascension hardly caused a ripple.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1986, when Kupchak joined the front office, he has been
moving, step by step, toward this day. It has been taken as a given
that Kupchak would one day succeed West, and that made for a smooth
transition when owner Jerry Buss made the promotion official
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   For 14 years, Kupchak has learned at West's side. For the last
two seasons, in particular, he has been taking on greater
responsibility and exerting more influence over day-to-day
operations. At every stage, Kupchak has been groomed for the job by
the man many consider the best executive in pro sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the Laker fans hope that somewhere along the line,
somehow, someway, some of Jerry's magic has found its way to me
over the years,''Kupchak said. ``And I also feel after 14 years of
working with Jerry that nobody can be more prepared than I am for
this job right now. And I embrace the opportunity and I look
forward to working and walking in Jerry West's footsteps.''
</P>
<P>
   Kupchak, who retains his title as general manager, has
three-plus years left on his existing contract _ a deal he signed
in 1998 when he nearly left to take over the Denver Nuggets. There
have been many such opportunities for the highly regarded Kupchak,
but each time he has chosen to stay with the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   Now all he has to do is replace a living legend.
</P>
<P>
   He seemed unfazed at the prospect, however, knowing he inherits
a team well positioned for the near future.
</P>
<P>
   They have just won a championship, stars Shaquille O'Neal and
Kobe Bryant are under contract for several years and coach Phil
Jackson has four years remaining on his contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``The very good news is that the cupboard is full, not unlike it
was 12 to 14 years ago when we had Magic (Johnson) and Kareem
(Abdul-Jabbar),'' Kupchak said. ``We have two pretty good players
on this team that my hope is they'd be around for a long time. And
that will provide the people in this city and our owner with a lot
of comfort, knowing that going forward we're going to win a bunch
of games. And each move in a team like this is a crucial and a
critical move. But by and large, when you have those two players,
the organization is in pretty good hands.''
</P>
<P>
   Ask those who know Kupchak well, and they'll offer the same
assessment. He is respected around the league and well-liked within
the organization. And significantly, he's the one West wanted to
replace him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have the utmost respect for and confidence in Mitch
Kupchak,'' Buss said in a prepared statement. ``He is Jerry West's
hand-picked successor and was trained by the best.''
</P>
<P>
   Insiders say the passionate, ever-stressed-out West is much more
impulsive than Kupchak, who admits he's more likely to take his
time making a decision. But Kupchak said he and West have similar
eyes for talent _ a quality he referred to as West's ``gift.''
</P>
<P>
   The No. 1 lesson he learned from West? ``To follow your gut
instinct.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's totally prepared,'' longtime Lakers broadcaster
Chick Hearn said. ``I think he's a totally different personality. I
think he's slower to make a judgment. . . . I have great faith in
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Kupchak's first moves could come quickly, although neither one
will involve acquiring a much-needed power forward. The Lakers are
on the verge of signing, or trading for, Nets swingman Kendall
Gill, and are pursuing former Lakers forward Cedric Ceballos, now
with Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Sources say the Lakers have offered center Travis Knight and
guard Tyronn Lue for Ceballos, who has one year left on his
contract. But they have bigger concerns as well, primarily
frontcourt depth and what to do with unsigned free agent Glen Rice.
</P>
<P>
   Kupchak knows the credit and blame for such matters are now his
alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``So to a degree, the pressure that goes along with that
position is there, and there's no doubt about it,'' he said. ``But
it is the most challenging and the most satisfying part of the job.
And it's really the part that I look forward to.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
