<SLUG> BC-LABOR-dnc-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNION WORKERS WILL KEEP PEACE DURING CONVENTION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICK ORLOV 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; With an agreement guaranteeing labor peace inside
next week's Democratic National Convention, organizers Monday
seemingly had a united message: Let the hype begin.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will be the greatest convention of this century and last
century,'' declared Terry McAuliffe, chairman of the convention
committee. ``It is being held in the greatest state, in the
greatest city, in the greatest arena. This will be the convention
that people remember.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Gov. Gray Davis, not known for overenthusiasm, got caught
up in McAuliffe's spirit after witnessing some three dozen
volunteers handpainting signs for Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will be the best Democratic convention we have ever seen,
and it will be far different than what the Republicans did in
Philadelphia,'' Davis said. ``The nation will see the real Al Gore
and see us talk about real issues of importance to the American
family.''
</P>
<P>
   Also on Monday, Los Angeles police arrested four people from the
Ruckus Society who were attempting to hang a banner from the
Figueroa Hotel, which directly faces Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses said the banner was a depiction of the American flag
with corporate logos across it. The banner was to have covered an
Apple Computer mural with the theme of ``Think Different'' and
images of the late President Franklin Delano Roosevelt, Eleanor
Roosevelt, Sen. Robert F. Kennedy and labor leader Cesar Chavez.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, Staples Center President Tim Liewecke signed
a labor peace agreement with Miguel Contreras, secretary-treasurer
of the Los Angeles County Federation of Labor, AFL-CIO, and
representatives of a dozen unions that have workers at the
facility.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we came up with the concept of Staples Center, it was
always with the idea of working with the unions,'' Liewecke said.
``We did this not to win the Democratic convention, but as a goal
toward helping working people.''
</P>
<P>
   From the union's standpoint, Contreras said it sent an important
message to union workers in the city as well as to the Democratic
Party nationally even though the agreement affects a maximum of
about 3,000 workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will guarantee labor peace inside Staples Center and the
Convention Center, where all the workers will be union workers,''
Contreras said.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, however, he said it would not stop local
unions from protesting such as at the Loew's Santa Monica Beach
Hotel, which will be the home of the Democratic Congressional
Campaign Committee and where, coincidentally, union organizers feel
their efforts have been blocked.
</P>
<P>
   Also, while national labor leaders have pledged to not have any
massive disruptions of the convention, Contreras said he believed
many would come out and join various protests.
</P>
<P>
   ``One-third of the delegates are from labor, and I'm sure they
want to show their support to co-workers,'' Contreras said.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
