A5500 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-KRIKOR-COLUMN-LAD     08-08 0952
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KRIKOR-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN THE END, WEST WENT OUT ON OWN TERMS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 c.2000 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   As he departed Monday for his annual two-week summer vacation at
the Greenbrier golf resort in his native West Virginia, Jerry West
had to be in an euphoric mood, or at least as close to such a
blissful state as his frayed nerves will allow.
</P>
<P>
   First, the Los Angeles Lakers finally made official what he had
done several weeks ago and what he had threatened to do on several
other occasions in recent years _ resign as the team's executive
vice president of basketball operations.
</P>
<P>
   Second, he had visited his cardiologist earlier in the week and
been pronounced in perfect health, meaning there were no signs of
the irregular heartbeat that had plagued him during the playoffs
and that had even kept him from attending any of the Lakers' games
during the NBA Finals against the Indiana Pacers.
</P>
<P>
   Third, Lakers owner Jerry Buss had emphasized to West during a
recent meeting that his old position always would be open to him at
the same $4 million annual salary and that Buss still would like to
confer with West at least twice a month.
</P>
<P>
   And, finally, West had worked out an amicable severance
agreement with Buss, which some insiders believe to be in the $6
million range. This was a particularly generous gesture by an owner
known to be committed to cutting his payroll and not legally
obligated to give West anything since West voluntarily forfeited
the opportunity to finish out the three years he had left on his
Lakers contract.
</P>
<P>
   So, Jerry West, whose 40-year incumbency with the Lakers spans
nine American presidents and dramatic demographic and sociological
changes in the Los Angeles area, whose dominant presence here as a
player and executive across four decades have made him among the
most revered sporting icons in Southern California history, is
gone.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps not for long.
</P>
<P>
   As his former teammate and longtime friend, Elgin Baylor, said,
``I look for Jerry to take a year off and then come back again.
Basketball is too much in his blood.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe so. But maybe not.
</P>
<P>
   Financially, West is now secure and doesn't have to work again
if he so chooses, especially after the deserving bonus he received
from Buss for his exemplary work as a Lakers executive _ he was
responsible for putting together four world-championship teams.
</P>
<P>
   West always has lived within his means and has made sound
investments over the years. His major concessions to wealth are the
home he owns in Bel Air and the membership he has in the Bel Air
Country Club.
</P>
<P>
   There will be loud media debates over the real reason West has
decided to skip out on the Lakers after a 67-win,
world-championship season in which the two men he maneuvered to
obtain in 1996, Shaquille O'Neal and Kobe Bryant, played the most
important roles.
</P>
<P>
   There are some pundits who insist that the presence of the
strong-willed Phil Jackson pushed West over the precipice, that
Jackson's spouting off publicly about his need for a power forward
and his well-chronicled exhibition-season desire for Ron Harper
were a cultural shock to West.
</P>
<P>
   After all, West had always been accustomed to making all the
Laker roster moves himself and to previous coaches like Mike
Dunleavy, Randy Pfund, Del Harris, Kurt Rambis and even Pat Riley
remaining silent on such matters.
</P>
<P>
   While I'm sure West felt uneasy about Jackson's public candor,
I'm not sure he was so upset about it that it inspired his
resignation at a time when the Lakers might be on the threshold of
another Showtime-like dynasty with the 28-year-old O'Neal and
21-year-old Bryant.
</P>
<P>
   West continually confided to me throughout the past season that
he had no problems working with Jackson, and that he had tremendous
respect for Jackson as a coach. Remember, West endorsed Jackson
strongly to Buss as the person Buss should hire to succeed Rambis.
</P>
<P>
   And it also must not be forgotten that Jerry West had come close
to departing the Lakers twice in recent years before Jackson even
came aboard _ only to reluctantly change his mind both times at the
final moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know when I quit, people are going to say that it was
because I didn't get along with Phil Jackson _ and that's just a
lie,'' said West. ``I'm quitting because I want to keep living.''
</P>
<P>
   It is the overwhelming feeling here that serious health concerns
compelled Jerry West finally to bid farewell to the Lakers, with,
incidentally, Buss' blessing.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, I've been told from one Lakers insider that Buss
actually told West at their last meeting, ``I think it's a good
idea you're getting away from it awhile.''
</P>
<P>
   It's ironic that the same maniacal competitive juices that
fueled West as a player _ and he was such an extraordinary player
as a guard with the Lakers that his likeness now adorns the NBA
logo _ also carried over when he joined management.
</P>
<P>
   Before doctors advised him to stop attending playoff games, West
would sit in Buss' Staples Center suite and nervously watch the
Lakers perform, fidgeting throughout the proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know how a drug addict has to keep doing more and more
drugs to catch the high he once got,'' he once told me. ``Well, in
a weird way, that's happened to me. Basketball is my drug and it's
just become a greater strain for me as each season passes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just can't wait to live a normal life, to not get bugged all
the time by the press, to not worry about if the Lakers win or
lose. I'd just like to take some time off, and fish and play golf
and enjoy life without all the pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   And so this is what Jerry West has done.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-08-00 0130EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
