<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-ASSOCIATES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPUTER ASSOCIATES RESHUFFLES ITS SENIOR MANAGEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   By BARNABY J. FEDER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Searching for a way to bolster its sagging stock, Computer
Associates International reassigned senior managers on Monday and
said it intended to use spin-offs or other strategies to tap the
value of fast-growing units that are currently overshadowed by the
company's main businesses.
</P>
<P>
   The management changes start at the top with Charles B. Wang,
the company's founder, turning over the job of chief executive to
Sanjay Kumar, who had been president and chief operating officer.
</P>
<P>
   Wang (whose name rhymes with ``long'') will continue as
chairman. He will devote his attention to creating new ventures for
the company, which is based in Islandia, N.Y., and is a leader in
software for mainframe computers and management of large networks,
including data storage and security.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the other management changes were related to the
formation, announced Monday, of iCan-ASP Inc., which will include
Computer Associates' fast-growing collection of technology for
so-called application service providers. Such companies, known as
ASP's, provide services including accounting, e-mail and data
processing to other companies over the Internet. Nancy Li, who is
chief technology officer of Computer Associates, will become chief
executive of iCan-ASP.
</P>
<P>
   Computer Associates said it was studying the best way to spin
off iCan-ASP. Computer Associates also affirmed its plan to
eventually spin off ACCPAC, which provides accounting software for
desktop computers, and said that it was looking for ways to get
more value out of its telecommunications joint ventures. It has
retained Credit Suisse First Boston and Morgan Stanley Dean Witter
as advisers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to unlock the value and the talent of this company,''
said Wang, the company's 55-year-old founder, whose personal
fortune has declined by more than $1.2 billion as Computer
Associates shares have fallen from their 52-week high of $79.4375
to below $24 last week.
</P>
<P>
   Investors reacted with little enthusiasm to what many analysts
described as minor tinkering. The company provided no financial
details on the size of the ventures it intended to spin off, other
than to say that their total revenues were small enough that it
expected to make them up through growth in other businesses. It
told analysts not to revise their estimates for the year. Computer
Associates' shares edged up $2.3125, to $27.625 on the New York
Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market is looking for better performance out of the core
business,'' said Kevin M. Buttigieg, who follows the company for
PaineWebber. ``They didn't really address that today.''
</P>
<P>
   Buttigieg said the company's biggest problem was a ``Y2K
hangover.'' Many customers bought more large computers like IBM's
390 series than they needed while modernizing their systems to
avoid Year 2000 computer disruptions. Until the sales of such
hardware pick up again, Computer Associates and others that provide
software for such computers will face a tough market, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Slow sales forced Computer Associates to warn Wall Street in
June that its quarter ending June 30 would produce disappointing
results. In late July, it reported net income of just $23 million
on revenues of $1.14 billion for the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Kumar, who is 38, said that the reorganization would be
accompanied by more focused marketing in the core businesses,
including a plan to assign some research workers to the field sales
force to help close sales in new areas like software applications
for Internet portals. The company will also start providing Wall
Street with more financial information on fast-growing segments
that it wants investors to pay more attention to, said Kumar,
citing Computer Associates' $900 million in network-management
revenues as an example.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's so much sitting under the C.A. umbrella that we are
not getting credit for,'' Kumar said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
