<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-RAMBIS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOYAL LAKER RAMBIS EMBRACES NEW ROLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By VINCENT BONSIGNORE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL SEGUNDO, Calif. _ With a new job comes a fresh look for Kurt
Rambis, who ditched his famous glasses 11 days ago thanks to laser
eye surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Rambis, the Los Angeles Lakers' new assistant general manager,
says it's much easier now to see which way the waves are breaking
when he's out surfing. Of course, Lakers' fans hope Rambis'
improved eyesight enables him to uncover talented players, which
he'll be counted on to do under director of basketball operations
Mitch Kupchak.
</P>
<P>
   So does Rambis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sure hope so,'' Rambis said Monday at a press conference
announcing team president Jerry West's retirement after 40 years
with the club, the elevation of Kupchak to top man and the addition
of Rambis as his assistant.
</P>
<P>
   For Rambis _ the loyal Lakers company man who has served in
every imaginable role with the team _ going from player to
assistant coach to head coach and most recently advisor to owner
Dr. Jerry Buss, the first task might be locating his new office and
not reporting to the old one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very excited about my new job and I'm very excited about
getting my fourth set of business cards from this franchise,''
Rambis joked.
</P>
<P>
   All kidding aside, Rambis seems prepared for his new job. He
certainly didn't waste time as Buss' advisor. He used that
opportunity to study the complicated NBA salary cap, perhaps to the
point of mastering it, if that's humanly possible.
</P>
<P>
   Rambis' cap knowledge will be invaluable to Kupchak as they plot
the Lakers' future together with Buss and Phil Jackson. Rambis will
also handle most of the day-to-day operation such as training camp,
practice sites, practice games and scouting, freeing up Kupchak to
concentrate on personnel issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cap is something that, probably in the last year or so,
Kurt has gone from not knowing much about it to really being pretty
proficient in it,'' Kupchak said. ``Just in the last three or four
weeks working together, he's shown me how much he's learned.''
</P>
<P>
   Rambis was nothing if not resourceful as a player, so it's no
surprise he set aside any bitterness when the Lakers passed on him
as head coach after his ill-fated, half-season interim stint in
1998-99. He left the bench but not the organization, turning down
other offers to stay on as an advisor to Buss, who's always
considerd Rambis one of his favorites.
</P>
<P>
   Kupchak and Rambis' friendship goes all the way back to 1981,
when they started their Lakers careers together. The cozy
relationship mirrors that of the one West and Kupchak enjoyed and
should make the transition period easier.
</P>
<P>
   Kupchak looks forward to working with his old friend.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kurt played the game, he coached the game, he's broadcast the
game and he's played for different teams and different coaches,''
Kupchak said. ``The experience level that he brings to the
organization and what he'll bring to me on a daily basis is
something that, within an organization, you just can't go out on
the street, look for and find in a day.''
</P>
<P>
   Rambis hasn't ruled out a return to coaching, but for now he's
content in the front office.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very exciting to be learning and helping out the business
aspect of running the franchise,'' Rambis said. ``And I hope Mitch
will listen to some of my gut instincts too, as he follows his
own.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
