<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 01:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5504 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN-(SLA     08-08 0648
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS LOSE THIRD STRAIGHT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Ah, the soft part of the schedule. You know, the
Philadelphia Phillies, the Milwaukee Brewers, the Chicago Cubs. The
teams good teams beat upon.
</P>
<P>
   If the Los Angeles Dodgers hadn't beaten Pittsburgh two out of
three, think where they would be.
</P>
<P>
   As it is, the Dodgers' so-called easy portion of the schedule is
proving to be nothing of the sort as setbacks to anemic teams add
up. The latest was a 7-3 loss to the Cubs in the opener of a three-
game series Monday at Dodger Stadium in which rookie Matt Herges
pitched well in his first major-league start but had nothing to
show for it.
</P>
<P>
   He was outpitched by Cubs rookie Ruben Quevedo, who won for the
first time in his major-league career. Quevedo (1-3) allowed seven
hits and pitched a complete-game as the Dodgers (58-53) dropped
their third straight.
</P>
<P>
   Since winning three of four at Colorado and being poised to make
a run at first place in the National League West, the Dodgers have
dropped six of 10 to the Phillies, Pirates, Brewers and Cubs. That
quartet entered Monday a combined 56 games below .500.
</P>
<P>
   Cubs right fielder Sammy Sosa led off the ninth with a towering
homer to right-center field. It was his 35th of the season, tying
him with the Dodgers' Gary Sheffield for the major-league lead.
</P>
<P>
   Herges (8-1) was inserted into the starting rotation after a
magnificent four months in which he went 8-0 with a 3.00 ERA in 44
appearances as a reliever. However, when lefty Carlos Perez had
trouble in his last two starts, it was Herges whom manager Davey
Johnson turned to.
</P>
<P>
   Herges pitched well, yielding three runs on five hits in six
innings, but he still saw his winning streak end at eight. It was
the best start by a rookie since Livan Hernandez won his first nine
decisions in 1997. With eight straight wins, Herges also equaled
the best start by a pitcher since Fernando Valenzuela began the
1981 season 8-0. Pedro Martinez was the last Dodger to win eight
straight decisions, in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers gave Herges a 1-0 lead in the first inning, but it
could have been much more. Tom Goodwin led off with a single and
scored on Mark Grudzielanek's double to the right-center field gap.
</P>
<P>
   Grudzielanek went to third on Quevedo's errant pick-off throw
but then was caught straying too far from third on Gary Sheffield's
bouncer back to Quevedo. Grudzielanek was tagged out at the plate
and Sheffield compounded the problem when he was caught between
first and second to complete the double play.
</P>
<P>
   The only inning Herges had difficulty in was the third. He
allowed a leadoff single to Jeff Reed and Eric Young's one-out
single put runners on first and second. Ricky Gutierrez put the
Cubs ahead 2-1 with a triple to right-center field and he scored on
Mark Grace's sacrifice fly to give the Cubs a 3-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Still-slumping Shawn Green, who began the day batting .274,
connected for his 20th homer of the season on the first pitch he
saw from Quevedo in the fourth inning to pull the Dodgers within
3-2.
</P>
<P>
   Goodwin's one-out single in the fifth presented the opportunity
for him to showcase his speed, but he was thrown out trying to
steal second.
</P>
<P>
   Herges reached his pitch-count after six innings (he threw 79
pitches) and was relieved by right-hander Antonio Osuna, who
quickly allowed the Cubs to build upon their lead. Young walked
with one out and Gutierrez followed with a two-run homer as Chicago
went up 5-2.
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs extended their lead to 6-2 in the eighth as Osuna, who
was unavailable Sunday because of illness, continued to have
problems. He caught a break when Quevedo bunted into a double play
with two on and none out, but he couldn't capitalize and allowed a
run-scoring single by Young.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
