<HEADER>
A5506 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBN-DODNOTE-LADN-(SLA     08-08 0625
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODNOTE-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITE WANTS MALONE'S EAR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Los Angeles Dodgers outfielder Devon White sought
manager Davey Johnson for a hallway meeting Monday to once again
discuss his role, which has changed since Tom Goodwin's arrival a
week ago.
</P>
<P>
   White got the same answer he was given when he met with Johnson
a week ago in Pittsburgh _ he was going to be the fourth outfielder
and start when Gary Sheffield or Shawn Green need a rest.
</P>
<P>
   But White, a 14-year veteran and seven-time Gold Glove winner,
is bothered that general manager Kevin Malone hasn't talked to him
personally since Goodwin's arrival. It was Malone who inked White
to a three-year, $12.6 million contract after the 1998 season.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said he reiterated to White that the speedy Goodwin
would make the majority of starts because the club needs his
leadoff ability.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kevin Malone doesn't owe me (anything),'' White said. ``But I
think a veteran would have gotten respect that (front office
personnel) can come down and tell (a player) what's going on. I've
been here for three days now and he hasn't made an effort to come
down, and I'm not going up to his office because that's not my
position.
</P>
<P>
   ``So far, I've never been in the position where management
hasn't told me (the plans), so I don't know what the future plan
is. So we have to wait and see what comes up. I did speak to Davey,
but Malone didn't come down here and tell me what the scoop was.
Not that he has to, but I think as a veteran player, I deserve that
much respect.''
</P>
<P>
   White's agent, Eric Goldschmidt, spoke with Malone via telephone
Monday to discuss White's role. Goldschmidt and Malone were
scheduled to meet today, but that meeting might not happen.
</P>
<P>
   When Goodwin was acquired in a trade for Todd Hollandsworth at
the trading deadline, the Dodgers were on the road and Malone was
in Los Angeles. When the club returned home Friday, Malone left to
watch the Dodgers' Double-A affiliate in San Antonio. He returned
Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``The manager talks to his team. (White) plays for the
manager,'' Malone said. ``I have a whole organization to run. I've
been out of town in Texas for four days. That's really not my role.
My understanding was he understood what his role is.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just wants to play and it'll work itself out. He's
frustrated. Right now we're going to see what Goodwin can do and
try to keep everybody fresh down the stretch.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Perez's position: Dodgers lefty Carlos Perez was pulled from
the starting rotation, and though he doesn't like it, he said he's
willing to do whatever the club wants.
</P>
<P>
   However, Perez still doesn't appreciate finding out about the
move only when he was questioned by reporters last Wednesday in
Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that was the right thing,'' said Perez, who
pitched 5 scoreless inning of relief Sunday but hasnt won since May
20. ``If you're the manager, you're supposed to come to me and tell
me. Call me into your office and tell me, `OK, we're going to make
a move.' That's fine. But that was a big surprise when (reporters)
came to me and told me what's going on. I didn't even know what
happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Team sources said Perez not only trashed the clubhouse after
being pulled after four innings in his last start, against
Pittsburgh, but he also got into a profanity-laced shouting match
with Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   __ Odds and ends: Left fielder Gary Sheffield returned to the
starting lineup after missing one game with a jammed right thumb. .
. . Utility player F.P. Santangelo served the last of his five-game
suspension Monday and is eligible for tonight's game against the
Cubs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-08-00 0151EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000808.0033 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 01:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5507 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-TEN-TENNIS-LADN-(SLAN     08-08 0568
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-TENNIS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHE STRUGGLES WITH A SMILE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICH HAMMOND  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANHATTAN BEACH, Calif. _ Alexandra Stevenson flashes an
easy-going smile, as every 19-year-old should, but the pleasant
facade masks the growing pains that have dominated not only her
tennis game, but also her life of the past 13 months.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other day I saw my friends who are in college, and I said,
`I feel about five years older than you guys,' '' Stevenson said
after defeating Silvija Talaja of Croatia 4-6, 6-4, 6-2 Monday in
the first round of the estyle.com Classic at Manhattan Country
Club.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're living in a different hotel every week . . . and
lugging your luggage around the airport. Everybody thinks it's
glamorous, and it's not. They think it's all limousines and
chocolate, and it's not.''
</P>
<P>
   Surely you remember Stevenson, the Wunderkind of the last year's
Wimbledon, the first female qualifier to reach the tournament's
semifinals and the center of a publicity firestorm after it was
learned she is the daughter of NBA Hall of Famer Julius Erving.
</P>
<P>
   Now, a year later, Stevenson is ranked 87th in the world after a
post-Wimbledon high of 36th. She tries desperately to be an
exceptional player on the court and a normal person off of it.
</P>
<P>
   She's putting off college to live her dream of being a
professional tennis player, and even though this year she has been
eliminated in the first round of 10 of her 19 tournaments and lost
in the second round at Wimbledon, Stevenson denies being
discouraged.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think tennis is about 90 percent mental,'' Stevenson said.
``It's important to focus hard on every point, and instead of being
up and down with every point, to just go through the entire match
on one level.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday's match was a step in that direction. Stevenson won the
first three games of the first set but had her serve broken three
of the next four times and lost the set.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the first set, I was very upset,'' Stevenson said. ``She
fought back and played hard, but I just made a lot of silly
mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   Stevenson went up a break at 3-2 to take control of the second
set and was never threatened in the third.
</P>
<P>
   Stevenson credited her strong play late in the match to improved
training, which she said has intensified over the past three weeks
in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   At 6-foot-1, Stevenson lacks the pure quickness of many of her
contemporaries and seeks to make up for that with power and
stamina.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've spent my whole life sitting in a classroom, not working
out all day,'' Stevenson said. ``These girls out here can get every
(shot) back, and they can stay out there all day. I want to stay
out there even longer.''
</P>
<P>
   Stevenson advances to face No. 4-seeded Conchita Martinez of
Spain, who had a first-round bye, in a second-round match probably
on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   In Monday's other first-round matches, Elena Dementieva of
Russia beat Nathalie Dechy 6-4, 4-6, 6-4; France's Anne-Gaelle
Sidot beat Ai Sugiyama of Japan 6-3, 6-4; and American Chanda Rubin
beat Julie Halard-Decugis of France 6-2, 6-1.
</P>
<P>
   Halard-Decugis, a finalist last year at Manhattan Beach, dropped
her first service attempt in each set and struggled to keep up with
Rubin's powerful ground strokes.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin, a finalist in 1995, advanced to face top-seeded Martina
Hingis in the second round.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-08-00 0157EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000808.0034 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 02:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5509 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f BC-BUILD-HUD-LADN     08-08 0533
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUILD-HUD-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CISNEROS, KAUFMAN AND BROAD TO DEVELOP NEW HOMES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREGORY J. WILCOX 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; Hoping to tap a well of urban pioneer spirit,
former Housing and Urban Development Secretary Henry Cisneros and
Westwood-based Kaufman and Broad Home Corp. on Monday formed a
joint venture to build new homes close to the core of some
metropolitan areas.
</P>
<P>
   The new venture, called American CityVista, will focus on infill
projects of homes that will be affordable to average-income
families. And the San Fernando Valley will likely be a key market.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will look at places like Reseda, San Fernando, Pacoima,
East Los Angeles, San Pedro and Long Beach,'' Cisneros said.
</P>
<P>
   Cisneros, 53, resigned as president and chief operating officer
of Los Angeles-based Univision Communications, parent company of
the nation's top Spanish-language television network, to
concentrate on the new venture. He served as HUD's chief during
President Clinton's first term and was a four-term mayor of San
Antonio, where the new company will be based. It will also have a
Los Angeles office and Cisneros will have a seat on Kaufman and
Broad's board.
</P>
<P>
   American CityVista will be jointly financed by the home builder
and Cisneros.
</P>
<P>
   The company will select sites and plan the tracts as well as buy
the land and build the homes.
</P>
<P>
   It should be in operation by September and will look for
building sites in 28 communities in California, Texas, Arizona,
Nevada and Colorado. The majority are in California.
</P>
<P>
   Infill development is commonplace now in many sections of the
Valley.
</P>
<P>
   But Cisneros said the new venture has a broad vision.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the differences here is the scale we're talking about.
We're trying to get (projects) of really substantial scale so we
can effectively create villages within the city, a critical mass of
citizens that can fight for good schools,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The housing will not be subsidized.
</P>
<P>
   Cisneros acknowledges that it may be easier to build this kind
of housing in other states.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, this is not going to be easy,'' he said. ``This is a
difficult challenge. The low-hanging fruit has been picked. The
sites to be developed on tend to be on the tougher side and there
are delays built into the entitlement process.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nationally, there is great momentum for new development in
central cities, and city leaders recognize that large-scale
homeownership provides community stability,'' Cisneros said.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles alone has a thirst for this type of housing: There
is a shortage of about 200,000 housing units across the county,
according to the Los Angeles County Economic Development Corp.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there is a big market,'' said Jack Kyser, chief
economist at the nonprofit group. ``There is just a real shortage
of affordable housing around the area. This looks like a very
interesting venture and I think people will probably be surprised
at the results they have.''
</P>
<P>
   Other California areas the company is eyeing include
Riverside/San Bernardino, Bakersfield, Anaheim, San Diego, Fresno,
Sacramento, Modesto and Stockton.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-08-00 0207EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000808.0035 </DOCNO>
