<HEADER>
A5511 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v PM-BUDGET-NYT     08-08 2373
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 PM-BUDGET-NYT 
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; For TUESDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Tuesday, Aug. 8.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-PAKISTAN (Undated) _ Behind President Clinton's blunt
warning last spring that South Asia was the world's most perilous
region lay an assessment from American intelligence agencies that
the likelihood of a war between India and Pakistan that could erupt
into a nuclear conflict had increased significantly, according to
officials with access to the secret intelligence. By Judith Miller
and James Risen.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   UNDERGROUND-TANKS (Hartford, Conn.) _ While private industry has
spent millions to meet a 1998 federal deadline to upgrade leaking
underground fuel tanks _ the nation's leading cause of groundwater
pollution _ state and local government agencies continue to operate
thousands of antiquated tanks in danger of leaking chemicals into
water supplies, records show. By Paul Zielbauer.
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH-TIMBER (Union Mills, N.C.) _ In a major shift, timber
companies have stepped up logging operations in the South, where
they face less regulation than in the carefully monitored forests
of the Pacific Northwest. Timber harvests in North Carolina,
Tennessee and 11 other Southern states increased by 50 percent from
1977 to 1997, according to the draft of a federal report. By
Douglas Jehl.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT20) has been sent to NYT photo clients. Map
has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CAMPAIGN _ (Moved in ``p'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   LIEBERMAN-ASSESS (Washington) _ News analysis: After struggling
mightily for two years to move out of President Clinton's shadow,
Vice President Al Gore, in a bold but risky choice of a running
mate, effectively thrusts Clinton and impeachment front and center
in the 2000 presidential campaign. By Richard L. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   LIEBERMAN-PROFILE (Undated) _ A man-in-the-news profile of Sen.
Joseph Lieberman. By Robert D. McFadden.
</P>
<P>
   LIEBERMAN-RECORD (Washington) _ In two terms in the Senate,
Joseph Lieberman has often taken positions at odds with Vice
President Al Gore and important constituencies of the Democratic
party on school vouchers, regulation of managed care, capital gains
taxes and product liability. But he sided with the Clinton
administration on all important budget votes, and unlike many other
Democrats, supported the administration's positions on trade and
welfare. His views are completely in tune with the vice president's
on abortion, the environment, gun control and gay rights. And he
usually supported the Clinton administration on foreign policy
issues. By David E. Rosenbaum.
</P>
<P>
   LIEBERMAN-RIGHT (Undated) _ In Sen. Joseph Lieberman, Al Gore
has managed to choose as his running mate an Orthodox Jew whom many
Christians _ and especially conservative evangelicals _ regard an
ally on many social and moral issues. Although he wears a yarmulke
on his head, Lieberman has been seen by some Christians as a
kindred spirit for his willingness to wear his religion on his
sleeve. His talk of the Talmud inspiring both his values and his
vote has often been cited by those Christians who believe the Bible
ought to guide public policy. By Laurie Goodstein.
</P>
<P>
   LIEBERMAN-CLINTON (Undated) _ In a Senate speech on Sept. 3,
1998, Sen. Joseph Lieberman sharply criticized President Clinton's
conduct in the Monica Lewinsky matter, but he voted against
impeaching the president, giving his reasons in a statement
released on Feb. 11, 1999. Exerpts from these two statements.
</P>
<P>
   GORE-ANNOUNCE (Undated) _ The Gore campaign is getting all the
publicity they can out of the selection of Joseph Lieberman as a
running mate. They're stretching it out over two days. By Peter
Marks.
</P>
<P>
   GET-OUT-THE-VOTE (Washington) _ Republicans say they will spend
a record $100 million on a get-out-the-vote operation this fall;
Democrats acknowledge they are likely to be well out spent, but are
looking to labor unions, the NAACP, abortion-rights and other
groups to gin up their core voters. By James Dao.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   VERIZON-WIRELESS (Undated) _ Want to watch public relations
executives from the nation's biggest communications companies get
uncomfortable? Ask them about their unions. ``Under the current
circumstances I think our executives would rather stay out of this,
so we're going to decline to get involved in this story,'' Burke
Stinson, an AT&AMP;T spokesman, said on the second full day of a strike
by 87,000 union workers at Verizon Communications. By Seth
Schiesel.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-SMALL-SHOPS (Machida City, Japan) _ Roughly 10 years have
passed since Japan began to dismantle the litany of licenses,
permits and other regulatory approvals that were long part of
breaking into business here. Under deregulation, competition has
grown, the number of stores has increased and Japanese consumers
now enjoy many of the same benefits as Americans in areas ranging
from convenience banking to the purchase of gasoline. But the
endangered shotengai, or local shopping district, has become a
rallying point against deregulation among Japanese who are worried
that they are destroying something precious. By Stephanie Strom.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   BLODGET-MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ Henry Blodget's words used to
add rocket fuel to the new economy. On Monday, Merrill Lynch's star
Internet analyst re-entered the atmosphere, downgrading 10 of the
26 companies he covers. Four months after the start of the April
bloodbath that halted the Internet's unfettered charge, one of the
most reliable of Internet bulls is finally showing signs of doubt.
By Danny Hakim.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   IMF-KOHLER (Washington) _ Poor nations are fighting a proposal
by the leading industrialized countries to raise the cost of
borrowing from the International Monetary Fund and the World Bank,
dealing a blow to Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers' campaign to
change the lending agencies. By Joseph Kahn.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-AD-COLUMN (Undated) _ In its annual forecast, Veronis
Suhler, the investment banking firm, predicted that the popularity
of the Internet as an advertising and information medium would
continue to increase rapidly in the short term, though not to the
exclusion of more traditional media like magazines and newspapers.
The firm's 14th annual communications industry forecast, released
on Monday, found that total advertiser spending grew 9.1 percent,
to $165 billion, last year; it expects spending to grow 8.6 percent
annually, climbing to $249.1 billion in 2004. By Jane L. Levere.
</P>
