<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 02:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5513 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBN-DODGER2-LADN-(SLA     08-08 0656
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGER2-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    ... WRITETHRU 
DODGERS LOSE TO ANOTHER PATSY
</HEADLINE>
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Ah, the soft part of the schedule. You know, the
Philadelphia Phillies,the Milwaukee Brewers, the Chicago Cubs. The
teams good teams beat.
</P>
<P>
   If Pittsburgh didn't throw a wrench into the situation by losing
two of three, think where the Los Angeles Dodgers would be.
</P>
<P>
   As it is, the Dodgers' so-called easy portion of the schedule is
proving to be nothing of the sort as losses to anemic teams mount.
The latest was the 7-3 defeat to the Cubs in the opener of a
three-game series Monday at Dodger Stadium in which rookie Matt
Herges pitched well in his first major-league start, then
eloquently laid out the Dodgers' travails.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in the thick of it and as I've said before, and maybe it
offended people, but these are teams we should beat up on and we're
not,'' Herges said after allowing three runs in six innings.
``Right now we have to be winning. If we want to be there in the
end, which we all believe we can, games like this are definitely .
. . definitely frustrating.''
</P>
<P>
   Herges was outpitched by Cubs rookie Ruben Quevedo, who earned
his first major-league victory. Quevedo (1-3) allowed seven hits in
a complete-game win as the Dodgers (58-53) dropped their third
straight.
</P>
<P>
   Since winning three of four at Colorado and being poised to make
a run at first place in the National League West, the Dodgers have
dropped six of 10 to the Phillies, Pirates, Brewers and Cubs. That
quartet entered Monday a combined 56 games below .500.
</P>
<P>
   Cubs right fielder Sammy Sosa led off the ninth with a towering
homer to right-center field. It was his 35th of the season, tying
him with the Dodgers' Gary Sheffield for the major-league lead.
</P>
<P>
   Former Dodgers leadoff man Eric Young, who's had a public feud
with Dodgers manager Davey Johnson, went 3 for 4 with a walk and
scored twice in his return to Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always love coming back to L.A.,'' Young said. ``This is
where I started. It's always special to come back here. It was good
to get on base. I was trying to put the pressure on.''
</P>
<P>
   Herges (8-1) was inserted into the starting rotation after a
magnificent four months in the bullpen. But when lefty Carlos Perez
had trouble in his last two starts, it was Herges to whom Johnson
turned.
</P>
<P>
   Herges' eight-game winning streak equaled the best start by a
Dodgers pitcher since Fernando Valenzuela began the 1981 season
8-0, and was the longest by a Dodger since Pedro Martinez won eight
straight in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs took a 3-1 lead in the third inning on Ricky
Gutierrez's two-run triple and a sacrifice fly by Mark Grace, but
it was reliever Antonio Osuna who was pounded. He allowed four runs
in three innings as the Cubs stretched a 3-2 lead after six innings
to a 7-3 win thanks to a two-run homer by Gutierrez in the seventh,
a run-scoring single by Young in the eighth and Sosa's homer in the
ninth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Osuna, I don't know what his problem was,'' Johnson said. ``He
didn't throw the ball the way he did all year. That's one of the
few times the bullpen hadn't kept us right there, and our offense
is sluggish.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers gave Herges a 1-0 lead in the first inning when Tom
Goodwin scored on Mark Grudzielanek's double to the
right-center-field gap, but it could have been more. Grudzielanek
went to third on Quevedo's errant pick-off throw but was thrown out
at the plate on Gary Sheffield's bouncer back to the mound.
Compounding the blunder was that Grudzielanek didn't stay in a
rundown and Sheffield was tagged out heading to second.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to say we let down after that, but it was kind
of like, 'We could have scored 10 this inning,' '' Herges said.
``That's how we felt in the dugout. We were pumped. I can't say it
affected us too much, but maybe it did.''
</P>
</TEXT>
