<DOCNO> NYT20000808.0039 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 10:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5597 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-TECH-LAYOFFS-ART-BOS &LR;      08-08 1874
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-LAYOFFS-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 DOT.COM FIRMS' LAYOFFS FOSTER NEW CORPORATE CULTURE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX PHAM AND STEPHANIE STOUGHTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mimi Bloom shrugged off her recent layoff from SmartPlanet, a
San Francisco start-up that offers classes over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The 35-year-old graduate of Harvard University and the
Massachusetts Institute of Technology was let go after just eight
months on the job, but she is planning to go to work for another
start-up.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the second time I've been laid off,'' said Bloom, who had
also lost a job three years ago in New York. ``The first time
around, it felt much more shameful. The general public wasn't as
aware of the dot-com world and the risks you have to take being in
that world. I definitely felt I had more explaining to do then.
Now, it's considered common.''
</P>
<P>
   There's a practical reason for this newly casual attitude toward
layoffs: To encourage the kind of risk-taking needed to spur
entrepreneurs to hack away repeatedly at the American Dream,
failures must be easily forgiven.
</P>
<P>
   And, increasingly, they are. ``There's no such thing as blood on
a resume,'' said Ann Peckenpaugh, a veteran recruiter for
Schweichler &AMP; Associates in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, it's no longer unusual, especially in Silicon Valley,
for technology workers to change jobs within two years or less.
</P>
<P>
   In a sense, this unsentimental new attitude is a response to the
massive corporate layoffs of the late 1980s and early 1990s, which
left hundreds of thousands of workers stranded and disillusioned.
Today, there are no hard feelings, because job opportunities abound
and workers no longer feel they have to stick with a company until
retirement.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't mean all the rules have been chucked out the
window.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though there's lots of opportunity, it still doesn't feel
good'' to be laid off, said Paul Angeli, who in May lost his job at
Petstore.com in Emeryville, Calif. ``On the other hand, this isn't
devastating either. Sometimes you win, and sometimes you lose.
That's the name of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Peckenpaugh recalled a piece of advice she got from Tom Perkins
of the Kleiner Perkins Caufield &AMP; Byers, Silicon Valley's top-tier
venture capital firm: ``It is to a certain extent in the best
interest of venture capitalists to encourage people to keep trying,
to not be afraid of failure. We need people to take a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, it's not whether you fail, but whether you
ultimately succeed.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, failure is ``a badge of honor,'' said Amy Vernetti who
is a ``human capitalist'' for Garage.com, a venture capital
investment bank in Palo Alto, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's OK to have a failure on your record,'' Vernetti said.
``Mistakes are how you learn.''
</P>
<P>
   What has Bloom learned from working at companies that have
failed? That ``anything can change on a dime,'' Bloom said. ``And
you need to be prepared for it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   These days, in the dot-com world, the game is fast-paced,
brutally intense, and exhilirating. And that's what is drawing
people like Derek Regier.
</P>
<P>
   Regier left his job with Nortel Networks Corp. in Dallas a year
ago. He had climbed the corporate ranks of the telecommunications
equipment company, but he dreaded the meetings. As executives
droned on, Regier kept his sanity by reading e-mail messages,
planning his weekly agenda, and mapping out his own company
strategies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would have meetings to plan meetings,'' the 29-year-old
executive said. ``We would have meetings to agree on the process of
decision-making at future meetings. We would have meetings to make
the decision.''
</P>
<P>
   When Regier left Nortel for the world of technology start-ups,
he knew the risks would be much higher. But he also knew he would
be more comfortable working at Internet speed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted high risk, high reward,'' said Regier, now senior
vice president of business development for Allmystuff Inc., an
enterprise software company in Austin, Texas. ``I didn't feel I
would get that in a corporate environment.''
</P>
<P>
   Allmystuff was not Regier's first Internet start-up. He had
previously worked for Cozone.com, a Marlborough, Mass. online store
for CompUSA.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was extremely fast-paced,'' he said. ``We launched in
October and had $7.5 million in sales in our first quarter.
Decisions were made quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Cozone collapsed in March. Regier said he was disappointed but
did not regret the move, which taught him how to launch an Internet
company in a short time.
</P>
<P>
   This is a typical day at his current employer: Attend a quick 8
a.m. meeting at Allmystuff's headquarters. Fly to Dallas to meet
customers and partners, and take a recruit out to dinner. Fly back
to Austin and rush to the office to answer e-mail messages. Arrive
home at 1 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Regier says he has never been happier with his career. And the
risks in this fast-moving world, he adds, do not seem to be as high
as everyone thinks.
</P>
<P>
   Even if a dot-com fails, ``your valuation skyrockets anyway,
because you have that experience,'' he said. ``And you never would
have had that experience if you hadn't left the security blanket of
your existing environment for a more dynamic environment.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Because dot-coms and their business plans can morph at any
moment, workers must also move fast, often putting aside any
company loyalty.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more job-hopping you do, the more experience you get,''
said Brent Durst, a Web site producer who was laid off a month ago
from HealthCentral.com after nine months at the Emeryville company.
``It's OK as long as you're getting the skills you want.''
</P>
<P>
   Durst recalled that the woman who had recruited him to
HealthCentral.com left soon after he was hired. ``There's just a
lot of turnover,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Many recruiters agree that churn is a major part of the
technology workplace today.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's out of control, especially here in the Valley,'' said
Jack Van Berkel, vice president of human resources for Netigy
Corp., an e-commerce consulting firm in San Jose, Calif. ``People
jump jobs incredibly fast.''
</P>
<P>
   In Silicon Valley, there is a joke that people can change jobs
without having to tell their families; they simply drive off in
another direction the following Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
   The attitude is encouraged by a similarly nonchalant view by
companies that euphemistically refer to layoffs as ``reducing burn
rate'' _ that is, reducing the rate at which the company is burning
through its cash, according to Vernetti.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, that attitude toward employment is taken by a
typically younger class of workers than those who were laid off a
decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are some of the youngest people in the industry,'' said
Peckenpaugh. ``In the past, it's been middle-aged men with
retirements at stake and kids in college. They've had a much harder
time dealing with a layoff. It's a lot easier for younger people.
They know they can just spring right back. They also didn't come in
with the expectation that they would put the best years of their
life into the company and retire.''
</P>
<P>
   As Durst, 30, said of his layoff, ``It wasn't such a big deal.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, a huge part of the reason why workers can take
layoffs so casually is because they know there are plenty of other
jobs awaiting them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reality is that the second someone is laid off, they have
five other opportunities to look at,'' Vernetti said.
</P>
<P>
   Some recruiters routinely scan for news of troubled dot-coms, in
hopes they can lure away workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The demand for technology talent is immense,'' said Van
Berkel, whose company has more than 100 openings. ``The
unemployment rate for technology-related fields is essentially
negative because there are more jobs than people to fill those
positions. So what happens is employees of companies being laid off
get attacked by search firms.''
</P>
<P>
   Smart recruiters don't wait for the layoff notices. They begin
recruiting as soon as they start picking up vibes of financial
trouble at a company, Peckenpaugh said.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be frank, by the time the layoffs hit the papers, these
people have already been approached, and some have already lined up
their next job,'' she said. ``It's not quite as easy as shooting
fish in a barrel.''
</P>
<P>
   After Cozone folded, Regier received a multitude of offers from
both established technology companies and dot-coms.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good to be loved,'' Regier said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's not as if all the old rules are irrelevant. On the East
Coast, especially, traditions die hard.
</P>
<P>
   Take Josef Blumenfeld, a public relations executive, who lost
his job at Cozone. He jumped to DriverFX.com, a Maynard, Mass.
start-up in the automotive accessories market. After a major
partner pulled its support, DriverFX.com slammed on the brakes in
June.
</P>
<P>
   In an all-too-familiar scene, the company's chief executive
asked Blumenfeld and other employees to gather around. Then he
launched into his farewell speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``I literally started to cackle,'' Blumenfeld said. ``I thought,
`Oh great! More worthless options!' ''
</P>
<P>
   For a brief moment in his days of unemployment, Blumenfeld
considered leaping to another dot-com. Then he remembered the stack
of business cards he had collected in his travels from companies
that no longer existed.
</P>
<P>
   In July, Blumenfeld opted to take a position with Concord
Communications, a fast-growing but more mature technology company
in Marlborough.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want stock options,'' he said. ``I want health
insurance.''
</P>
<P>
   Economists and job-placement firms say they are not surprised by
Blumenfeld's reaction. Even with the local boom in Internet
start-ups, Massachusetts employees have long been more conservative
than their job-hopping counterparts out West.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is somewhat less job switching in Boston than in Silicon
Valley,'' said Sara Johnson, chief regional economist for Standard
&AMP; Poor's DRI. ``I think there's more of a standard of company
loyalty in Boston, whereas job switching is the norm in Silicon
Valley.''
</P>
<P>
   Some recruiters in the Boston area seem to look down on dot-com
job-hoppers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stay focused on ones that are successful,'' said Ed Takacs,
chief executive of HighTech Ventures, a Cambridge, Mass. recruiting
firm.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Fraize, who lost his job when Internet retailer
Toysmart.com collapsed this spring, said he has no desire to jump
from job to job. The high-risk, high-rewards game, he said, is not
for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm scared to death of not working,'' said Fraize, who now has
a job as a design developer for Event Zero in Woburn, Mass. ``I
have bills to pay.''
</P>
<P>
   But even in Silicon Valley, labor is not entirely
``frictionless.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You've dedicated your time and focus to helping a company
succeed,'' Angeli said. ``You're tied into that success with stock
options. So the employee loses when a company fails. You have to
start all over again. I don't think the fields are totally green.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Alex Pham reported from Emeryville, Calif., and Stephanie Stoughton
reported from Boston.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
