<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-ROUNDUP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
E-COMMERCE: PRIVATE MATTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEPHANIE STOUGHTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was supposed to work like Good Housekeeping's seal of
approval. A TRUSTe logo on a Web site would reassure consumers that
their personal information would be safe from prying eyes.
</P>
<P>
   But critics say online privacy seal programs such as TRUSTe,
which includes 2,000 sites as members, provide little protection
for consumers who leave their tracks on Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   TRUSTe's opponents grew more vocal after Toysmart.com, a
Waltham, Mass. online seller of toys, collapsed in May and tried to
auction off data that included customers' names, addresses,
shopping preferences, and children's birthdays. Toysmart.com was a
TRUSTe member and had promised its shoppers it would never sell
their information to a third party.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesman Dave Steer noted that TRUSTe contacted the Federal
Trade Commission after hearing about Toysmart.com's plans to sell
the data. ``I think we've been very firm and clear,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gomez Advisors Inc. of Lincoln, Mass. has become a high-profile
reviewer of consumer Web sites. But lately, the critic has been
facing criticism.
</P>
<P>
   In April, several Web sites that ranked low on the company's
lists challenged Gomez to disclose its rating criteria. Last month,
Realty Times, an online real estate news service based in Dallas,
joined the fray. Reporter Blanche Evans called the latest Gomez
survey of home-buying sites ``a mess.''
</P>
<P>
   Evans quoted sources as saying employees worked under one-week
deadlines to produce the ratings. In some cases, she wrote, Gomez
analysts fell short of researching the more than 150 criteria
points that consumers were promised.
</P>
<P>
   ``The site also seems confused by its own grading criteria,
nit-picking over the inclusion of 800 numbers for some sites while
overlooking glaring feature omissions such as listings,'' Evans
wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Alex Stein, an executive vice president at Gomez, said Web sites
sometimes do not have features such as 800 numbers before Gomez's
cut-off date _ though they may have added them at a later date.
Gomez does not have one-week deadlines and ``we do take into
account the number of listings,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Stein suggested that that Gomez has been attacked more than
rivals because of its rigorous reviews of thousands of sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our ratings matter,'' Stein said. ``They matter to consumers.
They matter to the industry.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Many Internet surfers click first on search engines such as
AltaVista and Lycos to help them locate Web sites and data on
subjects ranging from illnesses to appliances.
</P>
<P>
   But they often don't look past the first few pages of matches,
forcing Web site managers to scramble for position.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're not found in the Top 30 to 50 matches, you have
built a billboard in the woods,'' said Fredrick Marckini, chief
executive of Iprospect.com in Arlington, Mass. ``No one will find
you. No one will come.''
</P>
<P>
   Marckini's company has emerged as a sort of real estate broker
in the search-engine world, helping clients such as Sharp
Electronics and Carpartsonsale.com scale the rankings.
</P>
<P>
   Iprospect.com employees know major search engines have varying
ways to determine a site's relevance based on keywords. They make
sure that keywords used to describe a client's site are the same
ones that Web surfers type on search engines. In Sharp's case, the
retailer had not moved fast enough to secure the sharp.com address
on the World Wide Web. And at the search engines, Internet users
had trouble locating the company's sharp-usa.com site.
</P>
<P>
   Today, a Web user can type ``Sharp'' and ``microwave'' in
Lycos's search box _ and the first listing pops up as Sharp
Electronics. ``Seriously, that did not happen before,'' said Mark
Pusateri, Sharp's interactive marketing manager.
</P>
</TEXT>
