<SLUG> BC-TECH-AUDIOMINING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUDIOMINING: COMING INTO ITS OWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; BURLINGTON, Mass. _ If you're among the millions of Americans
whose work calls for attending industry conferences and
conventions, you may have noticed recently that a vast number of
sessions and speeches get recorded or videotaped.
</P>
<P>
   But did you ever wonder who, beyond desperate insomniacs, ever
goes back to watch or listen to executives droning on about some
obscure new realm of the profession or the technology?
</P>
<P>
   Now there's a faster way. Imagine you didn't get to attend the
Potato Processing International Exposition but were eager to find
out if anyone had insights into how, say, the wireless Net is
expected to affect the production of French fries.
</P>
<P>
   With a new service developed by the former Dragon Systems unit
of Lernout &AMP; Hauspie, you could go to the potato processors' Web
site and search conference video clips posted there to see if any
speaker uttered the phrase ``wireless Internet'' during the
proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   Up would pop a graphic showing, let's say, the five occasions on
which three different speakers mentioned the vaunted wireless Net.
With a point and click and the right RealPlayer version installed,
you could play back those video segments on your computer, starting
about five seconds before the actual phrase so you understood the
context.
</P>
<P>
   After years of development and promises, speech recognition
technology has finally emerged as viable, aided by ever more
powerful computer chips to decode spoken words.
</P>
<P>
   Exemplifying the trend was last week's initial public offering
for SpeechWorks International of Boston that valued the company at
a dizzying $1.6 billion. SpeechWorks makes voice-prompt systems
that allow you to do things like use your voice to order 100 shares
of a stock, or ask the arrival time of an airline flight and hear
the answer spoken back to you.
</P>
<P>
   The phrase-searching product offered by Lernout, the Belgian
speech-recognition company with North American headquarters in
Burlington, is part of a new application for speech technology
called ``audiomining,'' or using speech recognition to index video
and audio tapes and glean facts from them.
</P>
<P>
   For now, Lernout offers the product only as a service where you
pay the company as little as $300 per hour of tape to convert it
into a searchable database, plus the cost of hosting it on a Web
page so people can log in and search it.
</P>
<P>
   Lernout's main customer to date is PlexisNet Broadcasting, which
uses the technology for clients such as trade-show organizers and a
company that tapes every hearing on Capitol Hill. Some trade show
and conference organizers, in fact, have found there is a huge new
revenue source in selling search access to conference proceedings
for people who couldn't attend.
</P>
<P>
   By next year, said Robin Gaynor, the product line manager,
Lernout hopes to have an off-the-shelf product people could buy and
use themselves to put searchable video and audio tapes on their Web
sites. In the current version, it takes about two hours to process
one hour of videotape into a searchable archive, basically by
playing it back on a recorder hooked up to a desktop computer.
</P>
<P>
   Right now it is pretty remarkable technology, with some obvious
limitations. It works off a vocabulary of only about 60,000 words,
so if you want to be able to search a tape for people's names or
obscure technological jargon, you have to give Lernout a list of
those special index words before it processes the tape.
</P>
<P>
   (In one recent trial, for example, the system decided the name
of Iraqi Foreign Minister Tariq Aziz was actually ``to read
disease.'')
</P>
<P>
   In our own playing with it, we found the system also does much
better at finding a phrase such as ``manufacturing inventory'' than
``big heart'' _ although it did find occurrences of the admittedly
obscure word ``recusal'' in a soporific congressional hearing we
scanned.
</P>
<P>
   You also have to bear in mind that a videotape of a trade-show
speech will be much lower quality than, say, an ABC News broadcast,
and thus it may be much harder to precisely identify a word or
phrase and find it in a search.
</P>
<P>
   One of Lernout's few competitors in this market, Silicon Valley
streaming-video provider Virage, which uses IBM speech technology,
has done several video-indexing deals with TV networks including
ABC and CNN. But Lernout thinks there's still a big unserved market
for services aimed at sub-broadcast-quality video or audio.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never know what we are going to get here for recording
quality, so it's been developed to be speech recognition that you
can really pound on,'' Gaynor said.
</P>
<P>
   The same technology behind the video product is being applied by
Lernout for what is called ``phonemining,'' or processing thousands
of hours of calls into a customer care center to glean information
such as product popularity. And coming soon could be a Lernout
product where you could record, transcribe, and index your
company's conference calls.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-08-00 1036EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
