<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-WALMART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAL-MART WANTS NEW WEB LOOK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEPHANIE STOUGHTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jeanne Jackson brought a lusterless Banana Republic back into
fashion. And she pushed Banana Republic and its parent company, Gap
Inc., to Internet success.
</P>
<P>
   But can she wave that magic wand a third time to turn unwieldly
Wal-Mart.com into the real Wal-Mart of the Web before Christmas?
</P>
<P>
   ``We know we have a lot of work to do,'' acknowledged Jackson,
chief executive of Wal-Mart.com Inc., which has tapped Sapient
Corp. of Cambridge, Mass. to help it revamp its clunky Web site.
</P>
<P>
   After disappointing sales online, Wal-Mart Stores Inc., the
world's largest retailer, announced early this year that it would
set up a separate company for its Web site. The Internet operation
in Palo Alto, Calif., is jointly owned by Wal-Mart and Accel
Partners, a venture capital firm in the Silicon Valley.
</P>
<P>
   In March, Wal-Mart.com hired Jackson, former chief executive of
Banana Republic, to add some pizazz and Internet savvy to the site.
</P>
<P>
   Under Jackson, the company purchased Homewarehouse.com, a robust
site that will serve as Wal-Mart.com's platform. The company also
has been quietly working with Sapient, a technology consulting firm
and systems integrator, to improve its Web site design and
navigational tools.
</P>
<P>
   The last time Wal-Mart redesigned its site, it worked with
consultant Cambridge Technology Partners Inc. and several other
technology firms. But Wal-Mart executives were unhappy with the
site's debut in January, and the retailer is no longer working with
Cambridge Technology.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say Sapient ranks among the top companies now building
Web sites. And so far, it has avoided having its name attached to
Web disasters by making sure its clients understand ``when
something makes sense _ and when it doesn't,'' said Christine
Overby, an analyst with Forrester Research.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Wal-Mart.com and Sapient have their work cut out for
them.
</P>
<P>
   The site has received harsh reviews from both consumers and
analysts who complain that it's hard to navigate and contains scant
product information. Wal-Mart.com did not even make Media Metrix's
Top 25 e-commerce sites in June, the latest rankings available.
</P>
<P>
   ``Currently, we do not believe we are giving our customers the
level of service that they deserve'' online, said Melissa
Berryhill, a Wal-Mart spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   Berryhill said Wal-Mart.com also needs to improve its
fulfillment operations. Fingerhut Companies Inc. now fills orders
for the site. But Wal-Mart.com appears to be exerting more control
over its back-end operations. Last week, Wal-Mart announced plans
to build a distribution center in Georgia to handle Internet
orders.
</P>
<P>
   While Wal-Mart has struggled, its rivals have taken the lead.
Amazon.com Inc. has emerged as the Internet's biggest retailer,
selling books, music, dishwashers, and tools.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Wal-Mart.com and other stragglers will be playing
catch-up at a time when the rate of consumers coming online is
slowing. ``The chances to acquire new consumers and dictate their
buying patterns are getting fewer and fewer,'' said Jon Frey, a
Sapient manager who works with the firm's retail clients. ``This is
a big holiday season to get that customer base established so you
have a critical mass of consumers going forward.''
</P>
<P>
   One problem with Wal-Mart.com and other online sites is that
they were designed for men, Frey said. Now that women are taking
over many online shopping decisions, much as they do on the ground,
Wal-Mart.com needs to tweak its Web pages.
</P>
<P>
   Research shows that women prefer to browse stores and enjoy the
experience of shopping _ and the same trends have applied to
cyberspace. Men are surgical buyers. They want to make their
purchases and leave.
</P>
<P>
   Wal-Mart offers an impressive 600,000 items on its site. But
analysts say the retailer has had a tough time bringing its mantra
_ ``always low prices'' _ to the Web.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is little reason to go back to their site,'' said Steve
Wolin, a principal with Mercer Management Consulting in Boston.
``They are stuck in the world of competing on price _ and they're
not terribly good at that online right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, many of the items stocked on Wal-Mart.com's shelves seem
to belong in the big outlets _ not in the online store.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after Jackson arrived at Wal-Mart.com, an employee informed
her of a 25-cent plastic glass offered on the Web site. Also for
sale on the site are felt-tip pens for a dollar each that cost
about $5 to ship. ``All you have to do is do the mathematics and it
doesn't make sense,'' Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson said she hopes to decrease the number of items sold on
the site, including merchandise that shoppers are more likely to
buy in stores than they are online.
</P>
<P>
   The Gap, for instance, discovered that leather clothing sold at
a surprisingly fast rate online.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes sense,'' Jackson said. ``You're going to spend a
certain amount to ship the goods. And $7 to $8 to ship a $300
leather jacket makes a lot more sense than spending $7 to $8 to
ship a T-shirt.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-08-00 1037EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
