<DOCNO> NYT20000808.0044 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 10:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5602 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-TECH-VENTURE-BOS &LR;      08-08 0756
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-VENTURE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BANKS FIND PROFITS IN FILLING DEBT GAP FOR START-UPS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BETH HEALY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; What's the first thing a start-up does when it lands a big
chunk of money from venture capitalists?
</P>
<P>
   It hires a banker.
</P>
<P>
   Even in this age where equity is king, bankers are enjoying the
growth of a multimillion-dollar debt business that's sprouted up
alongside high-tech deal flow. They manage venture assets, both for
venture firms and for entrepreneurs. And they lend money to
start-ups that have secured venture backing, to finance things such
as computers and real estate leases, and to bridge brief
stress-filled gaps between VC rounds.
</P>
<P>
   That may sound risky, compared with lending to established
companies. But there's built-in protection you don't find in
typical loans: deep-pocketed VCs. And there's some equity upside,
in the form of warrants.
</P>
<P>
   ``By traditional banking standards, these loans would be
considered high risk,'' says Diane Russell, a BankBoston leveraged
buyout chief in the mid-1980s who started a Boston lending office
for Los Angeles-based Imperial Bank five years ago. But there's
less speculation involved than you think, she says.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, Imperial gets to keep a closer eye on its clients
than most banks do, because it typically manages their cash
accounts.
</P>
<P>
   The bank earns fees for managing those millions of dollars in
cash. And when it makes loans (priced as other business loans,
based on the prime rate) it's first in line to be repaid. Sometimes
the bank can tap the venture capitalists if the start-up runs out
of money. There's also collateral in the form of computer equipment
or intellectual property.
</P>
<P>
   But there are more successes than sob stories lately, despite
the difficulties some e-commerce companies have faced since April.
</P>
<P>
   Imperial recently feted one of its winners at the Van Gogh
exhibit at Boston's Museum of Fine Arts. Variagenics Inc., a
Cambridge, Mass. company involved in genomics and drug
personalization, got $1.2 million in loans from the bank, on top of
about $51 million in venture capital. It went public two weeks ago
and its shares have surged 94 percent to $27.125.
</P>
<P>
   That kind of stock pop is part of what makes this business more
profitable than standard lending, Russell said. Imperial takes
warrants with certain loans, giving it the right to buy a percent
or two of a client's stock for as little as a penny per share. With
$7 billion of assets, Imperial has amassed warrants in several
hundred companies, Russell says.
</P>
<P>
   Entrepreneurs tap banks to avoid giving away more of their
company than they have to. Say the venture firms provide $5 million
and get a 25 percent ownership stake in a start-up in return. The
founder, by taking a $1 million loan, then has $6 million to put to
work without giving away a bigger slice of the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why you go out and get the cheaper money from the bank
instead of expensive money from venture capitalists,'' says Bob
Garrow, chief of Citizens Capital, the venture arm of Citizens
Bank.
</P>
<P>
   On the flip side, young unprofitable companies typically can't
get loans without venture backing. Garrow and other VCs often send
entrepreneurs to institutions like Imperial and Silicon Valley
Bank, a pioneer in the field with $5.4 billion of assets. Banks
such as FleetBoston tend to get involved at later stages.
</P>
<P>
   Staying close to the venture capitalists is key to the bankers,
Russell says. For one thing, the VCs deliver most of the business.
And if a venture firm is turning lukewarm on a portfolio company,
that's a warning sign for the bank, she says.
</P>
<P>
   She concedes some loans have been revisited since the stock
market plummeted in April and venture money in realms like
e-tailing dried up. But the flow of new deals is vast, she says,
and likely to continue as long as there's money to back new
companies.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, despite the industry's fears, activity did not slow in
the second quarter. According to the National Venture Capital
Association, a record 1,695 companies nationwide got funding in the
period, up from 1,627 deals in the first quarter. They received
$24.58 billion, down from the fourth-quarter peak of $25.17
billion, but up 96 percent from a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Says Russell: ``There are unlimited amounts of capital right now
feeding this community.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Beth Healy is a member of the Globe's staff. She can be reached
by e-mail at bhealy(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
