<HEADER>
A5604 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-TECH-ICET-BOS &LR;      08-08 0772
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-ICET-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RECORD LABELS, POST-NAPSTER? AN ICE-COLD VIEW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX PHAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; LOS ANGELES _ Most people know Ice-T as the in-your-face
gangsta rapper who exploded on the American political and musical
scene in 1992 with his song ``Cop Killer.''
</P>
<P>
   Less celebrated is the fact that he is a now a bona fide
Internet entrepreneur. Ice, as his friends like to call him, is
starting CoronerRecords.com, an online label for up-and-coming
musicians.
</P>
<P>
   In his new capacity, Ice, a.k.a. Tracy Morrow, last week sat on
a panel on ``The Future of Music,'' sponsored by Red Herring
magazine. Clad in a blue and red Hawaiian shirt, white sneakers and
a navel-length gold chain and matching pinkie ring, he looked out
of place next to his fellow music industry executives, who favored
sports jackets and loafers.
</P>
<P>
   The discussion inevitably gravitated towards Napster, the
Internet sensation that lets music fans swap songs for free and is
threatening the multibillion-dollar record industry. While other
panelists talked about ``bandwidth'' and ``portability,'' Ice took
a philosophical approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of businesses get put out of business by other
businesses,'' he ruminated. ``It's about evolution.''
</P>
<P>
   The way Ice sees it, Napster is stealing from the record
industry, which is stealing from artists like himself.
</P>
<P>
   Ice, who grew up in South Central Los Angeles after his parents
were killed in an auto accident, has an entirely pragmatic
philosophy based on survival.
</P>
<P>
   So while he compares major record labels to ``gangsters,'' he is
also among the musicians that have joined the record industry in a
copyright infringement lawsuit against Napster Inc., the San Mateo,
Calif., company that distributes the swapping software over the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   He also thinks the lawsuit is futile.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't stop technology,'' he said. ``Five years from now,
Napster will morph into something even more devastating. The world
is now an open book. There's a cyberwar coming. Technology is
coming in a mean way. The artist has to figure out a way to get
ahead of it, 'cause it's gonna get real crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   His solution? If you can't beat 'em, join 'em. Over the past
year, he's been experimenting with the Internet, developing his own
Web site (MCIceT.com), producing music videos that can be viewed
only on the Internet, and selling his music through the online
music label, AtomicPop.com.
</P>
<P>
   His latest effort involves CoronerRecords.com, an online music
label he has launched with his own money. Like AtomicPop,
CoronerRecords seeks to represent artists who want to distribute
their music online. Because digital distribution and promotion is
viewed as much cheaper than the traditional model of selling
compact discs in stores, online labels can make money on smaller
volumes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to create a business model where you can sell 3,000
records and get a check,'' he explained, adding that this is a way
for ``small cats'' to make money from selling mail-order CDs online
or from sales of downloaded music.
</P>
<P>
   These small cats are unlikely to make big-time money on
downloaded music, however, at least in the near future.
Notwithstanding that fans can get songs for free by using Napster,
selling digitally downloaded music has not caught on with consumers
because it's still hard for people to get the music out of their
computer and into their stereos, according to Ice-T, who said most
of his sales continue to be in the form of CDs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hardware needs to catch up to the software,'' he said.
That will happen, and when it does, the 40-year-old hip hop artist
said he plans to be ready.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ice-T is one of those artists who get it,'' said P.J. McNealy,
senior analyst with the Gartner Group. ``CDs as we know it are
going away. The ability for music fans to sample tracks on the Web
is huge. It all leads to people downloading single tracks vs.
having to buy an entire album.''
</P>
<P>
   Ice's status as media executive is likely to beg the question
from fans: Is this the same musician whose persistently provocative
lyrics have earned the enmity of law enforcement activists,
feminists, and politicians? Has Ice lost his edge?
</P>
<P>
   Unlikely. The rap artist still sees himself as a hard-core
subverter. CoronerRecords gets its name because he thinks
traditional record labels will perish in the new digital
millennium. In the end, only the coroner survives.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet is where the action is,'' he said. ``If we can't
sell music there, we'll figure something else out. We go rob a bank
or something.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
