<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 10:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5605 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-TECH-SONUS-ART-BOS &LR;      08-08 2069
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-SONUS-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 SONUS EXECUTIVES LOOK TO LONG TERM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WESTFORD, Mass. _ One Friday afternoon almost exactly three
years ago, Rubin Gruber was eating a pizza with his cousin when he
finally got talked into pursuing an idea that has turned out to be
worth more than $12 billion: Sonus Networks.
</P>
<P>
   Sonus, which makes advanced voice and data telecommunications
switches for phone companies, has been one of the region's hottest
public offerings this year. It soared in value 900 percent in its
first 40 trading days before slipping, as of Friday evening to a
mere $195 over its $23-a-share offering price.
</P>
<P>
   Already, in fact, there's a little skepticism among industry
analysts and short sellers who think that the 290-person business
may be a great new company _ but not possibly as great as Wall
Street's valuation suggests.
</P>
<P>
   Three summers ago, Gruber, one of the classic ``serial
entrepreneurs'' of the Interstate 495 belt, had taken what he
thought was going to be a wonderful early retirement at age 52. But
he came to two painful realizations: ``I found out I didn't like to
play golf, and serving on boards was the most boring thing in the
world.''
</P>
<P>
   Gruber, whose past companies include Videoserver (now Ezenia),
Davox, and Cambridge Telecommunications, was sitting at New London
Style Pizza in Concord talking over life with his cousin when he
got going about what he was convinced would be the next big thing
in telecommunications: transmitting voice calls by converting them
into Internet-style data packets.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first time I have seen you
</P>
<P>
   really excited about doing something in a year,'' Gruber
recounts his cousin saying. ``Why don't you do this?''
</P>
<P>
   What happened next sounds too easy to be true. Gruber pulled out
his cell phone on the spot, called a venture capital friend at
Bessemer Venture Partners, and gave him a three-minute rundown of
the idea. The VC instantly agreed to fund it.
</P>
<P>
   Within months, partners at other local firms including Matrix
Partners and Charles River Ventures had persuaded Gruber to team up
with another area entrepreneur who had some similar ideas, Michael
Hluchjy (pronounced Ha-LOOG-ee), a data networking star who holds a
Massachusetts Institute of Technology doctorate.
</P>
<P>
   Sonus Networks, whose name comes from the Latin word for sound,
was born and funded in the fall 1997. A year later, it brought in
as chief executive Hassan M. Ahmed, a former top executive with
Cascade Communications, a now-legendary foundry of local telecom
talent. Alumni of Cascade, now a part of Lucent Technologies,
include the founders of Sycamore Networks in Chelmsford and a
passel of other area start-ups.
</P>
<P>
   Sonus went public at $23 a share in late May of this year,
boosted by big product sales to Global Crossing and Williams
Communications and admiration for Sonus's management team.
</P>
<P>
   The stock doubled its first day and soared to over $250 a share
in late July, in part on the strength of more deal announcements,
including a $75 million pact with Time Warner Telecom.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Sonus shares shot up $15.875 to close at $218,
attaching a value of more than $12.2 billion to a company that in
the first six months of this year had only $7.6 million in sales _
and losses of $18 million.
</P>
<P>
   Like a 23-year-old Rhodes Scholar, Sonus seems to face the
problem of what can it possibly do with the rest of its life beyond
merely living up to the world's daunting expectations.
</P>
<P>
   While the markets Sonus is serving are projected to be worth $20
billion to $60 billion globally within three years, Sonus faces
plenty of ``fast box'' rivals in converged voice and data. Its
competitors range from Cisco Systems down to emerging local
challengers such as Convergent Networks of Lowell, Unisphere
Solutions of Chelmsford, and Telica Inc. of Marlborough.
</P>
<P>
   Just to match the ratio of market value to revenues of Wall
Street darling Nortel Networks, Sonus would have to increase sales
to roughly 100 times current levels to support the current stock
price _ forgetting about profits.
</P>
<P>
   Already, many industry insiders fear Wall Street has bid up the
company's shares past rationality, even given the vast
opportunities the company has to rival Lucent Technologies and
Nortel Networks in supplying gear to help the world's telephone
networks cope with explosive Internet data traffic.
</P>
<P>
   ``The products they have serve a hot market, and they are one of
the first vendors to go public in this market, but I don't think
the valuation that Sonus has is sustainable over the long term,''
said Christen Flynn, a Yankee Group analyst who follows and admires
the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't have the revenues to support it,'' Flynn said. ``At
some point, it's got to become a more realistic valuation for the
company.''
</P>
<P>
   Flynn's is a nice way of expressing some of the sharper opinions
of short sellers who, in recent weeks, have begun to attack Sonus
shares. Up to 1.5 million Sonus shares have been sold short at
times last month in expectation the price will plunge.
</P>
<P>
   ``The price doesn't pass the silly test,'' one wrote on the
Sonus chat board at the Raging Bull financial Web site recently.
Chimed in another short seller: ``This is a big fat pig waiting to
be slaughtered.''
</P>
<P>
   But even at near current levels, Wall Street titan Goldman Sachs
has rated Sonus a market outperformer, crediting it with ``a
leading share of a rapidly growing market with huge barriers to
entry and unlimited market potential'' and citing ``a management
team clearly capable of growing this company into billion-dollar
revenue status.''
</P>
<P>
   And even companies that have not bought its gear see Sonus as
being right in the sweet spot of telecom. Stuart Elby, director of
network architecture for Verizon Communications, the former Bell
Atlantic, said: ``We're a great believer in voice over Internet
protocol.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly there's a place for . . . equipment like the Sonus
equipment,'' said Elby. ``In the long run, packet voice is going to
be the more cost-effective way to deliver voice, and we expect to
move in that direction,'' probably first in areas of the country
where Verizon is building new networks and later in areas where it
will replace ``legacy'' equipment from Lucent, Nortel, and others.
</P>
<P>
   Gruber and Ahmed insist they are not ticker tape watchers and
are neither fazed nor deluded by the recent market moves that have
added several hundred million dollars to their and Hluchjy's
wealth. According to the most recent filings, Ahmed owns over 3
million shares, while Hluchjy owns 2.3 million and Gruber owns 1.3
million.
</P>
<P>
   ``I generally don't pay much attention to the stock price,''
said Ahmed. ``They're kind of more buying the stock in terms of
what they think our potential is. I think what Wall Street is
looking at is, who's getting the traction? Who's making this
happen?''
</P>
<P>
   Added Ahmed: ``We're going to change the way the public network
is built. That's a very big opportunity. These things don't happen
every day. You have to swing for the fences.''
</P>
<P>
   Within the next two years, Ahmed said, ``the odds are pretty
good'' that Sonus will close megadeals with a Baby Bell or a big
long-distance carrier such as AT&AMP;T or WorldCom.
</P>
<P>
   Ahmed is a highflier in more ways than one. He owns a six-seater
Cessna 310 he often uses for business trips to Washington and New
Jersey _ or loads up with his wife and four children for quick
trips to see his family in Ottawa, where the Pakistan native moved
with his physicist father and family when he was 4. He also holds a
master's degree in aeronautics in addition to his Stanford
doctorate in electrical engineering.
</P>
<P>
   While Sonus makes devices known as ``voice over Internet
protocol'' switches, what they do is far different from the ham
radio-quality international calls many people have made from
computers over the Net. Sonus switches use the same system as
shooting data packets over the Net to transmit phone calls with
better-than-Bell-System quality on controlled private networks.
</P>
<P>
   That technology means several things. One is smaller boxes.
Sonus switches can handle thousands of phone calls in one-20th as
much space as equivalent voice-circuit gear made by an old-line
Lucent or Nortel, and at perhaps half the cost per line served.
</P>
<P>
   Those are powerful selling points given that some of the world's
most treasured real estate today is floor space inside windowless
old phone company central offices where carriers entering a local
market may have to spend $25,000 to $90,000 a month to rent 100
square feet.
</P>
<P>
   Once a phone company has a Sonus box in place, adding new lines
and calling features to cope with rapid growth can be as simple as
slipping more cards into a box and tweaking software.
</P>
<P>
   As the Internet age has flooded telephone networks with data
traffic, many carriers such as Global Crossing are migrating to
carrying voice calls over far more efficient data networks rather
than stuffing more data onto 20th century voice-circuit systems.
That conversion will require billions of dollars for years to come.
</P>
<P>
   Carriers have found they can install Sonus-type gear into their
networks far faster than traditional voice equipment. In April
1999, for example, Global Crossing had ordered a Sonus switch to
test.
</P>
<P>
   Just four hours after hooking the box up to their network,
Global executives placed a conference call from Denver to Sonus in
Westford. The call went through perfectly. ``We were perhaps even
more amazed than we should have been,'' Ahmed recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Another compelling sales point for Sonus and other ``packet
voice'' players is that, for phone companies, their technology
greatly simplifies adding features such as unified messaging
services combining voice mail and e-mail, or one-number plans that
ring people's office, home and cell phones.
</P>
<P>
   Over the long haul, Ahmed said he thinks offering such services
will be as big a selling point for Sonus as the cost and size of
its products. Already, the company has signed up 40 businesses for
an ``open services partner alliance'' to spur development of new
communications features and services using IP systems.
</P>
<P>
   Tulsa-based Williams Communications is using Sonus switches as
it builds a 33,000-mile, 125-city network that by next year is
expected to serve local and national carriers in Boston and several
southern New England cities. The company also has invested in
Sonus.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Saville, vice president of network planning for Williams,
said a key selling point for Williams was being able to offer
``amazing'' advanced calling services for its phone-company
customers to offer to subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sonus provided us with the best-balanced machine out there.''
He declined to comment on reports that Sonus beat out Cisco for the
deal.
</P>
<P>
   While some of the stock market runup may reflect speculation
that Sonus is a ripe takeover target, Ahmed and the cofounders
steadfastly insist they are all in for the long haul and want to
build what Ahmed calls ``a significant company.''
</P>
<P>
   Gruber speaks derisively of telecom start-ups some call
``burgers _ box companies that were made to flip'' to an acquirer.
``We're not going to be a burger,'' Gruber said.
</P>
<P>
   Without naming any names, Ahmed said Sonus may become an
acquirer. Besides being ``a financing event'' to raise money, he
said, the May IPO was intended to create ``a public currency so we
can be acquisitive'' and follow Lucent, Nortel, and Cisco in using
richly appreciated stock to buy up other companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to provide more and more of the pieces of the
technology,'' Ahmed said.
</P>
<P>
   That could mean moving beyond providing switches for the heart
of a network to offer on-ramp devices supporting high-speed
Internet access, wireless services, and phone service over upgraded
cable television systems.
</P>
<P>
   But while the spring slump in telecom shares may suggest to some
that Sonus should pounce while its shares are still high, Ahmed
said, ``I don't feel any pressure to go out and strike while the
iron is hot. At the point that we find a deal that makes sense,
we'll do it. We're not feeling any time pressure to make a bad
move.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-08-00 1042EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
