<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 10:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5608 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-MONEYTALK0809-COX     08-08 0995
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEYTALK0809-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Payouts, ignored in boom times, are noticed now
 &HT;    By Hank Ezell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ As the stock market gets tippier, more Americans are
turning to an old-fashioned way of growing their portfolios:
dividends.
</P>
<P>
   At one time, before the memory of many current investors,
dividend yield was an important consideration in picking stocks.
</P>
<P>
   That was before we all discovered that the stock market could go
up 20 percent or more, year after year. With appreciation like
that, who needed cash payments now?
</P>
<P>
   But the super-growth years are not a sure thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we get into a period of more modest returns, perhaps even a
down year, people are going to start paying attention to dividends
and thinking about getting that check,'' said Tom Huber, manager of
T. Rowe Price's Dividend Growth mutual fund.
</P>
<P>
   Dividends are cash payments, usually four times a year, to
owners of shares in a company. Historically they have accounted for
nearly half the growth in stock values.
</P>
<P>
   Over the first 102 years of the Dow Jones Industrial Average,
prices of the 30 bellwether stocks have gone up 5.4 percent a year.
Add in dividends paid on those stocks and the growth rate leaps to
9.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The chart indicates the difference. Finance professor Meir
Statman of Santa Clara University puts it this way: With reinvested
dividends, the Dow would have grown 71 times higher.
</P>
<P>
   There is a second reason for liking dividends.
</P>
<P>
   ``It tends to cushion the fall in a bad market,'' said Carol M.
Lippman, an equity strategist with the A.G. Edwards brokerage in
St. Louis. Like Huber, she specializes in identifying companies
that increase dividends regularly and can continue doing it.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want to have high-flying growth, that's fine,'' Lippman
said. ``But dividend-paying stocks can keep chugging along and can
support the value of your portfolio.''
</P>
<P>
   Lippman and others believe that dividends are important not just
to older investors who want the income to live on, but to younger
investors.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they can start early and put money into this kind of stock,
I think they will be pleased with the dividend checks they can
receive in retirement,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Lippman's master list includes 102 stocks which have growing
dividends and which can be expected to keep up the good work.
</P>
<P>
   She offers General Electric as an example. GE has increased its
dividends an average of 12.9 percent for the last 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think GE can increase its dividends about 15 percent a
year,'' she said. ``If it can do that over a 10-year period, it
will be paying a $2.23 dividend.'' Right now the annual payout is
55 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Dividends are not a magic bullet.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no assurance that companies are going to be able to
continue increasing dividends,'' Lippman pointed out. Her studies
showed more than 1,000 companies met the test during the 1980s. But
only 490 made her list during the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Taxes are another consideration. Dividends are taxed at ordinary
income tax rates, in the year they are paid. The alternative is
non-dividend stocks, which might well retain dividend money and
make the company grow faster.
</P>
<P>
   You wouldn't owe taxes until you sell the stock, and then it
would be at lower capital gains rates.
</P>
<P>
   That is why many investors put their dividend-paying stocks in
IRAs or other tax-deferred accounts, said Sue Stevens, director of
financial planning for investment researcher Morningstar Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Investment style is another issue: Dividend-paying companies
tend to be slow, steady growers.
</P>
<P>
   ``High-growth companies rarely pay dividends, because then need
to reinvest all their profits,'' observed Laura Pavlenko Lutton, a
stock analyst at Morningstar.
</P>
<P>
   Dividend yields have been going down steadily, as the chart
shows. The yield from S&AMP;P 500 companies sagged to 1.2 percent in
the last half of 1999. It's even lower this year: 0.8 percent at
the end of May, according to Lutton.
</P>
<P>
   Rapid increases in stock prices are one reason, Huber said. The
second reason is that technology companies like Cisco Systems and
Microsoft are a bigger slice of the market, and they typically do
not pay dividends.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Morningstar's database of 7,623 stocks includes 234
companies with yields of 8 percent or more.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of July, the highest average yields came from tobacco
companies, 7.6 percent; real estate investment trusts, 6.6 percent,
and electric utilities and construction companies, each at 3.9
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Also near the top: forestry and wood products companies, savings
institutions and banks.
</P>
<P>
   How do you pick the good ones?
</P>
<P>
   One more thing to watch out for is implausibly high dividends.
Yields grow fast when a company's stock price plunges, and there is
often a good reason for such drops.
</P>
<P>
   The highest yield reported in Morningstar's database is 118.2
percent. The company still pays a dividend, but it is bobbing
around on the edge of bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to do your homework, as you would with any
investment,'' Lutton said. ``We suggest looking at how fast the
company itself is growing, and how profitable it is. Is it
financially healthy? And does it have an attractive price?''
</P>
<P>
   Huber and Lippman work up lists of companies with growing
dividends, then whittle the list to the most promising ones.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some favorites from these experts:
</P>
<P>
   Lutton likes Philip Morris, Equity Office Properties Trust, Duke
Energy, TXU (formerly Texas Utilities).
</P>
<P>
   Lippman's list of 102 includes General Electric, Fannie Mae,
Gillette and Schering-Plough. The last three have increased
dividends at an annual rate of 15 percent or better over the last
10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Huber's top three holdings are Pfizer, Citigroup and Waddell &AMP;
Reed Financial. He has been adding to those holdings since he took
over the fund at the first of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
