<DOCNO> NYT20000808.0053 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 10:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5614 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN0809-CO     08-08 0604
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN0809-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The empty nest full of memories
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ My son, Kristofor, ran away from home in
1985. Since then, not much in his room has been changed. The same
comforters are folded across the foot of the same bunk beds he
moved into when he was two. His bears
</P>
<P>
   (Paddington, Pooh, and Twitchums) are still leaning against the
pillows, like maybe they're waiting for him to come home and crawl
in for a nap.
</P>
<P>
   His books still line the shelves over his desk and reflect a
growing boy's changing tastes. The National Geographic Society's
``Trails West'' is right next to a gory Stephen King. On the bottom
shelf, Ayn Rand's ``Atlas Shrugged'' leans against ``The Facts of
Love,'' a book I bought for him when he was 12, to help me with our
first official birds and bees talk. He thanked me for it, I
remember, but said he already knew all of that stuff. Keep it for
reference, I suggested. He promised to give it a look-see and get
back with me. I'm not sure we ever finished that conversation.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom dresser drawer is jammed with his collection of rock
concert tee-shirts, now shrunken and warped out of shape from too
many tumbles in the dryer. I'd always thought they were ugly
things, but he chalked up my lack of
</P>
<P>
   appreciation to the probability that I was ``over the hill'' and
careening rapidly ``around the bend.''
</P>
<P>
   A boy's lifetime collection of Monster magazines fills the top
shelf in his closet, remnants of the years he spent fascinated by
the terrifying creatures that stalked the screen of the old Alamo
theater in the little Georgia town where he did most of his growing
up. Front row center, Kristofor and his best buddy, Chuck, would
spend hours scrunched down in their seats begging to be scared out
of their grubby sneakers by one of stop-motion animation genius Ray
Harryhausen's thrillers _ ``The Beast from 20,000 Fathoms'' or
``Sinbad and the Eye of the Tiger.'' A little boy thing, I guess.
</P>
<P>
   On the desk are pictures of him at various graduations _ high
school, college, grad school _ as he grew progressively more
handsome with each milestone. Soft, boyish features subtly chiseled
themselves in manhood.
</P>
<P>
   Shoved into a dark corner of the attic are three empty fish
tanks and something that looks like it used to be a sleeping bag _
maybe the clean one that went off to camp with him each summer and
came back mud-caked and smelling like he'd been sharing it with a
weasel in dirty socks.
</P>
<P>
   A long ago outgrown blazer hangs in the garment bag, all cleaned
and ready for him to slip into, if he could. It's a little boy size
12 _ his long ago school crest still on the pocket.
</P>
<P>
   ``So why don't you come back home now?'' I'm asking him this
morning while he munches on breakfast _ in Philadelphia. ``You've
been gone long enough. A boy belongs with his mother. I've saved
your crib and everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Kristofor guffaws some grits into his cordless. I know how silly
I'm sounding but, for just this one moment, I'm deadly serious. I
want my kid back.
</P>
<P>
   Okay, so he didn't really run away all those years ago _ he went
off to college. Then more college. And now he has a lovely wife,
and a job, and lives only a short plane ride away. He's where he
should be and doing just fine. I know that.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, I think I have too much time on my hands.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail: 320 West
Madison, Gibsonburg, OH 43431 or e-mail: eschuett(at)nwonline.net
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
