<DOCNO> NYT20000808.0054 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 10:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5615 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-YOUNG09-COX     08-08 0667
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    No other options: we must draft lawmakers to classroom vacancies
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas - The Berlin Wall down, no armies mounting against
us, one might say that in the last eight years our closest thing to
a war effort has been attending to schools. At least rhetorically.
</P>
<P>
   Whether on reading, writing or warding off student massacres,
this nation has never had so many verbs on the march. Every
civilian has an opinion, a plan.
</P>
<P>
   This on something _ schooling _ Americans used to hand off to
others somewhat like they did milk bottles. Leave the kids on the
curb. Fill 'em up.
</P>
<P>
   Well, no more. This is national security, domestic tranquillity.
Come on. Collect and donate your spare syllables to the war effort.
</P>
<P>
   With all the attention, you'd think schools were thriving _
thriving like, for instance, the rivet industry in the Roosevelt
years.
</P>
<P>
   This is the greatest nation on earth. When duty calls, we have
the resources and the will to accomplish whatever we must.
</P>
<P>
   So it must confuse many to find out that the great state of
Texas has 40,000 teaching vacancies, part of an ominous national
trend.
</P>
<P>
   The Waco Independent School District has 50 vacancies with the
start of school days away.
</P>
<P>
   This national emergency would appear to require one thing, and
one thing only: reinstating the draft.
</P>
<P>
   The details momentarily _ but first, more rhetoric. It seems
someone would be summoned into our war room on this huge manpower
gap, someone with charts and pointers. Press conferences would be
called. Wolf Blitzer's pager would sound.
</P>
<P>
   Instead _ well, we get sound, just no charts, no pointers.
Everyone talks about education. The Texas governor talks about it a
lot. Indeed, as his party convened last week, a party that eight
years ago wanted to abolish the Department of Education, George W.
Bush came close to sounding the cry for nationalizing schools. His
accountability system would tie federal funds to standards judged
by Washington.
</P>
<P>
   It's fascinating to watch all the banter about accountability
while the human infrastructure that makes learning possible filters
away like a sand castle in foam.
</P>
<P>
   Forty thousand vacancies in Texas. It's like Fort Hood's 4th
Infantry Division turned up lost, and the 1st Calvary Division went
searching for it and vanished, too. In a war, we'd be frantic.
</P>
<P>
   Back to the draft? Yes. Of course, we don't want to draft just
anyone to teach. It's only because states like ours have done such
a pitiful job replenishing the ranks, and holding on to the good
teachers it has, that it just seems we'll enlist anyone.
</P>
<P>
   We should be true to the name of the Selective Service and make
it that. The first people we draft: lawmakers, the ones who set the
salaries and benefits, who talk up ``accountability'' and
``standards.''
</P>
<P>
   Under a nationalized school system (this is war), governors no
longer would be needed on the policy front. They would be the first
to go to the classroom. Dealing with pouty and petulant lawmakers,
they would be a perfect fit, say, for second grade.
</P>
<P>
   And of course legislators would be next to go. Assign each in
his or her area of expertise.
</P>
<P>
   You can say, ``But there are only 181 legislators in Texas, plus
one governor and one lieutenant governor. How can they make up for
40,000?''
</P>
<P>
   Simple. Once they feel the fires of perspiration, see the
challenges placed before them for the salaries and benefits
provided, face tasks according to the whims of politicians and
bottom-line school boards, they'll find a way as lawmakers. They'll
boost pay. They'll improve benefits, free teachers' hands to do
their jobs. They'll do whatever it takes to find 40,000 highly
qualified teachers. They'll make teaching rewarding. Oh, yes they
will. It's that or the trenches for them.
</P>
<P>
   John Young is Opinion Page editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
