<HEADLINE>
THE MATURE TRAVELER: CRUISE NEWS  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by WAY TO GO! clients. Nonsubscribers can use
this article only by special arrangement. For purchase information,
see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 PLEASE NOTE: Optional-trim indicators are included in this
article. 
 &HT;    
 (Color slide included.) 
 By ADELE MALOTT 
 Condensed from The Mature Traveler Newsletter 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    Repositioning cruises offer some of the best values in the
travel business. And the fall cruise season _ a time when cruise
lines begin moving their ships to new locations _ is a good
opportunity to try one.
 &HT;    The Cruise Lines International Association (CLIA) cites these
advantages for repositioning cruises:
 &HT;     _ ONE-OF-A-KIND ITINERARIES.  Because ships are moving from one
part of the world to another, the combination of ports visited is
unique. Often these itineraries include ocean or Panama Canal
crossings as well as ports not usually visited on other sailings.
 &HT;     _ VALUE.  Two-for-one fares, air-inclusive offers and a variety
of off-season promotional rates make cruise prices very attractive.
 &HT;     _ SPECIAL ENTERTAINMENT.  Cruise lines may enhance their
repositioning cruises with entertainment that isn't always offered
on other cruises.
 &HT;     _ EXTRA DAYS.  Longer itineraries allow more time at sea.
 &HT;    However, you should be aware that cruise lines may use
repositioning voyages to train new staff or to try new shore trips,
giving an experimental flavor to the cruise.
 &HT;    Contact your travel agent about these repositioning cruises or
others that will be offered this fall:
 &HT;    _ America Cruise Lines, which sails the waterways of the U.S.
East Coast year-round, will be in Baltimore on Nov. 4 before
heading to Jacksonville, Fla., for the winter months.
 &HT;    _ Costa Cruises Lines leaves Europe from Genoa to head for the
Caribbean Nov. 3 and 17. Ports of call: the Bahamas, British Virgin
Islands, Canary Islands, Guadeloupe, Leeward Island, Madeira,
Morocco and Spain.
 &HT;    _ Holland America Line moves five vessels from Alaska to the
Caribbean on trips ranging from 17 to 22 days. Departures are in
September and October with 17- or 22-day cruises that pass through
the Panama Canal.
 &HT;    _ Norwegian Cruise Line's Norwegian Wind leaves Vancouver Sept.
18 to sail a special 11-day Hawaiian Island itinerary before moving
on to the Caribbean.
 &HT;    _ After its inaugural season in Bermuda, the Pacific Princess
leaves New York on Oct. 29 to move to the Holy Land. There will be
16 days at sea with port calls in Ponta Delgada and Lisbon,
Portugal; Gibraltar; Barcelona; Cannes; Laverno; and Rome.
 &HT;    _ Royal Olympic moves its Stella Solaris from the Mediterranean
to the Caribbean with a Dec. 1 sailing from Piraeus, Greece. Ports
include Naples, Capri and Civitavecchia in Italy; Nice, France;
Cartagena, Spain; Tangier, Morocco; Lisbon and Madeira, Portugal;
San Juan; and Fort Lauderdale.
 &HT;    _ Seabourn Cruise Line has a Three Continent Discovery on its
Legend beginning Oct. 20 in Lisbon. Available in segments of six,
13 or 19 days, the itinerary has stops in Funchal, Madeira; Dakar,
Senegal; Bridgetown, Barbados; Virgin Gorda, BVI; San Juan; and
Fort Lauderdale.
 &HT;    
 BETTER BREATHING CARIBBEAN CRUISE  
 &HT;    The Better Breathing Club of Norwalk Hospital, in Norwalk,
Conn., is offering a cruise through the Eastern Caribbean for
travelers with chronic pulmonary diseases. Arrangements will be
made for those needing supplemental oxygen in flight and during the
cruise.
 &HT;    The cruise is aboard Celebrity's The Century, which leaves from
Fort Lauderdale, Fla., Nov. 4 for a week's cruise with stops in San
Juan, St. Maarten, St. Thomas and Nassau.
 &HT;    Traveling with the group will be a pulmonary physician, nurses
and respiratory therapists. Prices start at $1,018, including port
charges. Air, insurance, oxygen and special equipment is extra. For
more information, call (800) 536-9383.
 &HT;    
 $1,000 SAVINGS  
 &HT;    First European Cruises is offering a $1,000 savings per person
on September and October sailings aboard the Mistral in the Eastern
Mediterranean. It sails round trip from Venice on seven-day cruises
to Dubrovnik, Katakolon, Santorini, Mykonos, Rhodes and Piraeus
(Athens). Discounted departure dates are Sept. 2, 9, 16, 23 and
Oct. 7, 14, 21 and 28.
 &HT;    The cruise-only promotional rates start at $1,250/double for an
outside cabin. Round-trip airfare add-ons from Venice are available
from 50 gateways and for $950 from the East Coast, $1,200 West
Coast. For more information, call (888) 983-8767, or visit
www.first-european.com.
 &HT;    
 NEW HAWAIIAN SHIP  
 &HT;    Starting Dec. 9, the United States Lines' first ship, the ms
Patriot (formerly Holland America Line's Nieuw Amsterdam), will
begin cruise vacations to four Hawaiian islands on a seven-night
itinerary. The ms Patriot leaves each Saturday. Fares start at
$1,599/double in value season; airfares cost $399 from most Western
gateways; $699 from the East Coast. For more information, call
(877) 330-6600, or visit www.unitedstateslines.com on the Web.
 &HT;    
 RAIL/CRUISE COMBO  
 &HT;    America West Steamboat Co. is adding 10-night departures to its
seven-night programs that blend rail travel on the Amtrak Coast
Starlight with overnight cruises on the Queen of the West on the
Columbia, Snake and Willamette rivers. The Queen of the West is an
overnight paddlewheel cruise ship that travels the Pacific
Northwest.
 &HT;    All departures include two nights on Amtrak between California
and Portland, Ore., with travelers boarding the Coast Starlight at
any of its regular stops between San Diego and Sacramento.
Departures on the 10-night programs start Nov. 9, while seven-night
itineraries start Dec. 28.
 &HT;    Prices vary, but the seven-night program that leaves from
Sacramento starts at $1,409/double; while the 10-night prices start
at $1,878. For more information, call (800) 434-1232, or visit
www.columbiarivercruise.com on the Web.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS HERE.)
 &HT;    
 CRUISE DEAL  
 &HT;    A group of six cruise lines _ Holland America, Windstar,
Seabourn, Cunard, Costa and Carnival _ now offer discounts of 20
percent to 50 percent to repeat cruisers in a program called
Vacation Interchange Privileges (VIP).
 &HT;    For example, if you have sailed on any of the six lines, you
could be eligible for up to 35 percent discounts on sailings with
Holland America or up to 50 percent on Windstar.
 &HT;    To be eligible, a customer must book a cruise through any travel
agent, who then informs the cruise-line reservations agent about
the past-guest status at the time of the booking.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS HERE.)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Readers are invited to submit questions and comments to Adele
Malott, c/o The New York Times Syndicate, 122 East 42nd St., 14th
Floor, New York, N.Y. 10168. Send Adele a postcard from your trip
with ideas, questions and information on the bargains you find for
seniors.
 &HT;    Questions may also be sent to Adele by electronic mail. The
address is MatureTrav(at)aol.com. (For (AT) use the symbol on your
keyboard.)
 &HT;    Adele Malott is the publisher of THE MATURE TRAVELER: Travel
Bonanzas for 49ers-Plus, a newsletter for mature travelers.
