<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'')
</P>
<P>
   SEGAL-MURDER (San Francisco) _ Daniel Alas had consumed the
equivalent of more than 20 12-ounce beers when he killed striptease
club doorman Anton Segal with a car security device on Nov. 21,
1998, according to his attorney. In his opening statement at Alas'
first-degree murder trial Monday, defense lawyer Michael Gaines
said evidence would show that Alas had an estimated blood-alcohol
level of at least 0.25 percent at the time of the crime, more than
three times the legal limit for drivers. By MICHAEL DOUGAN.
</P>
<P>
   PRISON-SUIT (San Francisco) _ Attorneys for guards at the
troubled Pelican Bay State Prison are disputing another brutality
suit, telling a federal court jury that a prisoner who claimed
excessive force had actually been the aggressor and had been
treated properly. By BOB EGELKO.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FBN-NINERS (Stockton, Calif.) _ San Francisco 49ers Coach Steve
Mariucci puts the best spin on the situation, calling it
``healthy'' and ``good for everybody.'' But the fact is, he's got a
bit of a problem on his hands. The 49ers have four quarterbacks in
camp, which is probably one too many. Starting quarterback Jeff
Garcia hasn't shown much yet. Giovanni Carmazzi, the team's
third-round draft pick, has been slow to adjust to the 49ers
system. And the two that have played the best _ eighth year
vagabond Rick Mirer and seventh-round pick Tim Rattay _ may be the
two who were least expected to do that well. By BRUCE ADAMS.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Al Gore picked Connecticut Sen.
Joe Lieberman as his running mate, raising the question, ``What
does `Gore-Lieberman' look like on a bumper sticker?'' In the last
century, there have been only three presidents with one-syllable
names, Taft, Ford and Bush. Only one had a vice president with more
than two syllables in his last name. That was Gerald Ford's vice
president Nelson Rockefeller. By ROB MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   FOREST-FIRES (Whitefish, Mont.) _ As forests busily grow, they
grow fuel. If that fuel isn't removed, either through timber
harvest or prescribed burns, it will eventually and inevitably
remove itself in a spectacular and deadly manner, such as we are
now witnessing in the rash of forest fires sweeping the West. Can
we burn safely in a tinderbox? It's obvious we can't. We simply
must conduct appropriate timber harvests alongside appropriate
burning programs, and do it as soon as we possibly can. If we do
not...if we simply run away, someday we won't be able to run fast
enough. By DAVE SKINNER.
</P>
