A5649 &Cx1f; tab-z
u e BC-FRANCES-O'CONNOR-INTE     08-08 0804
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRANCES-O'CONNOR-INTERVIEW-FAIRCHILD-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIVE LA FRANCES  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by clients of ``HIGH STYLE AND MORE.''
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 By MERLE GINSBERG 
 (One color slide is available) 
 From W magazine 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    When director Harold Ramis was looking for someone to play
opposite Brendan Fraser in his new farce, ``Bedazzled,'' the
casting director said she was sending a very talented Australian
actress to meet him.
 &HT;    ``She told me this actress was youthful but still had a kind of
maturity,'' Ramis remembers. ``That she was really skillful as an
actress, tons of technique. Anyway, I was auditioning this lovely
actress, thinking, `Too bad this isn't her,' until I realized _ it
was. I said, `Where's the accent?' And she said, `Oh, I'm speaking
American for the role.'''
 &HT;    That actress was Frances O'Connor, and yes, she got the part.
 &HT;    ``I knew everything about Harold Ramis, and he knew nothing
about me,'' O'Connor says gleefully. ``It's quite fun in L.A.,
because no one knows who I am.''
 &HT;    Needless to say, that's about to change _ fast. The 30-year-old
Australian _ following in the footsteps of compatriots Nicole
Kidman, Cate Blanchett and Russell Crowe _ has come seemingly from
nowhere to snag the lead not just in ``Bedazzled'' but also in
Steven Spielberg's upcoming science-fiction epic ``A.I.,'' opposite
Jude Law. She also stars in ``About Adam,'' a small Miramax comedy.
 &HT;    Before this latest blitz, O'Connor had made several
well-received but small films, including ``Kiss or Kill'' and last
year's adaptation of Jane Austen's ``Mansfield Park.'' For the
latter, she had gone in to audition for a small part and came out
with the lead.
 &HT;    After that film, O'Connor landed the title role in the BBC's
``Madame Bovary,'' which aired on PBS last winter. Now Hollywood
types are comparing her to Blanchett, Kidman and Kate Winslet.
 &HT;    But sitting in one of Beverly Hills' hottest lunch spots, Il
Fornaio, O'Connor _ with no makeup and the most casual of pants and
T-shirt _ scoffs at her new hype.
 &HT;    ``Oh, that's just a thing people do,'' she says dismissively.
``That's just noise. At least they're flattering comparisons.''
 &HT;    In ``Bedazzled,'' a remake of the Dudley Moore/Peter Cook '60s
classic, Fraser is a Northern California computer nerd who can't
get anywhere with the popular girl at work, Allison (O'Connor). But
when he's visited by the Devil _ played tongue-in-cheek by
Elizabeth Hurley _ he sells his soul for eight opportunities to
show Allison what a great man he could be.
 &HT;    Together, he and O'Connor play out the imaginary scenarios: He's
a Colombian drug lord and she's his mistress; he's a rock star and
she's a groupie; he's a Pulitizer prize-winning author and she's a
'50s intellectual, etc.
 &HT;    Fraser says O'Connor's transitions from character to character
were seamless.
 &HT;    ``That's how scary good she is with dialects,'' he says, ``not
to mention her chameleon-like talent for playing characters wildly
different from each other.''
 &HT;    For O'Connor, going from period to contemporary _ in this case,
all in one movie _ is just part of the gig.
 &HT;    ``Any actor should be able to do all of those things,'' she
says.
 &HT;    But playing the object of Brendan Fraser's overwhelming longing?
That was the hard part.
 &HT;    ``It's hilarious to play `the beautiful girl,''' she says,
``totally not who I am at all.''
 &HT;    No matter what she thinks, Spielberg was determined to cast her
in ``A.I.'' _ which he co-wrote with Stanley Kubrick _ just after
her CAA agent, Kevin Huvane, slipped him a tape of ``Madame
Bovary.''
 &HT;    ``I think if Steven gets an instinct about someone, he trusts
it,'' says O'Connor, who's steeling herself for the attention that
will inevitably accompany the role. ``My agents keep saying I don't
realize how big this is. And I keep saying, `I think I do.'''
 &HT;    
 c.2000 Fairchild Publications 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Merle Ginsberg is a writer for Fairchild Publications.)
</P>
