<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EYE-SCOOPS-FAIRCHILD-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EYE SCOOPS!  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by clients of ``HIGH STYLE AND MORE.''
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 By THE EDITORS OF WWD, DNR AND W MAGAZINE 
 (Color art is available.) 
 From WWD, DNR and W magazine 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    
 THE POM-POM CLUB  
 &HT;    ``I wasn't born to be a cheerleader, and I'm not a giant fan of
the color pink,'' Natasha Lyonne said on July 23 at the Los Angeles
premiere of ``But I'm a Cheerleader.''
 &HT;    Clea DuVall, Lyonne's co-star and friend, laughed as she
recalled the shoot.
 &HT;    ``I just remember watching Natasha sitting there, getting her
hair done, smoking and saying, `I don't want to do this anymore.'''
 &HT;    Those who weren't in the film had a rosier view of the baton
arts.
 &HT;    ``I'd love to be a cheerleader, actually,'' said Jennifer Jason
Leigh, who popped into the prescreen cocktails with Alan Cumming.
``As long as I could be in the center.''
 &HT;    ``I saw a documentary on cheerleading once,'' Cumming said. ``I
love to see people trying really hard at something that's so
meaningless.''
 &HT;    A few nights later, the troops came out to toast Harrison Ford's
latest bone-chiller, ``What Lies Beneath.''
 &HT;    ``Even I got scared,'' said his co-star, Michelle Pfeiffer.
``There were parts I forgot about that made me jump.''
 &HT;    Amber Valletta, who makes her screen debut as the ghost that
haunts a married couple played by Ford and Pfeiffer, said the movie
posed a challenge altogether different from shooting a Versace
campaign.
 &HT;    ``For one thing, I was made to look scary instead of pretty,''
she said. ``I've made four movies this year, though I'm now
preparing for the biggest role of my life,'' she said, rubbing her
pregnant belly.
 &HT;    
 KOBE PUTS ON A REALLY BIG SHOE  
 &HT;    Although he's just 21, L.A. Lakers star guard Kobe Bryant
already has an NBA championship ring; a 50 percent stake in famed
Italian basketball team Olympia Milano; an equity stake in
Broadband Sports/Athlete Direct, a company that manages fan Web
sites for professional athletes; an album titled ``Visions''
that'll debut later this year; and more endorsements and corporate
sponsors than one can imagine.
 &HT;    Who could ask for anything more?
 &HT;    Bryant can _ and he's getting it: a basketball shoe named after
him, made by Adidas, his apparel endorser, and car manufacturer
Audi.
 &HT;    ``It's always been a dream of mine to have my own shoe,'' Bryant
said recently at the Hilton in Hasbrouck Heights, N.J., during the
ABCD Camp, a basketball training camp where top college recruiters
go. ``All the basketball stars I grew up with, like Magic Johnson
and Michael Jordan, had them. But I wanted a sneaker that was
different, a concept in and of itself that hasn't been done
before.''
 &HT;    The Kobe will debut Nov. 3 at sporting-goods stores and
specialty stores and will retail for $125. Tuxedo (black) will be
the first color wave to launch, followed by white, silver and
yellow in each of the next three months.
 &HT;    Bryant, who wears a size 14, wanted a sneaker that would best
represent his personality: ``simple _ something that's not going to
steal the show.'' Adidas didn't have to look any further for
inspiration than Bryant's own backyard, Southern California.
 &HT;    In determining what defines that part of the country, the
athletic maker came up with its car culture. Specifically, the Audi
TT Roadster, designed in part and influenced by Southern
California, which became the model for the sneaker.
 &HT;    At a glance, the TT Roadster has three main features: a
continuous line, a clean surface body side and a bullet-nosed
front. These elements are reflected in The Kobe, as well as in
Adidas' longstanding grooved shell-toe.
 &HT;    The main shoulder line continues around the arches and through
the bottom of the shoe, just as the Audi TT's continuous loop runs
from the side of the vehicle around the wheel arches and under the
car.
 &HT;    ``I don't think people realize how complex the logistics are in
designing a car,'' said Derek Jenkins, assistant chief of the Audi
design studio in California. ``There are so many parameters to
follow: whether it's crash safety, manufacturing techniques, cost
or aerodynamics, as well as the need to stay true to your company's
identity and history. But with a shoe, at the end of the day it's
really about a style first, then function.''
 &HT;    
 YAHOO BALLYHOO  
 &HT;    David Bowie, Lauren Hutton, Betsey Johnson and a few other
survivors of the '70s were there _ but it was a long way from the
heyday of Studio 54.
 &HT;    The legendary disco-turned-theater was the site of the 3rd
Annual Yahoo! Internet Life Online Music Awards on July 24. No
go-go boys, no cocaine on the dance floor (actually, no dance
floor) and an audience who had be to told that Steve meant Rubell.
 &HT;    Although 21st-century music and technology were the order of the
day, major awards went to two 1980s favorites, Prince (Best
Internet Only Single) and Aimee Mann (Best Internet Only Album),
and grand old man Sir Paul McCartney (Best Live Event Online).
 &HT;    Leading the award pack was Bowie, who won the Online Pioneer of
the Year Award and Best Official Artist Site. The 50-plus-year-old
rocker also led the sartorial pack, accepting his first award in a
stunning black suit and white shirt, then changing to an equally
attractive gray suit for his magnificent performance and acceptance
of the Pioneer Award.
 &HT;    Also dressing up were host John Leguizamo, ``Late Show With
David Letterman'' bandleader Paul Shaffer and MTV's Kurt Loder.
 &HT;    Meanwhile, presenter/performer Isaac Hayes _ whom Leguizamo
dubbed rightly ``the coolest man in the world'' _ took the middle
ground with a black sport jacket over a T-shirt with his own
likeness.
 &HT;    On the more casual front, Phat Farm's Russell Simmons and singer
Duncan Sheik went for the shirt-only look, and presenters Chuck D
and film director Doug Liman (Swingers) decided a T-shirt was just
fine to face the public.
 &HT;    
 EMMYS GET ONLINE  
 &HT;    LOS ANGELES _ A 360-degree red-carpet camera view, live ratings
of arrivals' looks and a Nokia-sponsored contest with a $100,000
cash prize are set for the Primetime Emmy Awards Webcasts planned
by ABC.com and iCast.com, a fledgling entertainment Web site allied
with the Academy of Television Arts and Sciences.
 &HT;    ABC.com, the official Webcaster of the 52nd Annual Primetime
Emmy Awards, is aiming for a humorous, gritty behind-the-scenes
look at the Emmys with features such as ``Diary of a Nominee.''
 &HT;    The diary will follow an Emmy nominee through the preparations
leading up to the Sept. 10 show, from dress fittings to beauty
appointments. As of press time, the featured nominee had not been
named. Nor has the comedic talent who will host the live
commentary.
 &HT;    ``It'll be someone young, a fresh face,'' said Brian Bowman,
ABC.com's vice president and general manager.
 &HT;    ABC.com is also planning preshow fashion coverage, including
pictorial fashion do's and don'ts, the buzz on show-night baubles,
interviews and tours of top designers' showrooms. Site visitors
will also have an opportunity to vote on which gown a nominee
should wear to the Emmys.
 &HT;    During the show, a roving Webcam will go backstage to interview
caterers, security guards and assorted extras, said Bowman. Webcams
will also be posted at the red carpet, as well as where the winners
are being interviewed.
 &HT;    Web viewers can vote for Emmy winners and, if they hit six
winners in six categories, will become eligible for Nokia's
$100,000 cash grand prize.
 &HT;    Like ABC.com, iCast.com, the official content provider for the
the ATAS, was also hurrying to hammer out the details of its
Webcast at press time. Preliminary plans, according to iCast.com's
marketing director Terri Henry, will include a 360-degree Webcam
view on the red carpet and live interactive rating by viewers of
what attendees are wearing.
 &HT;    ``Instead of only Joan Rivers-type commentary, we can see what
Main Street America thinks of the looks,'' Henry said. She added
that the site is in talks with fashion journalists to provide
preshow fashion and beauty coverage.
 &HT;    Emmys.org, the official site of ATAS, will link to both
Webcasts, as well as post a list of winners.
 &HT;    
 c.2000 Fairchild Publications 
