<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIRTUAL-DRESSING-ROOM-FAIRCHILD-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GETTING DRESSED ONLINE _ VIRTUALLY  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by clients of ``HIGH STYLE AND MORE.''
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 By KARYN MONGET 
 From WWD 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    NEW YORK _ At first glance, the female figures on the computer
screen look like cyber Stepford Wives.
 &HT;    In virtual reality _ through a cutting-edge 3D application
called C-Me _ the figures can be shaped, coiffed and styled into
whatever look a consumer wants, whether it's a flawless,
image-perfect figure, or a realistic simulation of a consumer's
actual measurements, including height, bra cup and the size of a
woman's hips and waistline.
 &HT;    The applications can also zero in on skin tone, hair color and
eye color, in addition to customizing facial features such as the
nose and the shape of the eyes.
 &HT;    The male representations have the clone-like quality of a Ken
doll.
 &HT;    The concept, though, isn't a game. Yanir Farber, president of
Tel Aviv-based Browzwear, and his brother Avihay Feld, were here
this spring on a mission to sell their e-commerce concept to a
number of U.S. retailers. They said they expected to launch it
first in Europe _ primarily Germany, Belgium and England _ this
fall.
 &HT;    Browzwear, which was founded in Israel in January by Farber and
Feld, is being financed by Delta Galil Industries, a diversified
apparel manufacturer that specializes in seamless products, and Dr.
Yossi Vardi, an Israeli high-tech guru.
 &HT;    The company has its sights set on becoming a leading provider of
real-time personalized services to online retailers, including
major click-and-mortar department stores and specialty chains, as
well as catalogers and independent e-tail sites.
 &HT;    The company's signature product, C-Me, will provide consumers
with a virtual fitting room based on a personal 3D figure called
Avatar, which is a 3D model representation of the user's image.
 &HT;    Online shoppers can visit an apparel e-tailer's site to dress
their virtual 3D image with items that have been merchandised by
Browzwear. When someone decides to purchase an item, Browzwear will
link the shopper to the e-tailer's site, where the transaction can
be completed.
 &HT;    The consumer can make her decision by rotating an Avatar figure
dressed in that clothing, on a 3D form, to get a full-rounded view,
and can zoom in to inspect a fabric's texture. A consumer will also
be able to determine the drapability of a fabric on petite, average
and plus-size figures.
 &HT;    ``The service will be free to consumers,'' said Farber, noting
the company has invested close to $1 million in the technology.
``Retailers in the U.S. have been very interested. Some are even
interested in investing in the company.''
 &HT;    Other than to say Browzwear will ``make a commission'' from
participating retailers, Farber would not elaborate. He did say,
however, that ``It will be up to the retailers to push this idea.''
 &HT;    Interestingly, Feld said he did not believe the concept would
take with a specialty retailer such as Victoria's Secret.
 &HT;    ``Victoria's Secret deals with fantasy. Everybody wants to look
sexy like their supermodels,'' Feld said. He added, though, that
the company will eventually develop an application for lingerie _
most likely shapewear _ this year. So far, apparel categories
include men's and women's sportswear and ready-to-wear and
swimwear. Children's wear also is planned for next year.
 &HT;    ``We won't do lingerie until the third or fourth generation of
this application,'' Feld said. ``When we do, a woman will literally
be able to see how a dress will fit by wearing a certain shaper.''
 &HT;    Feld further noted that the concept is based on Israeli
technology that was originally created for educational studies of
``space and the universe. It showed students how to navigate in
space and interact with the stars.''
 &HT;    Added Farber, ``One of the most important aspects of this
technology is the privacy we are offering. Nobody will be able to
see a person as they are trying on clothes in their virtual fitting
room.''
 &HT;    The technology also can aid shopping the international
marketplace, Farber noted, saying, ``If I liked some clothing at a
retailer in New York, and I wanted my mother in Israel to see what
the garments would look like on me, all I have to do is invite her
to visit my virtual closet.''
 &HT;    
 c.2000 Fairchild Publications 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Karyn Monget is a writer for Fairchild Publications.)
</P>
