<HEADER>
A5696 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-MARTINEZ-HIDDEN-TREAS     08-08 1306
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARTINEZ-HIDDEN-TREASURE-COLUMN-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALI BABA'S SECRET CAVE
</HEADLINE>
   (For use Wednesday, Aug. 2, or thereafter.)  
 ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by MARTINEZ-COLUMN clients. Nonsubscribers can
use this article only by special arrangement. For purchase
information, see end of text. 
 By TOMAS ELOY MARTINEZ  
 c.2000 New York Times Special Features  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The writer Jorge Luis Borges once said that history's greatest
teachers were oral teachers. But man still searches in books for
visionary wisdom and that breath of eternity that seems
unattainable anywhere else: not in the fleeting images of movies,
nor in the virtual navigation of the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Bookstores are an infinite breeding ground of thieves,
dust-jacket readers, penniless students, people searching for
pearls of wisdom, conversationalists, the idle, the handicapped and
those who aspire to Parnassus. In mammoth bookstores this wildlife
increases proportionately and the cellars, the hidden shelves and
corners become ideal places for these visitors to confidently
reveal their true selves.
</P>
<P>
   New York has the honor of being home to two of the largest
bookstores in the world. ``The Guiness Book of Records'' confers
first place to Barnes &AMP; Noble, at the corner of 5th Avenue and 18th
Street, with its 12.5 miles of shelves. In this enormous space,
however, there is such an immense quantity of old best sellers, so
many dead pages of dictionaries and kitchen recipes (an average of
50 copies for each title) that those 12.5 miles can be reviewed in
half an hour.
</P>
<P>
   The real paradise of bibliophiles, though, is The Strand
Bookstore which boasts that in the dusty corridors of its central
building at Broadway and 12th Street you can find any title you
desire. The Strand's publicity is modest. It mentions an inventory
of 2 million books. In fact, it is 3 million. There's reputed to be
8 miles of shelves. But actually, there are nearly 10, plus another
one-third mile of rare books kept in the building next-door and of
course the one-and-a-quarter miles of shelves at the Wall Street
Annex, at John Street.
</P>
<P>
   The Strand's charm is not in its quaint and ancient image nor in
its 160 incredibly erudite employees, who can tell you which shelf
in the cellar will proffer a collection of Tiffany's catalogs or
which area of the Science Section is home to the 10 to 12
encyclopedias of exotic or extinct fish that the bookstore has
acquired over the last three years. No. The real attraction is the
fact that everything is half price.
</P>
<P>
   Several signs advertise recently published books at half price
over the tables near the entrance, where boys, languid as algae,
and frenetic matrons with busy hands battle each other with more
passion than at a Macy's sale.
</P>
<P>
   On my first visit, a very severe looking lady who, losing her
self-control and startling those nearby, screamed: ``Look what I
found! My God! Nasaw's Hearst for only $8! This is definitely my
lucky day.'' She was talking about ``The Chief,'' David Nasaw's
excellent biography of newspaper tycoon William Randolph Hearst, a
book nobody'd dare put on a bargain table and that even the
cheapest bookstore would not sell for less than $30.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody in the bookstore converged on the table to see if they
could find another copy, but in vain; the same miracle rarely
occurs twice at The Strand.
</P>
<P>
   Three or four years ago a miracle, still talked about today, did
happen to Fred Bass, son of the founder and the bookstore's oracle
of last resort for obscure inquiries. Bass bought from an old house
on Manhattan's East Side a collection of 100 volumes of first
editions, knowing that many customers looked for such books. The
collection included a copy of ``The Great Gatsby,'' another of
Hemingway's ``A Farewell to Arms,'' and also of ``Virgil's Death,''
by Hermann Broch.
</P>
<P>
   The crown jewel of the collection was a box that had never been
opened. Inside was supposed to be one of the 100 numbered volumes
of ``Ulysses,'' by James Joyce _ published in 1922 by Shakespeare
and Co. in Paris _ that were distributed only among the writer's
friends and editor, Sylvia Beach. Since nobody knew what kind of
condition the book was in, Bass agreed to pay $3,000, sight unseen,
for the contents of the box.
</P>
<P>
   It was winter, Christmas Eve, and the sky was red and full of
snow. When the bookstore closed its doors that night a little after
9:30, Bass, his 20-year-old daughter Nancy and Marvin Mondlin, the
Rare Books Section's expert, tackled the box, sealed on one side
with sealing wax. On the other side they could detect the dolorous
tracks of moths. The three held their breath. Opening it, Bass
found in perfect condition not one, but two volumes of that
mythical edition, each bound in brown leather and signed by Joyce
himself. Inscribed in the colophons were their numbers of origin:
66 and 67.
</P>
<P>
   The first Strand Bookstore, founded by Benjamin Bass in 1929,
was a little store _ originally a used-books exchange _ on 8th
Street, in Greenwich Village near New York University. When
Benjamin moved to 4th Avenue, again close to Greenwich Village, he
discovered that big editorial houses occasionally sold what they
called ``printing overruns'' at very low prices. Bass, keeping a
narrow margin of profit for himself, would sell those books at 50
or 60 percent less than his competitors. By 1955 his store had
grown so much that he had to move again, opening The Strand at
Broadway and 12th Street.
</P>
<P>
   The 3 million books there today are arranged in alphabetical
order. Between 12 and 14 employees constantly glide along the
corridors, returning books to their correct places after customers
glance at them. Some of the sections in the furthest corners of the
bookstore _ ``Religion,'' ``Political Sciences'' and ``Science'' _
are in themselves complete bookstores.
</P>
<P>
   There are tables full of volumes for 48 cents or five for $2,
that in no way can be considered trash. Once, on one of those
tables, I found an edition of ``Suspense,'' by Joseph Conrad, dated
1925 (maybe a first edition), a ``Theory of Semiotics'' by Umberto
Eco edited by Bloomington University Press and a critic's copy of
Toni Morrison's ``The Bluest Eye.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside, several steps beyond the mobile bookstands that defy
the biting winter wind, New York seems a civilized and almost
benevolent city. Round the corner from The Strand, in front of
Union Square, the office building of publishers Farrar Straus &AMP;
Giroux towers over the many street vendors peddling roasted
chestnuts and pretzels with mustard.
</P>
<P>
   Further south, cinematography or comparative literature students
flutter along the sidewalks among New York University's violet
pennants. And in the local Irish pubs, more serious types, fueled
by torrents of beer, talk of changing the world.
</P>
<P>
   At nightfall, couples, arms about each other, approach movie
theaters or music stores to window-shop while they sway to a music
only they can hear. The Strand closes at 9:30, after 12 hours of
bustle, and its shelves, now darkened, disappear like birds in the
night.
</P>
<P>
   (Tomas Eloy Martinez is the author of ``The Peron Novel'' and
``Santa Evita.'' He is chairman of the Latin American studies
department at Rutgers University and travels widely as an editor
and journalist.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NONSUBSCRIBERS: To publish a ``separate-buy'' feature article, it
must be purchased. Please contact one of these sales
representatives:
</P>
<P>
   --U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.
</P>
<P>
   --Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942.
</P>
<P>
   --Latin America: ANA PENA in New York, 212-499-3333; fax,
212-499-3382. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
