<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 12:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5699 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      08-08 0900
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     GORE PICKS UP A FEW SYLLABLES OF CREDIBILITY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ROB MORSE  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Vice President Al Gore picked Connecticut Sen.
Joseph Lieberman as his running mate, and the media were off to the
races _ make that religions and moralisms.
</P>
<P>
   Has Gore deflected Republican moral attacks by choosing the
senator who made Bill Clinton say he was sorry for lying about his
affair with Monica Lewinsky?
</P>
<P>
   Can a Jew be elected vice president, especially an Orthodox Jew
who doesn't work on the Sabbath? Never mind the fact that vice
presidents don't work any day of the week. Never mind that Ronald
Reagan quit working at sundown every day.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman himself has called for religion to be part of public
life, and now it is in a big way, at least on the talk shows. But
forget religion. This is the age of superficiality in politics, as
Reagan, Clinton and George W. Bush all have proved. A politically
astute friend raises the biggest problem of all.
</P>
<P>
   ``What does `Gore-Lieberman' look like on a bumper sticker?''
she said. ``How do you fit it on a button? How can you say it?''
</P>
<P>
   That's it. The question isn't one of potential anti-Semitism but
of anti-syllabicism.
</P>
<P>
   In the last century, there have been only three presidents with
one-syllable names, Taft, Ford and Bush. Only one had a vice
president with more than two syllables in his last name.
</P>
<P>
   That was Gerald Ford's vice president Nelson Rockefeller.
``Ford'' and ``Rockefeller'' never had to be squeezed on a button
because the two weren't elected, but took office after Nixon
resigned. And when Ford ran against Jimmy Carter, he had Bob Dole
as a running mate. It was a nice pairing for a button, but hardly
for excitement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush-Cheney'' are two short names with a pleasant ring, as
long as you don't hear what they stand for.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gore-Lieberman'' trips off the tongue about as fluidly as,
well, Gore gives a speech. It won't work on a button at all.
</P>
<P>
   Either you make Gore's name very small, which Democratic
strategists probably would like to do. Or you put Gore's name in
the middle and run Lieberman's around it like the defensive shield
it is.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, there's only one thing for the Democrats to do. They have
to print ``Al and Joe'' on all their buttons.
</P>
<P>
   It sounds like two guys who run a diner or an auto parts store.
It sounds down to earth, which is just what the Democrats need
right now.
</P>
<P>
   By picking Lieberman, Gore has hit the Republicans with a big
barrel of Shut Up. Shut up about diversity and big tents. Shut up
about the need for morality and religion in government. Shut up
about Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman, as everyone has heard in the last two days, once
called Clinton's behavior in the Monica Lewinsky matter ``sad'' and
``sordid.'' For some reason, telling the truth about Clinton's not
telling the truth won Lieberman lots of points.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman is part of a morality tag-team with Republican
moralist William Bennett. He also served on the Council of Civil
Society, made up mostly of conservatives, which issued a report on
``why democracy needs moral truths.''
</P>
<P>
   The report said America is in a moral decline that should be
stopped by strengthening obstacles to divorce, reducing sex and
violence in the media and increasing the role of religion in public
life.
</P>
<P>
   This week, religious questions are everywhere. Some of the
questions about Lieberman's Orthodox Jewish religion seem relevant,
too.
</P>
<P>
   What happens if Lieberman becomes president and the Russians
launch a nuclear attack between sundown on a Friday and sundown on
a Saturday? Will he bring in Al Haig as a Shabbas goy?
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman has been called a right-wing Democrat by some members
of his party. Why?
</P>
<P>
   One: In 1995, when California voters were asked by then-Gov.
Pete Wilson to ban affirmative action, Lieberman said he opposed
racially based affirmative action, saying that ``America's about
individuals, not averages or groups.''
</P>
<P>
   So what? Affirmative action turned out to be a loser among
voters.
</P>
<P>
   Two: Lieberman has worked ceaselessly to get the entertainment
industry to quit producing violent and sexually explicit rap music,
movies, television shows and video games.
</P>
<P>
   So what? Players of Doom don't vote.
</P>
<P>
   Three: Lieberman and values pal Bennett created ``The Silver
Sewer Award,'' which has been given to Fox TV, Jerry Springer and
CBS for putting Howard Stern on the air.
</P>
<P>
   So what? All Americans like to pretend they hate Springer and
obscenity in the media.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman may be a bluenose censor and he may want to see more
religion in the public sphere, but he's also a strong supporter of
labor unions, environmental protection, campaign finance reform,
abortion rights and gay rights. These are the kind of moral issues
liberals really care about.
</P>
<P>
   The question now is whether anything can help Gore. Has he shown
courage by picking a man of apparent integrity who happens to be
Jewish? Or is picking a man of integrity a cynical Gore move?
</P>
<P>
   At least now we have a race and a clear choice of moralistic,
boring guys. Bush and Cheney, or Al and Joe? They're as different
as day and night, and not just on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
