<HEADER>
A5702 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-ROEPER-TELEMARKETING-     08-08 0970
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROEPER-TELEMARKETING-COLUMN-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TELEMARKETING WITH A COMIC TWIST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use Tuesday, Aug. 8, or thereafter.)  
 (ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's ROEPER COLUMN. For more information about
purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of the ROEPER COLUMN _ contact one of the New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the text.) 
 By RICHARD ROEPER  
 c.2000 The Chicago Sun-Times  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   I'm warning you at the top: Don't complain to me if you buy this
CD and you find it juvenile and stupid.
</P>
<P>
   I did too. But I also laughed out loud at least a dozen times,
and that's twice as many guffaws as I got from ``Scary Movie.''
</P>
<P>
   The CD is titled ``Hey, You Called Me!'' (available at
www.heyyoucalledme.com) and it's the homemade creation of Chris,
27, who works for a Chicago advertising agency.
</P>
<P>
   Note that I'm not using Chris' last name. That's because he
doesn't want to be removed from lists used by telemarketers. That's
right, he hopes to be disturbed at home by jargon-spewing
terrorists who are capable of delivering 500-word sales pitches
without coming up for breath.
</P>
<P>
   After all, that's where the comedy is born.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, You Called Me!'' is a collection of 17 conversations
between Chris and various cubicle-dwelling drones who were
unfortunate enough to draw his name from their roster of cold
calls. Whereas the Jerky Boys had astonishing success (gold
records, tons of press, even a feature film) with prank calls they
made to businesses and individuals, Chris waits for his dupes to
reach out to him before he tries on his comedy hats.
</P>
<P>
   ``It all started over a year ago,'' he told me. ``In the
beginning of 1999, I started receiving these telemarketing calls
constantly. Finally I got fed up. I started messing with these
people _ and they took it!''
</P>
<P>
   Well yes. Imagine the lot of the telemarketer _ getting three
instant hang-ups, four ``F--- you's'' and five ``Sorry, not
interested'' responses for every hint of a nibble. If someone
sounds interested or just stays on the line, you'll keep talking to
him even if you suspect he's nuts and/or a clown.
</P>
<P>
   That's what happens on a track called ``Obsessive Compulsive.''
The telemarketer wants to send Chris ``a free, brand new pager'' _
even if that means he has to tailor the pitch to Chris' obsessive
compulsive tics.
</P>
<P>
   CHRIS: ``I have to wash my hands. I really want to hear what
you're saying, saying. I don't know if you've ever heard of
obsessive compulsive, compulsive. I want to hear what your offer
is, but I have to repeat the last word of a sentence, so please
don't feel offended, offended. I gotta wash my hands.''
</P>
<P>
   TELEMARKETER: ``I understand your hesitation sir.''
</P>
<P>
   CHRIS: ``I'm very long on habits, habits. I want to hear what
you have to say, but just bear with me, me. So it would really put
me at ease if the last word of your sentence _ just repeat it, OK?
OK? I gotta wash my hands. Hands.''
</P>
<P>
   TELEMARKETER: ``OK. ... We're sending you a full-service pager,
service pager. A value of $79.95 for no charge whatsoever.''
</P>
<P>
   CHRIS: ``You didn't say it.''
</P>
<P>
   TELEMARKETER: ``Whatsoever.''
</P>
<P>
   CHRIS: ``Thank you.''
</P>
<P>
   On and on it goes, like a 21st century Abbott and Costello
routine, with the pitchman desperately saying, ``Do you want to get
a free pager, we can set this up for you!'' even as Chris is
wailing, ``I gotta wash my hands!''
</P>
<P>
   Another tele-seller is victimized by the grade-schooler's
favorite taunting trick: Repeating whatever somebody says in a
sing-song voice.
</P>
<P>
   SALESWOMAN: ``And we'd like to send you a free gift.''
</P>
<P>
   CHRIS: ''...like to send you a free gift.''
</P>
<P>
   SALESWOMAN: ``Hello?''
</P>
<P>
   CHRIS: ``Hello?''
</P>
<P>
   SALESWOMAN: ``Can you hear me?''
</P>
<P>
   CHRIS: ``Can you hear me?''
</P>
<P>
   SALESWOMAN: ``May I continue, sir?''
</P>
<P>
   CHRIS: ''...continue sir?''
</P>
<P>
   Click.
</P>
<P>
   They want to sell him things. He wants to pretend he's in the
bathroom, or that he believes he's talking to his bookie's
enforcer.
</P>
<P>
   They want to offer him a better deal. He wants to act like a
lonely soul: ``You have my number, perhaps you'd like to get
together on a social basis ...''
</P>
<P>
   It's all very Adam Sandler-esque. There are times when you feel
sorry for the persistent, polite caller who, after all, didn't grow
up dreaming of becoming a telemarketer some day and is just trying
to scrape out a living _ but then you remember how much you HATE IT
when those people call you at home, and you cackle at the
silliness. (The names of the callers and their companies have been
edited out of the tapes.)
</P>
<P>
   My apologies to the ambitious authors, fine musicians, comedic
hopefuls and indie filmmakers who send me their stuff each month,
looking for a plug, a mention, a column, something. No doubt your
material is more worthy.
</P>
<P>
   But cheap laughs have to count for something in this deadpan
world.
</P>
<P>
   (Richard Roeper (rroeper(at)suntimes.com) is a columnist for the
Chicago Sun-Times and the co-host of ``Ebert &AMP; Roeper &AMP; the
Movies.'')
</P>
<P>
   -------------------------------------------------
</P>
