<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAMBLIN-AFRICA-AIDS-COLUMN-ADV08-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$ADV08 
 SHOULD WE SEND MONEY TO HELP AFRICA WITH ITS AIDS CRISIS?
</HEADLINE>
  For release: Tuesday, Aug. 8, or thereafter 
 (ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's HAMBLIN COLUMN. For more information about
purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy,'' contact one of the
New York Times Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of
the text.) 
 By KEN HAMBLIN  
 c.2000 Ken Hamblin   
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   According to a dispatch from the Washington Post a couple weeks
ago, our government's export-finance agency has succumbed to
political pressure and the politics of AIDS by lending up to $1
billion a year over the next five years to governments and private
health care groups in sub-Sahara Africa.
</P>
<P>
   I understand the do-gooders hope that, by distributing
AIDS-related drugs and services provided by U.S. businesses, they
may help check the spread of HIV and AIDS before black Africa is
essentially depopulated of its inhabitants.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not about to suggest that the United States turn a deaf ear
and a blind eye to the HIV and AIDS ravaged nations of Africa.
</P>
<P>
   But still, I wonder whether this is the best and most efficient
way to help, in many cases literally save, the poor souls looking
to the western world for medical relief from HIV and AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   I have doubts because of the rampant cultural, political and
moral corruption that is rife among African businessmen, political
dictators and military despots who historically have grabbed with
both hands every grain of rice or farthing that the caring nations
of the world have shipped their way.
</P>
<P>
   Delivering billions of U.S. dollars into the seemingly
bottomless pit of black African corruption may satisfy those among
us in search of an emotional placebo, but it could well be a cruel
trick to play on the men, women and children who are wasting away
from AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   Their numbers, of course, are enormous and I have written of
this atrocity on numerous occasions. According to statistics
provided by the World Health Organization and the United Nations,
AIDS is so rampant in countries like South Africa and Zimbabwe that
one fifth to a quarter of the adult population is infected. Medical
authorities predict that AIDS may claim the lives of about half of
all 15-year-olds in those nations.
</P>
<P>
   In Botswana, one in three adults are already HIV-positive _ the
highest infection rate in the world _ and two-thirds of all
15-year-old boys will fall to AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   According to a recent U.N. report:
</P>
<P>
   ``The current trends in HIV infection will increasingly have an
impact on rates of infant, child and adult mortality, life
expectancy and economic growth in many (black African) countries.''
</P>
<P>
   Peter Piot, Executive Director of UNAIDS, has warned that:
</P>
<P>
   ``The AIDS toll in hard-hit countries is altering the economic
and social fabric of society. HIV will kill more than one-third of
the young adults of countries where it has its firmest hold, yet
the global response is still just a fraction of what it could be.
We need to respond to this crisis on a massively different scale
from what has been done so far.''
</P>
<P>
   I couldn't agree more. Something massively different must be
done.
</P>
<P>
   I don't doubt that the United States is sincere about its
willingness to help the HIV/AIDS infected nations of Africa.
</P>
<P>
   But I believe that it would be wiser, and certainly in the best
interest of Africa's AIDS victims, if the United States and other
participating governments were to establish a credit fund from
which pharmaceutical companies, medical doctors and researchers
involved in trying to stem the disease would be paid for services
rendered.
</P>
<P>
   The cold truth is, that if African leaders are not circumvented
from getting their hands on that cash, black people will continue
to fall like autumn leaves.
</P>
<P>
   As usual, however, the best interests of the HIV and AIDS
infected people of sub-Sahara Africa is not the primary
consideration. That would disrupt the way business is conducted
among the fat cats in countries like South Africa, Zimbabwe and
Botswana.
</P>
<P>
   So, while the world is busy weeping for Africa's most recent
wave of victims, I feel certain that the continent's politicians
and generals have already begun to contemplate salting away a good
portion of those U.S. dollars for that political rainy day when
every black African leader is compelled to run for his life.
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Hamblin is the author, most recently, of ``Plain Talk and
Common Sense'' (Simon &AMP; Schuster, 1999). He writes a column for the
Denver Post and has been a radio talk-show host for 16 years. His
program is syndicated by American View Inc., and currently is
carried by 120 stations across the country.)
</P>
<P>
   -------------------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDITOR: Don't forget to visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site
at http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on Ken Hamblin
and other features. &QL;
</P>
