<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 12:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5719 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-FOREST-FIRES-HNS &LR;      08-08 0687
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOREST-FIRES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     FOREST MANAGEMENT WOULD CUT FIRE RISKS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DAVE SKINNER  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WHITEFISH, Mont. _ I live in Whitefish. Although the nearest
major fire is at least a hundred miles away, I can smell smoke.
It's all over the news. Even my Dad in New York called me the other
night to ask me what the hell is going on out West.
</P>
<P>
   The best way to find out is hitting the National Interagency
Fire Center's fascinating Web site (www.nifc.gov) tracking large
(over 100 acres each) wildland fire activity. Please take a look:
There are maps, links to regional fire centers, press releases,
toll-free phone numbers for fire information, and lots of
background material available.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, as of Sunday, NFIC reported 64 ``large'' wildland
fires (over 100 acres each) totaling 941,771 acres.
</P>
<P>
   So far this year, there have been 63,242 fire events burning
3,979,033 acres. By comparison, the 10-year average _ for the
entire year _ is 54,138 fires scorching 2,168,083 acres. Wow. Not
only are we looking at nearly twice the acreage burned, but we have
at least six weeks to go in a ``fire season'' that has barely
started.
</P>
<P>
   Average fire size is also up. The 10-year average is 40 acres
per fire, while the year 2000 average fire size is running at about
63 acres, 57 percent bigger. We are now facing more and bigger
fires that are obviously more difficult to control.
</P>
<P>
   So how bad will the fire season of 2000 be? In 1988, the year of
the Yellowstone fire, 7.4 million acres burned. This year may be
far worse. As of Aug. 6, 1988, 2,691,442 acres had burned, while
this year we are already at nearly 4 million. We could then expect
nearly 11 million acres to go up _ and it might be more.
</P>
<P>
   The National Weather Service is predicting dry lightning for
areas of the Pacific Northwest, which has been fairly quiet
fire-wise. Firefighting resources are already stretched tight, with
all available airborne assets at full utilization, with Marines and
Army troops on the fire lines, with deals being made to bring in
Australian and Mexican firefighters, and plans being made to fight
only fires that threaten human life. Some property, perhaps a lot
of private property, will be destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   While Congress specially appropriated $240 million in the wake
of the Los Alamos fire fiasco, Forest Service Chief Mike Dombeck
told reporters his agency is running through $15 million per day _
that's 16 days worth at current levels, and remember, in hot, dry
years the fire season often runs into October.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, $845 million was spent by federal agencies on 4.7
million acres, or $178 per acre.
</P>
<P>
   Extrapolating that out over 11 million acres of fires this year
and you get just short of $2 billion _ not adjusted for inflation,
property losses, pollution, destruction of selected critical
wildlife habitats, and not counting the utter waste of wood.
</P>
<P>
   In all fairness, NIFC also posts data on fire acreage since
World War I, and in the 1930s, the average number of fires per year
was over 167,000 fires, torching a shocking 39 million acres each
year. As late as 1953, over 10 million acres a year burned. After
World War II, of course, demand for commercial timber combined with
more sophisticated firefighting methods and equipment reduced the
acreage burned.
</P>
<P>
   Losing 11 million acres to wildfires today, however, makes it
clear that we are losing the ability to control wildfires despite
massive applications of skilled manpower and sophisticated
equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Why? As forests busily grow, they grow fuel. If that fuel isn't
removed, either through timber harvest or prescribed burns, it will
eventually and inevitably remove itself in a spectacular and deadly
manner, such as we are now witnessing.
</P>
<P>
   Can we burn safely in a tinderbox? It's obvious we can't. We
simply must conduct appropriate timber harvests alongside
appropriate burning programs, and do it as soon as we possibly can.
</P>
<P>
   If we do not _ if we simply run away _ someday we won't be able
to run fast enough.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
