<HEADLINE>
HEDGE FUNDS TRYING TO EDGE CLOSER TO PENSION CHIEFS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BETH HEALY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ MFS Investment Management is quietly rolling out a
hedge fund for pension managers and endowments, and several other
local firms best known for their prowess in mutual funds are
expected to follow suit, according to people in the industry.
</P>
<P>
   MFS, the nation's oldest fund group, is still raising money for
its hedge fund, which was launched July 1. The effort is shrouded
in the secrecy that typically surrounds these funds _ unregulated
portfolios with broad leeway to buy exotic securities and make big
bets on stocks rising or falling.
</P>
<P>
   The move comes as large institutions look to expose some of
their assets to the lucrative returns hedge funds have provided to
the wealthy for years. But pension managers say they need to break
through the mysteries and risks of hedge funds first.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are interested in looking at hedge funds,'' said Scott
Henderson, executive director of the $31 billion Massachusetts
state pension fund. But he wants the same disclosure from them that
he would have from any other portfolio manager. ``Do they own 50
stocks or five? That's very important information for me, or I
don't know if the return I'm making is worth the risk.''
</P>
<P>
   A private meeting of hedge fund managers and institutions was
held in Boston July 7 to discuss this very issue, industry sources
said. It was a kind of risk summit and a first effort to forge a
compromise on the privacy hedge fund managers say they need but
that pension managers decry.
</P>
<P>
   Massive losses in a few high-profile hedge funds in recent years
have made many pension managers nervous about diving into
the &UR;  &LR; sector.
</P>
<P>
   The 1998 Long Term Capital Management debacle sparked a global
furor over the dangers of powerful hedge funds operating in nearly
total secrecy and surprising clients with poor results.
</P>
<P>
   Julian Robertson shut down his renowned Tiger Management hedge
fund this year due to flagging performance, while heads rolled in
the shop of currency maven George Soros amid double-digit losses.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the hedge fund business is booming, as investors keep
looking for aggressive returns from managers who are paid
handsomely for their efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Assets in the sector worldwide have more than doubled since 1995
to about $450 billion at the end of last year, according to Van
Hedge Fund Advisors Inc., a Nashville, Tenn., research and
consulting firm. A decade ago, $94 billion was invested in hedge
funds.
</P>
<P>
   Firms like MFS want a share of this booming market, not least
because they can reap larger-than-normal fees. A firm might earn
0.2 to 0.4 percent of assets for managing an institutional account,
but can charge 1 to 2 percent on a hedge fund. It's also standard
for managers to pocket 20 percent of the investment returns.
</P>
<P>
   Customers expect large returns, in the realm of 20 percent to 25
percent a year, for the leap of faith they take when they hand
money over to a hedge fund. The fund managers relish the privacy
with which they are able to run money, even if their approach is as
mainstream as buying and selling hot technology stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Hedge funds operate with little oversight because they don't
have small investors as customers. They don't have to disclose
their moves to regulators or clients and typically show investors
their results only quarterly.
</P>
<P>
   MFS's fund is expected to use leverage, or to borrow to make
bets on stocks. The company declined to comment on its plans.
</P>
<P>
   Some pension managers are particularly interested in considering
hedge funds because they worry about the bull market petering out.
With a long-short strategy, for example, a manager could bet that
some stocks would rise while simultaneously betting that others
would fall.
</P>
<P>
   But the fears persist. Said Tony Ryan, chief of corporate
pension-fund sales for State Street Global Advisors in Boston,
``Few pension execs want to wake up and find out they lost a
significant amount of money because of a series of trades a hedge
fund has made.''
</P>
<P>
   State Street already offers hedge funds to institutions,
particularly to endowment funds. For fund firms like MFS, which
have seen key managers leave to start their own hedge funds, the
vehicle offers an attractive carrot to employees. More established
hedge funds like institutional money because it tends to stick with
a manager longer than do the assets of wealthy individuals.
</P>
<P>
   Sources said Putnam Investments, through its T.H. Lee, Putnam
Capital arm, is planning to introduce hedge funds. Fidelity
Investments may be mulling such a product as well.
</P>
<P>
   Maarten Nederlof, chief of Deutsche Banc Securities' pension
strategies group, said the disagreement between institutions and
hedge fund managers could linger: ``The institutions really are
interested,'' he said. But ``there's definitely more talk than
there is action.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
