<HEADLINE>
`FRANCHISING GURU' STRUGGLES IN OFF YEAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLS STEIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some days you get the chicken, some days the chicken gets you.
</P>
<P>
   George Naddaff, the entrepreneur who became famous by building
Boston Chicken into a national fast-food phenomenon, is struggling
through a year he'd probably prefer to forget.
</P>
<P>
   Corners Inc., the Framingham, Mass. picture-framing company in
which Naddaff invested both time and money, recently filed for
Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection. The company, once called Frame
King Express, and Naddaff parted ways about two months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Mortgage.com, a Florida company that counts Naddaff as its vice
chairman and a major shareholder, has seen its stock tumble from a
high of $17.50 last fall to just over a buck per share.
</P>
<P>
   Worst of all, Naddaff has been forced to suspend other business
interests and jump in as acting chief executive of Ranch 1 Chicken
Inc., another fast-food chain that specializes in grilled, skinless
chicken breast sandwiches for the health-conscious crowd. He had
been a big investor since 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Ranch 1 had already shelved plans for an IPO when its former
chief executive and vice chairman were indicted two months ago with
more than 100 other people in a huge federal case targeting
organized crime involvement in the stock market. The company itself
was never charged with any wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   Naddaff, 70, of Newton, Mass., has a long history of working an
entire portfolio of budding business prospects at the same time.
He'd be happy to rattle off a few current prospects without getting
into details: companies in the candy business, the concierge
business, and even one bundling energy services.
</P>
<P>
   But there's no getting around the fact that this year already
has held more than its share of very visible disappointments.
Naddaff will tell you that, in so many words.
</P>
<P>
   ``As an investor in companies, you win some and you lose some.
What can I say?''
</P>
<P>
   Like baseball players, serial entrepreneurs aim for a solid
batting average and suffer the occasional whiff, but they can
become immortalized with a single swing in just the right
situation.
</P>
<P>
   In a way, this is the story of Naddaff and Boston Chicken, a
concept created by Arthur Cores and Kip Kolow. Cores and Kolow
eventually sold the franchising rights to Naddaff, who rolled the
concept out through the Northeast and built the company into a
high-profile success.
</P>
<P>
   Boston Chicken eventually changed its name and, later, went
belly up, but that was long past Naddaff's watch. He had sold the
company in 1992 to two former Blockbuster Entertainment Corp.
executives, and it went public the following year. The company
filed for bankruptcy protection in 1998 and most of its business
was liquidated this year in a sale to McDonald's Corp.
</P>
<P>
   But Naddaff became sort of a small-business cult hero because of
his Boston Chicken experience and has been described as a
``franchising guru.''
</P>
<P>
   Naddaff is known for his boundless enthusiasm, so it was no
surprise when he popped up in the press last year talking about big
expansion plans and a possible IPO for Corners, the custom framing
business.
</P>
<P>
   Rapid expansion appeared to be the main problem when the company
filed for Chapter 11 protection in US Bankruptcy Court July 28. The
chain had already cut the number of its stores by 10 to a total of
31.
</P>
<P>
   ``The company had grown probably too quickly and was not able to
keep up with its debt,'' said chief executive Stuart Needleman, who
joined the company about four weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Needleman said Corners needed time to regroup, but he was
confident it could regain its health while the stores continue to
operate. ``Everything is business as usual,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Naddaff had invested in Corners and joined the board at a time
when several venture capital firms also were sinking money into the
business. ``I was just one of the investors,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Another Naddaff investment, Mortgage
</P>
<P>
   .com Inc., fits the profile of any number of Internet-oriented
public companies. And that isn't good news for shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which went public nearly a year ago, has a track
record of operating losses and even suffered declining revenues as
it refashioned itself into a business-to-business model. The stock,
which went public at $8 per share and more than doubled by last
fall, has been sinking steadily ever since. It finished at $1.03
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything `dot-com' is having a tough time,'' said Naddaff, who
has owned or held options to a total of 1.6 million shares.
``Internally, they're doing very well.''
</P>
<P>
   Naddaff seemed to have another chance for a public stock score
at Ranch 1, one of his many food-oriented ventures with a growing
following.
</P>
<P>
   The company put its IPO on hold early this year, saying the
timing was not right. But by May, Naddaff and chief executive
Sebastian Rametta were still named finalists for Ernst &AMP; Young's
Entrepreneur of the Year award.
</P>
<P>
   Then the roof fell in. Rametta and James Chickara, the company's
vice chairman, were accused of being associates of the Colombo
crime family in the FBI's sweeping stock market investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Naddaff, who had been the company's chairman, stepped in as
interim CEO and still serves in that role. With the IPO off the
table for now, Naddaff said he is trying to secure financing for
Ranch 1 before finding a permanent chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Naddaff has put other business interests on the shelf, including
1RoofRealty.com of Cambridge, Mass., where he is chairman.
``Clearly my energies were needed (on Ranch 1) and that's where I
put them,'' he said. ``I'm in New York four days a week and, at age
70, I don't want to feel like I'm jumping on planes back and
forth.''
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of the setbacks, Naddaff continues to talk
optimistically about solving problems and, of course, the chance to
find new companies for investment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The climate is still out there,'' he said. ``It's a question
of how many deals can you pay attention to.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
