<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 13:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5735 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-SCI-NONFAMILY-EMBRYOS     08-08 1763
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-NONFAMILY-EMBRYOS-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (Has sidebar, ADOPTED-EMBRYO)  
 EMBRYOS ON ICE: A TROUBLING NEW FORM OF ADOPTION  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ADAM PERTMAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   They are the microscopic carriers of the chromosomes of the
couples who created them, the children-to-be of infertile men and
women to whom they provide a hope of biological parenthood. But
they also are the ultimate orphans of new technology, the vast
majority stored indefinitely in liquid nitrogen without any
prospect for being implanted in anyone's womb.
</P>
<P>
   Medical clinics nationwide are increasingly using these frozen
embryos _ left over from in-vitro fertilization treatments _ in
what has essentially become a new form of adoption. Infertile
patients who provided neither the eggs nor the sperm used to
produce them are receiving this surplus of embryos, raising
provocative questions about family relationships and genetic
disclosure.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the process is taking place in the absence of state
and federal laws, professional oversight, or thorough examination
of the long-term impact on the people involved.
</P>
<P>
   Child-welfare specialists and medical ethicists worry about
where this may lead. Unscrupulous practitioners, they warn, could
sell frozen embryos, a practice that may or may not be legal since
state statutes prohibit the sale of human beings, but don't address
the thorny question of whether fertilized eggs fall into that
category. And even well-intentioned clinicians could inadvertently
coerce poor patients into ``donating'' their frozen embryos in
exchange for fertility treatments, which can cost tens of thousands
of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no way to know . . . but I'd be very surprised if some
of this weren't going on already,'' said Madelyn Freundlich,
executive director of the Evan B. Donaldson Adoption Institute in
New York and the author of a new study on the parallels between
adoption and assisted reproduction.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Cooper, a psychologist at the Reproductive Science Center
in Waltham and a nationally recognized expert on the subject,
agreed. ``There already are clinics doing donation in a very
cavalier manner,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   After helping a few clients provide their unused embryos to
other infertile couples, officials at the Waltham clinic held a
retreat several years ago to reassess what they were doing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of us, including me, came to the conclusion that we were
crossing the line from medical assistance for the person who came
to us for treatment . . . to effectively facilitating a new form of
adoption,'' Cooper said. ``We're not social workers or adoption
professionals trained to do that. So we stopped.''
</P>
<P>
   No governmental or medical group tracks how many embryos are
stored in cryogenic states by the more than 300 clinics in the
United States that offer in-vitro fertilization, but experts
estimate that the count has doubled, to about 200,000, in just the
past three years. A spot check of the 10 in-vitro fertilization
clinics in Massachusetts indicated there are 15,000 to 20,000
frozen embryos in the state.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors produce as many as a dozen embryos at a time by using
fertility drugs to stimulate the creation of eggs in a woman and
then mixing them with sperm. Just two or three embryos are
typically implanted in a woman for any one cycle, however, and the
rest are placed in liquid nitrogen.
</P>
<P>
   The vast majority are retained for use by the couples whose
genes they contain. A minority are donated for research, and a
small percentage are contributed anonymously for use by people
without the physical capability _ or, sometimes, the money _ to
attempt in-vitro fertilization on their own.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Sheryl Kingsbert of Case Western Reserve University in
Cleveland conducted a survey in which she found that 40 of the 96
facilities that responded had facilitated one or more transfers of
frozen embryos, resulting in at least 53 babies.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, hundreds, if not thousands, more donated embryos
have been implanted, specialists say, and probably have led to
scores of additional births. Because the success rates of such
procedures are steadily rising, the percentage of women who get
pregnant in this manner seems certain to keep climbing.
</P>
<P>
   Most clinics are believed to abide by guidelines for embryo
donation issued by the American Society for Reproductive Medicine
in 1998. Among other things, these call for screening to determine
whether the donated embryos might carry any diseases, for
recipients to release donors from any liability, and for donors to
relinquish all their rights to the embryos and to any children they
might produce.
</P>
<P>
   Adherence to the guidelines is voluntary, however, and there is
no mechanism for determining compliance.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no rules and no one is watching, as far as I can
tell,'' said George Annas, chairman of the law department at Boston
University's School of Public Health, and one of the country's
leading medical ethicists. ``So, we're taking a giant step forward,
in terms of the technology itself, without having resolved even the
most basic issues that it raises.''
</P>
<P>
   Even doctors who say infractions are rare acknowledge that some
clinics avail themselves so routinely of the medical technologies
available to them that they do not always consider potential
problems _ or provide couples with sufficient counseling about the
long-term consequences of their actions.
</P>
<P>
   Drawing from adoption's lessons, for instance, child-development
professionals say most children benefit from knowing about their
biological backgrounds as they get older and often want to
communicate with their genetic parents or siblings. In addition,
most genetic mothers, and sometimes fathers, decide later in life
that they want information about or contact with the children they
placed for adoption, which many specialists believe will be the
case for embryo donors as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest problem is that nobody is learning from either
adoption's past or from the similar problems we've already
encountered with anonymous sperm and egg donation,'' said Susan
Crockin, a lawyer based in Newton and a member of an American Bar
Association panel that is formulating a model act it hopes states
will use to pass laws on the ethical use of frozen embryos.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doctors have to realize that they are now doing much more than
just providing medical treatment to individual patients,'' Crockin
added. ``They have crossed the bridge into the uncharted waters of
family formation.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Alan S. Penzias, director of the egg-donor program at Boston
IVF, the largest infertility clinic in the country, said such
questions are a principal reason his facility and many others
around the nation don't offer embryo donation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people who do it are almost always trying to do
good,'' he said. ``But it's not being done in an organized fashion
where people are sitting down and saying, `Let's talk about this
before we do it.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Existing programs are usually small, Penzias added, because a
vast majority of couples decide not to contribute their embryos
once they are informed of all the ramifications.
</P>
<P>
   The considerations are generally far different at the receiving
end. Many infertile people are so eager to become pregnant that
they are willing to cope with whatever consequences may arise _
such as telling their children why they have little knowledge about
their backgrounds _ and feel less threatened if they can get
embryos from unidentified donors.
</P>
<P>
   It was this combination of low supply and high demand that led
Mark Sauer, director of reproductive technology at Columbia
University, to take a daring step several years ago: Doctors at his
clinic began implanting embryos that the clinic had created itself
using eggs and sperm from people who did not donate as couples and
who typically didn't know each other.
</P>
<P>
   Critics, including other fertility specialists, decried the
practice as a step toward ``designer'' babies, children with
specific traits picked by designating whose sperm and eggs would be
used. A state task force formed to study the issue also raised
concerns that Sauer's work could lead to the formation of large
banks of human embryos from which doctors or their patients could
effectively shop for their selections.
</P>
<P>
   Sauer halted the procedure after the task force issued its
report, and his clinic now creates embryos with donor eggs only if
the recipients choose the sperm provider. Specialists, however, say
some other facilities around the country are still using the
controversial technique of creating and implanting embryos that the
clinics, rather than the egg and sperm donors together, have
decided to create.
</P>
<P>
   In Massachusetts, most clinics appear to be proceeding
cautiously. Dr. Mark D. Hornstein, clinical director of the Center
for Reproductive Medicine at Brigham &AMP; Women's Hospital in Boston,
said his facility offers embryo donation only under narrow
conditions: It does not advertise its program, so as not to
stimulate demand; donors and recipients are identified, usually
know each other already, and agree to their matches among
themselves; and everyone receives intensive counseling.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Hornstein said, the program has performed only a
``small number'' of implants during its two years in existence.
</P>
<P>
   Most specialists believe demand for donated embryos will
continue to grow, mainly because many people want the experience
the raising of a baby from birth rather than, say, adopting an
older child. But money is also a factor.
</P>
<P>
   A single in-vitro fertilization cycle at a typical Massachusetts
clinic costs about $5,600 if no supplementary procedures are used
and up to $8,000 if they are. Massachusetts is one of only seven
states in which insurance firms pay nearly all the costs of
reproductive procedures; in other states, the corresponding prices
range from $8,000 to double that amount.
</P>
<P>
   Implantation of a frozen embryo, by contrast, costs as little as
$1,200 anywhere, although the process does not guarantee either a
pregnancy or a live birth.
</P>
<P>
   ``As this field continues, there will be mounting pressure for
this, not only because of rising demand, but because we keep
producing more and more embryos,'' said Michael Lee, laboratory
director at the Fertility Center of New England in Reading, Mass.
``Something's going to have to be done with them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
