<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-NOTES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THOSE UNUSUAL SIGHTS ON THE GROUND BELOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD P. CARPENTER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Your plane is coming in for a landing. You look down at the
fields and the roads and then the buildings, and you ask yourself:
</P>
<P>
   ``What the heck is that?''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to well-known sights, some cities have unusual
buildings or other structures that leave airborne travelers
wondering just what they are looking at. Consider the structures in
these cities:
</P>
<P>
   --Nashville. The tall building sports twin spires and a sloped
roof, a look that has earned it the nickname ``The Batman
Building'' because of its resemblance to the Caped Crusader. It's
actually Tennessee headquarters of Bell South.
</P>
<P>
   --Chicago. That white, domed building is the Baha'i House of
Worship, a nine-sided temple that comes together at the apex of a
dome.
</P>
<P>
   --Dallas/Fort Worth. The large, square building is emblazoned
with the words ``Grapevine Mills.'' But this is no factory or
processing plant; it's a shopping-entertainment complex that is one
of the most-visited attractions in the area. (Grapevine Mills is
also the source for the information on these buildings, not that we
weren't familiar with most of them. Well, some of them.)
</P>
<P>
   --Boston. That new building on the waterfront, which even some
Bostonians aren't yet familiar with, is not a modern lighthouse, as
it might appear to be when illuminated. It's the Hyatt Harborside,
with its distinctive Lighthouse Tower.
</P>
<P>
   --Miami. There's a huge outline of an airplane atop this round
facility. It's the new American Airlines Arena, and the airplane
design was added specifically for overhead travelers. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Travel Trivia: Which major US city has the lowest average relative
humidity? (Answer at end of column.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
In a name: There is a town in Texas called Ding Dong. (With thanks
to faithful contributor Mike Schuster of Foxborough.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
Quotable: ``American tourists like to arrive in a place with no
knowledge about where they have landed. They bring with them their
misconceptions, an amazing lack of geographic knowledge and, best
of all, wallets full of American money'' _ Sandra Porteous, in a
column titled ``Welcome to Canada'' in The Daily News of Halifax,
Nova Scotia. (She's exaggerating about everything but the money . .
. isn't she?) &QL; 
 &QL; 
Today's loopy law: Massachusetts forbids allowing gorillas to ride
in the back seat of a car. &QL; 
 &QL; 
The pause that costs: A Coca-Cola costs about $14.50 at the Westin
Tokyo. But the hotel is so attractive you almost don't mind paying.
Almost. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Sign of the times: A sign at Dinosaur World in Ossineke, Mich.,
informs you: ``Open Everyday except when closed.'' (With thanks to
the offbeat quarterly Two Lane Roads.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
Patriots galore: Captain Samuel Cherry's Company, of the New
Hampshire 2d Infantry Regiment, is ready to re-fight the
Revolutionary War. The reenactment group will pitch camp alongside
the Franklin Pierce Homestead in Hillsborough, N.H., Saturday and
Sunday, Aug. 19-20, from 10 a.m to 5 p.m. There will be military
drills, including one for children, musket firing, period cooking
and crafts, marching, the ``punishing'' of a deserter, and a
military fashion show. Also featured will be campfire songs,
demonstration battles, 18th-century weapons, and moving tales of
Hillsborough area men who fought for freedom. Admission is $4 for
adults, $2 for children, and $9 per family; children under 5 are
free. For more information, call the Hillsborough Historical
Society at 603-478-3165. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Did you guess it? Las Vegas, with 31 percent average relative
humidity, according to the National Climatic Data Center. &QL; 
 &QL; 
