<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 13:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5737 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u t BC-TRAVEL-SICK-BOS &LR;      08-08 1387
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-SICK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN ADVENTURE INTO THE UNEXPECTED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES BALL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Perfect, trouble-free vacations tend to be dull.
</P>
<P>
   That's the conclusion my wife and I have come to, perhaps as a
hedge against expectations gone awry or, more likely, unexpected
travails (notice how closely the word resembles ``travels'') such
as illness or even the unsettling news of a plane crash.
</P>
<P>
   For example, picture yourself miserable with fever in a lodge in
the remote interior of Costa Rica.
</P>
<P>
   Well, not Dr.-Livingston-I-presume remote, but surely, we
thought, there would not be a doctor within miles of our cloud
forest. Aha, but just as surely the hotel manager located a
physician from San Jose, the capital, who was serving a clinic in a
nearby town.
</P>
<P>
   When he arrived, looking young enough to have graduated from
medical school the day before and carrying his medical supplies in
what appears to be a fishing tackle box, we were less than
confident but nevertheless glad to see him. Anyway, he was
central-casting handsome and Harriet immediately fell in love.
</P>
<P>
   He asked my age, probably wondering whether I was worth saving,
and began his examination.
</P>
<P>
   His effort to peer into my ears ended in failure because the
batteries were dead in the instrument he used. No matter, he said,
as he announced my temperature in Celsius and was unable to convert
it into Fahrenheit. Not much fever, he said, in halting English,
dismissing it with a wave of his hand.
</P>
<P>
   I was not surprised. I had begun to feel better, perhaps
defensively.
</P>
<P>
   After checking my lungs with a stethoscope that presumably did
work, he said I ought to have an antibiotic and a shot that would
make me feel better for 24 hours, allowing us to continue our trip.
</P>
<P>
   What kind of shot, we asked. Something along the lines of an
anti-inflammatory, he replied. (We later learned it was a steroid.)
We had never heard of such a shot for what appeared to be an
upper-respiratory infection. But we told him to go ahead _ the
promise of a full day of wellness was too good to pass up _ as long
as a reaction was unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   He had never seen a reaction, he said, but we did not get the
sense that he had been practicing long enough to have seen many
reactions, bad or good.
</P>
<P>
   He retrieved antibiotics, a vial of medicine, and a syringe from
his box and glanced at his watch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, I have to go,'' he nearly shouted. ``My girlfriend has
come by bus from San Jose and she is waiting for me in the rain.
I'll be back in 20 minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   He dashed from the room as my wife and I looked at each other in
bemusement, and managed our first good laugh of an otherwise
difficult day.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty minutes later, he knocked on the door and entered with a
drop-dead gorgeous woman and, by now, I was feeling much, much
better.
</P>
<P>
   In an aside, he told my wife that he brought his girlfriend to
the room to prove to her that he was indeed with a patient. She
introduced herself as a pharmacy student from San Jose.
</P>
<P>
   We made a cozy group as he filled the syringe and plunged it
into my backside.
</P>
<P>
   I paid him $100 ($60 for the visit and $40 for the medicines)
and a day later considered it money well spent.
</P>
<P>
   I felt terrific.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A few days later, I found there are times you just have to
deceive your wife.
</P>
<P>
   We were checking out of the lodge before driving back to San
Jose, where we would stay overnight before flying on a local
airline to Quepos, a resort area on the Pacific coast.
</P>
<P>
   A newspaper lay on the counter, its front page filled with the
photograph of a plane that had crashed into a building. My limited
Spanish told me it was the same carrier we were to fly the next day
and that four people had been killed. The plane had left San Jose
on a flight to a resort on the Atlantic coast.
</P>
<P>
   As my wife approached the checkout desk, I turned the paper over
and went about my business.
</P>
<P>
   Harriet is a resolute traveler, but she does not suffer planes
gladly, particularly the small variety. And the plane we were
flying on the next day was a puddle-jumper with room for about six
passengers, including the empty copilot's seat.
</P>
<P>
   Now, if she were to decide not to fly from San Jose to Quepos, a
20-minute flight over mountains, we would be facing a four- or
five-hour drive over roads that inspire T-shirt messages in Costa
Rica along the lines of ``I survived the drive to Monteverde.''
</P>
<P>
   So it was time for some mild deception.
</P>
<P>
   In our hotel room in San Jose, I flicked on the television but
quickly turned it off when the crash appeared on the screen.
</P>
<P>
   Then, with my wife in the bathroom, I placed a call to one of
our children to tell him, in case he or the others read of the
crash in the newspaper (and they did), that we were OK.
</P>
<P>
   As I was saying goodbye, Harriet reappeared in the room and
heard me mention my son's name.
</P>
<P>
   I hung up, but she wanted to know why I had called home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, because of the change in our plans I wanted him to know
where we'd be staying,'' I lied.
</P>
<P>
   We had, in fact, altered our plans slightly, and she accepted
the explanation.
</P>
<P>
   So far, so good.
</P>
<P>
   The next morning, as we took a hotel shuttle van to the airline
terminal, the driver chatted with us in fluent English and I
worried that he might mention the crash. At the terminal, just a
tiny waiting area really, a small television near the ticket
counter was on, repeatedly showing newscasts of the crash.
</P>
<P>
   It was a crowded, rather chaotic area, and Harriet settled in to
read a book while we waited, never glancing at the TV.
</P>
<P>
   Five of us finally boarded the plane, including an American
couple who seemed exceedingly edgy. I wondered if they knew about
the crash and, if so, hoped they wouldn't mention it, at least
until we were in the air. My own feelings at this point were that
the law of averages was working very much in our favor, in that two
crashes in as many days weren't a likely event. I don't know if
Harriet would have taken comfort from that observation.
</P>
<P>
   The flight was uneventful except for a few down currents over
the mountains and before you could say, ``There's nothing to be
worried about,'' we were on our final approach to the airport
outside Quepos.
</P>
<P>
   Scratch the word ``airport.''
</P>
<P>
   Peering out the window, I could see nothing but jungle below as
the plane descended ever lower, until finally a narrow, unpaved
strip appeared, slicing through the vegetation. We landed with
barely a bump and taxied to the terminal, again something of a
misnomer since it consisted of an enlarged hut that fit in rather
well with the leafy surroundings.
</P>
<P>
   Harriet, perhaps more resolute that I gave her credit for (she
is an uncomplaining traveling companion), hopped off the plane and
into the van taking us to our hotel without complaint or comment.
</P>
<P>
   Still, we had to return to San Jose several days later, so I
decided to keep my secret to save her any unnecessary worry.
</P>
<P>
   My effort ended in the hotel lobby when an American tourist
pointedly asked if we had heard about the crash.
</P>
<P>
   I tried to shush him, but it was too late.
</P>
<P>
   It was time to let go of my deception and hope that Harriet
would forgive me (and, more importantly, be willing to fly back to
San Jose).
</P>
<P>
   As I confessed, she gave me instant absolution, saying she would
have flown on a kite to avoid another torturous trip on unpaved
roads.
</P>
<P>
   The return flight was particularly smooth, unburdened by the
weight of my guilt.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Finally, there are times when misadventure can convey better
than anything else the nature of the people you are visiting.
</P>
<P>
   When I became seasick on a coastal cruise in a small sailboat,
the captain, without our asking, waved down a charter fishing boat
returning to port and asked its captain if he would take Harriet
and me aboard.
</P>
<P>
   We made the transfer and found that the owner was on an outing
with his family, all of whom greeted us warmly as we came on board.
</P>
<P>
   They couldn't have been friendlier or more helpful _ like
virtually all the Costa Ricans we met.
</P>
<P>
   More evidence, still, that when bad things happen on a trip,
they can produce memories rich in understanding and, yes, laughter.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Charles Ball is the Globe's summer intern adviser.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
