<SLUG> BC-FBN-NINERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     49ERS WEIGHING HOW TO PLAY ITS QUARTERBACK QUARTET 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By BRUCE ADAMS  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   STOCKTON, Calif. _ Coach Steve Mariucci of the San Francisco
49ers puts the best spin on the situation, calling it ``healthy''
and ``good for everybody.'' But the fact is, he has a bit of a
problem on his hands.
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers have four quarterbacks in camp _ starting quarterback
Jeff Garcia, third-round draft pick Giovanni Carmazzi, eighth-year
vagabond Rick Mirer and seventh-round pick Tim Rattay.
</P>
<P>
   Something has to give. Mariucci said it was possible that the
team could keep four quarterbacks during the regular season, though
he has hinted he would prefer to go with three. With three
exhibition games remaining, and a need to give more practice time
to quarterbacks who will play the most in games, now and in the
regular season, the clock is ticking.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where they came from and how they got here doesn't have as
much to do with it as how ready they are,'' Mariucci said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to find a way to continue to evaluate four guys, some
in games, some team work, seven-on-seven drills, individual drills,
and after practice and in tests.''
</P>
<P>
   Mariucci is firm on one point. Garcia remains his starting
quarterback, even though he hasn't been able to sustain drives or
get the ball into the hands of the 49ers talented wide receivers in
two exhibition appearances.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel that Jeff is getting better and better,'' Mariucci
said Monday in a conference call with reporters. ``Whether that has
showed up statistically or not is another thing.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said that Garcia's evaluation would not be based just on
his relatively brief appearances in two games. ``He has learned and
he has improved,'' Mariucci said. ``He has a better understanding
now of what we're doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Mirer, with his fifth team in five years, relieved Garcia in
Saturday's 23-20 exhibition loss to the San Diego Chargers and in
the second half led two touchdown drives _ the team's first two of
the young exhibition season.
</P>
<P>
   ``He graded out fairly well,'' Mariucci said. ``There were some
plays he'd like to have back. There were things he did that were
good decisions. He showed some athleticism, he showed some poise,
he showed some veteran qualities.''
</P>
<P>
   Rattay came into the game later and came close to putting
together a scoring drive, with the team a foot short of the end
zone, and the winning touchdown, as time ran out.
</P>
<P>
   ``They all show potential and they all show good things,''
Mariucci said. That's especially true of Mirer, who on Saturday had
clearly the best effort by a 49er quarterback to date.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least he showed that he's worth continuing to look at
because he did some good things,'' Mariucci said. ``Does that
complicate it a bit? Well, good. That's a good problem to have.''
</P>
<P>
   Mariucci said coaches would be meeting soon to determine where
the team will go from here with the four quarterbacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to consider how well they've been playing, not only
in games but in practice as well,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   One solution would be to keep four quarterbacks on the roster,
with one taking a slot on the practice squad. ``It's not out of the
question,'' the coach said. ``It's a possibility.''
</P>
<P>
   In two exhibition games, Garcia has completed 11 passes in 14
attempts for 76 yards. He has been sacked four times and
intercepted once.
</P>
<P>
   Rattay, also in two games, is 14-for-31, for 170 yards. He has
been sacked four times.
</P>
<P>
   Carmazzi is 3-for-7 for 19 yards, with two sacks.
</P>
<P>
   Mirer is 12-for-23, for 103 yards, with one sack.
</P>
</TEXT>
