<HEADLINE>
SENATOR, WIFE DISAPPOINTED, RELIEVED AT THE SAME TIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GLEN JOHNSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For Senator John F. Kerry, Monday was the second
personal setback in a little more than a week, but far from the
worst.
</P>
<P>
   For his wife, Teresa Heinz, there was pain in seeing her spouse
passed over for a job he wanted.
</P>
<P>
   Yet for both of them, Al Gore's decision to choose Senator
Joseph I. Lieberman of Connecticut instead of Kerry as this year's
Democratic vice presidential candidate brought an unexpectedly
liberating end to a three-month selection process.
</P>
<P>
   To Kerry, the end seemed less a setback to his political career,
even a mortal blow, as some speculated, but perhaps the beginning
of the next phase. He said he will not feel the constraints of
being a vice presidential nominee as he speaks out about education,
health care and the environment, and as he ponders his own possible
bid for the White House should the Gore-Lieberman ticket falter.
</P>
<P>
   For Heinz, who agonized by her husband's side all weekend inside
their Georgetown home, there will be no ``10-fold'' repeat of the
scrutiny she and her husband faced in his 1996 reelection campaign
against former governor William F. Weld. Instead, she is free of
the rigors of the campaign trail and able to pursue the
all-important job of doting over her first granddaughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel sort of liberated in a sense,'' said Kerry, arm wrapped
around his wife's waist, after Gore's selection was leaked to the
media. ``I think it's always good to be the master of your own
destiny, and there are mixed blessings in being part of something
else that you don't have that kind of control over.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he had just missed his best chance to one day be
president, the 57-year-old laughed and replied: ``I consider myself
a young man. I've got a lot of energy and a lot of passion about
the issues and I intend to fight for the election of Al Gore and
Joe Lieberman. If that doesn't pan out for us as a party, I will
regret it because I think it's important to us as a party, but if
it doesn't, after that I'll consider where I am and what options
are available.''
</P>
<P>
   Heinz, meanwhile, dispensed her views as she poured peach iced
tea to reporters waiting on the stoop for reaction to Gore's
decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, in Portugese, there's a very good saying. It says,
`God writes straight on crooked lines.' So there's a meaning for
everything. .. . . You just have to write your own fortunes, and I
certainly know in my life there's been a lot of unexplained things
. . . and you just roll with it,'' she said. Her first husband,
Pennsylvania Senator John Heinz, was killed in a 1991 midair
collision.
</P>
<P>
   Then, flashing an impish grin, Heinz added: ``I told you, I was
going to see my granddaughter today, which I would have not been
able to see.''
</P>
<P>
   In public comments and a private interview over lunch after
Monday's decision, Kerry talked about regaining control of his
political future while Heinz talked about the freedom to return to
what she described as their full and happy lives.
</P>
<P>
   The senator said he had given ``no thought about it, none
whatsoever'' to the prospect of running for governor in 2002. He
hedged, though, when asked if he might take an appointed position
in a Gore administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the job I have tremendously; I've said that before this
consideration began. It would have to be pretty exciting and pretty
good arm-twisting to get me to leave what I'm doing right now,'' he
declared.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, he confessed that talk of running with Gore stoked
his White House ambitions, acknowledging that he had even started
writing notes for a possible acceptance speech at next week's
Democratic National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be a liar if I didn't say to you there's a little
disappointment in being able to follow through on that and do it,''
Kerry said as he dug through a lunch plate heaped with sesame
noodles, red potato salad, cayenne chicken, and a dessert of
chocolate mousse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I invested in it in the last few days when things got a little
more serious. I'd say once the list came down to narrow
possibilities I began to think about message, things I wanted to
say,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Kerry termed the waiting process an unsettling ``kind of
limbo,'' a feeling quickly overwhelmed by grief at the July 29
death of his father, 85-year-old former diplomat Richard Kerry.
</P>
<P>
   ``It kind of obliterated the process,'' the senator said.
Preparing for the funeral and tending to his 87-year-old mother
Rosemary, ``made time indifferent, in a funny way, and it was just
such a preoccupation that I wasn't really thinking about the other
that much.''
</P>
<P>
   During the span, he played his guitar and immersed himself in
David Kennedy's book, ``Freedom from Fear.''
</P>
<P>
   Heinz said her husband was actually quite anxious to team up
with Gore and campaign against the Republican ticket of George W.
Bush and Dick Cheney.
</P>
<P>
   ``My husband, he's a windsurfer, he loves everything that's
action, so being active for him is great. That just a personal
trait, can't keep him down,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Heinz said she was intrigued as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know what I was looking forward to and I think John McCain
mentioned that he hoped somebody would campaign on the issues, and
really focus on the issues,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Kerry, while wearing a tired expression, said the two slept
soundly as he waited for Gore's call.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to bed last night,'' he recalled. ``It was in fate's
hands and what was going to happen was going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he and Heinz flew off to their home on Nantucket, both
oddly satisfied with the outcome of his flirtation with the vice
presidency.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
