<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-JOURNAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR JAGGER'S EX, `GRADUATE' PERFORMANCE GETS HARSH LOOK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Jerry Hall learned a hard lesson last week: Just about
anyone can take their clothes off in the West End, but the British
still expect them to be able to act.
</P>
<P>
   Hall, the former supermodel and estranged wife of Rolling Stones
singer Mick Jagger, pulled off the former with aplomb, but by most
accounts did not account herself well of the latter.
</P>
<P>
   Hall, a straight-talking Texan who left Jagger last year because
of his serial infidelity, is more popular in Britain than her ex,
who, while appreciated for being a rock 'n' roll legend, is seen by
more than a few Britons as something of a stingy, tax-dodging cad.
</P>
<P>
   But Hall's attempt to replace Kathleen Turner as the seductress
Mrs. Robinson in the stage production of ``The Graduate'' has
showed that fame and popularity will carry you only so far when you
have to bare it all on the floorboards of London's West End.
</P>
<P>
   The stage version of Mike Nichols's classic 1967 film has become
a phenomenon in London. Last spring, after Turner stripped naked in
the play's seduction scene during previews, the play's three-month
run sold out overnight. It was extended indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   According to London's notoriously fickle critics, the play has
been more a triumph of marketing than theater, a reputation that
only grew when Hall was recently named to replace Turner.
</P>
<P>
   By most accounts, Hall has a better figure than Turner. But by
those same accounts, Turner is an accomplished actress, while Hall
is still widely regarded as an accomplished model and mother who
suffered the repeated public humiliations of her perpetually
adolescent husband.
</P>
<P>
   It is not unusual for accomplished models to become accomplished
film actresses. Andie MacDowell comes to mind, even if Ali MacGraw
does not. But there are far fewer examples of those who make their
living being photographed making a successful transition to live
theater.
</P>
<P>
   That precedent, however, has not deterred the unsinkable Hall,
who took the offensive against Jagger last year when he tried to
avoid alimony payments by claiming their 1990 marriage in Bali
wasn't a marriage at all.
</P>
<P>
   Hall eventually got her alimony, and all appears to be forgiven,
or at least accepted, as Jagger was in the opening-night crowd when
Hall began a week of preview performances before the official
opening night last week.
</P>
<P>
   Jagger said his ex was wonderful. Critics thought otherwise.
Under a headline that read, ``Enter Jerry Hall, barely acting,''
the Times savaged her performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``A clothes horse she still is, and she looks undeniably
magnificent for a woman of 44,'' the Times opined. ``But the
trouble with having endless legs and almost equally extendible arms
would seem to be that you do have to have some idea what to do with
them between delivering the lines.''
</P>
<P>
   When Hall's philandering character describes her husband as ``so
boring,'' some in the audience at the Gielgud Theatre could not
help glancing toward Jagger. But according to the couple's friends,
Jagger helped Hall memorize her lines, evidence that the estranged
couple have agreed to disagree with each other's lifestyles but
remain friends.
</P>
<P>
   By most accounts, Hall, who eschewed nudity even in her
supermodel days, is less revealing than Turner was, choosing to
drop her towel for about 20 seconds in very dim lighting.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Billington, the Guardian's acerbic critic, suggested
that ``anyone seeking erotic satisfaction out of the moment would
either have to be pretty desperate or in possession of cats'
eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   Comparing Turner's and Hall's performances, Billington was
characteristically cutting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Turner brought to the alcoholic, sex-hungry Mrs. Robinson a
mocking stillness, a gin-smoked voice and Mae West timing, all
derived from a lengthy film and stage career,'' he said. ``Hall,
having appeared on stage once before in `Bus Stop,' brings only a
wealth of inexperience.''
</P>
<P>
   But then wealth is a relative thing. Some theater critics
suggest that Hall is pocketing $15,000 a week for the role.
</P>
<P>
   The sellouts at the Gielgud, meanwhile, have cemented a trend
here in which famous, attractive women put bums in the seats by
baring their bums. Nicole Kidman started the trend last year with
her nude performance in ``The Blue Room.'' Turner continued the
trend, while Hall has made it bankable. There are now more more
than 20 productions of the play planned internationally.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the critics say, Hall will not be the last famous woman
to take her clothes off in the West End this year, or next.
</P>
<P>
   Catherine Bennett, a columnist for the Guardian, said she was
tired of listening to critics debate whether the phenomenal success
of ``The Graduate'' is because of its dramatic content or the fact
that the female lead has a nude scene.
</P>
<P>
   ``So long as our sexual infantilism endures,'' Bennett sighed,
``there need be no theatrical flops.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Kevin Cullen is chief of the Boston Globe London bureau.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
