<SLUG> BC-POP-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AGING `COWBOYS' GIVE YOUTH A RUN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Let us now praise older men.
</P>
<P>
   ``Space Cowboys'' earned $17.6 million in its opening weekend,
good enough for a third-place finish behind ``Hollow Man'' and
``Nutty Professor II.'' In a summer where a handful of films have
enjoyed debut weekends above $30 million, it's a respectable, if
unspectacular, box office take. That is, unless you consider that
the film's four stars range in age from 53 to 72.
</P>
<P>
   With so much emphasis in popular culture on all things youthful
_ how else to explain the careers of Freddie Prinze Jr., Carson
Daly, and Jessica Simpson? _ there's something remarkable about a
successful film starring, in age order, James Garner, 72; Clint
Eastwood, 70; Donald Sutherland, 65; and Tommy Lee Jones, 53. The
Washington Post's Rita Kempley called the cast ``the most geriatric
payload since a community of retirees lifted off in `Cocoon.' ''
And with an average age of 65, who can argue.
</P>
<P>
   A comedy-drama, ``Space Cowboys'' concerns a group of retired
astronauts who missed their chance to go into space in 1958, but
are recalled into service more than 40 years later after an
obsolete Russian communications satellite goes haywire. Not
surprisingly, the movie finds much of its humor with the notion of
these craggy, creaky codgers enduring the rigors of NASA's fitness
program, and the teasing of the younger astronauts. But they never
back down, and ultimately prove that advanced age has nothing to do
with ability.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, youth and beauty ain't got nothing on age and
experience _ old people rule.
</P>
<P>
   And that's the message the movie sends to Hollywood as well.
</P>
<P>
   From Paul Newman, 75, to Anthony Hopkins, 62, to Morgan Freeman,
63, to Michael Caine, 67, some of our best actors may be eligible
for AARP membership, but they still have oh-so-much to offer. (The
treatment of older actresses, however, is appalling, but that's
another rant for another day.)
</P>
<P>
   See, acting ability isn't like athletic ability. It doesn't
erode and diminish simply because actors age. In fact, it often
ripens and deepens into something more meaningful. It's the sheer
talents of Eastwood, Garner, Jones, and Sutherland, four of our
wiliest actors, who keep ``Space Cowboys'' afloat.
</P>
<P>
   In an increasingly shallow culture, youth and beauty are
wonderful accessories. They open doors and instantly garner
attention whether it's deserved or not. These days it seems having
actual talent is a distant second _ if it is considered at all _ to
the allure of good looks and a hot bod.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps because all those controlling, self-involved baby
boomers are now sliding (kicking and screaming, of course) into
their golden years, there's an effort to portray senior citizens as
strong, capable, and valuable, not as doddering old folks shuffling
off to the grave. Consider one of the more entertaining commercials
on the air these days that comes from the ``Got Milk?'' folks _ a
group of geezers whip the living daylights out of a bunch of young
beefy thugs terrorizing people in a diner. It's not only amusing
but offers hope that, even in old age, we won't take any guff from
anyone.
</P>
<P>
   Will the success of ``Space Cowboys'' change Hollywood's
obsession with youth? Probably not, but there are at least two
major films due in theaters soon, which also feature other members
of acting's group of elder statesmen. At the end of the month, Burt
Reynolds, 64, and Seymour Cassel, 65, will star with relative
youngsters Richard Dreyfuss, 53, and Dan Hedaya, 60, as retired
mobsters in ``The Crew.'' And Gene Hackman, 70, and Morgan Freeman,
63 (Give him an Academy Award. Now.), will soon be seen in the
thriller ``Under Suspicion.'' All of these actors continue working
because they're just plain good at what they do _ not because
they're gracing the covers of magazines.
</P>
<P>
   Think about it _ will anyone really flock to see Tom Cruise
movies after those floppy bangs have receded, or Brad Pitt films
after those abs melt into flab? Come to think of it, judging from
the box office numbers for such recent duds as ``Meet Joe Black''
and ``Fight Club,'' Mr. Jennifer Aniston might not have to wait
that long to find out.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Renee Graham covers the pop scene for The Boston Globe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
