<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 13:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5760 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u t BC-TRAVEL-MAINE-ART-BOS &LR;      08-08 1113
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-MAINE-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 THE MAINE COAST, BY THE BOOK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: Photos are being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILLIAM A. DAVIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WELLS, Maine _ The building that houses Doug Harding's used-book
store was built in 1888 as a private railway depot for the
president of the Boston &AMP; Maine Railroad, who had a summer home
nearby. At the time, the station was described admiringly as
``standing amid pastoral tranquillity.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, Route 1 in southern Maine is pretty much nonstop road
rash and it's the bookstore that is tranquil. Other things,
however, haven't changed much in the last 112 years. ``We have
customers whose families have been vacationing in Maine for
generations,'' says Harding, ``and they're looking for the same
sort of books people who come to Maine have always looked for.'' In
other words, books about Maine and interesting and entertaining
books to read at the beach, on a cottage porch, or in a hammock.
</P>
<P>
   Superstores such as Barnes &AMP; Noble and Internet booksellers like
Amazon.com and its used and rare book subsidiary, Bibliofind.com,
are transforming readers' buying habits. But traditions die hard
Down East, and for many visitors to coastal Maine, leisurely
browsing through book barns and antique bookstores remains as much
a part of the Pine Tree State experience as a bracing dip in the
Atlantic Ocean or eating lobster in the rough.
</P>
<P>
   Wells, for instance, which has a resident population of about
10,000, boasts four large antiquarian bookstores, more than many
good-sized American cities can claim. The steady stream of
potential book buyers driving up and down Route 1 _ also known as
the Post Road and, in effect, the town's main street _ is probably
a prime reason for the unusual concentration of book dealers here.
</P>
<P>
   Wells has another attraction for those buyers and sellers: its
long stretches of sandy beach. Browsing for used books or antiques
on cold or rainy non-beach days is an old coastal Maine custom, and
in Wells, beaches and bookstores are practically next to each
other.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always wanted to live by the ocean,'' says Harding, who
moved here 20 years ago from Nashua and opened Douglas N. Harding
Rare Books, now the largest antiquarian bookshop in southern Maine.
</P>
<P>
   The spacious old depot contains about 90,000 volumes, ranging
from paperback novels to hard-to-find books on specialized
subjects, including 19th-century guidebooks, antique children's
books, town and family histories, and first editions of works by
Maine authors. He also stocks a large selection of maps and prints,
the latter mostly of New England maritime scenes.
</P>
<P>
   The sign outside the nearby Book Barn, located at the
intersection of Route 1 and South Street, advertises: ``Books Rare,
Medium, and Well Done.'' The Book Barn, operated by Harry and Ann
Polizzi, delivers on the boast with an eclectic collection of
roughly 40,000 volumes. Most are general interest fiction or
nonfiction, including paperback books ideal for beach blanket
reading. Stephen King fans will not leave empty-handed.
</P>
<P>
   The Book Barn also sells autographs and comic books and has a
good collection of works by Maine writers, particularly those who
lived in the immediate area and wrote about it. ``There is a lot of
interest now in writers like Sarah Orne Jewett and Kenneth
Roberts,'' Ann Polizzi says. Jewett wrote the classic ``The Country
of the Pointed Fir,'' an evocative collection of short stories
about late-19th-century coastal Maine. Roberts titled one of his
bestsellers ``Arundel,'' the original name of Wells's neighbor
Kennebunk.
</P>
<P>
   East Coast Books and Art, owned by Merv and KayeSlotnick, is on
Depot Street (Route 109), just east of Route 1. Housed in a
two-story, 1840s farmhouse, it has a varied collection of about
20,000 books, but is particularly strong on American history and
art books. The store also sells paintings by artists from Maine and
around the country, and letters and autographs. Another sideline is
ephemera, printed items intended to be used only once such as
wedding invitations, theater programs, and posters advertising
concerts or sporting events.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Civil War is very hot these days,'' Kaye Slotnick reports.
``There is a great demand for letters written during it that
mention historical events, and it doesn't matter if they're not
written by famous people.'' There is always steady demand, she
adds, for first editions of works by Jewitt, Roberts, and King, as
well as other nationally known Maine writers like Ruth Moore
(``Spoonhandle'') and Gladys Hastings Carroll (``As the Earth
Turns'').
</P>
<P>
   The literary Holy Grail sought by many Maine book browsers, by
the way, is a first edition, now quite rare, of Stephen King's
first published novel, ``Carrie,'' set in the high school of a
small Maine town. When he wrote it, King was an impoverished
schoolteacher living in a trailer with his young family.
</P>
<P>
   The fourth antiquarian bookstore in town is The Arringtons, run
by George and Eleanor Arrington and occupying a 19th-century
building on Route 1 that once housed a general store. The
Arringtons has some general books and vintage paperbacks, as well
as antique postcards, but most of the nearly 20,000 volumes on its
shelves are on military subjects. ``I have hard-to-find unit
histories and British military books,'' George Arrington says,
``and a lot of both nonfiction and fiction about the Vietnam War,
World Wars I and II, and the Civil and Revolutionary wars.'''
</P>
<P>
   Arrington is one bookseller who believes the Internet is more
blessing than curse for a small niche bookstore like his. ``I think
it's great, because now I can locate books all over the world,'' he
says. ``I just bought a bunch of stuff from Latvia.''
</P>
<P>
   Bibliophiles may have trouble leaving Wells, but there are good
used-book stores all along the Maine coast, some of them a Maine
experience all by themselves. For instance, the states's
self-proclaimed ``largest antiquarian book dealer'' is _ and this
is not a joke _ Big Chicken Barn Books and Antiques.
</P>
<P>
   Located on the south side of Route 3 between Bucksport and
Ellsworth, just south of Bar Harbor, Big Chicken _ which occupies
the cleaned-up cavernous main building of a defunct poultry
breeding company _ is more book coop than book barn. Into its
21,000 square feet of space are packed some 100,000 books on
assorted subjects as well as a variety of antiques and
collectibles.
</P>
<P>
   Where chickens used to nest and lay and cluck, book buffs and
antiquers now happily browse.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
