<HEADLINE>
GETTING A PASSPORT QUICKLY AND EASILY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's good news for the 7 million people expected to apply for
a passport this year. In many cities there is a new automated
telephone appointment system that makes getting a last-minute
passport easy. And for those not in a rush, the passport agency has
added more local post offices to obtain or renew a passport.
</P>
<P>
   Passport agencies that have installed the automated appointment
system include New York, Boston, Miami, Los Angeles, Washington,
Chicago, Houston, San Francisco, Philadelphia, and Stamford, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   If you are traveling internationally within the next 14 days, or
need a passport quickly for visa purposes, you'll be able to
schedule an appointment 24 hours a day, seven days a week.
</P>
<P>
   Appointments will be verified upon arrival at the Passport
Agency. Travelers must present acceptable evidence of their US
citizenship such as a certified birth certificate, previous US
passport, or naturalization certificate, and valid identification
such as a driver's license.
</P>
<P>
   Proof of travel within 14 days or urgent need to obtain foreign
visas is required, such as an airline ticket or a confirmed
airline-generated itinerary.
</P>
<P>
   Two identical, standard passport photos (2x2 inches), a
completed application and appropriate fees are needed (for those 16
and older, the charge for them is $60 and they are good for 10
years; for those 15 and younger, the fee is $40 and the passport is
valid for five years).
</P>
<P>
   Travelers not urgently needing a passport should apply at
passport acceptance facilities such as post offices, municipal
offices, or clerks of court. Using one of those services, travelers
should receive a passport within 25 business days. Expedited
service allowing for the processing of a passport within three
business days is also available for $35. Two-way overnight delivery
is strongly recommended for those concerned about timely receipt of
their passports.
</P>
<P>
   Those renewing passports may be eligible to do so by mail
without requiring a personal appearance.
</P>
<P>
   For information on obtaining a passport, places to do so, or to
check on the status of a passport, call the National Passport
Information Center (a private agency) at 900-225-5674 (recorded
information is 35 cents a minute and available 24 hours a day; to
check on passport status and speak to a representative _ available
Monday through Friday 8:30 a.m. to 5:30 p.m. _ the cost is $1.05 a
minute, or with a credit card $4.95 total) or for those with a
major credit card, call 888-362-8668.
</P>
<P>
   The agency's Web page contains passport as well as a wealth of
travel-related information. Visit www.travel.state.gov. The site
also lists local post offices.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NE video
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Memories are an important part of any vacation. And one of the
best souvenirs of a visit can be a video of the area. Offering a
very positive and colorful image of this region is ``New England: A
Tribute.'' This 49-minute video covers the region from the Pilgrim
landing at Plymouth to the fall foliage in Vermont and New
Hampshire. It's a great video for those who haven't been to the
area as it highlights the history, beauty, foods, and attractions.
Besides Pilgrims, you'll learn about witches, the sea, lobsters,
and famous authors. The video is part of the Tribute Series, which
includes Tuscany and Umbria, Mexico, California, St. Petersburg,
and Indiana. The videos are produced by Jim and John Hilgendorf.
``My idea was to begin a series of beautiful films that would build
bridges of understanding and appreciation between different peoples
of the world,'' said Jim Hilgendorf. The videos are $24.95 each
plus $3 shipping from The Tribute Series, PO Box 641056, Los
Angeles, CA 90064; telephone 310-444-9255 or visit
www.tributeseries.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Monument reopens
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Washington Monument has reopened after a two-year
restoration project. Entry is controlled through timed-entry
tickets. Free tickets will be distributed at the kiosk on the
monument grounds each morning. Advance tickets are available
through Ticketmaster at 202-432-7328 (service charges apply). For
information, call 202-619-7222.
</P>
</TEXT>
