<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 13:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5762 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUM     08-08 0786
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RULES HAVE CHANGED IN THE CLUBHOUSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Not so long ago, Mo Vaughn was the Red Sox'
best everyday player and club leader. Playing for the Anaheim
Angels, 3,000 miles from Fenway, he is removed from the inner
workings of the Red Sox clubhouse, but he knows what would have
happened if a teammate disrespected manager Jimy Williams when he
was around.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would not want that to happen,'' said Vaughn, who homered
his first time up against the Red Sox Monay night. ``You have to
try to put those fires out. We've had situations here, you put the
fire out. In my clubhouse, we don't need any of that. That's just
the way I would handle it.''
</P>
<P>
   Carl Everett's apologists _ and they are legion, because this
guy can really play _ invent excuses for most of his tirades, but
it's hard to find anyone who'll condone what Everett did after his
Saturday morning shouting match with Williams.
</P>
<P>
   When it was over, Jurassic Carl stormed out of the manager's
office, walked through the Sox clubhouse, and yelled, ``I never
liked that guy in the first place.''
</P>
<P>
   There. This time, it wasn't a sportswriter or an umpire. It was
Everett's own manager. And Everett blurted out the remark in the
presence of several reporters and a good number of teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a player, I have to respect my manager,'' said Vaughn. ``I
don't know what transpired there this year, but I know Jimy. We had
a great relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Red Sox went to the World Series 14 years ago, Don
Baylor was the team leader and matters were handled firmly and
internally. Certain behavior was not tolerated. Actions had
consequences. It was the same when Vaughn was around. Ballplayers
policed themselves. There was accountability. It's different now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't know him but he's too good a player to be
getting in those type of situations,'' Vaughn said of Everett. ``As
much as you can, in Boston you want the fans and media on your side
because even when things are going well, it's tough over there.
Just go play your game and leave it at that.''
</P>
<P>
   Clubhouse leadership, like clubhouse karma, is probably
overrated, but the Sox seemed more cohesive when Vaughn and Mike
Stanley were around. Pedro Martinez and Nomar Garciaparra are the
two best players, but Pedro plays only once every five days and
Nomar keeps to himself and leads by example _ playing 100 percent
every second of every game. This will have to do. Perhaps it is
enough.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Williams continues to take the high road, but what
kind of a team allows this stuff to go unchecked? Everett plays
every day, shows up when he wants to show up, blames the media for
his tantrums, and Sox management continues to give him the double
thumbs-up. Just Carl being competitive, you know. It's the media
that makes him into a monster, right?
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, a deal has been struck. Everett has emerged as the new
Albert Belle, but as long as he can put up Triple Crown-type
numbers, he will be tolerated and applauded by Dan Duquette and
most fans at ``Friendly Fenway.'' And the Sox will pledge to keep
things ``in house.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, Carl took it out of the house and put it on
national television when he went after umpire Ronald Kulpa. And how
he has publicly ripped his manager, who is forced to act as if he
doesn't care.
</P>
<P>
   Those who were there claim Jimy cared quite a bit Saturday when
he was giving it right back to Everett behind closed doors. This
should help the manager's already high stock in the clubhouse. But
where's the backing from Duquette, who actually joked that maybe
Carl ought to yell at Jimy every day if he can follow it up with a
3-for-5 performance?
</P>
<P>
   Also, where was the ``in house'' attitude when the Sox asked Mo
to undergo alcohol evaluation? Why was Vaughn a bad guy who had to
go, while Carl is emerging as top candidate for BoSox Club ``Man of
the Year''?
</P>
<P>
   ``Times were different,'' Vaughn said. ``I don't know what
happened with me or what reason. I haven't been over there, but one
thing I do know, it's a tough enough job to play over there without
any extracurricular activity.''
</P>
<P>
   For Sox fans the good news is that the Duke is being careful
about who is worthy of wearing the Sox uniform. Boston passed on
Jose Canseco, allowing the Yankees to grab the goofy, aging, and
oft-injured slugger. The Sox don't want Jose's type polluting the
clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   Carl? He's OK. The guy is hitting .319 with 27 homers and 76
RBIs, for gosh sake.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Dan Shaughnessy is a Globe columnist. He can be reached by e-mail
at dshaughnessy(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
