<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GRAPEVINE: News, notes from the wrestling industry
 &HT;    By John Allen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rumors citing the demise of every top boss in World Championship
Wrestling are everywhere on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Brad Siegel, Eric Bischoff, Vince Russo and a host of wrestlers
have all been fired, quit or been moved, according to reports on
the Internet. What WCW is saying? Nothing. No comment. But Vince
Russo's interview on Monday's `Nitro' did shed some light on his
activity with WCW over the past year.
</P>
<P>
   He obviously didn't understand how political WCW was or at least
did not understand his position and did not have the backing he
expected from management. The most interesting thing from the
interview was that Russo would like to get John Rocker in the ring
in Long Island, N.Y., for ``Starcade.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't expect that, but here are some things you can expect:
</P>
<P>
   1. Goodbye Lex Luger and Roddy Piper. You haven't seen him on
televion and you won't see him back with WCW unless they take a
major pay cut. Piper's dismissal may be a bad move as he is still
good for getting the younger wrestlers over, but no one will miss
the stiff working Luger. WCW needs to trim payroll desperately.
</P>
<P>
   2. No more television for Bischoff and Russo. Bischoff has been
off the air since Kimberly Page left the fold. His role behind the
camera will continue to be a vacant as his role in front of the
camera.
</P>
<P>
   3. No more Hulk Hogan ... at least in 2000. Hogan's contract
makes it difficult for WCW to make money on pay-per-views given he
must have a percentage. So, don't expect Hogan at any more
pay-per-views and therefore any television.
</P>
<P>
   4. More Booker T, Lance Storm, Shane Douglas, Mike Awesome,
Billy Kidman, etc. The new, cheaper wrestlers will be the
foundation for the WCW in 2001. But if WCW thinks Booker T is the
man, they need to think again. When he tagged with Sting and Kronic
last week, Sting was the one who the fans cheered loudest. WCW
should be hanging its hat on Lance Storm, who should be the
second-coming of Bret Hart.
</P>
<P>
   5. Speaking of Hart, it seems his career is over. It is fast
approaching one year since he stepped in the ring and the
concussion that has kept him from wrestling does not seem to be
improving. With his WCW deal set to expire soon, both sides may
quietly choose to part ways.
</P>
<P>
   6. Whoo!! One last time. Ric Flair will begin a farewell tour
when he returns from shoulder surgery sometime in October. Expect
the 15-time champion to get the gold one last time before he hangs
it up next year when his autobiography is expect to hit the
bookstores.
</P>
<P>
   _ Love has been in the air at the World Wrestling Federation.
Both the Undertaker and Chris Jericho were part of injury angles so
they could take some time off for their honeymoons. Undertaker was
married on July 21st and was ``injured'' on the ``Raw'' show on the
24th. Jericho was married on July 30 and was ``injured'' on
``Smackdown'' which taped on the 25th. Jericho's wedding was huge
news in Winnipeg, where it was held. The Winnipeg Sun ran a front
page story on the marriage of Manitoba's sexiest man to long-time
girlfriend Jessica Lockhart. In attendance were Don Callis
(Gangrel), Billy Kidman, Lance Storm, Edge, Christian and Disco
Inferno.
</P>
<P>
   _ The WWF will be filling your newsstand in the coming months.
September's WWF The Magazine features Edge and Christian on the
cover. And also has articles on Kane, X-Pac and Trish Stratus. The
WWF is also planning on releasing a special magazine on The Rock.
The magazine is scheduled for release on Sept. 18. Finally the WWF
King of The Ring video will be in stores on Aug. 22.
</P>
<P>
   _ With Raven expected to join the WWF in September, the former
ECW and WCW star should have another similar gimmick to the Raven's
Flock. How will fill out the list of followers? A good guess at
this point would be demoted WWF wrestlers Gangrel and Viscera,
Perry Saturn (who is in desperate need for a good gimmick) and
maybe recent signee Sickboy, who was with Raven at WCW. Expect the
trimmed (he's lost over 50 pounds) Paul Bearer to be the
mastermind.
</P>
<P>
   _ The weekly ``Stone Cold'' Steve Austin return watch is saying
the Rattlesnake may have a role as a referee or enforcer at
``SummerSlam.'' It's doubtful, a late fall return is more likely.
</P>
<P>
   _ The latest news on Billy Gunn has the former DXer returning to
the ring from rotator cuff surgery Sept. 24.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
