<HEADLINE>
SENIORS ARE TRAVELING MORE, TAKING MORE ACTIVE VACATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Life begins at 50. Sure, many fear turning the Big Five-Oh, but
for travelers 50 is nifty and 60 is even better.
</P>
<P>
   If 50 is so good, why is 60 even better? Simple, that's when the
discounts begin, and for growing numbers when early retirement
begins allowing more time to hit the road.
</P>
<P>
   In the travel world, senior or ``mature,'' as some tour
companies like to say, now begins as early as age 50. The best
deals, though, begin at 60, 62, or 65. So, accept your senior
status and realize your travel power as more and more tour firms,
and destinations, court you with deals. And don't think just
because you've reached senior status, you're over the hill. Active
or adventure travel is the fastest growing senior travel market.
</P>
<P>
   Tour operators are redefining their programs to cater to this
growing market. According to the National Tour Association, the
mature travel market is more independent, leans toward cruising,
has special interests, and is fitness-conscious.
</P>
<P>
   Another growing area for mature travelers is ``grandtravel'' _
grandparents taking their grandchildren. There's even a travel
agency, Grandtravel, in Maryland (800-247-7651 or
www.grandtravel.com) that offers trips with grandchildren that
range from national parks to African safaris.
</P>
<P>
   Loews Hotels, recognizing the growing trend of grandparents
traveling with grandchildren, has just introduced a new package at
14 of its hotels in the United States and Canada. Loews offers a
``Generation G'' program with features such as an adjoining room at
reduced rates, a take-home memory album, a phone card (to call
parents and others), an ``In Grand Style Package'' designed for
teens with behind-the-scenes sports and cultural tours, and even a
Grand Adventure Package with customized adventures for those 10 and
older. (Also included is a goodie bag with helpful ``Tips for
Successful Grandparent Travel.'') For more information, call
800-23-LOEWS or visit www.loewshotels.com.
</P>
<P>
   Marriott says it will have a grand destination for grandtravel
beginning Sept. 22 when its Marriott Village at Little Lake Bryan
near Orlando, Fla., opens. Located near Disney World, the village
includes three Marriott hotels under one roof (Courtyard, Fairfield
Inn, and SpringHill Suites). Among amenities are refrigerators in
all rooms, a food court, a 24-hour convenience store, free
transportation to Disney parks, and guest laundry. Pre-opening
rates begin at $69 a room. Mariott notes a recent survey rated
Orlando the number one destination for grandparents to take
grandchildren. (For a copy of the Orlando Visitors Guide and Mature
Travel Discount Brochure, call 800-972-3308.) For Marriott
information, call 877-682-8552 or visit www.marriott-village.com.
</P>
<P>
   Even seniors traveling alone find Disney World a place for the
young at heart. Walt Disney once said that Disney World was
designed for those from ``3 to 93,'' which still appears true.
``I've noticed that seniors are more willing to take the time
visiting our parks to breathe in the total experience,'' said Greg
Emmer, vice president of the Magic Kingdom. ``They enjoy the
storytelling we do through architecture, music, background sound,
and aromas.'' Disney officials note that seniors seem to appreciate
attractions like River Country, which reminds many of places they
knew growing up, and activities ranging from tennis and fishing to
dancing to the sounds of top bands. And for seniors for whom the
spirit is willing but the feet aren't, motorized self-drive
vehicles may be rented.
</P>
<P>
   Seniors 55 and older can also join the Magic Kingdom Club and
obtain discounted admission prices to Disney parks and reduced
rates at Disney resort hotels. Call 800-89-DISNEY for information.
</P>
<P>
   Grand Circle Travel, a Boston-based firm that has been in
business for more than 40 years catering to senior travel, also
owns Overseas Adventure Travel, a 20-year veteran in adventure
tours, and Vermont Bicycle Touring, a 27-year-old pioneer in bike
tours in New England and elsewhere. These purchases by Grand Circle
reflect the changing interests of the ``mature'' travel market.
</P>
<P>
   Travel has become a passion for many 50-plus travelers. One
senior wrote to Grand Circle saying ,``Never mind that I have spent
my children's inheritance. I have seen the Great Wall, viewed the
Taj Mahal, and rode a camel to the pyramids. . . .''
</P>
<P>
   One doesn't have to break the bank or mortgage the future to
enjoy travel. Many seniors are finding their disposable income is
up, and the cost of travel is down. Elderhostel, a nonprofit
organization, which specializes in learning tours around the world,
has proved that a great tour doesn't have to cost a fortune. While
learning is a key part of the tours, no prior formal knowledge of
the program is required. Elderhostel says, ``All that is required
is an open, inquisitive, mature mind.'' Most programs in North
America are a week long, and elsewhere last up to four weeks with
weeklong stays at one or more sites.
</P>
<P>
   Interhostel, another international study/travel program
sponsored by the University of New Hampshire, utilizes colleges and
their facilities around the world to help cut costs. ``Our major
concern is the educational component. We try to provide a good
overview of the host country: its history, culture, and what makes
the local people tick,'' said Carol Bense, Interhostel manager.
``We want every person who participates to say, `Wow, I never knew
that.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Travelers, even those just 50 years old, will find discounts on
accommodations, dining, entrance fees, rental cars, and more if
they ask. While most discounts are for those 60 or older, it still
pays to ask. Seniors, and others, should also take advantage of
savings offered by organizations such as AAA or the American
Association of Retired Persons. There are publications keyed to the
older traveler: The Mature Traveler is a newsletter that has been
around for some time, and is filled with deals and information. A
recent issue mentioned joining Servas (212-267-0252), which
promotes peace through visiting and offers stays with members
around the world. Travel 50 &AMP; Beyond is a quarterly magazine with
information ranging from deals to health matters. Arthur Frommer's
Budget Travel is a monthly magazine with good deals for all ages.
</P>
<P>
   Many airlines offer discounts of 10 percent or special fares for
those 62 and older on many flights (companions can be any age on
most lines). Some airlines such as Virgin, British Air, Air Canada,
and Canadian have lower fares for those 60 and older. Amtrak offers
those 62 and older 15 percent discounts on most trains; Rail Europe
offers seniors 60 and older various discounts.
</P>
<P>
   Another way seniors save is to stay in one place. Untours, a
Pennsylvania company, has been specializing in two-week stays in
private homes or apartments in Europe and elsewhere for years. The
company makes all the arrangements, even has a local representative
to help in touring and any problems. Collette Tours, a Pawtucket,
R.I. , firm that has been in business 80 years, now features ``hub
and spoke'' programs, which focus on a smaller area and longer
stays at one or two places in the region rather than covering a lot
of ground and moving from hotel to hotel daily.
</P>
<P>
   Cruises are a growing area for seniors, and are definitely no
longer just for the sedentary crowd. Saga Holidays, another
Boston-based firm that specializes in travel for those 50 and
older, has its own cruise ship, the Saga Rose, the former Cunard
Sagafjord, and carries 583 passengers at least 50 years of age. The
company specializes in packages for mature travelers who ``want to
venture off the beaten path without sacrificing comfort.''
</P>
<P>
   Another idea for senior travel is to volunteer your time in
service projects. Elderhostel now features service programs where
hostelers ``learn by doing'' with organizations such as Global
Volunteers, which has programs just about everywhere.
</P>
</TEXT>
