<HEADLINE>
THIS `MILLENNIUM' HAS AN ABRUPT FINISH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDRISANO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is most unfortunate that racing fans in the United States
never got the chance to see Dubai Millennium race in the flesh.
Considered the fastest horse in the world, Dubai Millennium
fractured his right rear cannon bone while working out at Newmarket
Saturday, and has been retired to stud following surgery to insert
three screws in his leg.
</P>
<P>
   A 4-year-old son of Seeking The Gold, Dubai Millennium won 9 of
10 starts for the Godolphin Stable of Sheik Mohammed of Dubai.
Dubai Millennium was originally named Yaazar, but Mohammed was so
confident the horse would capture the Dubai World Cup in March that
he changed his name for the occasion. Dubai Millennium came through
with a breathtaking front-running score of 6 lengths to justify the
faith of his owner.
</P>
<P>
   The only time Dubai Millennium tasted defeat, he could not
handle the 1 1/2 miles of last year's Epsom Derby, finishing ninth.
However, he had been impressive in all of his other starts, most
recently in another eye-catching tally as he romped home by 8
lengths in the Prince Of Wales at Ascot June 21.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can wait 20 years and never get a horse like this,'' said
Mohammed. ``I have never seen or owned a horse like him with the
way he trains and the way he looks. He is quite outstanding.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll always remember him as the best horse I've ridden,'' said
regular jockey Frankie Dettori. ``Hopefully, his offspring will be
as good as him.''
</P>
<P>
   The American audience lost out, because the sheik's major goal
was to win the $4 million Breeders' Cup Classic at Churchill Downs
Nov. 4. In fact, the situation was really heating up, as Mohammed
had challenged Michael Tabor to a $6 million match race, Dubai
Millennium vs. Tabor's Montjeu. The challenge was issued the day
before Dubai Millennium was hurt.
</P>
<P>
   Montjeu, who won last year's Prix de l'Arc de Triomphe, had
scored an easy victory in the King George VI and Queen Elizabeth
Diamond Stakes July 29, and Tabor had suggested that the horses
meet in the Irish Championship Stakes at the Curragh Sept. 9,
saying, ``It's what the public would like to see.'' Mohammed
responded by saying that he had already planned two other prep
races for Dubai Millennium, adding, ``Why didn't Montjeu come to
Ascot last month (for the Prince Of Wales)? He is most welcome to
take us on in the Breeders' Cup, and I will even pay his entry
fee.''
</P>
<P>
   Mohammed was criticized in the press for not accepting Tabor's
invitation, and the sheik is not fond of criticism. He then
suggested the match race, to be run at 1 1/4 miles, with each side
putting up $6 million, the purse of the Dubai World Cup, under
winner-take-all conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Dubai Millennium's injury put an end to all that. So now we'll
just have to wait until the Breeders' Cup to find out who really is
the fastest horse in the world.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `Lemon Drop' was sweet &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The events of the weekend clarified the handicap picture, with
Lemon Drop Kid emerging as the undisputed leader of the pack via
his victory in the Whitney at Saratoga, but further muddied the
already murky 3-year-old scene, as there were upsets in the Haskell
at Monmouth and the Jim Dandy at The Spa.
</P>
<P>
   Lemon Drop Kid, who has turned into a monster since blinkers
were added to his equipment, defeated Behrens and Golden Missile,
his two top challengers for postseason honors, in the Whitney. The
4-year-old son of Kingmombo, who has now won the Brooklyn, the
Suburban, and the Whitney since trainer Scotty Schulhofer put the
blinkers on him, has become a legitimate candidate for Horse of the
Year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like he's at the top of his game, and all we have to
do is keep him healthy and strong,'' said Schulhofer. ``There is a
month to the Woodward, then a month to the Jockey Club Gold Cup,
and three weeks to the Breeders' Cup. He's the best horse I've ever
trained. I've had a lot of good ones, but he's the best.''
</P>
<P>
   The Whitney made Lemon Drop Kid the winner of the ``NTRA
Champions on Fox'' series, which earned his connections $230,000.
Lemon Drop Kid received a flat $100,000 bonus for best performance
in the 20-race series, and another $130,000 based on his
accumulated points.
</P>
<P>
   While Derby winner Fusaichi Pegasus and Preakness winner Red
Bullet remain in hiding, Dixie Union won Sunday's $1 million
Haskell, paying $11.40, and Graeme Hall took Saturday's Jim Dandy,
the prep for the $1 million Travers Aug. 26, at $13.80.
</P>
<P>
   Dixie Union has made a recovery from knee chips that he suffered
in last year's Breeders' Cup Juvenile. If he has fully returned to
his 2-year-old form, look out. Graeme Hall, who flipped his palate
and had to be eased in the Kentucky Derby, is an in-and-outer, but
when he's on, he's very strong.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he was the best 2-year-old around last year, but
then he chipped his knee in the Breeders' Cup,'' said Richard
Mandella, trainer of Dixie Union. ``We're looking at the Travers,
but that depends on how he comes out of the Jim Dandy. If the race
sets him back, we wouldn't go. If he's OK, we'd love to go.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to give the horse credit, he ran every step of the
way,'' said Todd Pletcher, trainer of Graeme Hall. ``Obviously,
when you win the Jim Dandy, the Travers is the race you're pointing
for. As long as he comes out of this in good shape, that's where
we're heading.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Material from publicity departments at various racetracks was used
to prepare this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
