<HEADLINE>
SUN SETS ON WEST'S NBA CAREER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHIRA SPRINGER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As testament to the impact Jerry West made before his 40-year
NBA career concluded Monday, unrestrained praise came from
colleagues and former bitter rivals alike. Their comments added to
a list of accomplishments that already spoke volumes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jerry West was the best player to ever become a general
manager,'' said Red Auerbach, who faced West as coach of the
Celtics' championship run during the 1960s. ``He's a good friend of
mine and a great player. He was very persistent. He's always kind
of been a winner. I always liked him because he's a hard worker.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know the old saying, `If you want something done right, do
it yourself.' He would do it himself. He took the blame. I think
the league's going to miss him.''
</P>
<P>
   West, 62, retired from his position as head of basketball
operations for the Los Angeles Lakers, leaving behind an impressive
legacy that includes seven NBA titles (one as a player, two as a
consultant, four as GM), Hall of Fame enshrinement, and 14 All-Star
appearances. Since becoming the Lakers' No. 1 draft pick (second
overall) in 1960, West has been one of the pillars of the
franchise.
</P>
<P>
   Earning the nickname ``Mr. Clutch'' as an indomitable guard,
West led Los Angeles to nine NBA finals and the 1971-72 league
title. During three seasons as a coach, West compiled a 145-101
record. As general manager since 1982 and executive vice president
of basketball operations since 1995, he constructed teams that
appeared in the postseason 17 times, won four championships, and
posted a 972-472 record, and he earned 1995 Executive of the Year
honors.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter released by the Lakers, West addressed fans and
thanked them for their support over the past four decades: ``This
is a difficult yet happy time for me personally as I retire my
position with the Los Angeles Lakers and enter another period of my
life, one that will allow me more freedom to enjoy my friends and
particularly my family, unburdened with the pressures of
professional athletic business . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been blessed with the privilege to play for and work
for the best athletic franchise in all of sports, and I will always
treasure the experience. As I watch their progress with great
interest and pride, I will remain their biggest fan.''
</P>
<P>
   General manager Mitch Kupchak will succeed West, and Kurt Rambis
will serve as assistant general manager. Owner Jerry Buss, however,
recognized that the retirement leaves a large void in the
organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, Jerry West is irreplaceable,'' said Buss. ``What
he's meant to the Lakers' franchise over the past 40 years is
immeasurable.''
</P>
<P>
   Members of rival Celtics teams, whose dominance in the 1960s
kept West from winning more than one championship ring as a player,
complimented his skill as a player and intelligence as an
executive.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's difficult for an athlete to feel any compassion for an
opponent,'' said Celtics Hall of Famer Bob Cousy. ``But with Elgin
(Baylor) and Jerry, after we won four or five, I started to think
in my heart of hearts that those guys deserved one.''
</P>
<P>
   Said fellow Hall of Famer K.C. Jones, ``He's shown genius and
intelligence and high perfectionism being a general manager. I have
high praise for this man and great respect.''
</P>
<P>
   As a 2-guard with outstanding quickness and long arms, West was
a threat both offensively and defensively. His shooting prowess
puts him at or near the top in several NBA all-time scoring
categories. A career scoring average of 27.0 places West fourth in
NBA history. His playoff scoring average of 29.1 ranks second,
behind only Michael Jordan. With 25,192 points, he is the Lakers'
all-time leading scorer.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you weren't ready to play, he just dominated,'' said
another Celtics great, Jo Jo White. ``When you played the Lakers,
you thought about it in the games leading up to it, knowing you had
to face this guy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fear you might feel was when the game was on the line and
you were facing him. That's why they called him `Mr. Clutch' _
because he knew when to take a shot, what shot to take, plus he
could shoot. Jerry would shoot the high-percentage shot every
time.''
</P>
<P>
   The most difficult move of West's career may have been his last
_ leaving the NBA behind.
</P>
</TEXT>
