<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-SIMMONS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIMMONS TRYING HARD NOT TO DROP OUT OF SIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SMITHFIELD, R.I. _ There was no shortage of candidates for
poster boy of the sadly underachieving 1999 Patriot offense, from
oft-predictable offensive coordinator Ernie Zampese, to
oft-confused quarterback Drew Bledsoe, to slow tight ends who
seldom got open, to runners who didn't run and blockers who didn't
block.
</P>
<P>
   But wide receiver Tony Simmons seemed the perfect symbol of
everything that went wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Simmons was not a key player, his breathtaking fall
from being a young player with high hopes and huge promise at the
start of the season to being a forgotten liability at the end was
symbolic of the entire offense.
</P>
<P>
   Simmons did not run precise routes. He at times would leisurely
run out of bounds inside the first-down marker instead of turning
upfield and fighting for extra yards, a la teammate Troy Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Worst of all, Simmons dropped key passes, most notably in the
final two minutes against the Jets in Foxborough when Bledsoe hit
him with a perfect pass on a fourth-and-33. A week later, in Miami
against the Dolphins, Simmons dropped a long pass over the middle
in the second half that stalled another key drive that might have
turned a defeat into a victory.
</P>
<P>
   Like the offense in general, Simmons could not be trusted to
make the play that had to be made. So he was virtually banished,
catching only two passes in the final 10 games. Only a year
earlier, the speedy Simmons had been seen as the perfect complement
to deep threat Terry Glenn.
</P>
<P>
   And now?
</P>
<P>
   ``It took a lot out of me,'' Simmons said Monday of his
banishment to special teams in the last half of the 1999 season.
``Last year I wasn't really prepared for playing that much on
special teams.'' Which Simmons quickly proved by fumbling the
opening kickoff in a ragged 24-9 loss to Philadelphia in December.
</P>
<P>
   But what had sent him to special teams were those earlier
dropped passes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had never dropped a pass like that,'' Simmons said of the
drop against the Jets. ``It was the last play of the game (for the
Patriots' offense) and we were trying keep it going. I knew I
should have caught it. But I just didn't catch it. I did everything
fundamentally right, I looked it in and everything, but I just
didn't hold onto the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Simmons said he was shocked by the drop, that ``in college (at
Wisconsin) I was always called on to make plays like that and I
never dropped a pass like that.''
</P>
<P>
   He said his confidence was shaken enough that he dropped the
next key pass to him, the following week against the Dolphins.
After that, Simmons seldom was sent onto the field in key
situations.
</P>
<P>
   In his rookie season of 1998, Simmons had caught 23 passes for 3
touchdowns and a gaudy 20.6 yards-per-catch average. He was seen as
a receiver with huge potential. Last season, though, his numbers
drooped to 19 catches for 2 TDs and a 14.5-yard average.
</P>
<P>
   Now that Zampese is gone, Simmons repeated words that defensive
backs in Miami, Buffalo, Indianapolis, and New York had said last
season about the Patriot pass offense: It was very predictable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most defenses knew what I was going to do _ that I was going
to go deep,'' said Simmons. ``They'd say, `That's his thing; he's
going deep.' So they'd have somebody play deep on me and stuff and
I'd run past them and we'd have somebody come up underneath me and
catch a nice flag route. That was the scheme, and (defenses)
schemed it perfectly.''
</P>
<P>
   That Simmons dropped those passes, that he didn't catch a pass
at all in the final five games, that he no longer is looked upon as
a receiver with huge potential, is all beside the point, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's all in the past,'' said Simmons. ``And I don't really
want to look in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   And the future? Can he regain the form of his rookie year?
</P>
<P>
   ``I can get back to that, but I don't really want to get back to
it,'' said Simmons. ``I want to be better than that. That's my
goal. I'm trying to look forward to something better than my rookie
year. OK, rookie year I had a good season because (other receivers)
got hurt, but I don't want to do that anymore. I want to be in the
offense before that happens.''
</P>
<P>
   But before that can happen, Simmons must peel off the label that
was affixed to him after the 1999 season: that his speed cannot
hide a lack of focus and a lack of achievement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody can think he can be the NFL's best,'' said Simmons.
``But you've got to do it on the field. Thinking it gives you the
hope for it, but then you've got to do it on the field. And doing
it on the field gives you the confidence.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
