<HEADLINE>
FOXBORO STADIUM A BASTION OF PATRIOTISM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Guatemala wants to increase its home-field advantage, it
schedules games at intimate stadia in remote locations at midday or
at an elevation that requires oxygen tanks for the visitors.
</P>
<P>
   The US strategy is similar. For must-win games, the US books a
moribund, concrete-and-steel bowl whose original construction costs
wouldn't pay for a luxury suite at a new stadium.
</P>
<P>
   But Foxboro Stadium has been good to the US national team. The
US has a 4-0-3 record (8-0-4, including women's games) on Route 1.
And even though the US will be heavily favored in next Wednesday's
World Cup qualifier against Barbados, US Soccer Federation
officials want to use every advantage.
</P>
<P>
   They also are seeking a supportive venue for a tough-sell game.
The sense of qualifying drama seems premature since this is only
the third of a possible 12 games.
</P>
<P>
   The US is difficult to cast as an underdog in anything, but the
fact is the team is in last place in Group E and will likely have
to defeat Barbados, Guatemala (Sept. 3 at RFK Stadium), and Costa
Rica (Oct. 11 at Columbus Crew Stadium) to advance to the next
round for the 2002 World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Barbados is hardly a marquee opponent, though the Bajan Rockets
are a potentially fascinating underdog story.
</P>
<P>
   With the Japan/Korea 2002 finals so far off, there is almost a
sense of unreality about these qualifying games. That should change
as the US' home campaign begins.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Bruce Arena plans to make several changes.
</P>
<P>
   Brad Friedel will be the starting goalkeeper and Tony Meola the
backup. Kasey Keller will be allowed to remain with Rayo Vallecano
to ensure he has a chance to earn a starting position. This will
also help Friedel retain his work permit in England, where he is
expected to move from Liverpool to join Joe-Max Moore at crosstown
rival Everton, or rejoin former coach Graeme Souness at Blackburn
Rovers.
</P>
<P>
   D.C. United's Jeff Agoos and Carlos Llamosa, and possibly
Chicago's C.J. Brown, will bolster the defense.
</P>
<P>
   Brian McBride and Moore could be the starting strikers. McBride
is the leading US scorer at Foxboro Stadium with two goals, both in
a 4-2 win over El Salvador Nov. 16, 1997 _ the last time the US
men's team performed in Massachusetts. And Moore converted 21 goals
at Foxboro as a member of the Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   What will the US do, however, when its favorite stadium is
demolished to make way for the new Patriots stadium in 2001?
Probably move right in.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, soccer plays an important part in the new stadium
design. The first event there will be a soccer game, likely a Major
League Soccer match though a better idea might be an exhibition
between, say, the Revolution and the US national team. And there
will be many more soccer games than any other events there,
including NFL games.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, atmosphere at soccer games is still created by the
fans themselves, and New England soccer supporters are probably the
most persistent (judging by Revolution crowds) and varied in the
country. They have been pro-US; in 12 dates involving national
teams, attendance has been 416,254. And they have also been
pro-Italy (the Azzurri are 3-0-0 at Foxboro), pro-Ireland (2-1-2 at
Foxboro), pro-Argentina and pro-Colombia (both 2-0-0 at Foxboro),
supportive of Portugal and its club teams, and even El Salvador,
Greece, Mexico, and Nigeria (combined 1-9-1 at Foxboro).
</P>
<P>
   By the time the new venue is completed, the US will be either in
the middle of the final qualifying round or in the midst of a major
crisis. And the old Foxboro Stadium could be remembered either as
the place that launched a three-game US rally or where its 2002
hopes ended.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Future shock
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The US will not likely be a candidate for the World Cup soon,
despite setting attendance records in 1994. The principle of a
rotation system starting in 2010 was accepted during the FIFA
Congress, involving all but one of the 204 nations in Zurich last
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The US would be relegated deep into that rotation, possibly not
until something like 2034, unless FIFA switches to a biennial
schedule.
</P>
<P>
   In this hemisphere, the US would fall in line behind South
America _ probably Brazil _ and possibly Mexico. The rotation
system would be fairer than the current one, which caused such
rancor that South Africa, the 2010 host, called for arbitration
concerning the 2006 vote.
</P>
<P>
   Asian countries are feeling the effects of the 2006 vote, since
the Asians supported Germany over South Africa. The Africans have
vaguely threatened revenge.
</P>
<P>
   And FIFA must now clarify a controversy over the hosting of the
2001 Confederations Cup, envisioned as a trial run for the
Japan/Korea finals. The Japanese said the announcement was ``very
sudden, without any consultation beforehand, neglecting the
Japanese association's independence.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
