<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRACES-ADULTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE GAP CLOSES: BRACES NOT ONLY FOR THE YOUNG 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MEGAN SCOTT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Betty DeSimone never laughed without covering her mouth. Her
overbite made her so self-conscious that she used her hands to
cover her teeth. Then, at age 38, she decided to get braces.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I smile now I know that what people see are beautiful,
straight teeth,'' said the Boston dental office manager, now 52.
</P>
<P>
   DeSimone is part of a revolution at orthodontists' offices, as
grown-ups join youngsters in getting braces _ ond often the
nickname ``metal mouth.'' According to the American Association of
Orthodontists, more than 1 million people over the age of 18 in the
United States and Canada wear braces or other orthodontic
``appliances,'' making up 20 percent of all orthodontia patients.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the young, who have embraced braces as a kind of fashion
statement, though, adults still have to swallow some pride when
they join the children in the waiting room. Even the explosion in
the number of celebrities who have worn braces _ from Brett Favre
of the Green Bay Packers to tennis player Zina Garrison and singers
Diana Ross and Cher _ makes many adults feel only slightly less
awkward.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big difference between getting them when you're young and
old is that everyone has them when you're young, and it's not a big
deal,'' said Barbi Pecenco, 26, who endured taunts of ``jaws'' from
some co-workers when she wore braces a year ago. ``But when you're
older, people look at you twice.''
</P>
<P>
   The growing number of adults shelling out $3,500 to $5,500 for
orthodontic care underscores Americans' growing emphasis on health
and self-improvement. People want to look and feel better, and they
realize that a winning smile can mean better self-esteem.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doing orthodontics is like what women are going through with
cosmetic surgery,'' said Dr. Donald Feldman, an orthodontist in
East Boston. People ``want to feel better about themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Chris Cutter, age 29, got his white, ceramic braces about four
weeks ago. He wanted them as a teenager, but didn't think his teeth
were bad enough. When his father offered to pay for them, he jumped
at the chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was pure vanity, I guess,'' said Cutter, who does public
relations in Framingham, Mass. ``I decided, why not close up the
gaps and straighten everything out?''
</P>
<P>
   Vanity is not the only reason that adults in their 30s, 40s and
50s are now so willing to endure the ``tinsel teeth'' look. Today's
braces are also less expensive (in relative terms, anyway), less
ugly and more effective than the braces of old.
</P>
<P>
   Although the cost of getting braces has gone up at least 50
percent since 1980 _ when the average treatment cost about $2,200 _
the price has not risen as swiftly as inflation. As a result, the
real cost of braces is actually declining as the robust economy is
giving people more money to spend on cosmetic procedures. Most
orthodontists are willing to stretch out payments, and insurance
plans sometimes help pay the cost.
</P>
<P>
   Age has never been a bar to getting braces, orthodontists say.
Although associated with young, growing mouths, braces can correct
underbites, close gaps and straighten teeth in people of any age.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as the surrounding, supporting tissue is healthy, we
can move teeth in any way,'' said Feldman. ``The only limiting
factor is if someone has a tremendous amount of bone loss.''
</P>
<P>
   Morevoer, the braces and other appliances of today simply work
and look better than before. Because of advances in orthdontics,
adult patients can be treated in less time, with appliances that
are less obtrusive.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't have the traditional, metal mouth look,'' said Dr.
Richard Ulbrich, an orthodontist in Wellesley, Mass. ``Technology
has made it much more patient-friendly.''
</P>
<P>
   Most adults choose to have small metal and ceramic,
tooth-colored brackets bonded to the front surface of the teeth, or
so-called ``invisible'' braces, called linguals, applied to the
back of the teeth.
</P>
<P>
   However, many orthodontists say that the lingual braces are not
as efficient or as easy to work with. More popular in Europe than
here, they can impede speech and cost up to twice as much as
regular braces.
</P>
<P>
   Another choice, nickel-titanium wires, made from an alloy
developed by NASA, are more elastic, which results in reduced
discomfort related to tooth movement and increased time (6-8 weeks)
between orthodontics appointments.
</P>
<P>
   The ceramic braces ``are smooth. They're not sharp. The new
wires they have move their teeth quicker, using a lighter, gentler
force,'' Feldman said.
</P>
<P>
   For adult patients who don't want brackets or wires, a procedure
called invisalign straightens teeth with a series of clear,
customized removable appliances called aligners. The procedure
costs slightly more than traditional braces, and the length of
treatment is virtually the same.
</P>
<P>
   But for adults who aren't shy about being temporary ``metal
mouths,'' many choose to wear the colorful, rubber bands favored by
children. Feldman said that in his office, after a couple of months
with ceramic braces, 40 percent of the adults opt for the colored
bands.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are no longer self conscious about wearing the
appliances,'' he said. ``They just want to end up with the best
possible results in the shortest period of time. How they look with
the appliances doesn't matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who want an instant, post-braces smile can see an esthetic
dentist for ``accelerated orthodontics,'' a technique that reshapes
and bonds the teeth, covering them with a thin, porcelain veneer.
The procedure can be completed in two to three visits.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you look at the Hollywood stars and models, many times it
looks like they have perfectly natural teeth, but many times they
have porcelain veneers,'' said Dr. Thomas Orent of the Center for
Esthetic Dentistry in Framingham. ``The results are absolutely
gorgeous. In many cases, the results are better than braces.''
</P>
<P>
   But Orent is quick not to dismiss braces. He offers almost 95
percent of his patients braces first.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the cosmetic benefits of a million-dollar smile, there
are major dental health benfits of straighter teeth, orthodontists
say. They are easier to clean, which decreases the chance of
periodontal disease, cavities and tooth loss. Correction of an
overbite decreases the risk of wearing down the teeth when chewing
and biting.
</P>
<P>
   Getting braces ``is the best thing I've ever done,'' said
Antonella Dalessio, 24. ``I actually smile now, and before I
didn't. Whether you get them when you're young or older, I'd say
they're very well worth it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
