<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-HUNTINGTONS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO QUICK CURE AFTER DISCOVERY OF HUNTINGTON'S GENE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD SALTUS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It had been dubbed the ``Holy Grail of genetics'' _ the gene
causing the horrendous inherited killer, Huntington's disease. And
in 1993, when scientists finally found the gene after an exhaustive
10-year effort, hopes soared among researchers and families.
</P>
<P>
   Even as the champagne flowed, some scientists believed that,
with the mutant gene in hand, new ways of stalling or curing the
disabling brain degeneration wouldn't be far off.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was huge excitement because everyone figured, `We have
the gene; we'll just crack it,' '' said Dr. Jang-Ho Cha, a
Huntington's disease researcher at Massachusetts General Hospital.
``But here we are in the year 2000, and we still haven't cracked
it.'' He added, ``I'm tired of saying to patients, `there's nothing
we can offer you.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The disappointed hopes of the victims of Huntington's disease
and their loved ones serve as a cautionary tale for the Age of
Genomics. As much as scientists have learned in the last decade
about the human genetic blueprint, they still face enormous
difficulty in curing even the simplest genetic disease: one caused
by a single defective gene.
</P>
<P>
   And it serves as an antidote to the euphoria surrounding the
announcement in July that scientists had mapped all 3.1 billion
biochemical ``letters'' of human DNA, the complete instructions for
operating a fully functional human being.
</P>
<P>
   The immense gene-mapping project was designed to make it easier
to locate disease-causing genes in DNA. But it is becoming
increasingly clear that going from finding the gene to devising a
treatment is a long, rough road.
</P>
<P>
   For example, mapping the gene that causes cystic fibrosis,
discovered in 1990, has failed so far to produce a treatment. Nor
has the finding of the Duchenne muscular dystrophy gene in 1986
helped sufferers of that lethal malady.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something may come from that, but I would be very surprised''
if biotech companies using genome information to find disease genes
``made a big killing in the next 10, 20 or 50 years,'' said Dr.
David Waltz, assistant director of the cystic fibrosis unit at
Children's Hospital. He noted that since the cystic fibrosis gene
was found, all efforts to treat the lung disease by transferring
new genes into lung cells have failed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had 10 years to study (the mutant gene), and we know now
that there's more we don't know than we know,'' said Waltz.
</P>
<P>
   Finding the gene for a disease is a bit like tracing a glitch in
a car to a certain part. If you don't know what the part normally
does or why its malfunction makes the car fail to run, fixing it
can take a very long time. And with diseases like Huntington's, it
appears that the main disease gene is influenced by still other
genes whose roles are unknown.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Waltz and other researchers maintain they are
uncovering important clues about how the flawed genes do their
dirty work. They're confident that treatments do lie ahead. The
impatience, in cases like Huntington's, is because the diseases
cause so much suffering not only in the afflicted person but in
their families as well.
</P>
<P>
   Huntington's toll can be appreciated in a visit to SunBridge
Care and Rehabilitation in Lowell, one of the very few facilities
that specialize in caring for Huntington's disease patients.
</P>
<P>
   The outlook is grim. The disease, whose symptoms don't usually
appear until the 30s or 40s, relentlessly progresses toward death
10 to 20 years after diagnosis. Dying brain cells _ caused by an
inherited mutant gene _ lead to dementia, mood swings, muddled
thinking, sometimes psychosis. Loss of balance and motor control
culminates in total disability _ like a man seen at the SunBridge
Care and Rehabilitation facility here, slumped in a wheelchair,
head flopping, tongue hanging out.
</P>
<P>
   ``This disease has just run rampant through our family,'' said
Connie Sullivan of Wellesley, the mother of two sons who have been
placed in the facility. Her former husband also had Huntington's,
and his angry behavior _ which wasn't recognized as Huntington's at
the time _ destroyed their marriage.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Gieras, 49, used to work in a camera repair shop, but
now his only job, since coming to SunBridge six months ago, is
sorting popsicle sticks in a sheltered workshop. Even when he's
sitting, Michael's body ripples with tics and writhing movements _
a hallmark of Huntington's, along with unsteady balance, erratic or
aggressive behavior, depression, psychosis, dementia.
</P>
<P>
   Michael is soft-spoken and optimistic, but his brother, Jesse,
is said to be belligerent and aggressive: he refuses to talk to his
brother or mother.
</P>
<P>
   Some residents are in advanced stages of HD: A number of
patients are equipped with white crash helmets to prevent injuries
in the inevitable falls.
</P>
<P>
   In the final stages, ``they can't do anything. They can't eat,
walk, talk. It's sad,'' said Dr. Walter Koroshetz, a neurologist at
Massachusetts General Hospital who has several patients at
SunBridge.
</P>
<P>
   About 30,000 people in the United States are afflicted with
Huntington's. But researchers are also concerned about another
150,000 people who are at risk because a parent had Huntington's.
</P>
<P>
   Because the symptoms of Huntington's often don't appear until
adulthood or mid-life, many victims have already had children
before they are diagnosed. The child of a Huntington's sufferer has
a 50 percent chance of inheriting the disease. It's not unusual for
SunBridge to have related residents: at present, three sisters from
one family are here.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to SunBridge, where 63 of 160 residents are
Huntington's disease patients, Tewksbury State Hospital specializes
in their care. Massachusetts is known for these facilities, which
Koroshetz of Mass. General said provides some comfort, especially
for people who have been diagnosed but have not yet been disabled
by the disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``They know what they're in for, and if there's no place where
they can feel comfortable going to when they need to go, it's
frightful,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Massachusetts we have the best delivery of care for
Huntington's disease of anyplace in the world,'' added Cha, the
Mass. General researcher.
</P>
<P>
   While the Huntington's disease gene finding hasn't led to a
cure, it has drawn money and research talent into the pursuit of
many leads.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are more people working on this disease now than you
would believe,'' said James Gusella, the Mass. General
neurogeneticist who found the first clue to the location of the
Huntington's disease gene in 1983 and who headed the team that
finally plucked out the gene itself 10 years later.
</P>
<P>
   Having the gene in hand has provided enormous leverage to the
research because it enabled scientists to create strains of mice
that carry the gene _ even though they don't develop quite the same
symptoms as humans do.
</P>
<P>
   With an animal model, scientists can try to determine why the
abnormal protein, called huntingtin, made by the Huntington's
disease gene causes brain cell death. In an intriguing experiment,
researchers created a Huntington's mouse in which they could turn
the production of the mutant huntingtin protein on and off.
Astonishingly, when they turned the protein off, the mice improved,
suggesting that the brain damage might be to some extent reversible
if the protein could be blocked.
</P>
<P>
   The animal version of Huntington's also lets scientists rapidly
test drugs in search of one that slows the damage. Two drugs are
now being tried in human Huntington's patients, the first
large-scale drug trials in the disease.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, a few patients have been treated with implants of
fetal brain tissue designed to supply some of the nerve signal
chemicals that are lost when Huntington's disease patients' brain
cells die. But Koroshetz said he hasn't seen much benefit from the
surgery.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, Boston scientists found that a common antibiotic,
minocycline, slowed the pace of the disease in mice, extending
their lives by 14 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Robert Friedlander, a neurosurgeon at Brigham and Women's
Hospital, led researchers who showed that minocycline blocked the
action of enzymes called caspaces that trigger premature brain cell
death in Huntingon's disease. He and other scientists are moving to
start a clinical trial this year.
</P>
<P>
   The Huntington's disease community is cautiously excited about
the results, because minocycline is a drug that's already approved
for human use in treating arthritis and acne.
</P>
<P>
   Such a modest potential advance as minocycline might not seem
like a big payoff 10 years after researchers found ``the Holy Grail
of genetics,'' but researchers say they're learning to be humble
about how well they understand human genetics. And they're learning
to appreciate how far they've come.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the understanding my lab has gained has depended on
cloning the Huntington's gene,'' said Friedlander.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-08-00 1352EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
