<DOCNO> NYT20000808.0113 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 13:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5773 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-NEWENG-SLAVES-BOS &LR;      08-08 1228
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWENG-SLAVES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW ENGLANDERS UNEARTHING PAINFUL FAMILY TIES TO SLAVE TRADE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TATSHA ROBERTSON AND ROSS KERBER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRISTOL, R.I. _ There, laid out atop the antique table, were
pieces of Deborah Howe's family history that she had never seen
amid the portraits and place-settings of her upstanding New England
family: a coiled whip with a woven-hemp handle, and a thick, rusty
pair of iron leg shackles.
</P>
<P>
   Growing up, Howe had heard the story of how her wealthy
ancestors, the Dewolfs, had helped build Bristol into a bustling
seaport. Now her cousin, who had found the whip and shackles in a
basement, was confirming the whisperings she had heard about the
source of the family's prominence: the trans-Atlantic slave trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't like the Dewolfs were saying `Please come to our New
World' _ it was brutal and horrible,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   When talk turns to slavery, New Englanders recall the
abolitionists who loudly pounded their lecterns until the force of
their objections reverberated throughout the country. But that's
just part of the story. Before the Civil War, merchants from the
North like the Dewolfs were so heavily involved that riches from
the slave trade shaped the region _ spawning textile mills,
building towns like Bristol, and founding institutions like Brown
University, which takes its name from a known slave trader.
</P>
<P>
   Now, a new desire to strip back the curtains on an earlier, more
painful chapter in New England's racial history is laying bare a
truth that is still shocking.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was most nervous about how the older generation was going to
react to my wanting to raise these issues,'' said Katrina Browne,
Howe's cousin, who is researching a documentary on the family's and
New England's deep ties to the slave trade. Some of them were
``questioning the value of looking toward the past.''
</P>
<P>
   The roots of slavery went surprisingly deep in the North,
historians say.
</P>
<P>
   The slaves were headed to the plantations of the South, but many
of the ships that carried them were owned by Northern merchants
like the Dewolfs, and built in shipyards in Boston, Providence, and
other commercial centers. The slave trade also built entire
industries, from rum distilleries to insurance companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``The North was probably more deeply involved in the trade than
the South,'' said Richard Newman of Harvard University's W.E.B
DuBois Institute of African-American Research. ``It's a critical
issue that has never been dealt with in the North.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past few months, two longstanding New England
institutions, The Hartford Courant and Aetna, have publicly
disclosed their involvement in slavery. The Courant took money for
printing ads encouraging readers to return runaway slaves for large
cash awards. Aetna profited from insuring slaves.
</P>
<P>
   The region's institutions need to do more to make amends, argues
Deadria Farmer-Paellmann, a 34-year-old New York lawyer who
discovered Aetna's slave connection. She plans to file a lawsuit on
behalf of African-Americans against a dozen Northern financial
institutions, many from New England, that she claims profited from
the slave trade and never made amends.
</P>
<P>
   Browne, a descendant of James Dewolf, began to look into her
family background three years ago. She was reading her
grandmother's account of their history when she was struck by one
paragraph. ``I haven't the stomach enough to describe the ensuing
slave trade,'' her grandmother wrote. ``Suffice to say that all of
Bristol was involved as everyone profited from these ventures.''
</P>
<P>
   After the Revolutionary War, the American shipping industry
began to thrive. And nowhere did the slave-trading business
flourish more than in the seaports of Rhode Island.
</P>
<P>
   Three generations of Dewolfs took advantage of those golden
years, making 88 voyages and becoming the nation's leading slave
traders. The family would return from the slave voyages, spreading
their profits in gold on a table, according to historians.
</P>
<P>
   James Dewolf became one of the richest men in Rhode Island. He
had honed his seafaring skills on African voyages with John Brown
of Providence. Soon, he bought his own ship.
</P>
<P>
   As the Dewolfs flourished in the slave business, so did the
town. Shipbuilders and factory workers all had a hand in the
industry. The Dewolfs built businesses throughout Bristol. Even
today, streets and stores are still named after the family. A wharf
as well as a mansion they built still exist.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the slave trade legally ended in 1808, 402 Rhode
Island men had become ship owners or captains, and their ships
carried 93,400 African slaves along the so-called Middle Passage,
according to the DuBois institute.
</P>
<P>
   According to the author George Howe, who is a relative of
Katrina Browne and Deborah Howe, Bristol ``owed its wealth in this
golden age to the slave trade.''
</P>
<P>
   This wealth, of course, was built on suffering. It was a common
practice, writes George Howe, to cast ill slaves off the ship. One
legend claims a captain on one of Dewolf's ships cut off the hands
of Africans clinging with all their might to the edge of the boat.
</P>
<P>
   The money would shape the region in complicated ways. Even the
blacksmiths who made the chains for the slaves and the barrels for
the rum made money from the voyages, say historians. The trade
ultimately spawned dozens of ancillary businesses such as the
turn-of-the-century cotton mills and iron foundries, said Joanne
Pope Melish, a visiting professor at Brown University.
</P>
<P>
   James Dewolf later used his fortune to build a textile mill
called Arkwright Manufacturer in northern Rhode Island. The
business, renamed Arkwright Inc., is now owned by a Dutch company
and builds overhead transparencies, according to a company
executive.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, financial institutions such as Providence Bank were
built by slave traders like Brown University's Johh Brown. The
now-defunct Hartford Life Insurance Co. reportedly also sold slave
policies. And, Boston insurance companies at the time made up the
majority of the underwriters for Rhode Island slave voyages, said
Browne.
</P>
<P>
   But the same trade that brought so much wealth and prominence to
New England families also helped split them: Moses Brown was an
abolitionist who fiercely fought his brother, John Brown, a
successful slave trader and congressman. The elaborate home of John
Brown, who later became a US senator, still stands on the edge of
the Brown University campus.
</P>
<P>
   As the abolitionists began to win victories in the slavery
debate, the repercussions were felt up and down the coast,
especially in Bristol.
</P>
<P>
   In 1825, with the slave trade over and money drying up, a Cuban
sugar plantation owned by another Dewolf family member, George
Dewolf, failed to deliver the cargo he had promised. The failure
took down the whole town, said Louis P. Cirillo, executive director
of Linden Place, the former home of George Dewolf, which is now a
museum.
</P>
<P>
   In the middle of the night, Dewolf gathered his wife, Charlotte,
and their children and quietly left, said Cirillo.
</P>
<P>
   News spread across the country that a Dewolf business deal had
failed. Soon, merchants were refusing to honor bank notes from
Bristol. And, in a town partially built on slavery, residents tried
to put the past behind them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
