<HEADLINE>
QUARTZ AND OBSIDIAN: WHAT'S THE DIFFERENCE? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. What is the difference between smoky quartz and obsidian,
both in technical and common terms? They seem so similar.
</P>
<P>
   J.M., Middleboro, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Quartz is a fairly transparent crystalline mineral made of
silicon and oxygen with two atoms of oxygen to each silicon.
Crystalline means that it is made of a regularly repeating pattern
of atoms, as opposed to a sort of amorphous blob, which is usually
called ``glass.'' Quartz can acquire color by having impurities _
for example, amethyst is quartz that contains traces of iron or
manganese, and has a purple color. Quartz can also be darkened by
exposure to radiation from radioactive minerals or from cosmic rays
that hit the Earth all the time. Radiation creates tiny defects in
quartz that can absorb light. When this happens to a piece of
quartz that started out clear, you end up with what is called
``smoky quartz.''
</P>
<P>
   Obsidians are natural volcanic glasses (not crystals) that form
from rapidly cooled lava. They flake quite easily, leaving sharp
edges, and thus are ideal for primitive societies to make cutting
implements, such as knives and arrowheads. Chemically, obsidians
vary widely, but to a large extent are similar to quartz, though
they often contain many other substances and can range in color
from clear to black to green, red, or brown.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
