<DOCNO> NYT20000808.0115 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 13:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5775 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-SCI-ADOPTED-EMBRYO-BO     08-08 0679
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-ADOPTED-EMBRYO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LIFE HISTORY WITH A NEW TWIST 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Sidebar with NONFAMILY-EMBRYO)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ADAM PERTMAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Elizabeth and her husband are like most adoptive parents in
almost every way. Except one.
</P>
<P>
   They are the first people in the country to have given birth to
a baby they adopted as an embryo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe with all my heart that this should happen more, and
will,'' said Elizabeth, who asked that her name and location in
Southern California not be disclosed because she believes it should
be her daughter's decision, once she's old enough, whether to share
her story with the world. ``What we did . . . is an ethical, moral
solution to a very difficult problem.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``problem,'' to a devout Christian like such as Elizabeth,
is that the 200,000 frozen embryos in this country are all living
beings who deserve a chance to grow up in loving homes.
</P>
<P>
   An undetermined number of these fertilized eggs are being
donated by their genetic parents to infertile couples. But many
mental-health specialists believe the anonymity usually involved
isn't healthy, particularly for the children, and Elizabeth agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are the ones who are going to have to explain this to our
daughter one day,'' she said. ``Are we going to tell her that she
was donated? I don't think so.''
</P>
<P>
   The convergence of Elizabeth's religious beliefs and her views
on openness in family relationships prompted the formation a few
years ago of the nation's only adoption agency for frozen embryos.
Then Elizabeth and her husband became the first clients of
Snowflakes Embryo Adoption Program, part of Christian Adoption &AMP;
Family Services in Fullerton, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   This new phase in adoption and science history began while
Elizabeth and her husband were discussing their infertility with a
doctor in late 1996. As he explained the creation of embryos
through in-vitro fertilization, Elizabeth started crying.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can't we adopt any embryos that are already there?'' she
recalled asking, without knowing at that time what such a process
might entail, or even if it were possible. The doctor did not seem
interested, but the notion seized her, so she called a friend who
put her in touch with a lawyer at Christian Family Services.
</P>
<P>
   He liked the suggestion and began talks within the agency about
providing such a service. Meanwhile, Elizabeth had contacted Focus
on the Family, a religious organization in Colorado, and told
officials there about her idea; they, too, were intrigued.
</P>
<P>
   Within months, a couple came to Focus on the Family saying they
had 20 frozen embryos remaining from their IVF treatments, didn't
want more children themselves, and were morally opposed to both the
embryos' destruction and their use for research. And they didn't
believe in secrecy, either.
</P>
<P>
   So, using the model of adoption as it is generally practiced,
the couple pored over letters and photos from several prospective
parents _ then chose Elizabeth and her husband.
</P>
<P>
   The 20 cryogenically stored embryos were shipped to a clinic in
Pasadena, where Elizabeth had arranged for implantation. Of the 12
thawed for her first attempt, just three turned out to be viable,
and none took hold to achieve a pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
   One of the three that survived a second thawing made it,
however, and Grace was born on New Year's Eve of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Joanne Davidson, the program director for Snowflakes, said that
her agency has matched embryos for 14 families since June 1997, and
that four women currently are pregnant as a result. Only Elizabeth
has given birth so far, Davidson said.
</P>
<P>
   Snowflakes arranges only open adoptions for embryos. That is,
the two sets of parents make contact, reach an agreement, and stay
in touch to whatever degree they find comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to replay all the mistakes adoption made during
its secretive past,'' Davidson said. ``Now that we understand the
benefits of openness in traditional adoption, we also want to get
it right with what we're doing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
