<TRAILER>
NYT-08-08-00 1357EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000808.0117 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 13:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5778 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-SPCL-RAVAGED-ANGOLA-2     08-08 1224
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPCL-RAVAGED-ANGOLA-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 KUITO, Angola: ... for it.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The doctor grew up in a suburb of Brussels, the son of a pencil
factory owner, but he feels his upbringing was not so far removed
from what he sees now in Angola. He pointedly notes billions of
dollars that have funded the war came from diamonds, and the
world's diamond-trading hub is his native Belgium.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here I am cutting off legs from mines paid for by diamonds,''
Rijs said. ``I think about it all the time. It's crazy. Antwerp,
the capital of the diamond industry, is a very nice town. I know it
well. I studied medicine there.''
</P>
<P>
   Later that day, as 10-year-old Silva emitted little cries of
pain in his bed, he finally strung together a few words of mercy
for his father, ``Please, father, cover me. I'm cold.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, son,'' said the father, moving the blanket over the boy,
leaving exposed only his wrapped left arm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Please, father, please cover me,'' the boy said again.
</P>
<P>
   The father moved the blanket over the arm. He has stayed at the
hospital with the boy since the accident. They share the same bed.
They both lie awake most nights, the boy from his pain, the father
from hearing the boy's pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ask God to heal my son,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He pulled out a Bible and read from Psalm 8, speaking in a
forceful voice that bounced off the 14-foot ceilings of Infirmary
No. 4:
</P>
<P>
   ``Thou whose glory above the heavens is chanted by the mouths of
babes and infants, Thou hast founded a bulwark.''
</P>
<P>
   Willpower and faith are the only weapons most people have.
</P>
<P>
   At the United Nations, one might expect some sensitivity to
questions about last year's ranking of Angola as the worst place to
be a child. But there was none.
</P>
<P>
   It is widely believed to be accurate. The rankings were culled
from the under-5 mortality rate, the percent of children
underweight, the percent of children not attending school, whether
the country was at war, and the HIV/AIDS rate for 15- to
49-year-olds. Right behind Angola were Sierre Leone, Somalia,
Afghanistan, and Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the places at the bottom of the list are war places,''
said Olara Otunnu, the UN special representative on children and
armed conflict. ``In every respect, there's a very direct link
between the deterioration of the quality of life and war. You see
it in the breaking up of families, the losing out on school, the
losing out on health, the girls being raped. All this dramatically
rises in war, and when war persists for decades as it has in
Angola, everything is broken in its path. And with that breakdown,
children are the most vulnerable.''
</P>
<P>
   At the UNICEF office in the capital of Luanda, Dr. Oscar
Castillo, UNICEF's project officer for health, said one simple way
to measure the war's impact on children was to ask a child his or
her age.
</P>
<P>
   ``You ask a boy who is about this height, his age,'' said the
doctor, putting his hand about 3 1/2 feet from the ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``He says, `12.' You say, `No, wait, I said what is your age?'
He says, `12.' There is a whole generation of stunted children and
this from a people who are genetically tall. Then you wonder how it
is going to affect them psychologically, mentally. Even if the war
ended now, the country will take a generation to solve this issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``And, you know,'' he said, ``for a child, tomorrow is too
late.''
</P>
<P>
   It is too late for Candilo Quarasma, 15, who lost his right leg
six years ago. He was following his older brother in a field when
he stepped on a mine. His brother had the luck of a longer stride.
</P>
<P>
   ``I fell down,'' Candilo said. ``I didn't feel anything. I saw
my leg was not there, so I started crying. My brother carried me,
and we got to the hospital. I stayed two months.''
</P>
<P>
   He said his favorite activities now are to spend time in a
nearby garden, to play soccer on his crutches, and to run. Asked if
he could remember what it was like to run with two legs, he said:
``I can't remember that at all. I can't run as before, and my
crutch hurts my arms, but I still like to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   His father, Jean Sao Paulo Genge, 58, listened to him. He said
Candilo often turns sad.
</P>
<P>
   ``He starts to cry, and I tell him, `Don't cry. There are lots
of other children without legs.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Neither father nor son expressed anger about the laying of the
mines. ``All the cities are surrounded by mines,'' the father said.
``We don't get upset. It's like a fate.''
</P>
<P>
   If so, the fate is horrible to see.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem with mines is that they are really dirty,'' said
Rijs, preparing to go once again into the operating room. ``All the
dust and dirt is blowing upward, sometimes going up really high
into the leg muscles. To prevent infection, you cannot close it for
the first few days. You leave it open and everything comes out.''
</P>
<P>
   He remembered well the night of Feb. 14, when a truck from
Camacupa pulled up at dusk to the hospital. Inside the truck bed
was a bundle of moaning people, all victims of an antitank mine
that had exploded under their truck.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to the MSF house, got a big solar lamp just to see what
was in the truck. There were open fractures, people lying over each
other, their luggage everywhere. It's almost night. There's no
electricity. A fuel shortage. We got a generator up and running. I
did triage. It was war surgery, from 7 that night until 3 the next
morning,'' he said. In that truck were 18 injured people and three
bodies. ``It was horrible, and it was exceptional how we worked
together. I went home and had a whiskey.''
</P>
<P>
   The doctor began scrubbing his hands with soap in a sink and
walked into the operating room, where a nurse poured iodine over
his hands. The iodine, another precaution against the spread of
infection, spilled through his hands to the floor and onto his
sandals, staining them red. The doctor kept talking.
</P>
<P>
   ``One woman that night, her name was Maria de Leudes, she's just
outside here,'' he pointed to the hallway, where five patients
waited on beds. ``Can you believe it? Maria de Leudes, named after
the place where miracles happen. She lost her brother, her husband,
her son, and her leg.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's incredible is that life goes on for her and for the
others after this. They keep going on. They are fantastic people.
They smile. They laugh. They are in the (expletive) war now for 30
years.''
</P>
<P>
   He told nurses to begin checking for infections in the wound of
his first patient, Luis Manuel.
</P>
<P>
   He had three amputated legs to look at, those belonging to
Manuel, Victorino Canhala, and Daniel Miguel. He also had to check
abscesses in the amputated legs of Maria de Leudes and Pelina
Chova.
</P>
<P>
   Rijs will leave his post Thursday. He will be replaced by
another Medecins Sans Frontieres surgeon. This morning he was in a
testy mood. Angola has been a trial, even after work in Cambodia,
Chad, South Africa, and southern Sudan. When he leaves, he said, he
will spend two months in the Alps, time to forget all the limbs
that he has cut.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not nice,'' he kept repeating under his mask, as he cut
tendons, snipped out infected muscle, and then poked his index
finger inside a hole in Manuel's right leg only to find a
pinkie-sized piece of metal. He held the metal up to the light. It
was a piece of a mine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not nice,'' he said of his work. ``But it has to be done.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
