<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 13:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5780 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-SPCL-RAVAGED-ANGOLA-A     08-08 1280
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPCL-RAVAGED-ANGOLA-ART-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 THE GAPING WOUNDS OF ANGOLA'S WAR 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN DONNELLY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KUITO, Angola _ There was nothing sacred in the operating room,
not the thoughts of the doctor, not the body of the patient, not
the blood dripping off an operating table that was shaped like a
cross.
</P>
<P>
   Nurses tied the teenager's slender wrists with nylon rope to the
table. They didn't touch his leg, his left leg.
</P>
<P>
   A land mine had taken the right.
</P>
<P>
   The surgeon, Dr. Jean Rijs, began unwrapping the sticky bandages
around Victorino Canhala's right stump. He kicked a blue bucket
under the table. The bucket rattled as the boy's blood spattered
inside it.
</P>
<P>
   The doctor was fed up. This is what he had been doing for a year
_ one, two, three amputations a week.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not nice surgery,'' he said through a mask that left only
his dark eyes visible. ``It's not surgery at all. This is what
war's about _ cutting legs.''
</P>
<P>
   It is also a lens through which to see Kuito, a city of hundreds
and hundreds of people with just one leg, and to see the whole of
Angola, maimed as it is.
</P>
<P>
   Angola is the worst place in the world to be a child, UNICEF
said. It has more amputees per capita than anywhere else. Its land
is believed to be sown with more land mines per square mile than
any other nation.
</P>
<P>
   And yet such depths of misery elicit only a few peeps of
response from outside powers. The war here keeps grinding on into
its fourth decade far from the view of the outside world, seen only
in the byproduct of the river of displaced people, who at last
count neared 2 million.
</P>
<P>
   They flee the fighting and banditry in the countryside for huts
in camps or urban warrens full of drunks, prostitutes, and
malnourished children wandering about with open wounds, scenes that
resemble the postnuclear horrors of a ``Mad Max'' movie.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Western governments and the diamond industry agreed
in Belgium to belated steps that will make it harder for the
Angolan and Sierra Leone rebels to sell diamonds and fund war
chests. But diplomats here say the impact in Angola may be at best
a slowing of the war, the application of a loose tourniquet, but
not enough to end the fighting.
</P>
<P>
   A UN plea last month for $8.4 million to help 300,000 recently
displaced people in disease-ridden camps received two quick
pledges: $2 million from the US State Department and $560,000 from
Sweden. Groups such as Oxfam, CARE, and Medecins Sans Frontieres,
or Doctors Without Borders, also have been active, making appeals
for private funding for operations here.
</P>
<P>
   But what is especially tragic about such emergency requests is
that without war, Angola could be extraordinarily wealthy. Not only
does it have huge diamond reserves, but it is also expected soon to
be Africa's leading oil producer. It now supplies 7 percent of US
oil imports, a figure that could double in five years.
</P>
<P>
   There is no end in sight to the war, said a Western diplomat who
noted that Angola's government and the UNITA rebels both have been
busy laying more mines, even as the British charity, the Halo
Trust, has been removing mines from fields.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I asked my bosses what they would consider a success from
my tenure here, they had no answer for me,'' the diplomat said.
``It means they have no agenda for Angola. They expect nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   There are no UN forces here, and there are no plans to send
them, ever since they were pulled out 18 months ago when rebels
shot down two UN planes. And the government has rejected peace
feelers from the rebel chief, Jonas Savimbi, as untrustworthy
offerings. Savimbi has broken peace accords twice before.
</P>
<P>
   Angola is a glimpse into the beyond, where evil moves like a
parasitic disease, worming its way into the lives of innocents who
know of the dangers but still cannot avoid them.
</P>
<P>
   At the almost exact geographical center of Angola sits Kuito, a
city of nearly 1 million people that has swelled by 200,000 in
recent months with outlying villagers displaced by rural fighting
and new minefields.
</P>
<P>
   There is no safe way into the city on the ground. The airspace
outside city limits also is unsafe, and pilots flying UN World Food
Program planes enter the city at high altitudes and then pirouette
their aircraft in tight descending circles for landing, to avoid
the rebels' Stinger missiles.
</P>
<P>
   All supplies are flown in, even fuel. All international aid
workers are forbidden to travel outside city limits.
</P>
<P>
   The government controls the city, but that's all.
</P>
<P>
   The people here are not just cordoned off from the rest of the
world, they live in a place frozen in time. Government troops and
rebels shelled this city for nine months in 1993 and '94, killing
30,000 to 50,000 people and leaving behind the skeletons of
once-majestic buildings constructed by Portuguese colonials.
</P>
<P>
   The buildings, painted in disconcertingly tropical colors
reminiscent of Miami Beach _ bright yellow, pink, raspberry, azure,
and mauve _ look like jigsaw puzzles with hundreds of missing
pieces.
</P>
<P>
   The police station lacks outer walls. The post office, long ago
shut down, has rows of metal boxes full of bullet holes. The Bank
of Angola's grand stairwell is still lined with Italian tiles, but
the roof's barrel tiles will blow off in a windstorm and the weeds
on the second floor have sprouted 2 feet high.
</P>
<P>
   Today, evidence of war arrives more stealthily than the
onslaught several years ago. It arrives on foot, in the number of
wounded civilians appearing every morning at the doors of the
Provincial Hospital of Kuito, Dr. Rijs's lair.
</P>
<P>
   Rijs, a youthful 40, his shock of black hair standing almost on
edge and a stubble of whiskers covering his chin, is the only
surgeon at the 400-bed hospital. He works for Medecins Sans
Frontieres, last year's winner of the Nobel Peace Prize for its
healing work and its record of speaking out about zones of
conflict.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're overcrowded,'' he said, starting his rounds one day
recently. ``It's because I had a lot of gunshots last week. We also
have a lot of people injured from mines.''
</P>
<P>
   In Infirmary No. 4, he stepped over a female patient lying on
the floor and stopped at bed 22, which held Silva Chivinda, 10.
</P>
<P>
   The boy whimpered softly.
</P>
<P>
   He had been cutting wood with a machete on June 16 _ UNICEF's
Day of the African Child _ when the machete struck a mine. Silva
was bent at the waist, and the mine tore into the entire front of
his body. In the bed, his legs and arms were wrapped in white
gauze, his left eye was an exposed socket and his right eye was
nearly shut.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's lost sight in both eyes,'' the doctor said softly in
English, as the boy's Umbundo-speaking father, Avalino da Silva,
tried to understand the words. ``I had to remove one.''
</P>
<P>
   Rijs moved on, pointing to each bed and giving one-phrase
explanations, ``gunshot in the leg,'' ``another gunshot,'' ``mine
victim,'' ``mine victim,'' ``gunshot.''
</P>
<P>
   He finally paused. ``You never get used to this. Never, never,
never,'' he said. ``For me, it's not surgery. It's _ what do you
call it _ it's butchery. When you see how these people come in to
the hospital, it's awful. That boy who lost his eyes. Oh, my God.
What's his future? Sure there are bad stories everywhere here. But
for what?
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a guy who was digging graves and a mine exploded on
him,'' the doctor said. ``He died after a week. But that small boy,
that's awful. There are no words for it.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
