<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 14:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5781 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN-COX     08-08 0680
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: So, why not Lieberman?
 &HT;    For immediate release.
 &HT;    By HOWARD KLEINBERG
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The question for almost a decade now _ since Colin Powell
emerged exalted from the Gulf War -- has been this: ``Is America
ready for a black president?'' The general and his wife decided not
to try to force an answer to that just yet. Then there were the
female prospects beginning with Shirley Chisholm in the '70s and,
most recently, Elizabeth Dole. Not yet, the country seemed to say.
</P>
<P>
   Now there's a new question: ``Is America ready for a Jewish vice
president, only a heartbeat away from the presidency?''
</P>
<P>
   And the answer needs to be a typical Jewish one, a return
question: ``Why not?''
</P>
<P>
   What is it about Joseph Lieberman that makes him a controversial
candidate? His Jewishness. Not his record, but his Jewishness.
</P>
<P>
   Which raises the question: ``What's Dick Cheney's religion?''
Yes, it's Christian, but what kind of Christian? Is it important?
Not to me. I voted at least three times for Southern Baptists even
though that religion's formal body decided that because of my
religion, I'm not going to get to heaven. I voted for the men, not
their religion.
</P>
<P>
   Since word leaked out early Monday that Al Gore was going to
select Connecticut Sen. Joseph Lieberman as his vice-presidential
running mate, I've been monitoring the reaction on America Online's
selected message board. That's the place where the bigots get to
sound off anonymously. Unless John Rocker has a half-million
different screen names, he's not the only bigot in this country.
</P>
<P>
   That's sad, but I do not believe it represents the nation. And
judging by the spelling errors in those electronic reactions, the
administration that takes office next year needs to beef up
education spending.
</P>
<P>
   Forty years ago, an issue was whether the Roman Catholic John F.
Kennedy would be representing the Vatican in the White House. It
took up the early part of his campaign but was quickly defused, and
he became the first Catholic elected to the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman also must undergo an early acid test. No matter his
position on abortion, school vouchers, Cuba or Bill Clinton,
Lieberman's religion takes center stage.
</P>
<P>
   The silliest concern, of course, is whether Lieberman, being an
Orthodox Jew, will be able to function when his Sabbath begins at
sundown Friday and continues to sundown Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   One needs only to check airline reservations out of Washington
D.C. on Friday afternoons, returning early Monday morning, to
recognize that no one -- not Jews, not Catholics, not
Presbyterians, not anyone -- puts in weekend work in the capital
unless there is a major crisis. Lieberman already has said, and
demonstrated, that his Sabbath will not deter him from critical
needs and decisions that day.
</P>
<P>
   While Lieberman would generally take Saturday off, he could be
working hard on Sunday while everyone else was playing golf.
</P>
<P>
   What Gore did with the selection of Lieberman was pull off a
political stunt. He's using Lieberman's centrist political beliefs
and recognized morality to buck the Clinton monkey from his back.
Gore didn't pick Lieberman because he was Jewish. He picked him for
what he represents.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, Lieberman's religion will play a role in how the Arab
states look at us, but that's only if he's elected. And what choice
do the Arabs have? George Bush already has said that if he's
elected, he'd move the U.S. embassy from Tel Aviv to Jerusalem.
That's the last thing Arabs wanted to hear; Joe Lieberman couldn't
say or do anything that would more horrify them.
</P>
<P>
   To those who fear Lieberman as vice president of the United
States, here's a lighter observation: At least we'd have someone as
President of the Senate who would be cutting the pork out of the
federal budget.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
