<P>
   &UR; Angola is believed to be sown with more land mines per square
mile than any other nation. And yet such depths of misery this
produces elicits only a few peeps of response from outside powers.
The war here keeps grinding on into its fourth decade far from the
view of the outside world, seen only in the byproduct of the river
of displaced people, who at last count neared 2 million. &LR;   &UR; In a
special report, Globe diplomatic staff reporter John Donnelly and
