 AM-NYT-BUDGET  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR WEDNESDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Wednesday, Aug. 9:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (``p'' code)
</P>
<P>
   GORE-LIEBERMAN (Nashville) _ Vice President Gore formally
announces that Sen. Joseph Lieberman will be his running mate. By
Katharine Q. Seelye. (1500 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   GORE-SELECTION (Nashville) _ How the Gore vice presidential
selection process worked. By David Barstow.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   GORE-ASSESS (Washington) _ A news analysis on how the selection
of running mates has changed over the years. By R.W. Apple Jr.
</P>
<P>
   JEWS-SOUTH (Atlanta) _ Jews have had difficulties running for
office in the South, but that seems to be in the past. By David
Firestone.
</P>
<P>
   LIEBERMAN-BUSINESS (Washington) _ Campaign donation records, and
the many of his Senate votes, show Lieberman has been cozy with
pharmaceutical companies, insurance companies and other business
interests. By David E. Rosenbaum.
</P>
<P>
   Other Gore-Lieberman stories as appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   REFORM-PARTY (Long Beach, Calif.) _ The Reform Party executive
committee wrangles over Buchanan's delegates. By Michael Janofsky.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS (Undated) _ Notes from the campaign trail.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   WEST-FIRES (Hamilton, Mont.) _ At the scene of the worst of
scores of forest fires around the country. With feeds from
California and Colorado. By Ross E. Milloy.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   WEST-FIRES-CLINTON (Burgdorf Junction, Idaho) _ President
Clinton, on a visit here, thanks the hard-working military troops
and civilians fighting fires across the West. By Marc Lacey.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-BOMB (Moscow) _ A bomb rips through a busy underground
walkway packed with hundreds of commuters and shoppers in central
Moscow, killing eight people, according to news reports. The
Interfax news agency said that in addition to those killed, 18
others were injured in the blast underneath Pushkin Square. By
Patrick Tyler.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA-U.S. (Washington) _ The Clinton administration, in a
reversal of policy on Sierra Leone, says it will dispatch American
special forces to train and equip seven African battalions, five of
them from Nigeria, at cost estimated between $50 million and $100
million. The idea is that the battalions will bolster the U.N.
presence and the government in Sierra Leone, and help crush the RUF
rebels. By Jane Perlez. (1200 words)
</P>
<P>
   DRUG-CERTIFICATION (Mexico City) _ U.S. drug czar Barry
McCaffrey, here on a two-day visit, announces his support for
ending the unilateral U.S. drug certification program, which has
been a main component of America's drug policy toward Latin America
and heated point of contention among presidents of the nations in
the region. By Ginger Thompson. (800 words)
</P>
<P>
   MALAYSIA-IBRAHIM (Kuala Lumpur) _ In a terse ruling that capped
a long, corrosive legal battle, a judge has found Malaysia's former
deputy prime minister, Anwar Ibrahim, guilty of sodomy and
sentenced him to nine years in prison. By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   SRILANKA-UNREST (Colombo, Sri Lanka) _ President Chandrika
Kumaratunga's long-awaited peace plan for this war torn nation _
embodied in a new constitution that would have given greater
autonomy to the Hindu Tamil minority in this majority Buddhist
Sinhalese nation _ has foundered. By Celia W. Dugger.
</P>
<P>
   KASHMIR-UNREST (New Delhi, India) _ Kashmir's peace process hung
in tatters Tuesday, after the Hizbul Mujahideen militant group
called off its cease-fire and directed field commanders to resume
fighting Indian forces. By Barry Bearak.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-GANGS (Tokyo) _ The economic crisis has now hit the
country's gangs. Six members have been arrested in a midday
shootout between gangs in Tokyo that left two dead. The were
fighting over a debt that was forcing one of gang to shut down. By
Calvin Sims.
</P>
<P>
   CHILE-PINOCHET (Santiago) _ The Chilean Supreme Court is to
officially release its decision on stripping Gen. Augusto Pinochet
of his senatorial immunity. The court may also order him to undergo
more physical (mental?) testing. By Clifford Krauss.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   VERIZON-STRIKE (Undated) _ Developments in strike against
Verizon Communications. By Simon Romero.
</P>
<P>
   And
</P>
<P>
   VERIZON-NORTHPOINT (Undated) _ Verizon Communications acquires a
55 percent stake in NorthPoint Communications Group for $800
million and will merge the digital subscriber line businesses of
the two companies. Verizon also reports a 5.1 percent rise in
second-quarter earnings but warns that earnings for the rest of the
year will be below analysts' forecasts. By Seth Schiesel.
</P>
<P>
   ACCOUNTING-CONSULTANTS (Undated) _ Looking at the growing
importance of consulting to the big accounting firms, and what
impact or lessons, if any, can be gleaned from the settlement,
announced Monday, between the feuding Andersens. By Reed Abelson.
</P>
<P>
   CISCO-EARNINGS (San Francisco) _ Cisco Systems reports
fourth-quarter earnings after the market closes. 15 cents a share
is the consensus forecast. By Lawrence M. Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily marketplace column. By
Jonathan Fuerbringer.
</P>
<P>
   FIRST-ENERGY-GPU (Undated) _ First Energy of Ohio agrees to
acquire GPU, a big New Jersey utility company, for $4.5 billion. By
Neela Banerjee.
</P>
<P>
   DIAL-RESIGN (Undated) _ Dial, maker of soap, air fresheners and
canned meat, says its chief executive, Malcolm Jozoff, has resigned
and will be replaced by Herbert Baum, president of Hasbro. Dial
warns that 2000 profit will miss estimates. By Greg Winter.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS-TRAVEL (Undated) _ The business travel column. By Joe
Sharkey.
</P>
<P>
   HYUNDAI-EARNINGS (Seoul, South Korea) _ Hyundai Motor says its
first-half profit tripled as it sold more luxury cars in South
Korea and expanded exports, especially to North America. The
earnings report comes as creditors demand that Hyundai Motor be
separated from the debt-burdened Hyundai Group. By Samuel Len.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MANAGEMENT PAGE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   LEROY-RESTAURANTS (New York) _ Warner LeRoy, owner of Tavern on
the Green and the Russian Tea Room.
</P>
<P>
   DIVORCE-STOCK-OPTIONS (Undated) _ Divorce courts are now
catching up to the explosion in stock options as compensation. In
the last few ears, judges in several states have taken a closer
look at the wealth locked up in unexercised options _ and made
decisions that are aimed at awarding at least some of it to the
former wives of the corporate managers who hold them. By Amy
Zipkin.
</P>
