<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 14:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5805 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-PRISON-SUIT-HNS &LR;      08-08 0623
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRISON-SUIT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     LAWYERS DISMISS PRISON BRUTALITY CLAIMS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By BOB EGELKO  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Lawyers for guards at the troubled Pelican Bay
State Prison are disputing another brutality suit, telling a
federal court jury that a prisoner who claimed excessive force had
actually been the aggressor and had been treated properly.
</P>
<P>
   Inmate Thomas Brissette ``chose to fight, to resist every step
of the way,'' and was not attacked or set up by guards as he
claimed, Deputy Attorney General Susan Myster said in opening
statements Monday to a U.S. District Court jury.
</P>
<P>
   But Brissette's attorney, Michael Gevertz, said guards had
deliberately placed Brissette in a cell with a known gang member,
over his objections, then broken up their fight by beating him,
shooting him with rubber bullets and a stun gun, dropping him
face-first onto a litter and banging his head against the walls.
</P>
<P>
   ``A human does not cease to be a human being because he is a
prisoner,'' Gevertz told the eight-member jury.
</P>
<P>
   Jurors were not told that Brissette was serving a life sentence
for murder.
</P>
<P>
   The trial is the latest court case involving allegations of
brutality and civil rights violations at the maximum-security
prison near Crescent City in far Northern California.
</P>
<P>
   One guard, David G. Lewis, was sentenced to more than seven
years in prison in May for shooting an inmate without provocation
in 1994. Two other guards have been indicted on federal charges of
conspiring to arrange attacks on prisoners from 1992 to 1995.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Thelton Henderson ruled in 1995 that the
rights of Pelican Bay prisoners had been violated by systematic use
of excessive force as well as substandard medical care.
</P>
<P>
   Brissette's lawsuit dates from July 1991, when he was being held
in Pelican Bay's Security Housing Unit, where prisoners spend
nearly the entire day in their cells. He spent the first three
months in a cell by himself, but officers said they had run out of
room and ordered him to share a cell with a prisoner named Harvey
Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Gevertz, Brissette's attorney, said prison documents showed that
Hill was known to be a gang member, had been violent in prison and
was considered a threat to other inmates. He said Brissette had
pleaded not to be put in Hill's cell, but guards ``responded with
threats of violence and racial slurs.''
</P>
<P>
   But lawyers for the seven guards sued by Brissette said he had
simply refused to move and had not said why. Myster, who represents
six of the guards, also said they had no conclusive evidence at the
time that Hill was a gang member _ but even if he was, it wasn't
considered dangerous to house him with a fellow black inmate like
Brissette who wasn't in a gang.
</P>
<P>
   Gevertz said guards had broken up an immediate fight between the
two men by shooting Brissette repeatedly with a 38mm gas gun, which
fires rubber pellets; shocking him with a taser gun; clubbing him
with a baton; then hogtying him and dropping him 3 feet onto a
litter that lay on the concrete floor. While wheeling Brissette to
an infirmary, a guard slammed his face into adjoining walls and
crowed that he ``got him good,'' Gevertz said.
</P>
<P>
   Myster's account differed sharply. She said the 6-foot-5,
240-pound Brissette had attacked the 5-foot-8, 170-pound Hill as
soon as Brissette's hands were uncuffed, requiring guards to use
force to rescue Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Brissette was not beaten up or hogtied, was lowered rather than
dropped onto the litter, and suffered only minor injuries, Myster
said. She also said guards might have used profanity, since ``this
is not kindergarten,'' but had never used racial slurs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
