<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 15:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5837 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-MIDEAST-DISEASEQ$ADV1     08-08 0727
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-DISEASEQ$ADV12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ISRAELI MEDICAL CENTER FIGHTS DISEASE, POLITICS
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (l) Lifestyle categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sat., Aug. 12 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Their common enemies are microscopic. Their team
consists of both Arabs and Israelis.
</P>
<P>
   Medicine has long been one field that crossed lines between
Israelis and Palestinians. Building on that tradition, the Kuvin
Centre(CQ) for the Study of Infectious and Tropical Diseases, based
at Israel's Hebrew University in Jerusalem, has projects ranging
from Israel to Tunisia.
</P>
<P>
   ``The world doesn't know these things go on,'' said Dr. Sanford
Kuvin, a Palm Beach, Fla. infectious disease specialist who founded
the center in 1976. His explanation for the teamwork is simple:
``Mosquitoes don't recognize borders.''
</P>
<P>
   Kuvin, 70, knows mosquitoes. In 1962, he helped develop an
antibody test for malaria, a major breakthrough in detecting the
mosquito-borne disease.
</P>
<P>
   He has testified before the U.S. Congress about AIDS and
Hepatitis B policy. And he was the medical advisor to Kimberly
Bergalis, a Florida woman who died after becoming the first
confirmed case of a patient contracting AIDS from her dentist.
</P>
<P>
   In 1964, Kuvin came to Israel to meet with colleagues and saw
the potential for research in a country with high medical standards
in a region with many tropical diseases.
</P>
<P>
   He set up the center in 1976. It became a lead agency in the
fight against the Rift Valley Fever, which killed thousands of
Egyptians and threatened to eliminate Egypt's cattle stock in the
late 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   The collaboration between Israeli and Egyptian health workers
coincided with the peace process between their two countries.
Together, they vaccinated every head of cattle in Egypt and Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, with money from the U.S. Agency for
International Development, the European Union and the German
Science Foundation, the Kuvin Centre has worked in several
countries _ including Greece, Mali, Jordan and Brazil. It also
works on projects with countries where Israel does not have full
relations _ such as Morocco and Tunisia.
</P>
<P>
   In Jerusalem, the focus is on leishmaniasis(CQ), a disease that
can cause disfiguring boils and, in a less common form, death. The
disease afflicts 400,000 people a year, mainly in the Mediterranean
region, Latin America and India.
</P>
<P>
   It is carried by parasites in sand flies. The flies bite
animals, including dogs, which are then infected and carry the
disease. Other flies spread it from the infected animals to humans.
There are cures, but they involve highly toxic drugs that can
damage organs.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers collect sand fly larvae from the West Bank and
Israel, study the flies' behavior and genetic make-up. The goal is
to control the spread of the disease and find better cures.
</P>
<P>
   The project is based at the Kuvin Centre, but includes the
Palestinian Al-Quds University.
</P>
<P>
   Together, they are applying for grant money to expand the
project, including a Palestinian clinic for treating and
researching the disease.
</P>
<P>
   Ziad Abdeen, dean of research at Al-Quds and the Palestinian
coordinator on the project, said such cooperative projects used to
be frowned upon by other Palestinians. Now, with the school
involved in more than 52 joint projects, Palestinians recognize
that such efforts are ``good for Palestinians and good for the
peace process.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not all science,'' he said of his relations with his
Israeli peers. ``They get to know our attitudes, our culture.
Through collaboration you get to understanding, and trust.''
</P>
<P>
   The skills Palestinians learn researching leishmaniasis can be
used on other diseases, improving the young crop of Palestinian
healthworkers in their new health system.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not feel inferior. I have studied at some of the best
schools in the world. But, my system is inferior. We do not have
the facilities,'' Abdeen said.
</P>
<P>
   (Larry Kaplow's E-mail address is: larryk(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   For more information on infectious disease research at Hebrew
University see:
</P>
<P>
   www.md.huji.ac.il/depts/parasitology/p-3-11.html
</P>
<P>
   For Al-Quds University see:
</P>
<P>
   www.alquds.edu
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-08-00 1504EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000808.0133 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 15:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5838 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN09-CO     08-08 0785
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN09-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   DISPATCHES FROM DREAMSVILLE: Home, heart and hearth in a
one-room house
</P>
<P>
   (''Dispatches from Dreamsville'' is an occasional series in
which readers share with Cox Newspapers senior writer Joe Murray
their memories of growing up in small-town America. Back then, or
at least the way we remember it, life was like a dream.)
</P>
<P>
   By Orland L. Johnson
</P>
<P>
   Special to Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   I do not remember Nov. 19, 1925. My birth certificate tells me
that I was issued to Imogene Clark Johnson and Roy Leonard Johnson
in the town of Hemphill, Texas, County of Sabine.
</P>
<P>
   My earliest recollection of life was trying to cut on a young
pear tree in the backyard of my grandfather Clark's house. The
knife turned backwards and split the middle finger of my left hand
up and through the fingernail. The scar is still with me.
</P>
<P>
   I remember my dad coming home from a hospital in a far off place
called Houston after he had been in an accident that broke his
back.
</P>
<P>
   Dad worked in the East Texas lumber industry. His job was to
load cut logs onto wagons with chains and mules. A chain broke and
whipped him in the back, breaking it in two places.
</P>
<P>
   His condition was sometimes good and sometimes bad. When it was
good he was like a normal person, but when the nerve pinched his
spinal cord he would fall down and every fiber in his body would
contort.
</P>
<P>
   The pain must have been more than he could bear, and I think the
doctors of today could have helped him. This condition existed
until his death at age 33. I was 13.
</P>
<P>
   When he came back from the hospital that first time, I was
probably about 3. It must have been just before Christmas because
Santa Claus brought me a little jar of mints and a wind-up toy that
did all sorts of jumps and flips.
</P>
<P>
   My mother was a school teacher. She'd walk to the two-room
school about a mile away, along a sandy wagon road through the deep
East Texas pineywoods.
</P>
<P>
   Once she took me with her, and I sat on the front steps until
dinnertime.
</P>
<P>
   We had been living with my grandmother Johnson at this time. My
dad had two younger brothers, the youngest only 7 years older than
I was. My grandfather Johnson had died soon after the youngest was
born.
</P>
<P>
   After that, we lived in a large house with several families.
Each family had a bedroom, but there was only one kitchen. Everyone
had kitchen privileges and there was a small individual table in
one large room.
</P>
<P>
   At breakfast time, I remember walking around the room to see who
I wanted to eat with.
</P>
<P>
   Later we built our own house on grandmother Johnson's 88 acres,
just down the hill from her house.
</P>
<P>
   Ours was a one-room house with a tarpaper roof, and we lived
there for the next couple of years.
</P>
<P>
   It had a front door and a back door and a little woodburning
stove. To the far side of the room was an open place in the floor
and wall. This is where we would build our mud fireplace and
chimney.
</P>
<P>
   A pine pole scaffold was erected next to the open hole in the
floor, and a mixture of mud and moss ``cats'' about the size of a
small loaf of bread were packed around the pole skeleton to form
the chimney.
</P>
<P>
   On the inside of the house a mud hearth replaced the hole in the
floor. I had my fourth birthday in this house.
</P>
<P>
   The winter of '29 was a bad one. Snow was up to the porch, maybe
15 inches high. Dad had to break the ice on the chicken troughs so
that they could get water.
</P>
<P>
   I have heard the expression ``ugly as a mud chimney.'' I have
often thought, ``Thank goodness for our ugly mud chimney.''
</P>
<P>
   It was here _ five miles south of Center, Texas, in this
one-room house with a tarpaper roof and a mud chimney, down the
hill from grandmother Johnson's log house, near a place called
Short -- that a beautiful baby girl came into this world on Oct. 6,
1929. My sister was given the name Wanda Jean. It rained all night.
</P>
<P>
   In 1946, on returning from the Navy after the big war was over,
I drove to the Short community and searched the pine and gum
thicket where the little house once stood.
</P>
<P>
   All I found was a three-foot high mound of clay that had been
our ugly mud chimney. As I stood there in the underbrush, tears
came into my eyes as I remembered the warmth and love that had
existed there for a little family of four, so very long ago.
</P>
<P>
   (Orland L. Johnson, 74, is a retired electronics technician,
holds a private pilot's license and a amateur radio license, and
his hobbies that include rock hunting, gardening, wood craft and
jewelry craft. He lives in Mr Dreamsville stories, visit
http://www.coxnews.com/newsservice.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-08-00 1506EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
