<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000808.0139 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 15:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5876 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r p BC-BUSH-SHANTYTOWNS-HNS &LR;      08-08 1268
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-SHANTYTOWNS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     TEXAS SHANTYTOWNS A FESTERING ISSUE WELL BEFORE BUSH 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (Eds: Note optional trim)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By RUSSELL GOLD and PEGGY FIKAC  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Sitting on a library shelf here is a 1977 report
by University of Texas researchers on ``colonias,'' the Spanish
name for the rural subdivisions near the Rio Grande where thousands
of people live in homes without drinking water or flush toilets.
</P>
<P>
   The picture the researchers painted is dramatic: isolated areas
marked by poverty, substandard housing and high rates of infectious
diseases.
</P>
<P>
   The colonias remain today. And the state government's failure to
eradicate them has become fodder for political battles, including
the current presidential race between Texas Gov. George W. Bush,
the Republican nominee, and Vice President Al Gore, the Democratic
hopeful.
</P>
<P>
   ``The same things we found 25 years ago are still prevalent
today,'' said Jorge Garces, one of the researchers in 1977 who now
serves as the Texas secretary of state's border affairs manager.
``The same problems.''
</P>
<P>
   The endurance of the colonias, now home to an estimated 350,000
people, has plagued more than a generation of state politicians.
</P>
<P>
   Colonias began to proliferate in the 1950s on ``agriculturally
valueless'' property, such as land in floodplains, according to a
report by the Federal Reserve Bank of Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Developers sold small lots on land with little or no
infrastructure. The low-income buyers did not receive title to the
property until they made the final payment. They generally built
their own homes, many of which lacked electricity, plumbing and
other basics.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic National Committee recently produced a videotape
of the squalid conditions in colonias. The video challenges Bush's
claim to being a ``compassionate conservative.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's record is more complex.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of colonia residents have received water and sewer
connections during his five years in office, but most of the work
and funding was in place before he became governor. Bush has signed
legislation meant to prevent the proliferation of colonias, but has
not reached too deeply into the state treasury to finance the
effort.
</P>
<P>
   He told his secretary of state to put a hard emphasis on the
issue, but waited four years into his term to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Bush defends his record, pointing to projects under his watch to
hook up colonia residents to water and sewer lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ours is the first administration to aggressively pursue
hookups for the colonias,'' he said last month. ``We'll have
thousands of people (connected) who heretofore had no water or
sewer at their homes by the time my administration is over.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush and Secretary of State Elton Bomer threaded together $25
million in grants from the federal government and the North
American Development Bank to help low-income colonia residents pay
the $1,200 average cost for water and sewer connections.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1999, the program has brought potable water to 4,161 homes
and sewerage service to 7,948 homes, according to state
information.
</P>
<P>
   But it was Bush's predecessors who secured $600 million in bonds
to install water mains and sewer lines, and to build
water-treatment facilities. But the program stalled because
residents could not afford to pay for the final few feet of
3/4-inch pipe that would connect their homes to the water-delivery
system.
</P>
<P>
   Crisscrossing the country as a candidate for president, Bush has
made campaign stops in poor neighborhoods. But he never has toured
a colonia in his five years as governor, aides say.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's very unimportant,'' Bomer said. ``Governor Bush
is the only governor so far who has done anything for colonias in a
substantial way _ not just lip service.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, state lawmakers created the Texas Bootstrap Loan
Program to assist low-income Texans who either are building new
homes or fixing existing ones. The state housing department
received $5.6 million over two years to fund the program. Bush has
promoted the plan as an important accomplishment.
</P>
<P>
   But critics say he could have done more.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers originally proposed a $20 million program, which would
have passed if Bush aides had indicated the governor approved of
it, said John Henneberger, co-director of the nonprofit Texas Low
Income Housing Information Service.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a poor reflection on the state's commitment to do
anything with the colonias,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Allies of Bush dispute this and said the governor supported the
Bootstrap program.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just one more case of trying to blame the governor,''
said Jane Dees, spokeswoman for Bomer.
</P>
<P>
   Since Bush signed the pared-down bill into law in June 1999, the
program has sputtered. The first of five contracts with local
nonprofit agencies that will administer the loans was signed last
month.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, we would love to have this done a lot faster,''
said Homero Cabello Jr., director of the state Office of Colonias
Initiatives. ``Because it was new, we did spend a little more time
than anticipated to get the contracts out.''
</P>
<P>
   While the agency has been accused of moving slowly on the loan
program, the Office of Colonias Initiatives received the federal
Hammer Award a year ago in recognition of ``government that works
better and costs less.'' A framed certificate sits in the reception
area outside Cabello's Austin office.
</P>
<P>
   It is signed by Gore.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bush's presidential race isn't the first time colonias have been
in the political spotlight. Bush used the plight of colonia
residents as an issue in his successful bid to unseat Democratic
Gov. Ann Richards in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly six years later, opponents are firing back at the
Republican governor.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't talk about compassion and turn your back on the
colonias,'' said Jenny Backus of the Democratic National Committee,
whose videotape shows shacks made of plywood and tin and lays out
the lack of electricity, running water and sewage systems in a
colonia in the Rio Grande Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Bomer said Bush has done anything but turn his back on colonias.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is this the border, or Appalachia, Tennessee?'' he said in
reference to a poverty-stricken area of Gore's home state.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one is blaming him (Gore) for the poverty in Appalachia.
... You won't see us blaming him for that. It's ridiculous, just
like it's ridiculous to blame Bush for poverty along the border
we've had for the last 50 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Some lawmakers point out that Texas had a record budget surplus
in 1999, but very little of it went to colonias. Additionally, a
proposal to commit significant funds to the colonias _ a
constitutional amendment to sell $100 million in bonds to finance
affordable housing _ died in the Texas House.
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Eddie Lucio Jr., a Democrat from Brownsville, credits
Bush for supporting his bill to close loopholes that allowed
colonias to proliferate.
</P>
<P>
   But referring to the $1.7 billion tax cut that bush pushed
through the Legislature, Lucio said: ``Should we have used those
resources to build schools or help colonias? I would rather do that
than get a $60 or $80 tax credit as a citizen.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush supporters say his achievements are in plain sight. ``If
someone is asserting the problem is solved, I would sure disagree
with that,'' said state Sen. David Sibley, a Republican from Waco.
``But if someone wants to assert that the governor has done
nothing, I would sure disagree with that also.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
