A5881 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-GRILLRECIPES0809-COX     08-08 0565
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRILLRECIPES0809-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Barbecue guru mixes up marinades, sauces
 &HT;    By Ann Heller
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio - When Steven Raichlen came to my house to cook, he
whipped up a lovely lunch. Two kinds of grilled chicken, one with a
spicy rub that he basted with his impromptu mop sauce and a
barbecue sauce he fixed in a jiffy. But the best part of lunch was
the marinated chicken breast.
</P>
<P>
   For that he made a freehand version of a marinade that's a star
in his ``Barbecue! Bible: Sauces, Rubs and Marinades, Bastes,
Butters &AMP; Glazes'' (Workman, $12.95).
</P>
<P>
   He used a different mixture of herbs he snipped from my garden
and more garlic than called for in the recipe. He substituted limes
that I had on hand for the lemons that I didn't. He also spooned in
some hot Thai chile garlic paste he found in my refrigerator. This
only goes to show that you can tinker with the recipe.
</P>
<P>
   I've used the marinade several times since _ it's as successful
on chicken seared on the kitchen stove as it is on the grill.
</P>
<P>
   As Raichlen says, the virtue of this marinade is its freshness;
use it within one or two hours of making it. Stir again before
using.
</P>
<P>
   THE ONLY MARINADE YOU'LL EVER NEED
</P>
<P>
   Makes 1 cup
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup fresh lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon hot pepper flakes
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon cracked black
</P>
<P>
   pepper
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon coarse salt (kosher or sea salt)
</P>
<P>
   4 strips lemon zest
</P>
<P>
   3 cloves garlic, crushed
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup coarsely chopped fresh parsley
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup coarsely chopped fresh basil, cilantro, dill or oregano,
or a mix
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup extra-virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Combine the lemon juice, hot pepper flakes, cracked pepper and
salt in a glass, ceramic or stainless steel bowl. Whisk until the
salt crystals are dissolved. Add the lemon zest, garlic, parsley
and basil. Stir or whisk in the olive oil.
</P>
<P>
   Our mix included tarragon, lemon thyme, lemon basil and sage.
</P>
<P>
   Although a lemon marinade is best freshly made, rubs can be made
ahead and in quantity to have on hand. Raichlen's rubs range from a
sweet and smoky Kansas City rub to a steak rub without a lick of
sugar.
</P>
<P>
   Figure on using 2 to 4 teaspoons rub per pound of meat. Let the
spices work their cure in boneless chicken breasts and fish fillets
for 30 to 90 minutes, steaks and chops for one to three hours and
on ribs or whole chickens four hours to overnight.
</P>
<P>
   This steak rub is also good on roasts, brisket, pork, chicken
and even seafood, Raichlen says.
</P>
<P>
   LONE STAR STEAK RUB
</P>
<P>
   Makes 1 3/4 cups
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup coarse salt
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup cracked or coarsely ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup paprika
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons pure chile
</P>
<P>
   powder
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons cayenne pepper
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons garlic powder
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon ground cumin
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon dried oregano
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon dried thyme
</P>
<P>
   Combine ingredients and store in a covered jar, away from light
and heat. It will keep for several months.
</P>
<P>
   Pure chile powder is not the same thing as supermarket chili
powder, which includes cumin and other ingredients. Look for pure
chile powder at specialty stores.
</P>
<P>
   Mop sauces, so named because the pit jockeys actually use a
clean cotton floor mop to apply the sauce to large quantities of
ribs and pork shoulders, may be the holy water of the barbecue
religion. At home, barbecue cooks can use a spray bottle.
</P>
<P>
   This Cider Squirt was inspired
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
