<HEADER>
A5882 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-GRILLS-TIPS0809     08-08 0225
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRILLS-TIPS0809 </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Grill tips
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who is going to grill can benefit from these tips from
Steven Raichlen:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Invest in an inexpensive chimney starter for your charcoal
grill. That lighter fluid, used by almost 50 percent of grillers,
smells up the neighborhood as well as your food. Who wants to eat
anything that tastes like petroleum?
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Build a three-step fire, dividing the grill in thirds. Have a
deep bed of hot coals, at least two coals deep, and another shallow
bed of coals. Leave a third of the space open. This allows you to
sear meat over hot coals, then cook over medium heat or indirect
heat.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Wait until the coals are hot to add the grate. Let it heat.
That's the time to take a stiff wire brush to grate. Then fold
paper towel into a pad, hold it in tongs and dip it in oil; use the
pad to oil the grate. That not only lubricates the grate but takes
off the last smudges of residue from the last cookout. You'll be
surprised at what comes off on the towel.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Try a triple-flavoring approach to grilling meats and poultry.
First, use a rub. Put it on, rub it in and let it rest for a couple
hours. While cooking, baste with a mop sauce. In the last five
minutes, brush on a barbecue sauce.
</P>
<P>
   _ Ann Heller
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
