<SLUG> BC-GRILLSWOMEN0809-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Grill talk
 &HT;    Love the flavor, but leave the barbecuing for the boys
 &HT;    
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   To: Steven Raichlen, author of ``Barbecue! Bible: Sauces, Ribs
and Marinades `` (Workman, $12.95).
</P>
<P>
   From: Ann Heller, Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   Dear Steven:
</P>
<P>
   Just a note to let you know that your chicken breasts were very
good _ well, as good as chicken breasts can be.
</P>
<P>
   And I appreciated your one-on-one backyard lesson in the art of
grilling. Although I'm a cook _ and a pretty good one, I think _ I
don't grill. Most women don't. Generally we pass the marinated meat
to the male sitting on the other side of the kitchen counter and
let him light the fire and man the grill (no pun intended).
</P>
<P>
   I don't want to get into gender stereotyping here. Actually I
think the roles are a matter of function, not sexual identity.
</P>
<P>
   I know there are exceptions to the rule, but most home cooks are
women. And we don't have time to stand at the grill watching meat
sizzle.
</P>
<P>
   It's the cook in the house who does it all, from setting the
table and slicing the bread to cooking the potatoes and beans and
maybe making dessert and coffee and possibly pouring the wine. Not
to diminish your skills, but the grill cook generally does just one
thing. (You did impress me with the side dishes, the grilled corn
and roasted red pepper and bruschetta, but let's be honest _ you're
a professional at the grill.)
</P>
<P>
   In fact, you were an inspiration, so I gave it a try. First baby
back ribs, nicely seasoned with the extra rub you left in the
kitchen. I guess my fire was too hot, for they cooked much too
quickly. Your leftover Coca-Cola barbecue sauce helped mask the
result.
</P>
<P>
   The next night I tried chicken, just the way you fixed it, with
The Only Marinade You'll Ever Need. I'd forgotten I was supposed to
be going out for dinner, and when my friend arrived I told her I
was grilling and we'd have dinner at my house. She stopped dead in
her tracks. She also comes from the I-Don't-Grill-School. She
decided to make a couple business calls nearby and left me to
struggle on alone.
</P>
<P>
   I spread the coals, creating the three-tiered fire you suggest.
The fire was a bit too hot so I slipped back into the kitchen to
fix the basil pesto for the zucchini I was going to grill
alongside.
</P>
<P>
   I gathered the basil and got out the blender, and I admit, I did
get distracted and decided to set the table and peel the salad
tomatoes. By then the fire had burned down. I added more charcoal
and soon had another roaring fire. The dinner hour was roaring on,
too, so I hurried to grill the zucchini. They skittered across
theand get a crust you'd envy. Ditto the salmon, and sometimes I
give it the benefit of one of those rubs like you love. I can do it
while cooking three other things, and do it in air-conditioned
comfort while my downdraft exhaust takes care of the smoke.
</P>
<P>
   But I'll let anyone so inclined do their cooking on my grill.
</P>
<P>
   And that includes you the next time you're in town.
</P>
<P>
   Sincerely,
</P>
<P>
   Ann
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
