<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Kermit Lynch's life work makes him an importer extraordinaire
 &HT;    By Mark Fisher
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio - Wine drinkers (wine writers, too) in these parts
tend to focus only about those who produce wines and rarely about
those who import them. Their names are usually tucked away on the
back of the bottles, in fine print, ignored by the vast majority
who choose a wine by the ``name'' on the front of the label.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe we should start turning those bottles around.
</P>
<P>
   One importer who has carved a name for himself above the others
is Kermit Lynch, a wine fanatic who spends half the year in France
and half in Berkeley, Calif., where he runs a retail shop. When not
running the shop, Lynch is tending to his import business, focusing
on French wines of character and breeding, many from relatively
obscure regions of France, and virtually all distinctive and
delicious.
</P>
<P>
   Lynch is an immensely talented wine writer: If his book,
``Adventures on the Wine Route'' (Noonday, $15), doesn't make you
want to drop everything and spend a year in France soaking up wine
and rustic food, then your heart is not beating. But his single
greatest accomplishment in the wine business _ at least from the
consumer standpoint _ lies in transportation. Lynch was a pioneer
in insisting that his wines be shipped from Europe in refrigerated
containers so they wouldn't get cooked and ruined while baking in
the hulls of ships as the vessels snaked through the Panama Canal.
</P>
<P>
   If you've ever tasted an Alsatian white from Zind-Humbrecht, or
a Chateauneuf du Pape from Vieux Telegraphe or a Bandol rose or red
from Domaine Tempier, you have benefited from Lynch's life work.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Lynch's regional sales director, W. Matthew Cain,
stopped in Dayton on a typically whirlwind tour, and the wines he
brought to sample illustrated why Lynch's name on the back of the
bottle is among the closest things to a quality guarantee as you'll
get in selecting French wines. Wines such as the 1998 Chateau
Graville Lacoste (a $14.69 dry white Bordeaux made from semillon
and sauvignon blanc), a super-rich 1996 Clos La Coutale Cahors
($11.99 dry red made of malbec, merlot and tannat), a Burgundylike
1998 Domaine Diochon Moulin-a-Vent from Beaujolais ($19.69) and the
finest dry (and I do mean dry) rose in the world, the 1999 Domaine
Tempier ($24.69), all represent the finest expressions of the wines
from their regions.
</P>
<P>
   There are other fine French-wine importers whose names on the
bottle usually translate into high quality _ Alain Junguenet,
Robert Kacher, Weygandt-Metzler. But Lynch seems to add an extra
dose of passion.
</P>
<P>
   Makes the back of the bottle worth reading.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Wine of the week: 1998 Vega Sindoa Merlot ($9.99). Mmmm, a
ripe, rich, robust dry red from Spain that emphasizes the cherryike
fruit of merlot but has just enough tannin and other components to
keep it in balance. This simply blows away its precious few
American competitors in its price range. For merlot fanciers,
there's a lot to like here.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Contact Mark Fisher at 225-2258 or by e-mail at
markfisher(at)coxohio.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
