<SLUG> BC-MASTER-CHEF-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHAMPAGNE MELON SOUP WITH RASPBERRY ICE BALLS 
</HEADLINE>
  This is the last of eight columns by Michel Richard, the chef and
owner of Citronelle in Washington. They have been written with
Marian Burros. Next week: Eberhard Muller, the chef and an owner at
Lutece. 
 By MARIAN BURROS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Melon with port is a traditional combination in France, the wine
served in half a Cavaillon or other melon, but I always thought it
could be improved. The color is not appealing to me, because the
beautiful pastel shades of the melons are lost in the deep
red-purple of the wine. Port is also too strong, overwhelming the
taste of the fruit. To me, this wine goes better with chocolate.
</P>
<P>
   But I wanted to serve melon in the summer, so I thought of
matching it with Champagne. I was raised in the Champagne region
and love the wine's beautiful delicate color, bubbles and
celebratory feel.
</P>
<P>
   First, I made a simple melon soup by pureeing the flesh of
cantaloupe and honeydew, and adding lemon for a touch of acidity
and a little sugar to heighten the sweetness. I serve this in a
scooped-out cantaloupe half with melon balls and raspberry ice
cubes, which keep the melon cool without diluting the soup. The ice
cubes are actually ball-shaped, which makes them look like
watermelon. The cubes add color and another flavor dimension to the
soup, which is quite intense: they make it taste like a kir royale.
</P>
<P>
   The way we serve the soup is striking: after people are sitting
at the table and have the melon in front of them, we pour in the
Champagne. The aroma comes to your mouth and the bubbles make it
alive. The first taste is of Champagne; the second of almost
cassis, like a kir.
</P>
<P>
   The raspberry balls are made by freezing strained fresh
raspberry juice in decorative trays. I garnish them with julienne
mint sprinkled with sugar, which makes the leaves look iced.
</P>
<P>
   I keep raspberry cubes in the freezer for more than just this
soup. You can also drop them into a glass of Champagne or a
martini.
</P>
<P>
   CHAMPAGNE MELON SOUP WITH RASPBERRY ICE BALLS
</P>
<P>
   Time: 1 hour 15 minutes, plus freezing time
</P>
<P>
   2 cups raspberries
</P>
<P>
   Sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 ripe honeydew melon
</P>
<P>
   2 ripe cantaloupes
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons fresh lemon juice, or to taste
</P>
<P>
   12 large mint leaves
</P>
<P>
   1{ cups Champagne.
</P>
<P>
   1. In a blender, combine raspberries with 4 tablespoons water.
Puree until smooth. Line a strainer with cheesecloth, and set over
a bowl. Pour in puree, and twist cloth to squeeze out puree. Stir
in 4 teaspoons of sugar, or to taste. Spoon mixture into an ice
cube tray that makes round balls or another decorative shape.
Freeze until firm.
</P>
<P>
   2. Cut honeydew melon in half, and remove seeds. Using a melon
baller, remove flesh from melon to within } inch of peel. Set aside
melon balls. Using a large spoon, scrape out and reserve remaining
flesh. Discard peels.
</P>
<P>
   3. Cut cantaloupe in half, using a straight cut or saw-toothed
design. Remove seeds. Using a melon baller, remove flesh to within
\ inch of peel; reserve any extra flesh. Cut off bottoms of
cantaloupes so they stand securely. In a large bowl, mix honeydew
and cantaloupe melon balls with lemon juice. Place an equal amount
of melon balls in each melon half, and refrigerate.
</P>
<P>
   4. In a blender, puree any honeydew or cantaloupe flesh that has
not been shaped into balls. Press through a fine strainer, and add
2 teaspoons of sugar. Refrigerate if desired.
</P>
<P>
   5. To serve, spoon 2 tablespoons of melon puree over melon balls
in each cantaloupe half. Allow to sit at room temperature for 30
minutes. Meanwhile, cut mint leaves into very thin strips, and dust
lightly with sugar. Arrange 4 raspberry balls in each melon half,
and sprinkle with mint. Set each melon half in a soup bowl. At the
table pour Champagne directly into cantaloupe halves, and allow to
fizz out and over cantaloupes.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-08-00 1551EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000808.0145 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 15:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5886 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-WINE-TALK-NYT &LR;      08-08 0919
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OREGON STEPS OUT OF CALIFORNIA'S SHADOW 
</HEADLINE>
   By FRANK J. PRIAL    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MCMINNVILLE, Ore. _ Every few years, I like to come here to the
Willamette Valley to check up on the Oregon wine business.
</P>
<P>
   I could do it in New York, I guess; tasting a lot of wines and
talking to the winemakers by phone. But it's not the same as being
here and, to be honest, it's certainly not as much fun. By staying
home, I'd miss the International Pinot Noir Celebration, a
free-spirited yearly gathering in this town in the heart of the
Oregon wine country.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the owners and winemakers of 34 Oregon wineries
turned up at the end of July for the three-day gathering on the
campus of Linfield College. Joining them were winemakers from
California, Burgundy, Alsace, Australia, New Zealand and British
Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   Pinot noir, which is the red wine grape of Burgundy, is slowly
taking an honored place in the rest of the world. Over the last
three decades, it has become the principal red wine grape in
Oregon, too.
</P>
<P>
   When I first visited the Willamette Valley in the 1970s, there
was little more than a handful of wineries, most of them
underfinanced and overshadowed by their already glamorous
California colleagues. There were a few hundred acres of pinot noir
grapes. It is a frustratingly difficult grape to grow, and there
were plenty of experts around ready to write off the grape, and by
inference the Oregon wine industry as well.
</P>
<P>
   Today in Oregon, there are 150 wineries, ranging from modest,
artisanal producers Like Eyrie Vineyards, where it all started, to
big California-style wineries, like King Estate in Eugene, rivaling
in size and output almost anything in the Napa Valley. What's more,
business is thriving. For every new winery under construction,
dozens of investors are putting money into new vineyards. There are
10,000 acres of wine grapes in the state with thousands more
scheduled for planting, growers here say.
</P>
<P>
   Land prices have shot up, from around $4,000 an acre 10 years
ago to at least $20,000 an acre now. But that's still less than
half of what they would cost in the prime grape-growing areas of
California.
</P>
<P>
   What makes success particularly sweet for the Oregonians is the
fact that, rather quietly, the Californians are coming up to join
them. Recent arrivals include the dynamic Benziger family, who have
60 acres of Oregon land in pinot noir and expect to release their
first Oregon wines in a year or two. Tony Soter, one of the Napa
Valley's legendary winemakers at Spotteswood and more recently at
Etude, also has a vineyard here, producing 9,000 cases of Oregon
pinot noir a year. Benton Lane, founded by the veteran Napa Valley
winemaker Carl Doumani, is another acclaimed Oregon winery with a
California antecedent.
</P>
<P>
   Oregon winemakers _ the pioneers, anyway _ never let anyone
forget that when the famous Burgundy producer Joseph Drouhin
decided to invest in America, it was the red hills of Oregon rather
than the valleys of California that became home for Domaine Drouhin
Oregon. Many local winemakers believe it was the arrival of Drouhin
in 1988 that gave the budding Oregon industry the self-assurance
and the credibility it needed. The French winemaker is such a
fixture in the region that it has been afforded the nickname DDO,
much as the famed Domaine de la Romanee-Conti in Burgundy is called
the DRC.
</P>
<P>
   Like the region itself, the Oregon celebration is a militantly
informal gathering. Notebooks, furrowed brows and studious
expressions are discouraged. Which does not preclude the overall
impression that Oregon pinot noirs have come of age. Caught in such
a profusion of delicious wines, it would have been sheer
recklessness to announce that this one was obviously from Oregon,
that one from the Cote de Beaune, that one from Carneros or the
Anderson Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Is there an Oregon style? Yes, Oregon pinots are leaner and less
full-bodied that the California versions. And perhaps less
delicate, less velvety than many Burgundies. But no sooner does one
deliver that sort of pronouncement here then someone appears with a
bottle saying ``Try this,'' and another hypothesis bites the dust.
</P>
<P>
   If any trait has developed over the years I've been coming here,
it is consistency. It appeared in the vertical tastings of Ponzi
Vineyards and Domaine Drouhin going back to 1980 in the case of
Ponzi and 1988 with Drouhin. I remember it, too, from a vertical
tasting several years ago of David Lett's Eyrie Vineyards going
back even further. His first wines were made in the late 1960's.
</P>
<P>
   While Oregon is known particularly for its pinot noirs, the
state's winegrowers are also constantly experimenting with other
varieties. There is quite a bit of chardonnay around, but Oregon
pinot gris is a wine to single out. It's got the weight of
chardonnay but (usually) without the oak and cloying sweetness.
Some of its boosters claim that it was invented to go with another
local commodity: salmon.
</P>
<P>
   It's worth noting that not only the Oregonians are making fine
pinot noir these days. Thanks to the the gathering here, I
discovered a remarkable New Zealand pinot, a 1999 from the Felton
Road winery in Central Otago. Another came from, of all places, the
Okanagan Valley in British Columbia. It was a 1997 from Blue
Mountain Vineyard and Cellars. Then, too, there was the 1998
Nuits-St.-Georges Premier Cru, Clos de Forets-St.-Georges, from the
Domaine de l'Arlot, but that's another column. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-08-00 1553EDT &QL; 
