<HEADER>
A5890 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-SIMPLE-COOKING-NYT &LR;      08-08 0508
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIMPLE-COOKING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STANDING IN FOR BASIL 
</HEADLINE>
   By MARK BITTMAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like pesto, tapenade is an all-purpose sauce based on a single
pungent ingredient. The Provencal olive paste can be used as a dip
for raw vegetables, a spread for bread or a flavorful partner for
anything from grilled shrimp or fish to chicken. I especially like
to add it for heft and taste to an easy salad of tomato, basil and
mozzarella. And then the salad itself can be taken to another level
by spooning it onto grilled bread to make a quick bruschetta or
even onto pasta as an uncooked sauce.
</P>
<P>
   Tapenade is a welcome change from pesto at this time of year,
but it also has the distinct advantage of being easy to make year
round. Unlike fresh basil, olives are always in season. The base is
almost always black olives in brine, which are better for this
sauce than oil-cured olives. Green olives make an interesting
alternative, though. Tapenade is usually spiked with anchovies and
capers, although I find that one or the other is sufficient.
</P>
<P>
   California ripe olives are not great for tapenade, but there are
literally tons of good, inexpensive olives from Italy, Greece,
Spain and France. Avoid those that have been seasoned, because the
best tapenade is dominated by the strong flavor of olives and
little else.
</P>
<P>
   The quickest way to pit them is to press them with the flat side
of a knife or the bottom of a skillet so that the olive splits and
can be pulled off the pit. To make the puree, a mortar and pestle
produces the perfect texture, but a blender or food processor is
quicker and easier. The best texture for tapenade is slightly
chunky, not creamy.
</P>
<P>
   The salad itself is fairly straightforward, although I cut the
tomatoes into wedges and the mozzarella into chunks instead of
slices. It can be varied by using a good fresh sheep's milk cheese
or thin slices of Parmigiano-Reggiano in place of the mozzarella.
</P>
<P>
   If you choose to use the salad as a sauce for pasta, cut the
mozzarella very small.
</P>
<P>
   TOMATO SALAD WITH TAPENADE
</P>
<P>
   Total: 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   4 ripe medium tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   4 ounces pitted black olives, about 1 cup
</P>
<P>
   2 anchovy fillets or 1 teaspoon capers, or both
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons sherry vinegar
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   { pound mozzarella, preferably fresh
</P>
<P>
   { cup shredded or roughly chopped basil
</P>
<P>
   1. Core the tomatoes, and cut them into eighths. Salt them
lightly, and let sit while you make the tapenade.
</P>
<P>
   2. Combine the olives, anchovies or capers, vinegar, oil and 1
tablespoon water in a blender or small food processor. Blend until
pureed, but not too fine. Add more water if necessary; the mixture
should be fairly loose. Taste the puree and add salt and pepper as
you like.
</P>
<P>
   3. Cut the mozzarella into chunks and toss with the tomatoes and
about half the tapenade; season with salt and pepper if necessary
and add more tapenade to taste. Garnish with basil and serve
immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-08-00 1602EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
