<DOCNO> NYT20000808.0149 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 16:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5892 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-COCONUT-BOOK-REVIEW-N     08-08 1085
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COCONUT-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THAI SECRETS, FOR COOKS WITH TIME 
</HEADLINE>
   By FLORENCE FABRICANT    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The challenge for Su-Mei Yu, a Chinese woman who was born in
Thailand and grew up there, was to explain Thai cooking and to try
to simplify it for the American home cook without compromising its
authenticity. In her book, ``Cracking the Coconut: Classic Thai
Home Cooking'' (William Morrow, $30), she does a first-rate job of
getting to the heart of this complex and compelling cuisine, for
which there are so few good cookbooks, and making it
understandable. But simplify it? That's another matter.
</P>
<P>
   Yu, who has lived in the United States since she was 15 and now
owns a restaurant, Saffron, in San Diego, provides a collection of
vibrant recipes, which, if followed in traditional Thai fashion,
become a fascinating weekend's adventure. The first time I opened
this book I embarked on a far-flung shopping expedition for
fermented shrimp paste and various fresh and dried chilies and
herbs before settling in for an afternoon's and evening's workout.
I finally put an excellent moderately spicy chicken stew with
jasmine rice and a refreshingly tangy green papaya salad on the
table at 9 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, this is not a book for cooks primarily looking
for a quick and easy menu for dinner.
</P>
<P>
   Preparation of the basic seasoning pastes, for example, cannot
be hurried. They are best made in a good-size stone mortar, with
each of the 10 or 12 ingredients, some of which are toasted first,
added in succession while the cook pounds away. You think the
mixture will never come around, but then, after a good 30 minutes,
you have the paste you need. (Occasionally a food processor is
suggested instead of the stone mortar for making short work of a
bunch of ingredients, but Yu warns that the result will not have
perfect complexity, subtlety and texture.)
</P>
<P>
   In preparing fresh coconut milk, one step requires squeezing
ground coconut through a cloth 89 times, a Thai tradition. Why not
90 times, or 40? For a task that only the most determined cooks are
likely to tackle anyway, the author does not offer an explanation.
</P>
<P>
   Yu, fussy about her ingredients, grudgingly accepts lime zest as
a substitute for shredded kaffir lime leaves, and ginger in place
of fresh galangal, a similar rhizome. She doesn't even suggest the
coconut oil that is so common in Thai cooking (some recipes call
for olive oil), and she allows tinned coconut milk as a substitute
for fresh.
</P>
<P>
   Most of her recipes require an immensely detailed shopping list,
with some ingredients, like lemon grass and jasmine rice, often
sold in supermarkets, and others, like nam pla sauce and green
papayas, available only in Asian markets or by mail.
</P>
<P>
   The author tries to reassure the cook that all this shopping and
preparation is easy and simple. But no cookbook can be called
simple if it recommends 30 minutes of pounding in a mortar or
washing and trimming the tiny roots from a bunch of cilantro and
then mincing them.
</P>
<P>
   Yu's contribution has been to make Thai cooking interesting and
thoroughly satisfying. In that vein, she explains how Thai cuisine
has evolved over hundreds of years, absorbing influences from other
Asian kitchens, the Arab world and the West. She devotes chapters
to the cuisine's essential components like coconut, rice, seasoning
blends, curries and salads.
</P>
<P>
   The cooking techniques in this book are not difficult, just
time-consuming, and the recipes are not as complicated as
assembling a galantine or making a gateau St.-Honore. It certainly
helps to have some of the proper equipment, like a roomy mortar, a
spice mill and a Chinese cleaver. I happen to own an authentic
wooden Thai coconut grater in the shape of a rabbit (the business
end is its nasty iron tongue), which I took from its spot on a
display shelf for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   A handful of recipes are relatively quick to prepare, among them
grilled lobster salad, shrimp with bamboo shoots and grilled tuna
with green mango. I even dared omit some of the garnishes, like
green beans in the spicy green papaya salad, and never missed them.
</P>
<P>
   But for the most part, you have to be ready for a serious
kitchen session to produce dishes that you are unlikely to find in
a Thai restaurant, like the rich green curry and coconut soup with
corn-studded meatballs, or the fiery keang chu-chi shrimp.
</P>
<P>
   For the beef and green papaya stew, Yu even says that ``the
secret is patience.'' That about sums up the book, but the effort
is not wasted.
</P>
<P>
   GRILLED LOBSTER SALAD
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from ``Cracking the Coconut: Classic Thai Home Cooking''
</P>
<P>
   Time: 1 hour
</P>
<P>
   Sea salt
</P>
<P>
   \ cup fish sauce (nam pla, sold in Asian markets)
</P>
<P>
   5 tablespoons sugar
</P>
<P>
   { cup fresh lime juice
</P>
<P>
   2 cloves garlic, minced
</P>
<P>
   12 fresh bird chilies or 8 serrano chilies, half seeded, half
not, all minced
</P>
<P>
   1 cup white wine
</P>
<P>
   1 {-inch piece ginger, sliced thin
</P>
<P>
   3 scallions
</P>
<P>
   3 sprigs cilantro
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon white peppercorns, preferably Thai
</P>
<P>
   3 1{-pound lobsters
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   3 shallots, sliced thin
</P>
<P>
   3 stalks lemon grass, trimmed down to core, core minced
</P>
<P>
   5 kaffir lime leaves, slivered, or julienne strips of zest of 1
lime
</P>
<P>
   10 sprigs fresh mint
</P>
<P>
   6 to 7 Napa cabbage leaves, finely shredded
</P>
<P>
   1. Mix { teaspoon sea salt with fish sauce and sugar in small
saucepan. Heat until sugar dissolves, about 2 minutes. Transfer to
mixing bowl, and cool. Stir in lime juice, garlic and three-fourths
of the chilies. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   2. Fill stockpot three-fourths full with water, and bring to a
boil. Add wine, ginger, scallions, cilantro and peppercorns. Boil 5
minutes. Add lobsters, cover and boil 10 minutes, until lobsters
are red. Drain lobsters and let cool.
</P>
<P>
   3. Preheat broiler or grill. Split lobsters in shells. Discard
tomalley and coral. Sprinkle cut sides with salt, and brush with
oil. Broil, cut side up, or grill, cut side down, about 7 minutes,
until lightly browned. Remove lobster meat from tail shells and
claws, and cut in bite-size pieces. Place in large mixing bowl. Add
shallots, lemon grass and lime leaves or zest, and toss gently.
</P>
<P>
   4. Taste reserved dressing. Add some or all remaining chilies,
to taste. Pour dressing over lobster salad. Sliver leaves from 4
sprigs of mint, and fold in. Line platter with shredded cabbage,
top with lobster salad and garnish with remaining mint sprigs.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 6 appetizer servings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
