<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 16:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5901 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d BC-BOOKLOOMIS-SFCHRON &LR;      08-08 1292
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKLOOMIS-SF </SLUG>
 CHRON  
 Cook's Books: Loomis Reveals Italian Farm Cooks' Secrets  &HT;       
 By Karola Saekel 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; Susan Herrmann Loomis can't keep a secret. But in
the case of this veteran cookbook author, that's a good thing.
Because many of the secrets entrusted to her by farm cooks all over
Italy will help American home cooks bring the flavors of the
countryside to their own tables.
<P>
   Sometimes a secret, or  &LR; segreto &LR; , in her new ``Italian Farmhouse
Cookbook'' applies only to a specific dish; at other times, it's a
hint that will improve many similar preparations. For example, the
tip with a Tuscan vegetable soup advises, ``When `sweating' or
gently cooking vegetables until they are translucent, add them to
the skillet along with the oil. This way, the ingredients heat up
gently and you avoid burning them around the edges.''
</P>
<P>
   Loomis obviously likes farms. Her two previous books were
``Farmhouse Cookbook'' and ``French Farmhouse Cookbook.'' Just as
she did for those volumes, she spent a good part of two years
crisscrossing Italy and coaxing country cooks into sharing their
traditional recipes with her. In the process, she acquired a
working knowledge of the language and made friends with many of her
hosts, resulting in chatty essays interspersed with the recipes.
</P>
<P>
   In country cooking, produce plays a far more important role than
meat, fish or fowl. So while this is not a vegetarian cookbook,
people who eschew meat _ including vegans _ will find a lot to
like.
</P>
<P>
   Loomis is more than a cook with a knack for writing. She is an
astute observer of customs and manages to put her observations into
historical perspective. She relates the basic simplicity of Italian
country cooking to the historic poverty of most Italian peasants,
caused in part by harsh environments and to an even greater degree
by oppressive land policies, including some as recent as the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   Despite this somewhat gloomy situation, Loomis found a wonderful
variety of traditional dishes that bear the stamp of their
particular region and the ingredients it produces.
</P>
<P>
   Basically, she states, you can divide Italian cuisine by north
and south. In the north, corn, butter and cream rule; in the south,
it's olive oil and wheat. But defining this division by provinces
and adding a map would have been welcome clarifications. Tuscany,
for example, is a stronghold of olive oil, but it's in northwestern
Italy, not in the south.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever. Within Italy's major regions there are many
variations, not only attributable to the crops that flourish but to
historic imprints left by the many cultures that swept through this
land in its long history. Veneto, for example, over the centuries
has been influenced by its contact exposure to foreign ideas,
thanks to the port of Venice. Sicily is about the only region where
fish and seafood loom large on the farm table, since in most other
regions the coastal areas are marshy and hence not farmed.
</P>
<P>
   It may come as a surprise to read that salads are notably few on
the Italian farm despite the abundance of greens grown. Most
Italian farmers, Loomis found, prefer their greens cooked.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, Loomis did a lot of testing in her American kitchen
to get things right, since many times her question about how much
of a given ingredient was needed was answered with,  &LR; ``quanto
basta'' &LR;  _ when there is enough.
</P>
<P>
   Cooking from her book shows that she figured out what
constitutes ``enough'' _ the recipes are clear and easy to follow,
and they deliver excellent, honest food.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; ``Italian Farmhouse Cookbook,'' by Susan Herrmann Loomis &LR; 
 &LR; (Workman Publishing Co.; 460 pages; $16.95 paper, $28.95 &LR; 
 &LR; hardcover). &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; SMOTHERED CAULIFLOWER
</P>
<P>
   This recipe is from Nunzio San Fillipo, a cook at a stately farm
in Sicily. He suggests mixing leftovers with al dente pasta.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1 large onion, thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   2 large heads cauliflower, cut into florets with stems
</P>
<P>
   4 anchovy fillets, minced
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup raisins
</P>
<P>
   12 oil-cured black olives, pitted, coarsely chopped
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Fine sea salt
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup hearty red wine
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup gently packed flat-leaf parsley leaves
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Scatter half the onion slices over the bottom of a medium-size
deep skillet. Arrange half the cauliflower florets over the onion,
stems toward the center, so that when you look in the pan, you see
simply florets. Sprinkle the anchovies, raisins, olives and 3
tablespoons of the oil over the cauliflower.
</P>
<P>
   Arrange the remaining cauliflower, stems down, over the top,
pressing the florets down firmly atop the filling. The cauliflower
will mound up over the top of the pan. Scatter the remaining onions
over the cauliflower and drizzle with the remaining 1 tablespoon
oil, 1/4 cup water and salt to taste.
</P>
<P>
   Loosely cover the skillet with aluminum foil, place over medium
heat and cook, checking often to make sure the cauliflower isn't
sticking. If it is, add water, a tablespoon at a time. As it cooks,
press on it so that it sinks slightly into the pan. As soon as you
can when it has sunk enough, remove the foil, cover with a lid that
fits over the cauliflower and inside the skillet, and add 4 pounds
of weight to that to press the cauliflower as it cooks.
</P>
<P>
   Adjust the heat to medium-low and continue cooking, checking the
cauliflower occasionally, until it is soft and nearly cooked
through, about 11/4 hours. Remove the weight and lid. Pour the wine
over the cauliflower and cook until it is completely tender and the
cooking liquid is reduced by about two-thirds and darkened to a
deep caramel color, about 40 minutes more.
</P>
<P>
   Place a large, shallow serving bowl, top side down, over the
skillet and quickly invert it, so the cauliflower and its juices
drop into the bowl. Let the cauliflower cool to room temperature.
</P>
<P>
   Just before serving, mince the parsley and sprinkle it over the
cauliflower.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 8 to 10.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 170 calories, &LR;   &LR; 3 g protein, 15 g carbohydrate, &LR; 
 &LR; 11 g fat (1 g saturated), 2 mg cholesterol, 715 mg sodium, 3 g &LR; 
 &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; MARIA'S FRIED TOMATOES
</P>
<P>
   This preparation from Malvarina, near Assisi, is best made with
flavorful but slightly under-ripe tomatoes, which are fried till
they are almost black.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   3 pounds (about 8 medium) firm, flavorful tomatoes, cored and
cut lengthwise in half
</P>
<P>
   Fine sea salt
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup loosely packed fresh thyme leaves
</P>
<P>
   2 cloves garlic, cut in half, green germ removed
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Pour enough oil into a heavy skillet to make a thin but even
layer on the bottom of the pan (for a 10-inch skillet, use half the
oil) and heat over medium-high heat until it is hot but not
smoking. Add as many tomatoes, skin side down, as will easily fit
into the pan without crowding. Cook until the skin is spotted very
dark brown to black, about 4 minutes. Turn and cook until the cut
side is very dark brown as well, 4 to 5 minutes more. Reduce the
heat to medium and continue cooking, turning the tomatoes
regularly, until they are very dark around the edges and have
almost melted but still keep their shape, 16 to 20 minutes. Adjust
the heat so the tomatoes brown but don't burn.
</P>
<P>
   Transfer the tomatoes to a serving dish. Repeat the process with
the remaining tomatoes, adding more oil to the pan as necessary.
Sprinkle the cooked tomatoes lightly with salt.
</P>
<P>
   Just before serving, very finely mince the thyme and garlic
together and sprinkle over the tomatoes.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6 to 8.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 88 calories, &LR;   &LR; 1 g protein, 6 g carbohydrate, &LR; 
 &LR; 7 g fat (1 g saturated), 0 cholesterol, 11 mg sodium, 2 g &LR; 
 &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
