<SLUG> BC-GROCER-SF </SLUG>
 CHRON  
 Grocer Story Inspires Readers to Tout Their Favorite Markets  &HT;       
 By Karola Saekel 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; A quick glance into the culinary crystal ball for
the Bay Area brings one fairly safe prediction: Independent grocers
are here to stay.
<P>
   Two weeks ago, we ran a story titled ``The Last of the
Independents,'' highlighting five one-location, upscale independent
grocery stores. Along with it, we ran a list of other markets that
fit the category and invited readers to let us know of similar
stores they favored.
</P>
<P>
   And that opened the flood gates _ readers wrote, called and
e-mailed. The message that came across is that customers feel loyal
and connected to these markets. They appreciate that the stores are
tailored to specific neighborhoods; responsive to customers'
preferences and expectations; that they are run by identifiable
people rather than corporations; and that in addition to providing
fine food, they foster a sense of community.
</P>
<P>
   Not all the markets recommended completely fit the profile of
the original story. Some are reliable sources for all basic grocery
needs but hardly upscale. Some are niche stores _ natural food
stores, produce markets _ that don't supply all of a household's
grocery needs. Some operate in more than one location.
</P>
<P>
   We took a look at some of the most-recommended stores, and
here's what we found.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SAN FRANCISCO &LR;
</P>
<P>
   First among the favorites is  &UR; Marina Super &LR;  (2323 Chestnut St.,
near Scott Street, San Francisco; 415-346-7470) which, we are happy
to report, is alive and well, though we had been told otherwise and
erroneously called it defunct.
</P>
<P>
   This is one of the few markets that does home delivery ($30
minimum order by phone; $20 if you order in-store). The store
hasn't changed much over the decades _ the two rear sections hold
staples, but the front room is the main attraction, particularly
the deli/meat/take-out food counter. Marina residents who don't
want to cook love this market. There is meat loaf to be taken home,
a variety of prepared pasta dishes, grilled marinated chicken
breasts, turkey meatballs in sauce, roasted Harris Ranch beef
tri-tip, Greek salad and more. This old-fashioned store can serve
up a complete not-so-old-fashioned dinner at reasonable prices.
</P>
<P>
   CONTRA COSTA
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
COL. 1 of GROCER 8 (109984 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;   &UR; Diablo Foods &LR;  in Lafayette (3615 Mt. Diablo Blvd., near Dewing
Street; 925-283-0737), strictly speaking, doesn't fit the category
since it has a second location at 10 Dana Plaza in Concord. But the
store and its owners, Ed and Betty Stokes and their family, are so
much part of the community _ and received so many reader
nominations _ that we checked it out anyway.
</P>
<P>
   This is a handsomely appointed market with many artisan foods, a
bright floral shop, fine meat/poultry /fish department and
top-notch produce, all attractively displayed. The deli, undergoing
a brief remodel, features take-out main courses and salads and
stellar sandwiches at down-to-earth prices, including the best and
most generous chicken salad sandwich encountered in a long time _
for $4.49.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sl  &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR; PENINSULA
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  Kevin Bianchini's namesake market,  &UR; Bianchini's &LR;  in Portola
Valley (3130 Alpine Road, west of Highway 280; 650-851-4391), also
has a companion store, Foodville, at 616 Laurel St. in San Carlos.
It is owned by his father, Al, who helps run the meat department in
Portola Valley.
</P>
<P>
   One of Bianchini's focal points is the service meat counter
where butchers are undaunted by special requests. The market offers
a lot of organic food products and take-home entrees that range
from down-home comfortable to dinner-party elegant _ think
burritos, Maui ribs, marinated salmon or cooked lobster.
</P>
<P>
   The store offers an inviting outside eating area by a fountain.
</P>
<P>
   Another top vote getter on the Peninsula is  &UR; JJ&AMP;F &LR;  (520 College
Ave., near El Camino Real, Palo Alto; 650-857-0901). This
family-owned market has a fine selection of produce, a service meat
counter and a good wine selection. One Stanford staff member
e-mailed us that the staff here is ``so friendly they even remember
the Stanford students who used to shop at the store 10 years ago.''
Here, too, there are many organic items, including Judy's handmade
vegan bread from Mendocino.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sl  &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR; MARIN
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
COL. 2 of GROCER 8 (109984 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  Two San Rafael markets have a lot of loyal and vocal supporters.
 &UR; Bruno's &LR;  (688 Point San Pedro Road, near Loch Lomond Drive;
415-456-5730) is a spacious market with a good selection of
interesting jams, condiments and the like, better-than-average
produce and extensive service meat and deli departments. Sandwiches
and salads are plentiful, as are no-hassle dinner options _ baked
stuffed potatoes, pizza, burritos, chicken chow mein.
</P>
<P>
   The other San Rafael market,  &UR; Scotty's &LR;  (620 Freitas Pkwy., in
the Terra Linda Shopping Center; 415-479-2363), is easily one of
the most attractive shopping destinations. From modern shelving to
good lighting and user-friendly displays, this market makes
shopping easy. Many food items come from relatively small
producers, like Panama Canal ravioli, and there is a
restaurant-rivaling selection of prepared foods. An in-house sushi
bar and pretty selection of flowers complete the picture of the
Marin life-style.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sl  &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR; NAPA
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  St. Helena shoppers are partisans of two neighboring markets.
Some swear by  &UR; Keller's &LR;  (1320 Main St., near Adams Street;
707-963-2114), which one reader describes as a ``small,
well-stocked store that has been locally owned forever ... you can
have a charge account and they know your name. They will even
deliver if you get sick or are elderly.''
</P>
<P>
   The market carries fine sweets from Model Bakery, and the back
of the store is home to Ernie's Meats, which specializes in
housemade sausages as well as marinated meats.
</P>
<P>
   Just a couple blocks away is  &UR; Sunshine Market &LR;  (1115 Main St.,
at Pope Street; 707-963-7070), which also offers a great butcher
shop. Some locals judge the produce here the best, and the deli
draws a big crowd.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
COL. 3 of GROCER 8 (109984 ) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   END OF STORY  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
