 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Each week, The San Francisco Chronicle's panel of
professional tasters tries a different product available in
supermarkets.  
 
 Taster's Choice: Kraft Finds Balance in Balsamic Vinaigrette   By Robin Davis  
 c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  There's no better time for salads than August with
all of the wonderful fresh produce at its peak. Sliced tomatoes
right off the vine with a drizzle of balsamic vinaigrette can be
heaven.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Today's panel tasted 12 bottled balsamic vinaigrettes. Panelists
were disappointed by the category as a whole and felt better
vinaigrettes could easily be made at home with a good quality olive
oil and balsamic vinegar.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the primary complaint was the inferior taste of the
ingredients. Most of the vinaigrettes used vegetable oil instead of
olive oil. Many also incorporated white vinegar into the dressing,
taking away from the balsamic characteristics.
</P>
<P>
   The panel tasted the vinaigrettes alone and tossed with mixed
greens. No low-fat or nonfat vinaigrettes were included.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Kraft &LR;  (14 ounces, $3.75 at Safeway) took top honors. Panelists
agreed that this vinaigrette had the best balance of flavors; one
commented that this brand seemed to use high-quality ingredients.
But one panelist didn't think it tasted much like a balsamic
vinaigrette. Others thought the finish tasted sweet and artificial.
Three would buy it, one might buy it and one would not.
</P>
<P>
   Second place went to  &UR; Cardini's &LR;  (121/2 ounces, $3.49 at
Andronico's). Two panelists particularly liked the balance of
flavors. One panelist thought the addition of herbs added to the
appearance without taking away from the flavor, but two others
didn't like the dried-herb taste. Two would buy it, two might buy
it and one would not.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Trader Joe's &LR;  (12 ounces, $2.79 at Trader Joe's) _ the only
vinaigrette that must be refrigerated even before opening _ came in
third. Three panelists described the flavor as too tart and sharp.
Two others thought it had good balance, but one noted that it would
be easy to make a better vinaigrette at home. Four might buy it;
one would not.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Spectrum &LR;  (8 ounces, $3.59 at Whole Foods) received a
fourth-place ranking. Three panelists described this dressing as
too sweet; one detected berry notes (there are no berries, but
white grape concentrate is one of the ingredients). Another liked
the flavor, citing a particularly good balance of tart-sweet notes.
One would buy it; four would not.
</P>
<P>
   Fifth place went to  &UR; Bernstein's &LR;  (16 ounces, $3.39 at Safeway).
Two panelists thought the dried herbs and garlic tasted artificial,
and another thought it had too much herb flavor. Two panelists
liked the tart quality, but one noted it didn't taste much like a
balsamic vinaigrette. Two might buy it; three would not.
</P>
<P>
   The panel also tasted Newman's Own, Consorzio, Whole Foods, Wild
Thymes, Wish-Bone, Annie's Naturals and Silver Palate, but they
scored too low to rate.
</P>
<P>
   Panelists were Meryl Bennan, food writer and consultant; John P.
Carroll, cookbook author; Patricia Hart, food writer and
consultant; Roland Passot, chef-owner La Folie in San francisco and
Left Bank in Larkspur and Menlo Park; and Kirk Webber, chef-owner,
Cafe Kati, San Francisco. A perfect score for any product would be
100. All products are tasted blind. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
