<P>
   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   DEMS-VEEP (Nashville, Tenn.) _ Vice President Al Gore formally
introduces Sen. Joseph Lieberman of Connecticut as his running mate
before an enthusiastic Tennessee crows. By BENNETT ROTH.
</P>
<P>
   With: DEMS-HADASSAH
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-SHANTYTOWNS (Austin, Texas) _ A 23-year-old report on the
colonias, or shantytowns, along the Rio Grande painted a dramatic
and painful picture of rural poverty and substandard housing.
Today, the colonias remain and the state government's failure to
eradicate these pockets of poverty has become fodder for the
presidential battle between Texas Gov. George W. Bush and Vice
President Al Gore. By RUSSELL GOLD and PEGGY FIKAC. (Already
filed.)
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   COLOMBIA-DRUGS (Washington) _ A State Department probe of
anti-drug efforts in Colombia challenges the effectiveness of U.S.
assistance in anti-drug efforts there, even as America prepares to
spend $1.3 billion to beef up Colombia's war on narcotics
traffickers. The report, by the department's inspector general,
finds that an expensive U.S. effort to spray coca and opium plants
with herbicide has been a failure. By MICHAEL HEDGES.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-EXECUTIONS (Austin, Texas) _ Texas plans to execute two
more inmates, one of them mentally retarded, raising again a
troubling moral issue as Gov. George W. Bush campaigns for the
presidency. By POLLY ROSS HUGHES.
</P>
<P>
   STANDOFF-EXTREMIST (Trinidad, Texas) _ Texas law enforcement
officials are trying to avoid a deadly confrontation with a heavily
armed survivalist member of the Embassy of Heaven sect who has been
holed up for the past 18 months with at least six children and 10
or more adult relatives. By JIM HENDERSON.
</P>
<P>
   CONFEDERATE-TEXAS (Austin, Texas) _ As the presidential hopefuls
debated the presence of South Carolina's battle flag earlier this
year, many a Confederate ghost haunted the halls of the Texas
Capitol where George W. Bush presides as Texas' governor. By POLLY
ROSS HUGHES.
</P>
<P>
   SPACE-STATION (Houston) _ The unmanned Progress capsule
containing life support equipment heads to a rendezvous with the
international space station. By MARK CARREAU.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ On Monday, USA Today's headline
read: Bush over Gore by 17 points. On Tuesday, USA Today reported:
Bush's lead has almost disappeared. The sudden shift between
Monday's weekend poll and Tuesday's quickie reaction to Gore's
selection of Sen. Joseph Lieberman is likely to be repeated over
and over during the coming campaign. This is going to be a tight,
closely-matched race and the only poll that matters is on election
day. By MARIANNE MEANS.
</P>
<P>
   HINES-COLUMN (Washington) _ Al Gore has come down with a highly
symbolic, and possibly highly selective, case of ``Clinton
fatigue.'' Gore wants his selection of Sen. Joseph Lieberman as the
Democratic vice presidential nominee to be seen as at least a
modified declaration of independence from President Clinton. By
CRAGG HINES.
</P>
<P>
   ELY-COLUMN (Houston) _ Like George W. Bush's choice of Dick
Cheney as his running mate, Al Gore's decision to select Sen.
Joseph Lieberman as the Democratic nominee for vice president makes
little difference in the presidential race. By JANE ELY.
</P>
