<SLUG> BC-WALKOAK-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Food Lovers' Walks is a bi-weekly column that covers
neighborhoods in San Francisco and other Bay Area cities where a
casual stroll turns up culinary treasures. &HT;     
 Food Lovers' Walks: Oakland Chinatown Walk Brings Together a 
 Variety of Tastes   By Kim Severson  
 c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; OAKLAND, Calif. _  &LR; Fresh from Burma, Philip Chu stepped onto the
streets of Oakland's Chinatown in 1969. The tiny immigrant district
wasn't much more than a handful of stores and restaurants clustered
around the intersection of Eighth and Webster streets.
<P>
   More than 30 years later, the district snakes out well past its
core, roughly a 12-block square defined by Seventh and 11th streets
and Broadway and Harrison.
</P>
<P>
   Like the boundaries, the cultures represented in Chinatown have
stretched beyond the Cantonese immigrants who started the place
more than 140 years ago. All of which makes for a fascinating
shopping trip. A few hours strolling around the heart of Oakland's
Chinatown capped by lunch at one of several restaurants in the area
is a fine way for a food lover to spend the day.
</P>
<P>
   For a guide, I invited Chu and his wife, Nancy, who cook
well-regarded Burmese food at Nan Yang in Rockridge. They started
out in Oakland's Chinatown in a little restaurant near Eighth and
Harrison streets. They left in 1996, but still shop in Chinatown
almost daily.
</P>
<P>
   In today's Chinatown, almost nothing is a pure distillation of
one culture. Certainly, Chinese food dominates. But Vietnamese and
Filipino goods spill out onto sidewalks, the shopkeepers often
ethnic Chinese from those countries. In almost all the stores,
shoppers can find Thai curry pastes, Japanese pickles, Burmese
spice mixes, Korean kimchi and even some Western staples. A good
place to start is the corner of Ninth Street and Broadway, where
the European cafes and Victorians of Old Oakland give way to a
strip of mostly Vietnamese run produce stands and grocery stores
along Ninth Street.
</P>
<P>
   The block allows for quick price comparisons. Long beans, for
example, can run from $1 to $1.20 a pound. Bags of pea vines, which
Chu suggests stir-frying in hot oil and garlic, then finishing with
a shot each of chicken stock and rice wine and a pinch of sugar and
salt, cost just under $1 a pound at the stands. Inside the stores
along the strip, packages of soft, white Vietnamese rice noodles
vary from 99 cents to $1.20.
</P>
<P>
   To keep you fortified before lunch, stop in at the spanking new
 &UR; Best Tea House &LR;  on Ninth Street and Webster for an iced drink with
plump, dark balls of tapioca swimming in milky sweet tea. If the
new Taiwanese drinks aren't to your liking, the calm little spot
offers a wide array of traditional teas. A short, quiet rest here
and you'll be ready to head for the heart of Oakland's Chinatown
and browse Chu's favorite shops.
</P>
<P>
   The couple often makes a stop at  &UR; Harvest Fish Market &LR;  on Eighth
Street. Chu points out the clean smell and the freshly scrubbed
rubber mats that line the narrow shop. He also likes the table and
tank displays that allow a good, close look at the shiny snapper
fillets ($2.99 a pound), whole catfish ($1.69 a pound), live
lobsters ($6.99 a pound) and small, dark live abalone ($12.50 a
pound). The labels are both in Chinese and English, which makes it
easy for shoppers who aren't bilingual.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby, the Chus often duck into  &UR; Sam Yick Market &LR; , a store
owned by an ethnic Chinese family from the Philippines. Because of
the mix, the Chus can find traditional Chinese produce like bitter
melon and food more typical in Filipino cooking, like okra.
</P>
<P>
   Along the shelves that line the upper reaches of the shop is a
suprisingly large selection of imported pottery. Some of it is
kitschy, but other items are real deals. A large, rose-covered vase
would be perfect in a garden and costs a mere $26.99. White mugs
covered with peaked lids and painted with blue carp would be
perfect for tea or soup _ and a bargain at $2.49 apiece.
</P>
<P>
   Barbecued duck and chicken are essential treats from Chinatown,
and the Chus have their favorite spot for them _  &UR; Gold &LR; 
 &UR; Medal Restaurant &LR; , across Eighth Street from the Sam Yick Market.
It offers steamy bowls of jook and fried, savory Chinese doughnuts
for breakfast and barbecued and roasted meats throughout the day.
</P>
<P>
   A truly superior whole crispy duck with a cup of soy-based
dipping sauce costs $9.50 a bird. Roast pork, with soft, snowy meat
and crackling-crisp skin, is $4.95 a pound. Have the staff pack up
a couple of pounds for a late-afternoon snack or dinner.
</P>
<P>
   Before lunch, take a little time to wander in and out of the
Chinese apothecaries. The array of dried roots and herbs are likely
baffling to Westerners, but Chu says the medicinal soup recipes
they are used in are thousands of years old.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Pacific Seafood &LR; , a brightly lit shop on the corner of Franklin
and Eighth streets that specializes in all sort of dried fish, also
is worth a stop. Chu is particularly fond of the mahogany-colored
dried scallops, which range in price from $42-$70 a pound, and
smooth-shelled ginkgo nuts ($4.59 a pound), which he says are fine
to crack like pecans and boil with jook or sweet fruit soup.
</P>
<P>
   For lunch, the Chus recommend  &UR; Restaurant Peony &LR; . The restaurant
is only five years old _ a mere pup in a district that began
serving food to Chinese gold miners in the mid-1800s.
</P>
<P>
   On the second floor of the new six-story  &UR; Pacific Renaissance &LR; 
 &UR; Plaza &LR;  on Ninth Street between Franklin and Webster, the Peony has
the Asian branch of the Oakland library as a downstairs neighbor.
Many older Chinese-Americans live upstairs in 200 condominiums, a
short elevator ride away from trusted herbalists, Chinese-speaking
grocers and restaurateurs cooking a familiar style of Cantonese
food.
</P>
<P>
   With seating for 800 people, the Peony is a massive stretch of
round tables and hustling waiters under miles of drop-tile ceiling.
Two of the Chus' sons had their wedding banquets here. The food is
so good, the Chus say, that many consider it the most authentic
Hong Kong-style dim sum place in the Bay Area.
</P>
<P>
   Dim sum at the Peony is so popular that there is a line even on
a Monday afternoon.  &LR; Sui mai  &LR; is a standout, as are dishes of
tender tripe and plump  &LR; har gow &LR; . But the Peony has other
surprises, like rectangular slices of steamed taro root stuffed
with shrimp paste and quickly deep-fried and served in a light
mushroom sauce.
</P>
<P>
   In the new Chinatown, the food has to be that good, the Chus
say. No longer will people settle for the sticky sweet and sour
pork or dry, flat patties of egg foo yong that once passed for
Chinese food in the area. There are too many new immigrants, too
many people with sophisticated tastes, too many competitive chefs
who know they can only survive by being better and more creative
than the cook down the street _ or across the Bay, for that matter.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; OAKLAND'S CHINATOWN &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The area code for the following businesses is (510).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; STORES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Harvest Fish Market &LR; , 376 Eighth St., (between Webster and
Franklin streets); 893-8716
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Pacific Seafood, Inc. &LR; , 800 Franklin St., (at Eighth Street);
834-8898
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Sam Yick Market, Inc. &LR; , 362 Eighth St., (between Webster and
Franklin streets); 832-0662
</P>
<P>
   &UR; RESTAURANTS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Best Tea House &LR; , 395 Ninth St. (near Franklin Street);
268-1139
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Gold Medal Restaurant &LR; , 381 Eighth St. (near Webster Street);
268-8484
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Restaurant Peony, &LR;  388 Ninth St., (on second level of the
Pacific Renaissance Plaza on Franklin Street); 286-8866
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; CHINATOWN STREETFEST &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The 13th annual Oakland Chinatown Streetfest Aug. 26 and 27 will
fill 10 blocks with parades, cooking demonstrations, food booths,
live music and arts and crafts.
</P>
<P>
   The festivities begin at 10 a.m. each day and end at 6 p.m.
Admission is free. Call (510) 893-8979 for more information.
</P>
</TEXT>
