<HEADER>
A5909 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d BC-PALETTE-SFCHRON &LR;      08-08 3078
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PALETTE-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
 Technicolor Cooking: White carrots, yellow beets and ripe
green  tomatoes make up a culinary palette   By Janet Fletcher 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; At San Francisco's elegant Fifth Floor restaurant,
it takes one cook to make the heirloom tomato soup and two to serve
it.
<P>
   Working with three ladles between them, the cooks simultaneously
pour chilled yellow, red and green tomato purees into each bowl so
that the mixtures meet but don't mingle. For diners, the dish is an
invitation to explore the nuances of a favorite summer food that,
not so long ago, came only in red.
</P>
<P>
   Fifth Floor chef George Morrone's tricolor meditation on tomato
soup is just one of the more refined examples of the Technicolor
revolution in today's kitchens. With local markets overflowing with
white zucchini, striped beets, golden peppers and purple potatoes,
Bay Area cooking has never been more colorful.
</P>
<P>
   Although chefs insist that flavor always comes first, a glance
at the dishes coming out of their kitchens proves that they are
reveling in their expanded palette.
</P>
<P>
   ``It perks you up,'' says Annie Somerville, chef at Greens in
San Francisco. ``With such beautiful contrasts and colors _ it just
makes things more enticing and more fun to work with.''
</P>
<P>
   Diners at Greens might find a three-beet soup, made with red,
golden and red-and-white-striped Chioggia beets and served like
Morrone's tomato creation.
</P>
<P>
   The restaurant's antipasto plate sometimes features a pairing of
purple ``huckleberry'' potatoes with golden Yellow Finns.
Multicolored peppers are roasted and scattered over pizza or
braised together with garlic and herbs for  &LR; peperonata &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   At Stars, chef Christopher Hernandez uses golden, red and
striped beets with watercress and shaved  &LR; ricotta salata &LR;  in one of
his favorite salads. He scatters lemon cucumbers over the top to
add a fluorescent yellow-green.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Downing, the chef at Spiedini in Walnut Creek, uses
Orchid watermelon, which has a vibrant yellow-orange color, to
create a cooling summer soup. For a whimsical touch, he carves
other pieces of melons into classic vegetable shapes like beans,
potatoes, carrots and celery. He also grills French Grey zucchini _
a varietal with light greenish-white skin _ and serves it with
yellow and purple tomatoes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Color creates a visual texture that you pick up on the
palate,'' says Downing.
</P>
<P>
   Eggplant also comes in designer colors this year. Giovanni
Perticone of Splendido uses different varieties in chartreuse,
rose, green, white and lavender and sautes them together with olive
oil, garlic, pine nuts, raisins and balsamic vinegar.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Colorful History &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Despite the relatively recent commercial influx of white beets,
orange peppers, violet carrots and the like, produce experts say
these differently colored vegetables are nothing new.
</P>
<P>
   ``Carrots used to be white or yellow or violet,'' says William
Woys Weaver, the Pennsylvania author of ``Heirloom Vegetable
Gardening'' (Henry Holt, 1997). ``The Romans knew white and yellow
carrots. The orange was bred into (carrots) in the 18th century by
Dutch horticulturists.''
</P>
<P>
   The earliest wild beets were white or yellow, says Weaver. Along
the beaches of the Mediterranean, you can still pull up such pallid
tubers. But some of the leaves have pink stems and patient growers
eventually got the pink to creep down the stem and into the roots,
breeding them darker and darker to achieve the blood-red beets we
know today.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've just controlled it,'' Weaver says. ``All (these colors)
are artificially induced on nature. But we've created commodities
out of them, so that what most people see in their supermarket is
very limited. That's why I like heirlooms.''
</P>
<P>
   By saving selected seeds from his heirloom vegetables, Weaver
can create a variety all his own. When some yellow-ribbed chard in
his garden showed a touch of red in the ribs, he saved the seed and
planted successive generations, always replanting only the seed of
the reddest ones, until he gradually produced a chard with a
deep-orange rib.
</P>
<P>
   Although orange-ribbed chard and purple beans may look like the
wayward experiments of a genetic engineer, produce experts say that
biotechnology isn't involved _ and isn't likely to be. There's not
enough profit in golden beets or white carrots to interest the
biotech industry, where research costs are huge. And because these
colors are found naturally in many species, as Weaver discovered
with his red-tinged chard, they're easy to achieve by conventional
breeding.
</P>
<P>
   For example, purple-podded pole beans, which some shoppers may
think are bioengineered, were grown in American gardens in the late
18th century, Weaver points out. But like most cooks, Weaver agrees
they look best on the pole _ the striking purple color turns khaki
green when the beans are cooked.
</P>
<P>
   Violet carrots also turn an unappetizing shade when cooked but
are visually striking and delicious when grated raw, he says. And
purple-hued tomatoes, like Cherokee Purple, can be stunning in a
salad. ``They look like raw tuna when they're sliced,'' Weaver
says. ``You can have tomato sushi.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Flavor Beats Color &LR;
</P>
<P>
   For Zuni Cafe chef Judy Rodgers, purple beans and purple peppers
are among the few vegetables she would happily toss on the compost
heap of history. What she calls ``that whole slew of purple-hued
stuff'' is mostly a grand disappointment. ``It draws you in at the
market because it's unusual and a lovely rich, regal hue,'' she
acknowledges. ``But once you cook the thing, (the color) goes away.
It's a lovely enticement that doesn't make it to the plate.''
</P>
<P>
   She does embrace purple asparagus, which she slices on a
mandoline into lengthwise ribbons like pappardelle and dresses with
olive oil, lemon, salt and chopped pistachios. Given this
treatment, the vegetable's color is dazzling, she admits, but that
alone doesn't persuade her to buy. ``If it didn't taste really
good, I wouldn't keep buying it,'' says Rodgers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Golden beets have been my favorite beet from the first time I
had one,'' Rodgers says. Roasted, grated and stirred into a
risotto, they contribute a subtle sweetness and a color that looks
like you've added a fortune in saffron.
</P>
<P>
   Many chefs say flavor beats color every time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think in terms of color,'' says Craig Stoll,
chef-owner of Delfina in San Francisco. ``If the food's beautiful,
it's beautiful. It's an added bonus if it's colorful.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, when Stoll can get good-tasting beets in multiple
colors, he uses them in his beet and cress salad, topped with
Humboldt Fog goat cheese. If their flavor meets his standards,
he'll use variously colored tomatoes in his  &LR; insalata &LR;   &LR; caprese &LR; ,
along with housemade mozzarella and basil oil. The gazpacho recipe
that he perfected after a trip to Spain is ``killer'' made with
meaty yellow paste tomatoes, he says.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, chef Traci des Jardins of San Francisco's Jardini &LR; e &LR; re
says she never buys on color alone, but is not immune to the allure
that color can contribute to a dish. Occasionally she makes a
layered tomato terrine using different colored tomatoes, and serves
it with tapenade and goat cheese crostini. Recently, she garnished
a lobster salad with a rainbow of beets and a bright green chervil
vinaigrette. And a favorite summer salad at Jardini &LR; e &LR; re showcases
haricots verts, yellow wax beans and romano beans with baby greens
ringed by beets of various colors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Often I'll try to integrate something colorful, but it's not
there purely for color,'' she says. Golden beets may be ravishing _
in color and taste _ but the best chefs don't scatter them around
without reason, any more than they would resort to the tired
parsley sprig garnish.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; Help the Farmer
</P>
<P>
   ``Celebrating colors is a wonderful idea,'' says Bill Fujimoto
of Berkeley's Monterey Foods. Too many shoppers pass up the unusual
out of fear that it won't cook or taste the same as the familiar
variety, he says, and they miss out on some delicious experiences.
Purple carrots, which the store has carried, are quite tasty, he
says. So are white, striped and golden beets, which can be cooked
just like red beets with the added advantage of not staining
everything in sight.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, buying these Technicolor vegetables can pay
long-term dividends, Fujimoto says. ``The people who grow these
varieties are specialty farmers, and specialty farming is the niche
for small farmers. If you go to the store and always buy a bag of
Fuji apples, celery, navel oranges and that same romaine for your
salad, the small farms will disappear.''
</P>
<P>
   For Bay Area shoppers with a taste for adventure, the season is
now. From Sunburst squash to Evergreen tomatoes, a rainbow of
summer produce awaits.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
GREENS' LINGUINE WITH ZUCCHINI, CHERRY TOMATOES &AMP; GREMOLATA
</P>
<P>
   A &LR;   &LR; final sprinkle of gremolata (minced garlic, lemon zest and
Italian parsley) heightens the flavor of squash and tomatoes in
this summer pasta.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1/4 pound each, golden and green zucchini, or scalloped summer
squash
</P>
<P>
   11/2 cups cherry tomatoes of different colors, such as Sweet
100, Sungold, red or yellow pear
</P>
<P>
   3 garlic cloves, finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons finely chopped lemon zest
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons chopped Italian parsley
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper, to taste
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound fresh linguine
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon fresh lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons toasted pine nuts
</P>
<P>
   Grated Parmesan cheese, as desired
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Bring a large pot of water to a boil over high heat.
</P>
<P>
   Cut the zucchini in half lengthwise, then slice diagonally into
1/4-inch-thick pieces. (If you're using Sunburst or pattypan
squash, halve through the stem end and slice into 1/2-inch-thick
wedges.) Halve the cherry tomatoes if large.
</P>
<P>
   Set aside 1 teaspoon of the garlic. Make the gremolata by
combining the remaining garlic with the lemon zest and parsley. Set
aside.
</P>
<P>
   Heat 2 tablespoons of the olive oil in a large skillet. Add the
squash, reserved 1 teaspoon garlic, and salt and pepper. Saute over
medium-high heat for 2 to 3 minutes, just long enough to heat the
squash through.
</P>
<P>
   Add 1 teaspoon salt to the pot of boiling water. Add the
linguine and cook until just tender. Before draining the pasta, add
a few tablespoons of the cooking water to the saute pan, along with
the cherry tomatoes and remaining 1 tablespoon olive oil.
</P>
<P>
   Drain the pasta and add it to the pan. Add the gremolata, lemon
juice and pine nuts. Season with salt and pepper. Reduce the heat
to low and toss well. Serve immediately, garnishing each portion
with Parmesan.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 2 or 3.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 465 calories, &LR;   &LR; 13 g protein, 65 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 18 g fat (2 g saturated), 0 cholesterol, 12 mg
sodium, 2 g &LR;   &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; DELFINA'S YELLOW TOMATO GAZPACHO
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   21/2 pounds yellow or gold tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound bread (not sourdough), crusts removed  &LR; _ &LR; 2 tablespoons
sherry vinegar + more if needed
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons red wine vinegar + more if needed
</P>
<P>
   1 small Japanese cucumber (about 1/3 pound), peeled and cut into
1-inch pieces
</P>
<P>
   1/2 yellow or gold bell pepper, deribbed and cut into 1-inch
pieces
</P>
<P>
   1/2 red onion, sliced
</P>
<P>
   1 or 2 garlic cloves, finely minced
</P>
<P>
   Kosher salt, to taste
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup extra virgin olive oil + more, if needed
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Peel and core the tomatoes and cut them in half. Strain the
juice in the seed cavities and reserve, discarding seeds.
</P>
<P>
   Tear the bread into chunks and place in a large bowl. Add the
tomato juice, 2 tablespoons sherry vinegar and 2 tablespoons red
wine vinegar. Stir to moisten the bread. Add the cucumber, bell
pepper, onion, garlic and tomatoes. Season with salt. Let marinate
at room temperature for 1 to 2 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Puree this mixture in a blender or food processor, adding 1/4
cup oil to emulsify.
</P>
<P>
   Strain the puree through a medium sieve.
</P>
<P>
   Taste and adjust seasoning with oil, vinegar and salt.
</P>
<P>
   Chill thoroughly before serving.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 240 calories, &LR;   &LR; 4 g protein, 25 g carbohydrate, &LR; 
 &LR; 15 g fat (2 g saturated), 0 cholesterol, 124 mg sodium, 5 g &LR; 
 &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; GOLDEN BEET RISOTTO
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   8 small or 6 medium-size golden beets
</P>
<P>
   Approximately 51/2 cups chicken broth (if canned, dilute 50-50
with water)
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1/2 yellow onion, minced
</P>
<P>
   11/2 cups Arborio or other short-grain Italian rice
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground pepper, to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon minced parsley
</P>
<P>
   Freshly grated Parmesan cheese (optional)
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 375 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   If the beet greens are attached, remove all but 1 inch of them.
(Save the greens for another use.) Put the beets in a baking dish
with 1/4 inch of water. Cover and bake for 45 minutes or more,
depending on size, or until a knife pierces them easily.
</P>
<P>
   When the beets are cool enough to handle, peel and grate on the
coarse side of a box grater. You should have about 11/2 cups.
</P>
<P>
   Bring the broth to a simmer in a small saucepan and adjust heat
to maintain a gentle simmer.
</P>
<P>
   Melt 1 tablespoon of the butter with the olive oil in a medium
saucepan over medium heat. Add the onion and saute until softened.
Add the rice and cook, stirring, until the rice is hot. Begin
adding the hot broth 1/2 cup at a time, stirring often and adding
more broth only when the previous addition has been absorbed. After
10 minutes, stir in the grated beets. It should take 18 to 20
minutes for the rice to absorb all or most of the liquid and become
al dente, still firm but with no hard core.
</P>
<P>
   Risotto should be creamy, neither soupy nor stiff. If you need
more liquid to achieve the proper consistency, use boiling water.
</P>
<P>
   Season the risotto with salt and pepper. Cover, remove from heat
and let stand for 2 minutes. Uncover, add the parsley and the
remaining 2 tablespoons butter and stir vigorously until the butter
melts. Add a little Parmesan, if desired.
</P>
<P>
   Serve immediately in warm bowls.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6 as a first course, 4 as a main course.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 280 calories, &LR;   &LR; 7 g protein, 43 g carbohydrate,
9 &LR;   &LR; g fat (4 g saturated), 16 mg cholesterol, 28 mg sodium, 1 g &LR; 
 &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; STARS' ROASTED BEET SALAD WITH WATERCRESS &AMP; RICOTTA SALATA
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from a recipe from Stars chef Christopher Fernandez.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   8 small beets of various colors
</P>
<P>
   2 or 3 thyme sprigs
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon fresh orange juice
</P>
<P>
   Pinch grated orange zest
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon minced fresh tarragon
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground pepper, to taste
</P>
<P>
   2 lemon cucumbers
</P>
<P>
   2 small bunches watercress
</P>
<P>
   1/4 pound ricotta salata, in one piece
</P>
<P>
   The Vinaigrette
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon minced shallots
</P>
<P>
   11/2 tablespoons red wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon Dijon mustard
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon minced fresh thyme
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 375 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Place the beets in a baking dish with about 1/4 inch of water.
Add the thyme sprigs, cover and bake about 45 minutes, or until a
knife pierces the beets easily. When the beets are cool enough to
handle, peel them and cut into wedges. Keeping the red beets
separate to prevent ``bleeding,'' dress beets with the olive oil,
orange juice, orange zest and tarragon. Season with salt and
pepper.
</P>
<P>
   About 30 minutes before serving, peel the lemon cucumbers, cut
into wedges and season with salt.
</P>
<P>
   Remove any large stems from the watercress.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; To make the vinaigrette:  &LR; Cover the shallots with wine vinegar
in a bowl and let stand for 5 minutes. Whisk in the mustard, thyme
and olive oil. Season with salt and pepper. Taste and adjust
balance as needed.
</P>
<P>
   Toss the watercress with enough of the dressing to coat the
leaves lightly. Add the cucumbers and toss again.
</P>
<P>
   Divide among serving plates. Scatter the beets evenly over the
salads. Using a vegetable peeler, shave the ricotta over the salads
in long, curly slivers.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 270 calories, &LR;   &LR; 7 g protein, 10 g carbohydrate, &LR; 
 &LR; 23 g fat (7 g saturated), 25 mg cholesterol, 386 mg sodium, 4 g &LR; 
 &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
SPAGHETTI WITH RED &AMP; GOLD TOMATOES &AMP; FETA
</P>
<P>
   Hot spaghetti with a cool sauce makes a refreshing dinner on a
balmy evening.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   11/2 pounds tomatoes of mixed colors, peeled, halved, seeded and
thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Splash red wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   2 garlic cloves, minced
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground pepper, to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 pound spaghetti
</P>
<P>
   24 basil leaves
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound Greek, Bulgarian or French feta
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Combine the tomatoes, olive oil, vinegar, garlic, salt and
pepper in a large bowl. Let stand for 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Cook the pasta until al dente in plenty of boiling salted water.
While the pasta cooks, tear the basil leaves into small pieces and
add to the tomatoes.
</P>
<P>
   Drain the pasta and transfer to the bowl with the tomatoes. Add
the feta, crumbling it as you add it. Toss the pasta well.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 720 calories, &LR;   &LR; 25 g protein, 95 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 28 g fat (10 g saturated), 50 mg cholesterol, 647
mg sodium, 2 &LR;   &LR; g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; SUMMER BEAN SALAD WITH CHERRY TOMATOES &AMP; FETA
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   11/2 tablespoons white wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1/2 small red onion, minced
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground pepper, to taste
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound green beans, such as Blue Lakes
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound yellow wax beans
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound small cherry tomatoes (preferably mixed red and gold
varieties), halved
</P>
<P>
   24 basil leaves, torn into pieces
</P>
<P>
   2 to 3 ounces feta cheese
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Whisk together the oil, vinegar, red onion, salt and pepper in a
large bowl. Let stand for 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Boil the green and yellow beans in a large quantity of salted
water until al dente (boil the two colors separately if they are
not the same size); drain and transfer to ice water. When cool,
drain again and pat dry.
</P>
<P>
   Add the beans to the bowl with dressing and toss. Add the
tomatoes and basil and toss again. Crumble the feta into the bowl
and toss again. Taste and adjust seasoning. Beans need a lot of
salt. Serve immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 180 calories, &LR;   &LR; 5 g protein, 12 g carbohydrate, &LR; 
 &LR; 14 g fat (4 g saturated), 13 mg cholesterol, 168 mg sodium, 3 g &LR; 
 &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
