<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 16:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5912 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-RIVAL-CIRCUS-ART-2     08-08 0772
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-RIVAL-CIRCUS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG APPLE CIRCUS CRIES FOUL AT NEW RINGLING'S HOLIDAY SHOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.)  
 By GLENN COLLINS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ And now, ladies and gentlemen and children of all
ages, direct your attention to the stupendous holiday war between
two big-top circuses.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time the City of New York will permit the Ringling
Brothers and Barnum &AMP; Bailey Circus to raise a custom-made Italian
tent in Bryant Park to present a high-end, one-ring,
family-oriented circus during the Thanksgiving and Christmas
holidays. After eight months of deliberation, the mayor's office,
the Parks Department and the Bryant Park Conservancy have given
Ringling their blessing.
</P>
<P>
   But for 23 years a feisty hometown show, the Big Apple Circus,
has become a holiday entertainment tradition by raising its
custom-made French tent in Damrosch Park at Lincoln Center to
present its own upscale, one-ring, family-oriented circus.
</P>
<P>
   The Ringling show hopes to turn a profit, and Big Apple _ a
nonprofit organization _ is crying foul. ``It could be an enormous
financial blow to us, because the Lincoln Center season is key in
providing income for the Big Apple Circus,'' said Alan B. Slifka, a
Big Apple board member who was its first board chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Slifka said ``it is possible that we could be driven out of
existence,'' adding that ``we hope that this decision will be
reconsidered by the mayor as the serious threat to our circus that
it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Green, the New York City public advocate, wrote a letter
last week to Rudy Washington, deputy mayor for Business Services
and Community Development, urging the city to reschedule the
performance of the Ringling one-ring show because ``we are dealing
with a small potential audience, and this conflict risks
diminishing both events,'' he said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   The new circus, called ``Barnum's Kaleidoscape,'' was created 16
months ago by Ringling and has visited 12 American cities.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Feld, Ringling's 51-year-old producer and chief
executive, said ``Kaleidoscape'' would be ``the ultimate Christmas
ornament for New York City,'' referring to the champagne-colored
tent with its red stars and stripes. The elaborately produced, $10
million show offers the comforts of crushed-velvet padded seats
with backs, and red-carpeted hardwood flooring, as well as premier
``couch'' seating at $75 a head.
</P>
<P>
   Customers will be welcomed by costumed ticket-takers and ushers,
and will be encouraged to buy not only cotton candy and popcorn,
but also high-end fare ranging from panini sandwiches to designer
water.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the right kind of entertainment for that time of year,''
said Michael Fuchs, chairman of the Bryant Park Restoration Corp.,
the nonprofit group that oversees the park.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Kaleidoscape'' crew will erect its reception tent around
the fountain in Bryant Park. Like all attractions using the park,
Ringling is contractually obligated to replace any damaged grass or
shrubbery.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kaleidoscape'' will also return part of every ticket sale to
the Bryant Park Restoration Corp., the total amounting to ``several
hundred thousand dollars,'' Feld said.
</P>
<P>
   Several city managers with knowledge of the deal said that
Ringling had guaranteed the park a minimum of $200,000 for the run.
</P>
<P>
   At Lincoln Center, Big Apple will hold the debut of its new
show, ``Clown Around Town,'' from Oct. 19 through Jan. 7, charging
$18 to $62 for seats. The show features 12 horses and 2 dogs; some
120 of its 140 performers and crew members live in the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kaleidoscape'' will charge $20 to $75 for seats. It will raise
its tent on Nov. 16 and have its debut on Nov. 21, two days before
Thanksgiving Day. The closing performance will be New Year's Eve.
It has 62 performers, 54 crew members, 8 horses and 27 geese. Only
the show's musical composer, Linda Hudes, is a New Yorker.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Binder, the 57-year-old founder and artistic director of
Big Apple, said he did not want to be quoted ``in a sour grapes
way'' about ``Kaleidoscape,'' which he has seen and said is
``extraordinary.''
</P>
<P>
   Binder added: ``I love the show, and I love the performers in
that show. I am only sorry that they have chosen to compete with
us.''
</P>
<P>
   Slifka was not as sanguine. ``For New York to invite Ringling in
to crush the Big Apple Circus,'' he said, ``it's almost as if the
city invited a for-profit opera company to come in and compete with
the Metropolitan Opera.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Fuchs said that ``we weren't trying to harm the Big Apple
Circus,'' adding that the city ``no longer puts money into Bryant
Park, so we are dependent on the money we can bring in,'' namely,
fees for such activities as fashion shows, concerts and
movie-screening nights.
</P>
<P>
   Feld's personal connection with Fuchs helped cement the deal.
The ``Kaleidoscape'' proposal ``seemed to our staff so out of the
ordinary that it sort of got turned down automatically,'' said
Fuchs, formerly the president of HBO.
</P>
<P>
   But he said that when Ringling came back to him: ``I knew Ken,
and I said we'd look into it. The more we got into it, the more we
thought it was a good idea.''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, he said, the go-ahead was given by the office of
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani during the last few weeks. Parks
Commissioner Henry Stern declined comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Initially I was concerned about elephants and lions in the
park,'' said Washington, who explained his involvement by saying
that the approval was ``a parks function, and parks reports to
me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But when we learned that it would be geese, and horses, that
wasn't a problem,'' he said. ``We deal all the time with mounted
police.''
</P>
<P>
   Washington said that Big Apple ``shouldn't be upset,'' because
``it's not as if each show will have an audience of 20,000
people.'' He added, ``The audiences for each circus are so small
that everyone can do well, and help our economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Big Apple plays to 450,000 annual circusgoers in Damrosch Park,
paying several hundred thousand dollars a year to Lincoln Center
for the privilege. Big Apple estimates that it turns back a third
of its $19 million yearly budget to city community programs, health
institutions and charities. ``Any money that Feld takes out of our
box office,'' Binder said, ``is lost to the children and the
families of the city of New York.''
</P>
<P>
   For years Big Apple has done fund-raisers for city charities and
other nonprofits like Mount Sinai and Montefiore Hospitals. It runs
the Big Apple Circus Clown Care Unit, which sends 25 trained clowns
into seven city hospitals to perform for sick children.
</P>
<P>
   It teaches circus arts to inner-city schoolchildren and gives
free performances for blind and hearing impaired children and
donates 50,000 free tickets to poor children.
</P>
<P>
   Slifka, a principal at a Manhattan investment management firm,
contended that Ringling chose New York ``to cripple the Big Apple
Circus.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There are probably 50 other cities that Ringling could invade
that don't have not-for-profit circuses,'' he said. ``The only
reason for them to come at Christmastime is to compete with us.''
</P>
<P>
   But Feld said he chose the city because ``New York is the
ultimate goal of any entertainment attraction.'' He hopes it will
attract attention for future additional Ringling one-ring shows
intended to tour the United States and foreign countries.
</P>
<P>
   Ringling, however, has its own claim to New York tradition.
``Its three-ring circuses have played in Manhattan back into the
last century,'' said Greg Parkinson, a circus historian who is the
executive director of the Circus World Museum in Baraboo, Wis.,
``and there was P.T. Barnum's American Museum,'' a forerunner of
the Ringling show established in Lower Manhattan in 1842.
</P>
<P>
   The arrival of ``Kaleidoscape'' will be ``the first time that
Ringling has pitched a tent in Manhattan,'' Feld said, as the
Ringling show has for decades occupied Madison Square Garden in its
various incarnations. Big Apple bills itself as the city's original
tented circus, since of the 18 circuses that played New York before
its arrival, all performed in buildings.
</P>
<P>
   If Slifka termed the battle of the circuses David and Goliath,
Big Apple, which was founded in 1977, is hardly an impoverished
neophyte. It bolsters its $19 million budget with yearly tours to
nine cities including Atlanta, Boston, Chicago and Washington.
Nevertheless, Slifka said that Big Apple ``operates on a very tight
budget.''
</P>
<P>
   But Parkinson, the historian, said that in the winter season,
``Paris is able to support five competing circuses, which all seem
to do well.'' He added: ``I can understand Big Apple's sensitivity
to the arrival of another one-ring circus in New York, but a
competitive rivalry could lead to near-record sales for both
circuses. New York is a very big city.''
</P>
<P>
   If Feld brought ``Kaleidoscape'' to Manhattan in the spring, he
would be competing with his own three-ring extravaganza, scheduled
to return to Madison Square Garden next March 30.
</P>
<P>
   The holidays were ``the only time Bryant Park was available,''
Feld said, given the summer and fall fashion shows and the peak
occupancy by visitors during the summer, ``and it is the time of
year when people want to see things.''
</P>
<P>
   But Fuchs of Bryant Park Restoration said that ``for our
purposes they could come in during February,'' adding, ``we felt OK
about any time in the winter.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Kaleidoscape'' will feature David Larible, who was for years a
star clown of Ringling's three-ring performances, as well as Sylvia
Zerbini, who performs on the trapeze and with horses, and Alex
Petrov, a wire walker who balances a spangled lady atop his head on
a 12-foot pole.
</P>
<P>
   Ringling executives have confirmed that Feld spent $10 million
to start ``Kaleidoscape,'' but several circus marketing experts
said under the condition of anonymity that the company had spent
more than $20 million thus far on its one-ring venture without
turning an overall profit, partly because of the show's elaborate
sets and its luxury seating, which require transport by a
staggering 50 trucks.
</P>
<P>
   But Feld insisted that ``Kaleidoscape'' ``is going to be a major
profit center for this company.''
</P>
<P>
   And although Ringling has only a one-year contract to bring the
circus to Bryant Park, Feld said that ``Kaleidoscape'' hopes to
return ``year after year.''
</P>
</TEXT>
