<TEXT>
<P>
   Editors:
</P>
<P>
   TheStreet.com column for TUESDAY, AUGUST 8, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   THE KING OF SILICON VALLEY INVESTMENT BANKING, by Adam Lashinsky
</P>
<P>
   Talking with Frank Quattrone, the grand pooh-bah of Silicon
Valley investment banking, is a lot like shooting the breeze with
Oracle CEO Larry Ellison. Each has made gazillions on the
decade-long drunken orgy of Silicon Valley success, each is one of
the recognized leaders in his field with an ego to match, and each
is willing to speak his mind.
</P>
<P>
   Slugged BC-THESTREETCOM-LASHINSKY-NYTSF
</P>
<P>
   TheStreet.com column for MONDAY, AUGUST 7, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   NEWSPAPERS: THE NEXT DOT-COM BATTLEGROUND?, by James J. Cramer
</P>
<P>
   What do you do with a dot-com that is moving full-tilt toward an
IPO and the window closes? What do you do when you are spending a
ton of money to grow a business, confident that it will get a huge
valuation from the public market, only to find that it has no hope
of going public and the money is no longer there?
</P>
<P>
   That's where the newspaper chains of America find themselves.
They have produced these terrific dot-coms that have good reach and
lots of good demographics. They are Media Metrix winners. However,
they are huge money losers.
</P>
<P>
   There's a ton of private ``I told you sos'' going on in every
newsroom, believe me.
</P>
<P>
   Slugged BC-THESTREETCOM-CRAMER-NYTSF
</P>
<P>
   For info about daily commentary from TheStreet.com, call The New
York Times Syndicate at 1-888-269-8796.
</P>
