<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-BOMB-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOMBING IN DOWNTOWN MOSCOW KILLS AT LEAST 7, INJURES DOZENS 
</HEADLINE>
   (editors: this will be updated later)  
 By CHRISTOPHER S. WREN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   At least seven people were killed and dozens of others were
injured Tuesday when a bomb blew up inside a busy pedestrian
underpass during rush hour in downtown Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   No one immediately claimed responsibility for the bombing at
Pushkin Square, a popular intersection on Tverskaya St., only a few
blocks from Red Square and the Kremlin. But the police treated the
explosion as a terrorist act and flooded the area with
reinforcements, halting motor traffic above ground and checking
other underpasses for more bombs.
</P>
<P>
   Moscow's mayor, Yuri Luzhkov, expressed the suspicion, shared by
many other Russians, that Chechen separatists, who have set off
previous bombs, were to blame.
</P>
<P>
   ``The nature of the crime is obvious _ the explosion hit in a
place packed with people at rush hour,'' Luzhkov told reporters at
the scene.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick E. Tyler, The New York Times bureau chief in Moscow,
said that the bombing, following a weekend when Moscow was under a
state of emergency because of threats from Chechen separatists,
would have the same impact on Russians that terrorist bombings or
apartment buildings had last year. Those bombings galvanized
support for a new Russian military offensive in Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Moscow's pedestrians rely heavily on downtown underpasses like
that in Pushkin Square to avoid the chaotic vehicle traffic and to
gain entrance to the city subway system. The underpasses also
contain small shops and are frequented by private vendors,
musicians and panhandlers.
</P>
<P>
   Pushkin Square lies at the crossroads of three busy subway
lines. And with its distinct statue of the 19th century Russian
poet Alexander Pushkin, Pushkin Square engenders a special
reverence for many Russians, in addition to being a favorite
meeting place for families, friends and lovers. In the old Soviet
Union, dissidents gathered in the square for demonstrations.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Russian and Western news agencies and television news reports
underscored the carnage of Tuesday's bombing in downtown Moscow,
describing or showing dazed bleeding pedestrians in torn, sooty
clothes as they staggered or were carried out of the smoke-filled
tunnel. Some collapsed on the sidewalk while others wandered around
the square, searching for relatives or friends.
</P>
<P>
   Tyler, who went to Pushkin Square after the bombing, reported
that smoke was still billowing from the underpass as victims lay
injured and dying near the square. One commuter said she had been
knocked down by shock waves from the blast.
</P>
<P>
   Initial reports said that seven people were killed and more than
20 left wounded, but casualty toll of injured kept rising to more
than 30, and above 40.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian security forces had been put on alert to watch for
attacks by Chechen separatists marking the fourth anniversary of
the rebels' capture of their capital Grozny from the Russians.
</P>
<P>
   Grozny was largely demolished earlier this year when Russian
forces seized the capital in the latest round of warfare. The
Russian offensive was motivated in part by earlier bombings in
Russian cities that killed more than 300 civilians and turned many
Russians against the Chechens.
</P>
<P>
   The last big bombing ripped through an apartment complex in the
southern Russian town of Vologdansk last September, killing 18
people and wounding more than 200.
</P>
<P>
   The Interfax news agency reported Tuesday that President
Vladimir Putin had been informed about the bombing at Pushkin
Square by Interior Minister Vladimir Rushailo.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
