<SLUG> BC-TRIVIA-Q&AMP;A-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS TRIP IS WORTH THE PRICE OF THE T-SHIRT
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By ROGERS CADENHEAD 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: When something is far off, such as a car in a parking lot,
why do we say it is ``in Timbuktu''?
</P>
<P>
   _ B.S., Fort Worth
</P>
<P>
   A: There are several popular expressions about the Saharan
desert city in central Mali, including ``to Timbuktu and back'' and
``knock you clear to Timbuktu.''
</P>
<P>
   The city, which has a population of about 20,000 today, was once
one of the largest centers of commerce in Africa, positioned
between thriving salt and gold mines.
</P>
<P>
   In 1593, Timbuktu was sacked by invaders and faded from
prominence, becoming legendary for its remoteness. ``Timbuktu is
smack dab in the middle of desert surrounded by nothing except more
desert,'' according to the Epinions travel guide at
www.epinions.com. ``Getting there may be the best part of it (that,
and the T-shirt that reads, `I've been to Timbuktu and back
again').''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Can you still buy Clark bars?
</P>
<P>
   _ K.B., Arlington, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A: In Fort Worth-Dallas, some of the retailers who carry Clark
bars are Kroger, Rite Aid and Dollar General stores, according to
the manufacturer.
</P>
<P>
   The rights to the Clark bar have changed hands four times in 17
years. In May 1999, the New England Confectionery Company (NECCO)
purchased the assets of Clark Bar America and begin distributing
the product.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since purchasing the assets of Clark last spring, we have been
working to re-establish distribution of the Clark bar,'' NECCO
marketing assistant Joanna Forney said. ``In the next few months
you should be able to find Clark bars more easily.''
</P>
<P>
   The Florida retailer HomeTown Favorites sells more than 400
well-known but hard-to-find products, including Clark bars, Oh
Henry bars, Squirrel Nut Chews, Teaberry Gum and Wonka Bottlecaps.
To order, call (888) 694-2656 or visit www.hometownfavorites.com.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where can I write to the singer Bonnie Raitt?
</P>
<P>
   _ A.M., via the Internet
</P>
<P>
   A: Write to Raitt in care of Monterey Pennisula Artists, 509
Hartnell St., Monterey, CA 93940.
</P>
<P>
   Raitt, 50, was inducted in March into the Rock and Roll Hall of
Fame. ``It doesn't seem like I've been famous long enough to
deserve this,'' said Raitt, whose first big commercial success was
the 1989 album ``Nick of Time,'' which won four Grammy awards.
</P>
<P>
   The singer and songwriter is also raising funds for the Rhythm &AMP;
Blues Foundation, a nonprofit group that offers financial support
and recognition for musicians of the '40s, '50s and '60s.
</P>
<P>
   For more information, write to Rhythm and Blues Foundation, 1555
Connecticut Ave. NW, No. 401, Washington, D.C. 20036-1111 or visit
www.bonnieraitt.com/randb.html.
</P>
<P>
   (Rogers Cadenhead writes a trivia column for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. He can be reached at the Star-Telegram, Box 1870,
Fort Worth, Texas 76101; or by E-mail at trivia(at)prefect.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-08-00 1624EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
