<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 16:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5932 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a k BC-LEASE-COLUMN-NYTR &LR;      08-08 0768
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEASE-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WE'VE GOT A NEW BARREL OF TOBACCO-INDUSTRY WHOPPERS
</HEADLINE>
  By DARYL LEASE   
 Herald-Tribune, Sarasota, Fla.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   Bemoaning the sins of the tobacco
industry these days is kind of like shooting smelly, rotten,
stone-cold fish in a barrel. It doesn't seem terribly sporting, and
about the only thing you get when you fire off a new round is more
fish goo on your shoes.
<TEXT>
<P>
   But just when it looks like it's time to put a lid on the barrel
and move on, something else emerges about the tobacco industry that
sets the ol' fishing-finger to itching again.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, for example, the World Health Organization released a
255-page report detailing the tobacco industry's secret, slimy
efforts to sabotage the U.N. agency's anti-smoking programs in
developing countries. The report relies on a variety of sources,
including industry documents made public as part of recent
lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   Tobacco company memos are notoriously weird, but even by those
standards, these particular ditties make for bizarre and
entertaining reading. As I perused the WHO report online at
www.who.int/toh, I kept picturing Philip Morris chairman Geoffrey
Bible smashing a bass guitar at a stockholders meeting and singing,
``Talking 'bout my d-d-degeneration ...''
</P>
<P>
   One chapter focuses on a meeting Bible and fellow Philip Morris
muckety-mucks held in Florida in 1988. The Boca Raton Action Plan,
as their chat became known, specifically targeted the WHO. Among
other things, the executives discussed efforts to ``discredit key
individuals'' in WHO; lobby journalists to question the WHO budget
and its focus on smoking; and submit anti-WHO columns to newspapers
without revealing that the authors had financial ties to the
tobacco industry.
</P>
<P>
   The WHO report also details industry efforts to set up bogus
``grass-roots'' groups to spread disinformation about smoking; slip
``consultants'' into WHO headquarters to sit in on meetings and
sneak out confidential documents; and disrupt WHO-sponsored events.
</P>
<P>
   The latter idea makes for especially entertaining reading. The
industry had particularly high hopes for wrecking the
clunkily-named 8th World Conference on Tobacco OR Health in Buenos
Aires in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   The report quotes from memos in which tobacco officials talked
about training hand-picked reporters to dominate press conferences
with tobacco-friendly questions. ``We must teach (the journalists)
how to be pushy and press the speakers aggressively,'' says the
memo. (Teach a journalist to be pushy? Great idea, and let's
schedule fish for swimming lessons while we're at it!)
</P>
<P>
   Tobacco officials also talked about having ``selected
reporters'' question Ted Kennedy, a conference attendee, about
``his alcohol dependence and highlight the sexual harassing blamed
on him in the USA, thus reducing the importance of his presence.''
</P>
<P>
   Somebody also dreamed up the idea of staging an international
soccer match on the day former President Jimmy Carter was scheduled
to arrive at the conference. Soccer is big in developing countries,
the reasoning went, and everyone would ignore Carter.
</P>
<P>
   The report says it's not clear how many of these wiggy plans
were actually implemented, but some _ like the bogus grass-roots
groups _ definitely materialized.
</P>
<P>
   The foreign market was, and still is, essential to the
industry's survival. As The Washington Post recently noted, the
adult smoking rate in our country plummeted from 40 percent in 1964
to 23 percent in 1997. The rate in developing countries, meanwhile,
is going up 3 percent a year. The yearly death toll is expected to
hit 10 million worldwide by 2030 or sooner _ with two-thirds of the
deaths in Third World countries.
</P>
<P>
   Think tobacco companies are doing anything, anything at all, to
discourage it? Think they've given up on the ``Look, everybody,
Teddy's a drunken womanizer!'' tactics?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe if we listen to the WHO, we won't get fooled again. I'm
not buying the tobacco companies' slick TV commercials claiming
they've put their degenerate days behind them. I'm not won over by
the sight of industry executives crying puddles over their alleged
poverty. (Poor? Philip Morris has given more than $600,000 to the
GOP alone since 1999, making it the party's single largest
corporate donor.)
</P>
<P>
   I don't know about you, but I'd rather the tobacco companies put
a lid on it. My fishing-finger is tired.
</P>
<P>
   (Daryl Lease is a columnist for the Herald-Tribune in Sarasota,
Fla. Contact him at daryl.lease(AT)herald-trib.com.The
Herald-Tribune is a member of the New York Times Regional
Newspapers.)
</P>
</TEXT>
