<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
the Page 1 of Wednesday, Aug. 9. The N.Y. Times News Service night
supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-BOMB (Moscow) _ A bomb exploded in a pedestrian underpass
at Pushkin Square in the center of Moscow at the height of
rush-hour Tuesday evening killing eight, seriously injuring eleven
and sending dozens of people fleeing smoke and flames that scorched
the large underground plaza. Moscow Mayor Yuri Luzhkov described
the explosion as a ``terrorist act,'' and appealed to Muscovites to
redouble their vigilance after a weekend in which the city had
declared a state of emergency to guard against terrorist attacks
threatened by rebel leaders in Chechnya on the anniversary of their
uprising year ago. No organization claimed responsibility for
setting the bomb. By Patrick E. Tyler.
</P>
<P>
   CHILE-PINOCHET (Santiago, Chile) _ The Chilean Supreme Court
officially ruled Tuesday to divest Gen. Augusto Pinochet of his
senatorial immunity, removing a giant legal hurdle for the possible
arrest and trial of the former dictator on charges that he was
involved in the kidnapping, torture and murder of thousands of
people during his 17 years in power. By Clifford Krauss.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   WEST-FIRES (Hamilton, Mont.) _ At the scene of the worst of
scores of forest fires around the country. With feeds from
California and Colorado. By Ross E. Milloy.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
