<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXASATLARGE-CHAPMAN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PADRE ISLAND VERDICT CASE REMINDER OF FORGOTTEN HISTORY
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By ART CHAPMAN 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Anglicized history of the Texas Rio Grande Valley too often
begins with the 1846-48 Mexican War, when U.S. troops massed along
the river and built what eventually became Brownsville.
</P>
<P>
   The incomplete history ignores a proud culture that prevailed
before the Army wrestled the ``Wild Horse Desert' '_ the land
between the Rio Grande and the Nueces River _ away from Mexico.
Native Americans are forgotten, as are the Spanish, who began their
settlements there in the 1750s.
</P>
<P>
   Ignored are the enormous cattle ranches that were formed north
of the Rio Grande and the strong and unique culture that had been
created by the 1800s. Proud hidalgos, the frontier noblemen, raised
their families with a love of tradition that evolved from Spanish
to Mexican to eventually Tejano. These families held millions of
acres.
</P>
<P>
   But those acres and that history were lost in the transition
from Mexico to Texas to the United States. Latter-day scholars call
it the ``gran despojo,'' or great robbery.
</P>
<P>
   That's what the recent Balli suit in Brownsville was all about:
ignoring history, stealing land.
</P>
<P>
   The case pitted the heirs of Padre Nicolas Balli, who was given
a Spanish land grant for Padre Island in the 18th century, against
90-year-old New York lawyer Gilbert Kerlin. Kerlin bought the
island from the Balli heirs in 1938, and agreed to pay the family a
share of any oil or gas discovered beneath the tropical beaches.
</P>
<P>
   Oil wells were established, but the family never received the
promised royalties. Kerlin contended that the Ballis didn't really
own the property at the time of the sale, and essentially all
agreements with them were off.
</P>
<P>
   An all-Hispanic jury in a state district court sided with the
Balli heirs.
</P>
<P>
   The Balli family, ranging from 300 to 500 descendants in this
litigation, never demanded that they get the island back. They only
asked for the unpaid oil and gas royalties agreed upon.
</P>
<P>
   ``And most of all, they want the record to reflect _ as it
should for all South Texas Mexicans and Mexican-Americans _ that,
unlike U.S. history would have it, we once were somebodies,'' wrote
Cecilia Balli, a family member and a reporter for the San Antonio
Express-News.
</P>
<P>
   She acknowledges that the Ballis and other Mexican landed
families colonized the area's native and nomadic Indians, and that
they built their own classist and racist society that
discriminated, based on gender, birth and skin color.
</P>
<P>
   But Balli, who was not part of the suit, went on to write: ``The
underlying resentment is that the arriving Americans, who at first
adopted Mexican customs and intermarried the Mexican daughters,
later would end up with all that land by sale, coercion or
manipulation of the law.
</P>
<P>
   ``And that in the larger U.S. imagination _ after all the wars
that changed South Texas' identity from Spanish, to Mexican, to
Texan, to American _ we somehow would forget about the rich life
that already was.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ballis won't get rich again from their settlement. The money
is huge, but so, too, is the list of people among whom it must be
divided. But the Ballis have become empowered.
</P>
<P>
   In a similar but unrelated suit, another Balli line of heirs
seeks compensation from the famed Kenedy Ranch, which they say has
leased more than 300,000 acres from the Balli family for the past
140 years. The Balli family says it is owed oil and gas revenues
from the lease.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation that runs the ranch says it bought the land
outright and owes the family nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Once again the courts will decide. But the course may already be
set.
</P>
<P>
   One attorney called the earlier decision a ``a wake-up call for
those who for years have denied the claims of land grant heirs.''
</P>
<P>
   For those who have ignored history.
</P>
<P>
   (Art Chapman writes a weekly column on things Texan. You can
call him at (817) 390-7422, or e-mail: artc(at)star-telegram.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
