<HEADER>
A5937 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-CHEF-DUCASSE-2TAKES-N     08-08 1295
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHEF-DUCASSE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIXED WELCOME GREETS DUCASSE 
</HEADLINE>
   By MARIAN BURROS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The transition has been stunning and fast. Seven
weeks ago, Alain Ducasse was France's gift to New York, a chef with
eight Michelin stars, opening the ultimate in luxurious
restaurants. The anticipation surrounding the restaurant, Alain
Ducasse at the Essex House, had it booked for months, and had
produced a six-month waiting list with 2,700 names.
</P>
<P>
   Then the doors opened, and everything seemed to go wrong.
</P>
<P>
   The food world buzzed about the disappointing cooking and the
absentee chef. Endless stories mocked the $500 tabs, the wine list
with some bottles marked up 1,000 percent, and the pompous
dining-room rituals like the presentation of a selection of knives
with every squab and a choice of expensive pens for signing the
check. The coverage went from bad to worse, hitting bottom with an
article in Fortune magazine headlined ``Ishtar: The Restaurant.''
The restaurant took out a classified ad seeking employees a couple
of weeks after opening, amid rumors that waiters were quitting
because of paychecks that were slow in coming and tips that were
minuscule.
</P>
<P>
   All of a sudden, it was possible to book a table for the very
next day.
</P>
<P>
   A two-page cartoon in The New Yorker titled ``A Cancellation at
Alain Ducasse'' subtly belittled the place for its pretensions. The
review in The New York Post was scathing. William Grimes, the
restaurant critic of The New York Times, wondered in a column about
an evening at the restaurant, ``Would I ever lay eyes on Ducasse?''
</P>
<P>
   The Guardian in London weighed in 10 days after the restaurant
opened asking why the first New Yorkers to try it ``say it's only
`OK''' The Daily Telegraph of London asked if ``the opening of
Ducasse will prove to have been an important cultural watershed,
marking the beginning of the end of the cult of celebrity chef.''
Within the last week, New York magazine and U.S.A. Today concluded
that, for the price, the place falls short.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Ducasse's good notices have appeared either in fringe
publications or have not been reviews of the food.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't the welcome expected by Ducasse, who was interviewed
through an interpreter about his New York reception. He is the only
chef in the world with two Michelin three-star restaurants _ one in
Paris, one in Monte Carlo _ plus two one-star restaurants scattered
among his other 10.
</P>
<P>
   A decade ago, at the age of 33, he was the youngest chef to be
awarded three stars. But even in Paris, he said, he initially faced
the same sort of bad press when he opened, in 1986. In New York, he
said, ``perhaps it is a little surprising how aggressive it is.''
And he added that ``if people will not accept this price, we will
go elsewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Andre Soltner, who was famous for not leaving the stove in his
four-star restaurant, Lutece, said that if Ducasse talked in this
way ``he's kaput, because New Yorkers don't have to accept that.''
</P>
<P>
   Soltner, who sold the restaurant five years ago, was interviewed
by telephone from France, where he is on vacation. ``When people
spend $300 or $400 for a meal they want you to be there,'' he said.
``They want you to cook a little. They want a little personal
attention and they want the food to be perfect. If New Yorkers
think they are being taken for a ride, then Ducasse will have
problems. If the food is not as good as about 20 restaurants in New
York then he will have to pack up and leave.''
</P>
<P>
   Soltner has not eaten at the restaurant yet, he said, because he
wanted to give it a chance to settle in. Something the 2,700 people
whom the restaurant said were on the waiting list were not willing
to do.
</P>
<P>
   The claim that it is booked until December is apparently highly
inflated. In fact, using several names that would be unknown to the
restaurant, on a recent Thursday I was able to book for the
following Monday; last Tuesday, I booked for dinner the next night;
last Wednesday, I booked for lunch the next day. There have been so
many no-shows that the restaurant now charges $150 to a credit card
when a table is booked.
</P>
<P>
   Others have reported the same experience. Michael Batterberry, a
co-founder of Food Arts magazine, who ate lunch there recently,
said six or seven of the 18 tables were empty, a situation other
diners at lunch have also reported.
</P>
<P>
   Empty tables only compound a problem that some waiters
complained about bitterly: with just 65 seats in the restaurant,
and only two lunches and five dinners a week, each with only one
seating, total tips can be lower than at a place that is open for
lunch and dinner and where the tables turn at least twice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figured that out myself,'' said one former waiter. He said
he left because he is an actor and wanted to be in Los Angeles. The
gratuity system at the restaurant rewards points to each dining
room employee depending on his job.
</P>
<P>
   But he added that if he were a professional waiter he would have
stayed there even though he could have earned more money elsewhere.
``It's a great place to work for a professional waiter because you
learn a lot,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Urs Kaufmann, the manager of the restaurant, said that some
staff members did quit in the first weeks, but that was common at a
new restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   Kaufmann acknowledged problems with the pay in the beginning,
but he said the restaurant was not fully booking nor was it serving
private parties for the first couple of weeks. Four servers are
assigned to four or five tables at each meal, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what their expectations were,'' Kaufmann said,
``but one waiter confronted me in front of the entire staff with an
absolutely ludicrous number. He said you can go and work at Jean
Georges and make $3,000 a week. I was left speechless, because that
is just rubbish.''
</P>
<P>
   But, Kaufmann said, there were so many complaints when the
paychecks turned out ``so much below everyone's expectations, we
quickly issued extra cash checks to ease the tension.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``If a large number of staff leave and we constantly
have to retrain staff, it costs so much time and effort and in the
long run we could never sustain that.''
</P>
<P>
   There might be another reason some of the waiters left: the
system of payment. At many restaurants, tips are distributed
nightly; at Ducasse tips are included in the paychecks, with taxes
withheld. ``I'm not sure they were used to this system,'' Kaufmann
said.
</P>
<P>
   Ducasse insists that giving diners the table for the entire
evening is essential to the mood of the restaurant and it is one of
the reasons he charges at least one-third more than the other top
restaurants here. The food, he said, is only part of the
experience. He said the chef doesn't need to be present all of the
time.
</P>
<P>
   ``The importance of the chef is to form a good team to function
without the chef being there,'' he said. He added that he had spent
a year teaching his kitchen staff technique, and that ``18 chefs in
the kitchen is sufficient for 65 covers.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, because of the criticism about his absence, Ducasse
says he is spending more time at the restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want to talk about price, you have to talk about what
you are getting,'' he said. ``The luxury of space and time. Our
guests are still sitting here at 11:30.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good service, even down to the details of the waiters' suits,
bread that is baked twice a day, organic flour that is imported
from South America, the best ingredients. The idea that we are
pretentious because we offer a selection of knives is ridiculous. I
don't know any other restaurant where they do that. Perhaps the
people who are writing that have only average knowledge of what
they were writing about.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  But it isn't only the critics who have failed to be overwhelmed
by the food. Many people who have eaten at the restaurant have been
disappointed, including some chefs who describe Ducasse as a
genius.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went once, but we're not going a second time,'' said Amy
Stein, a harpist who lives in Manhattan. ``The atmosphere was
fantastic. The food was very nice, but it didn't make me cry like
some restaurants in Paris do. You can go to other restaurants in
New York and have a great meal for less money.''
</P>
<P>
   Other reports mentioned blood in the foie gras and that the
pigeon was cooked medium when it should have been medium-rare.
</P>
<P>
   But Ducasse dismisses such criticism by suggesting that the
diners don't know what they are talking about. For example, there
have been numerous complaints about the toughness of the lobster in
the lobster ravioli. To that Ducasse said, ``A perfectly cooked
lobster is slightly rubbery.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The clientele in New York are capable of understanding what we
do,'' he continued. ``Mai oui. Bien sur. Bien sur.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that's the problem. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
