<SLUG> BC-TRASH-TALK-PRESIDENTS-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUBYA'S DADDY ADMITS `I WENT TOO FAR' IN THREATENING CLINTON  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary, Political Editors)   (This 475-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By MARY DEJEVSKY  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Former U.S. President George Bush conceded that he
went too far last week in threatening to say just what he thought
of his successor, Bill Clinton, ``as a human being and a person,''
if Clinton persisted with personalized attacks on his son.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made a mistake,'' Bush told Time magazine in an interview in
Monday's issue. ``I went too far.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush senior had been riled by a string of comments made by
Clinton at a fund-raising event in New England last week about his
son, the Republican presidential nominee.
</P>
<P>
   Mocking what he said was George W. Bush's rationale for his
presidential bid, Clinton said: ``How bad can I be? I've been
governor of Texas. My Daddy was president. I own a baseball team.
Their fraternity had it for eight years, give it to ours for eight
years.''
</P>
<P>
   The ridicule of George W. drew howls of laughter from Democrats
and admiration from political pundits, who saw in Clinton's ability
to sum up George W. Bush weaknesses so succinctly still more proof
of his political genius.
</P>
<P>
   The pact of Clinton's attack was only reinforced when George
Bush senior took it upon himself to respond on his son's behalf.
</P>
<P>
   Asked by a television interview to react to the president's
remarks, Bush swallowed the bait and said that he would give
Clinton one month and if he had not ceased his attacks, he would
tell the same reporter exactly what he thought of Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   His son was far more careful, refusing initially to comment, and
then remarking: ``It's amazing to me that the president of the
United States would spend time trying to be a political pundit.''
</P>
<P>
   The former president's threat raised eyebrows on two counts. Not
only would any attack on Clinton breach the convention that former
presidents do not attack incumbent presidents; it also sent the
message that George W. Bush was a ``Daddy's boy,'' incapable of
fighting his own battles.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's mother, former first lady, Barbara, has also come close
to attacking Clinton on her son's behalf, reportedly drawing a
rebuke from her son.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush parents' defensive intervention before the New
Hampshire primary was seen as one factor in their son's loss in
that state to John McCain, and their role in the campaign was
scaled down thereafter.
</P>
<P>
   While the ``daddy's boy'' charge will remain potentially
damaging for George W. Bush, any sustained attacks by Clinton on
Bush risk exposing Vice President Al Gore, to the charge that he is
not his own man.
</P>
<P>
   One telling cartoon depicted the small figures of George W. and
Al Gore slugging it out in a boxing ring, while gigantic depictions
of the current and former presidents yelled exhortations to their
surrogates on from opposite corners. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 475-word article from THE INDEPENDENT newspaper in
London, it must be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's
sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is weyded(at)nytimes.com. If
unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at
816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
