<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 16:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5942 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-OLYMPICS-EMERGINGSTAR     08-08 0814
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLYMPICS-EMERGINGSTARS-1000(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HYPE HOPES: WHICH OLYMPIC ATHLETES WILL VAULT FROM SPORTS TO FAME?
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By ROBERT PHILPOT 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Amy Acuff, one of America's top Olympic hopefuls, is in midleap,
blond hair and muscular legs thrown back, eyes squeezed shut in
concentration, arms outspread.
</P>
<P>
   But something isn't quite right. For one thing, the top-ranked
high jumper is wearing a black leather bikini instead of a track
suit. And instead of the gritty sports realism one often sees in
Sports Illustrated photographs, the image is charged with the
unmistakable sexuality typical of cheesecake shots of starlets.
</P>
<P>
   Which was exactly the intention. The photo is the August cover _
one of three covers, actually _ of Esquire magazine, which
celebrates 10 of this year's female Summer Olympics hopefuls.
Esquire's not dishonest about its intentions: The cover line is
``Strength &AMP; Beauty _ a portfolio of America's 10 sexiest
athletes.'' And the magazine does at least give lip service to the
sporting abilities of Acuff, triathlete Lokelani McMichael and
pentathlete Mary Beth Larsen, as well as the seven other women
athletes in the magazine who don't grace one of the ``collector's
covers'' of the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Such photo spreads are an increasingly common part of the
Olympics hype machine, and some athletes might even hope these
efforts will arouse the interest of a Hollywood talent hunter or
two. After all, these women are about to get national prime-time
television exposure, and as the careers of Jenny McCarthy, Carmen
Electra and other untrained actresses prove, that's half the
battle.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's probably that rare athlete in Sydney or in Salt Lake
City who will cross over'' to a TV or movie career, says U.S.
Olympic Committee spokesman Mike Moran. ``TV is huge, and with that
kind of close-up look at them and their faces and their
personalities, they may get crossover appeal.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that Hollywood stardom is what these athletes necessarily
have in mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never been interested in acting,'' Acuff says via e-mail.
``I'd rather live my life than pretend to live other people's
lives. I'm convinced it's not as glamorous as it seems because many
actors dream about being famous recording artists or sports
stars.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, few Olympic athletes who have crossed the street to
Hollywood's dream factory have much to show for it. Swimmer Johnny
Weissmuller, still the most famous Tarzan of the movies, had a
seven-film career, but in only one _ the 1946 B-movie ``Swamp
Fire'' _ did he stretch beyond his signature King of the Jungle
role. Figure skater Sonja Henie, who competed in three Olympics in
the '20s and '30s, appeared in a series of inconsequential musicals
in the '30s and '40s and is largely forgotten today. To name a few
recent examples, 1976 decathlete Bruce Jenner appeared in the 1980
Village People romp ``Can't Stop the Music'' (as well as the TV cop
show ``CHiPs''), and gymnast Mitch Gaylord starred in a virtually
unwatchable 1986 bomb called ``American Anthem,'' before being
relegated to straight-to-video pictures.
</P>
<P>
   ``My suspicion is that there are some Olympians who have visions
of movie careers,'' says Todd Thaler, a casting director who has
worked on such movies as Sylvester Stallone's ``Cop Land'' and
Barbra Streisand's ``The Mirror Has Two Faces.'' ``But I can't say
that I watch the Olympics with an eye toward who has crossover
potential. ... I always have an eye toward who's the hot new
property, but it's more likely that I'd find them through a talent
show at a conservatory training program.''
</P>
<P>
   So why do athletes like Acuff, who deny an interest in
Hollywood, play the glamour vamp for national magazines? That's
easy, she says: to raise awareness of her sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard for most people to remember in detail something that
happens only (every) four years in the span of 16 days,'' Acuff
says of the Olympics. ``It seems like El Nino comes to the U.S.
more often than track-and-field coverage.''
</P>
<P>
   So, with the days of amateur, part-time athletics gone forever,
Olympians sometimes go to great lengths to get our attention _ and
sponsors. They employ makeup artists and image consultants and go
all out in colorful, form-fitting outfits that look like they've
come straight from the Milan fashion runways.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the change in dress and style is not only a result of
economics, but also of a change in attitudes.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty years ago, says Moran, when the Olympics was a
battleground for Cold War ideologies, people thought differently
about the Games. The Olympics was front-line work for the greater
democratic good, and athletes dressed and acted accordingly. Now
the quadrennial event is marketed and packaged almost purely as
entertainment, and the athletes have evolved with the times.
</P>
<P>
   MORE nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-08-00 1636EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
