<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 16:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5944 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-NJ-BLUEBERRIES-ART-2N     08-08 1424
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-BLUEBERRIES-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 HAMMONTON, N.J.: and birds.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Most of the fresh berries Worrell sells are picked by hand,
because they command a better price. Machine harvesters, both the
deluxe, Zamboni-like model and the smaller kind towed by a tractor,
are boxy contraptions that straddle the bushes, brushing berries
off with spring-loaded feelers. The berries collect in a trough,
and a conveyor deposits them in a bin.
</P>
<P>
   The machines, though, are rougher on the berries and
significantly less picky than the pickers. Machine-harvested
berries are most often sold to companies like Ocean Spray to be
made into purees, syrups and juices.
</P>
<P>
   Even the most subtle flaw in a crop, the presence of a green
berry in a pint, or a faintly darker cast to the lot, will
influence the price. Blueberries are moderately perishable;
handpicked at the perfect moment of firm ripeness, they will keep
10 to 15 days if refrigerated. (They also freeze extremely well.)
</P>
<P>
   The Tru-Blu Cooperative is the first test of a farmer's product.
On a radiant Sunday afternoon, a steady stream of trucks laden with
tall pallets of blueberries pulled up to the cinder-block storage
shed and loading dock in New Lisbon. Sheri Sansone, who manages the
operation in season, drove a forklift, hoisting pallets of berries
from the trucks onto the dock, to be ferried to the walk-in cooler
to chill before pickup the next morning.
</P>
<P>
   When she wasn't on the forklift, Sansone was on the phone,
fielding calls from buyers for supermarkets and cajoling growers to
harvest more berries. In her role as the Tru-Blu inspector, she
picked through a pallet of pint containers and removed a
picture-perfect sample: rotund berries with taut skins and perfect
bloom, the powdery, silvery appearance of a blueberry still on the
bush.
</P>
<P>
   For all the domestic demand for blueberries, a market is
building overseas. The bilberry, a close relative to the blueberry,
is native to France and parts of Europe, but so far New Jersey
berries are not big sellers there. In Japan, they are used to make
jelly candies and other treats, packaged to appeal to children and
teen-agers. Korea and China are also starting to buy blueberries.
</P>
<P>
   Growers in New Jersey are keen to open new markets, because
every year seems to find new competition, both from large growers
in the United States and from Central America. In the last 20
years, varieties of blueberry have been developed that are suited
to the hotter climates of southern states like Florida and North
Carolina, which now produce millions of pounds of fruit.
</P>
<P>
   But at least for the moment, blueberries are doing well, helped
by a 1996 study by the Department of Agriculture at the Human
Nutrition Research Center on Aging at Tufts University, which
ranked 40 fruits and vegetables for antioxidant properties, which
are said to mitigate the effects of aging on the body. The study
put blueberries on top, with blackberries, kale and garlic
following. The findings were well publicized last year and led to
what has been a recognizable, if not dramatic, uptick in blueberry
sales.
</P>
<P>
   But in the end, what makes blueberries irresistible is their
taste. A fistful of fresh berries might be the most expedient way
to experience them, but cooking with them, for those who can defer
gratification, can intensify their flavor. Heating blueberries
moderately with a little water and sugar makes a simple, versatile
sauce. After a few minutes on the flame, the berries redden and
liquefy, reducing to a vivid blueberry concentrate, delicious
drizzled over vanilla ice cream or a pound cake. The syrup keeps
for several days in the refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   Although they are frequently combined with other berries in
baked desserts, prefer to keep blueberries to themselves, to avoid
outflanking them with an assertive strawberry or raspberry flavor.
Lemon, lime and cinnamon, used sparingly, can complement and
enhance the natural essence of blueberry. Or toss a cinnamon stick
or even a bay leaf (a distant cousin of the blueberry) into the
simmering sauce to add complexity.
</P>
<P>
   But always, be careful not to oversweeten blueberry desserts,
which too many cooks do. Go easy on the sugar and instead, add more
blueberries. A handful more never hurt a recipe. And it just might
help you live longer.
</P>
<P>
   BLUEBERRY-BANANA PANCAKES
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from ``The Black Dog Summer on the Vineyard Cookbook,'' &QL; 
by Joe Hall and Elaine Sullivan (Little, Brown &AMP; Co., 2000)
</P>
<P>
   Time: 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   1{ cup unbleached all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   { buckwheat flour
</P>
<P>
   { cup whole wheat flour
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons cornmeal
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons sugar
</P>
<P>
   2{ teaspoons baking powder
</P>
<P>
   } teaspoon baking soda
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   3 teaspoons cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   4 eggs
</P>
<P>
   2{ cups whole milk
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons unsalted butter, melted
</P>
<P>
   1 pint fresh blueberries
</P>
<P>
   1 thinly sliced banana
</P>
<P>
   1. Mix dry ingredients together in a medium sized bowl. In a
separate bowl, beat eggs with 2{ cups milk and the melted butter.
</P>
<P>
   2. Add wet mixture to dry ingredients and mix gently with a
wooden spoon. Add additional milk if mixture is too thick. Gently
fold in blueberries.
</P>
<P>
   3. Heat a griddle, adding a small pat of butter. Ladle batter
onto hot griddle and place three or four slices of banana on each
pancake. Cook until tops are dimpled with tiny bubbles, then flip
and finish cooking for a minute longer. Serve with butter and maple
syrup.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 6 servings.
</P>
<P>
   BLUEBERRY SHRUB
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from ``American Home Cooking,'' by Cheryl Alters
Jamison &QL; 
and Bill Jamison (Broadway Books, 1999)
</P>
<P>
   Time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   2 pints blueberries, rinsed and de-stemmed
</P>
<P>
   1{ cups sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 cup brandy
</P>
<P>
   Lemon wedges
</P>
<P>
   Mint sprigs.
</P>
<P>
   1. Combine blueberries and sugar in a saucepan with one-third
cup water. Cook at a low simmer for 5 minutes, stirring
occasionally, until blueberries are very soft. Strain juice through
a fine sieve into a pitcher (or using a funnel, into a clean, empty
wine bottle). Press gently with the back of a spoon to release all
juice from berries. (If desired, pass juice through a cheesecloth
to remove seeds.) Add brandy to pitcher or bottle, and refrigerate.
Shrub will keep for several weeks.
</P>
<P>
   2. To serve, fill a tall glass with ice. Then fill it halfway
with cold water or sparkling water. Top off glass with shrub, and
garnish with a mint sprig and a lemon wedge.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 6 servings.
</P>
<P>
   ORANGE SOUR CREAM CAKE WITH BLUEBERRY COMPOTE
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from March
</P>
<P>
   Time: 45 minutes plus cooling time
</P>
<P>
   For the cake: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1{ cups sifted cake flour
</P>
<P>
   } cups sugar
</P>
<P>
   } teaspoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   \ teaspoon baking soda
</P>
<P>
   Grated rind of 1 orange
</P>
<P>
   Pinch of salt
</P>
<P>
   4{ ounces (9 tablespoons) butter, at room temperature
</P>
<P>
   { cup sour cream
</P>
<P>
   3 large egg yolks
</P>
<P>
   { teaspoon orange extract
</P>
<P>
   { teaspoon vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   Nonstick vegetable oil spray
</P>
<P>
   For the compote: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   \ cup lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon cornstarch
</P>
<P>
   { cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 pints (8 cups) fresh blueberries, washed and dried
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon elderberry essence, optional (see note)
</P>
<P>
   Pinch of salt.
</P>
<P>
   1. To prepare the cake: Preheat oven to 350 degrees. In bowl of
a mixer with a paddle attachment, combine flour, sugar, baking
powder, baking soda, orange rind and salt. Cut butter into small
pieces and add to bowl. Mix at low speed until crumbly.
</P>
<P>
   2. Add \ cup sour cream. Mix at medium speed until smooth and
paste-like. Scrape bowl and add remaining \ cup sour cream and egg
yolks. Beat at high speed for 1 minute. Scrape bowl and add orange
extract and vanilla extract. Beat at high speed until light and
fluffy, about 1 more minute.
</P>
<P>
   3. Coat bottom and sides of an 8-inch cake pan with nonstick
spray. Scrape batter into pan and smooth with a spatula. Bake until
top is golden brown and a toothpick inserted in center of cake
comes out clean, about 30 minutes. Remove from oven. Cool.
</P>
<P>
   4. To prepare compote: In a medium glass, enameled or other
nonreactive saucepan, combine lemon juice, cornstarch and sugar.
Mix until smooth. Add blueberries, vanilla extract, elderberry
essence and salt. Stir gently to mix. Place over medium-low heat
and simmer just until liquid thickens and blueberries darken in
color. Remove from heat and transfer to a bowl.
</P>
<P>
   5. To serve, remove cake from pan. Slice and serve topped with
blueberry compote.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 6 to 8 servings.
</P>
<P>
   Note: A four-ounce bottle is $12 from European Connections,
(877) 866-5544.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
