<HEADER>
A5945 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-OLYMPICS-EMERGINGSTAR     08-08 0804
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLYMPICS-EMERGINGSTARS-2ndTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
 UNDATED: with the times. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Athletes today are ``more informed about our culture,'' Moran
says. ``They're more willing to pose for things, do things that
they wouldn't do 10 or 20 years ago. Most of our marquee athletes
have agents now. I think it's simply reflective of a media culture
all over; they're just a different athlete because of it.''
</P>
<P>
   And the media _ and fans _ respond to them in kind. Esquire
wasn't the only lifestyle magazine to do an Olympics spread this
summer. GQ did a fashion shoot featuring Olympians of both genders.
Men's Journal also weighed in, though it actually treated them as
athletes, writing about the Olympics' most pitched rivalries. Maxim
reportedly also has an Olympics-themed spread in the works, but
given the magazine's penchant for scantily clad celebrities, don't
expect it to maximize coverage of the players' athletic talents.
</P>
<P>
   We're talking almost exclusively U.S. Olympians here, by the
way. But the flood of lifestyle-magazine coverage isn't inspired by
a burst of patriotic fervor _ or by Olympics fervor, for that
matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not particularly excited about the Olympics,'' says David
Granger, Esquire's editor in chief. ``I do think it's sort of a
golden age of the female athlete, and that's caused by all the
obvious things _ the women's World Cup team and the dawn of the
WNBA _ but I can't say that I'm all that excited about these
athletes because they're in the Olympics. I just think we're in a
really interesting time as far as the image of the woman athlete
goes.''
</P>
<P>
   Granger says that he began considering doing a feature on the
Olympics as early as April but didn't decide to make it the cover
story until he saw the strength of the photos _ particularly that
of pentathlete Larsen, which depicts her on horseback, decked out
in jeans and sports bra, scowling in front of a stormy sky as if
she were a Valkyrie.
</P>
<P>
   Like Larsen, all the women in the layout have the poise and
pouts of professional models, which for many is a better fit than
acting. Swimmer Ashley Tappin and surfer Malia Jones have done some
professional modeling, as has Acuff, who plays it down as a
necessary evil.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have done some modeling in Los Angeles, where I now live,
but this is mainly for professional income,'' she says. ``Rent is
expensive here. Unless you're Maurice Green or Marion Jones, track
and field is not a lucrative sport, and to make any money in my
event, it's imperative that I stay in the top five in the world and
win some key meets. With a little injury, suddenly an athlete is
making $0.''
</P>
<P>
   Such concerns can lead an athlete far afield, especially if
they're far from shy. Last year, Acuff posed, along with 11 other
members of the U.S. track-and-field team, for a 2000 pin-up
calendar; Acuff was Miss July, naked save for red-white-and-blue
paint. She has also appeared on the ``Today'' show and ``The
Tonight Show With Jay Leno,'' where she high-jumped over a variety
of objects, including a bar festooned with her favorite weakness _
Krispy Kreme doughnuts.
</P>
<P>
   She even has a Web site, www.amyacuff.com, but then so do many
of her fellow athletes; the Internet is even more of a presence for
this year's Olympics than it was as recently as the 1998 Winter
Games. Basketball contender (and WNBA athlete) DeLisha Milton also
has a Web site, www.delishamilton.com. Tappin, Marion Jones and
Michael Johnson are among those who have sites under construction.
</P>
<P>
   These celebrity trappings, some athletes have found, cut both
ways. It can be disconcerting when they're no longer sure if the
attention they receive comes from their athletic accomplishments or
from performing stunts for Jay Leno, though Acuff says she finds
positive uses for her fame regardless.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do get embarrassed when I'm in the grocery store in my
hometown and someone stops to praise me, because I don't know how
to respond except to say `Thank you,''' she says. ``That's about
the biggest level of celebrity I've experienced to date.
Ultimately, I think the best thing about having a degree of
celebrity is that it can allow people to be a voice for those who
aren't being heard, to help people in need, or to inspire people.
That's the most attractive element.''
</P>
<P>
   Moran, however, says that the pursuit of fame as an end unto
itself increasingly motivates Olympians in today's media-dominated
world, and that trend is likely to continue.
</P>
<P>
   ``The athletes,'' he says, ``clearly understand, after they hit
the elite level now, that there's a lucrative lifestyle out
there.''
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is an entertainment critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7872, or e-mail:
robp(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
