<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; ATTENTION EDITORS: &LR;  The following is the budget for the New
Scientist for material available the week of MON., AUG. 7, 2000,
and anytime thereafter. This material is free for use for New York
Times News Service clients. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DRY-MARTIAN-FLOODS-NEW-SCIENTIST-NYTSF &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DRY FLOODS ON MARS
</P>
<P>
   The giant canyons on Mars may not have been carved by water, as
most scientists believe. According to an Australian geologist, the
canyons were formed by flows of gas, ash and rubble from erupting
volcanoes. If he's right, life on Mars may never have had a chance
to evolve.
</P>
<P>
   BC-HUMAN-ORIGINS-SANS-EVE-NEW-SCIENTIST-NYTSF &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MIXED ORIGINS
</P>
<P>
   Eve is dead, say Michigan paleontologists. Their analysis of an
Australian hominid fossil overturns the hypothesis that all modern
humans are descended from a hypothetical African ``Eve,'' who
completely replaced Homo erectus. The researchers believe that
modern humans are the product of worldwide gene flow between
ancient hominids.
</P>
<P>
   KILLER-PARTICLES-NEW-SCIENTIST-NYTSF &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   HOLD YOUR BREATH
</P>
<P>
   A fresh analysis of a classic pollution study has confirmed its
original conclusion that city-dwellers in Europe and the US are
dying young because of microscopic particles in the air. This time
the US study controlled for factors such as education, poverty, and
health care.
</P>
<P>
   QUAKE-PROOF-STUCCO-NEW-SCIENTIST-NYTSF &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   COULD STICKY STUCCO QUASH QUAKE DAMAGE?
</P>
<P>
   Scientists think they know why so many houses in California
remain standing after an earthquake. An outer layer of stucco, a
water-resistant coating commonly used on many of the houses in the
State helps the buildings stick together, preventing damage during
earthquakes.
</P>
</TEXT>
