<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CELEBRITYSKEWERING-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CELEBRITY SKINNED: NEW BOOK SKEWERS THE CULTURE OF FAME
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By JEFF GUINN 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As a screenwriter and free-lance journalist whose work has
appeared in publications ranging from Salon to the San Francisco
Examiner, 32-year-old Cintra Wilson has met enough famous people to
conclude there's something wrong with most of them _ and with us,
for making them famous. Wilson's satirical book, ``A Massive
Swelling: Celebrity Re-Examined as a Grotesque Crippling Disease
and Other Cultural Revelations,'' has just been published by
Viking. The Fort Worth Star-Telegram reached Wilson in her Brooklyn
apartment, where she ruminated about the nature _ and dangers _ of
modern-day fame.
</P>
<P>
   Question: What made you decide to write a book about fame and
its ramifications?
</P>
<P>
   Wilson: The publisher of Salon helped me get a book deal before
I knew what I wanted to write about. Then I saw some play that had
a line, ``Fame is the spiritual disease of the 20th century.'' So I
stole that idea.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you really believe the modern concept of celebrity is bad
for both famous people and their fans?
</P>
<P>
   A: Of course it is! Look at the intense emotions nontalents can
stir up. Kathie Lee Gifford's a good example. She has some fans who
think she's perfect, and millions of people who think all her
orifices ought to be stitched up. We spend time even thinking about
Kathie Lee Gifford? What does that say about us?
</P>
<P>
   Q: Yet you make a living writing about just that kind of
celebrity.
</P>
<P>
   A: Well, I've also been a fairly unsuccessful screenwriter. I've
done a couple of things for Francis Ford Coppola. I rewrote some
material for HBO. I really got started as an underground playwright
in San Francisco, which is where I'm from. I put together eight
full productions in six years. But that turned out not to be
enough. What I really wanted to do was eclipse Madonna.
</P>
<P>
   Q: So you want to be famous, too?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's better that I didn't get to be. I think I would, if
famous, make a rotten diva of a human being. The servants would be
selling their stories to the National Enquirer. I think the real
story of my career is that I have never been able to sell out
successfully.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What qualifications do you, personally, have for fame?
</P>
<P>
   A: I'm a smart-mouth. Isn't that enough?
</P>
<P>
   Q: You also may be in trouble after some celebrities read what
you've written about them in ``A Massive Swelling.'' Cher, for
instance, may not like all the comments about plastic surgery.
</P>
<P>
   A: It's true I better never write a screenplay that ends up with
Cher starring in it. Hey, I'm not the first person to slag off on
Cher. She ought to be used to it by now. See, that's the thing
about these so-called celebrities _ they at least ought to have a
sense of humor about themselves. When they don't, that's when you
know they're never going to last. I'd like to think Cher might read
about herself in my book and laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You think that would ever happen?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yeah, right.
</P>
<P>
   Q: ``A Massive Swelling'' also suggests Michael Jackson's odd
personal tendencies outweigh his artistic talents.
</P>
<P>
   A: When I look at Michael Jackson I just think, ``Where's the
nose?''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Are you also critical of publications that exist to glorify
celebrities, like, say, People?
</P>
<P>
   A: People? Fish wrap.
</P>
<P>
   Q: So what is it, really, that you think is so dangerous about
fame?
</P>
<P>
   A: Too many people want it too badly, and often ruin their lives
pursuing it. The rest of us encourage them; our fascination with
famous people is just as bad.
</P>
<P>
   Q: So if you hate fame so much, are you willing to renounce
still wanting to be famous yourself?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes _ no _ yes _ no! I don't know! See? Wanting to be famous
is a filthy little addiction. It's a horrible kind of disease,
particularly since I think my own chances of becoming famous are
slim.
</P>
<P>
   (Jeff Guinn is books editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
