<SLUG> BC-CHILE-PINOCHET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHILE'S HIGH COURT ENDS PINOCHET'S IMMUNITY FROM PROSECUTION 
</HEADLINE>
   By CLIFFORD KRAUSS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTIAGO, Chile _ The Chilean Supreme Court announced Tuesday
that it would revoke Gen. Augusto Pinochet's senatorial immunity,
removing a giant legal hurdle for the arrest and trial of the
former dictator on charges he was responsible for the kidnapping,
torture and killing of thousands of people during his 17 years in
power.
</P>
<P>
   The vote of 14-6 confirms a lower court ruling in May by the
Chilean Court of Appeals and will allow an investigation, and
possible trial, to go forward. The actual decision was made in a
secret vote, but not announced until Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of Pinochet have argued that he should be stripped of
his immunity because of a wealth of evidence linking him to the
disappearance of Chilean citizens opposed to his rule.
</P>
<P>
   The Chilean government has said secret police were responsible
for the disappearance of 3,197 people in the nearly two decades
Pinochet was in power.
</P>
<P>
   Pinochet took power after he led a coup in 1973 to bring down
Chile's Marxist government. He exercised that power through a
campaign of terror.
</P>
<P>
   Pinochet faces more than 100 criminal complaints, mostly filed
by family members of the more than 3,000 people who disappeared.
Judge Juan Guzman is prosecuting Pinochet, has anchored his case on
and the disappearance of 19 people immediately after the 1973 coup.
He has said he hopes to question the former dictator about these 19
incidents. Opponents of Pinochet believe the 19 were executed on
the orders of top government advisers.
</P>
<P>
   He has denied ever ordering any killings or torture.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, Pinochet took the position of ``senator for life,''
largely to give himself the protection from prosecution that public
officials enjoy. Pinochet was never elected to the Senate. He
assumed the seat by applying a constitutional provision written
during his rule, which lasted until 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Pinochet, who is 84 years old and suffering from heart ailments
and diabetes, could die before he is convicted of any crimes in
Chile. But his opponents say that holding him accountable for his
actions is an important step toward creating a civilian-run
democracy based on the rule of law.
</P>
<P>
   Pinochet's lawyers have said they can prove he is not guilty of
the charges against him if he goes to trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a defeat,'' Gustavo Collao, a lawyer for Pinochet
told The Associated Press on Tuesday. ``Our next step, if a trial
actually takes place, is to prove the complete innocence of General
Pinochet.''
</P>
<P>
   Pinochet's lawyers are likely to argue that he is not healthy
enough to direct them competently and therefore should not be
forced to stand trial.
</P>
<P>
   The general's lawyers have said that they will not allow their
client to undergo tests of mental fitness, a stance that could lead
to another legal battle that might further delay proceedings
against Pinochet. Under Chilean law, all criminal defendants over
70 must undergo an examination before trial. Mental illness can
prevent any trial from going forward.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers who mounted the case against Pinochet said they were
happy with the court's decision, but uncertain as to whether
Pinochet would ever be punished.
</P>
<P>
   The strongest push to investigate and try Pinochet began after
the former dictator was detained in England in late 1998 on a
Spanish warrant that charged him with human rights crimes. He was
held there under house arrest during 16 months of legal wrangling.
Lawyers for Pinochet claimed immunity from prosecution because of
his position as a senator. Pinochet was released by the British
after doctors said he was neither physically or mentally fit to
stand trial.
</P>
<P>
   During the proceedings, no evidence ever linked the general
definitively to any single crime. But prosecutors are hoping that
his deteriorating legal status will encourage several retired
officers who are already imprisoned to testify that the former
dictator was aware of their crimes or helped cover them up.
</P>
<P>
   The case in Britain, which ultimately involved four countries,
brought about a fundamental change in international law that gives
universal jurisdiction to the prosecution of crimes considered
human rights atrocities, no matter where they were committed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
