</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KASHMIR-UNREST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KASHMIR GROUP ENDS CEASE-FIRE AFTER INDIA REFUSES PAKISTAN ROLE IN
TALKS 
</HEADLINE>
   By BARRY BEARAK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW DELHI, India _ The prospect of peace in Kashmir _ a flicker
of hope that had burned unsteadily for the past two weeks _
appeared to die out completely Tuesday when the militant group
Hizbul Mujahedeen called off its cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``This peace offensive has not been reciprocated by India, who
have demonstrated their traditional intransigence,'' said Syed
Salahuddin, the organization's chief, at a crowded news conference
in the Pakistani capital of Islamabad.
</P>
<P>
   The group had insisted that Pakistan be allowed to join in any
talks, something India refused to allow, alleging that Islamabad is
guilty of sponsoring the ``cross-border terrorism'' that has made
Kashmir one of the world's most violent places since 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Hizbul Mujahedeen, one of the main insurgent groups in the
Himalayan territory, declared its unilateral, three-month cease
fire in a surprise announcement on July 24.
</P>
<P>
   India was receptive to the peace initiative, but the move drew
immediate and harsh criticism from other militant groups whose
leaders said Hizbul was off on a fool's errand. To make sure that
errand failed, some of the guerrillas murdered more than 100
innocents _ many Hindu pilgrims _ during one bloody night last
week.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Hizbul field commanders and Indian officials
managed to hold a preliminary round of talks on Thursday in
Kashmir's summer capital, Srinagar. They agreed to continue
negotiations on setting terms for the cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
   But all optimism was quickly moderated when the Hizbul made
another surprise announcement, this time an ultimatum: India had
until Tuesday to agree on including Pakistan in any talks or the
cease-fire was off.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Atal Behari Vajpayee of India made several
conciliatory statements about open-ended conditions for talks, but
the inclusion of Pakistan was not among them.
</P>
<P>
   Hizbul made good on its threat. ``As the deadline has expired,
we direct all the commanders with the mujahedeen in the field to
break the cease fire and go ahead with all target-oriented
missions,'' Salahuddin said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Hizbul chief sounded defiant, but there will now surely be
behind-the-scenes attempts to revive the peace process and, in
replying to a question, Salahuddin said that his group might review
its stance if India made necessary concessions.
</P>
<P>
   In its official reaction to Tuesday's events, the Indian
government spared Hizbul its wrath and placed all blame on
Pakistan: ``Pakistan's object has been to derail the peace process
by seeking to involve itself as a party in discussions between
India and the Hizbul Mujahedeen. The sabotage of the peace process
by Pakistan clearly shows its callous disregard for the welfare of
the people'' of Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
   Kashmir, a territory about the size of Utah with a population
whose majority is Muslim, is wedged between India, Pakistan and
China. Its ownership has been disputed between predominantly-Muslim
Pakistan and largely Hindu India since both gained independence in
1947. The two nations _ the world's newest nuclear powers _ have
fought two of their three wars over Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
   In 1989, an insurgency broke out in the Kashmir's storied
valley. Pakistan has backed many of the militant groups that have
taken up arms _ some of whom favor an independent Kashmir, some of
whom prefer union with Pakistan. The Indian military has attempted
to crush the militancy, often using tactics condemned by human
rights groups. An estimated 25,000 to 40,000 people have died
during the decade of violence.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
