<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 17:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5973 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-BOMBING-0809-C     08-08 0884
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-BOMBING-0809-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BOMB CONSIDERED A 'TERRORIST ACT' ROCKS DOWNTOWN MOSCOW; KILLS
7, WOUNDED 53
 &HT;    By MARGARET COKER 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ A bomb tore through a street underpass packed with
rush-hour shoppers and commuters in downtown Moscow on Tuesday,
killing at least seven people and fueling fears that Chechen rebels
have again brought their war to the heart of Russia.
</P>
<P>
   More than 50 wounded, including women and children, crawled and
staggered out of the passageways that run underneath two of
Moscow's busiest streets and between three subway lines at Pushkin
Square. Charred bodies lay crumpled on the street, as police and
ambulances rushed to the scene shortly after the 5 p.m. (Moscow
time) blast.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard an enormous bang behind me and saw smoke streaming
from the entrance,'' said Irina Selimbaeva, 17, who was sitting
with friends on a park bench just 10 feet away from one entrance to
the underpass when the bomb went off. ``We were too surprised to be
scared, until we saw the wounded come out.''
</P>
<P>
   Interior Minister Vladimir Rushaillo(CQ), the highest-ranking
government official to visit the bomb sight, was quoted by the
Interfax news agency as calling the blast ``a terrorist act.''
</P>
<P>
   Immediate suspicion fell on rebels fighting a second war against
Russia for independence in the southern republic of Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's fatal incident comes almost one year after three
blasts destroyed multi-story apartment buildings in Moscow, killing
more than 300 people. Those explosions were blamed on Chechen
rebels, and led to a renewed military campaign in the breakaway
republic.
</P>
<P>
   ``The nature of the crime is obvious _ the explosion hit in a
place packed with people at rush hour,'' Moscow Mayor Yuri Luzhkov
told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   However, Chechen President Aslan Maskhadov Tuesday denied
responsibility for the blast.
</P>
<P>
   ``Neither the regular Chechen forces nor the special services or
warlords have anything to do with the explosion at Pushkin
Square,'' Agence France Press quoted Maskhadov as saying.
</P>
<P>
   Russian President Vladimir Putin called an emergency session of
his top law enforcement officials Tuesday night, and in a written
statement expressed his condolences to the families of the victims.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors treating the estimated 53 wounded warned the death toll
could rise above seven, as some people brought to the hospital were
in serious condition. Police were placed on heightened alert and
ordered to check the many underground passageways around Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   Russian authorities had earlier in the day called for heightened
security in all major cities, after the Interior Ministry reported
that authorities had confiscated a large amount of explosives in
other parts of Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Moscow city police said there was no warning ahead of the early
evening blast.
</P>
<P>
   An official with the Emergency Situations Ministry said the bomb
probably came from a suitcase left in the underpass, which is
crowded with flower stalls, cosmetic stores and airline ticket
kiosks. The official said a detonation device had been found in the
corridor between two subway stations. He provided no details about
the size or type of the bomb.
</P>
<P>
   Rescue officials found and defused a second bomb found in the
underpass, Interfax reported. That report could not be immediately
confirmed with federal officials.
</P>
<P>
   The scene at Pushkin Square, Moscow's equivalent to New York
City's Times Square, was sheer panic for the first two hours after
the explosion.
</P>
<P>
   One woman was carried to an ambulance, her flesh severely
charred and blood gushing from her nose. A younger woman, her hair
matted with blood and shirt torn off, sat with her face in her
hands as passersby rushed over to help.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tried to find our way out. We couldn't see or breathe. We
covered our noses. I passed one other wounded and then another, and
another,'' said one black-haired middle-aged man, his hands shaking
and his glasses broken and askew on his smoke-stained face.
</P>
<P>
   But by 9 p.m. (Moscow time), crowds milling around the bomb
scene had tapered off. Businesses around the square, including a
movie theater and several restaurants, remained open. People sat in
outdoor cafes, drinking beer and discussing the day's events.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course it's scary that this has happened in the capital. We
don't want to think about who did it. The answer is too
frightening,'' said Lilia Alimbaeva, a curious onlooker who stopped
to view the aftermath on her way home from work.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of last year's explosions, Chechen rebel leaders
also denied responsibility. No one has been charged with any crime
for those blasts. Some analysts and Russian citizens believe that
Russian security services planted the bombs to give Vladimir Putin,
who had just been named prime minister and now is Russia's
president, as excuse to wage war in Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   In the last week, Chechen rebels have been dropping pamphlets
around Chechnya warning civilians to flee ahead of a planned new
offensive against Russian troops.
</P>
<P>
   Margaret Coker's E-mail address is: megc(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   For more information:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.kolumbus.fi/kavkaz/english/index.html
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
