<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 17:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5974 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-BC-CONFEDERATE-TEXAS-     08-08 0937
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BC-CONFEDERATE-TEXAS-HNS,2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
CONFEDERATE-TEXAS-HNS,2TAKES &HT;    CONFEDERATE MONUMENT DISPLAY IN CAPITOL DISPUTED
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients) 
 &HT;    By POLLY ROSS HUGHES 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ A plaque on the ground floor of the Texas state
Capitol declares that the Civil War was neither a rebellion ``nor
was its cause to sustain slavery.''
</P>
<P>
   A giant portrait of Confederacy President Jefferson Davis is
perched at the right hand of the lieutenant governor as he wields
his gavel in the Texas Senate.
</P>
<P>
   An ancient soldier, believed to be the last survivor, poses in
uniform next to the Confederate battle flag as he stares from a
painting in the office of the Texas House speaker pro tem.
</P>
<P>
   And that's just the beginning. An official inventory by the
state turned up a dozen items on display which make overt
references to the Confederacy. The list doesn't include countless
other Confederates portrayed in portraits wearing civilian clothes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Capitol grounds and the Capitol interior serve as a
virtual modern-day Confederate museum,'' Gary Bledsoe, president of
the Texas NAACP, said after a recent visit. ``... What is
mind-boggling is the obvious dominance of Confederate symbols
throughout the Capitol and its grounds.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, as presidential candidates debated the presence of the
Confederate battle flag atop South Carolina's statehouse earlier
this year, many a Confederate ghost inhabited the Texas Capitol
where Republican presidential nominee George W. Bush presides as
governor.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just the way it is. It's part of our history,'' said
Rick Crawford, executive director of the State Preservation Board.
</P>
<P>
   The abundance and prominence of Capitol art commemorating the
Confederacy is partly the result of a faithful, $200 million
historical restoration begun in 1989 in which the Capitol was
returned to its turn-of-the-century elegance. By holding true to
pre-1915 photographs of the chambers, however, the preservationists
locked in the undoubtedly Confederate spirit of the times.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has made it clear that relics of all six governments that
have ruled Texas will remain in the Capitol complex. He responded
in June, however, to Bledsoe's plea to remove two Confederate
plaques from the Texas Supreme Court building. One displayed the
Confederate battle flag while the other bore the Confederate seal.
</P>
<P>
   The action dismayed descendants of Confederate soldiers who kept
up a daily vigil in the following weeks, braving the Texas summer
heat and decked out in Confederate regalia to wave the battle flag
in front of the court. The Confederate buffs let off plenty of
steam elsewhere, refusing to let the issue die.
</P>
<P>
   Demp Toney, an Austin actress and granddaughter of a Civil War
veteran, recently appeared before the General Services Commission,
waving her own small Confederate battle flag and not-so-subtly
implying that Bush is a carpetbagger. At the GOP convention in
Philadelphia, the Southern Heritage Coalition of North Carolina
flew a Confederate battle flag attached to a banner saying, ``Bush:
Put the Tx vets plaques back!'' &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; The debate over appropriate display of Confederate symbols most
often centers on the battle flag itself, which has been adopted by
various hate groups, including neo-Nazi skinheads in Germany.
Gradually, however, questions of what might be deemed offensive
have grown.
</P>
<P>
   OPTIONAL TRIM
</P>
<P>
   In May, for instance, a portrait of former Texas A&AMP;M University
President Gibb Gilchrist was removed from a building on the
school's campus. The removal followed a complaint that an image of
Confederate Gen. Robert E. Lee was looking over Gilchrist's
shoulder and suggested racial intolerance.
</P>
<P>
   Yet any visitor to the state Capitol can view far more than a
single portrait-within-a-portrait of Robert E. Lee.
</P>
<P>
   OPTIONAL TRIM
</P>
<P>
   Just inside and right of the front gate of the Great Walk
leading to the south entrance stands the massive Confederate
Soldiers monument, erected in 1903 by surviving comrades. It speaks
of state's rights being trampled upon and is topped by a bronze
statue of Jefferson Davis above four other bronze figures,
representing the various branches of the Confederate Army.
</P>
<P>
   On the left of the walk nearer to the Capitol entrance, a
monument of a mounted soldier honors Confederate members of a
cavalry unit called Terry's Texas Rangers. Just east of the Capitol
stands the tallest monument on the grounds, erected in 1910 and
honoring the battles of John B. Hood's Texas Brigade, which is
topped by a bronze statue of a Confederate soldier.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Gov. Rick Perry's office contains a portrait of former Texas
Gov. Lawrence ``Sul'' Ross in a Confederate uniform. Inside the
Senate chamber, Jefferson Davis is joined by a large portrait of
Albert Sidney Johnston, general of the western division, standing
in uniform next to the official ``stars and bars'' flag of the
Confederacy.
</P>
<P>
   On the House side are two identical portraits of Confederate war
hero Dick Dowling of Galveston. In the Capitol office of Rep. Tom
Uher, the speaker pro tem and Bay City Democrat, a portrait of
Walter Wade Williams, who claimed to be the oldest survivor of the
Confederacy, also depicts the Confederate battle flag.
</P>
<P>
   Uher, dean of the Texas House with 33 years seniority, requested
permission to hang the painting from the state collection,
according to the State Preservation Board. Uher's staff hands out
information sheets on Williams that say he lived to be 117 years
old.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
