<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000808.0201 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 17:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5975 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-BC-CONFEDERATE-TEXAS-     08-08 0970
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BC-CONFEDERATE-TEXAS-HNS,2ND </SLUG>
 TAK-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
CONFEDERATE-TEXAS-HNS,2ND TAKE
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN: 117 years old.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the least conspicuous of Confederate reminders is also
among the most provocative. It is a small plaque located on the
ground floor in a tiny hallway between the elevators and the Senate
stairwell.
</P>
<P>
   Erected by the Texas Division of the Children of the Confederacy
in 1959, it contains the group's creed. In it, the organization
pledges to ``study and teach the truths of history (one of the most
important of which is, that the war between the states was not a
rebellion, nor was its underlying cause to sustain slavery)....''
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokeswoman Linda Edwards said the Capitol's Confederate
plaque does not raise the same issues as the other plaques that the
governor agreed should be removed from the state's highest court.
</P>
<P>
   ``This plaque represents the sentiments of this particular
group,'' she said. ``The Texas House passed a concurrent resolution
in 1959, allowing the erection of that plaque.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, Bledsoe said Texas lawmakers should consider using state
resources to provide more balance and accuracy in relaying the
history of the Confederacy at the Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can we tell the story of the Confederacy without
mentioning the slaves, the declaration of causes or the ordinance
of secession?'' he asked. ``What we see displayed at our Capitol
and its grounds is revisionist history that suggests slavery was
not the focal point of this war, and which does this in a way as to
be an affront to the government of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   The Texas ordinance of secession, adopted in February 1861,
repeatedly complains of the Northern states wanting to stop slavery
in the South.
</P>
<P>
   It also describes the ``beneficent and patriarchal system of
African slavery'' and protests the ``debasing doctrine of the
equality of all men, irrespective of race or color _ a doctrine at
war with nature... ''
</P>
<P>
   It's now 139 years later, but reminders of bygone days of the
Old South still stir passionate emotions in both the descendants of
plantation owners and slaves.
</P>
<P>
   For the battle flag-waving protester Toney _ who says her
ancestors fought in the Civil War, Texas Revolution and American
Revolution _ tributes to the Confederacy elicit deep emotions of
pride and great sadness for the fallen soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I grew up hearing stories about the Confederacy, the hardships
of the South. In my family is a cannon ball that one of them
brought back from the Civil War. It's kind of a sacred thing that
we love dearly,'' she said as she toured Confederate memorials at
the Capitol last week.
</P>
<P>
   Toney, who won't reveal her age, said she remembers being a
little girl and hearing her mother crying as she retold the stories
her own father, a Civil War veteran, had told her.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had nothing to come back to because immediately after the
war, the carpetbaggers from the North swarmed over the Mason-Dixon
line like vultures circling a deserted battlefield,'' Toney said.
</P>
<P>
   Toney said her mother lived on a sugar cane plantation, and the
family had owned slaves. She still has deeds of slave trades and
sales and believes the slaves were not abused but ``cared for.''
They were ``investments'' after all, she said.
</P>
<P>
   For her, the Capitol's tributes to the Confederacy have
``incredible meaning.''
</P>
<P>
   It is also a shared history, as Karen Haller of Houston sees it.
She is a descendant of Nathan Haller, one of the last former slaves
to serve in the Texas Legislature during Reconstruction. Nearly 70
years would pass before African-Americans, including Barbara
Jordan, returned to the state Legislature. Haller said she, too,
knows some die-hard Confederates.
</P>
<P>
   ``They hold that near and dear to their heart,'' Haller said.
``For people to say it wasn't about slavery _ what else was it
about?''
</P>
<P>
   As far as she is concerned, lessons of the Confederacy can be
better taught in history books.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it should go _ all of it,'' she said of the
Confederate monuments, paintings and plaques at the Texas Capitol.
``Slavery is a part of history and so is lynching, but you don't
see a slave hanging in front of the Capitol. You don't today,
anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   She pointed to the dragging death of James Byrd Jr., a black man
in Jasper, as evidence that the dehumanization slavery represented
still exists today.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's history. We still have our reminders and we
still have people who believe the same things as their ancestors
did. We perpetuate racism.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, as old wounds heal slowly, new monuments might eventually
broaden the scope of how the Old South is depicted in the state
capital. Land has been set aside for a monument on the south lawn
commemorating Juneteenth, when Texas slaves learned belatedly they
had been liberated. And on April 13, 1999, the State Preservation
Board approved a site north of the Capitol for another monument to
honor black Texans, the result of legislation passed by Houston
Democrats Sen. Rodney Ellis and Rep. Garnet Coleman.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Svatora, a legislative aide to Ellis, said the Confederacy
is part of Texas history, and the senator does not wish to deny the
existence of one of the six governments that ruled Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to acknowledge that we had a rough past,'' he said.
``The history of Texas is tumultuous, but the diversity is a
strength.''
</P>
<P>
   Coleman said the history of African-Americans in Texas is
extraordinarily interesting and partly because it is so rarely
told.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just amazed. I don't know why people don't understand the
hurt,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tradition has been the biggest excuse for you to make other
people uncomfortable and get away with it,'' he added. ``What's one
group's tradition is another's nightmare.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
