<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 17:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5976 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-CHEERLEADER-DANCE-$AD     08-08 0632
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHEERLEADER-DANCE-$ADV13-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHERE   THEY PREFER MISFITS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Aug. 13)  
 By KEVIN GIORDANO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In the show ``Wanted: X-Cheerleaders,'' a squad of 10
real-life ex-cheerleaders rant and cheer about women's issues.
Their routines, which feature flying pompoms, kicks and jumps, are
at once authentic cheerleading drills and carefully choreographed
movement.
</P>
<P>
   ``The piece is somewhat theatrical in that we have a script and
an order, but it's not a narrative,'' said the choreographer Jody
Oberfelder, who, with the director Kim Irwin, created
``X-Cheerleaders.'' ``What we're doing defies category.''
</P>
<P>
   Although ``X-Cheerleaders'' may not fall under the rubric of
contemporary dance, it is exactly the kind of movement-dominated
performance that is carving out a niche in the New York
International Fringe Festival, which will envelop the Lower East
Side for 12 days beginning on Wednesday. Now in its fourth year,
the festival (on the Web at fringenyc.com), will present at least
40 theater shows a day at 20 different venues. Of the 180 shows,
about 20 can legitimately be called contemporary dance or
performance art.
</P>
<P>
   The best-known fringe festival is the one at Edinburgh, founded
in 1947, which was created to give unconventional theater companies
a chance to present their work. Today there are fringe festivals
all over the world and in American cities like Seattle,
Philadelphia and Houston. John Clancy, the artistic director of the
Present Company, founded the New York festival in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``The festival succeeds in the creation of a common meeting
ground for artists, where artists can see each other's work and
collaboration can take place,'' said Clancy, who heads a 30-member
panel that selects applicants' work for the festival, contrary to
the usual fringe standard of first-come, first-served. ``What we
provide for the audience is challenging new work and convenience.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the New York festival is predominantly a theater event,
dance companies like Ben Munisteri, Open 24 Hours/Pam Tanowitz, Neo
Labos and Claire Byrne have performed there in the past. This year,
FringeNYC will hold a symposium to discuss issues concerning
choreographers and dance companies. The panel will include David R.
White, director of Dance Theater Workshop; Laurie Uprichard,
executive director of Danspace Project; Steve Greco, a committee
member of New York Performance and Dance Awards (the Bessies); and
Gus Solomons Jr., a dancer and choreographer.
</P>
<P>
   ``In that first year, we made a commitment to dance, to
multimedia work, to the old term `performance art,''' said Clancy.
``What's great about the Fringe is that it's a flexible beast.''
</P>
<P>
   For Clancy, ``X-Cheerleaders,'' which had its premiere at P.S.
122 in 1994, is emblematic of what FringeNYC is all about. ``It's a
perfect example of the emerging style of performances that do not
fit comfortably into any category,'' he says. ``What do you call
that style? It's theater, but it's dance.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to ``X-Cheerleaders,'' there will be a collection of
other dance-oriented performances. Tony Silva Dance and Music will
present ``Air Born''; Falling Plaster will show ``Full Frontal
Facts''; Caroline Jauch and Co. are offering ``The Handless
Maiden''; Artichoke Dance Company will perform ``Ho-Down
Showdown''; Stratton Gonzalez Dance Theater will offer ``A Place in
Line''; and Vickie Mendoza/vicdog 3d will show ``Three Worse
Flowers.''
</P>
<P>
   For Oberfelder, Fringe performances are yet another chance to
cheer on the blending of dance and theater. ``It's a funny thing
with Fringe,'' she says. ``It's sort of outsider art in a way.
Hopefully, what we do makes accessible the edgier kind of work that
packs a punch.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
