<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 17:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5980 &Cx1f; tab-z
u a BC-CURATORS-POLS-NEWHOUS     08-08 1700
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CURATORS-POLS-NEWHOUSE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YESTERDAY'S CONVENTION IS TODAY'S HISTORY TO SMITHSONIAN
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: This article from NEWHOUSE NEWS SERVICE for
Tuesday, AUGUST 8, is available as a ``separate-buy.'' For
information about purchasing the article, contact DEBRA WEYDERT of
The New York Times Syndicate at 1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697;
e-mail: weyded nytimes.com.) 
 ART ADV:With two photos, of Larry Bird (NNS4) and Harry Rubenstein
(NNS5) 
 By DELIA M. RIOS  
 c.2000 Newhouse News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   On the evening that Republican vice-presidential nominee Dick
Cheney spoke to his party's convention, just before delegates were
called to order, Larry Bird stood beside the Texas delegation, a
cell phone to his ear, patiently waving his arm in the direction of
the Pseudo.com skybox.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a curator at the Smithsonian Institution,'' Bird repeated
to at least three Pseudo employees as they disbelievingly passed
the phone around.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm waving at you,'' Bird added hopefully, straining to be
seen amid the crowd on the convention floor.
</P>
<P>
   Pseudo CEO David Bohrman was skeptical.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to think that the Smithsonian wants something that
you're using,'' he sheepishly admitted later.
</P>
<P>
   But, indeed, the Smithsonian did -- specifically, an Internet
camera valued at upwards of $20,000 that was transmitting
gavel-to-gavel convention coverage to the Pseudo.com site from a
Texas delegation perch.
</P>
<P>
   Bird and his colleague, Harry Rubenstein, wanted to add the
camera to the political collection at the National Museum of
American History, where it would join the microphones from FDR's
fireside chats, Thomas Jefferson's lap desk, and placards from the
1963 civil rights March on Washington. A day of negotiations later,
Pseudo and the camera's manufacturer, BeHere, happily announced at
a Republican Party-sanctioned press conference that they were
honored to make the donation.
</P>
<P>
   All in a day's work for Bird and Rubenstein -- better known as
Larry and Harry -- as they scavenged the convention floor with an
eye toward history. It's a hunt they'll take to Los Angeles next
week when the Democrats convene to nominate Al Gore for president,
searching for political memorabilia with inherent wit and appeal
but also the commonplace and the mundane. Brace yourself, but this
year their wish list includes a ``Convention Barbie.''
</P>
<P>
   The 2000 presidential election is months off, but room is
already being made for its place in history. Long after President
Bush or President Gore leaves the White House, something of this
summer's conventions and our times will survive in the museum's
political collection -- already sizable at 90,000 objects, some of
them older than the presidency itself.
</P>
<P>
   Not that collecting comes easily -- even when posterity is
invoked.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never know what you really need until you see it,'' Bird
explained.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we want is what they can't give away,'' Rubenstein added.
``We rely a lot on the Smithsonian reputation.''
</P>
<P>
   (FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS)
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, the curators meet any number of conventioneers only
too willing to be a small part of history. Delegate Paula Maxwell
did her civic duty by handing over a cowboy hat with ``ARIZONA''
printed in block letters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to have a hat; now it's making history,'' Maxwell said,
a touch of resignation in her voice.
</P>
<P>
   But as unfailingly polite and engaging as they are -- Bird
approached a West Virginia delegate by asking, ``Sir with the hat?
Can I talk to you?'' -- the curators' pitch can be a hard sell.
Delegates often don't want to give away their prized mementos, for
sentimental or other reasons.
</P>
<P>
   (FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS)
</P>
<P>
   A Delaware delegate they approached, for one, allowed as to how
her delegation had been offered $100 and even a bottle of Puerto
Rican rum for their black tri-corner hats. The hats evoked the
spirit of Caesar Rodney, revered in Delaware for riding by
horseback to Philadelphia -- although he was dying of cancer -- to
cast a critical vote for the Declaration of Independence as a
member of the Continental Congress. The curators eventually left
with a promise that a hat would be sent to them at the museum.
</P>
<P>
   And then there was the tussle over the Texas standard.
</P>
<P>
   The curators persuaded the Texas delegation to give them the
red, white and blue rectangular sign imprinted with their state
name. Susan Weddington, the delegation chair, extracted an
assurance that any Texan could visit the standard, any time.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll be able to commune with it in perpetuity,'' Bird
promised.
</P>
<P>
   ``You got a deal,'' Weddington replied.
</P>
<P>
   Bird explained that the standard needed a protector. After the
nominee's speech, exuberant delegates leaving the floor tend to
consider anything they see a personal souvenir.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people would like to have this,'' Bird told
Weddington.
</P>
<P>
   Prophetic words, as it turned out.
</P>
<P>
   The standard disappeared Thursday night after Bush addressed
delegates. The curators found it in the possession of determined
conventioneers. Not even the Smithsonian's name could dislodge it.
But by the following Monday, the Republican National Committee had
secured the standard and promised the curators it was on its way to
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   It's a nice touch to have the home state standard of the
nominee, and just the kind of thing that Americans might expect to
see in a museum exhibit. But it's the Internet camera discovered in
Philadelphia or the ``go'' light used to prompt speakers at the
1996 Republican convention in San Diego that tell a fuller story
about political life at the turn of the century.
</P>
<P>
   The ``go'' light will allow historians to illustrate how
scripted the conventions have become, while the Internet camera may
become a relic of a transforming technological moment -- something
like the primitive appearance of television in 1948 when both the
Republicans and Democrats met in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why it's so interesting to a historian,'' Bird said.
``What does it mean? We'll see.''
</P>
<P>
   And there are the intangibles.
</P>
<P>
   The curators wanted the Bush/Cheney signs the delegates
brandished because the letters of Cheney's name were smaller.
Typically, the names of the presidential and vice-presidential
nominees are printed in the same size to symbolize the new team.
``So,'' Bird speculated, ``there's something going on here.''
</P>
<P>
   They also were intrigued by blank poster boards left for
delegates to write their own political messages. All those
hand-painted signs delegates wave at television cameras are usually
mass-produced and designed to convey specific party themes.
Rubenstein interpreted the blank posters as a sign that Republican
officials were confident enough in the convention's unity to allow
renegade signs. Even those, he said, were ``pretty much on
message.''
</P>
<P>
   Protest voices were muted, and the curators took notice where
they did emerge.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of red meat rhetoric, you get red meat items,'' Bird
said.
</P>
<P>
   Two cases in point: ``Life of the Party'' vests worn by abortion
opponents,and the political buttons popping up on delegates that
were, Rubenstein said, a lot less subtle than the official rhetoric
about restoring dignity to the Oval Office.
</P>
<P>
   The curators must be discerning in their search. What they bring
back to the museum is the raw material from which future historians
will work. Bird and Rubenstein, curators in the museum's Division
of Political History, are acutely aware of that responsibility --
they are drawing now, in fact, on the museum's extensive collection
for an exhibit opening Nov. 15 called ``The American Presidency: A
Glorious Burden.''
</P>
<P>
   Bird has attended conventions since 1984, and Rubenstein joined
him in 1988. Their travels this year extended to the Iowa caucuses
and the New Hampshire primary where they took inventory of
potential objects. When they arrive in California, among the
artifacts they'll be on the lookout for is that ``Convention
Barbie.'' Word had it that Republican delegates had them in
Philadelphia, but the curators never actually saw one.
</P>
<P>
   And they'll be attuned to the coded language Democrats use and
how that gets translated onto the signs television viewers see. In
Philadelphia, for example, signs blared the words ``honesty'' and
``integrity.'' With the choice of the widely respected Connecticut
Sen. Joseph Lieberman as Gore's running mate, Bird says similar
signs might show up on the floor in L.A.
</P>
<P>
   Smithsonian curators have gone to the conventions since the mid-
to late 1960s to expand on a private collection left to the
institution by Washington, D.C., attorney Ralph E. Becker --
described by Bird as a premier assemblage of campaign Americana.
Becker had attended Republican conventions since the 1940s, and
began seriously collecting memorabilia in the 1950s. The campaign
collection was folded into the broader political history
collection.
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND OPTIONAL TRIM FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   With the rise of television in the 1950s, delegates gave more
emphasis to putting on a good show. There certainly was evidence of
that in Philadelphia. Rubenstein, finding himself face-to-face with
a Colorado delegate wearing patriotic leather chaps and several
bottles' worth of glitter spelling out her state's name, asked,
``Just out of curiosity, why are you doing this?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm proud of my state,'' she answered. Sure enough, she was on
television the night Bush accepted the convention's nomination.
</P>
<P>
   The curators also have learned to work television. Nothing
inspires a delegate's generosity more than a news crew at his or
her side. It was an interview on Fox television that finally
convinced Bohrman, the Pseudo.com CEO, that the curators were
legit.
</P>
<P>
   Once that was settled, however, he invited Bird to the company's
skybox for an Internet interview. As Bird took questions from the
site's chat room, Rubenstein peered over a computer screen and
watched his colleague do the museum's work in real time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-08-00 1712EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000808.0207 </DOCNO>
