<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 17:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5982 &Cx1f; tab-z
u v BC-LIEBERMAN-HILLARY-NEW     08-08 0715
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIEBERMAN-HILLARY-NEWHOUSE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IF LIEBERMAN'S SO PRAISEWORTHY, WHY'D HE SAY YES?
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: This article from NEWHOUSE NEWS SERVICE for
Tuesday, AUGUST 8, is available as a ``separate-buy.'' For
information about purchasing the article, contact DEBRA WEYDERT of
The New York Times Syndicate at 1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697;
e-mail: weyded nytimes.com.) 
 By JAMES LILEKS  
 c.2000 Newhouse News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lieberman! Of course! Why, it's the obvious choice for veep,
especially when you factor out all the charismatic fellows from
important states.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone's praising the choice, but that's standard operating
procedure these days; if Al Gore had appeared at a news conference
with a monkey on his shoulder, and announced that Screechy the
Lemur would be his Veep, Dems would praise the choice, and
Republicans would let it be known how much they admire Screechy.
``I worked with him during the budget battles,'' former Speaker of
the House Newt Gingrich said, ``and although we were adversaries, I
admired his diligence, command of the details, and ability to pick
nits out of my back hair.''
</P>
<P>
   Blah, blah. Politics nowadays are one long answer to Rodney
King's plaint: Yes, it seems we can all get along. It makes you
long for someone to stop with the nice-talk, do a spit-take on CNN:
``Lieberman? Joe the Drone? Nice guy, but listening to him orate
isn't exactly like flossing with a Roman Candle. The man's a cross
between Alfred E. Newman on downers and Droopy with a mouthful of
Novacain. What was Al Gore thinking?''
</P>
<P>
   Good question. Perhaps Gore feared that Dick Cheney would
monopolize the vexatious-prostate demographic. Perhaps Gore needed
moral cover -- and Lieberman is now portrayed as Gandhi from
Connecticut, with super-human ethical abilities that cancel out
Gore's evasions. New, concentrated Joe detergent -- gets out even
the toughest White-House Coffee stains!
</P>
<P>
   The real question, however, is what Sen. Lieberman was thinking.
He is, by all accounts, a sharp and decent fellow. Moral, upright,
ethical, all those old Scout virtues. And that's why it's sad to
watch him clamber in the sack with Gore. Let's remember two key
moments in the impeachment drama. Lieberman issued a stern, sad
denunciation of his old friend Bill. The president, said Lieberman
in his nerdy warble, ``had extramarital relations with an employee
half his age and did so in the workplace in the vicinity of the
Oval Office. Such behavior is not just inappropriate. It is
immoral.''
</P>
<P>
   Right. Now, let's recall Al Gore's speech on the White House
lawn, where he insisted President Clinton was the by-gosh bestest
president a fella could have, and he was proud to be his
boot-licking vassal. Or words to that effect. So one has to ask:
Why does Sen. Lieberman want to be Veep for an immoral creep's
apologist?
</P>
<P>
   Power, of course. Next stupid question?
</P>
<P>
   OK, what does he bring to the ticket? Well, as the first Jewish
Veep choice, he breaks a precedent. Much will be made of how much
is not being made of Lieberman's religion. It startles one to
realize that it's taken this long to name a Jew for this position.
At this rate, we can expect black presidents and female Veeps of
Arab or Hispanic extraction around the time we admit the Pluto
Colony to the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   He also brings diversity of opinion, although it's hard to see
why this matters. Supposedly, Cheney was named to bolster George W.
Bush's lack of foreign policy expertise. If the Russians moved into
Ukraine, the Dems suggest, Bush would hide in the well of his desk;
Cheney would pry him out, slap him, and present the options.
</P>
<P>
   But Lieberman is in a different position. On many issues he
holds positions contrary to Gore: Parental notification. Missile
defense. School vouchers. Letting municipalities sue gun makers.
Gore won't change his mind on any issue because Joe has another
opinion -- in fact, the reverse will happen. Surely Lieberman knows
that he's the one who'll be carrying Gore's water, drinking it, and
pronouncing it to taste like champagne.
</P>
<P>
   Does anyone look forward to hearing Lieberman explain why he's
now in favor of all the things he used to oppose? Have a nice ride,
Joe. Hope it's worth it.
</P>
</TEXT>
