u v BC-GROWNUP-POLS-NEWHOUSE     08-08 0964
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GROWNUP-POLS-NEWHOUSE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IS THE POL A GROWN-UP? NEW CATCHWORD UNDERSCORES GENERATIONAL POWER
SHIFT
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: This article from NEWHOUSE NEWS SERVICE for
Tuesday, AUGUST 8, is available as a ``separate-buy.'' For
information about purchasing the article, contact DEBRA WEYDERT of
The New York Times Syndicate at 1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697;
e-mail: weyded nytimes.com.) 
 By DRU SEFTON  
 c.2000 Newhouse News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you've been listening to political banter of late, you may
think the presidential campaign is taking place in a preschool,
what with all this chatter about ``grown-ups.''
</P>
<P>
   Grown-up. It's the catchword lately among pundits and
journalists both inside and outside the Beltway. Just in the past
week alone:
</P>
<P>
   -- An editorial in The Wall Street Journal identified
Connecticut Sen. Joseph Lieberman, Democratic candidate Al Gore's
new running mate, as ``a political grown-up.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Ron Reagan Jr. chastised Republican candidate George W. Bush
in The Washington Post for having made a snide comment about an
executed inmate: ``No grown-up would ever do that.''
</P>
<P>
   -- A Boston Globe writer termed Bush's acceptance speech ``the
ultimate grown-up act.''
</P>
<P>
   -- David Gergen of U.S. News &AMP; World Report agreed on
``Nightline'' that during the speech, ``gone was the sense that
this is a fellow that's not quite grown up.''
</P>
<P>
   -- And MSNBC talking head Chris Matthews declared that Bush's
speech was ``a brilliant summation of the Republican strategy. ...
On the topic of Al Gore, don't even give him the credibility of a
grown-up.''
</P>
<P>
   As with so much political talk, the term ``grown-up'' carries
different meanings, said Diana Carlin, professor of communication
studies at the University of Kansas-Lawrence and an expert on
political rhetoric.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being a baby boomer myself, I know that in our own minds, a
lot of boomers still don't see themselves as now running things,''
Carlin said. ``We've been a generation that has not wanted to grow
up.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the first presidential election with two baby boomer
candidates, Bush and Gore. When Bill Clinton ran against President
George Bush, and later Kansas Republican Sen. Bob Dole, those
contests were seen as the baby boomers vs. the World War II
generation.
</P>
<P>
   So what America is witnessing with this election is the final,
total generational power shift.
</P>
<P>
   ``And any time there is a shift, we really have to,
symbolically, through language, suggest that now is the time for
the next generation to take over,'' Carlin said.
</P>
<P>
   As in John F. Kennedy's now-famous inaugural phrase, ``The torch
has passed to a new generation of Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking at it with a negative spin, the term grown-up ``is a
veiled reference, obviously, to the Clinton problems'' with intern
Monica Lewinsky that took place in the Oval Office, Carlin said.
``Some would view that as not being very grown-up behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Buchanan was quoted last week in The Christian Science
Monitor as saying that Bush's wife, Laura, makes sure the candidate
``acts mostly like a grown-up.''
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan is a professor of government specializing in
presidential politics at the University of Texas at Austin.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I meant was that she was keeping his inner scamp under
control, his desire to show disrespect,'' Buchanan said. ``Bush has
a chip on his shoulder toward various icons, particularly Eastern
intellectuals, and Laura reins him in on that.''
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan said that in other cases, he thinks ``grown-up'' refers
to ``maturity. As John McCain said in one of his speeches, it
embodies the responsibility to interests larger than
self-interest.''
</P>
<P>
   And, specifically in Bush's case, sobriety and ``the possibility
of redemption,'' Buchanan added.
</P>
<P>
   Use of the term within the political arena goes back several
years, Buchanan said. After ``Newt Gingrich and company and all
their breathing fire and hurling spears, it was said that when
Gingrich left, the grown-ups came back to power,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan also agreed that the shadow of Clinton hides behind the
term.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely,'' he said. ``Self-control is an element of being a
grown-up as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Longtime Republican strategist Ken Duberstein last week told
Knight Ridder/Tribune News Service that Gore had to ``find a
grown-up in the Democratic Party'' for his vice-presidential pick.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started using that term a few weeks ago,'' said Duberstein,
who served President Reagan as chief of staff. ``I was talking
about the fact that both Bush and Gore needed grown-ups.''
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, ``the person had to be seasoned, experienced,
ready,'' Duberstein said. ``Not simply good for the ticket, but for
governing. Not an old-fashioned choice, someone who would deliver a
certain state, but someone to govern, to be an adult, someone who'd
been around the track.''
</P>
<P>
   And that's exactly what happened, Duberstein added.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, in Dick Cheney, George W. got an adult. Cheney's a
former White House chief of staff, congressman, a Republican leader
in the House, the secretary of defense. A member of the governing
class,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The selection of Cheney put pressure on Gore,'' Duberstein
continued. ``And with Lieberman, Gore eliminated some people who
would have been perceived as wet behind the ears, and he found
someone clearly mature and grown-up.''
</P>
<P>
   Duberstein sees a positive outcome to all this public talk of
grown-ups.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's reassuring that even with all the complaints and
criticisms of the selection process for the president and vice
president, the system works,'' he said. ``We ended up with four
adults running.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-08-00 1712EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
