<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 17:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5987 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-SRI-LANKA-UNREST-465&AMP;     08-08 1028
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SRI-LANKA-UNREST-465&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SRI LANKA EFFORT TO END CIVIL WAR VIA NEW CONSTITUTION IS SET
BACK 
</HEADLINE>
   By CELIA W. DUGGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLOMBO, Sri Lanka _ President Chandrika Kumaratunga's
long-awaited peace plan for this war-torn nation _ embodied in a
new constitution that would have given greater autonomy to the
Hindu Tamil minority in this majority-Buddhist Sinhalese nation _
foundered Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Kumaratunga had planned to push the proposed constitution
through Parliament after only three days of debate, with a final
vote on Wednesday. But Tuesday, her government postponed voting
indefinitely, apparently bowing to the reality that it lacked the
necessary two-thirds majority.
</P>
<P>
   The six-year term of this Parliament will end in a little more
than two weeks. And national elections must be held by early
November.
</P>
<P>
   Kumaratunga, the Sinhalese leader who more than any other has
reached out to the Tamils, told Parliament last week that her
proposal would help end one of the world's most intractable
conflicts _ a civil war that has cost more than 60,000 lives on
this island nation of 18 million off the southern tip of India.
</P>
<P>
   It would convince the Tamils, she said, that the Sinhalese were
sincere about sharing power with them and that the Tamil people no
longer need support the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam, a group
of separatist rebels who have been fighting for a Tamil homeland in
the country's north and east for 17 years.
</P>
<P>
   But her proposal, written and rewritten during the past six
years, was a compromise that ultimately failed to satisfy the
moderate Tamil politicians who risked their lives _ as did
Kumaratunga _ in the search for a political settlement, or to
mollify the Sinhalese right wing and the influential Buddhist
clergy who feared it was a threat to the majority population.
</P>
<P>
   Nor, despite months of negotiations with the opposition United
National Party _ the country's other major Sinhalese-dominated
party _ was Kumaqrtunga's Sri Lanka Freedom Party able to achieve a
bipartisan consensus for the constitution.
</P>
<P>
   A frenetic effort by the government in recent days to collect
enough votes came up short. Kumaratunga last week proposed
increasing the number of members of Parliament in the upcoming
election to 298 from 225. Political analysts said the move was a
naked last-minute attempt to woo members of the opposition to
support the constitution with the promise they could run under her
party's banner.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition leaders also accused ministers in Kumaratunga's
government of trying to bribe its members of Parliament to defect
with promises of cash, houses and utility vehicles _ accusations
the government denied.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the tactics, the government did not get enough
crossover votes from the opposition and also discovered that some
leading Tamil moderates it had counted on were planning to vote
against the constitution.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Tuesday morning, a protest against the proposed new constitution
by hundreds Sinhalese nationalists and Buddhist monks turned into a
victory celebration. A cheer rose from the throng of monks gathered
at the gates of Parliament when their priestly leaders announced
that the vote had been postponed. The men joyfully waved placards
that called anyone who supported the constitution a traitor.
</P>
<P>
   Although the proposed constitution empowered the central
government to stomp out secessionist movements and reserved for
Buddhism ``the foremost place,'' the monks said they believed it
was a first step towards the country's division and a threat to
Sinhalese Buddhists, who make up 70 percent of the population.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is trying to divide the country and hand it over to Tamil
terrorists and stay in power all her life,'' said M. Ananda, a monk
who shielded himself from the blazing sun under a multi-colored
umbrella. ``That is her ulterior motive. We Sinhala Buddhists have
more than 2,000 years in this country. We have no other country. We
have to preserve it for future generations.''
</P>
<P>
   While the monks accused the president of going too far to
appease the Tamils, Tamil political leaders said she had not gone
far enough towards creating a federal system of government with
adequate powers for the north and eastern region that Tamils regard
as their historic homelands.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the proposed new constitution would give the
regions authority over health and education, but says such
authority must be exercised in line with national policy.
</P>
<P>
   It also deletes the description of Sri Lanka as ``a union of
regions.'' And it does not give the regions authority over publicly
owned lands _ an emotional issue for Tamils who say the central
government colonized Tamil areas by settling Sinhalese people on
government lands in past decades.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of the Tamil United Liberation Front, who had been
deeply involved in earlier efforts to shape the new constitution,
said Kumaratunga diluted it too much in her recent negotiations
with the opposition United National Party.
</P>
<P>
   Their decision not to support her was particularly poignant,
they said, since it was a member of Parliament from their party,
Neelan Tiruchelvam, who was the chief Tamil architect of the
earlier drafts _ and who was assassinated a year ago because of his
peace-making efforts. The Tamil Tiger rebels, who have killed off
many Tamil leaders who favor a political solution, are believed to
have sent the suicide bomber who killed him.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed constitution had finally made it to Parliament last
week after the spilling of what Kumaratunga called ``a river of
blood.'' Not only was Tiruchelvam killed, but Kumaratunga lost the
sight in one eye in another Tiger suicide attack in December, which
also injured the main Sinhalese author of the new constitution, her
justice minister, G. L. Peiris.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am sorry for this lady,'' said V. Anandasangaree, senior
vice president of the Tamil party, referring to the president.
``She had moved heaven and earth to find a solution to the problem,
but the UNP took her for a ride and then dropped her like a hot
potato.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
