<DOCNO> NYT20000808.0213 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 17:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5992 &Cx1f; tad-z
r p BC-POL-TICKER0809-COX     08-08 1542
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER0809-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gore, running mate start on the stump in Nashville
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Al Gore showed off his new running mate Tuesday in Nashville,
Tenn., and declared that their Democratic ticket will ``tear down a
mighty wall of division'' by making Joseph Lieberman the first
Jewish vice president of the United States. Gore compared their
quest to the election of John Kennedy as the first - and only -
Roman Catholic president in 1960. He said the Democrats made
history then, and with Lieberman's nomination, will do it again.
Lieberman praised Gore for breaking a barrier by choosing him. He
said the vice president showed his faith in the tolerance,
diversity and ``basic fairness of the American people'' by choosing
him.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT A DIFFERENCE A DAY MAKES
</P>
<P>
   A USA Today/CNN/Gallup Poll taken Monday night after Joseph
Lieberman's selection by Al Gore shows that George W. Bush's lead
has almost disappeared among registered voters. Bush's lead was
reduced to 2 points, 45-43 percent, in the poll (4 percentage point
error margin) that included Lieberman on the Democratic ticket.
That's down from 19 points among registered voters in a similar
poll taken Friday and Saturday. Gallup senior editor David Moore
says polls of registered voters are not as accurate as those of
likely voters. Moore also noted that one-day polls are subject to
errors not found in polls taken over more than a day.
</P>
<P>
   A HOT TICKET FOR HILLARY, TOO
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Clinton, trying to court New York's crucial Jewish
electorate in her Senate race against Rick Lazio, said today she's
already asked Joseph Lieberman to campaign with her. Clinton said
she and Liberman talked by phone after he was selected as Al Gore's
running mate. ``Here in New York, it's going to drive up the vice
president's numbers which will be great for the ticket,'' she said.
``I hope he'll be here, but I can't be greedy because he's got a
lot of ground to cover.''
</P>
<P>
   GOTTA GO WITH SOMEBODY WHO'S GOT A CHANCE
</P>
<P>
   The United Auto Workers decided to overlook its dissatisfaction
with Al Gore's support for normal trade relations with China and
endorse the Democrat for president. The Detroit-based union, with
1.3 million active and retired members mostly in the key
battleground states in the Midwest, said its international
executive board was unanimous in endorsing Gore. Back in May, UAW
President Stephen Yokich said his union might back Green Party
candidate Ralph Nader.
</P>
<P>
   BIGOTS WITH WEB CONNECTIONS
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore's selection of Joseph Lieberman as his vice presidential
running mate prompted a flood of anti-Semitic hate messages on the
Internet from people objecting to the fact that he is an Orthodox
Jew. The Anti-Defamation League, which monitors hate speech on the
Internet, said that offensive language and anti-Semitic slurs were
sprouting on message boards, discussion groups and e-mail lists.
The New York Times reported today that a chat room about the
Lieberman selection drew 14,000 postings _ half, at times,
attacking Lieberman's religion.
</P>
<P>
   SOME RELIEF WITH THE SETBACK
</P>
<P>
   For Sen. John Kerry of Massachusetts, there was disappointment.
For Kerry's wife, Teresa Heinz, there was pain in seeing her spouse
passed over for a job he wanted. Yet for both of them, Al Gore's
decision to choose Joseph Lieberman instead of Kerry brought an
unexpectedly liberating end to a three-month running-mate selection
process. Kerry termed the waiting process an unsettling ``kind of
limbo.'' He did, however, acknowledge in an interview with the
Boston Globe that he had started writing notes for a possible
acceptance speech at next week's convention.
</P>
<P>
   SOME UPHEAVAL WITH THE EUPHORIA
</P>
<P>
   Lynne Cheney knew her life would not be the same when a truck
toting a satellite dish and a camera suspended from a pole parked
in front of her home in a Dallas suburb soon before George W. Bush
chose her husband as his running mate. For the past few days she's
been riding a vintage train with more than 100 journalists, a slew
of Secret Service agents, dozens of 20-something campaign workers
and a mobile satellite dish for film crews. She plans to campaign
full-time with husband Dick when he separates from Bush on the
campaign trail starting today. The Cheneys will focus on the
nation's conservative voters, while Bush courts independents with
John McCain at his side.
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU WANNA BE A TOP BANANA . . .
</P>
<P>
   In the three days before the Democratic convention, President
Clinton and Hillary Clinton will be dominating Los Angeles with a
whirl of celebrity-packed fund-raisers and appearances. Even though
Clinton agreed to leave the city after addressing delegates on
Monday, the convention's opening night, the Washington Post reports
that some members of Al Gore's team, chronically anxious about
whether the president is overshadowing their man, are irritated by
Clinton's ability to command the spotlight and soak up Hollywood
money.
</P>
<P>
   FRACTURED PARTY COULD USE SOME REFORM
</P>
<P>
   Reform Party activists gathered in Long Beach, Calif., for a
national convention and a showdown over the party's future, its
presidential nomination, and the $12.5 million taxpayer dollars
that come with it. The process of deciding who gets the money began
behind closed doors _ and in a dispute in the lobby outside _ as
supporters of Pat Buchanan and party founder Ross Perot fought to
seat a committee that will take up still more disputes, among them
whether Buchanan followed the rules in the party's primary or
should be disqualified from receiving the nomination.
</P>
<P>
   HE'S CLEANING UP _ IN SEVERAL WAYS
</P>
<P>
   The Republican National Committee is launching a $3.7 million ad
campaign critical of Al Gore's handling of the environment on his
own property to air in 17 battleground states starting today and
running through the week. The ad says George W. Bush offers a
positive issue agenda while Gore is spending his time on the
attack. ``George Bush is cleaning up Texas,'' the ad says.
</P>
<P>
   SO, CAN YOU TELL THE DIFFERENCE?
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush is flourishing in the polls, but a majority of
Americans in two new surveys don't consider him to be ``a different
kind of Republican'' as claimed by his campaign. A CBS News poll
said 35 percent consider Bush a different Republican, while 52
percent said he is ``a typical Republican.'' An ABC News-Washington
Post poll had similar results on that question, with 35 percent
saying he was different and 56 percent saying he's the same as
other Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   THOMPSON REPRISING PART IN SEQUEL
</P>
<P>
   The Bush-Cheney campaign is calling on Tennessee Sen. Fred
Thompson _ Watergate lawyer-turned movie star-turned political star
_ to reprise his most recent, successful role as Republican
spinmaster. Thompson spent last week expounding on Republican
positions in a series of network interviews during the GOP
convention. This time he's been asked to be at the Democratic
convention, in his old stomping grounds, Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   THOSE OTHER FIVE STATES COULD BE CRITICAL
</P>
<P>
   Green Party candidate Ralph Nader has submitted enough
signatures to appear on 34 state ballots and hopes to be on in as
many as 45 states this fall, said campaign manager Theresa Amato.
In addition, the campaign has filed lawsuits challenging tough
ballot access laws in North Carolina, Illinois, South Dakota and
Oklahoma. The campaign also began airing a slick new TV ad, ripping
the two major party candidates and demanding that Nader be included
in the fall debates.
</P>
<P>
   DOES THE `P' STAND FOR PRISON?
</P>
<P>
   George P. Bush, the son of Florida Gov. Jeb Bush and and nephew
of George W., was, according to WSVN-TV of Miami/Fort Lauderdale,
``the subject of a 1994 Miami-Dade Police report for burglary and
criminal mischief.'' Said WSVN: ``The police report contains
allegations that George P. broke into the Killian-area home of his
ex-girlfriend. It also accuses him of driving his Ford Explorer
through two front lawns, doing an estimated $300 in property
damage.''
</P>
<P>
   $100,000? CONVENTION PETTY CASH!
</P>
<P>
   The man accused of being the ringleader of the illegal street
protests during the GOP convention had his bail reduced from $1
million to $100,000 as defendants contended that the Philadelphia
police were guilty of jailhouse brutality and city officials
maintained there was a criminal conspiracy to shut down the city.
The reputed ringleader is John Sellers, 33, leader of the Ruckus
Society of Berkeley, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   RINGLING BROS. SHOULD CHECK THEM OUT
</P>
<P>
   Two women scaled the 15-story downtown Figueroa Hotel in Los
Angeles and tried to unfurl a giant banner across from the Staples
Center denouncing corporate dominance at the Democratic convention.
Within an hour, the banner was cut down by police, and the two
climbers and two others were arrested. The banner, modeled after
the U.S. flag with corporate logos in place of stars, got snagged
on one side and was never fully unfurled.
</P>
<P>
   _ Compiled by Ernie Freda from staff and news reports.
</P>
