<HEADLINE>
PRESSING THE CASE FOR DEAD AMERICAN SLAVES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By ROBIN FINN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Corporations beware: if you were born before 1865,
Deadria C. Farmer-Paellmann is looking for slaves in your archives
and may have bad news for you.
</P>
<P>
   The sleuthing started in 1992 when, as artistic director of the
protest (a 26-hour ``drum vigil'') that halted excavation of a
17th-century African burial ground near City Hall, Farmer-Paellmann
got insider privileges to crunch a hard hat over her dreadlocks and
crash the site. There she stumbled on a scene that changed _ and
channeled _ her life's work.
</P>
<P>
   On property the government planned to convert to a parking lot
were the skeletons of some of her ancestors, the 20,000 slaves who
helped build the city where she grew up poor on public assistance
but now lives comfortably _ no apologies _ in a Second Avenue
duplex with doormen at her beck and call. After all, she's nine
months' pregnant.
</P>
<P>
   But back to the past and the deceased slaves for whom
Farmer-Paellmann, 34, is a legal advocate.
</P>
<P>
   Some skeletons were intact, many skulls bore tribal markings,
and the way she remembers it, all wore the same expression: ``They
looked like they were screaming.'' Her shock subsided only slightly
when assured by an archaeologist that decomposition caused the
grimaces.
</P>
<P>
   But first impressions don't lie, and she tends to trust hers.
That's how she wound up married to a white German who works in
corporate finance. For someone whose Afro-centric commitment
extends to her hairdo _ dreadlocks since 1990 _ that might count as
three strikes against him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was concerned there might be a perception I didn't think
black guys were good enough, but what was I supposed to do, pass
him up because he wasn't black?'' she explains. ``I looked beyond
race,'' she adds, sounding defensive. ``Plus, he treats me like a
queen.'' Plus, he supports the mission she adopted after seeing the
skeletons: pressing the case of the dead slaves of America versus
the corporations that turned a profit exploiting them.
</P>
<P>
   ``They lived, worked and died in this city, and they never got
their reparations _ it moved me,'' says Farmer-Paellmann, whose
search for ``tainted corporations'' in the Northeast has turned up
a dozen offenders. First, she wants the companies to apologize.
Second, using a tactic that echoes the German Parliament's
endorsement of a corporate-financed reparation fund for World War
II slave laborers, she wants part of their profits assigned to a
trust fund.
</P>
<P>
   If she's a little fuzzy on how this fund will be dispersed, not
to worry: so far, no one has contributed. It's been rough just
extracting apologies. But thanks to a pending alliance with two law
firms, she anticipates that her targets will soon pay her more
attention. And pay up.
</P>
<P>
   In February, in conjunction with Black History Month,
Farmer-Paellmann, a 1999 graduate of the New England School of Law,
began her offensive: she castigated Aetna, the insurance giant, for
having written policies on slaves with the owners as beneficiaries.
She also charged that the FleetBoston Financial Corp. had ties to
slavery, including loans to John Brown, the Rhode Island slave
trader whose family helped to found Brown University.
</P>
<P>
   Aetna apologized publicly in March, and The Hartford Courant,
confessing to slave advertisements in its classifieds, did the same
last month. She says that Fleet declined to deal with her.
</P>
<P>
   In the ensuing spurt of coverage, a Canadian newspaper called
her ``a moral extortionist.'' Is she?
</P>
<P>
   ``No one calls the Jewish Holocaust survivors and their
descendants moral extortionists,'' she fumes. ``I know this is
justice. People say we waited too long, but these guys were on it a
hundred years ago, the ex-slaves themselves,'' she asserts, waving
a copy of a reparations bill the Senate vetoed in 1898. ``The
government crushed it. It's tragic.''
</P>
<P>
   When her grandfather's grandparents, Clara and Able Hinds, ran
away from the rice plantation on St. Helena Island, S.C., where
they were enslaved, they did not live happily ever after.
</P>
<P>
   When Farmer-Paellmann moved with her mother and five sisters
from East New York, where the Black Panthers ran the summer lunch
program for kids but gangs ran the streets, across Brooklyn to
Bensonhurst in 1973, they didn't live too happily either. And not
just because (with a semi-deadbeat dad in the picture) they relied
on welfare.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was 7 years old and I found out that that black people were
still called nigger,''says Farmer-Paellmann, who also discovered
hers was the only black family on the block. ``The day the
neighborhood kids got back from summer camp, they saw us in the
window, threw a can at us and called us niggers, and I thought,
`Whoa.' Probably not a day went by when I didn't hear it. It seemed
like every time the window was repaired, something would get thrown
through it again.''
</P>
<P>
   Back then, Farmer-Paellmann escaped into music via a piano, a
gift from her grandmother. But she hankered, inexplicably, to be a
lawyer: ``My father used to say, `You have an excuse for
everything' and I'd say, `Dad, there's a reason for everything.'''
</P>
<P>
   Except slavery.
</P>
<P>
   ``How long are we going to stay asleep on this?''
Farmer-Paellmann asks. ``I don't mind starting this alone: I'm the
wake-up call.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
