<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 17:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5997 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-LEROY-RESTAURANTS-NYT     08-08 0629
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEROY-RESTAURANTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REALITY ON YELLOW BRICKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Warner LeRoy is the owner of Maxwell's Plum, Tavern on the Green
and the Russian Tea Room, all in New York, and the developer of
Great Adventure  in  Jackson, N.J.; this was written with Patricia
R. Olsen)  
 By WARNER LEROY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ My grandfather was Harry Warner, one of the pioneers
of the film industry. My father was Mervyn LeRoy, who produced and
directed more than 95 movies, including ``The Wizard of Oz.'' I
grew up on the back lot of the Warner Brothers studio.
</P>
<P>
   I was on all the movie sets. One day, when everyone took a lunch
break during the filming of the yellow brick road scene with the
Munchkins, I was skipping down the yellow brick road. All of a
sudden I hit the wall. I didn't realize that the road was only 12
feet long and the rest was a painted background. I was only 4, but
it was my first moment where fantasy and reality came together.
</P>
<P>
   We had a screening room in the house _ all our friends did _
with a popcorn machine and a cotton-candy machine. Paintings in my
dad's fine art collection lined the walls, and the movie projectors
were behind one wall. He'd push a button and the bottom of a
Picasso painting would lift up to allow a movie to be projected. My
Uncle Jack had the best screening room. His screen rose from the
floor. A kid could climb on top of it and rise to the ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   I also spent time on the Warner ranch, 2,000 acres in the San
Fernando Valley. My grandfather lived on 100 acres; the rest was
devoted to movie sets, with permanent fixtures of 45 cities from
around the world.
</P>
<P>
   My parents divorced when I was 7. Both their houses were always
filled with movie stars. It was nothing to come home and see Frank
Sinatra and Judy Garland singing at our piano. I didn't know there
was anything special about this. I was going to Europe by myself
when I was 11, and at 12 I visited a Paris nightclub.
</P>
<P>
   In my teens, I went to private school in Switzerland. The
beginning was a disaster because I knew no French. My classmates
were the shah of Iran, the king of Belgium and some of the
Rothschilds. My roommate was Karim, now the Aga Khan. I spent many
weekends with his family at their palazzo in Cannes. In French,
``le roi'' means ``the king,'' so whenever I'd walk down the
hallway with Karim the servants would bow to me. They didn't know.
Sometimes we'd fly to Ireland, where the family had a major racing
stable.
</P>
<P>
   At Stanford, I was student head of the drama department. After I
came East, I first worked with Garson Kanin. Off-Broadway didn't
exist; I was one of the founders. I opened a theater at 64th and
First and directed or produced plays by writers like Tennessee
Williams and Maxwell Anderson. When a coffee shop on the corner
went out of business, I decided to turn it into an open sidewalk
cafe like the ones in Paris. I spent 15 years working on
regulations with the city for sidewalk cafes.
</P>
<P>
   Maxwell's was the first New York restaurant that had an American
theme, with a massive, glass-enclosed sidewalk cafe. Back in 1966,
it was called a ``singles place,'' where women felt comfortable
coming alone. The line that spread around the block _ it reached
six people across at times _ became part of the street life. A
person could meet someone in line.
</P>
<P>
   In 1973, when I wanted to build Tavern on the Green, New York
was in trouble financially. I finally obtained the license at
midnight on New Year's Eve, the last day of John Lindsay's tenure.
Now it's the highest-grossing restaurant in America.
</P>
<P>
   I developed Great Adventure in Jackson, N.J., and five other
parks. I also rebuilt the Russian Tea Room; it took more than four
years to talk the former owner into selling it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
