<P>
   SMOKE-JUMPERS _ Smoke jumpers are tech-age consultants. Like
their namesake firefighters who parachute into a blaze, these
fix-it specialists spend 3 to 6 months repairing the business end
of high-tech startups neglected by young entrepreneurs who are
really good at designing web sites, but forget to hire bookkeepers.
One smoke jumper had to get ready for an audit of a dotcom sorting
financial records in boxes. (Joyner, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   BROADBAND _ With more and more users going to broadband what
will eventually happen to good old fashioned dialup Internet access
providers such as EarthLink and America Online. (Katz, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 35.
</P>
<P>
   SAFIR _ New York City Police Commissioner Howard Safir resigned
today to join ChoicePoint Inc., an Alpharetta, Georgia-based
company that provides background checks and other services for
business. (Grantham, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   WEBMD _ WebMD scrambled this week to counteract what it said was
an unfair and inaccurate report that alleged that Jim Clark had not
followed through on his promise to buy $200 million in WebMD
shares. The report noted that WebMD stock had soared following
Clark's promise _ only to come slowly crashing back to earth since,
while Clark has bought a relative pittance. The company claims
Clark was constrained from buying by Securities law. The columnist
in the New York Times wrote that was not the way the SEC interprets
the rules in question. (Kanell, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 15.
</P>
<P>
   DSL _ The process of extending high-speed Internet access over
phone lines in Texas and elsewhere has stressed Southwestern Bell
and its affiliate companies. One prominent Austin Internet service
provider, Jump.Net Inc., is so fed up with delays and miscues by
SBC that it has stopped taking new orders for DSL service delivered
by Bell. But on Monday a state trade association representing
Internet service providers
</P>
<P>
   ironed out a new agreement with SBC that could alleviate many
service problems. (Ladendorf, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   TOURISM _ It's on everything from buttons to saltwater taffy to
mega-oxygenated drinking water. The FLAUSA logo is part of a brand
that the private/public partnership is trying to push. (Smith, Palm
Beach Post).
</P>
<P>
   MONEYTALK _ Personal finance advice. This week: Stock market
dividends. (Ezell, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
