<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 17:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6004 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBO-HOTDOGS09-COX     08-08 1310
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-HOTDOGS09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Showboating takes over The Show
 &HT;    By Dave Andrews
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Marlins closer Antonio Alfonseca launched into his usual
post-save routine. He screamed, pounded his chest and pointed
toward the heavens. Then he glared into the Braves' dugout.
</P>
<P>
   The problem with the whole episode, which took place July25 in
Atlanta, was that Alfonseca didn't register a save. Instead he
struck out Steve Sisco, a .111 hitter, in the eighth inning with
the Marlins losing 6-4.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody in our dugout got (ticked) off after he did his
little jig,'' Atlanta third baseman Chipper Jones said. ``He stared
into our dugout with his team losing by two runs. That's showing a
guy up. I mean, who can't pitch when his team's behind?''
</P>
<P>
   From Alfonseca's ``jig'' to Houston pitcher Jose Lima's
contortions to San Francisco outfielder Barry Bonds' penchant for
not leaving the batter's box until his homers clear the wall,
players and managers say there has been a decline in traditional
baseball etiquette this season.
</P>
<P>
   Refer to it however you want: showing up a player, showboating
or showing off. By any name, players and managers say it has gotten
so bad that even players who are losing, such as Alfonseca, will
strut their stuff like they just won the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``Showing off is bad for baseball,'' Marlins manager John Boles
said. ``It's running rampant. Baseball's etiquette throughout the
years has changed. There was no fanfare back then. You didn't even
shake hands until a guy got back to the dugout (after hitting a
home run).
</P>
<P>
   ``Now you have guys ripping imaginary chain saws across their
necks after hitting a homer or you see guys doing the electric
slide after a strikeout. They get to see themselves on
`SportsCenter' doing it 70 times a day.''
</P>
<P>
   Marlins broadcaster and former major-league player Tommy Hutton
said he has seen a boom in players showing each other up, but
today's players aren't the first to do so.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the mid- to late '70s it really took off, but there's a lot
more of it now,'' Hutton said. ``Back then you had guys like Reggie
Jackson doing his curtain calls (after hitting a home run). Guys
like Mickey Rivers, Tito Fuentes and Willie Montanez had flair and
were considered hot-dogs.''
</P>
<P>
   Today opposing pitchers expertly show up hitters and vice versa.
Players are quick to criticize other teams for demonstrative
actions on the field, but what do fellow Marlins think about
Alfonseca's exuberance after a strikeout?
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not going to tell him to chill out because he's part of
this family here,'' Marlins outfielder Cliff Floyd said. ``But I
think he's showing up a hitter.''
</P>
<P>
   Alfonseca, the league leader in saves with 33, said he has heard
the criticism of his antics on the mound, especially from Jones and
Mets pitcher John Franco.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care about Atlanta or Chipper Jones,'' Alfonseca said.
``I don't care about John Franco. John Franco does his job and I do
my job. And I have a championship ring.''
</P>
<P>
   Championship rings equal clout. So does winning 20 games and
hitting 40 home runs. But Cubs catcher Joe Girardi apparently
doesn't think the Marlins have any.
</P>
<P>
   After Floyd hit a game-winning home run in the bottom of the
10th inning against the Cubs on June26, his teammates congratulated
him as he crossed home plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think for a young team they have an arrogance about them.
It's bad,'' Girardi told a South Florida radio station after the
series finale. ``I think they showed people up. I've always been
taught to play the game hard, pat yourself on the back, don't do a
dance.''
</P>
<P>
   Boles said Girardi never specified what bothered him and didn't
think the Marlins did anything excessive. Floyd said he can't
believe Girardi would make a comment like that because he plays
with Sammy Sosa.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Cubs have one of the best home-run hitters in the game,
and when he hits one he doesn't just run around the bases,'' Floyd
said. ``He does his hop and stares at it. As a pitcher what are you
going to do, hit him? No. You are just going to let him hit his 66
home runs a year and let him hop around the bases 66 times because
of who he is.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not saying Sammy is a showboat. That's his thing. He's the
man. But what I'm saying is, how can Girardi make that comment
about us? We did nothing different from another team after a guy
hits a game-winning home run. I've seen a ton this year, and I
haven't seen one team wait for the guy at the stairs of the
dugout.''
</P>
<P>
   Floyd said hitters are subjected to a double standard by
pitchers. Hitters aren't allowed to celebrate like pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't as hitters show the pitcher up because pitchers have
control over the whole situation,'' Floyd said. ``I don't think you
should have to worry about the next time you are up if you are
going to get hit in the head.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of pitchers get on my nerves, and I'm talking about
pitchers who haven't done nothing in the league, either. If we hit
a ball that goes over the wall and it's a game winner, you get
criticized or you hear the pitcher chirping at you.
</P>
<P>
   Hitters who celebrate excessively irk Marlins pitcher Ryan
Dempster.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing wrong with celebrating when you win a game, but I'm
not big fan of pumping a home run when the game isn't close,''
Dempster said. ``It's tough because you can't retaliate because if
you hit someone you'll get suspended.''
</P>
<P>
   Floyd said he doesn't celebrate excessively on the field for a
simple reason: He doesn't want to look stupid.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know if I watched the ball, glared at a pitcher or
showboated, the ball wouldn't go out of the park,'' Floyd said.
``That would be my luck. The wind would bring it back in once it
got to about 385 (feet) and I would be stuck on first base looking
stupid. That's why I just run out everything I hit and if I got a
homer I'll slow down once I get to second.''
</P>
<P>
   There is, however, one pitcher Floyd would love to show up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do owe Jose Lima and I will get him,'' Floyd said. ``When I
hit a home run off him, I am going to rub it in. I am going to ask
the good Lord to give me one home run off him. I don't care if it's
the only one I hit the rest of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did the electric slide after he struck me out with an
82-mile-per-hour changeup. (Showing off) will always come back and
bite you. I'm so happy he's stinking it up this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Lima, after a 21-win season in 1999, is 4-13 this season and
dyed his hair and goatee blond to try to break out of his slump. He
said nothing worked until he recently began being more emotional on
the mound.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I go out and strike a guy out I like to do my dances,''
Lima said. ``I get away with it because I won 21 games. I have
earned the respect in the league. I tried to change it (at the
beginning of the season) and it's not working, so I have to go back
to my old style.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't like what I do, then don't play against me that
day. Hitters get mad when you show them up but there is nothing
they can do.''
</P>
<P>
   Astros manager and former major-league pitcher Larry Dierker
said he has become immune to celebrating by players.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see Lima every fifth day and that's about as excessive as it
gets,'' Dierker said. ``He's the most emotional player I've ever
seen in 35 years in baseball. You just expect it now from him.''
</P>
<P>
   Dierker said the demonstrative actions of baseball players today
bother him and he hates when he has to tell his own players to
knock it off.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes me feel like an old man,'' said Dierker, 53. ``They
act like they don't know what I'm talking about, look at me like
I'm crazy. When I was playing, if you started yelling and screaming
at the other team, someone would get hit with a pitch. The game has
changed.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
