<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Wednesday, Aug. 9, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   Clusters of thunderstorms will dissipate early Wednesday over
the Great Lakes and Ohio Valley. More thunderstorms will erupt
across the interior Northeast during the midday and afternoon,
especially from the Appalachians to the eastern Ohio Valley as a
cold front approaches.
</P>
<P>
   Areas near the Northeast coast will have another very warm and
humid day with hazy sunshine. Thunderstorms will arrive from the
west late in the day and at night.
</P>
<P>
   The Southeast will be hot and sultry with ample sun. Scattered
afternoon thunderstorms will form near the Gulf Coast and southern
Appalachians, but most of the region will stay dry.
</P>
<P>
   Unusual heat will persist over a large area from the interior
West to the Plains. Scattered afternoon lightning storms may
exacerbate wild fires near many mountain ranges.
</P>
<P>
   Hurricane Alberto, with winds of 75 mph, will pass far north of
the Lesser Antilles by Friday.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: THE REAL SEASON
</P>
<P>
   Although the period between June 1 and Nov. 30 is the official
hurricane season in the Atlantic, the period between mid-August to
mid-October is when most tropical storms occur. Roughly 70 percent
of all Atlantic tropical storms and hurricanes form between Aug. 10
and Oct. 20, when tropical seas are warmest. Ocean temperature is
the most important factor in the development of hurricanes and
typhoons.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
