<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-CHILE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHILE'S STEP TOWARD JUSTICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even if former Chilean dictator Augusto Pinochet never stands
trial for any of the atrocities of his 17-year reign, the ruling
Tuesday by Chile's Supreme Court to strip him of his immunity
heralds a strengthening commitment to the rule of law in that
country. It also sends a warning to human-rights abusers worldwide:
Even cronies in the military and business community may not deter
justice.
</P>
<P>
   The 14-6 ruling, which upholds a lower court decision, answers
those who said the general should face a court only in Chile _ and
not in foreign countries that were home to some of his regime's
more than 3,000 victims. It was one such country, Spain, that in
1998 first ordered the extradition of General Pinochet to face
trial for crimes against Spanish citizens.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Pinochet was in England. British authorities put
him under house arrest while the nation's courts weighed the
Spanish request. Although England's highest court eventually found
his arrest lawful and his extradition was ordered, the British
government finally decided he was too ill to face extradition and
sent him home to Chile in March.
</P>
<P>
   The Chilean court showed impressive fortitude Tuesday in
standing up to the bullying tactics by Pinochet supporters after
the lower court decision in May. The military's chief of staff made
an official visit to Pinochet in a demonstration, he said, of
``institutional support'' for the leader of the 1973 coup that
seized power from the democratically elected socialist government
of Salvador Allende. Pinochet's son spoke darkly of a repeat of
1973 if the lawsuits against his father were not dropped.
</P>
<P>
   Pinochet is diabetic, has a pacemaker, and, say his doctors,
suffered two strokes in England that caused brain damage. Chilean
officials may find him as unfit to stand trial as Britain's home
secretary did. But, as Isabel Allende, daughter of the president
and now a congresswoman, said Tuesday, ``We have shed our fear of
this man. Through this case we have discovered that we are building
a real democracy in Chile.'' That is a worthy monument to the
memory of Pinochet's victims.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-08-00 1804EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000808.0230 </DOCNO>
