A6013 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-JAPAN-GANGS-(TRIMS)-N     08-08 0782
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-GANGS-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOKYO RELIEVED AFTER 6 GANGSTERS ARRESTED IN SHOOTOUT 
</HEADLINE>
   By CALVIN SIMS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Residents of this normally safe city were horrified
Monday at a shootout in an upscale business district but breathed a
sigh of relief Tuesday after police arrested six members of one of
Japan's largest organized crime syndicates in the case.
</P>
<P>
   The incident, which sent shock waves across this relatively
crime-free city of 8 million people, unfolded at 3:20 p.m. Monday,
when about 15 gangsters wielding knives and swords stormed the
office of a right-wing group with ties to the same syndicate in
Tokyo's Chiyoda district.
</P>
<P>
   Police said the gang members, who are affiliated with the
Sumiyoshi-kai, one of the three biggest organized crime syndicates
in Japan, came to collect on a loan the group owed them. The
situation exploded as three members of the right-wing group opened
fire on the gangsters, killing Tetsuo Nagashima, 52, and Hideo
Takahi, 49, whom police identified as mid-level mob bosses. Five
people were injured.
</P>
<P>
   Public shootouts are rare in Japan, and the incident was
especially troubling because it violated what has long been an
unspoken agreement with gang members. Police do not meddle in their
affairs as long as the mob operates within set boundaries in its
prostitution, gambling, and low-level extortion operations and
avoids public violence.
</P>
<P>
   The shooting also reflected growing turmoil within Japan's mob,
or yakuza. The mob has been battered both by a weak economy and by
a recent crackdown on some aspects of organized crime by the police
and community groups. Rival factions, often from the same clan, are
increasingly fighting one another for control of shrinking criminal
enterprises.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``This type of `Godfather' violence is not supposed to happen in
Japan,'' said a senior police official. ``Yes, we have organized
gangs in Japan, but like everything else in our society there are
set rules and parameters to keep the wa, or harmony.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of the recession, revenues from the gangs' legitimate
businesses like construction have dropped, along with the illegal
traffic in drugs and guns.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Of the five people injured in the shootout, four were from the
crime gang and one was from the right-wing group Sofusha, or Blue
Wind Group, which police said has 30 members and was established in
1983 by former members of gangs related to the same Sumiyoshi-kai
syndicate.
</P>
<P>
   Police said the rightist group had a business arrangement,
including cooperation on loan collection, with the other gangsters
but that relations between the two groups soured over how to divide
profits from the loan collection venture.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Sofusha is well known in Tokyo for its right-wing political
activities, especially its loud-speaker truck that has traversed
city streets demanding the return of four Russian-held islands off
the northern island of Hokkaido. In recent months, the group had
fallen on hard financial times and indicated it would disband,
police said.
</P>
<P>
   Two Sofusha members were arrested in 1988 on suspicion of
beating defendants accused of giving patients HIV-tainted blood
products.
</P>
<P>
   The right-wing group's office is located along Shinjuku-dori
Avenue near the Hanzomon district, where the Imperial Place and a
residential complex for lawmakers are situated.
</P>
<P>
   Tomonori Ikeda, a 30-year-old clerk who works in an adjacent
building, told the Japan Times newspaper that after the shooting,
he saw a man, covered with blood, running and using a cellular
phone. ``I can't believe a shooting happened here,'' Ikeda said.
</P>
<P>
   While the level of violent crime in Japan remains very low in
comparison with that in the United States and most other countries,
many Japanese have become alarmed at a recent increase in crimes,
especially by young people. Still, the streets of Tokyo and other
Japanese cities are relatively safe to walk at any hour.
</P>
<P>
   In March, authorities expressed concern over a series of
firebombing attacks against telephone dating clubs _ places where
men come to arrange for sexual encounters with prostitutes. Police
said the bombings were the result of increasing competition between
rival gangs related to Yamaguchi-gumi, Japan's largest crime
syndicate.
</P>
<P>
   In one attack, four patrons burned to death in the southern port
city of Kobe after gang members threw a gasoline bomb inside a
telephone dating club. The club's owners had refused to pay
protection money to a gang that was impinging on an affiliate's
turf, police said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-08-00 1806EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000808.0231 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 18:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6016 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      08-08 0862
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     THE AMERICAN POLL PARADE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARIANNE MEANS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ On Monday, the headline on the front page of USA
Today said: ``Bush lead on Gore grows to 17 points.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, USA Today reported that Texas Gov. George W. Bush's
lead had almost disappeared. Bush was only 2 points ahead of Vice
President Al Gore, within the statistical margin of error.
</P>
<P>
   The sudden shift in sentiment between the poll conducted after
the Republican National Convention and the quickie reaction to
Gore's selection of Connecticut Sen. Joseph Lieberman to be his
running mate is startling, but not surprising.
</P>
<P>
   Post-convention bounces don't always last, and the signals they
send can be contradictory. For instance, Bush has gained among
moderates, white women, middle-aged voters, independents and
college graduates. Yet barely 35 percent of those responding to the
USA Today/CNN/Gallup survey agreed with the campaign theme that
Bush is a ``different kind of Republican'' and 56 percent said he
is ``pretty much the same as other top Republicans.'' No clear
message there, except that a lot of voters are confused.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, 88 percent in the overnight post-Lieberman poll said
the fact he is Jewish would make no difference in their vote. Yet
the media were full of speculation about the potential impact of
his religion. Inescapably, this is a subject that will be on many
people's minds and debated in living rooms all over the country.
</P>
<P>
   And then, of course, there is Gore. It's his name at the top of
the ticket, not Lieberman's. Even though he has been vice president
for nearly eight years, voters don't know him very well. The
Republicans naturally painted a grim picture of him as President
Clinton's toady; no wonder he hasn't done well in polls. At his own
convention next week Gore gets equal time to portray Bush as
daddy's boy and present a more inspiring image of himself. The
political dynamics will change again. And again, and again.
</P>
<P>
   The polls are bound to go up and down and over and under
regularly during the coming campaign, in response to unfolding
events. Presidential races in which the candidates are so
mismatched that the outcome seems preordained are rare _ and this
is not one of them.
</P>
<P>
   And in this tight, closely-matched race the only poll that
ultimately matters is the one on election day.
</P>
<P>
   Polls taken now lack the crucial element of extended comparison
between the two tickets and their issues. They are driven by
momentary public whim, which is notoriously fickle. And results may
vary depending upon whether registered voters or only those likely
to vote are surveyed.
</P>
<P>
   The poll taken in the immediate afterglow of the successful
Republican convention but before the Democrats had a chance to
respond could never last, despite the self-congratulatory glee of
GOP backers. This was not the final word.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, a poll taken in the excited hours after a dramatic,
unprecedented veep pick, before voters have a chance to think about
what it might mean, reflects a transitory emotion. Lieberman is
hardly a household word; voters have yet to see him in action. Were
they really impressed or simply caught up in the excitement of the
moment?
</P>
<P>
   It would be sensible if voters would just ignore polls until we
get close to election day. But they fascinate us, because we love
the horse race aspect of politics, measuring each contestant
against the other as they trot along.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, you say, what about self-fulfilling prophecies? If we keep
hearing Bush is ahead, or Gore is ahead, won't we decide it's all
settled and vote accordingly? This is too convoluted to interpret.
Some supporters who think their man is losing might stay home in
despair. Or they might get angry and rush to the polls to help him.
Or supporters who think their man is winning might think their vote
is not needed. Or they might rush to the polls to join the
bandwagon. This sort of thing is unknowable.
</P>
<P>
   The private polls of the candidates serve a different purpose.
The Bush camp likes to denounce Gore as driven by poll numbers and
political calculation but in truth both men carefully monitor how
their words and deeds are playing with the public. They would be
fools not to do so. An uninformed candidate is a candidate who
makes needless mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   They tailor their words and their policies to appeal to the most
people and offend the least people. We all know this; we weren't
born yesterday. But this is OK. It may not be bold political
leadership but it has proven over time to be the way to get
elected. A democracy requires some attention be paid to what voters
want.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has consistently tried to ignore the polls in public,
particularly because he has sometimes been behind and never far
ahead. The Bush team has also dismissed the polls, predicting they
would narrow as the campaign progressed. They may have been trying
to lower expectations but they also seem to have been correct.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means can be reached at the e-mail address means(at)
hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
