<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 18:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6022 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-MALAYSIA-ANWAR-510&AMP;AD     08-08 1157
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MALAYSIA-ANWAR-510&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIAN COURT CONVICTS ANWAR OF SODOMY, CONCLUDING TWO-YEAR
DRAMA 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds., fyi, skedded earlier as MALAYSIA-IBRAHIM) 
 By MARK LANDLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia _ The widely expected sodomy conviction
early Tuesday of Malaysia's former deputy prime minister, Anwar
Ibrahim, could snuff out the career of a charismatic leader who was
seen as one of the rising stars in Asian politics.
</P>
<P>
   The terse ruling capped a long, corrosive legal battle, and came
on top of a previous conviction for corruption.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Arifin Jaka found Anwar guilty of sodomy and sentenced him
to nine years in prison. He declared that Anwar had committed
``despicable acts in our society,'' and deserved the ``utmost
condemnation.''
</P>
<P>
   The verdict marked the end of a two-year drama that had riveted
this nation of 22 million, and had repercussions beyond it. Anwar's
trial called into question the motives of Malaysia's leaders and
credibility of its courts. It also exposed a deeply traditional
country to a relentlessly sordid spectacle.
</P>
<P>
   Anwar, 52, reacted with a mix of coolness and anger. He smiled
and hugged members of his family who had gathered in the courtroom,
but later exploded in frustration, saying: ``Bloody, rotten
judiciary!''
</P>
<P>
   Before the sentence was read, Anwar delivered a withering
denunciation of his former boss, Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad.
He accused Mahathir of orchestrating a conspiracy to destroy him,
and said Malaysia's judiciary had demeaned itself by doing his
bidding.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dr. Mahathir's lust for power is insatiable,'' said Anwar,
brushing aside angry protests from the judge. ``He will lie and
force others to lie.''
</P>
<P>
   The judge found Anwar's adopted brother, Sukma Darmawan, 39,
guilty of sodomy as well, sentencing him to six years and four
strokes with a rattan cane. Anwar escaped the caning because that
penalty is not given to people older than 49. Both men were
convicted of engaging in homosexual relations with Azizan Abu
Bakar, a former driver for the family.
</P>
<P>
   Anwar's lawyers said they would appeal the sentence, which one
described as ``mind-boggling.'' Although the judge could have
imposed a 20-year term, Anwar said he was expecting six years.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of Anwar predicted the harsh sentence would unleash a
new wave of political unrest here.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to sustain the opposition movement to Dr.
Mahathir,'' said Chandra Muzaffar, the deputy president of the
National Justice Party, which was formed last year after Anwar's
first conviction. ``People are going to see it as another example
of Mahathir's cruelty.''
</P>
<P>
   But outside the Moorish-style courthouse, there was little
evidence of the outrage that drew thousands into the streets after
the first verdict. This morning, several hundred supporters of
Anwar gathered at a mosque behind the courthouse. A few carried a
banner that said, ``Free Anwar.''
</P>
<P>
   The government had threatened to crack down on any pro-Anwar
demonstrations. That warning, combined with a formidable array of
riot police and water-cannon trucks, seemed to work. Police quickly
dispersed the protesters, arresting at least 12 people amid a
handful of scuffles.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The verdict will do little for Malaysia's tarnished reputation
overseas. Amnesty International and other human rights groups
condemned the decision, as did the New Zealand government. Human
Rights Watch, based in New York, said, ``The verdicts are another
blow to justice in Malaysia.''
</P>
<P>
   Anwar's case has always been about more than his sexual
practices. From the day he was dismissed by Mahathir in September
1998, Anwar has been waging a war against his former mentor for the
soul of Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
   Mahathir, 74, a onetime country doctor, presided over a great
Asian success story _ transforming a fractured, ethnically polyglot
former British colony into a well-oiled economy. He had carefully
groomed Anwar, a Muslim youth leader with Western sophistication,
to be his successor.
</P>
<P>
   But when the regional economic crisis tore through Malaysia's
palm plantations and semiconductor factories, the two men began to
clash over policy. Anwar favored the remedies of the International
Monetary Fund, while Mahathir inveighed against foreign currency
traders.
</P>
<P>
   Some economists argue that the differences between the two men
were overblown. But there is no question that Mahathir felt
threatened. Rather than fading away _ or being toppled like his
Indonesian counterpart, Suharto _ the prime minister made a
pre-emptive strike.
</P>
<P>
   The nature of the charges against Anwar guaranteed that his
trial would be a lurid affair. Homosexuality is taboo in this
Muslim country, and Malaysians were alternately enthralled and
repelled by the talk of furtive encounters and soiled mattresses.
But as the trial dragged on, public interest flagged.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of Anwar said the sexual misconduct case was
hopelessly flimsy. The government prosecutors switched the dates on
which Anwar was supposed to have committed sodomy three times.
Azizan, the former driver, said he had been asked by the police to
testify to a new date.
</P>
<P>
   But Arifin said, ``I'm satisfied the prosecution has proven its
case against both accused beyond reasonable doubt.''
</P>
<P>
   Anwar must serve the nine-year sentence after his six years for
corruption. Even if both terms are reduced by one-third for good
behavior, Anwar faces a decade behind bars. Under Malaysian law, he
is forbidden to run for office for five years after his release.
</P>
<P>
   Mahathir, by contrast, was re-elected handily last November. His
coalition amassed a huge majority in Parliament. The prime
minister, who has been in power 19 years and is Asia's longest
ruling leader, said that this term will be his last.
</P>
<P>
   Anwar's allies noted Mahathir had paid a price for his attacks _
losing many of the Malay voters who were the bedrock of his party,
the United Malays National Organization. Disgusted by the trial,
these voters switched their allegiance to Malaysia's Islamic party
in the elections.
</P>
<P>
   Still, even Anwar's most fervent supporters acknowledge their
jailed hero can no longer be the driving force of the anti-Mahathir
movement. ``He was very important to the `reformasi' movement,''
said Chandra of the Justice Party. ``But the struggle for change
needs to go beyond Anwar.''
</P>
<P>
   For her part, Anwar's wife is confronting the prospect of life
without her husband. Sitting in the sun-drenched living room of her
home here last week, Dr. Wan Azizah said she wanted her children to
recover a sense of normalcy after the turmoil of the past two
years. She has urged her eldest daughter to stay out of politics to
concentrate on her college studies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish in my heart that Anwar won't spend years and years in
jail,'' Wan Azizah said wistfully. ``But I feel this doom looming
over me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
