<HEADER>
A6027 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TV-LIVE-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      08-08 0879
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-LIVE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`LIVE THROUGH THIS': ANCIENTS MAKING NEW HISTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   By NEIL GENZLINGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For several reasons, ``Live Through This,'' the dramatic series
that has its premiere Wednesday night on MTV, ought to come with a
sort of reverse parental advisory. Something like ``May not be
suitable for viewing by people who were at or near the original
Woodstock.''
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, there's the premise of the show: a once-mighty
rock band reunites to go on tour, with the band members taking
along their children, ages 16 to 23. But the jarring thing, for
viewers of a certain age, is that the heyday of this has-been band
was in the late '70s and early '80s. That, apparently, is what
today's MTV audience thinks of as ancient rock history. Ouch.
Despite what Mick Jagger sang (in 1964), time, time, time is not on
our side.
</P>
<P>
   Also unsettling, for the geezer-age viewer, is the dialogue of
the show's young adults, which is drenched in slang of the moment,
or perhaps it's slang that the writers just made up hoping that it
would become slang of the moment by the time the show hit the air.
``He's such a buzzkill'' and ``That would be totally spank'' and
``He would be stoked to see me,'' and so on.
</P>
<P>
   After a half-hour of this, it begins to become unclear what's
slang and what isn't. When a band member, Drake Taylor (Ron Lea),
tells his son, Travis (Matthew Carey), that one of the group's old
CD's now sells for $100 on eBay, Travis replies, ``Steep.'' Is he
merely saying, ``That price seems steep''? Or is ``steep'' slang
for, ``I hate you, and the all-black outfit doesn't work with your
paunch''? Hard to say. In any case, the effect is to cause the
viewer to start seeing slang everywhere _ in the kitchen utensils,
in the mop closet. It's cuisinarting, to say the least.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, ``Live Through This,'' MTV's first attempt at an
hourlong dramatic series, has no intention of appealing to anyone
old enough to have been at Woodstock, or even anyone old enough to
have been fans of the Jackson Decker Band, the fictional group in
the show. The aim is much younger, and the show's writers go for
the target in a way that is almost manipulative. ``Live Through
This'' (a 1994 album by Courtney Love's band, Hole, has the same
title) is the world as a teen-ager might create it: the young
people are the smart ones, their parents the ones in need of
shepherding and discipline.
</P>
<P>
   Most obvious is that the band's tour is organized and run by
Chase (Tom Lock), the son of Keith Rooney (David Nerman), one of
the band's guitarists. He has an MBA from Stanford, a knack for
resolving crises, and more sense than the four band members
combined. When he's not lecturing one of them the way a parent
might lecture a wayward child, he keeps tabs on his sister, Olivia
(Jessica Welch), who is not quite as straight-and-narrow as he is.
</P>
<P>
   There is also Lu (Sarah Manninen), who selflessly keeps her
mother, the band's torch singer (played by Jennifer Dale), away
from alcohol and such, or at least tries to. Even sweet and
innocent Darby (Jane McGregor), who at 16 is the youngest of the
children on the tour, turns out to be a parental life-saver. Though
her dad, Rick Parsons (Bruce Dinsmore), the group's drummer, is now
neurotically overprotective, it emerges that back in the glory days
he was the band's bad boy; it was Darby's birth that jolted him off
of the Hendrix-Joplin-Etc. Highway.
</P>
<P>
   Consciously or unconsciously, the young-is-better worldview of
``Live Through This'' also extends to the performers. The actors
who play the band members seem to be sleepwalking much of the time,
and who can blame them, since they're playing stereotypes. The
younger actors are also playing stereotypes but are more spank
about it.
</P>
<P>
   In truth, the show would have been much better, downright fun
even, as a comedy. As a drama, despite the original premise, it
falls back on the same old parent-child tensions that have already
been explored, and better, by other shows. Still, with the
soap-operalike possibilities for couplings and recouplings, the
music and all that swell slang _ well, it's easy to be hoovered by
the show, if you're not too waxy-buildup.
</P>
<P>
   If only the dialogue were a little less self-consciously hip.
``Drake's obsessed with that guitar,'' Lu tells Travis in one
scene. ``Once he put it up for auction at a Save the Music benefit,
then yanked it at the last second. Sting still won't talk to him.''
</P>
<P>
   That Sting _ he's always going brillo.
</P>
<P>
   BROADCAST NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   LIVE THROUGH THIS
</P>
<P>
   At 10 p.m. Wednesday on MTV
</P>
<P>
   Stewart Harding, producer; Michael Siry, line producer; Bert
Tougas, director of photography; Sylvain Gingras, production
designer. A Telescene Film Group production. Bernie Lechowick, Paul
Painter, Robin Spry and Michael Yudin, executive producers; John
Miller, MTV executive in charge of production, and Jackie French,
director of original programming and series development.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Jane McGregor (Darby Parsons), Jessica Welch (Olivia
Rooney), Sarah Manninen (Lu Baker), Tom Lock (Chase Rooney),
Matthew Carey (Travis Williams), Bruce Dinsmore (Rick Parsons),
David Nerman (Keith Rooney), Jennifer Dale (Annie Baker) and Ron
Lea (Drake Taylor). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-08-00 1819EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000808.0237 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 18:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6032 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-IRAN-SINGER-NYT &LR;      08-08 1109
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAN-SINGER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARTS ABROAD: WORLD TOUR FOR A DIVA LONG BANNED FROM SINGING 
</HEADLINE>
   By HADANI DITMARS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   VANCOUVER, British Columbia _ In Pacific Coliseum sports
stadium, the Iranian pop diva Googoosh was about to begin her
second public performance in more than 20 years. Dressed in an
elegant simple blue silk dress reminiscent of her days as a Tehran
cabaret star, and encircled by replica pillars from the ancient
Persian site of Persepolis, she paused reflectively.
</P>
<P>
   Before launching into ``Gharibeh Ashenah'' (``A Stranger,
Familiar''), an old favorite from her '70s heyday, Googoosh, bathed
in green, white and red light, the colors of the Iranian flag,
proclaimed to the crowd, ``I wish that all Iranians could be here
with me tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Her words, which were met with a resounding cheer from the
thousands in the sports stadium, were at once defiant and wistful;
they expressed her wish that her fans in Iran could also hear her
live performance. For Googoosh, along with all other Iranian women,
has been banned from singing in public since the 1979 revolution.
</P>
<P>
   In Iran, Googoosh, 50, is not merely a pop star. She is a singer
whose fame and post-revolutionary exile from the public eye have
turned her into a national icon. When, later in the program, she
sang the song ``Captive Land'' from her new CD, ``Zartosht'' (which
she recently recorded in Toronto after the music was recorded in
Tehran), the allusions to imprisonment, pain and heartbreak could
have referred to her own life story as well as the plight of her
countrymen.
</P>
<P>
   For Googoosh's life _ which has traversed harassment by the
family of the shah and 20 years of isolation in post-revolutionary
Iran _ has become for many Iranians a metaphor of their own.
</P>
<P>
   But, auspiciously perhaps, and in a possible sign of the power
of reformist currents in Iran, Googoosh was recently given
permission to travel abroad. In the last few years the Iranian
authorities have softened their hard-line stance on pop music.
While the sale of pop music cassettes and CDs is still illegal,
possession is now allowed. In addition, some male pop singers have
been permitted to perform in public under certain circumstances.
While it is unclear whether President Mohammad Khatami himself gave
the green light for her public performances abroad, there were no
conditions attached to her departure. On July 29 Googoosh began a
world tour that will include dates in North America, Europe and the
Middle East. She is scheduled to appear in Los Angeles on Aug. 19
and at the Nassau Coliseum in Uniondale, N.Y., on Aug. 26.
</P>
<P>
   Googoosh's husband, the filmmaker Massoud Kimiai, is
accompanying her, and with a brother in Toronto and a grown son and
grandchild in Los Angeles, there is much speculation among Iranians
that she may eventually settle in North America.
</P>
<P>
   Despite recent reformist tendencies, it is still not known how
the singer, whose full name is Faegheh Atashin, would be received
if she does return to Iran. Already her world tour has been
condemned by outraged fundamentalists. And Kimiai was recently
summoned to appear in an Iranian court to defend the morality of
one of his films.
</P>
<P>
   But for her thousands of expatriate Iranian fans, hearing
Googoosh live after two decades of silence is a dream come true.
Her fame has often been compared to that of Elvis Presley in the
West.
</P>
<P>
   Lyrically and musically her work is complex. She has worked with
the best arrangers and poets in Iran.
</P>
<P>
   Her songs are a blend of East and West, rooted in serpentine
Persian melodies but often backed up by danceable bass lines and
electric guitars and, more recently, propelled by Gipsy Kings-style
rumbas. At the same time one senses in Googoosh's haunting alto the
influence of the French chanson, with her gift for deeply emotional
and compelling interpretation.
</P>
<P>
   With the post-revolutionary ban on public singing by women _ the
authorities contend that women's voices could corrupt men _ she
went from being a pop diva with her own palace, to singing only
occasionally for small groups of women in private. But her impact
on the Iranian public continued.
</P>
<P>
   Her voice and image have been kept alive by a huge fan base
inside and outside of Iran. There are several Web sites in Farsi
and English that offer video clips from her films and television
appearances.
</P>
<P>
   In Googoosh's appearance here in Vancouver, after an inaugural
one in Toronto, her fans were ecstatic.
</P>
<P>
   ``After all this time, she's only gotten better,'' said Mehrdad
Hashemi, 33, one of some 50,000 Iranians in Vancouver and one of
the 10,000 at the concert. ``We say she is like a carpet from
Kerman. The older and more worn down it gets, the more valuable it
becomes. She is precious to us now.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She has suffered, but she has triumphed,'' said Tahareh
Zahrah, a 42-year-old mother of two who last saw Googoosh perform
in 1977. ``Googoosh was my idol so this is a real thrill. Growing
up, we all used to imitate her _ what she wore, how she acted. She
used to change her hairstyle and her look as often as Madonna. We
just loved her.''
</P>
<P>
   Zahrah's friend Nahid Yusefi said that to this day her presence
was still palpable in Iran. ``When I went back home in 1995, you
could hear her old songs everywhere, in taxis, in the parks, even
in public buildings, you could hear the melodies,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what Googoosh meant to him, Zahra's 21-year-old son, Omid,
who was born just after the revolution and grew up in Canada, said,
``She represents the real spirit of what was the true country
called Iran.'' One factor in Googoosh's continued cult status is
veneration by a generation of young people who were not even born
when she last performed in public.
</P>
<P>
   Some left-wing critics of the Iranian government living abroad
object to her tour, arguing that it helps present a softer, false
picture of Iranian rule. And for fundamentalist elements inside and
outside Iran, she is still considered decadent. Opposition to the
tour has also been expressed by some Iranian pop singers in Los
Angeles who, after 20 years of struggling to make it in what they
refer to as Tehrangeles, are at least temporarily being upstaged by
a star from the past.
</P>
<P>
   But Rahmin Mahjouri, editor of Payvand, a leading Farsi weekly
in Vancouver, said that he believed making artists into political
apologists was unfair. ``Googoosh is simply doing what she loves
best _ performing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   This was certainly not overlooked by fans in Vancouver, who
seemed to cheer the loudest when she sang from her new CD, ``Why is
it these days that singing is a crime?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
