<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 18:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6036 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-RETIREMETN0809-COX     08-08 1515
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RETIREMETN0809-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Baby boomers heading for a nontraditional type of retirement
 &HT;    By Douglas Kalajian
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. - The generation that changed America in
the '60s is certain to change it again as the baby boomers enter
their own 60s.
</P>
<P>
   Exactly how is a multibillion-dollar question.
</P>
<P>
   The most fawned-over consumers in history are being asked again
and again what they'd like to do, where they'd like to live and how
they want to be treated in their leisure years. Just how leisurely
those years will be remains to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   One survey found that eight in 10 intend to keep working; others
show similar results.
</P>
<P>
   ``The leading-edge baby boomers are likely to work at least 20
hours a week,'' says Charles F. Longino Jr., professor of
gerontology at Wake Forest University in North Carolina. ``They'll
be returning for second careers. They'll be going back to school.''
</P>
<P>
   So much for bingo.
</P>
<P>
   Longino, who has made a continuing study of retirement trends,
is one of many who see the boomers headed for an oxymoronic future:
active retirement. Some will work to pay the bills; others to keep
from climbing the walls. After packing more rest-and-recreation
time into their working lives than any generation before, they'll
be more inclined toward surfboards than shuffleboard - and less
inclined to stay put.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been a very mobile generation,'' Longino says.
</P>
<P>
   Some will be adventurous in picking out-of-the-way destinations,
from the once-rural American South to jungle-fringed beaches of
South America. They'll be every bit as demanding, but they'll
demand features foreign to most of today's retirement homes.
</P>
<P>
   Del Webb Corp., the Arizona-based retirement builder, surveyed
boomers across the nation last year and found that nearly 60
percent would rather have a gourmet kitchen than a swimming pool;
most men (and many women) want a home office; and more than half
want a house at least as big as the one they live in now.
</P>
<P>
   Making mass predictions about boomers isn't easy because they
aren't one mass, just the coincidental byproducts of postwar
prosperity and pent-up passions. The label covers everyone born
between 1946 and 1964. The oldest will reach retirement age in less
than 12 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the most diverse generation in history,'' says John
Rother, legislative director of AARP. ``It is economically diverse.
It is ethnically diverse. There's also considerable diversity of
attitudes in men and women.''
</P>
<P>
   The age spread creates its own diversity: The oldest were born
before most Americans owned a television. The youngest were born
after President Kennedy was assassinated.
</P>
<P>
   America's over-60 population is already bigger than ever, at
more than 30 million. Many will still be going strong when the
boomers push the over-60 figure to 50 million by 2015. Late
arrivals will bring the swell to full strength in 2030 at 65
million.
</P>
<P>
   By that time, the boomers who rocked Woodstock and protested
Vietnam will be in their 80s, while the ones who grew up with the
Brady Bunch will still have to show IDs to get into senior citizen
buffet night.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever they want, at whatever age, the boomers are likely to
get it. Instead of being wheeled - or pushed - boomer retirees will
strut into their later years with a different attitude: More
assertive, more engaged in the world around them. Many will also be
more affluent than previous retirees.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll have the tools to make choices no one had before,''
says Rother.
</P>
<P>
   For most of history, retirement presented no choices at all
because it didn't exist.
</P>
<P>
   In Colonial times, retirement was for the rich, who didn't have
to wait until they were old. Otherwise, you worked in the mill or
the shop or the field until you either died behind the plow or
someone who wanted your job shoved you out of the way.
</P>
<P>
   Civil War veterans were probably the first mass group to get
pensions, but retirement still wasn't even a dream for small-town
shopkeepers and farmers as the 20th century approached. Few had to
worry long: Average life expectancy was about 50 in 1900, and only
about one in 25 Americans was 65 or older.
</P>
<P>
   Calls for old-age security had become standard fare for labor
organizers and social reformers by the end of World War I - the
idea had already taken hold in Europe - but who could hear the
clamor over the Roar of the Twenties?
</P>
<P>
   Then, suddenly, stock-market crash of 1929 made retirement an
unwelcome reality for millions. More than a dozen states enacted
old-age plans among other relief measures, but most were restricted
to the truly poor, and few were paid enn previous generations
missed: employer-subsidized stock plans, IRAs and considerable
equity in their homes.
</P>
<P>
   Some, however, won't be as lucky.
</P>
<P>
   Up to a third of boomers, including many women and minorities,
don't have pensions or health insurance, Rother says. ``A lot of
divorced women haven't saved for retirement,'' he says. ``Unless
something changes, they'll arrive at 65 with very few options
except to continue working.''
</P>
<P>
   Some boomers may think they're in better shape than they really
are.
</P>
<P>
   An annual survey released in May showed that most have some sort
of retirement strategy or retirement savings and that more
Americans than ever are very confident of having enough money to
last to the end of their lives.
</P>
<P>
   The same survey showed that most thought they'd need to save
only $50,000, that almost a quarter of all workers had actually
saved less than $10,000 and that many were underestimating their
expected life spans by 10 or more years.
</P>
<P>
   Worse: Two out of 10 boomers hadn't begun to save at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, there are signs that some of the confidence may be
misplaced,'' says Danny Devine of the Employee Benefit Research
Institute, a Washington think tank that conducts the annual survey
along with the affiliated nonprofit American Savings Education
Council.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Devine says the good omens in the survey outweigh the
bad.
</P>
<P>
   ``More people are paying attention to retirement,'' he says.
``They're beginning to understand that they have to make a plan.
They're taking small steps. Confidence comes from doing that.''
</P>
<P>
   WEB SITES TO PREPARE YOU FOR RETIREMENT
</P>
<P>
   Retirement isn't an impossible goal. All it will take is money -
very nearly as much as you make now.
</P>
<P>
   The experts say you'll need at least 70 percent of your
pre-retirement income. But that won't leave much wiggle room, and
all the surveys say you plan to do plenty of wiggling.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, the kids will be done with college. But will the house be
paid for? What about that cabin in North Carolina? What about jet
skis and greens fees? And do you really expect that Lexus to last
as long as you do?
</P>
<P>
   You'll most likely be around for at least 16 years after you
cash the first Social Security check, maybe a lot longer - plenty
of time to wear out just about everything you own. So, better to
figure you'll need closer to 90 percent of your pre-retirement
income. Here are some of the best places on the Web to start your
figuring.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Social Security Administration (www.ssa.gov): You won't find a
detailed account of your benefits, but you can request one
(1-800-772-1213). Meanwhile, you can use online calculators to work
up estimates and to find out when you'll be eligible for full
benefits. (Remember: The full retirement age is
</P>
<P>
   increasing in phases for anyone born in 1938 or later.)
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The American Savings Education Council (www.asec.org) has
printable and interactive calculators that will help you estimate
how far you'll have to stretch your savings after figuring in your
company pension and investment income. It also has tools to help
determine how much additional savings you can pile up in the time
that's left. There's also an online savings personality quiz that
can tell you how likely you are to blow it all before then. Also
available at the site: The new Retirement Confidence Survey
results, so you can see how others are doing.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The federal Administration on Aging
(www.aoa.dhhs.gov/retirement) offers a bonanza of information on
retirement finances, taxes and other advice, plus links to many
more retirement-related sites. So does the U.S. Department of
Labor's Pension and Welfare Benefits Administration
(www.dol.gov/dol/pwba).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  MSN Money Central (http://moneycentral.msn.com/home.asp) has
lots of information about money and investing, but one of its most
entertaining features (in a morbid sort of way) is a
life-expectancy calculator
(http://moneycentral.msn.com/investor/calcs/nexpect/main.asp) that
crunches much more detailed information than most. Don't expect
your date of death, but do expect to be surprised by how long you
may hang around - all the way to 102, for example, if you're a
reasonably healthy and trim woman of 45.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Other retirement-info sites: www.aarp.org,
www.gopbi.com/business/finance/calcs7.html
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Email: dougkalajian(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
