A6037 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-WEBMD0809-COX     08-08 0559
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEBMD0809-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Healtheon/WebMD responds to column
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - Healtheon/WebMD scrambled this week to counteract what
it said was an unfair and inaccurate report alleging that Jim Clark
had not followed through on his promise to buy $200 million in
WebMD shares.
</P>
<P>
   After making the vow, Clark _ who founded Healtheon before its
merger with WebMD _ bought $8.78 million worth of stock in April
and $311,000 in shares the next month. Clark made the promise April
7, professing continued confidence in the company even as its stock
_ which once traded above $100 a share _ languished below $22. As
news came that legendary Silicon Valley investor Clark was still
bullish, company stock jumped to $29.19.
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times column Sunday by Gretchen Morgenson noted that,
``at the rate Mr. Clark is buying, it will take roughly five and a
half years for him to buy $200 million worth of stock.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark said subsequent purchases were limited by securities
regulations meant to prevent either fraud or stock manipulation.
After assessing that defense, Morgenson concluded Clark and the
company had done a disservice to investors. Shareholders should
have been warned Clark's purchase of stock was not going to happen
as promised, she wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The suggestion of improper conduct made officials at
Healtheon/WebMD nearly apoplectic. They worked into the night
Sunday crafting a response, which was released the next morning.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Dennison, executive vice president and general counsel for
Healtheon/WebMD, said the column was peppered with errors. He said
Clark was constrained by the rules. ``It is not a matter of
interpretation. This is black-letter law.''
</P>
<P>
   Insider trading restraints are triggered when the official has
knowledge that _ if public _ could move the stock either up or
down, information that might change an investor's judgment on the
stock. Dennison found especially annoying the suggestion that the
company or Clark should alert investors to those times when he was
under restraint. ``You'd start all sorts of rumors. ... And you are
misleading the market. At best, this is incrediblurchases would be
subject to securities law.
</P>
<P>
   About 10 percent of the civil actions brought each year by the
Securities and Exchange Commission involve insider trading, said
spokesman John Heinie. Heinie said he could not comment on specific
cases. What an investor is permitted to do ``depends on the facts,
the circumstances.''
</P>
<P>
   David Stockton, who specializing in securities law for
Kilpatrick Stockton in Atlanta, said:
</P>
<P>
   ``If he (Clark) is in possession of non-public, material
information, then he shouldn't be trading in his company's stock.
But it's not black and white. What's material? It's difficult to
say.''
</P>
<P>
   An attorney's instinct is to urge caution, Stockton said.
Stockton said it appears the lawyers gave Clark good advice not to
trade _ but it is not precisely true to say that Clark was legally
required to refrain.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the column and the controversy did not dramatically
move the stock, which has fallen still further since in April.
Healtheon/WebMD was up 6.25 cents on Monday, dipping by the same
amount Tuesday to close at $12.63 a share.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
