<P>
   MANHATTAN-REAL-ESTATE (New York) _ Manhattan's over-the-top real
estate market, on a fast boil for more than four years, has lost
its frenzied upward momentum and seems to be cooling down. By
Tracie Rozhon.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-SWIMSUITS (Indianapolis) _ When the Olympic trials begin
here on Wednesday, American swimmers will make as much news for
what they are wearing as for what records they set in preparation
for the 2000 Summer Games next month in Sydney, Australia. A
bodysuit that fits athletes from neck to toe and comes with sleeves
has revolutionized the sport. At least 10 world records have been
set worldwide this year in the new swim suits. Speedo's version is
called the Fastskin suit, which contains tiny, v-shaped ridges that
allow water to pass over the swimmer more efficiently. The
super-stretch fabric also compresses a swimmer's muscles, therefore
reducing the buildup of lactic acid that causes fatigue. Swimmers
also say the suit lifts them higher in the water and makes it
easier to stroke. By Jere Longman.
</P>
<P>
   ENERGY-COST-IMPACT (Brooklyn, Iowa) _ For the poor, mounting
fuel prices and heating bills inflict painful choices _ especially
in cities without adequate public transportation and in small towns
and suburbs where long distances make driving a necessity. Here in
Iowa, according to a new study by the state Department of Human
Rights, many low-income families who faced higher rates for natural
gas during last year's relatively mild winter cut back on food,
health care, phones and electricity to pay for heat. With prices
rising, the department says that situation could worsen this year.
By Neela Banerjee.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
