<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 18:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6040 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-GERMANY-WINE-2TAKES-N     08-08 0627
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GERMANY-WINE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIEBFRAUMILCH: FAREWELL 
</HEADLINE>
   By ERIC ASIMOV    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   RUEDESHEIM, Germany _ At Georg Breuer, a leading wine estate in
this small town on the Rhine, I tasted three bottles of Ruedesheim
Berg Schlossberg, 1998, '97 and '90 vintages. Each had aromas that
were almost floral, and each was powerfully dry. The youngest was
almost mouth-puckering, but with age, the wines seemed to mellow,
emphasizing their extraordinary balance.
</P>
<P>
   Dry is hardly the description most Americans imagine when they
think of German wines. The images that arise are sugary
liebfraumilch, which was once a popular beginner's wine; fruity,
vibrant rieslings; and powerful trockenbeerenausleses, some of the
world's grandest (and most unpronounceable) dessert wines.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, what do the Germans themselves drink? Dry wines.
Occasionally, the wines are as exquisite as the Breuers. But as I
found on visits to almost two dozen wineries in the Rhine and Mosel
valleys, they are more often not simply dry, but so parching that
they seem to drain the mouth of every last bit of moisture. These
wines are often labeled halbtrocken and trocken, which translates
literally as half-dry and dry, but more accurately as dry and very
dry. And now, as the German wine industry ponders how to make its
product more appealing to Americans, many see dry wines as their
salvation, as a way to get in step with a world that may not know a
lot about white wines but wants them to be called dry.
</P>
<P>
   It's not merely a debate, but an identity crisis within a wine
industry in which everything seems to be open to challenge, from
the tortured methods for assessing the quality of German vineyards
and the Byzantine labeling laws to the recent history of German
winemaking itself. And, inevitably, statesmanlike solutions for
improving and simplifying German wine rules fall prey to politics,
which pits region against region and artisanal winemakers against
industrial producers.
</P>
<P>
   The economic stakes are high. Through the 1990s, the United
States imported about 10 million liters a year of wine from
Germany, way down from a high figure of about 60 million in 1984,
according to the German Wine Information Bureau in New York. Most
of that difference came from big German producers of sweet and
cheap wines, whose popularity nosedived along with that of most
American jug wines in the last 15 years. But these producers want
to get back into the American market and see dry wines as their
best bet.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say, `Italy had the same problem with Riunite and
lambrusco, and they came out with pinot grigio,''' said Johannes
Selbach, whose winery, Selbach-Oster, in Zeltingen on the Mosel
River, produces both fruity and dry wines. ``But we Germans should
not forget that there is a strong Italian restaurant scene and
market in the U.S., and they haven't had the problems with World
War I and World War II. That's a strategic disadvantage for Germany
that you cannot change with a change in style.''
</P>
<P>
   Backers of the trockens point not only to the worldwide market
for dry wines, but also to their popularity in Germany, where
trockens and dry Italian wines like pinot grigio are still popular.
</P>
<P>
   ``The '80s saw a boom in dry wines and a complete falling off of
the sweet wines,'' Selbach said. ``The trockens exploded, and
drinking anything but trockens was considered politically
incorrect.''
</P>
<P>
   Some say that the German embrace of dry wines is really a return
to the way German wines were made a century ago, before technology
allowed winemakers to control fermentation precisely. By this
argument, today's dry wines have a greater claim to authenticity
than the fruity style most people think of as traditional.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   ``People can misconstrue the move to a dry style as a move away
from the traditional German style, but I don't think that's true,''
said Stephen H. Metzler of Classical Wines in Seattle, which
imports Breuer and other dry rieslings into the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Because of climate, soil and other conditions, some areas in
Germany, like the Mosel-Saar-Ruwer, were always more suited to
making fruity wines than dry wines, Metzler concedes. But he says
that in areas like the Rheingau 90 to 95 percent of all wines made
100 years ago were bone dry. ``This is the way wines were made
until technology gave winemakers more methods of manipulation,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Others regard this as historical revisionism and wishful
thinking.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Germans were losing market share to dry Italian wines in
the late 1970s and said, `Why can't we make these wines?''' said
Terry Thiese, a leading American importer of German wines. ``First,
they wanted to sell more wines. Then, they came up with historical,
religious and health-oriented justifications.''
</P>
<P>
   Either way, the salient fact about the trocken wines is that
most Americans are not used to wines so dry and acidic. And yet,
many restaurants in Germany offer little besides trocken wines,
because that is what Germans say they want.
</P>
<P>
   ``I refuse to believe that human beings can enjoy shrill, sour,
ugly, dry wines,'' said Thiese, who estimates that trockens make up
20 percent of his sales in the United States. ``I have to believe
that the German market's embrace of these wines has nothing to do
with taste and everything to do with fashion.''
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the dry wines, like Armin Goering, director of the
German Wine Institute, which promotes German wines at home and
abroad, assert that they are better matches with food than fruity
wines. Others argue for a diversity of wines, especially in a
country with a wide range of cuisines like the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a place for trocken wines, and there's a place for
fruity wines, and it depends on what comes out of the kitchen,''
said Rudi Wiest, another leading American importer of German wines.
``I think they're illiterate when it comes to wine and food
pairings over there. They don't have the plethora of styles of food
that we have over here. This pushing of all dry wines, they're
barking up the wrong tree. Even American wines are not bone dry.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor are the best dry German rieslings, which are rare because
they are very hard to make.
</P>
<P>
   ``I defy anyone to sit with a glass of well-made trocken
riesling and say anything negative, but you have to taste through
hundreds of them to find anyone who knows how to do them,'' said
Willie Gluckstern, a wine-and-food consultant, author and
passionate proponent of German rieslings, dry and fruity.
</P>
<P>
   The glory of German riesling rests on a teetering balance of
acidity, alcohol and sweetness. When ripe grapes are picked, their
juice is full of sugar. When they ferment, the sugar is converted
to alcohol. If the fermentation stops before all the sugar is
converted, that residual sugar will sweeten the wine, which will
have less alcohol. If all the sugar is converted to alcohol, the
wine will be completely dry and more powerful.
</P>
<P>
   The wild card is acidity. Some residual sugar must remain to
balance the tartness of riesling's naturally high acidity. Yet, if
the residual sugar rises above 9 grams to a liter, by German law
the wine can no longer be branded with the magic word trocken. It
must be called halbtrocken if it has up to 18 grams of residual
sugar, though these wines may still taste bone dry because of their
high acidity.
</P>
<P>
   The tangle of German wine laws present problems to importers,
who recognize the American wine market's aversion to anything but
white wines labeled dry. Gluckstern, for one, plans to bring in
good-quality German wines to sell for under $10, but the
trocken-halbtrocken issue is nettlesome.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't have to go that dry to make a German white wine that
will appeal to Americans,'' he said. ``The problem with
halbtrocken, though, is if I write `half dry,' it's a death knell.
It means it's sweet.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as some of the greatest Italian wines can only be called
vino da tavola, because they do not adhere to Italian wine rules,
some leading German wine producers like Georg Breuer are choosing
not to play the labeling game, eliminating potentially prestigious
terminology like kabinett and spaetlese in favor of simple vineyard
sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the style of my wines,'' Bernhard Breuer said. ``If we
use terms like kabinett and spaetlese, it implies that there are
other sweetness levels.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Breuer does use terms like auslese, beerenauslese and
eiswein to describe his ultrasweet wines, which he makes in small
quantities, but not his dry wines.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't believe in trocken wines,'' said Breuer's importer,
Metzler. ``We believe in well-balanced flavorful wines. Trocken has
come to mean mediocre wines, in which the sweetness has been taken
out, exposing its mediocrity.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
