<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 18:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6043 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e BC-FIVESENSES-DIRECTOR-H     08-08 0875
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIVESENSES-DIRECTOR-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
SENSES OF DIRECTION &HT;    (Advance for release Thursday)
 &HT;    By LOUIS B. PARKS
 &HT;    c. 2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   Say ``Canadian film'' and many people think of an American movie
shot north of the border. So many domestic films and TV series have
been shooting in Canada that it's hard for film crews in the United
States to find work.
</P>
<P>
   But Canadians do make movies and have a film industry, even
though it seems like the only Canadian films we've seen here the
last few years have been those from director Atom Egoyan
(``Exotica,'' ``The Sweet Hereafter,'' ``Felicia's Journey'').
</P>
<P>
   Even Jeremy Podeswa, director of the Toronto-shot ``The Five
Senses'' didn't realize how many Canadian films there are.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the Toronto Film Festival this year, the programmers looked
at 140 feature films (from Canada), which sort of shocked me, and I
live there,'' Podeswa said in a phone call from Calgary, Alberta.
``Most Americans would see one or maybe two Canadian features in
their cinemas each year. Most Canadians would see only 10 or 15 a
year.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Five Senses'' won best Canadian film at last year's
Toronto festival. It's a low-key but compelling ensemble film about
a variety of people who live or work in a Toronto apartment
building. Some of them know each other, some don't.
</P>
<P>
   The title comes from the five human senses, each represented in
one or more of the characters. Podeswa got the idea from reading
Diane Ackerman's nonfiction book ``A Natural History of the
Senses.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It made me think about how we take a lot of things in our
lives for granted, including people and relationships,'' the
38-year-old Podeswa said. He thought it was a wonderful starting
point for a movie. ``If you gave that idea to 50 filmmakers, you
would have 50 films that are really interesting.''
</P>
<P>
   But he didn't want to make a film about the senses. Rather, he
wanted to use the concept to represent the connections and layers
between otherwise unrelated elements of the story _ and to put his
viewers in a thoughtful mood.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, this was a clue that I want you to think about
something else on another level,'' he said. ``There is some design
for this all happening.''
</P>
<P>
   Podeswa immediately realized that such a concept could only be a
starting point, not the focus of his film, or it would have become
a gimmick.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it isn't because I was very conscious of the fact it
could be gimmicky. If I had made it more gimmicky, I would have
changed the title,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very conscious thing on my part to let the characters
and the story take over, so all those other things became subtext.
As you watch the movie you may be thinking a little about the
senses, but as things go on, you start focusing on things that are
more important.''
</P>
<P>
   Much has been made of the fact that, although Podeswa's film was
the Toronto festival winner, Egoyan had withdrawn ``Felicia's
Journey'' from the competition. But the assumption that Egoyan, who
has won the award three times before, would have won again may be
wrong. Both films have gotten considerable praise and attention,
but people already expected a lot of Egoyan, especially after his
``The Sweet Hereafter'' was Oscar-nominated for best direction and
screenplay.
</P>
<P>
   When Podeswa was making his film, he expected to sell it in
foreign markets but not the United States, since so few Canadian
films show here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly I hoped that would happen,'' he said. ``It seemed
like it would happen when we got a standing ovation an Cannes. The
film sold very well internationally. (But) when I was making the
film, I had no idea.''
</P>
<P>
   It didn't hurt that one of leading actors in his excellent cast
is American Mary-Louise Parker (``Fried Green Tomatoes''). She
plays a baker who creates lavish cakes that taste awful. She's
having a fling with a visiting Italian who seems crazy about her,
but because of her own insecurities, she keeps interpreting
everything he does as suspicious.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had such a hard time casting that role in Canada,'' Podeswa
said. ``That role requires vulnerability, but also prickliness,
irony, and sexiness and humor and sensitivity. It's a really hard
package to find.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd always loved her from (her) movies I'd seen. I felt really
lucky when she came on board.''
</P>
<P>
   Podeswa readily acknowledges superficial similarities between
the films of Egoyan _ who is a friend of his _ and his own movies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We both look at film as a form of personal expression,'' he
said. ``We think of film in the same way we would think of
song-writing or novel-writing. We are trying not to be aware of the
whole thing as an industrial complex. All of our films reflect who
we are as people and what our preoccupations are.''
</P>
<P>
   Podeswa doesn't mind being compared to Egoyan _ ``I think Atom
is a brilliant filmmaker'' _ but he says it's a mistake to assume
they represent some sort of widespread Canadian film sensibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``We make a lot of kinds of movies,'' he said. (In the United
States) you've got a skewed perspective. You get such a tiny
fraction of what Canadian movies are, and you tend to see the art
cinema.``
</P>
<P>
   X X X END OF STORY
</P>
