<P>
   BILINGUAL-AMERICA _ BOSTON _ This summer, three former
housekeepers filed suit against a posh Boston hotel claiming they
were forced to speak English instead of Spanish by their managers.
As immigrants from non-English-speaking countries flow into the
United States, businesses and institutions increasingly face a
foreign-language test: How best to cope with new workers and new
customers whose first language is not English. The notion of
English as the sole language of American business and political
life is being challenged, swamped by new demographic and market
realities. The demand for translators and translation services has
soared. Hispanics spent about $380 billion last year on products
and services, up 84 percent since 1990. On Capitol Hill, lawmakers
are
</P>
<P>
   increasingly finding the need for Spanish speakers to deal with
constituents' inquiries. (Holmes, Cox News Service). Moving
Thursday.
