<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-NOTES-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
RECENT VIDEO RELEASES (Advance for release Thursday) &HT;    By BRUCE WESTBROOK
 &HT;    c. 2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Reindeer Games''
</P>
<P>
   If Ehren Kruger doesn't watch it, he may go quickly from hot new
screenwriter to one more cold nose pressed against the Hollywood
glass.
</P>
<P>
   ``Arlington Road'' was a potent enough thriller, but he brought
no invention to ``Scream 3,'' and his ``Reindeer Games'' is among
the most ludicrous scripts of recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it doesn't help that star Ben Affleck is miscast.
Clean-cut, good-guy Ben as a convict who grapples with violent
thugs upon his release from prison? Forget it.
</P>
<P>
   The setup _ which could only occur in a movie _ has Affleck
assuming the identity of his former cellmate, hooking up with a
lovely lass (Charlize Theron) who had written love letters to the
guy without ever demanding a photo.
</P>
<P>
   Things get ugly when her brother (Gary Sinise) and his gang pop
up, insisting that Affleck help them rob a remote casino where his
cellmate had worked.
</P>
<P>
   It's never clear why Affleck's supposed knowledge is so vital,
or why a scarily murderous Sinise doesn't kill him on several
occasions. Chalk it up to hopeless contrivance.
</P>
<P>
   Veteran director John Frankenheimer still handles action well
enough (albeit in a painful, brutal way), but characters and nuance
seem beyond him. ``Reindeer Games'' is as messy as its low-rent
robbery attempt.
</P>
<P>
   It's basically a stupid story about stupid people doing stupid
things _ sort of like ``A Simple Plan,'' but without the grounded
sense of drama. &QL; 
Grade: D &QL; 
2000, R, Dimension, CC, VHS priced for rental, DVD $29.99
</P>
<P>
   ``Dragonheart: A New Beginning''
</P>
<P>
   This effective and affecting movie is being released directly to
video as a sequel to 1996's ``Dragonheart,'' which starred Dennis
Quaid and had Sean Connery as the voice of its dragon.
</P>
<P>
   Our hero here is a young stable boy (Chris Masterson of
``Malcolm in the Middle'') who dreams of being a knight, then gets
a shot when he discovers a young dragon (voiced by Robby Benson)
hidden in a monastery. ``E.T.''-style, they become pals.
</P>
<P>
   Soon they're embroiled in a castle intrigue involving a
power-grabbing aide to a doddering king.
</P>
<P>
   Shot in Slovakia, the film has a fine sense of exotic detail,
apart from overly obvious shots of models standing in for distant
castles.
</P>
<P>
   Sprinkled with snow flurries, some scenes have an enchanting
sense of lighthearted magic. The action is spirited and colorful,
thanks to crisp swordplay, flashy martial arts (an Asian sage and
his spunky daughter appear) and fine computer-animated dragon
effects.
</P>
<P>
   Masterson is likably earnest without seeming naive, and his
allies make an eccentric and charming good-guy band. Harry Van
Gorkum also has wicked fun with the villain, Osiro.
</P>
<P>
   Luckily, not too much hinges on the beast _ unlike, say, in
``Godzilla.'' This is a solid family film without constant
bombardments of monstrous stunts. If anything, the dragon is a bit
too boyishly humanized and ordinary.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, ``A New Beginning'' is a satisfying youth-oriented
adventure, and it's often graced by Randy Edelman's stirring
musical theme from the first film. &QL; 
Grade: B &UR;  &QL; 
 &LR; 2000, PG, Universal, CC, VHS priced for rental, DVD $24.98
</P>
<P>
   ``Here on Earth''
</P>
<P>
   This chick flick didn't click, earning just $10 million in
theaters. Although video can be kinder to intimate stories, don't
count on it: Big screen or small, ``Here on Earth'' is a wretchedly
written mound of mush.
</P>
<P>
   Utterly predictable, it welds a romantic triangle onto the
socioeconomic chasms of ``Love Story.''
</P>
<P>
   It's set in a picturesque small town where residents have a
pathological hatred for elitist boys at a nearby prep school.
</P>
<P>
   Cross-cultural dating (the horror!) occurs when an arrogant
preppie (Chris Klein) romances a waitress (Leelee Sobieski).
</P>
<P>
   She seems sweet, but she is driven by lust. With one look at
Klein's pecs, she ditches her loyal farm-boy beau (Josh Hartnett),
whose only sin is having a bad-hair year.
</P>
<P>
   Forbidden love, of course, is that most enticing of young loves,
and the road gets even rockier _ for both the lovers and viewers.
</P>
<P>
   Yet these are fine young actors. They just deserve a better
script.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever the music swells or rain drenches our lovers in a
dripping embrace, we want to buy into this _ to revel in the sweet
ache of an emotional wallow.
</P>
<P>
   But when Klein quotes a Robert Frost poem that happens to be
Sobieski's favorite, we stop trusting him _ and the movie, which is
a slick but hollow entertainment masquerading as romantic
profundity. &QL; 
Grade: D &QL; 
2000, PG-13, Fox, CC, VHS priced for rental, DVD $34.98
</P>
<P>
   Due next week: ``The Naked Gun'' and ``Planet of the Apes''
series on DVD; ``Titus,'' ``Erin Brockovich'' and ``The Cider House
Rules.''
</P>
<P>
   Nanny bonanza
</P>
<P>
   If your favorite things include Julie Andrews nanny movies,
you're in luck.
</P>
<P>
   New in stores is a ``Gold Collection'' edition of ``Mary
Poppins'' ($22.99 on VHS, $29.99 on DVD). Due Aug. 29 is a
35th-anniversary edition of ``The Sound of Music'' ($14.98 on tape,
$29.98 on disc).
</P>
<P>
   ``Mary Poppins'' has been on tape since the '80s and even had an
earlier DVD release. But the new ``Sound of Music'' is big news.
</P>
<P>
   This marks the beloved film's debut on the booming DVD market.
Also, Fox is loading its two-disc sets with more than six hours of
bonus material, much of it never seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mary Poppins'' has far fewer spoonfuls of sugar. Its first DVD
had zero extras, and this one adds only a few, including
``Hollywood Goes to a World Premiere,'' a 10-minute featurette made
for theaters in 1964 to document the film's bow. (This also appears
on VHS.)
</P>
<P>
   There's also a 16-minute documentary, ``The Making of `Mary
Poppins,''' hosted by star Dick Van Dyke.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't new. ``Making of'' was produced for a previous VHS
edition in 1997. Oddly, ``Poppins''' new tapes don't have the
featurette.
</P>
<P>
   It's interesting to see fresh young stars of the era make their
glittering arrivals, from Mary Tyler Moore and ``enchanting Angie
Dickinson'' to ``Poppins''' Andrews _ beaming and wrapped in fur _
and Van Dyke, joined by his wife and kids.
</P>
<P>
   Other extras for DVD: a 16-question trivia game and a theatrical
trailer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mary Poppins'' is shown in wide-screen, with a 1.85-to-1
aspect ratio on DVD. As for the transfer, it looks exquisite.
</P>
<P>
   If you already own the film on tape or disc, Disney feels your
pain. The studio is offering a $5 ``upgrade'' rebate when you send
in the proof-of-purchase tab or UPC symbol from your original copy.
</P>
<P>
   XXX END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
