<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 18:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6048 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e BC-MUSIC-PAPAROACH-HNS &LR;      08-08 1274
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-PAPAROACH-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
ROCK 'N' ROACH 'N' RAGE &HT;    By MICHAEL D. CLARK
 &HT;    c. 2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Papa Roach is the hardest-working band I've been associated
with. They will be signed. It's just a matter of where and when.''
_ Gary Avila, Papa Roach manager, July 1999
</P>
<P>
   It's been a little more than a year since rock-rappers Papa
Roach played Big Shots pool hall in tiny Roseville, Calif., just
north of Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   The group was late for the sound-check because the van broke
down on a stretch of nowhere interstate in California's central
valley. Manager Gary Avila was still shopping for a record deal,
and until then there would be little money to fix the road beast
properly.
</P>
<P>
   Papa Roach couldn't have been happier.
</P>
<P>
   The van was coughing, but now parked in the strip-mall lot that
housed the billiard room. But they had made the gig. A group of 500
high school and college-age kids were lined up outside waiting for
the doors to open, and several commuters had waved and honked at
the band while it was broken down on the freeway shoulder earlier
in the day.
</P>
<P>
   Papa Roach had been recognized.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never really thought about it, but we are a successful
local band,'' said lead singer Coby Dick that day, with a sneering
smile much like Dennis Quaid's. ``That's so cool.''
</P>
<P>
   Guitarist Jerry Horton offered Dick a little perspective on this
new-found pride, ``Yeah, we're a successful local band with a
broken-down van.''
</P>
<P>
   A couple hours later Dick was jumping around in Big Shots' back
room, priming himself for the night's packed-house show.
</P>
<P>
   ``Limp Bizkit and those others started the party,'' he crowed,
beating on his chest for emphasis. ``We're here to clean it up.''
</P>
<P>
   What a difference a year makes.
</P>
<P>
   Three months ago, Papa Roach was playing side stages at radio
festivals. Now, behind the million-selling major-label debut
``Infest,'' the band can headline club shows and hold its own
opening for a band like Korn.
</P>
<P>
   Papa Roach is now a band in demand by late-night talk shows and
video music programs. A band that doesn't travel in beat-up vans or
play pool halls anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Avila's old California pager is now disconnected, but his home
number still works.
</P>
<P>
   A family member informs a caller that he is in Los Angeles with
P Roach (what the die-hards have called the band since it formed in
1993) on the set of the new video for ``Broken Home.'' It's the
second single from the DreamWorks-backed ``Infest.``
</P>
<P>
   Following a triumphant salutation from radio audiences with its
first single, ``Last Resort'' earlier this summer, ``Infest'' has
spent its entire shelf life on the Billboard charts, peaking as
high as No. 5. After 14 weeks it's only dropped a notch to No. 6.
That's eight places above Kid Rock's latest, ``The History of
Rock'' ( No. 14), and 36 notches above celebrated Sacramento peers
the Deftones.
</P>
<P>
   Both those highly anticipated summer releases were put out after
``Infest.''
</P>
<P>
   Avila remembers the night back at Big Shots and generously takes
the time away from the video crew to chat. He says interviews with
the band are no problem: They just have to be worked around the
current tour.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and it can't be on the day that the band is flying to New
York to play ``The Late Show With David Letterman'' or attending
the MTV Video Awards. The band is nominated for best new artist
against Sisqo, Pink, Macy Gray and Christina Aguilera. Dick readily
admits he doesn't figure P Roach will win, but the group will
perform for the broadcast, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   A couple more obstacles: Talks are ongoing about a fall tour
with Limp Bizkit and Eminem, all of which takes time to hammer out.
And discussions about what P Roach song will be included on the new
extreme-sports video game ``Tony Hawk's Pro Skater 2.'' Those
meetings will have to be worked around, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things are going crazy right now,'' Avila says. ``It's crazy
in a good way. When the band goes on tour, I'm going to move from
Sacramento to Los Angeles.''
</P>
<P>
   Singer Dick, 24, has no plans to move anywhere other than to a
better apartment in Sacramento. After years of living in a
run-down, low-rent square in a bad part of town, he says he plans
to head home and ``get my lady out of the ghetto.'' That could be a
while: The last time he spent any time there was last fall.
</P>
<P>
   Dick has no other life changes in mind. He plans to remain as
crazy and erratic as he always has been.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before a show we all get in a huddle and say, `Everybody hates
us,'`` he says. ``We make ourselves believe that we're hated, and
then we just hit the stage and kill it.''
</P>
<P>
   Papa Roach started slaying with its music right around the time
of that Big Shots' gig last summer. The group had just been granted
a demo deal with Warner Bros. in which the band got funding to cut
a few tracks for label consideration. In return, Warner Bros. got
the first option to sign the band.
</P>
<P>
   But Warner Bros. passed, opening the door for DreamWorks. P
Roach signed to the label late last year under a deal that gives
the band enough freedom to continue to rage as they did while
cutting self-financed demo tapes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still bringing it, only now it's with a DreamWorks
tag,'' Dick says. ``They're letting us be who we want to be, and we
have a lot of creative control.''
</P>
<P>
   DreamWorks must have recognized that P Roach's combination of
rock, rage and rhymes is perfectly timed. Starting with Rage
Against the Machine and culminating in several summers of the Korn
and Limp Bizket-led Family Values tours, rock 'n' rap is rivaled
only by shiny Brit-Sync pop as the dominant rhythm of radio.
</P>
<P>
   Dick's gruff megaphone growls can stretch from the fierce
punishing indictments of Henry Rollins to the confessional
philosophizing of Bush's Gavin Rossdale. Song titles from Infest
are a cross between scarred psyche nightmares (``Snakes,''
``Between Angels and Insects'') and a slightly altered version of
the seven deadly sins (``Binge,'' ``Never Enough``).
</P>
<P>
   Dick splits time in most songs between singing and rapping, and
buffers it with Horton's lipstick metal guitar squelches. Tobin
Esperance's sludge bass and drummer David Buckner's pounding
tom-tom blows enhance the storm.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike rap-heavy peers like Korn, P Roach is more democratic in
its use of rock 'n' rap to create a contrast on songs like ``Last
Resort'' and highlight track ``Between Angels and Insects.``
</P>
<P>
   It's a nice blend, but what will put this group over the top is
the ability to rapture with a metal ballad like ``Broken Home.''
</P>
<P>
   Dick appears to sense the importance of ``Broken Home.'' He
describes the video as a simulated look at a family gone nuclear,
with P Roach providing the soundtrack. It's clearly very personal
to the singer because it refers to his own life. Reminders of that
day back at the pool hall in Roseville, the van that barely got P
Roach to the venue and the local die-hards waiting to see the band
has silenced Dick for a rare moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, I have not had one minute to look back lately,'' he
says. ``Not long ago Mike Bordin (drummer for Faith No More) told
me to not look back _ don't even worry about reflecting, just keep
doing.''
</P>
<P>
   His comedown was over quickly, replaced by the vociferous
rapid-speak that is his norm.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do look at it, but how do you take it all in? It's all a
shock,'' Dick says. ``But we'll stick around for a long time. We
don't want to be a one-hit wonder and quit.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, Limp Bizkit and those others started the party,
but P Roach is here to finish it.
</P>
<P>
   X X X END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
