<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 18:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6055 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CAMP-SONGS-NYTR &LR;      08-08 0587
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMP-SONGS-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAMP SONG MEMORIES REKINDLED ON THE INTERNET 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Please note that tilde in parentheses has been used in the
8th and 17th grafs instead of an actual tilde character,
non-transmittable to many newspaper systems.) 
 By GARY KIRKLAND   
 The Gainesville (Fla.) Sun   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GAINESVILLE, Fla. _ There is something about camp songs that
makes them stick like a toasted marshallow in your memory.
</P>
<P>
   They are the sort of tunes thate come in handy in fighting
boredom on the road during family vacations, or as a method of
fighting drowsiness on long distance solo drives.
</P>
<P>
   Like a lot of people, Sarah Portier, a 20-year-old University of
Florida junior majoring in aerospace engineering, has camp songs
kicking around in the back of her head. But she is not content to
leave them there.
</P>
<P>
   Portier, who compiled songs during a dozen years in the Girl
Scouts, has posted them on the Web at
www.afn.org/(TILDE)afn26527/songindex.html. The site now has nearly
80 songs, and she said she has about 10 more to add.
</P>
<P>
   She said ``Father Abraham,'' a song that incorporates lots of
choreography, as well as vocals, was likely the first camp song she
learned. ``My Brownie troop was crazy about that one.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the songs borrow their tunes from old standards and
substitute new lyrics. Like the classic ``Pink Pajamas'' sung to
the tune of ``The Battle Hymn of the Republic.''
</P>
<P>
   I wear my pink pajamas in the summer when it's hot.
</P>
<P>
   I wear my flannel nightie in the winter when it's not.
</P>
<P>
   And sometimes in the springtime, and sometimes in the fall,
</P>
<P>
   I jump right in between the sheets with nothing on at all.
</P>
<P>
   Glory, glory hallelujah! Glory, glory, what's it to ya, balmy
breezes blowing through ya with nothing on at all!
</P>
<P>
   That song highlights one of the drawbacks of camp songs. Once
the alternative version is planted in memory, it can make it
difficult to take the original seriously, Portier said.
</P>
<P>
   There are songs, with lyrics that are incredibly silly, but are
too much fun to sing to pass up. In that category she includes
``McKinney and McCormick'' sung in two parts, one part handling the
melody to the tune of ``The Irish Washerwoman'' (a sample of it is
on the Web at www.acronet.net/(TILDE)robokopp/eire/irishwas.mid).
The second part, playing the role of human bagpipes, sings
``A-wang, A-wang'' in drone like fashion.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, McKinney is dead and McCormick don't know it,
</P>
<P>
   McCormick is dead and McKinney don't know it,
</P>
<P>
   They're both lying dead, dead in their beds.
</P>
<P>
   Neither one knows that the other one's dead.
</P>
<P>
   (then the parts switch)
</P>
<P>
   Portier said singing was usually done when walking in groups
between activities or when waiting in line to eat. ``We sang all
the time,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   When asked if she remembered the songs more than the camping,
she said the two go together _ the songs spark the memories.
</P>
<P>
   There are a few songs scattered in her collection that carry an
emotional wallop. The song ``Say When,'' frequently sung around a
final campfire, tells of saying goodbye. It can be a tough one to
sing with dry eyes. Or ``On My Honor,'' the song sung during the
ceremony when Brownies ``fly up'' to become Junior Girl Scouts,
Portier said, gets her every time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've tucked away a song or two, if you're feeling low there's
one for you,'' she said, quoting the lyrics.
</P>
<P>
   (The Gainesville Sun in Gainesville, Fla., is part of the New
York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
