<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 18:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6057 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-ANTI-SEMITISM09-COX     08-08 1152
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTI-SEMITISM09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lieberman choice may herald decline in anti-Semitism
 &HT;    By Bill Hendrick
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   One night in 1970, when Sam Massell was running for mayor of
Atlanta, he awoke to see a cross burning in his yard.
</P>
<P>
   Massell, undaunted, went on to win his race and serve as
Atlanta's only Jewish mayor. He says now that anti-Semitism wasn't
a major problem in Atlanta then, and it's even less of one today.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think conditions have improved dramatically, not just on the
surface, but in true understanding and respect for one's fellow
man,'' Massell says.
</P>
<P>
   There are good reasons for such optimism.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats have tapped a Jew, Sen. Joseph Lieberman
(D-Conn.), as their vice presidential candidate. And that gives
credence to polls by the Anti-Defamation League that show a long
decline in anti-Semitism. The percentage of strongly anti-Semitic
Americans dropped from 29 in 1964 to 12 in 1998. ``Things are
getting better,'' declares Jay Kaiman, Southeast director of the
ADL.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope I'm right, but I don't see that much anti-Semitism in
the country,'' says Deborah Lipstadt, a Jewish historian at Emory
University. ``I think people have just come a long way. I'm not
naive enough to think it's all gone away, but I still think it's a
whole lot better than it used to be.''
</P>
<P>
   And yet, even as the ADL releases hopeful polling data, it
continues to collect thousands of reports of anti-Semitic acts each
year, such as desecrations of synagogues, and to track hundreds of
hate groups.
</P>
<P>
   And even in 2000, many Jews _ long accustomed to blending in to
make themselves less likely targets of bigotry _ remain concerned
that their profile may be raised to uncomfortable levels by the
Lieberman nomination, says Barbara Babbitt-Kaufman, an owner of
Longstreet Press in Atlanta and an active member of the Jewish
community.
</P>
<P>
   This year Babbitt-Kaufman's company published ``The Jewish
Phenomenon'' by Steven Silbiger, which trumpets the successes of
American Jews. The book notes, for example, that one-third of all
American multimillionaires are Jewish, and that 20 percent of
professors at leading universities are Jewish.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very controversial,'' she says. ``Some wanted to scream
out the pride in what the Jews have accomplished. And others felt
it was better to keep it a secret among us.''
</P>
<P>
   Benjamin Hirsch, a 67-year-old Atlanta architect, came to
Atlanta as a child just before his family was arrested by Hitler's
Gestapo. He's writing a book on what it was like growing up Jewish
in Atlanta in the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was always in fistfights, several times a week until I was
16, about some anti-Semitic comment,'' Hirsch says. One gentile
eventually came to his aid. ``Then this big guy named Whitey
Kugler, who later died in a jet crash, decided to take up for me.
He just says, `Anybody who wants a piece of Ben has to come through
me first.'''
</P>
<P>
   Things have improved since then, he says. ``Now I would say most
anti-Semitism in Atlanta is more or less low key. But I can tell,
it's still there. Sometimes you hear jokes. And people look at me
funny because I wear a beret for religious reasons.''
</P>
<P>
   Playwright Alfred Uhry, 63, experienced anti-Semitism while
growing up in Atlanta. ``Sometimes, I'd be called `a dirty Jew,'''
he says. For the most part, though, his childhood was pleasant, and
when he depicted the lynching of Jewish factory manager Leo Frank
in the musical ``Parade,'' he made clear that the mob was not
originally motivated by anti-Semitism.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think he was hanged because he was Jewish,'' Uhry
says. ``What people in Georgia feared and hated in 1915 was Yankees
and bosses. And Frank was a Yankee boss. I think his Jewishness was
secondary until a lot of anti-Semitism was whipped up. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``The South has always been, though less now, motivated by
deeply Christian beliefs, people who see Jews as the killers of
Christ. And that can be whipped up easily.''
</P>
<P>
   Jews have lived in Georgia since 42 arrived at Savannah in 1733,
six months after James Oglethorpe landed. Jews fought with American
troops in the Revolution and every war since. Many Jews served in
the Confederate Army, and at least four Union generals were Jewish.
Judah Benjamin, a Jewish lawyer, was Jefferson Davis' chief
adviser. After the war, many, like the Rich family of Atlanta,
became prominent in business.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Jews had to look over their shoulders. It's worth noting,
Uhry says, that a statue of Tom Watson, a virulent racist whose
rhetoric incited the Marietta lynch mob, still stands on the
grounds of the state Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   Now, reaction to the Lieberman nomination may show whether the
optimists are right, and the most hateful anti-Semites really have
been marginalized, as the ADL poll seems to say.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Philip Self, assistant pastor at Johnson Ferry Baptist
Church, is hopeful. ``Maybe I'm just sheltered,'' he says. ``I find
it incredible the percentage could be as high as 12 percent. I
can't fathom that.''
</P>
<P>
   In a twist of historic irony, one group with lingering
anti-Semitism is African-Americans, according to the ADL poll. A
generation ago, Jews were blacks' strongest allies on civil rights.
But in 1998, fully 34 percent of blacks harbored anti-Semitic
attitudes, according to the poll, compared with 9 percent of
whites.
</P>
<P>
   The finding rankles some blacks. The Rev. William Sheals, of
predominantly black Hopewell Baptist Church in Norcross, says the
people he knows are not bigoted. ``That is an absolutely false
reading,'' he says of the ADL statistics on African-Americans. ``I
pray a man's religion doesn't become a big issue in this
presidential race.''
</P>
<P>
   Other groups that showed high levels of anti-Semitism: those
with high school or less education, 43 percent, and those age 65
and up, 22 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Another cautionary finding: Overall, though just 12 percent of
Americans indicated strong anti-Semitism, another 35 percent fell
in a middle range, indicating possible prejudice. And all the
numbers may be overly optimistic, the ADL's Kaiman says, because
people tend to understate bigotry in polls.
</P>
<P>
   Emory's Lipstadt, who in April won a decisive triumph over
British writer David Irving, who had sued her over her portrayal of
him in a book, says strong reactions to the Lieberman announcement
show that some level of prejudice remains.
</P>
<P>
   ``I must say I'm struck by the fact that so many people are so
excited about this,'' she says. ``It says we haven't come as far as
we thought. This should be a ho-hum matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jews are very excited, in the sense that it's a final barrier.
So many thought it was a given he wouldn't be chosen because he's a
Jew. I was excited when I heard, and very pleased, but also annoyed
that I was pleased. This should really be no news.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
