u a BC-BLK-COLLEGES-CRIME09-     08-08 0585
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLK-COLLEGES-CRIME09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Black colleges say crime figure are misleading
 &HT;    By Ernie Suggs
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _For the most part, black colleges have been the victims
of their environments _ when it comes to crime.
</P>
<P>
   Take the Atlanta University Center. With six separate colleges,
the AUC is known in some circles as the mecca of black education.
But it is also located in Atlanta's West End, which boasts one of
the city's highest crime rates and has the highest concentration of
public housing.
</P>
<P>
   ``When (Atlanta University) was founded in 1865, where were we
going to put it?'' said A.J. White, director of public safety at
Clark Atlanta University. ``We have to embrace the community.''
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to brainstorm on how colleges can better work with
communities, White has invited law enforcement officials from black
colleges to Atlanta for a conference designed to share ideas about
ways to make their campuses safer. The conference is being held
through Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   David Bergeron, chief of policy and budget for the U.S.
Department of Education, said no data exists that shows
historically black colleges as being more dangerous than white
schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that campus security has been a concern for many years
at black schools,'' said Bergeron. ``There is now a perception that
they are not safe, but I think one of the things the data will show
is that perception isn't rooted on fact.'' The idea for the
conference was born last November when a crime report predicted the
risk of becoming a victim of violent crime in neighborhoods
surrounding U.S. universities. It listed the west Atlanta community
that borders the AUC as the country's most dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   Morris Brown College topped a list of 25 schools. LeMoyne-Owens
College in Memphis earned the No. 2 spot, followed by Spelman
College, CAU and Morehouse College. All five are black schools, as
are the neighborhoods they are in.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia State and Georgia Tech ranked 13th and 19th,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
   But AUC officials called the report unfair and misleading,
because it did not consider actual crimes that took place on the
college campuses, or crimes that involve students who lived within
those campuses.
</P>
<P>
   White said CAU has a large and visible police presence on campus
and that most of the crimes committed on campus involve burglaries,
particularly car break-ins. Steve Bowser, director of public safety
at Spelman, there are about 150 officers, security guards and staff
working for the six campuses that make up the AUC. In Zone I, where
the schools are located, there are only 123 Atlanta Police officers
assigned to the zone.
</P>
<P>
   Current crime statistics for the immediate area surrounding the
AUC were not available, but a homicide study showed that between
1990 and 1999, there were 189 murders in that area. Comparatively,
there were 227 murders near Tech and 37 near Georgia State.
</P>
<P>
   White said CAU is working with the community to institute a
greater community policing presence. Beginning this semester,
students will be enlisted as sentinels to report crimes that occur
on or around campus. They will not intervene or get involved with
apprehension.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a pretty safe campus,'' said White, who came to CAU
two years ago. ``We have had no rapes. No murders. Last year, we
had a guy in the dorm who tried to fondle a student and we had him
within five minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
