<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIRST-ENERGY-GPU-295&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRSTENERGY TO ACQUIRE GPU IN $4.5 BILLION DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ohio, Pa., N.J.)   By NEELA BANERJEE with ANDREW ROSS SORKIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   FirstEnergy Corp., an Ohio-based utility company, agreed Tuesday
to acquire GPU Inc. of Morristown, N.J., for $4.5 billion in cash
and stock.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition would make FirstEnergy the sixth-largest energy
concern in the United States, based on customers served. Its
increased size and scale would also give it the potential to
produce and distribute electricity more efficiently, industry
analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, approved by the board of directors of both companies,
could save the companies $150 million the first year, a FirstEnergy
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   FirstEnergy is based in Akron, Ohio, and primarily serves the
Cleveland, Akron and Toledo markets and western Pennsylvania. Best
known for its past ownership of the Three Mile Island nuclear
plant, GPU provides power to central and coastal New Jersey, as
well as the northwestern part of the state and eastern and central
Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   The merger allows FirstEnergy, which generates electricity,
operates a transmission grid and services clients, to double its
customer base to about 4.3 million and to establish itself firmly
on the East Coast. GPU, for its part, would receive a significant
premium on its equity as part of the deal. FirstEnergy is offering
$36.50 for each share of GPU common stock, which rose 75 cents
Tuesday, to $31.4375 on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of FirstEnergy closed down 0.3 percent, or 6.25 cents, to
$25.3125 Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   GPU, has which divested itself of nearly all its power plants,
would have access to FirstEnergy's power generation and would also
be able to buy power more cheaply as part of a bigger company,
changes that could translate into lower rates for its current
customers in western New Jersey and eastern Pennsylvania.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Together with last week's announcement of a union between FPL
Group of Florida and Entergy, based in New Orleans, the FirstEnergy
acquisition may signal the start of another round of consolidation
in the electric utility industry, which was reshaped last year by
more than two dozen mergers.
</P>
<P>
   Share prices of many utilities have risen substantially since
the start of the year, increasing the temptation for management to
find buyers for their companies. Utilities also realize that in the
wake of last year's mergers, bigger companies have more
opportunities to cut costs, to market their electricity more
aggressively and to negotiate better deals for the purchase of
power.
</P>
<P>
   ``They need to be big to implement the most efficiencies and
have the economies of scale,'' said Barry M. Abramson, senior
utility analyst at PaineWebber.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer advocates in New Jersey expressed guarded optimism over
the sale of GPU. Blossom Peretz, the ratepayer advocate for the
State of New Jersey, a position appointed by the governor, said
rates charged by GPU and other New Jersey utilities were relatively
high, but that GPU had built a solid reputation as a company that
cooperates with customers and regulators. The state ratepayer's
office said it wanted to find out if GPU would be able to buy
cheaper energy as part of a larger company with better purchasing
power. Peretz also said her office expected FirstEnergy to share
with its customers any savings made from the merger.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're also concerned that none of the merger related costs go
to ratepayers,'' Peretz said, ``and that there be no rate shocks
due to the deal.''
</P>
<P>
   The market, however, had a negative reaction to the deal. When
word of a possible acquisition leaked out Monday, most analysts
downgraded their ratings of FirstEnergy, citing the burdens the
company will have to take on in purchasing GPU. Both companies are
growing at a rate of 4 percent to 5 percent a year, lagging behind
other utilities that show double-digit growth.
</P>
<P>
   FirstEnergy, which has no current debt on the parent company
level, will have to incur debt to make the acquisition. ``Financing
for the cash portion of the transaction is going to come from a
combination of public debt and bank financing,'' said Richard
Marsh, the chief financial officer of FirstEnergy, during a
conference call with analysts.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, FirstEnergy will assume GPU's $7.4 billion in debt,
which the latter racked up through a series of overseas investments
that are faltering.
</P>
<P>
   GPU entered the retail energy field in Australia at the height
of the market, but sold its venture recently for a loss. It also
bought into the British market at a time when industry observers
felt that utilities would be hit by a rate cut _ which is what
happened. And GPU sold its generation business before power
generators began making hefty profits because of high demand.
</P>
<P>
   Because it shed most of its generation capacity, GPU is also
short of power in Pennsylvania, a gap that FirstEnergy, whose own
capacity is stretched in summer, will have to address. Analysts
also said that the merger process would keep FirstEnergy tied up
for 12 months, which could stall other projects.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't see a lot of strategic value to it,'' said Andrew
Levi, senior utilities analyst for Credit Suisse First Boston,
which downgraded FirstEnergy from ``strong buy'' to ``hold'' on
Monday. ``It doesn't create anything but a big company that can cut
some costs.''
</P>
</TEXT>
