<HEADER>
A6061 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-GORE-ASSESS-NYT &LR;      08-08 1220
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: AFTER THE BOUNCE, DOES THE V.P. REALLY MATTER? 
</HEADLINE>
  (With GORE-LIEBERMAN, GORE-SELECTION) 
 By R.W. APPLE Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore's selection of Sen. Joseph Lieberman of
Connecticut as his running mate on Monday, the frenzy of
speculation that preceded it and the outpouring of analysis that
has followed it raise a number of insistent questions.
</P>
<P>
   First of all, do such selections ever decide presidential
elections? Do they make any difference at all, either to the
national popular vote or in individual states? Or are they merely
something to keep politicians and journalists busy, now that the
nominating races end so soon and conventions decide almost nothing?
</P>
<P>
   The candidate making the choice usually gets an uptick in the
polls after it becomes known. Gov. George W. Bush of Texas
benefited from the customary ``bounce'' after he chose Dick Cheney,
and Gore closed the gap with Bush after choosing Lieberman, at
least according to an overnight USA Today/CNN/Gallup survey.
</P>
<P>
   But such changes are almost always transient.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think political scientists pretty much agree that in the
long run, in November, these choices have very little impact,''
said Paul C. Light of the Brookings Institution, a student of the
vice presidency. ``Maybe you pick up half a percentage point, or
even a whole one, with a good selection and lose about the same
with a bad one. But that isn't often enough to swing an election
one way or the other.''
</P>
<P>
   That is not to say, of course, that selecting a running mate has
no meaning. Since World War II, five vice presidents have moved
into the Oval Office _ Harry Truman, Lyndon Johnson, Richard Nixon,
Gerald Ford and George Bush. Two have been nominated for president,
only to lose in November _ Hubert Humphrey and Walter Mondale.
</P>
<P>
   But much of the debate about whom to choose usually centers not
on the capacity of the prospective choice to serve as president, an
issue of transcendent significance, but on his or her capacity to
improve the performance of the ticket at the polls, an issue of
considerably less importance.
</P>
<P>
   George McGovern's choice of Sen. Tom Eagleton of Missouri in
1972 wrought no real damage, even though Eagleton was dropped from
the Democratic ticket after it emerged that he had been treated for
mental illness. George Bush's choice of Dan Quayle in 1988, viewed
in hindsight by most politicians as a major gaffe, did no
overwhelming harm to the Republican cause. But exit polls
nonetheless suggested that Quayle was a distinct liability,
especially when compared with the Democratic vice-presidential
nominee, Lloyd M. Bentsen. Quayle may have cost the Republicans as
much as 4 percentage points, which could have proved decisive in a
closer race.
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally, presidential nominees often chose running mates
to appeal to swing states or to sections of the country where their
own appeal was weak. The most successful example of that in the
modern era, it is often said, was John F. Kennedy's selection of
Johnson in 1960, because Texas then voted Democratic. But that view
is challenged by revisionist historians.
</P>
<P>
   The Kennedy-Johnson ticket, like the pairing of Adlai E.
Stevenson and Estes Kefauver on the unsuccessful 1956 Democratic
ticket, was an attempt to provide not only geographical balance but
also ideological balance. In choosing Quayle, Bush sought something
else: generational balance.
</P>
<P>
   But those modes of selection have gone out of style in more
recent elections. Warren Christopher, the former secretary of
state, who conducted the vice-presidential searches for Clinton and
Gore, said in an interview earlier this summer that the Clinton
choice put a new emphasis on the personal relationship between the
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can assemble all the material and do all the studies of
voting records and statements,'' Christopher said. ``But in the
final analysis, chemistry weighs very heavily. Between the two
candidates, compatibility is very important and, I think,
increasingly important as the vice president's role as an adviser
becomes more important.''
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton chose Gore, a man from the same part of the
country as he _ indeed, from an adjacent state _ and from the same
part of the ideological spectrum. This year, the two vice
presidential candidates come from states with relatively few
electoral votes _ Cheney from Wyoming and Lieberman from
Connecticut _ and both candidates are close ideological fits to the
men who picked them.
</P>
<P>
   Both selections provided a kind of inoculation. Cheney, well
seasoned in government, lent the inexperienced Texas governor some
needed weight. Lieberman, a politician known for his independence
and for his criticism of Clinton's sexual peccadilloes, lent Gore
some cover from those who think he has marched in lock step with
Clinton, regardless of the issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``People suspect vice presidents,'' said Light. ``Remember
Hubert? He was seen as Johnson's captive until he showed his mettle
in the speech in Salt Lake City where he broke free on Vietnam. It
came too late to save him. Well, I think that Lieberman could be
Gore's Salt Lake City, but earlier.''
</P>
<P>
   Vice-presidential nominees used to be chosen at conventions; in
the days, ending about a quarter century ago, when conventions
rather than primaries chose the presidential nominees, it was
considered poor form to talk about running mates until your own
nomination was official. The first breach in tradition came in
1976, when Ronald Reagan, seeking to halt Ford's march toward the
Republican nomination and to dampen talk that Reagan was too
conservative to win, stipulated before the convention that if
nominated he would choose Sen. Richard S. Schweiker of
Pennsylvania, a moderate, as his running mate.
</P>
<P>
   He never got the chance. Ford was nominated after all. But in
1984, Mondale, hoping to get voters to give him a second look,
despite Reagan's popularity, chose Geraldine Ferraro before the
convention and promptly announced the choice _ a dramatic one,
because she was the first woman on a major national ticket. Yet the
race quickly regained its equilibrium.
</P>
<P>
   The choice of a running mate has been a kind of litmus test of
judgment for many years, because it is always the first major
decision a nominee makes. But now that early selection has become
the pattern, the choice seems to have gained additional importance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Viewed narrowly, it is still not decisive at the ballot box,''
said professor Michael Nelson of Rhodes College in Memphis, another
vice-presidential scholar. ``But now that it comes on the eve of
the convention, the selection of a running mate shapes the media
coverage of the candidate and his party. They go in upbeat or
downbeat, with the delegates energized or enervated.
</P>
<P>
   ``That can carry over into the campaign in an important way. It
did for the Clinton-Gore ticket in 1992.''
</P>
<P>
   Another element has changed. The new system gives a presidential
nominee plenty of time to vet, and then to carefully consider, the
possibilities before him. In the old days, the choice was often
made late at night, in a hurry, by ad hoc groups of insiders _
``BOGSAT,'' as the political consultant Douglas Bailey once termed
them, a ``bunch of guys sitting around a table.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
