<HEADLINE>
BOND PRICES RISE AFTER PRODUCTIVITY REPORT EXCEEDS EXPECTATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  By ROBERT HURTADO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Bond prices rose on Tuesday after a
better-than-expected government report on productivity and labor
costs and a good start to the Treasury's quarterly debt sales.
</P>
<P>
   The productivity report increased optimism that the Federal
Reserve will leave rates alone when its policy makers meet on Aug.
22. The fresh supply of government debt kept an early cap on the
day's gains, but good results helped lift prices later to session
highs. The Treasury sold $10 billion of 5-year notes and plans to
auction $10 billion of 10-year notes on Wednesday and $5 billion of
30-year bonds on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Solid auction results on the 5-year maturity renewed interest in
other Treasuries as investors bought the issue at a
better-than-expected 6.060 percent yield. The number of bids
exceeded the size of the issue by a ratio of 3.06 to 1, the best in
years, though some of that could be attributed to the reduced size
of the auction.
</P>
<P>
   The price of the closely watched 30-year bond rose 11/32, to 107
13/32, while its yield, which moves in the opposite direction, fell
to 5.73 percent from 5.75 percent on Monday. The 10-year note, the
emerging bellwether issue, rose 8/32, to 104 7/32. Its yield fell
to 5.91 percent from 5.95 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Labor Department's numbers couldn't have been any more
friendly for bonds and stocks,'' said Robert Pugliese, senior vice
president and director of the fixed-income department at the J.W.
Genesis Financial Corp. in Boca Raton, Fla. ``But that doesn't mean
bond prices will rise simply because the Fed is not expected to
raise rates. We are still competing with abnormal rates of return
in equities.''
</P>
<P>
   The productivity of the nation's workers increased at an annual
rate of 5.3 percent in the second quarter compared with a revised
1.9 percent in the first quarter. The government also said unit
labor costs fell 0.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The surge in nonfarm business productivity blew past even the
most bullish forecasts on the Street,'' said Anthony Chan, managing
director and chief economist for Banc One Investment Advisors.
</P>
<P>
   Chan said last week's employment report and Tuesday's
productivity report might further encourage the Fed leave policy
unchanged when they meet later this month.
</P>
<P>
   ``One could argue that it calls into question whether any
further action can be expected from the Fed,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
