<SLUG> BC-MANHATTAN-REAL-ESTATE-ART-430&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN MANHATTAN, A BREAK IN APARTMENT PRICES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By TRACIE ROZHON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The fever has broken. Manhattan's real estate market,
overheated after more than four years of rising prices, seems to be
cooling down.
</P>
<P>
   Apartment hunters, who this spring seemed caught up in a ``grab
it now before it's gone'' panic, no longer have that desperate urge
to buy, a desperation that resulted in bidding wars and angry
recriminations. Within the last two months, real estate brokers and
statisticians say, bidding wars have declined, apartments have
stayed on the market longer before being sold, and hundreds have
even been marked down.
</P>
<P>
   Manhattan real estate prices appear to be finally leveling off.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things everyone is beginning to feel is that the
market is flat,'' said Deborah Beck, executive vice president of
the Real Estate Board of New York. In another sign of a cooling
off, the board measured a 14 percent drop in the number of
Manhattan apartments sold for the quarter ending June 30, compared
with the same period last year _ ``a significant slowdown,'' Beck
said.
</P>
<P>
   At the Corcoran Group, sealed bids, an indicator of unusual
levels of competition, were down 33 percent in July compared with
July 1999. Clearly, the experts say, this is not a case of the
seasonal summer blahs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The edge is off the market,'' said Jonathan Miller, president
of Miller Samuel, the appraisal firm that compiles statistics for
Douglas Elliman, the city's biggest brokerage firm.
</P>
<P>
   The experts link the slowdown to the Nasdaq plunge that began on
April 14, and to the Federal Reserve's half-point interest rate
increase in May, ``the one that really had the impact,'' said
Marilyn Harra Kaye, president of Prudential/MLBKaye Realty.
</P>
<P>
   The changing statistics mirror a national trend, but there is
nothing to indicate the start of a downward movement like the one
in the late 1980s and early '90s. Real estate experts repeatedly
pointed out that prices remain high _ the average apartment price
for the period April through June was a record $854,704. But that
figure represents contracts signed an average of two months before
_ in the white-hot months of February, March and April. Based on
contracts signed in July, Miller projected a rise of only 1
percent, to $864,000.
</P>
<P>
   While none of the experts were willing to predict where the
Manhattan market would be by the end of the year, no one labeled
the cooling temporary. One thing seems certain: One of the biggest
sellers' markets in New York history has suddenly tilted more
toward the buyer _ and the buyers are noticing.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE; OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   For the first time in his two years of looking, Tom Pappas, a
Midtown lawyer, has spotted the same properties showing up week
after week on his Internet searches. But he is not biting until
their prices go down. Then, he vowed, ``I'll be there.''
</P>
<P>
   For their part, brokers insist that no one is grasping at
lowball offers, but they concede that more sellers are accepting
modest reductions off the asking price than they were doing earlier
this spring.
</P>
<P>
   The market's softening is particularly evident with
cookie-cutter, ordinary apartments _ particularly fixer-uppers _
that have been selling for ``extraordinary prices'' over the last
two years, said Pamela Liebman, chief executive at the Corcoran
Group.
</P>
<P>
   Brokers cite myriad examples, including a five-room co-op
reduced in June to $535,000 from $615, 000. a one-bedroom lowered
to $305,000 from $335,000 and a studio dropped to $175,000 from
$190,000.
</P>
<P>
   A five-room penthouse at 834 Fifth Avenue, one of the city's
top-tier co-op buildings, went on the market in April priced at
$7.9 million. In late June, it was reduced to $6.49 million, and on
July 31, the price dropped to $5.8 million.
</P>
<P>
   Brokers are quick to say that many of these price decreases _
especially those in the multimillion-dollar category _ were the
result of overpricing. The two-bedroom penthouse ``ended up being
overpriced,'' said Hall Willkie, head of residential sales at Brown
Harris Stevens, the Upper East Side firm with the listing. ``We
were testing the market; we were aggressive, and we had to reduce
the price.''
</P>
<P>
   In the report Miller just finished, he found that the average
property spent 28 percent more time on the market than it did
during the same period a year ago, 118 days versus 92 days.
</P>
<P>
   These changes reflect a national trend. Fred Flick, the vice
president for research at the National Association of Realtors,
said the real estate market nationally was down 6 percent in
volume; by the end of the year, the association estimates that
volume will be down 9 percent. And while it still predicts average
price increases at 2 percent to 3 percent this year, that is less
than last year's 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've slowed from a blistering pace to a simmering pace,''
said Flick. The national slowdown was confirmed on Thursday, when
the Commerce Department reported that across the country, new home
sales fell 3.7 percent in June to the lowest level in two and a
half years. Median prices fell slightly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
