<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-BLAST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSH-HOUR BLAST KILLS AT LEAST 8 IN DOWNTON MOSCOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN WHITMORE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ A bomb ripped through a crowded pedestrian underpass in
downtown Moscow Tuesday, killing at least eight people, injuring
dozens more, and spreading fear across the Russian capital.
</P>
<P>
   The blast occurred during evening rush hour in a walkway under
Moscow's fashionable Pushkin Square, which was packed with hundreds
of commuters and shoppers.
</P>
<P>
   Police said they found and defused a second bomb in the same
underpass, which connects three busy subway stations.
</P>
<P>
   There were no immediate claims of responsibility, but many here,
including Moscow Mayor Yury Luzhkov, said they suspected separatist
rebels from Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   The blast came just weeks before the anniversary of a series of
apartment bombings that killed more than 300 people last fall, and
many Muscovites said they feared that it marked the start of a new
campaign of terror. The Kremlin blamed last year's bombings on
Chechen rebels and sent troops to subdue the breakaway republic a
few weeks later. The Chechens denied responsibility for those
blasts, which remain unsolved.
</P>
<P>
   President Vladimir V. Putin, who gained popularity after his
tough response to last year's bombings and his handling of the
Chechnya war, called an emergency session of his top law
enforcement officials.
</P>
<P>
   On the streets around the congested underpass Tuesday, medical
workers treated injured people lying in the road as wounded
pedestrians, covered with blood, their clothes burned and shredded,
staggered out of the subterranean passage.
</P>
<P>
   ``We heard a bang and the lights went out,'' Natalyya
Zulumatova, who was working in one of the small kiosks in the
underpass, told the Reuters news agency. The ends of her hair was
singed and her ankles stained with blood. ``I was hit by the blast
wave. There was smoke all over the place. We all managed to get out
in the smoke. I saw many injured people.''
</P>
<P>
   A videotape of the site, shown on Russian State Television,
showed charred corpses lying on shattered glass and rubble in the
underpass as police and emergency workers picked through the
smoldering ruins.
</P>
<P>
   On the street above, paramedics carried a woman, her flesh
burned and blood gushing from her nose, to an ambulance. Medical
workers bandaged another woman's legs as she screamed in pain.
</P>
<P>
   For hours after the explosion, smoke poured from the stairway to
the underpass, which thousands of Moscow residents use every day,
and a sulfuric stench filled the air. Officials said as many as 53
were injured, including small children, a pregnant woman, and
elderly people.
</P>
<P>
   Police released descriptions of two suspects, both men in their
late 20s with dark skin and ``apparently from the Caucasus
region,'' Russian State Television reported. Police said they would
soon distribute composite sketches of the suspects.
</P>
<P>
   According to law-enforcement officials, the suspects placed the
bomb, which was in a plastic bag, on the ground in front of a kiosk
in the walkway. The explosion had the force of one &UR;  &LR; to &UR;  &LR; three
pounds of TNT, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Luzhkov called the blast an ``act of terrorism'' and said there
was an ``obvious Chechen connection'' to the blast.
</P>
<P>
   ``The testimony from several witnesses who were able to answer
questions in hospital shows. . . it was 100 percent Chechnya,''
Luzhkov said. He said that witnesses reported that two young men
with dark complexions had been bargaining with a shopkeeper and
left a bag behind them. The explosion occurred shortly thereafter.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor went on to warn against indiscriminate anti-Chechen
sentiment in the capital.
</P>
<P>
   ``The attitude, expressed by some, that the only good Chechen is
a dead Chechen, is unacceptable,'' Luzhkov said. ``We need to
distinguish between terrorists and normal people.''
</P>
<P>
   News agencies quoted Interior Minister Vladimir Rushailo,
Russia`s top law enforcement official, saying they were
investigating several possible scenarios for the bombing, including
that it was the work of the Chechen rebels.
</P>
<P>
   There was no immediate statement from Chechen rebel leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Police across Russia had been on high alert for several days,
fearing that Chechen rebels would stage attacks to mark the August
6 anniversary of the day they drove Russian forces out of the rebel
region's capital Grozny in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   In raids earlier Tuesday, police seized large caches of
explosives in Moscow and the southern city of Ryazan. Law
enforcement officials said the explosives were intended for
terrorist acts by Chechen separatists.
</P>
<P>
   The scene of Tuesday's blast, Pushkin Square, is one of the
busiest parts of Moscow, at the junction of two major streets and
three subway stations. The passageway is a virtual underground
shopping center, lined with kiosks and shops selling cosmetics,
clothing, compact disks, candy, and alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   In the summer months, it is also a popular hangout for
teenagers, who often gather there to drink beer and flirt.
</P>
<P>
   Oleg Michaelin, 15, had just escorted several girls to the
subway station and was standing on the street near the underpass
when the bomb exploded.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very worried about the girls,'' Michaelin said,
standing with a group of friends. ``We don't know if they are all
right.''
</P>
<P>
   Police in Moscow were placed on heightened alert and ordered to
check the many underground passageways around Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to appeal to citizens to show the same vigilance you
showed a year ago,'' said Emergency Minister Sergei Shoigu in
televised comments.
</P>
<P>
   Following last September's apartment bombings, fear and paranoia
swept Russia's capital as police, amid accusations of racism, went
house to house rounding up thousands of Chechens and others from
the Caucasus region.
</P>
<P>
   Police searched basements and attics across the city as
residents kept round-the-clock watch over the courtyards of
apartment buildings. Police telephone lines were clogged with calls
from people informing on ``suspicious looking'' neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   Moscow has been jittery ever since, and many said Tuesday's
explosion had revived the fear that gripped the city barely a year
ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course we are frightened. This can happen at any time in
any place,'' said Svetlana Mikhailova, who was milling around the
blast site. ``There could be another explosion right where we are
standing. There could be a bomb in that car next to us.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-08-00 1921EDT &QL; 
