u a BC-WORCESTER-FIRE-BOS &LR;      08-08 0480
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORCESTER-FIRE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISMISSAL SOUGHT IN CASE OF PAIR ACCUSED IN FATAL FIRE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOANNA WEISS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WORCESTER, Mass. _ Two homeless people accused of setting a fire
in a warehouse last December are no more culpable for the blaze _
or the deaths of six firefighters _ than city officials or the
building's owner, defense lawyers said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``These two hapless souls shouldn't be here,'' said Edward P.
Ryan Jr., a lawyer for Thomas Levesque, 37. Levesque and Julie
Barnes, 20, have each been charged with six counts of involuntary
manslaughter.
</P>
<P>
   At a hearing in Worcester Superior Court, lawyers for the pair
argued that the charges should be dropped. Prosecutors disagreed.
Judge Timothy Hillman took the case under advisement, and is not
expected to rule before the end of the month.
</P>
<P>
   The debate centered on whether Barnes's and Levesques' actions _
accidentally knocking over a candle, then leaving the warehouse
without telling anyone _ constituted the ``reckless and wanton
conduct'' required for a manslaughter charge.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant District Attorney Larry Murphy said they did. Reading
from statements police took from the pair after the fire, Murphy
cited several indications of what he called reckless behavior in
the minutes before the fire. Barnes and Levesque were trespassing
in the warehouse, Murphy said; Levesque was smoking marijuana.
</P>
<P>
   And being ``aware of the fire in progress, . . . turning their
backs and walking away from the fire, is reckless,'' Murphy said.
</P>
<P>
   But defense lawyes said the couple had no legal duty to report
the fire. And Lou Aloise, a lawyer for Barnes, said the
firefighters themselves might have worsened the blaze when they
vented an elevator shaft. If they couldn't have foreseen the fire's
danger, he said, how could Barnes and Levesque have been expected
to?
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Ryan said, the building's owner and city officials
were aware of potentially unsafe conditions in the warehouse, ``and
they had the power to do something.'' Instead, Ryan said, police
arrested ``two of life's unfortunates, who were scared, who didn't
know any better.''
</P>
<P>
   Aloise later said defense lawyers believe no one should be
charged in connection with the fire.
</P>
<P>
   If a trial goes forward, prosecutors indicated they might treat
Levesque differently than Barnes. Murphy said it seems possible,
based on police statements, that Levesque was sexually assaulting
Barnes before the candle fell _ though he noted that Barnes and
Levesque seemed to be on friendly terms later that night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Levesque is more responsible for the start of this fire,''
Murphy said.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for Levesque and Barnes have been working jointly in
their fight for a dismissal. Both said the prosecution's statements
wouldn't change that relationship, for now.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-08-00 1922EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
