<DOCNO> NYT20000808.0262 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 19:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6073 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-DIVORCE-STOCK-OPTION-     08-08 0891
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIVORCE-STOCK-OPTION-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEEING STOCK OPTIONS AS INCOME, SOME DIVORCE COURTS RECONSIDER
SUPPORT AWARDS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV:  Graphic  is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By AMY ZIPKIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In just the last decade, stock options have gone from being
icing on the cake in many executive pay packages to the cake
itself, and the number of Americans holding at least some options
has soared from 1 million in 1992 to an estimated 10 million today.
</P>
<P>
   Now, America's divorce courts are playing catch-up in trying to
understand options as a compensation method. In recent years,
judges in several states have taken a closer look at the wealth
locked up in unexercised options and have made decisions that are
aimed at awarding at least some of that wealth to the former
spouses of those who hold the options.
</P>
<P>
   Though the rulings address different facets of the perplexing
question of how to evaluate unexercised stock options, legal
experts say they collectively reflect a social concern that is
central in family law: the best interests of the children.
</P>
<P>
   Academics may have developed mathematical models for valuing
unexercised options, notably the Black-Scholes method. But these
recent court decision are more about how to make sure ex-spouses
share in the wealth generated by options than about how to value
them.
</P>
<P>
   The court decisions hold the potential for inflicting a great
deal of financial pain on breadwinners who thought the ordeal of
their divorces was behind them.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the case of Richard John Kerr and his former wife,
Deedee Jean Kerr. In 1996, the couple went to court in California
for a permanent support hearing before the dissolution of their
20-year marriage. At the time, court documents show, Deedee Kerr
was a homemaker and Kerr was vice president of engineering at
Qualcomm Inc., a wireless communications company based in San
Diego, with an annual salary of $159,735. Two of their four
children lived at home.
</P>
<P>
   When they separated three years earlier, the couple, as required
by California law, had already agreed to an equal division of all
their property, including options in Qualcomm stock that Kerr had
acquired but not yet exercised. In addition, Kerr had agreed to pay
his ex-wife $3,309 a month in alimony and child support, based on
his salary at that time of $110,427.
</P>
<P>
   Deedee Kerr, however, asked Judge Edward Huntington to increase
the payments _ and after the hearing in 1996 he complied, raising
them 45 percent, to $4,806. His reasoning, legal experts say, broke
new ground. Stock options are a form of income, he ruled, and
because the income that the Kerrs had received in past years by
exercising Qualcomm options was a big factor in maintaining their
standard of living, the calculation of alimony and child-support
payments had to take into consideration the probable awarding and
exercising of future stock options.
</P>
<P>
   Huntington also ruled that Deedee Kerr should receive 40 percent
of all income that resulted from the future exercise of her
ex-husband's options, until both children had reached the age of
18, and 25 percent after that. Kerr was free to exercise the
options he currently held, as well as those awarded in the future,
at any time. He also had an incentive not to exercise the options
until the children reached 18. But if he declined to do so, legal
experts say, his ex-wife could ask for support based on income that
would be derived as if he had exercised the options.
</P>
<P>
   Kerr appealed, arguing that the court abused its discretion and
the award exceeded the needs of his ex-wife and children. But the
couple negotiated a confidential settlement before an appellate
judge could issue an opinion.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the ruling was the first in a string of court decisions
in several states that are setting important precedents in divorce
law, legal experts say: proclaiming options to be a form of income,
rather than a form of property.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue had been before the courts, but as best I know never
decided,'' said George Norton, a California family-law specialist
who has consulted and written extensively about options cases. ``In
California, options are not property subject to division if they
are `earned' after separation. The logic then becomes they must be
`income' earned after separation and then subject to support
awards. The concept is options can't be `nothing' _ either property
or income, but not nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   If options are property, most legal experts say, an ex-spouse
has no future claim to them. But once they are considered income,
they become eligible for alimony and child support awards. And
those can be changed at any time.
</P>
<P>
   In Ohio last year, a state appellate judge took the Kerr case a
step further and ordered a Procter &AMP; Gamble executive to make
additional child support payments based on an amount of money equal
to that which he would have paid had he exercised his stock
options.
</P>
<P>
   When the executive, Graeme Murray, and his wife, Susan, divorced
in 1994, she received half the options he held at the time. Three
years later, she asked a magistrate's court to increase his child
support payments because his income had increased from $212,702 to
$325,743.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   The court then re-examined the way Murray's income had been
computed and discovered that his salary, bonus, dividend and
interest income, and even taxable employee benefits, had all been
included, but not his stock options. After that court and a
subsequent trial court ordered Murray to pay more, he appealed the
decisions.
</P>
<P>
   In February 1999, an appeals court ruled that the value of
Murray's unexercised options in Procter &AMP; Gamble stock should be
included in his gross income for the purposes of determining child
support for his 16-year-old son. Since the options could be
exercised a year to the day after the grant date, the judge
calculated the appreciation that would have occurred as if Murray
had exercised the available options that year.
</P>
<P>
   For 1997 the appeals court valued the appreciation of the
post-divorce options at $421,167. Excluding the options from the
calculation, the court found, would allow an employee ``to shield a
significant portion of his income and deprive his children of the
standard of living they would otherwise enjoy.''
</P>
<P>
   Laurie Ahlers, Murray's lawyer in Cincinnati, described the
ruling as faulty because it would in effect force Murray to
exercise his options.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my mind it takes away his ability to plan for his financial
future,'' she said. ``With no other income, he would have no other
choice.''
</P>
<P>
   But Huntington, who ruled in the California case, said the
decision made sense: ``I see it as a logical extension of Kerr,''
he said in an interview. ``Smart companies and industries can find
creative ways to compensate employees and camouflage income as
something other than income. Children and spouses are entitled to
the fruits of those labors. Our job is to unmask the camouflage.''
</P>
<P>
   A court in Florida threw a sop to an ex-husband who suddenly
found himself with a bigger support bill: if the underlying value
of the stock options he held fell, the court might consider
reducing the payments he had to make.
</P>
<P>
   The ex-husband, Albert Seither, was a Southwest Airlines pilot
with annual income of more than $100,000 and 8,415 stock options
that vested at a rate of 1,403 options per year on Sept. 1 of each
year for five years beginning in 1998. The rest are to vest on
Sept. 1, 2003.
</P>
<P>
   Seither's wife, Katherine, a part-time dental hygienist with a
17-year-old daughter at home, went to court in 1998 for a two-day
final hearing on the dissolution of their marriage. After the
hearing, the court found that Seither had a need for $4,000 a month
in permanent alimony, not the $600 she had been receiving, in
addition to the $893 in child support to which Seither had agreed.
Court documents indicated that he had apparently accepted the
options in lieu of a salary increase. And an accountant who
testified on Seither's behalf said the theoretical value of the
options justified the substantial increase.
</P>
<P>
   The Florida court agreed.
</P>
<P>
   Like the courts in California and Ohio, it ruled that the
options were income, not property. And it ordered Seither to pay
alimony of $2,000 twice a month instead of the $600 monthly he had
been paying, in addition to his existing child support.
</P>
<P>
   A Florida state appellate court, while acknowledging that
options have a dual nature, upheld the judgment in December.
However, the appellate judge wrote, ``If the price of Southwest
Airlines' stock falls significantly below the CPA's predictions,
this change should be regarded as a potential ground for the
modification of alimony.''
</P>
<P>
   In yet another wrinkle in the developing legal consensus on how
to treat options in divorce proceedings, a Tennessee appellate
court ruled in October that an increase in income from exercising
yearly stock options as part of a bonus could be averaged and added
to an employee's base salary in calculating child-support payments.
</P>
<P>
   The new terrain these courts are exploring has pitfalls.
</P>
<P>
   Ahlers said she believed the Ohio court failed to grasp the
nature of stock volatility. In March, after Proctor &AMP; Gamble warned
that it would not meet its earnings forecasts, the stock dropped
from $89.87 a share on the grant anniversary date to $61.68 eight
days later. ``Now he's overpaying,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, some compensation specialists question whether the
judiciary should be meddling in an area as arcane as options. The
court-ordered exercise of options could harm an executive in a
couple of ways, says James Crawford Jr., a benefits attorney in
Davis, Calif. ``It could be construed by top management under
certain circumstances as not being beneficial to the company,'' he
said. Moreover, ``If the stock goes down, there's risk of loss if
he's forced to exercise; if the stock goes up, then there's gain
foregone.''
</P>
<P>
   With the specter of stock downturns, company attitudes toward
stock options may be changing. Watson, Wyatt Worldwide, a
consulting firm, tells clients that options are neither
compensation nor benefits: ``They are a behavior-changing employee
communication plan,'' said Carine Schneider, leader of
global-stock-plan services at Watson, Wyatt. Even though options
currently represent about $1 trillion in unexercised wealth
nationally, she said, companies are letting employees know they are
not entitled to this kind of compensation forever.
</P>
<P>
   Which may explain why mediated settlements instead of divorce
trials hold appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are talking about money, which gets people very
emotional,'' said Arnold Schienvold, president of the Academy of
Family Mediators, which is based in Lexington, Mass. He tells
clients to think, ``Not what do I have a right to, but what do I
need.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
