A6077 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-JEWS-TIMELINE09-COX     08-08 0572
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JEWS-TIMELINE09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jews in America: A people's journey
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _1654: First Jews arrive in America, at New Amsterdam
(New York).
</P>
<P>
   _ 1733: Jews are among the earliest colonists to arrive in
English-controlled Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   _ Early 19th century: Reform Judaism, which removes some of the
trappings of traditional Judaism and facilitates Jewish
assimilation in predominantly Christian America, originates in
Germany.
</P>
<P>
   _ 1801: David Emanuel of Georgia, a planter and former
Revolutionary War POW, becomes the first Jewish governor of a U.S.
state.
</P>
<P>
   _ 1861: Judah Benjamin, a Jewish friend of Jefferson Davis, is
appointed attorney general in the Confederate government.
</P>
<P>
   _ 1867: Morris Rich, a Jew, borrows $500 from his brother to
open a dry-goods store in downtown Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   _ 1877: The Hebrew Benevolent Congregation, later known as The
Temple, opens the first synagogue in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   _ 1900: Jews in metro Atlanta _ less than 2,000.
</P>
<P>
   _ 1913: Anti-Defamation League is founded.
</P>
<P>
   _ 1915: Leo Frank, a Jew from Brooklyn, is lynched in Marietta
after being convicted, probably wrongly, of murdering Mary Phagan,
a teenager who worked in the Atlanta pencil factory he managed.
</P>
<P>
   _ 1933: Adolf Hitler becomes chancellor in Germany; physicist
Albert Einstein renounces his German citizenship and settles in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   _ 1939: Felix Frankfurter becomes the first Jew on the U.S.
Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   _ 1945: Allied troops defeat the Nazis, whose death camps took
the lives of some 6 million Jews.
</P>
<P>
   _ 1948: United States recognizes Israel.
</P>
<P>
   _ 1950s-'60s: The Rev. Martin Luther King Jr. receives key
backing from Jews, most notably New Yorker Stanley Levison, whom J.
Edgar Hoover eventually attacks, apparently falsely, as a Soviet
operative.
</P>
<P>
   _ 1955: Jews in metro Atlanta _ about 11,500.
</P>
<P>
   _ 1958: The Temple, on Peachtree Street, is bombed after Rabbi
Jacob Rothschild expresses support for the civil rights movement.
</P>
<P>
   _ 1965: A memorial to Holocaust victims, the second in the
nation, opens at Greenwood Cemetery in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   _ 1970: Sam Massell becomes the first Jew to be elected mayor of
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   _ 1976: Griffin Bell, President Jimmy Carter's attorney general,
resigns from Atlanta's blue-blood Piedmont Driving Club because it
has no black or Jewish members.
</P>
<P>
   _ 1984: Jesse Jackson refers to New York as ``Hymietown,''
highlighting a rift between black and Jewish leaders over Israel
and other matters.
</P>
<P>
   _ 1993: The U.S. Holocaust Memorial Museum opens in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   _ 1999: Racist Buford O. Furrow Jr. attacks the North Valley
Jewish Community Center in Los Angeles. Five people, including
three children, are injured.
</P>
<P>
   _ 2000: Jews in metro Atlanta _ about 100,000. Jews in the
United States _ about 6.5million.
</P>
<P>
   _ 2000: ``Parade,'' former Atlantan Alfred Uhry's dark musical
about the Leo Frank lynching, retooled after a disappointing
Broadway run, premieres at the Fox Theatre. ``The Lynching of Leo
Frank,'' a drama that played off-Broadway, is scheduled to open
Wednesday at Marietta's Theatre in the Square.
</P>
<P>
   _ 2000: Joseph Lieberman, a Jewish senator from Connecticut, is
selected to run for vice president on the Democratic ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Cox News Service research by Jennifer Ryan, Shelia Jackson,
Richard Hallman
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
