<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 19:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6078 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-ELY-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      08-08 0828
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROUTINE &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    SPEAKING OF RELIGION, GORE DID US ALL A FAVOR
 &HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    By JANE ELY
 &HT;    
 &HT;    c.2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a very special way, Al Gore, the certain Democratic
presidential nominee, performed a terrific service to Americans of
all political persuasions when he formally chose Joe Lieberman to
be named his running mate at their party's national convention in
Los Angeles next week.
</P>
<P>
   Anytime a Democrat includes a prayer and many references to his
god in his first speech as the one tapped to be his party's
vice-presidential nominee, he surely helps ease the almost constant
Democratic harangue at the religious right of the Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, in the end, the fact Sen. Lieberman, D-Conn., is quite
public in his religion may have a far greater effect on the
presidential race than the reality his religion is that of an
Orthodox Jew.
</P>
<P>
   Though the great attention focused on Lieberman's religion and
the fact he is the first Jew to run for vice president is
dominating the early news of his selection by Gore, his religion
surely and simply can't be considered more controversial than that
of the Christian conservatives who certainly were in the great
majority at last week's Republican National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   To some, that may sound flip. It is not meant to be.
</P>
<P>
   It is meant to be the observation of one who respects all
reputable faiths and all those who embrace them _ with one caveat.
I do not want to be coerced to subscribe to any religion nor do I
want to be compelled to live my life by the religious tenets of &QL; 
others.
</P>
<P>
   It is inconceivable to me how anyone who professes a religion
could damn the professed religion of another. And it is beyond my
comprehension how even the staunchest of nonbelievers could object
to others believing _ so long as they are not pressured to believe
the same.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, it is my beliefs that make it almost impossible for
me to understand why Gore's selection of Lieberman can be
considered a particularly bold choice.
</P>
<P>
   Why in the world should it be considered ``bold'' for a
presidential candidate to choose as his running mate a man known as
``the moral conscience of the Senate,'' as a man of unflinching
integrity and a person of staunch personal morals?
</P>
<P>
   Is it ``bold'' because Lieberman is a Jew? If so, then this
``bold'' selection says more about us than it does about Vice
President Gore, who tapped him.
</P>
<P>
   So does the first general reaction to Gore's selection of
Lieberman and to George W. Bush's tapping of Dick Cheney as his
Republican running mate seem to tell us more about Bill Clinton
than most of us might wish.
</P>
<P>
   Here, we have almost unbounded admiration for the veep nominees,
respect for their integrity and esteem for the high regard in which
they are held by those in both major parties.
</P>
<P>
   And, on the other hand, we had President Clinton's vice
president and the man he chose to run as vice president in his own
presidential campaign speak for about an hour to a crowd that stuck
with them under a blazing Tennessee sun, and not once did Bill
Clinton's name pass their lips.
</P>
<P>
   Though this week and next week clearly are the political
province of Al Gore, so too are they Joe Lieberman's time of glory
and attention _ just as the last two were Bush and Cheney's. But,
when the sun goes down after the Democratic nominating convention,
so too will pretty much all the attention paid to Lieberman and
Cheney.
</P>
<P>
   Not even those who really try can suggest a time since the 1960
election when they can contend a vice-presidential nominee made a
difference to the election.
</P>
<P>
   It is not without irony that that ticket was the one headed by
John F. Kennedy, the first Roman Catholic ever elected president.
Many insist Kennedy's selection of then-Texas Sen. Lyndon Johnson
was essential to the Democratic victory that year, for, it is
maintained, Kennedy could not have won without Texas and he
couldn't have carried Texas without Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   There are those of us who question even that now near-ancient
political contention. We believe LBJ was an inherent pol of the
first order and think Kennedy could have cut a deal for Johnson to
help him carry Texas _ and about any other place where skilled
political arm-twisting was needed.
</P>
<P>
   Much has been _ and still is being _ made about Kennedy being
the first Roman Catholic elected president. When we think of that
win and then think of Joe Lieberman the Orthodox Jew, we need to
remember two things: &QL; 
No. 1, Kennedy was elected nearly 30 years ago. No. 2, Kennedy the
Catholic was elected president, and Lieberman the Jew is running
for veep. Those are two mighty big differences.
</P>
<P>
   How big? Let's say that's something only someone's god _
Catholic? Jewish? Protestant? Maybe, evangelical? _ might know. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ely is a Houston Chronicle columnist. (jane.elychron.com) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   XXX END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
