u f BC-VERIZON-DSL-BOS &LR;      08-08 0596
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VERIZON-DSL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$2.3B VERIZON DSL DEAL COULD SPEED SERVICE DELIVERY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Verizon Communications, struggling with a major strike and an
earnings disappointment that pounded its stock price, said Tuesday
it is merging its digital subscriber line high-speed Internet
operations with California-based NorthPoint Communications Group in
a deal valued at $2.3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Local customers of Verizon Online, the new name for the former
Bell Atlantic Infospeed DSL service, will see no immediate changes
in service offerings or prices. However, the deal could lead to
faster rollout of DSL services in areas served by Verizon,
including New England.
</P>
<P>
   NorthPoint operates as a wholesale DSL supplier for Internet
service providers, including Shore.net of Lynn and Quincy's Network
Plus locally. It counts 62,000 DSL lines in service nationally.
</P>
<P>
   Since it began building in Greater Boston last summer,
NorthPoint has grown to cover an estimated 75 percent of all homes
and businesses in the metropolitan region, according to NorthPoint
spokeswoman Caroline Howell.
</P>
<P>
   Verizon and NorthPoint will combine their operations into a
so-called ``new North Point'' that will be 55 percent owned by
Verizon and 45 percent by NorthPoint.
</P>
<P>
   Verizon will invest $800 million in the new unit, of which $450
million will be used to expand NorthPoint's network. The balance
will be distributed as $2.50 per share to NorthPoint shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   The deal is similar to a joint arrangement between SBC
Communications and Prodigy that allowed the mid-American Baby Bell
to turn over responsibility for its DSL services to what is widely
seen as a nimbler, more entrepreneurial company. Bell Atlantic had
been widely seen as a laggard in rolling out reliable, easily
installed DSL.
</P>
<P>
   Liz Fetter, who will continue as NorthPoint president and chief
executive after the merger, said the deal will make the two
operations ``a stronger competitor against cable and other
broadband service providers, delivering to customers . . .
innovation, increased choice and better service.''
</P>
<P>
   NorthPoint is now testing in the San Francisco area a planned
new national service called Blast offering video and computer games
to customers over high-capacity DSL links.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the year the combined operation is projected to
cover 3,000 phone company central offices nationwide with a
potential market of 63 million homes and businesses in 163 US
metropolitan areas. The operations now have more than 600,000 Bell
Atlantic, GTE and NorthPoint DSL lines in service.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, which is subject to approval by antitrust regulators
and NorthPoint shareholders, is expected to be completed by next
summer.
</P>
<P>
   The pact was announced as Verizon shares fell 12 percent, their
biggest drop since the 1987 crash, on warnings that the nation's
number one local phone company will fail to meet this year's
earnings estimates. Verizon was also in the third day of a
companywide strike over unionizing its wireless operations and
other issues.
</P>
<P>
   In New York Stock Exchange trading, Verizon shares dropped
$5.625 to $42.25. They were down 17 percent from the June 30
completion of the Bell Atlantic-GTE merger.
</P>
<P>
   Verizon said costs of merging operations and investing in new
technology, and lower than expected operation savings from the
merger, will cut this year's earnings per share to between $2.90
and $2.94, below analysts' consensus of $3.15 reported by First
Call/Thomson Financial.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
