<HEADER>
A6081 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u l BC-BARBIE-VANESSA-HNS &LR;      08-08 1047
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BARBIE-VANESSA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICS R US: SMART AND SENSIBLE VANESSA GIVES BARBIE A RUN FOR
HER MONEY. WITH BARBIE-SIDEBAR AND PHOTO
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By SHERRY THOMAS &HT;    c. 2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   Say what you will about Barbie, she sure is taking the heat off
of Al Gore and George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   America's favorite doll has found herself in hot water _ and
we're not talking the kind in her Pool Party Playset.
</P>
<P>
   Not only has Presidential Barbie 2000 refused to debate Surprise
Party candidate Vanessa, but she also was a no-show at the
Republican National Convention last week in Philadelphia _ only to
have Republican Delegate Barbie show up instead.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did challenge them to a debate. The response was `Barbie's
too busy being a delegate in the campaign races to have a debate
with us,''' said Jennifer Baker, Vanessa for President campaign
manager (and founder of the Philadelphia-based Getsetclub.com,
maker of Vanessa and the other four dolls in her Cabinet).
</P>
<P>
   ``How can she be a delegate and a presidential candidate at the
same time? Maybe she doesn't understand the job?''
</P>
<P>
   The doll race for president is shaping up like another
``Crossfire`` edition of ``she said, she said.'' Real or not, that
other race (you know, George W. Bush vs. Al Gore?) can't hold a
candle to the camp factor of this year's Barbie vs. Vanessa
face-off.
</P>
<P>
   Texas District 137 state Rep. Debra Danburg, D-Houston, took
time from the campaign trail (she's up for re-election, too) to
address the battle of the dolls:
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounds to me like Vanessa is more issue-oriented and wants
to have more debates on the issues,'' said Danburg, stressing she
wouldn't vote for a candidate ``just because she's a woman.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She is trying to appeal to a broader cross section of our
society, and has the educational background and range of experience
that would make her a better official if she were to win the
election.''
</P>
<P>
   Beltway insiders say the road to the presidency is not paved in
plastic shoes. Regardless of what the polls say, if Barbie wants to
lead the country, she'll have to beat Vanessa in November.
</P>
<P>
   Barbie, reportedly holed up at her Malibu Dream House with
longtime companion Ken, could not be reached for comment. Her
campaign manager, Julia Jensen of Mattel, defends her candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think with 41 years of experience, Barbie is uniquely
qualified to serve as president of the United States,'' Jensen
said. ``She's been a doctor, she's been a veterinarian, she's
served as a nurse, she's been in the armed forces several times.
She's been a teacher, she's worked in the communities and she's
really in touch with what's on the minds of young people in the
United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Armed with a hard-line, anti-pink agenda and unbelievably
sensible shoes, Vanessa's visibility at the GOP convention has
given the African-American presidential candidate new power in the
polls.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's more than just pretty in pink,'' said Baker, adding that
nonpartisan Vanessa is also booked for the Democratic National
Convention in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's smart. She's independent. She's the only candidate in
this campaign who can stand on her own two feet _ and I mean that
literally.''
</P>
<P>
   Poor Barbie. Until just a few weeks ago, she had been running
unopposed with an arsenal of feminist organizations behind her.
</P>
<P>
   Jensen said despite the not-nice behavior of the other side,
Barbie is keeping a pretty face about it all:
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Barbie, as well as Mattel, is thrilled that there's
such an interest in girls being exposed to running for such a high
office. That's really the crux of Barbie doll taking on the role as
president, and it's great that Vanessa is doing the same.''
</P>
<P>
   But even Barbie has a past. Long before Vanessa threw her faux
pearls into the ring, Washington observers questioned Barbie's
personal life.
</P>
<P>
   From her on-again, off-again relationship with Ken (so many
bridal gowns; never a wedding) to her ambivalence about committing
to a career (one day a glamorous astronaut; next a Malibu surf shop
operator) Barbie's image hasn't always been presidential.
</P>
<P>
   Not that she isn't trying, mind you. In fact, both candidates
have entered the ring with head-to-toe makeovers.
</P>
<P>
   Vanessa, typically seen in sporty pants, tops and tennis shoes,
has traded in the ``club kid'' look for a roomy blue pantsuit,
pearls, red loafers and a conservative, pulled-back hairdo.
</P>
<P>
   Barbie (who is constantly reinventing herself anyway) sports
shorter, bobbed hair for the campaign, complete with hairspray! And
her slinkier numbers have been cast aside for, yes, another blue
suit with campaign button and matching pumps.
</P>
<P>
   Helen Perry, a Houston-based corporate and personal image
consultant who dressed Louisiana Gov. Buddy Roemer and his wife,
Patty, said red and blue both work for political candidates.
</P>
<P>
   When rating the two candidates' outfits overall, Vanessa clearly
comes out on top.
</P>
<P>
   Barbie lost major points on her pantyhose, hot-blue numbers with
a seam up the back.
</P>
<P>
   ``That screams fashion victim,'' Perry said. ``She's trying to
be elected for something besides a political office. Definitely an
inconsistency there.''
</P>
<P>
   Vanessa's ready-for-U.N.-peace summit navy blue pantsuit,
however, was noted as a wise political maneuver.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pantsuit works, especially with the corporate casual
trend,'' she said. ``It makes her more approachable. Sometimes it's
more graceful for women when they sit down on TV.''
</P>
<P>
   Barbie's platform, which has received the backing of Girls
Incorporated as part of the nonprofit, nonpartisan White House
Project, is about showing girls from sea to shining sea that
``becoming president is possible.''
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone is buying the Barbie rhetoric.
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Schroeder, a former U.S. representative from Colorado,
has also voiced her opposition:
</P>
<P>
   ``What is the `Barbie for President' message?'' she wrote
earlier this year in the New York Times. ``I'm afraid it's `you can
be a president if you look like a 10!'``
</P>
<P>
   VOTER INFORMATION: Polls for this presidential race are open.
Early votes are being taken at www.getsetclub.com. A spokeswoman
for Barbie said the candidate is running as a write-in.
</P>
<P>
   X X X END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
