<HEADER>
A6083 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-OLY-SWIM-TRIALS0809-C     08-08 0609
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SWIM-TRIALS0809-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The spotlight is on suits at Olympic Swimming Trials
 &HT;    By Karen Rosen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS - The U.S. Olympic Swimming Trials open today with
the same tension and many of the same names, but a completely
different look.
</P>
<P>
   Skin is out, bodysuits are in - some stretching from neck to
ankle and wrist.
</P>
<P>
   Semifinals have been added for races up to 200 meters, so the
event - which is a carbon copy of the Olympics - now lasts eight
days.
</P>
<P>
   And with the Trials ending only one month before the Sydney
Games, some elite swimmers are banking on making the team without
being at peak form. They want to save their best for the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   More than 1,200 swimmers are here vying for a maximum of 52
spots, 26 each for men and women.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara ``B.J.'' Bedford, who is competing in her fourth Trials,
is one of many swimmers showing less skin than in `96, but in a
different way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I'm not shaving my head this time,'' said the
27-year-old backstroker, who despite her bald move finished one
spot short of the team in 1996. ``I think that added a little bit
of pressure last time.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Olympic Trials is unlike any other meet - ever. It's one
of the hardest, most heartbreaking meets for 99 percent of the
people who are out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Jenny Thompson knows that sinking feeling. She has five gold
medals and one silver, but no golds in an individual event.
Suffering from insomnia in 1996, she was crushed when she made the
team only on relays.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson had planned on retiring after Atlanta, but she said,
``That all changed when I felt I hadn't done what I needed to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides Thompson, other swimmers with unfinished business are
back, and the biggest names are in her event: There's a pair of
33-year-olds, Angel Martino and Dara Torres (Torres is 10 days
older). Martino, a two-time Olympian who lives in Milledgeville, is
married and the mother of a little boy. Torres returned from a
seven-year retirement and hopes to become the first American to
swim in four Olympics. And Amy Van Dyken, who won four golds in
Atlanta, is back from shoulder surgery.
</P>
<P>
   And then there are promising newcomers to the Olympic Trials,
such as 16-year-old breaststroker Megan Quann and 17-year-old
backstroker Aaron Peirsol, who haven't had their hearts broken.
</P>
<P>
   Quann hasn't reduced her yardage as much as usual because of the
closeness of the Trials to the Games.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sets you up well for the Olympics,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   However, in 1988, the last time the Trials were so late,
everyone except Janet Evans and Matt Biondi fizzled.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the world has been waiting, too, to see what the
U.S. can do. Australia set five world records at its Trials in May.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't swum fast this year yet,'' said backstroker Lenny
Krayzelburg, the world record holder. ``It's important for me to
make a statement.''
</P>
<P>
   Others will make only a fashion statement. The controversial
bodysuits were banned from the Trials, then reinstated when
manufacturers promised to make enough for everyone.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Malchow said the Speedo ``Fastskin'' helped him set the
world record in the 200-meter butterfly.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives me confidence,'' said Malchow, who won't shave his
body here so he'll be sleek in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   However, Bobby Brewer, a backstroker from Forest Park, may wear
the old-fashioned brief made by his sponsor, Tyr.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anybody should make (the bodysuits) at all,''
Brewer said. ``There's too much going on with the material. Are
they judging the best athlete or the best suit?''
</P>
<P>
   Internet: www.usa-swimming.org
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspaper
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
