<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 19:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6084 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-HINES-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      08-08 0727
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HINES-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROUTINE &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    SPLITTING THE SHEETS, DEMOCRATIC STYLE
 &HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    By CRAGG HINES
 &HT;    
 &HT;    c.2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   Al Gore has come down with a highly symbolic _ and possibly
highly selective _ case of ``Clinton fatigue.''
</P>
<P>
   Without publicly dotting the i's and crossing the t's, Gore
wants his selection of Sen. Joseph Lieberman as the Democratic
vice-presidential nominee to be seen as at least a modified
declaration of independence from President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   That's the main point Gore wants voters to take from the hoopla
surrounding his choice of Lieberman, a good, decent, thoughtful man
(as even the Bush-Cheney campaign warmly, wisely and quickly
conceded).
</P>
<P>
   What Gore doesn't want the electorate to reflect on are:
</P>
<P>
   1.The touch of desperation that the choice of Lieberman
represents. Gore, although seemingly a straight-shooter in his own
personal life, is tacitly admitting that his own fund-raising
scandals and his association with Clinton have exposed his ``moral
leadership'' flank. Gore felt the need to use the biggest moment of
the pre-convention campaign to attempt to cover it. Gore was
trailing and played defense.
</P>
<P>
   2a.The success of Bush, to this point, in capturing the middle
ground. Lieberman _ even more than Gore, in his current
``populist'' configuration _ represents the moderate ``New
Democrat'' wing of the party. Lieberman is chairman of the centrist
Democratic Leadership Council (or DLC), which Jesse Jackson once
derided as ``Democrats for the Leisure Class.'' Lieberman's
presence on the ticket makes class warfare a riskier endeavor for
Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's inroads in the center forced an uncomfortable choice on
Gore: to use his vice-presidential selection for the short-term
goal of shifting left to solidify the Democratic base (a task so
far not blessed with stellar results) or to look to the fall
campaign, in which reaching out to independents likely will be more
important. Gore, at least, has chosen the right option.
</P>
<P>
   2b.The success of Bush in advancing an agenda that features some
key points with which Lieberman agrees and Gore does not. This
includes Lieberman's support for such basic Bush tenets _ denounced
by Gore _ as limited use of Social Security tax revenues for
private retirement accounts and at least a test of federally
financed education vouchers to allow low-income families to get
children out of failing public schools.
</P>
<P>
   These are not the only differences in the Democratic ticket that
may be highlighted in the coming campaign.
</P>
<P>
   At its heart, Gore's selection of Lieberman represents the vice
president's apparent inability to tell _ or at least to convince _
Clinton to butt out of the campaign. Now, finally, Gore has decided
to let his selection of a running mate do the talking for him.
</P>
<P>
   In most forms of social intercourse it would be the height of
ingratitude to throw over one's patron and mentor so
unceremoniously. But this is politics, so rules of civilized
behavior have nothing to do with it.
</P>
<P>
   The public perception of Clinton as a sleazebag who has worn out
his welcome was costing Gore, so steps had to be taken. Luckily for
the vice president, Lieberman, the first Democratic senator to
speak out strongly against Clinton's sexual shenanigans with intern
Monica Lewinsky (``Immoral,'' he said) was at hand.
</P>
<P>
   But will Lieberman reinforce Gore's attempt at independence or
merely remind voters of what they don't like about Clinton and
about Gore's long-term association with and obeissance to the
president?
</P>
<P>
   Gore is counting on the electorate being able to perform what
may prove to be intricate surgery: severing him from the slime ball
part of the Clinton record without denying him any credit for the
happier portions, especially the economic boom.
</P>
<P>
   That would be a neat trick.
</P>
<P>
   This is, remember, the same Al Gore who stood in the Rose Garden
19 months ago and gave the newly impeached Clinton a big wet kiss:
``A man I believe will be recorded in the history books as one of
our greatest presidents.''
</P>
<P>
   Even during his brief time in divinity school, Gore picked up
the concept of situation ethics.
</P>
<P>
   Hines is a Houston Chronicle columnist based in Washington, D.C.
(cragg.hineschron.com)
</P>
<P>
   XXX END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
