<SLUG> BC-LIEBERMAN-PALESTINE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PALESTINIANS SEE SETBACK FOR PEACE TALKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHOSHANA LONDON SAPPIR  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Palestinian officials have been choosing their words
diplomatically when commenting on the choice of the first Jewish US
vice presidential candidate. But the buzz on the Palestinian street
Tuesday was that this would not favor their side in the Middle East
peace process.
</P>
<P>
   Like their Israeli counterparts, Palestinians were careful to
avoid the appearance of taking sides in US politics. But clearly
Senator Joseph Lieberman's Jewishness is not insignificant for
either side, and Palestinians privately voiced concern.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real feeling on the street is that here is another example
of the American unfairness and leaning towards Israel because of
the Jewish vote,'' said political analyst Ghassan Khattib, who
heads the Jerusalem Media and Communications Center. ``This is not
good news for the Palestinians.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope that he (Lieberman) will look at the issue of Middle
East peace through a wider lens and make balanced decisions,'' said
Faisal Husseini, the Palestinian official in charge of Jerusalem
affairs. ``I believe he can do so because he is informed about the
Middle East.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman has a solid pro-Israeli record, and was hailed by
Israeli politicians as a friend of Israel. Likud party stalwart
Moshe Arens, speaking on Israel Radio, referred to Lieberman as ``a
declared Zionist.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1997 Lieberman signed a letter to President Clinton
describing Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat as the ``villain'' of
the peace process, and accused him of refraining from stopping a
campaign of anti-Israeli bombings.
</P>
<P>
   Khattib said Palestinian concerns over Lieberman focus on his
political record, not his religion. As to the short-term effect of
the nomination on the chances of Israel and the Palestinians
signing a peace accord in the next weeks, Khattib doubted it would
make a difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will not have an effect on the peace process because it is
not working with or without him,'' he said. ``It can't be worse.''
</P>
</TEXT>
