by 8 p.m. ET.) 1,300 words.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-SWIMSUITS (Indianapolis) _ When the Olympic trials begin on
Wednesday, American swimmers will make as much news for what they
are wearing as for what records they set in preparation for the
2000 Summer Games next month in Sydney, Australia. A bodysuit that
fits athletes from neck to toe has revolutionized the sport. At
least 10 world records have been set worldwide this year in the new
swim suits. Speedo's version is called the Fastskin suit, which
contains tiny, v-shaped ridges that allow water to pass over the
swimmer more efficiently. The super-stretch fabric also compresses
a swimmer's muscles, therefore reducing the buildup of lactic acid
that causes fatigue. By Jere Longman. (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m.
ET in ``s'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   ENERGY-COST-IMPACT (Brooklyn, Iowa) _ For the poor, mounting
fuel prices and heating bills inflict painful choices _ especially
in cities without adequate public transportation and in small towns
and suburbs where long distances make driving a necessity. In Iowa,
according to a new study by the state Department of Human Rights,
many low-income families who faced higher rates for natural gas
during last year's relatively mild winter cut back on food, health
care, phones and electricity to pay for heat. With prices rising,
the department says that situation could worsen this year. By Neela
Banerjee. (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.)
1,900 words.
</P>
