<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 19:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6091 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-FBC-NCSTATE0809-COX     08-08 0646
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-NCSTATE0809-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Amato leading new-look NC State
 &HT;    By Norman Arey
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   RALEIGH, N.C. - There have been some amazing changes to North
Carolina State's football program since the Wolfpack lost to East
Carolina 23-6 to end their season Nov. 25.
</P>
<P>
   -Mike O'Cain, coach for seven years, was fired in late November.
</P>
<P>
   -FSU assistant head coach Chuck Amato was hired as head coach
Jan. 6.
</P>
<P>
   -Athletics director Les Robinson quit and went to The Citadel.
</P>
<P>
   -Amato hired a staff whose combined experience exceeds 200 years
and combined salaries exceeds $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   -State announced it will upgrade Carter-Finley Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and East Carolina is no longer on the schedule.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, like so many other programs, State fired its
coach, brought in a new one and gave him everything the old coach
had been asking for for seven years.
</P>
<P>
   Amato was a linebacker at State in the late '60s and welcomed
his chance to get back to his roots, despite leaving a program that
won the national championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``People ask me how many of our players could start at Florida
State,'' Amato said. ``I tell them zero, although three or four of
our players would be on their depth chart. Bobby Bowden doesn't
have any secrets down there. It's called speed.''
</P>
<P>
   Amato had been at Florida State since 1982. He owns a box full
of bowl rings and watches. one of which he wears on his right hand
along with his Rolex. ``Having the watch and the ring doesn't hurt
when I'm recruiting,'' he said. ``I tell 'em I like jewelry and I
want to add to my collection and you're the type person who can
help me do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Amato's all-star staff is headed by former BYU offensive
coordinator Norm Chow, who had worked with BYU coach LaVell Edwards
since 1976. Chow will get a chance to prove his worth early since
State will start a true freshman, Phillip Rivers, at quarterback.
Rivers takes over from four-year starter Jamie Barnette, who
finished his career as the record-holder in almost every
single-game, single-season and career passing category at State.
``We hate to have a freshman at quarterback, but Phillip is very
mature,'' Amato said. ``He picked up the system quickly and he
makes good decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   Ray Robinson, after an injury-plagued 1999, should open at
tailback. Koren Robinson was the 1999 ACC Rookie of the Year at
receiver, and along with Bryan Peterson, will give Rivers nice
targets to hit.
</P>
<P>
   The offensive line was the area most depleted after 1999, with
four starters gone.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive coordinator Buddy Green will have eight of 11 starters
returning, and defense will have to carry the Wolfpack in the early
going. There are four starters returning at linebacker, including
two who were on the preliminary Dick Butkus award list _ Clayton
White and Edrick Smith. The secondary is the weak link on defense,
with All-America corner Lloyd Harrison and sidekick Tony Scott
graduated.
</P>
<P>
   With three critical areas with little or no experience _
quarterback, offensive line and cornerback _ Amato sets his
journey. He admits he has a long road ahead.
</P>
<P>
   NORTH CAROLINA STATE
</P>
<P>
   -Location: Raleigh, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   -Enrollment: 28,011
</P>
<P>
   -Coach: Chuck Amato (First year as head coach)
</P>
<P>
   -Nickname: Wolfpack
</P>
<P>
   -Stadium (capacity): Carter-Finley Stadium (51,500)
</P>
<P>
   -All-time record: 468-469-55
</P>
<P>
   -Conference championships (number of titles, title years): 7 _
1957, 1963, 1964, 1965, 1968, 1973 and 1979
</P>
<P>
   -1999 record (overall, conference): 6-6 overall, 3-5 ACC
</P>
<P>
   -Schedule: Sept. 2, Arkansas State; Sept. 9, at Indiana; Sept.
16, SMU; Sept. 21, Georgia Tech; Oct. 7, at Clemson; Oct. 14, at
North Carolina; Oct. 28, Florida State; Nov. 4, at Maryland; Nov.
11, Duke; Nov. 18, at Virginia; Nov. 25, Wake Forest
</P>
