<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 19:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6095 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-BROADBAND09-COX     08-08 1218
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROADBAND09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EarthLink sticking to aggressive course
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ EarthLink Inc., the second-largest Internet access
provider in the country with 3.7 million dial-up subscribers, is at
a crossroads.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts worry about the company's stock price, which has
hovered around $11, down from a 52-week high of $31.88.
</P>
<P>
   Customers worry that with the company's explosive growth and the
departure of founder Charles Brewer that customer service _ the
catalyst for the company's early success _ will suffer.
</P>
<P>
   And there are fears that EarthLink's avowed goal of catching
rival ISP America Online is unrealistic.
</P>
<P>
   But the company remains committed to its aggressive plan to
catch AOL as well as grow its share of the high-speed broadband
market. Chief Executive Garry Betty said that with the completion
of a deal to acquire OneMain.com, Atlanta-based EarthLink will
reach 5 million subscribers by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   EarthLink plans more acquisitions by the end of the year.
Tuesday it said it will pay cash for the acquisition of the
consumer dial-up business of IBS Interactive Inc. IBS will receive
cash based upon what EarthLink said was the ``final determination
of the total number of subscribers who remain EarthLink
customers.''
</P>
<P>
   EarthLink would not disclose exactly how many subscribers would
be included with the IBS acquisition. Dow Jones News Service
reported that IBS has 17,000 dial-up subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   Acquisitions are one leg of EarthLink's plan for aggressive
growth. It plans to acquire dial-up customers, increase its
Web-hosting business and generate more non-subscriber revenue from
advertising and its personal start page. In recent weeks, the
company has placed increased emphasis on what may be the most
critical element of its strategy _ an aggressive rollout of
high-speed broadband services.
</P>
<P>
   Betty and President Michael McQuary contend the company can meet
its ambitious goals and eventually catch America Online, the
runaway leader with more than 27 million subscribers. But analysts
who follow the company are not so sure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Catching AOL is virtually impossible for EarthLink or any
other ISP _ even the free ones,'' says Joe Laszlo, a senior analyst
with Jupiter Communications. ``The only way ISPs can grow is by
acquisition. It's hard to find ISPs out there that can help them
grow to the size of an AOL. Virtually all ISPs want to poach
customers from AOL, but people who are new to the Internet still
tend to gravitate toward AOL's strength of brand.''
</P>
<P>
   While Laszlo said continued subscriber acquisition is one
indicator of how an ISP is doing financially, it's not all that
matters. The number of ISPs that can add substantial numbers to
EarthLink's base is beginning to dwindle. Laszlo said EarthLink
should continue to focus on customer retention, high-speed access
and alternative revenue streams. EarthLink already has aggressive
plans for each of those areas.
</P>
<P>
   Laszlo believes it is important to convey to Wall Street that an
EarthLink subscriber is more valuable in the long run than
customers going to the free ISPs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jupiter believes multiple revenue streams are key,'' he said.
``EarthLink's personal start page is a good strategy, and Wall
Street will be looking for growth in that area, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Miles Russ, an analyst with Atlanta-based Robinson Humphrey,
agreed. ``They're not going to catch AOL. There are not enough
subscriber bases out there for them to buy.''
</P>
<P>
   Russ said retention of EarthLink's dial-up customer base should
be its primary focus because eventually, EarthLink will be able to
convert customers to its more expensive broadband service.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both Gary and Mike McQuary have said they've seen higher churn
(cancellation rates) because people have gone to broadband. The
company has been very aggressively marketing high-speed (digital
subscriber line) telephone access,'' Russ said. ``If you look at
the last quarter, you'll see marketing costs went down. That's a
reflection of cutting back on sales and marketing and focusing on
DSL. I think it's a very smart move from management.''
</P>
<P>
   Russ believes that in the end broadband customers will be more
attractive to Wall Street. Broadband customers typically spend
about $49 monthly for access and spend more money and time online.
``They're going after a higher-quality customer,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The company is aggressively marketing and promoting its
high-speed broadband service to the point of taking out a full-page
ad in the Sunday New York Times. Currently, EarthLink has 80,000
broadband subscribers _ more than six times the amount it had last
year at this time and 78 percent more than in the first quarter of
2000.
</P>
<P>
   Laszlo said EarthLink's acquisition strategy is important, but
what's even more important is being able to hold on to its
subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They need to show a solid subscriber base and provide
information about what kind of subscribers are EarthLink
subscribers,'' he said. ``How much time do they spend online, and
how much to they shop online? That sort of demographic information
would help them a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   The departure of Chairman Charles Brewer, who left the company
and sold all his EarthLink stock, also raised red flags among some
investors, even though Wall Street is enthusiastic about the
appointment of EarthLink founder Sky Dayton as chairman. Many
onlookers feel Brewer's departure could mean EarthLink is willing
to sacrifice its legendary service and support in favor of
aggressive marketing.
</P>
<P>
   When the company released its second-quarter earnings July 27,
it also acknowledged that the quality of service has suffered in
the first few months after the merger between EarthLink and
MindSpring.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we had some rocky times in the first quarter,''
McQuary said. But he added that service would continue to improve.
In a recent interview, McQuary also said that as the company has
gotten larger (it now has about 5,500 employees), MindSpring's
original ``core values and beliefs'' have met with varying degrees
of passion.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he believes that commitment to service will not fall by
the wayside in the quest for new subscribers. He says it's up to
him and other top EarthLink executives to instill those values.
``We still have a pretty dedicated core of employees who think that
(the core values) are the main reason for working here, and that
will cast light on the others.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson-Humphrey's Russ said EarthLink's current position is
oddly reminiscent of the days immediately following MindSpring's
initial public offering.
</P>
<P>
   ``The company is battening down the hatches and trying to
re-prove themselves to the Street,'' he said. ``Nobody thought
(MindSpring) could make any money, either. But MindSpring insisted
they could, and they were going to stay the course. I'm seeing the
same thing with EarthLink as a merged company. They've come out and
said, `We are not going to go away.' They said, `We are not like
the other dot-coms, and we are not running out of cash.' I get a
sense from the management team that they know their stock is
undervalued but there's nothing else they can do but execute their
business plan.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
