<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDUCATION-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARLEM SCHOOL BATTLES THE ODDS AND THE BOTTOM LINE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, Michigan)   By ANEMONA HARTOCOLLIS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As school districts from New York City to Dallas to
Inkster, Mich., experiment with handing over the worst schools to
private managers in a last-ditch effort to save them, the
experience of the Sisulu Children's Academy in Harlem may offer
some insight into how well this new tactic will work.
</P>
<P>
   Sisulu, founded by a Wall Street financier who half-jokingly
compares himself to the heroic, persecuted protagonist in the movie
``Gladiator,'' opened last fall. It was one of New York City's
first two charter schools (publicly subsidized yet independent),
and the only one being operated with the intention of making a
profit.
</P>
<P>
   A look back at Sisulu's first year suggests, not surprisingly,
that private management is no magic bullet. Two of 12 teachers were
let go during the year, and three will not have their contracts
renewed next year. (Administrators point out that they were able to
act decisively to remove bad teachers because there was no contract
with the teachers' union.) Sisulu went up only to second grade in
its first year, so there are no test scores to compare it with
other Harlem schools.
</P>
<P>
   If there is an obvious academic difference, at this early stage,
between Sisulu and conventional public schools, it is just what one
might expect from a school run by a businessman: Vigilance for the
bottom line and a concern for the customers _ parents and
schoolchildren _ all too rarely seen in the traditional school.
</P>
<P>
   On the last day of school, every student at Sisulu (named for
the South African apartheid foe Walter Sisulu) went home carrying a
complimentary copy of one of E.D. Hirsch's ``core knowledge''
series of books. James Banks, a second grader, walked away with
``What Your Second Grader Needs to Know,'' filled with enough
lessons in history, math and literature to keep him busy all
summer. His mother was thrilled. The school also sent home a sort
of yearbook, long obsolete in most no-frills poorer elementary
schools, full of photographs of students, samples of their work and
testimonial letters from parents.
</P>
<P>
   Most Sisulu parents sent their children to this new charter
school in a search for a better education than they could find in
existing public schools, and, after the first year, most believe
they have found it. Of the 90 parents who responded to a school
survey 250 children are enrolled), 88 said Sisulu was either ``a
lot'' or ``a little'' better than the nearby public schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very convinced that it's a good social mission,'' said
Steven B. Klinsky, founder of Victory Schools, the company that
manages Sisulu. ``I would like to see it get to the point where it
will cover expenses.''
</P>
<P>
   Klinsky is already wealthy from his previous life as a corporate
raider and has a well-documented altruistic side: Seven years ago
he started an after-school program in the East New York section of
Brooklyn, in memory of his brother. As the head of New Mountain
Capital, a private equity firm, he certainly doesn't need to turn a
profit at Sisulu to make a living. But that doesn't mean he isn't
trying.
</P>
<P>
   Sisulu is what a loss leader might be in the retailing business,
the price of penetrating the market and achieving name-brand
recognition before expanding. To his frustration, Klinsky says, he
hasn't made a penny of profit yet.
</P>
<P>
   His company is reimbursed at the annual rate of $6,000 a
student, about 40 percent less than a conventional New York City
public school. To collect an additional $2,700 stipend for special
education, he would have to take special-ed children out of their
regular class for more than half the time, which he has refused to
do.
</P>
<P>
   It would also be prudent to buy, rather than lease, a building,
but he has not been able to fit it into his business plan.
</P>
<P>
   Klinsky says he feels like the gladiator in the movie, who,
having to fight the emperor, does so only after defeating a series
of other foes, and then while badly wounded.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, of course, the gladiator wins, and Klinsky could,
too. In part, it's the Amazon.com principle. As the first to enter
the market, he captures as much market share as he can, making it
harder for newcomers to survive. Already, he has received
permission to start two new charter schools on Long Island.
</P>
<P>
   If he's lucky, he becomes so big that the government can't get
rid of him. His constituents, the parents, will defend him; he will
lobby the government to change the financing formula. With so much
potential power, no wonder that other major lobbying group, the
United Federation of Teachers, doesn't like him.
</P>
<P>
   Soon he'll be going national, and his stock will soar. Unless,
of course, it turns out that charter schools are even less of a
magic bullet than anyone thought.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
