<SLUG> BC-TV-SURVIVOR-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SURVIVOR' ENDGAME: AND THE WINNER IS ... 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.2000, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kelly wins ``Survivor.'' But I'm probably wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone's wrong about ``Survivor.'' A lot of us figured Richard
was a goner on the first week. He's still in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Next, Gretchen was supposed to have the inside track. She
didn't.
</P>
<P>
   Then a computer hacker claimed he'd found a coding glitch at the
CBS Web site revealing Gervase as the winner.
</P>
<P>
   Wrong again; Gervase got the hook last Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   So television's best-kept secret is intact as ``Survivor''
backstabs its way toward a finale two weeks from Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   It'll be a big event, with the two-hour finale followed by a
one-hour town hall meeting. There will be four remaining
contestants at the start of the August 23 show.
</P>
<P>
   Whoever wins the million-dollar jackpot will survive two
``immunity challenges'' that night, and three tribal councils.
</P>
<P>
   Let's figure it out.
</P>
<P>
   The dominant force on ``Survivor,'' since the fourth week, has
been the Tagi tribal alliance of Richard, Susan, Kelly and
sometimes Rudy.
</P>
<P>
   The last five contestants voted off the island were in the rival
Pagong tribe, all tagged by the Tagis.
</P>
<P>
   Going into Wednesday night, the only Pagong who hasn't been
gonged is Colleen, a favorite of male viewers.
</P>
<P>
   True, the Tagi alliance is shaky. Rudy is too cranky to be
reliable. Last week's preview of Wednesday's show hinted at
squabbles. Also last week, Kelly claimed to have ethical qualms
about the alliance, though in the end she voted with Richard, Susan
and Rudy to oust Gervase.
</P>
<P>
   But if the alliance members are rational, they'll keep it
together Wednesday night. It's in their best interests.
</P>
<P>
   That means Colleen, who wore a ``sitting duck'' T-shirt to the
last tribal council, gets her island flame extinguished Wednesday
night.
</P>
<P>
   The other major possibility is Sean, the clueless neurologist
who last week abandoned his alphabetical-order voting scheme,
possibly because he'd soon have to vote to banish himself.
</P>
<P>
   It's one way or the other. Colleen, then Sean. Or Sean, then
Colleen. That leaves Richard, Rudy, Susan and Kelly as the four
finalists.
</P>
<P>
   The other three next gang up on Rudy. He's on the wrong side of
a generation gap, and he's too opinionated. He's out, even though
the others fear he'll track them down back home and slit their
throats.
</P>
<P>
   Richard is next. Now the core members of the alliance have to
turn against each other. But Susan and Kelly are tight.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody ever really liked Richard anyway. Susan and Kelly must
have wondered, along with the rest of us, why Richard is the only
contestant who appears to have gained weight on the island.
</P>
<P>
   So, exit Richard. The last seven to be ejected will choose the
winner from between Susan and Kelly. Susan's own deviousness will
now stand exposed. She'll be blamed more than Kelly for everyone
else's banishments. Richard avenges himself. Kelly wins.
</P>
<P>
   My scenario is clouded by variables. I don't know who succeeds
in the remaining immunity challenges. I don't know who wins a
luxurious stay on a yacht Wednesday night, possibly triggering an
envious backlash. Richard may want to keep Sean in the mix,
figuring Sean would be easy pickings in the ``Survivor'' endgame.
Maybe the alliance falls apart prematurely.
</P>
<P>
   But I do know this. Richard, Susan and their Tagi alliance will
haunt the next batch of ``Survivor'' contestants in the Australian
outback, when ``Survivor II'' reaches CBS in January.
</P>
<P>
   Those contestants will have seen the first ``Survivor.'' They'll
be loathsome from the get-go. Sixteen Richards and no prisoners.
Eee-haw.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
