<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SBC trips on supplying high-speed Internet access
 &HT;    By Kirk Ladendorf
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In its race to become a kingpin of high-speed Internet access,
SBC Communications Inc. has stumbled over logistical and personnel
hurdles this year, alienating some of its business partners.
</P>
<P>
   One of those business partners, Jump.Net Inc. of Austin, became
so frustrated with delays and miscues that it stopped submitting
new orders to SBC for the high-speed Internet service called DSL,
or digital subscriber line.
</P>
<P>
   SBC, the big San Antonio-based communications company,
acknowledged that its subsidiary, Advanced Solutions Inc., has run
into delays in installing the new service. But a spokesman said the
company has fixed most of its problems by adding more technicians
in Texas and the 12 states it serves and by changing its business
procedures.
</P>
<P>
   SBC is both a partner and a competitor to companies like
Jump.Net. It enables Jump.Net and other service providers to
deliver high-speed Internet connections over its phone lines, but
it also delivers the same service through its affiliate, Prodigy
Communications Corp., which it partly owns.
</P>
<P>
   But SBC's assurances have yet to convince Jump.Net marketing
vice president Dewey Coffman that the telephone holding company has
solved its problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a major fiasco right now,'' said Coffman, who said SBC's
problems include lost service orders, significant service delays,
incomplete installation and faulty installations. ``We have
hundreds of customers who are waiting for DSL service through SBC.
Some customers have been waiting three to four months. Some orders
have gotten lost three to four times.''
</P>
<P>
   Because Jump.Net resells high-speed Internet service from SBC,
its Internet customers complain to it rather than to SBC.
</P>
<P>
   Such service complaints are to be expected in an emerging
industry like DSL, according to analyst Mike Lowe with Cahners
In-Stat Group.
</P>
<P>
   Both SBC and Jump.Net have a lot riding on DSL service. SBC
reported that it had more than 300,000 DSL customers this spring,
making it the largest DSL provider in the country, according to
In-Stat. The communications giant has pledged to spend $6 billion
over the next three years to make DSL service available to the bulk
of its customers.
</P>
<P>
   In-Stat projects that DSL service will mushroom from less than 1
million lines in service early alternative companies to deliver DSL
to customers.
</P>
<P>
   When SBC does connect customers to DSL service, it occasionally
connects them to the wrong Internet service company. Jump.Net's
Coffman calls that practice ``slamming'' _ or intentionally trying
to switch customers to its own service company.
</P>
<P>
   But SBC spokesman Michael Coe said his company's incorrect
service connections have been inadvertent errors and not
intentional attempts to slam.
</P>
<P>
   SBC says it fixed its most pressing DSL-related problems in June
and July.
</P>
<P>
   ``Service levels were not where we wanted them to be in June and
July,'' Coe said. ``But we have been improving and we continue to
improve. We are doing so every day.''
</P>
<P>
   Most customers who request DSL service get it within 15 days,
the Coe said.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Robertson, who heads a trade group for Texas Internet
service providers, said Jump.Net's complaints are entirely
justified, but he added that SBC has made new assurances that its
ins
</P>
</TEXT>
