<DOCNO> NYT20000808.0294 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 19:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6111 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t BC-GETAWAY-NCMOUNTAINS09     08-08 1482
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GETAWAY-NCMOUNTAINS09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    North Carolina site offers cool, clear water and resort-caliber
fun
 &HT;    By Paula Crouch Thrasher
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKE LURE, N.C. _ It's been 13 years since this laid-back little
town, nestled in the foothills of the Blue Ridge Mountains around a
pristine 1,500-acre lake, doubled as New York's Catskills in the
film ``Dirty Dancing.'' Thirteen years since Patrick Swazye,
Jennifer Grey and the rest of the cast and crew took up temporary
residence at the historic Lake Lure Inn.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the 1987 coming-of-age drama _ which seems to be running
at least three times a week this summer on TBS _ remains the area's
primary claim to fame.
</P>
<P>
   Take an hourlong pontoon boat cruise from Lake Lure Marina, and
your guide will point out the very spot where Swayze taught Grey
the finer points of, um, dancing.
</P>
<P>
   You'll also learn that ``A Breed Apart'' (1984) _ with Powers
Boothe as a mountain climber up to no good, Rutger Hauer as a
conservationist and Kathleen Turner as a fishing supply store owner
_ was filmed here. So were scenes from ``Firestarter'' (1984) with
Drew Barrymore and, more recently, ``The Last of the Mohicans''
(1992) with Daniel Day-Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   But the real story of how one man's dream to build an upscale
resort in Hickory Nut Gorge was dashed by the Depression is far
more dramatic than any Hollywood movie.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after the turn of the century, Missouri physician Lucius
B. Morse came to the mountains seeking relief from tuberculosis.
Next thing you know, he was the proud owner of a giant granite
monolith called Chimney Rock and 64 surrounding acres. He began to
envision a sparkling mountain lake that would be the centerpiece of
the state's largest resort.
</P>
<P>
   He convinced Rutherford County leaders to dam the Rocky Broad
River and build a hydroelectric plant. By 1925, he had his
1,500-acre lake and was ready to proceed with his resort with
``five golf courses, two bathing beaches, amusement piers, fleets
of motor boats, stables, polo, fishing, athletic fields and much
more.''
</P>
<P>
   Then came the stock market crash of 1929. Morse's money was gone
_ along with his dream.
</P>
<P>
   While the Morse family still owns Chimney Rock, now a popular
attraction in the gorge, a string of businessmen and corporations
has bought and sold the property around the lake. Wealthy folk have
bought lots and built homes _ many quite grand _ along the shores.
</P>
<P>
   Today, at the top end of the lake, is the Lake Lure Golf &AMP; Beach
Resort, an upscale getaway owned by Fairfield Communities. The
sprawling resort _ not a far cry from what Morse imagined _ boasts
condo villas and resort homes for rent, two 18-hole golf courses
(Apple Valley and Bald Mountain), four tennis courts, a sandy beach
and marina, three swimming pools and a lakefront restaurant as well
as a golf bar and grill.
</P>
<P>
   The south end of the lake, hugged by U.S. 64-74A, is an
easygoing resort anchored by the circa-1927 Lake Lure Inn, a
50-room hotel across the highway from the Beach at Lake Lure.
Nearby is the marina, where you can rent boats, take a narrated
lake tour or enjoy a lazy stroll along a trail that skirts the
water, pausing to feed the panhandling ducks.
</P>
<P>
   We have come to the lake on a day trip from Hendersonville,
about 20 miles away. Our outing begins with a tour led by Capt.
Richie Cunningham, who introduces himself with the quip, ``That's
my real name. That guy you see on TV is an imposter.''
</P>
<P>
   He begins his spiel with the tidbit that ``National Geographic
calls this one of the 10 most beautiful man-made lakes in the
world,'' then proceeds to tell us the story of Morse.
</P>
<P>
   ``He paid 25 cents to ride a mule to the top of Chimney Rock,
where he envisioned a lake and hotel,'' says Cunningham.
</P>
<P>
   Later, he informs us we are directly above the spot where a
church in the community of Buffalo stood. Before the town was
flooded, the 80-foot steeple was taken off the top of the church.
It now rises heavenward atop the First Baptist Church of Chimney
Rock. We can catch a glimpse of it on the way back.
</P>
<P>
   Then, there's the story of how Snake Island was cleared of
snakes. Cunningham says six pigs were left on the island for 18
months to do the extermination job. ``The good news was the snakes
were gone,'' says Cunningham, ``but those six pigs had become 20
pigs that weighed 400 pounds each, and they couldn't get them off
the island.''
</P>
<P>
   Rumor has it that Elvis once owned a house on the island, also
called Yacht Island. ``Some people think he's still there,''
Cunningham says, completely serious, ``but I pass here every day
and I've never seen him.''
</P>
<P>
   When our cruise ends, the sun is high over the gorge and we're
ready to hit the lake. We spend the next few hours lazing on the
beach, hopping quickly across the hot sand to splash into the cool,
clear, blue-green water.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd is a mixed bag of locals and tourists, a cross section
of Americana, who've brought blankets, folding chairs and coolers
filled with soft drinks and picnic fixings. A NASCAR race roars on
a nearby radio. A chubby toddler gleefully kicks a beach ball
across the sand.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing exclusive or pretentious here, simply an old-fashioned
but well-maintained mountain retreat _ a good place to kick back.
And in the fall, one can just imagine the glorious palette of color
that will paint the scenic gorge.
</P>
<P>
   Day's end finds us dining on pecan-encrusted trout and crab
cakes at Larkin's on the Lake, which, as the name implies, has a
nice lake view.
</P>
<P>
   After supper, as twilight settles over the gorge, we drive
around the east side of the lake to check out Lodge on Lake Lure, a
rustic but elegant bed-and-breakfast inn, and around to the north
to see the sprawling Fairfield resort.
</P>
<P>
   It's dark by the time we head back to our inn in nearby
Hendersonville, discussing whether we would rather stay at the
hotel, bed-and-breakfast or resort _ or all of the above _ during a
future visit.
</P>
<P>
   That is, if they don't have the place tied up with filming a
``Dirty Dancing'' sequel that TBS can show over and over, say, in
2013.
</P>
<P>
   If you go
</P>
<P>
   Getting there
</P>
<P>
   Take I-85 north to U.S. 25 just east of Greenville, S.C. Go
north, pick up U.S. 64 in Hendersonville, N.C., and travel
northeast to U.S. 74A. Turn right and travel through Bat Cave and
Chimney Rock to Lake Lure. About a four-hour drive from Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Where to stay
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The Lake Lure Inn: In 1928 the New York Times called the hotel
``the little Waldorf of the South.'' Swimming pool, restaurant.
Rates through Nov. 15: $89-$99 (includes continental breakfast).
1-800-277-5873; www.lakelureinn.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The Lodge at Lake Lure: The lakeside lodge, decorated with
fine art and antiques, offers swimming, fishing and boating from
the boathouse. Through Nov. 15: $115-$155 (includes full
breakfast). 1-800-733-2785; www.lodgeonlakelure.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The Lake Lure Beach &AMP; Golf Resort: A full-service resort with
lots of amenities. Through Nov. 13: $90-$235 (weekly and multinight
specials and golf packages available). 1-800-260-1040;
www.lakeluregolf.com.
</P>
<P>
   Where to eat
</P>
<P>
   Restaurants on the lake include Larkin's on the Lake and
Bayfront Bar and Grill, at U.S. 64-74A and N.C. 9, 828-625-4075;
Point of View Restaurant, U.S. 64-74A at Buffalo Shoals Road,
828-625-4380; and Lakeview Restaurant, 112 Mountains Blvd. (at Lake
Lure Golf and Beach Resort), 828-625-3045.
</P>
<P>
   Attractions
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Lake Lure Tours: Hourly cruises on pontoon boats 10 a.m.-6
p.m. daily through November, $9; $5 ages 6-15; free under 6. Dinner
cruises (food additional), $15; $8 ages 6-15. Pontoon and electric
boats, paddle boats and canoe rentals available. 828-625-0077;
www.lakelure.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The Beach at Lake Lure: The beach has lifeguards, picnic
tables, a sandy beach and grassy areas. Day pass is $4; $3 seniors;
$2 children. Open through Labor Day. 828-625-8877;
www.lakelure.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Chimney Rock Park: The 1,000-acre privately owned Natural
Heritage Site is open year-round, although some trails to the
waterfall are closed mid-November through mid-April. An elevator
glides up a 26-story shaft blasted through solid granite to reach
the Chimney. Ticket plaza open 8:30 a.m.-4:30 p.m. (until 5:30 p.m.
during daylight-saving time); park open 1 1/2 hour later. The
annual Krazy With Kudzu! Weekend Sept. 16-17 features Kudzu Queen
Edith Edwards and her daughter, Caroline, the Kudzu Kid. Taste
kudzu jelly and French-fried kudzu leaves, and learn what can be
done with this ubiquitous plant (11 a.m.-4 p.m. on the top parking
lot). $10.95; $5 ages 6-12; under 6 free. 1-800-277-9611;
www.chimneyrockpark.com.
</P>
<P>
   Information
</P>
<P>
   Hickory Nut Gorge Chamber of Commerce, 828-625-2725.
</P>
<P>
   Paula Crouch Thrasher writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
