<HEADLINE>
THE POLITICS OF ADULTHOOD 
</HEADLINE>
   (New York Times OpEd for Wednesday, Aug. 9, and thereafter.)  
 ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's OPED news service. For more information
about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of the OPED news service _ contact one of the New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the text.)  
 By JEDEDIAH PURDY    
 c.2000 New York Times    
<TEXT>
<P>
   America wants to grow up. Underneath the barbs and platitudes,
that is the theme of this presidential campaign. Maybe it came out
of polls. But probably not. It has the ring of an unexpected truth,
the kind of thing a speechwriter, or even a candidate, sometimes
intuits and finds a way to express.
</P>
<P>
   The theme got under way with Bill Bradley's candidacy, which was
about the idea that a prosperous America could afford to pursue
higher goals through politics. Bradley proposed that self-interest
left people cold in the end, and that economically comfortable
voters were looking for ways to reduce poverty, create equality of
opportunity and address racial division. We'd had our good times,
and now was the time to act like adults.
</P>
<P>
   The growing-up issue survived the Bradley campaign. Karenna Gore
Schiff, a visible spokeswoman for her father, has made her
trademark a call to her peers to surrender their ``ironic
detachment,'' the emblematic adolescent attitude, and dare to get
passionate about presidential politics.
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush has defused questions about his own maturity by
appearing front and center in the campaign for national adulthood.
His acceptance speech at the Republican Convention took over
Bradley's theme wholesale. Bush, who by several accounts finished
his adolescence some 20 years after many of his peers, couched his
``prosperity with a purpose'' theme in an exhortation to his
generation to prove itself, to ``reclaim some essential values, to
show we have grown up before we grew old.''
</P>
<P>
   His generation ``tested limits'' in its youth, he said, but is
now coming to ``a responsibility era.'' That phrase animated the
final minutes of Bush's speech and captured his idea that
individuals, religious organizations, corporations and presidents
must temper their appetites and self-interest with a sense of duty
to children, neighbors, the needy, the nation, the natural world.
Everyone must begin acting like a grown-up.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Gore seemed to answer Bush's challenge by naming a
running mate who is more associated with positions of moral
responsibility than almost any other politician today. In fact, if
there has been a criticism of Sen. Joseph Lieberman this week, it
is that he becomes sanctimonious about higher purposes.
</P>
<P>
   The politics of adulthood is resonant for more than one reason.
The most obvious is the adolescent behavior of the Clinton
administration. These eight years have seen undisciplined
appetites, ceaseless experiments with looks and attitudes, and a
desperation to please that sometimes reverses itself into towering
arrogance. People learn to expect these irritations from their
children, but not from their leaders.
</P>
<P>
   A deeper reason is the widespread perception that, indeed,
prosperity is not enough. People who have provided for themselves
and their families are looking for ways to contribute to larger
communities, to give back and to put new meaning in their work.
Others are noticing that, as the country's wealth increases, its
inequalities grow more stark and unsettling. People worry that
``They got rich and threw a lot of parties'' is not history's
highest benediction.
</P>
<P>
   Many young voters take personal maturity and responsibility
seriously. Children of divorce, now coming to adulthood in force,
object to both hasty marriages and self-indulgent departures. Even
anti-sweatshop activists and youthful union organizers read up on
personal investment and build accounts for retirement, their
children's education, or just security. Thirty years ago this would
have seemed premature middle age. Today it has become common-sense
behavior. It is always reassuring to hear politicians echo common
sense.
</P>
<P>
   Yet there is a risk for candidates in too loudly enunciating the
politics of adulthood. Personal responsibility is as desirable in
citizens and leaders as in friends and family. But the main work of
politics is not to produce virtue, and personal virtue does not of
itself produce good politics. Saying that corporations must be
``responsible to leave the air and waters clean,'' as Bush did in
his acceptance speech, is a reason to pass strong and efficient
environmental laws, not a substitute for them.
</P>
<P>
   Politics matters because government enables us to do things
together that none of us could do alone: protect the environment,
keep the workplace safe, guard public health, and address poverty
and inequality on a national scale. Leading decent, successful
lives may not, by itself, make a good society.
</P>
<P>
   That is precisely why so many people now feel that prosperity is
not enough. When politicians only urge us to lead better lives, and
promise to do the same themselves, they may end up amplifying the
discontent that they set out to solve.
</P>
<P>
   (Jedediah Purdy, a student at Yale Law School, is the author of
``For Common Things: Irony, Trust and Commitment in America
Today.'')
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   EDITORS: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on OPED
articles and other features.
</P>
