<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPED-LIEBERMAN-BROWNBACK-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIEBERMAN, MY ALLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (New York Times OpEd for Wednesday, Aug. 9, and thereafter.)  
 ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's OPED news service. For more information
about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of the OPED news service _ contact one of the New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the text.)  
 By SAM BROWNBACK    
 c.2000 New York Times    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ I have often been asked how it is that Joe
Lieberman and I are frequent allies in the Senate. We wrote, along
with former Sen. Dan Coats, legislation to provide vouchers to
disadvantaged children in the public schools of the District of
Columbia. We have repeatedly joined in calling on Hollywood to stop
producing vulgar and violent entertainment. We co-sponsored a law
providing humanitarian help to religious groups being persecuted in
southern Sudan. Away from Capitol Hill, we are honorary co-chairmen
of the Healthy Culture Initiative, which promotes charities and
social projects _ including those that are faith-based _ in local
communities.
</P>
<P>
   I suspect Lieberman has been asked as often as I have how we
work together so easily. He is a Jewish Democrat from the
Northeast; I am a Christian Republican from the Midwest. But our
frequent collaboration is, I believe, based on more than a
collegial professional relationship.
</P>
<P>
   In a time when families of all faiths feel their values are
under attack, Lieberman and I are part of a political alliance that
is quite logically emerging between theologically orthodox
Christians and Jews. Certainly, there are significant differences
in outlook. But there is one sense where these two groups clearly
and strongly agree: We share a belief in universal Truths, in a
moral order ordained by God and discovered, not created, by man.
That shared conviction often translates into similar ideas of how
to improve our laws and our society.
</P>
<P>
   On many issues, including Social Security reform, supporting
missile defense and tort reform, Lieberman has followed his
conscience across party lines, making his record on these issues
more conservative than Al Gore's. It remains to be seen how the two
men's differences will play out as the presidential campaign takes
off in earnest.
</P>
<P>
   Including Lieberman on the ticket does give much-needed
integrity and decorum to the Democrats. History and experience
shows us, however, that the vice president's principles and
positions are subsumed by the president's agenda. If we are to
renew our culture and restore honor to the presidency, leadership
will have to come from the top of the ticket.
</P>
<P>
   (Sam Brownback, a Republican, is the senior senator from
Kansas.)
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   EDITORS: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on OPED
articles and other features.
</P>
