<SLUG> BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF  

</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: ABORTION BILL PROTESTS
</P>
<P>
   Responding to demonstrations against a Guanajuato state bill
that would forbid abortion even in rape cases, the state's
governor, Ramon Martin Huerta, said he would meet with opponents
and advocates of the measure before signing it into law. The bill
has aroused fears that President-elect Vicente Fox's conservative
and staunchly Catholic National Action Party will try to impose
similar legislation elsewhere. Abortion is illegal in most states
except in rape cases.
</P>
<P>
   PERU: RIVAL EASES CRITICISM
</P>
<P>
   Alejandro Toledo, who lost the race for president, softened his
stance against President Alberto Fujimori and said he would join
with the government in seeking a solution to the country's
political crisis. Toledo had previously called Fujimori's May
election illegitimate. He made known his change of heart as an
Organization of American States representative arrived to mediate a
settlement that would allow more freedom of the press and
independent elections.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   INDIA: CASE AGAINST HINDU
</P>
<P>
   The Bombay High Court overruled a month-old lower court decision
dismissing incitement-to-riot charges against the militant Hindu
leader Bal Thackery. The ruling paves the way for Thackery to stand
trial for writing inflammatory articles during 1992-93 Hindu-Muslim
riots that killed more than 1,000.
</P>
<P>
   THE KOREAS: REUNIONS NEAR FOR 200
</P>
<P>
   North and South Korea exchanged the names of 100 people from
each side who are to cross their heavily guarded border beginning
Tuesday for four-day family reunions. The visits will be the first
since 50 North and South Koreans were allowed across 15 years ago.
The lists were exchanged at the truce village at Panmunjom.
Officials also exchanged notes guaranteeing the visitors' safe
passage.
</P>
<P>
   MIDDLE EAST
</P>
<P>
   LEBANON: U.N. REPRESENTATIVE
</P>
<P>
   Secretary General Kofi-Annan assigned Rolf Knutsson, a
high-ranking aide, as his special representative in southern
Lebanon for at least the next six months, as an enlarged United
Nations peacekeeping force settles in along the border with Israel.
Knutsson, a Swede, has been director for Europe and Latin America
in the peacekeeping department and was later in charge of political
affairs in the secretary general's office. In the 1980s he had
peacekeeping assignments in both Lebanon and Israel.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   NAMIBIA: SUPPORT FOR ZIMBABWEAN
</P>
<P>
   Concluding their meeting in Windhoek, 10 southern African
leaders defended President Robert Mugabe and his land
redistribution program. The presidents _ who included Thabo Mbeki
of South Africa, Festus Mogae of Botswana and Joaquim Chissano of
Mozambique _ said Mugabe had promised to redistribute land
peacefully. Mugabe, who supports the continuing invasions of
white-owned farms by black squatters, has flouted several court
orders to remove the squatters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
