u f BC-VERIZON-STRIKE-BOS &LR;      08-08 0729
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VERIZON-STRIKE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VERIZON STRIKE VANDALISM, VIOLENCE INCREASES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE E. LEWIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As 85,000 telephone workers enter the third day of a strike at
Verizon Communications, a group of religious, legal and labor
advocates say they will demand a meeting with managers at the
company's wireless unit in Woburn, Mass. to discuss the alleged
harassment of nonunion workers.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, company officials reported that police are
investigating 455 acts of vandalism and violence, including severed
cables and rock throwing. In some cases, managers who are
substituting for front-line workers since the walkout began Sunday,
were pelted with eggs and rotten fruit.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Rabe, vice president of communications at Verizon, said
two-thirds of the incidents took place in New York City, where more
than 1,000 picketers took part in a mass rally in lower Manhattan
this week. Rabe said the company sought a court injunction to limit
the number of pickets at each exit or entrance to four.
</P>
<P>
   Verizon is offering a $25,000 reward for information leading to
the prosecution of strikers who have tampered with company property
or physically harassed any of the 30,000 managers who are
substituting for the strikers.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the Communications Workers of America and the
International Brotherhood of Electrical Workers, which represent
15,000 telephone operators, customer service representatives, cable
installers, and maintenance technicians in Massachusetts, struck
Verizon Communications over job security issues.
</P>
<P>
   Among other things, the unions are seeking the right to
automatically sign up employees of Verizon Wireless, a subsidiary,
without going through the union election process. The voluntary
plan, called a card check neutrality agreement, is a reaction to
prior court appeals by other employers who were challenging union
election results.
</P>
<P>
   Verizon has said in the past that it is against the unionization
of the wireless unit because increased labor costs would limit its
ability to compete with new, nimble startups and established
telecommunications companies.
</P>
<P>
   In Massachusetts, the company confirmed that cables had been cut
and some managers were harassed by strikers as they drove to work
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, state union official said that while negotiators were
hashing out the details of a card check neutrality agreement,
Verizon Wireless managers were distributing a memo to 48 wireless
workers in the Union Park office complex in Woburn designed to
dissuade them from supporting a union.
</P>
<P>
   The memo obtained by the Globe posed the following questions and
answers:
</P>
<P>
   Q: ``Can the union guarantee improvement of wages or benefits?''
</P>
<P>
   A. ``No. The union cannot guarantee improvement in wages or
benefits without agreement from the company. Afterall, it is the
company - not the union - that signs employee paychecks.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: ``Do I have to sign and return the union authorization card
to the union?''
</P>
<P>
   A: ``Absolutely not. You have every right to refuse to sign the
card.''
</P>
<P>
   Rabe said in a teleconference that the memo was intended to
answer questions about the impact of unionization on their wages,
benefits, and jobs. He said the intention was to inform rather than
intimidate.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Tuesday, the National Labor Relations began taking
statements from wireless workers who claim in a complaint filed
July 13 that they were threatened with discharge if they talked
about union organizing while on the job.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Jobs with Justice, a coalition of community, union
and religious groups, is scheduled to hold a press conference
Wednesday at IBEW Local 1505 in Woburn to discuss alleged
harassment at the wireless unit. ``We want the word to go out that
workers have the right to organize in the United States and, even
subtle attempts to intimidate them, are not welcomed,'' said
Jonathan Fine, director of the Interfaith Committee for Worker
Justice in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   One worker said in an interview that a manager told her he would
``get rid'' of her if she spoke to any of her colleagues about the
unions while on company property.
</P>
<P>
   CWA representative Steve Early said union officials sent the
memo to negotiators in Washington ``so they can talk to the company
about curbing this kind of management behavior.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
