<HEADER>
A6126 &Cx1f; tad-z
r p BC-GORE-VP-0809-COX     08-08 0603
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-VP-0809-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New Democratic ticket gets UAW endorsement
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nashville, Tenn. _ Under a sweltering sun Tuesday, Sen. Joseph
Lieberman basked in the historic moment of becoming the nation's
first Jewish vice-presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American Dream is alive and it is well,'' the Connecticut
Democrat told a cheering crowd at a downtown plaza after being
introduced by Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   In his first public comments about his choice of Lieberman to be
his running mate, Gore called his friend of 15 years a man
dedicated to helping average Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joe and I come from different regions and different religious
faiths, but we believe in a common set of ideals, and we both
believe with our whole resolve that, as Americans, we must make
real the great ideal that we are one country with a common
destiny,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   The new ticket got some good news Tuesday. The United Auto
Workers endorsed Gore after months of sharp criticism.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Yokich, president of the 1.3 million-member union, said
in a statement, ``It's no secret that we disagree _ and disagree
sharply. ... Yet even on trade, where we don't see eye to eye, Al
Gore is better, much better, than George W. Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush issued his first comment on Lieberman, saying he respected
``his convictions, his strong faith, and his record on Social
Security, missile defense and reforming our public schools.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope he will run a positive campaign and that the vice
president will use this opportunity to change his tone to that of
Senator Lieberman's level,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   At the Nashville rally, Gore emphasized the historic moment by
recalling that when John F. Kennedy, a Catholic, was nominated in
1960 in Los Angeles _ where Gore will be nominated next week _ the
nation ``voted with our hearts to make history by tearing down an
old wall of division.
</P>
<P>
   ``And when we nominate Joe Lieberman for vice president, we will
make history again,'' Gore said. ``We will tear down an old wall of
division once again.''
</P>
<P>
   At one point, Gore's voice cracked with emotion as he described
how Lieberman came South during the Civil Rights movement to
register African-Americans to vote, quoting Lieberman as having
written at the time, ``I am going because there is much work to be
done. I am an American, and this is one nation or it is nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   The rally afforded voters the first opportunity to see Lieberman
and Gore together as the ticket that will challenge Bush and his
running mate, Dick Cheney. The two Democrats plan three days of
campaigning together in Connecticut, Georgia and Pennsylvania
before next week's Democratic National Conventio to pledge his
allegiance to Gore _ a man he called the most accomplished vice
president in the nation's history _ and to introduce himself to
voters as a man of deep moral convictions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dear Lord, maker of all miracles, I thank you for bringing me
to this extraordinary moment in my life,'' Lieberman said. ``And Al
Gore, I thank you for making this miracle possible for me and
breaking this barrier for the rest of America forever.''
</P>
<P>
   Adopting Gore's latest campaign theme, Lieberman called the fall
election a choice between the new guard and the old guard. He
pledged to pursue an agenda focused on economic growth, balanced
budgets and midd. ``But it makes me feel that I have a mission to
go out and help this man get elected.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: Joseph Lieberman: www.senate.gov/(tilde)lieberman
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
