<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 20:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6128 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-LIEBERMAN-BUSINESS-AR     08-08 1033
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIEBERMAN-BUSINESS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIEBERMAN VIEWED AS PRO-BUSINESS DEMOCRAT 
</HEADLINE>
  (With GORE-LIEBERMAN) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By DAVID E. ROSENBAUM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ At a Democratic fund-raiser last month at the
Manhattan apartment of the singer Paul Simon, Vice President Al
Gore was introduced by Connecticut's senators, Christopher Dodd and
Joseph Lieberman.
</P>
<P>
   After some preliminary remarks about the strength of the economy
and the old ideas of Republicans, Gore began to bash big oil and
big insurance companies, a staple nowadays of his stump speech.
``We need to give the medical decisions back to the doctors, and
take them away from the accountants and the HMO's and the insurance
companies,'' he declared.
</P>
<P>
   The moment Gore uttered the words ``insurance companies,''
several of the people in Simon's living room snickered loudly.
Insurance is to Connecticut what oil is to Oklahoma, what
automobiles are to Michigan, what tobacco is to Kentucky. And
Lieberman has been a staunch ally of the industry.
</P>
<P>
   On a broad array of issues, Lieberman is perceived as a
business-friendly Democrat. On some issues, including those that
affect the insurance industry, he has been much more of a business
ally than Gore. This could help the Democratic ticket in its fund
raising and in reassuring corporate leaders who are nervous about
Gore's environmental views.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Lieberman is one of a handful of Democrats who
support legislation to limit the amount of damages that can be
collected from lawsuits. Such legislation has been at the top of
corporate America's Washington wish list for more than a decade.
Insurance companies have led the battle in favor of it. Trial
lawyers, among the Democratic Party's biggest contributors, have
led the fight against the limits on damages. Lieberman has always
been on the side of the insurance business. Gore has always been
with the lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We consider Mr. Lieberman a friend of the insurance
industry,'' said Jack Dolan, a spokesman for the American Council
of Life Insurance.
</P>
<P>
   By the same token, Lieberman has regularly voted for increases
in the Pentagon's budget. Two major defense contractors, General
Dynamics Corp. and the United Technologies Corp., have plants in
Connecticut that employ thousands of workers.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman has been an ally of other companies that Gore has
blasted in recent speeches, including pharmaceutical companies.
Several, including the Bayer Corp., Bristol-Myers Squibb Co. and
Pfizer Inc., have operations in Connecticut. In 1997, when the
Senate was considering legislation to reauthorize the Food and Drug
Administration, Lieberman was among the few Democrats who voted on
the side of the drug industry on important amendments.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman has been rewarded for this support with campaign
donations. The Center for Responsive Politics, a nonpartisan
organization that tracks campaign money, reported on Tuesday that
Lieberman had received more money from the insurance interests for
his Senate race this year than any other senator ($197,419), and
more from pharmaceutical interests ($91,150) than any other senator
except Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, who is chairman of the Finance
Committee's subcommittee on health. Lieberman has also received
nearly $100,000 from political action committees and individuals
connected to defense contractors.
</P>
<P>
   It is not surprising that Lieberman has been a standard bearer
for important industries in his state. A politician who did not do
that would not last very long in office.
</P>
<P>
   But as Democrats go, Lieberman has been quite friendly to
business generally. Frank Coleman, a spokesman for the United
States Chamber of Commerce, said that in his two terms in the
Senate, Lieberman had voted on the side of business interests more
than almost any other Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman is a vigorous supporter of international trade, a
position similar to Gore's but different from many Democrats, and
he is one of the few Democrats in the Senate who favors a reduction
in the capital gains tax.
</P>
<P>
   In Silicon Valley, Lieberman is hailed as the senator who saved
stock options.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, accounting rulemakers considered changing the
accounting procedures for stock options in a way that would have
reduced the reported profits of companies that granted options to
executives and other employees. It was one of the first
congressional issues to attract lobbying from executives in Silicon
Valley.
</P>
<P>
   First, Lieberman pushed through the Senate a nonbinding
resolution that denounced the Financial Accounting Standards Board,
the arbiter of accounting procedures, for trying to change the
rules. Then he introduced legislation to restrict the authority of
the board. After that, the board backed down.
</P>
<P>
   In part for his role in the options fight, the American
Electronic Association, a trade group of technology companies,
named Lieberman to the ``high-tech legislative hall of fame.'' Gore
considers the high-tech community an important constituency and has
held many fund-raising events and meetings with its executives.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman's record in support of business interests could help
Democratic fund raising for the fall campaign. ``Senator
Lieberman's record on fiscal responsibility and issues with regard
to business generally has been very strong, very moderate and ought
to be very attractive to the business community,'' said Joel
Jankowsky, who heads the lobbying arm of Akin, Gump, Strauss, Hauer
&AMP; Feld, a Washington law firm.
</P>
<P>
   There is a business constituency that remains nervous about
Lieberman: Hollywood. Entertainment executives, one of the
Democratic Party's most important cash constituencies, are
concerned about his embrace of the V-chip and his alliance with
William Bennett, the former education secretary under President
Ronald Reagan, in denouncing excessive violence and sex in movies,
television and music. But that will not stop entertainment
executives from organizing lavish parties for the Democratic ticket
next week at the Democratic convention in Los Angeles.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-08-00 2014EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
