<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 20:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6148 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-FIREFIGHTER-WORKPLACE     08-08 1096
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIREFIGHTER-WORKPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FURY OF A SCORNED VOLUNTEER FIREFIGHTER BECOMES A CRUSADE
</HEADLINE>
 By MARY WILLIAMS WALSH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   They light the fireworks on the Fourth of July. They pull people
out of burning buildings. They teach children not to play with
matches. By one estimate, they save taxpayers $37 billion a year.
</P>
<P>
   Few people embody America's ideals like its 1.1 million
volunteer firefighters. Gritty, charitable, self-reliant, they
answer millions of calls for help each year. And each year,
thousands get hurt.
</P>
<P>
   It is then that many discover that their generosity is not
necessarily matched by the society they serve. Disabled volunteer
firefighters generally get workers' compensation, but the benefits
vary widely. Some states match what career firefighters receive.
Some pay less. Some pay nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Nicholson got next to nothing after he was hit by a car
on a fire call in 1972, when he was a 17-year-old volunteer
firefighter in Bushnell Basin, outside Rochester, N.Y. Both his
legs were broken, his skull was fractured, his lungs collapsed, he
suffered a stroke, and he sank into a coma for three weeks. His
parents were told there was only a 50-50 chance he would live.
</P>
<P>
   When he regained consciousness, he required leg braces and
crutches to walk. A junior in high school, he could no longer
concentrate on his favorite subject, criminal justice. His memory
failed, and his emotions flared inexplicably. He needed speech
therapy but flew into a rage when the therapist told him to forget
his boyhood dream of becoming a state trooper.
</P>
<P>
   The state of New York agreed to compensate him with $80 a week
for his permanent disability.
</P>
<P>
   For more than 20 years, Nicholson struggled along on those
meager checks, unable to move out of his parents' house. Then, in
1993, an administrative judge laughed at his request for an
increase. It was a routine bureaucratic put-down, but Nicholson
could not shrug it off.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, he has led a crusade to overhaul the way the
workers' compensation system treats volunteer firefighters. Against
all odds, he scored victories in New York. Now he is gearing up for
the ultimate battle: to set a federal standard for compensation.
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else, his accomplishments show what one determined
human being can do to fix a system that most people do not notice
is broken because its victims are invisible. ``This sounds
quixotic,'' said Stewart Schwab, a professor at Cornell Law School
and an expert on workers' compensation. ``But he seems to have a
track record for knocking down a few windmills.''
</P>
<P>
   The energy behind his crusade comes partly from his belated
understanding of how serious his injuries were. It was not until
1990 that he underwent the neurological testing that disclosed that
his memory and emotions were so erratic because of brain damage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just thought that was the way I was,'' said Nicholson, who
needed three years to finish his senior year of high school and
five years to complete a two-year degree in criminal justice at
Monroe Community College. His first job, as a sheriff's dispatcher,
lasted only five months.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next 17 years, Nicholson was fired 27 times, from jobs
as seemingly simple as supermarket bagger. ``They'd holler at me
and tell me: `Hey! Don't you remember I told you not to do that?'''
he said. ``And I'd say, `No,' and they'd fire me.''
</P>
<P>
   New York state paid Nicholson so little in part because it, too,
had failed to understand the extent of his injuries and categorized
him as only partly disabled. But in a 1993 review of his case,
Nicholson told the judge that the new findings showed that he would
never be able to work and told the judge that $80 was not enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``He kind of laughed and said, `Well, if you don't like it,
change the workers' compensation law,''' Nicholson recalled. ``I'll
never forget the way he laughed. That's what made me determined to
try to do something.''
</P>
<P>
   It did not occur to him to appeal the judge's decision, he said.
Instead, he looked up an old friend, Jim Alesi, who had become a
state senator. He asked Alesi how to go about changing the law. The
senator said he supposed he could write a personal bill that would
legally raise Nicholson's payments to the 1992 rate of $400 a week
for cases like his. But he warned the former firefighter not to get
his hopes up.
</P>
<P>
   Undaunted, Nicholson spent four years making the rounds of every
fire hall, village board, town council and county legislature he
could find in his part of the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll never forget the day he walked into my office,'' said Ed
Riley, fire coordinator for Monroe County, which has 40 fire
departments. Nicholson, walking with a cane and carrying a cassette
player to record conversations _ without it, he often forgets what
people tell him _ spilled out his story, saying he could not bear
living under his parents' roof for the rest of his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was shocked,'' Riley said. ``I'd been in this job for 12
years, and my biggest thing is to make sure everybody's in good
shape. I was saying: `Where have you been? Why didn't anybody tell
me about you before?'''
</P>
<P>
   The answer was that because Nicholson could no longer play
baseball, march in parades or take part in other all-American
events that bring volunteer firefighters together, he had simply
been forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   Riley began taking Nicholson to the various meetings fire
officials attend. A groundswell began. Brigades wrote letters to
their representatives in Albany, N.Y., urging them to pass
Nicholson's bill. Fire chiefs around the state began wondering how
many other disabled volunteers might be lost in the system.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually about 30 disabled volunteer firefighters were
discovered, some housebound and receiving payments of as little as
$65 a week.
</P>
<P>
   In Albany, the legislature first enacted Nicholson's personal
bill, then a second personal bill for another disabled volunteer,
who died before the workers' compensation board released the higher
payments. A third general bill raised the benefits of all the
forgotten volunteers.
</P>
<P>
   Those victories have emboldened Nicholson to research state laws
on the Internet and get in touch with national firefighting
organizations to help him reach his goal of a federal standard.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an interesting twist,'' said Schwab, noting that most
attempts to standardize state compensation practices are the work
of insurance companies and other business interests, trying to
limit payouts. ``He's coming at it from the opposite perspective,''
he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
