<HEADER>
A6149 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-NC-DANCE-FESTIVAL-$AD     08-08 1032
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NC-DANCE-FESTIVAL-$ADV13-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIXING UP A SALAD OF DANCE STYLES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., Australia, Senegal, Germany)   (For release Sunday, Aug. 13)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By JACK ANDERSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dance is getting itself happily mixed up. Some choreographers
are having a ball with rock 'n' roll and all that jazz. Others are
uniting seemingly disparate music and dance styles. The results can
be artistically provocative, the best of such productions making
theatergoers gaze in wonder at both dance and the world from which
it comes.
</P>
<P>
   Take two refreshing productions at this summer's American Dance
Festival in Durham, N.C. Mark Dendy's new work was performed to a
potpourri of rock and pop music of the recent past. Although the
choreography reflected the musical moods, it seldom resembled
anything you'd see on MTV.
</P>
<P>
   The piece was easy to enjoy simply as a modern-dance energy
study. But Dendy called it ``I'm Going to My Room to Be Cool Now,
and I Don't Want to Be Disturbed.'' That title made it possible to
interpret the sometimes feverish action as the daydreams _
especially the erotic ones _ of an adolescent, confused by his
strong but inchoate urges and unsure of his sexual orientation, who
has locked himself in his bedroom to listen to favorite records.
</P>
<P>
   Trisha Brown presented the complete version of ``The Trilogy,''
excerpts from which had been seen previously in New York. In some
episodes of this full-evening jazz piece, she appeared to be
inventing her own eccentric form of jitterbugging. The choreography
certainly did swing. But most of the production, with its sudden
juxtapositions of rigorous order and wiggling, was as idiosyncratic
as its complex score by Dave Douglas. Some theatergoers even
wondered if the music was jazz at all, just as they did when they
heard Donald Knaack's score for another festival premiere, Twyla
Tharp's ``Surfer at the Styx,'' which, like Brown's creation, was
made possible through the Doris Duke Millennium Awards for Modern
Dance and Jazz Music Collaborations.
</P>
<P>
   When the question ``Is this jazz?'' was raised during a festival
symposium with Brown and Douglas, the composer replied that he
comes from a jazz background, considers his close collaboration
with Brown as an extension of his tradition and expressed an
interest in the way art forms can redefine themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Art keeps leaping over formal boundaries. So maybe the time has
now come for the Lindy Hop version of Stravinsky's ``Sacre du
Printemps.''
</P>
<P>
   The possibility of such a thing was suggested back in 1930 in
Carl Van Vechten's ``Parties,'' an incisive satirical novel about
Prohibition-era New York. During his long life (1880-1964), Van
Vechten was not only a fiction writer with a wicked tongue but also
an erudite music and dance critic whose interests extended from the
newest ballets and modern-dance experiments to the latest Harlem
dance styles. In ``Parties,'' recently reissued by the Sun and Moon
Press of Los Angeles, Van Vechten noted that because the strenuous
social dance known as the Lindy Hop involved an ``ecstatic flinging
about of arms and legs, and contortions of the torso,'' it could
produce an effect approaching ``the sensations of religious
ecstasy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It could be danced, quite reasonably and without alteration of
tempo to many passages in the `Sacre du Printemps,''' Van Vechten
wrote. His suggestion, though undeniably odd, is not totally
freakish; Stravinsky's work, after all, does depict states of
spiritual possession.
</P>
<P>
   As ease of travel and speed of communication make it easy to
become acquainted with the world's cultures, inquisitive,
internationally minded choreographers are combining styles and
techniques, just as imaginative chefs blend elements of several
cuisines to create their own distinctive recipes.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, many Japanese dancers have flocked to Spanish
flamenco classes. The schedule for this year's Jacob's Pillow Dance
Festival in Becket, Mass., included Compagnie Jant-Bi, a Senegalese
company, in ``Le Coq Est Mort,'' which was created for it by the
German Neo-Expressionist choreographer Susanne Linke. In her ``Pour
Antigone,'' shown last month at Lincoln Center Festival 2000, the
French choreographer Mathilde Monnier retold a Greek tragedy in
African terms with a cast of both African and European dancers. The
mixing and matching of dancers and styles can have fascinating
results.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, however they may be modified in specific productions,
traditional dance techniques should also be preserved in their
purity in honor of a culture's heritage. The dance world needs the
old as well as the new. And it is easy for new choreographic
composites to be merely messy.
</P>
<P>
   But at their best, stylistic potpourris can be entertaining and
aesthetically challenging. When Donald Byrd/The Group appeared at
the Joyce Theater last season, the company offered Byrd's ``In a
Different Light: Duke Ellington,'' a tribute affirming the
remarkable range of this great jazz composer. Some scenes were
lyrical. Yet one episode was a sexy _ indeed, raunchy _ comic romp
in what might have been a nightclub or brothel. At still other
times, Byrd's choreography was as cool and precisely patterned as
certain balletic abstractions by George Balanchine. All these
episodes were choreographically convincing responses to Ellington's
music, which, as Byrd's title suggested, can be interpreted in many
different artistic lights.
</P>
<P>
   When the Australian Ballet performed at City Center last fall,
its most unusual offering was Stephen Page's ``Rites,'' to
Stravinsky's ``Sacre du Printemps.''
</P>
<P>
   For this production, the ballet dancers were joined by members
of the Bangarra Dance Theater, an Australian aboriginal company.
Page turned Stravinsky's ballet, which originally depicted human
sacrifice in prehistoric Russia, into an aboriginal ritual honoring
earth, wind, fire and water. The concept was original and the
hybrid choreography convincing.
</P>
<P>
   So how about it? Is anyone inspired to try that Lindy Hop
``Sacre''?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-08-00 2037EDT &QL; 
