u a BC-TEXAS-EXECUTE-NYT     08-08 0521
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-EXECUTE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS BOARD REFUSES TO HALT EXECUTION OF LOW-IQ INMATE 
</HEADLINE>
  By RAYMOND BONNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Texas Board of Pardons and Paroles has turned down a request
for clemency from Oliver Cruz, who was sentenced to death for the
rape and murder of an Air Force enlisted woman.
</P>
<P>
   Cruz, who defense psychologists say is mentally retarded, is
scheduled to be executed at 6 p.m. Wednesday in Livingston, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The 18 members of the board voted unanimously on Monday to
refuse the clemency. They gave no reason. The board has rejected
all but one of the 74 clemency requests from death row inmates
since Gov. George W. Bush took office in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   At Cruz's trial, the state did not contest the defense's
evidence that Cruz was mentally retarded and had an IQ as low as
64. People with an IQ below 70 are generally considered to be
mentally retarded.
</P>
<P>
   But Tuesday, the San Antonio district attorney's office, which
prosecuted Cruz, began circulating a 1989 report that showed his IQ
as 83, said Barbara Hervey, an assistant district attorney there.
</P>
<P>
   Hervey said the district attorney, Susan D. Reed, received the
report on Tuesday based on a request to prison officials last week.
She said she did not know why the report had not been made public
earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Reed declined to make a copy of the report available.
</P>
<P>
   At Cruz's trial, the prosecutor had argued that one reason to
execute Cruz was because he ``may not be smart,'' and that made him
``more dangerous'' to society.
</P>
<P>
   Cruz's lawyer, Jeffrey Pokorak, was angry at the last-minute
disclosure of the IQ report by the district attorney's office.
</P>
<P>
   ``This just demonstrates how political this is,'' Pokorak said.
``They know they should not be killing a mentally retarded person,
so now they are coming up with new evidence that says he is not
mentally retarded.''
</P>
<P>
   Pokorak has asked for a full evidentiary hearing on the question
of Cruz's mental retardation.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Supreme Court is reviewing a request for a stay of
execution filed on Friday by Pokorak, who argues that the jury was
not properly instructed to consider the evidence of mental
retardation. If the court turns down the appeal, Cruz's fate will
be in the hands of the lieutenant governor, Rick Perry, who is
sitting in for Bush, who is out of the state. Under Texas law, the
governor can grant only a one-time 30-day delay of execution.
</P>
<P>
   The American Bar Association urged Bush late Monday not to go
forward with the execution.
</P>
<P>
   ``The execution of persons who are mentally retarded serves no
principled purpose and demeans our system of justice,'' Martha W.
Barrett, the organization's president wrote to Bush.
</P>
<P>
   The European Union on Tuesday called on Bush not execute Cruz,
saying that the execution of someone who is mentally retarded
violated international human rights norms.
</P>
<P>
   ``We urge you to demonstrate compassion with regard to this
case,'' it said in the letter to Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Cruz was sent to death row for the rape and murder of Kelly
Donovan, who was stationed at the Air Force base in Cruz's
hometown, San Antonio.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
