<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VP-HADASSAH09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hadassah keeps Lieberman grounded
 &HT;    By Brian E. Crowley
 &HT;    and Douglas Belkin
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKE WORTH, Fla. _ Joe Lieberman's wife, Hadassah, lived for
nearly three years in Palm Beach County while her father was rabbi
of Temple Beth Sholom.
</P>
<P>
   The Lake Worth temple had fewer than 50 families when Rabbi
Samuel Freilich, who had been a slave laborer under the Nazis,
became their spiritual leader in July 1958.
</P>
<P>
   Hadassah Freilich Lieberman, 52, was born in March 1948 in a
refugee camp in Prague, Czechoslovakia. Her mother, Ella, survived
Auschwitz and Dachau.
</P>
<P>
   After the war her father, a native of Czechoslovakia, worked
with Jewish refugees and organized schools in Prague and Budapest,
Hungary. In 1949, Freilich became a U.S. citizen.
</P>
<P>
   He was a rabbi in Gardner, Mass., before coming to Lake Worth to
take over the small congregation. Temple Beth Sholom was formed in
1953 by the Lake Worth Hebrew Benevolent Association with just 20
families. He left the temple in the summer of 1961, returning to
Massachusetts with his family. He died in 1993 at the age of 91.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Schuman went to Lake Worth Junior High School with
Hadassah and had a crush on her. When he saw her on television, he
couldn't believe his eyes. It was the same girl he kissed when he
was 12 years old, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``She liked me and I paid some attention to her, but she was the
rabbi's kid and I figured you don't mess around with the rabbi's
kid,'' Schuman said.
</P>
<P>
   A pretty girl, Schuman remembers Hadassah as a ``good kisser''
who was ``always upbeat, very, very positive but self-conscious of
her father's accent.''
</P>
<P>
   Hadassah Freilich graduated from Gardner High School in 1966,
and then Boston University. She was a divorced mother with a 6-year
old son in 1982 when she met Lieberman, hen a Connecticut state
senator. Lieberman also was divorced. He has two children with his
previous wife. The Liebermans married in 1983 and have a
12-year-old daughter, Hana.
</P>
<P>
   Deeply involved in her husband's political life, Hadassah also
has the role of making sure that Lieberman doesn't get too full of
himself. Once, on the way home from an event where Lieberman had
been called one of the great leaders in Connecticut history, he
turned to his wife and asked, ``How many truly great leaders are
there in the Western world today?''
</P>
<P>
   ``One less than you think,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Schuman, an attorney who lives in Lake Clarke Shores, still has
fond memories of Hadassah and a message for his old flame: ``Tell
her to get in touch with me and I'll deliver Florida.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
