u s BC-BBN-CHIPPER0809-COX     08-08 0388
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-CHIPPER0809-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Chipper Jones, Braves reach agreement on mega-contract
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI - Chipper Jones isn't going anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   The reigning National League MVP has reached an agreement with
the Braves on a six-year, $90-million contract. The Braves also
reportedly have options for an additional two years worth $30
million, bringing the total value to $120 million.
</P>
<P>
   An official announcement is expected Friday, after the Braves
return from their road trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're close,'' Jones said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Braves general manager John Schuerholz declined comment, and
Jones' agent, Steve Hammond, was not available for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Jones' annual salary of $15 million will make him the
highest-paid Brave, ahead of Greg Maddux, who will make $12.5
million in 2001. Jones' annual salary will rank at the top in
baseball, equaling that of Dodgers right-hander Kevin Brown. His
overall package also will rank among baseball's largest, behind the
contracts of Ken Griffey Jr. ($116.5 million), Brown ($105 million)
and Mike Piazza ($91 million).
</P>
<P>
   Jones, 28, is hitting .307 this season with 24 home runs and 79
RBIs. In his MVP season, he hit 45 homers, drove in 110 runs and
batted .319.
</P>
<P>
   Jones took what was considered less than market value when he
signed his last deal in 1996, worth $8 million over four years. He
was willing to take less money for the security of a longer-term
deal after injuring a knee and missing the 1994 season. The Braves
picked up their option this year, worth $4.75 million with
incentives.
</P>
<P>
   But this time around, Jones was adamant about getting his market
value and said he was prepared to test the free agent market.
</P>
<P>
   Jones' contract agreement shrinks a star-studded potential
free-agent group. Alex Rodriguez, Juan Gonzalez, Manny Ramirez,
Mike Mussina and Mike Hampton have contracts that expire at
season's end.
</P>
<P>
   While the signing is just a matter of time, Jones wasn't
prepared to start celebrating.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I can tell you is there is no deal done,'' said Jones, who
said he last spoke to his agent on Monday. ``We're talking. We're
grinding it out, but there's no deal in place. There has been no
signing it from me.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
