A6154 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-HUNLEY0809-COX     08-08 0717
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HUNLEY0809-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Confederate sub Hunley completes journey
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLESTON, S.C. - One hundred and thirty-six years after its
mysterious sinking, the Confederate submarine H.L. Hunley completed
its journey home Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The slender, barnacle-encrusted vessel returned to Charleston,
its iron hull still intact and its sand-packed innards presumably
holding the remains of nine crewmen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coming up in one piece, gosh, it is the best (vessel) we've
gotten out of the Civil War,'' said author and wreck diver Clive
Cussler, 69, who celebrated by jumping into the ocean, climbing
back in a boat, and offering a champagne toast.
</P>
<P>
   His team's discovery of the Hunley in 1995 spurred the estimated
$15 million-to-$20 million effort to recover and preserve it.
</P>
<P>
   The Hunley was the first sub to sink an enemy vessel. It also
went down in history as the Confederacy's last-ditch secret weapon
against the Union blockade of Charleston Harbor.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's recovery went well, said officials, who had worried
that the Hunley was under great pressure under 30 feet of water and
could crack open if mishandled.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the morning, working in a constant ocean swell and
steady breeze four miles off Sullivan's Island, divers completed
three months of work. It took eight hours to raise the sub,
transport it on a barge to a North Charleston conservation lab, and
lower it into a tank of fresh water, chilled to inhibit the sub's
deterioration.
</P>
<P>
   The top portion of the sub was visible along its 13-mile trip,
viewed by thousands who, despite sweltering heat, packed city
piers, rooftops and the deck of the retired USS Yorktown.
</P>
<P>
   Two hatches protrude from the sub's top, as do two wings near
the forward hatch that allowed the Hunley to dive. The 40-foot-long
vessel is sealed by a cementlike formation that scientists believe
has protected the hull from corrosive salt water.
</P>
<P>
   Watching from aboard the Carolina Clipper, one of hundreds of
boats that ringed the recovery site, state Sen. Ernie Passailaigue
(D-Charleston) was struck by the Hunley's small size and how
cramped the sailors must have been.
</P>
<P>
   ``That goes beyond the scope of anything I'll describe as
bravery,'' said Passailaigue, 52, a member of the state-appointed
Hunley Commission.
</P>
<P>
   With Confederate troops desperate to get supplies through
Charleston's port, the Hunley set out in the darkness Feb. 17,
1864.
</P>
<P>
   Turning the propeller from inside with a hand crank, the crew
rammed the USS Housatonic with a long spar affixed with 90 pounds
of black powder. Five Union soldiers died in the Housatonic's
sinking, as did all of the Hunley's crew when their vessel sank 30
feet to the bottom as it backed away from its target.
</P>
<P>
   Now scientists are poised to delve into the Hunley, piecing
together the history and lore that families have passed down.
</P>
<P>
   The sub eventually will go on display in the Charleston Museum.
The Hunley's crew, if found inside, will be buried next year in the
city's Magnolia Cemetery, along with the remains of two previous
crews who died during test runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am pleased ... that we have this wonderful exhibit to come,
but (I'm) also very sad about the people who died,'' said Richard
Barker, 67, of Jacksonville, great-great-grandson of James Wicks, a
Hunley crewman who left a widow with four daughters. In recent
days, divers lowered a metal frame into the water. Its open bottom
rested over the Hunley. Divers then looped synthetic straps under
the hull, attaching each end to the cage to form a sling cradling
the sub. For greater stability, workers pumped quick-hardening foam
into bags that had been placed between the straps and the hull.
</P>
<P>
   With hundreds of cameras poised at the surface, a big red crane
began its gradual, silent lift of the frame. The Hunley emerged
from the greenish gray water in the same position it had been
laying, at a 45 degree angle on its right side.
</P>
<P>
   On its journey through Charleston Harbor, the Hunley passed Fort
Sumter, where, in 1861, occupying Union soldiers exchanged cannon
fire with Confederate troops to start the Civil War. On the Web : A
history of the Hunley: www.hunley.org
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
