u a BC-HORSESHOE-CRABS-NYT &LR;      08-08 0759
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HORSESHOE-CRABS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOVERNMENT MOVES TO PROTECT HORSESHOE CRABS IN VIRGINIA 
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: Del., Va.)  By FRANCIS X. CLINES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LEWES, Del. _ Federal authorities on Tuesday announced plans for
a 30-mile-wide sanctuary from Delaware Bay out into the Atlantic to
protect the rapidly dwindling stock of horseshoe crabs that are
vital to the pharmaceutical industry and to the annual migration of
a dozen species of shore birds.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Commerce Secretary Norman Mineta ordered
Virginia to join 14 other Atlantic states that have recognized an
emergency in the horseshoe crab population and to voluntarily
reduce its catch or else find the state's industry shut down by
October by federal order.
</P>
<P>
   ``Virginia has been strip mining horseshoe crabs,'' declared
Daniel P. Beard, vice president of the National Audubon Society, in
praising the federal action to protect a critical resource
scientists say has been decimated in the past decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``Virginia's actions amount in our view to piracy,'' Beard said,
noting that Virginia watermen and marketeers have been gradually
monopolizing horseshoe crabs as prized bait for the booming conch
and eel export industries, while other states have cut back in the
name of the environment.
</P>
<P>
   While their state is singled out as a renegade, officials in
Virginia insist they have gone it alone because the other Atlantic
states' voluntary quotas are too severe to be justified by current
scientific research.
</P>
<P>
   The sanctuary, in which no horseshoe crabs could be taken, would
cover a 30-by-60-mile swath of the Atlantic centering on the mouth
of Delaware Bay, the world's prime population region for the crabs.
Ten years ago, an estimated 1.24 million crabs spawned on the
beaches of Delaware Bay, laying trillions of eggs vital to the
spring hemispheric bird migration.
</P>
<P>
   But scientists who favor the sanctuary say that the horseshoe
crab population has fallen by as much as 90 percent in the last
decade because of over-fishing. The crabs' egg production has been
measured in some studies at about 10 percent of its level in 1990.
This raises concern for the crabs' preservation and, scientists
say, for the survival of the 1 million shore birds who rely on
excess crab eggs for food for the final leg of their migration from
South America to the Arctic circle. Last spring, scientists
reported birds leaving under-nourished with their long journey in
doubt.
</P>
<P>
   Birdwatchers account for more than $35 million in Atlantic coast
tourist spending for what they rate a spectacular birding event _
the spring stopover of starving shore birds gorging on the eggs.
The horseshoe crab, an ancient, pre-dinosaur survivor species more
closely related to spiders than crabs, underpins an even richer $50
million industry in drug and medical research.
</P>
<P>
   The crabs' blue, copper-based blood is widely used to test drugs
for bacteria and to inhibit certain kinds of cancer cells. The Food
and Drug Administration mandates use of the crab blood in testing
all new injectable medicines, crab specialists note, emphasizing
that in most cases the blood can be taken without destroying the
donors.
</P>
<P>
   Mineta said that he hoped to negotiate a settlement with
Virginia fishery officials, but that he would not hesitate to close
down the state's horseshoe crab industry, if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   The other members of the Atlantic States Marine Fisheries
Commission, from Maine to Florida, have each accepted a quota of at
least a 25 percent cut in harvests. But Virginia has resisted its
recommended quota of 152,495 crabs and has become the main marketer
in the region for the valuable bait source, surpassing 1 million
crabs sold in one recent year.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no actual scientific basis for the quota,'' John Paul
Woodley, Virginia's secretary of natural resources, insisted in an
interview. Last month, he added, state officials compromised by
halving the state's own quota to 355,000 crabs, which still is more
than double the quota federal officials are demanding. Woodley said
Virginia also is mandating mesh bait bags for conch fishing that,
he said, will allow using the crabs more than once.
</P>
<P>
   But environmentalists have accused state officials of caving in
to the state's conch industry and its growing need for bait.
</P>
<P>
   Mineta said the sanctuary, which covers federal waters beginning
three miles off shore, would guarantee that horseshoe crabs survive
``to carry on their special role in the environment, as they have
for some 350 million years.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
