<SLUG> BC-VERIZON-NORTHPOINT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOW INVESTORS WALK OUT ON VERIZON 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also VERIZON-STRIKE, NY-VERISON) 
 By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Shares of Verizon, the nation's No. 1 local phone
company, had been under pressure for weeks. They crumpled Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   That is what happens when a company says that it will not be
able to meet its financial targets, as Verizon did, even when some
investors already suspected that such an announcement was coming,
as some did.
</P>
<P>
   But the magnitude of the shortfall was a surprise to most on
Tuesday, because Verizon also said it had agreed to acquire control
of NorthPoint Communications Group, a high-speed Internet provider,
in a deal that would further dilute Verizon's earnings.
</P>
<P>
   So as 86,000 unionized employees entered the third day of their
strike against the company, investors also walked out on Verizon,
sending the company's shares down by almost 14 percent Tuesday,
their sharpest one-day drop since 1987.
</P>
<P>
   It did not help the labor negotiations that the NorthPoint deal
could be seen as a provocative affront to Verizon's unions, which
have been trying to organize the company's Internet operation. And
it did not help Verizon with investors that the company also
announced financial results for the second quarter that failed to
meet Wall Street's expectations.
</P>
<P>
   In fairness, Verizon's inability to meet its financial targets
is not the result of bad execution in running its business. This
contrasts, for example, with AT&AMP;T, which has seen its shares tumble
amid criticism that it has mismanaged its units that serve business
customers. The issues at Verizon, formed in June by Bell Atlantic's
acquisition of the GTE Corp., reflect less poorly on the company's
executives.
</P>
<P>
   Until Tuesday, financial analysts surveyed by First Call/Thomson
Financial, a financial research firm, had predicted that Verizon
would earn $3.15 a share this year and the company's own guidance
had been that it would show per-share earnings growth of 13 percent
to 15 percent in 2001. After all of the adjustments, the company
said Tuesday that it would instead earn $2.90 to $2.94 a share this
year, and that figure could be expected to increase by 5 percent to
6 percent in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Part of that change could have been anticipated by outsiders.
Part of it could not have.
</P>
<P>
   Delays and concessions involved in winning regulatory approval
for the merger caused part of the problem. Bell Atlantic and GTE
originally anticipated completing the deal at the beginning of this
year rather than in midsummer. The delay meant they could squeeze
out only about half of the savings they had anticipated for the
year. In addition, federal and state regulators extracted various
commitments from Verizon that could cost hundreds of millions of
dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts on Tuesday expressed dismay that much of the
combined company's projected growth had been expected to come from
a change in accounting for GTE's pension liabilities; Verizon said
Tuesday it would not include the effect of the pension accounting
in its future operational results.
</P>
<P>
   The slower growth anticipated for next year is also largely due
to the timing and impact of acquisitions and outside investments.
Because Bell Atlantic, as a former part of the Bell System
monopoly, is not allowed to sell long-distance communications
services in most of its traditional territory, the combined Verizon
was required by regulators to sell to the public more than 90
percent of GTE's long-distance Internet subsidiary, formerly BBN
and now known as Genuity.
</P>
<P>
   Verizon, however, was counting on Genuity's rapid expansion to
help the larger company make its growth target, and now it cannot.
In addition, delays in the completion of Verizon's wireless joint
venture with Vodafone AirTouch PLC have also hampered Verizon's
ability to meet its growth targets for 2001.
</P>
<P>
   But the biggest negative impact on Verizon's growth prospects
next year will be the NorthPoint deal and Verizon's agreement
announced Monday to acquire the OnePoint Communications Corp., a
small private company, for an undisclosed amount. Between them, the
NorthPoint and OnePoint deals will dilute Verizon's per-share
earnings growth by about 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   While OnePoint is private, NorthPoint is public, and the
peculiar structure of Tuesday's deal reflects the difficult time
NorthPoint and its brethren have had winning investors' confidence.
</P>
<P>
   NorthPoint, along with competitors including Covad
Communications and Rhythms NetConnections, is in the business of
building systems in telephone offices around the nation that can
deliver torrents of Internet data over standard telephone wires,
using a technology known as the digital subscriber line, or DSL.
Shares in all three companies are trading significantly below
levels at which they offered stock to the public last year, largely
because the DSL business has proved more complicated than the
companies expected.
</P>
<P>
   Verizon is also in the DSL business. In Tuesday's deal, Verizon
agreed to combine its DSL unit and $800 million in cash into
NorthPoint in exchange for 55 percent of the company. What is
unusual is that $350 million of that figure is to be distributed
directly to NorthPoint's existing shareholders, as a kind of
special dividend of about $2.50 a share.
</P>
<P>
   In a capital-intensive, high-growth (and nonunion) industry like
the Internet, that money would almost always be expected to be
plowed back into helping the business grow. The only obvious reason
to direct that much cash directly to the shareholders would be to
compensate them for the shares' lackluster performance. In a news
release Tuesday the companies said that shareholders owning about
48 percent of NorthPoint had agreed to the deal, so it might appear
that the payoff was necessary to win their approval in the first
place.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of NorthPoint fell 75 cents, to $14.25 on Tuesday in
Nasdaq trading.
</P>
<P>
   Discounting many special charges including a one-time
pension-related gain, Verizon reported earnings of $1.97 billion,
or 72 cents a share, up from $1.87 billion, or 67 cents a share, in
the quarter a year earlier. Including the pension gain, the company
earned 81 cents a share, 2 cents less than the consensus estimate
of analysts polled by First Call/Thomson Financial.
</P>
<P>
   Revenue rose 16 percent, to $16.79 billion for the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Verizon ended the day down $5.8125, or 13.8 percent,
at $42.0625.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-08-00 2044EDT &QL; 
