<SLUG> BC-BUSINESS-TRAVEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS TRAVEL: FLIGHT DELAYS, BY THE NUMBERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Duplication warning: also sent with `t' code) 
By JOE SHARKEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   All summer long, weary business travelers have been grimly
playing the numbers game. Here's a question from the most recent
round: How many flights did United Airlines abruptly cancel last
Saturday, Sunday and Monday? The answer: 814, mostly out of
Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   United's no-fly stats have become truly impressive, even in this
worst-ever summer for airline passengers. However, the airline
industry in general is not having such a bad summer. The money is
rolling in. Most carriers are flying record numbers of customers
this summer in planes taking off at record capacities of 80 percent
and more.
</P>
<P>
   Before the summer rush got under way, United _ which has about
5,000 departures a day _ had already lopped a total of 4,800
flights off its schedule through August, and the airline recently
said it was cutting almost 2,000 flights out of its September
schedule.
</P>
<P>
   United blames the extraordinary number of delays and
cancellations largely on a job action by unionized pilots who are
refusing to work some overtime shifts, mostly in the carrier's hub
at Chicago's O'Hare International Airport. The union representing
about 10,000 United pilots disputes that, however, saying that the
company itself has caused the problems by not taking action to
remedy what the union says is a shortage of pilots.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, business travelers face the next round in the numbers
game this week, when the Federal Aviation Administration says it
will release its statistics for the number of delays on all
domestic flights for July. The 50,000 delays in June, as you might
recall, smashed all previous records. And July is a busier travel
month than June.
</P>
<P>
   Will the July numbers set still another record? Place your bets,
ladies and gentlemen.
</P>
<P>
   An FAA spokesman, Bill Shuman, wasn't quoting any odds Tuesday.
``July through the middle was good, but then the last part of July
was bad, particularly in the Northeast,'' he said. ``July is going
to be up there. The weather has been bad. It really affected travel
between Chicago and other points in the Midwest and the whole
Northeast corridor, Boston to Washington.''
</P>
<P>
   And while we're playing the numbers, here are some long-range
ones to contemplate as air travel grows and we try to figure out
how to safely and efficiently thread an increasing number of planes
through a finite amount of air space, without the whole system
collapsing into gridlock.
</P>
<P>
   World air travel, measured by the total number of miles flown by
airline passengers, will grow by 4.8 percent a year for the next 20
years, according to the newly released 2000 Current Market Outlook,
an annual report on the commercial aviation business published by
Boeing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
