<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 20:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6160 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-SAFIR09-COX     08-08 1289
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFIR09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New York's top cop quits to be consultant
 &HT;    By Russell Grantham and Peralte C. Paul
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ An Alpharetta company that helps insurance companies
and law enforcement agencies ferret out information on clients and
criminals has hired New York's outgoing police commissioner as a
consultant.
</P>
<P>
   Howard Safir, New York's third top police official to turn in
his badge recently, said he is resigning Aug. 18.
</P>
<P>
   His four-year watch over the department has been praised for a
steep decline in New York crime but increasingly criticized by
Hispanic and black residents for his department's involvement in
some alleged police brutality incidents, including the death last
year of an African immigrant shot 41 times by four officers.
</P>
<P>
   ChoicePoint Inc. said the 58-year-old commissioner will be a
part-time ``special consultant'' to the company's senior executives
on the use of information technology in law enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe he can add a lot of value,'' said Kelly McLoughlin,
ChoicePoint's vice president of investor relations. ``One of his
hot buttons ... is using DNA'' evidence to help solve crimes, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   McLoughlin said Safir brings extensive contacts from his 31-year
career in law enforcement, including several years with the Federal
Bureau of Narcotics, U.S. Drug Enforcement Agency and U.S.
Marshal's Office.
</P>
<P>
   ``(But) mainly, we think he can help us come up with
innovations,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ChoicePoint, a 1997 spinoff from Atlanta credit information
company Equifax Inc., sells information to law enforcement agencies
and other government entities.
</P>
<P>
   The company assembles credit reports, court records, drivers
license data and other information, for instance, to zero in on
criminal suspects and their companies or property, missing
children, and parents who are delinquent on their child support
payments.
</P>
<P>
   ChoicePoint had 1999 revenue of $430 million, about half from
government clients and half from providing credit report and
driving record information to insurance companies.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Warmington, an equity analyst with Robinson-Humphrey, said
Safir should play a useful role in helping ChoicePoint develop
efficient information search tools for law enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is very knowledgeable in how law enforcement operates and
how they use `credentialing,''' or the use of court and licensing
records and other data to profile a person or business, Warmington
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I view it as a positive,'' he said. However, he added, ``I'm
not adjusting my financial model in light of this event.''
</P>
<P>
   From a marketing standpoint, ChoicePoint stands to gain a lot
from the association, local public relations executives said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, they're looking at him as a rainmaker,'' said Jane
Shivers, a partner and director with Ketchum in Atlanta. ``There
are a lot of doors open to him that wouldn't be open to just anyone
they could have hired.''
</P>
<P>
   But other marketing experts warned that the company will still
have to deliver to those open doors.
</P>
<P>
   And others said the company will have to take care not to become
overshadowed by Safir's public image or become associated with some
of the baggage that comes with him as a result of some high-profile
brutality allegations and convictions that occurred under his
watch.
</P>
<P>
   Those included the death last year of African immigrant Amadou
Diallo, shot 41 times by four New York police officers who mistook
his wallet for a gun, and the 1997 beating and sodomizing of
Haitian immigrant Abner Louima by a white officer at a police
station.
</P>
<P>
   Safir will continue to live in New York. He announced earlier
this year that he had prostate cancer, but according to published
reports, the commissioner said that had nothing to do with his
decision to leave.
</P>
<P>
   Safir replaced Police Commissioner William ChoicePoint Inc. said
the 58-year-old commissioner will be a part-time ``special
consultant'' to the company's senior executives on the use of
information technology in law enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe he can add a lot of value,'' said Kelly McLoughlin,
ChoicePoint's vice president of investor relations. ``One of his
hot buttons ... is using DNA'' evidence to help solve crimes, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   McLoughlin said Safir brings extensive contacts from his 31-year
career in law enforcement, including several years with the Federal
Bureau of Narcotics, U.S. Drug Enforcement Agency and U.S.
Marshal's Office.
</P>
<P>
   ``(But) mainly, we think he can help us come up with
innovations,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ChoicePoint, a 1997 spinoff from Atlanta credit information
company Equifax Inc., sells information to law enforcement agencies
and other government entities.
</P>
<P>
   The company assembles credit reports, court records, drivers
license data and other information, for instance, to zero in on
criminal suspects and their companies or property, missing
children, and parents who are delinquent on their child support
payments.
</P>
<P>
   ChoicePoint had 1999 revenue of $430 million, about half from
government clients and half from providing credit report and
driving record information to insurance companies.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Warmington, an equity analyst with Robinson-Humphrey, said
Safir should play a useful role in helping ChoicePoint develop
efficient information search tools for law enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is very knowledgeable in how law enforcement operates and
how they use `credentialing,''' or the use of court and licensing
records and other data to profile a person or business, Warmington
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I view it as a positive,'' he said. However, he added, ``I'm
not adjusting my financial model in light of this event.''
</P>
<P>
   From a marketing standpoint, ChoicePoint stands to gain a lot
from the association, local public relations executives said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, they're looking at him as a rainmaker,'' said Jane
Shivers, a partner and director with Ketchum in Atlanta. ``There
are a lot of doors open to him that wouldn't be open to just anyone
they could have hired.''
</P>
<P>
   But other marketing experts warned that the company will still
have to deliver to those open doors.
</P>
<P>
   And others said the company will have to take care not to become
overshadowed by Safir's public image or become associated with some
of the baggage that comes with him as a result of some high-profile
brutality allegations and convictions that occurred under his
watch.
</P>
<P>
   Those included the death last year of African immigrant Amadou
Diallo, shot 41 times by four New York police officers who mistook
his wallet for a gun, and the 1997 beating and sodomizing of
Haitian immigrant Abner Louima by a white officer at a police
station.
</P>
<P>
   Safir will continue to live in New York. He announced earlier
this year that he had prostate cancer, but according to published
reports, the commissioner said that had nothing to do with his
decision to leave.
</P>
<P>
   Safir replaced Police Commissioner William Bratton, taking over
the top spot in 1996. He was earning $141,100 a year, a New York
Police Department spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
   ChoicePoint declined to disclose Safir's compensation in the new
position.
</P>
<P>
   Bratton, a consultant, now heads New York-based First Security
Consulting.
</P>
<P>
   It's no longer unusual for police executives and former chiefs
to go into consulting work, said George Cooley, deputy police chief
at the Birmingham Police Department.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now it's a pretty good field,'' Cooley said, explaining
his department had hired Bratton's firm in 1997 to help advise the
department with an overhaul of some of its policies and procedures.
</P>
<P>
   Police executives bring a lot of knowledge and experience that
companies are looking for when recruiting, Cooley said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
</TEXT>
