<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GALLOWAY-COL-COWBOYS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OK, COWBOYS FANS, DON'T PANIC _ YET
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS, Texas _ When it's the Cowboys involved, it's
never too early for fan panic or media panic. And based on what new
defensive coordinator Mike Zimmer says he's been reading and
hearing, that time has arrived, even with the NFL regular-season
opener still a sweaty month away.
</P>
<P>
   ``Apparently, a lot of people think we're in bad shape on
defense,'' Zimmersaid yesterday as the Cowboys shook off Japan jet
lag and got down to what coach Dave Campo promised would be ``one
tough week of practice.''
</P>
<P>
   But as far as any defensive Armageddons, particularly involving
those under-the-microscope rookie cornerbacks, Zimmer smiled and
replied in typical candid fashion:
</P>
<P>
   ``My advice to everyone is don't panic until you see me panic,
and believe me, if that becomes necessary, I will be the first.''
</P>
<P>
   But after two weeks of practice-field work in Wichita Falls, one
wasted week in Japan and two exhibition games, both losses, the
general sampling of street-talk opinion seems to center on two
areas:
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys have great potential to once again become a mighty
offensive force.
</P>
<P>
   But with this defense, they'll have to score 40 points a game
and then hope to win it in overtime.
</P>
<P>
   What we are obviously dealing with here is an overreaction in
both areas, which is logical for the Cowboys, and also when
opinions are being formed in early August. The offense isn't
``back.'' Not yet. And the defense isn't in trouble. Not yet. But
for those on the outside looking in _ fans and media _ those rookie
cornerbacks make everybody nervous. Campo said yesterday he
certainly had ``concerns'' in that area. Zimmer agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``But overall, I sit here today, basically in a positive mood
about where we are and what we've done thus far,'' said Zimmer, the
secondary coach for five seasons at Valley Ranch until Campo
promoted him to take his place as defensive coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's obvious that the major emphasis for us is what's going on
at cornerback,'' Zimmer added. ``People keep saying the rookies are
doing poorly, that they are constantly getting beat, and all that.
I see the game, I see the films, I see that \RAtlanta\S had only
187 yards passing, and I don't see anybody getting killed back
there. Plays are being missed. Guys will get beat, yes. But they
are rookies. Give these people some time.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite those burn marks on Mario Edwards, the sixth-round pick
out of Florida State, Zimmer still rates him as a player-to-be in
the NFL. ``Mario's got spunk and he's got fight,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It is definite one of the three rookie corners will have to make
a major contribution this season, and maybe start. Right now,
that's Kareem Larrimore, the fourth-rounder out of West Texas A&AMP;M.
``But a week ago, I'd have told you it was Edwards,'' Zimmer said.
</P>
<P>
   Second-rounder Dwayne Goodrich, however, seems to have lost
contact with the pack. To some, the Tennessee product is mentally
sagging at the moment, while also suffering a minor injury in Japan
that may keep him off the practice field this week. ``Of the three
rookies, \RGoodrich\S is the one who reacts the most like a
rookie,'' Zimmer said. No one, of course, is admitting Goodrich is
a mistake. Again, it's way too early for that. ``There have been a
couple of situations,'' Campo said, ``where he could have shown
improvement and didn't. That's a disappointment.''
</P>
<P>
   That's also the head coach being diplomatic, but, hey, it is
early August.
</P>
<P>
   Zimmer, for his part, spends a lot of time these days answering
questions about his rookie corners. But once the conversation moves
elsewhere on defense, he's got more news of a positive nature to
report.
</P>
<P>
   ``At linebacker, I feel better about things than I thought I
would at this point,'' he said. ``For one, Dat Nguyen is a player
in the middle. He has already gone beyond what we had anticipated.
We were hoping to see this or that, but, man, Dat looks good in all
areas.''
</P>
<P>
   That, of course, sounds like an old R.C. Slocum echo, who always
said of Nguyen, ``You don't realize how good he is until the ball
is snapped.''
</P>
<P>
   There has also been another training-camp surprise for Zimmer.
Taking a chance with a once-troubled Dimitrius Underwood is paying
off. At first, it was a question of his even making the team. But
at the moment, Underwood is a part of the four-man rotation at
defensive end with Ebenezer Ekuban, Peppi Zellner and a rapidly
healing Greg Ellis, who despite the wicked broken leg last season
appears ready to open the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dimitrius has been a bonus for us _ a big bonus,'' Zimmer
said.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing, of course, would help the cornerback situation,
particularly the rookies, more than the young foursome at end
becoming a pass-rushing force.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would make us all feel better, particularly me'' Zimmer
said, laughing.
</P>
<P>
   Panic? What panic? Not yet, anyway.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
