<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-LIEBERMAN-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE AND LIEBERMAN MAKE TOLERANCE CENTERPIECE OF FORMAL
ANNOUNCEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: 2nd Take is scheduled to move by 9:30 ET) 
(ART ADV: Photos _ NYT11,12,13,14 _ are being sent to NYT photo
clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling
888-603-1036 or 888- 346-9867.) 
 By KEVIN SACK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE, Tenn. _ Determined to transform a potential liability
into a defining asset, Vice President Al Gore on Tuesday formally
introduced Sen. Joseph Lieberman of Connecticut as his Democratic
running mate. He portrayed his selection of Lieberman, an Orthodox
Jew, as a measure of his devotion to tolerance and his willingness
to break barriers.
</P>
<P>
   In his remarks to thousands of supporters at Nashville's War
Memorial plaza, Gore compared his groundbreaking selection to his
party's choice of John F. Kennedy as the first Catholic
presidential nominee 40 years ago. ``When we nominate Joe Lieberman
for vice president we will make history again,'' Gore said. ``We
will tear down an old wall of division once again.''
</P>
<P>
   After word of Lieberman's selection leaked out on Monday, Gore
aides and Democratic leaders made it clear that Gore had selected
him despite his religion and any possible anti-Semitic backlash.
But Tuesday's event was remarkable for the forthrightness with
which Gore, Lieberman and their wives addressed Lieberman's
Jewishness as a topic not to avoid, but to celebrate.
</P>
<P>
   From Lieberman's opening with a prayer from Chronicles to his
wife's homage to her Holocaust-surviving parents to the senator's
labored use of the word ``chutzpah,'' the Liebermans' faith
provided the strategic and oratorical underpinnings of the entire
day. Campaign aides even volunteered that the Gores and Liebermans
shared a meal on Monday night that was prepared by a kosher
caterer.
</P>
<P>
   The intended message was that Gore, who has been characterized
throughout his career as an exceedingly tentative politician, had
acted boldly in making the most important decision of his
candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's be very clear about this,'' Lieberman said. ``It isn't
me, Joe Lieberman, who deserves credit and the congratulations for
taking a bold step. It is Al Gore who broke this barrier in
American history. And you know what it shows? It shows Al's faith
in the tolerance of this diverse nation in the basic fairness of
the American people.''
</P>
<P>
   The talk of tolerance was directed partly at the suburban voters
who were the primary targets of the spotlighting of minorities at
last week's Republican convention in Philadelphia. But it also was
clearly aimed at comforting the Democratic base about the selection
of Lieberman, who is conservative by party standards.
</P>
<P>
   To that end, Lieberman told of a conversation that he had on
Monday with the Rev. Jesse Jackson. ``He said something to me that
went to my heart and I hope it will to yours as well,'' Lieberman
said. ``He said to me, `You know, Joe, each time a barrier falls
for one person the doors of opportunity open wider for every other
American.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
