</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HYUNDAI-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RECORD AUTO PROFITS BOLSTER HYUNDAI, AND EMBOLDEN CREDITORS 
</HEADLINE>
  By SAMUEL LEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEOUL, South Korea _ The Hyundai Group, South Korea's largest
conglomerate, reported record profits in its automotive business on
Tuesday, an unexpected piece of good news from a company known
lately for its heavy debts, its drag on the national economy and
its defiance of pressure to change.
</P>
<P>
   The results at Hyundai's automaking subsidiaries, Hyundai Motor
Co. and Kia Motors Corp., reflected a rebound in demand for new
cars in South Korea and a record surge in exports, especially to
North America. But Hyundai creditors immediately seized on the news
to demand that the parent company hasten its promised restructuring
and separate the auto business from Hyundai's unhealthy
subsidiaries.
</P>
<P>
   Earnings at Hyundai Motor for the first six months of this year
surged to 310.4 billion won, or $278 million, from 110.2 billion
won a year earlier. Kia, which verged on collapse during South
Korea's economic crisis a few years ago, earned 82.6 billion won,
or $74 million, in the first half of this year, in contrast to a
loss of 33.8 billion won a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Hyundai Motor said sales rose 40 percent, to 8.47 trillion won,
or $7.5 billion. Sales at Kia rose 69 percent, to 4.8 trillion won,
or about $4.3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   For Hyundai, it was clearly the best news since June, when
DaimlerChrysler AG agreed to buy a 10 percent stake in Hyundai
Motor with an option to buy 5 percent more over the next three
years. That relationship is expected to make Hyundai a top global
car brand.
</P>
<P>
   Since the DaimlerChrysler alliance, however, Hyundai Motor's
parent company has been hurt by growing concern over a severe cash
shortage at another important subsidiary, Hyundai Engineering and
Construction. This has increased pressure from creditors who are
demanding the separation of healthy affiliates from the Hyundai
Group. The creditors are also seeking a far lower profile in the
group's management affairs by Hyundai's founder, Chung Ju-yung, 85,
and his sons Chung Mong-jun and Chung Mong-koo.
</P>
<P>
   The Hyundai Group's main creditor, Korea Exchange Bank, sent a
letter to the conglomerate on Tuesday demanding an acceptable
restructuring plan by next Saturday. The conglomerate had proposed
a restructuring plan over the weekend, but the creditor bank
rejected it, saying the plan failed to satisfy concerns about the
family's management roles.
</P>
<P>
   Although Hyundai Motor's strong results helped it to reduce some
debts, total debts at the construction unit and the group as a
whole are still high. Total debts at Hyundai Engineering and
Construction stood at 5.1 trillion won, or nearly $4.6 billion, at
the end of 1999, of which nearly half is due by the end of the
year. Total debt at the conglomerate stood at 52.6 trillion won, or
more than $47 billion, at the end of last year.
</P>
<P>
   Concern about Hyundai's debts has weighed on South Korea's stock
market and has made investors wary about the true extent of the
country's recovery from its 1997-98 economic crisis. Hyundai's
problems were an important reason that President Kim Dae-jung shook
up his cabinet on Monday, replacing the finance minister and other
important economic officials.
</P>
<P>
   Creditors of Hyundai regard the founding family as a major
impediment because family members have resisted efforts to make the
company's finances more understandable.
</P>
<P>
   In an apparent contradiction of vows made to shareholders two
months ago, when he announced he would relinquish his management
control of the Hyundai Group, the conglomerate's founder recently
raised his stake in Hyundai Motor.
</P>
<P>
   Chung Mong-koo, a son of the founder, still leads the carmaker.
Although analysts say that Chung Mong-koo is one of the few people
who know the full workings of the company and that he has a solid
grasp of the terrain of the domestic auto industry, critics say he
is intertwined in the group's complicated web of cross-debt
guarantees.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
