<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-TOURISM09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Florida gets its own label
 &HT;    By Stephanie Smith
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ David Gardener keeps a secret list of all the products
he'd like to bear the multicolored FLA USA logo.
</P>
<P>
   Gardener, brand development director for Visit Florida, the
state's tourism agency, has so far been able to cross phone cards,
disposable cameras, saltwater taffy and now, bottled water, off
that list.
</P>
<P>
   Iced tubs laden with FLA USA-labeled Aqua Clara water sat in
exhibit halls, meeting rooms and hallways at the 33rd Governor's
Conference on Tourism at Doral Golf Resort and Spa, which ended
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The 900 people who attended the three-day conference knocked
back nearly 5,400 of the 20-ounce bottles of oxygen-enriched,
purified tap water from Clearwater (''Aqua Clara'' means Clear
Water).
</P>
<P>
   This summer, bottles of Aqua Clara _ billed as containing 800
percent of the oxygen found in regular water _ hit 900 General
Nutrition Center stores in the Southeast and Puerto Rico, said E.
Douglas Cifers, who is chairman of Aqua Clara Bottling &AMP;
Distribution (OTC-BB: AQCB, 13 cents).
</P>
<P>
   Cifers, who also publishes magazines such as ``Florida Living''
and ``Florida Fishing &AMP; Boating,'' declined to disclose the royalty
arrangement with Visit Florida, but said he expects the agency will
see commissions in the low six figures this year.
</P>
<P>
   Gardener said any money the agency receives from its licensing
deals is a side benefit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's promotion of the brand,'' Gardener said. ``My job it to
get the brand out.'' So far, he said, 34 different products feature
the FLA USA logo.
</P>
<P>
   Slapping the FLA USA logo on taffy and bottled water isn't meant
to supplant the $9.5 million Visit Florida spends on TV and print
advertising or the $1 million it shells out for Internet
promotions. But tourism officials hope the colorful logo _ unveiled
in 1997 after $237,000 spent in development _ conjures up thoughts
of Florida vacations, just as the ``swoosh'' symbol is associated
with Nike's athletic products.
</P>
<P>
   Florida apparently leads the nation in aggressively licensing
its tourism logo, Gardener said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're the first, or we're at least one of the first,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   In California, for example, the state's tourism motto is also an
admonition _ ``Go California'' _ but state outlets such as the gift
shop at the Capitol building in Sacramento don't have trinkets
featuring the motto.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't really find things like bottled water with our
slogans on it,'' said gift shop clerk Monica Bratcher.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
