<HEADER>
A6174 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-WEST-FIRES-ART-1100(T     08-08 1140
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEST-FIRES-ART-1100(TRIM)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIREFIGHTERS STRETCHED TO LIMIT AS MASSIVE FIRES ENGULF THE WEST 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also WEST-FIRES-CLINTON) 
(ART ADV: a map is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ROSS E. MILLOY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DARBY, Mont. _ Surrounded by swirling woodsmoke, and with forest
fires crackling on a hillside just over the horizon, Craig Bobzien
waved an arm over acres of equipment and exhausted firefighters in
the Bitterroot Valley fire camp near here.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not enough. It's just not nearly enough,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   With fires raging out of control in a dozen Western states,
Forest Service officials like Bobzien are scrambling to find the
manpower and resources needed to combat the worst fire season in
more than 50 years.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Bobzien tramped through the muddy fire camp at the
Western edge of the state, row after row of military-style tents
stretched over several acres: a hospital tent, operations tent,
mess tent, even a finance tent to keep track of all the money being
spent to fight the fires.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got more than 60 fires going just in the district that I
manage, which is around a half-million acres. At least 130,000
acres of that area is on fire right now,'' said Bobzien, a Forest
Service ranger for the Sula and Darby districts. ``Until we get
rain or snow, it will only get worse.''
</P>
<P>
   Jack Sept, chief of external affairs at the National Interagency
Fire Center in Boise, Idaho, said: ``We've got something going here
that we've never seen before. We have most of the West burning all
at once, and it's really straining our resources to keep up.''
</P>
<P>
   The center, which coordinates the federal response to major fire
scenes, reported that eight people _ ``two civilians and six in the
line of duty'' _ had already been killed, though officials
cautioned that they were still gathering data.
</P>
<P>
   While there is no one explanation of why the fires are so
pervasive this year, Bobzien speculated that they were at least in
part a result of previous fire-fighting successes. That is, the
Forest Service can generally suppress most natural fires very
quickly, but as a consequence a buildup of combustible fuel occurs
over decades _ a tinderbox awaiting a season of hot, dry weather as
this summer.
</P>
<P>
   In Montana, officials said that more than 4,000 people were
fighting fires across the state.
</P>
<P>
   With hot, dry weather blanketing most of the country from the
Pacific Ocean to the Rocky Mountains _ and no rain in the forecast
_ firefighters are battling blazes in Alaska, Arizona, California,
Colorado, Idaho, Montana, Nevada, New Mexico, Oregon, Utah,
Washington and Wyoming.
</P>
<P>
   In California alone, officials are combating 12 separate forest
fires, including a 72,000-acre blaze in the Sequoia National
Forest.
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide, fire officials said that more than 4 million acres
have burned this year, despite government expenditures of $500
million to fight the fires.
</P>
<P>
   Bobzien said that the heavily forested mountains around this
river valley were the Forest Service's No.1 priority for the
moment. ``We've got several thousand people living in a long,
narrow valley with really only one highway in or out,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That highway, U.S. 93, was closed on Tuesday morning south of
Darby, and the route north was jammed with evacuees and flatbed
trailers hauling in earthmoving equipment to fight the fires.
</P>
<P>
   Thick smoke cut visibility to less than 100 yards at the Forest
Service's forward fire camp, and buses shuttled exhausted
firefighters back and forth between the blazing hills and their
tents.
</P>
<P>
   The Interagency Fire Center said that firefighters had come from
as far away as Australia, New Zealand and Hawaii. At least 1,200
military personnel are also fighting the fires, and President
Clinton met with some of them in Boise on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Rex B. Mann, an area commander for the Forest Service brought in
from Kentucky to help fight the Montana fires, said that skilled
firefighters were in short supply.
</P>
<P>
   Mann said that staff reductions at the federal level had
undercut the Forest Service's ability to deal with the multiple
fires in multiple locations the nation is experiencing this summer.
And, he said, the worst is yet to come.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our fire season usually doesn't start until about now or
slightly later,'' Mann, a 33-year veteran with the Forest Service,
said. ``We're going to have to take a whole new strategy in the
next 10 days if we're going to beat this thing.''
</P>
<P>
   That new strategy might include concentrating personnel and
equipment on certain areas. ``We'll have to make some tough
decisions about what fires we have a chance of stopping and which
ones we've got to let burn out,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Nearly 500 families were evacuated on Tuesday from communities
around Hamilton, 10 miles north of here, local officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We call it mandatory evacuation, but we're not forcing anyone
to leave,'' said Bobby Kitchens, an information officer for the
Forest Service. ``If they won't go, the deputies get their Social
Security number and contact information for their next of kin.''
</P>
<P>
   Charlie Baughman was visiting his daughter on Laird Creek Sunday
when, he said, fire officials told them ``If you don't leave now,
you won't get out.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a huge firestorm coming over the mountain on both sides
of the road as we got out. It sounded like the roar of a jet plane,
with flames 60 or 70 feet high, and the wind was howling like a
hurricane, but hot,'' he said. ``The whole mountain was on fire in
a matter of minutes.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   More than 50 homes near Darby have been destroyed in the last
two days, and officials have evacuated the communities of Springer
and Laird Creek.
</P>
<P>
   Betty and Charles Theis had just moved to Springer in June, but
on Tuesday they are living at an evacuation center in Hamilton,
wondering if they still have a home.
</P>
<P>
   They were part of a caravan of 60 cars, led by a truck with a
snowplow, that fought their way out of Springer Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd had fires all around us for a week, then suddenly we were
told to get out,'' Mrs. Theis recalled. ``As we left, there were
flames on all sides of us, roaring up the mountain, and the road
was covered with rocks and fallen trees. At one point, a flaming
log came rolling down the hill and slammed into one of the cars
ahead of us.''
</P>
<P>
   The wildlife, too, was trying to escape, she said. ``We saw four
bears, and tons of deer running in all directions. And, when we got
to the mouth of the valley, all the wild sheep had come down from
the hills and they were just huddled there together by the road,
shuddering.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
