<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 21:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6178 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-FOREIGN-FILMS-$ADV13-     08-08 1731
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-FILMS-$ADV13-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN   FOREIGN   MOVIES   MATTERED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, August 13)  
 By PHILIP LOPATE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For five weeks, through Sept. 14, Film Forum is
showing some wonderful foreign classics made in the years 1945-65,
everything from ``Children of Paradise'' and ``Open City'' to ``The
Seventh Seal'' and ``Breathless.'' The series is titled ``The
Golden Age of the Foreign Film,'' a challenging claim; it sounds
almost too good to be true.
</P>
<P>
   The notion of a golden age in any field must be viewed with
suspicion, in part because it is so often used as an unfair
reproach to the present. I can understand the impatience of younger
film lovers as they roll their eyes at yet another paean to the
good old days of the French New Wave, or one more elegy about the
death of cinema and the irrelevance of contemporary film criticism.
</P>
<P>
   My own sense is that brilliant, powerful, formally innovative
movies _ our future classics _ continue to be made at this moment,
all over the planet. Cinema is not at all dead. What is dead, or at
least diminished, is film culture, the whole support system of art
houses, influential movie magazines, Olympian film critics,
16-millimeter series operating in church basements like
revolutionary cells, all embracing the latest cinema while filling
in the historical gaps.
</P>
<P>
   What is gone is the excitement of an international movement, and
with it, the buildup, the anticipation of new sensations from
abroad. So I think it's valid to say that 1945-65 was a golden age
for foreign films. It was a remarkable, probably unrepeatable
moment, when masters from the silent era (like Luis Bunuel, Jean
Renoir, Yasujiro Ozu, Kenji Mizoguchi, Marcel Carne) were still
producing some of their greatest work, veterans entering middle age
(Federico Fellini, Akira Kurosawa, Roberto Rossellini, Luchino
Visconti, Ingmar Bergman, Vittorio De Sica, Michelangelo Antonioni)
were reaching their peak and newcomers (Jean-Luc Godard, Francois
Truffaut, Satyajit Ray, Andrzej Wajda, Jacques Demy) were stunning
the world with their audacity and reinvention of film form.
</P>
<P>
   Why were these two postwar decades, specifically, such a good
time for foreign film in America?
</P>
<P>
   One answer is the high quality of the films; another is the
receptivity of American audiences.
</P>
<P>
   The immediate postwar period was one of worldwide unease: the
fresh memories of unspeakable carnage; the returning soldiers'
difficulties adjusting to civilian life; the bitterness toward
those who had prospered; the situation of women who had acquired
some independence in the wartime workforce and now were being
coerced back into domestic roles; the refugees and ``stateless''
citizens waiting in displaced persons camps; the need to rebuild
cities reduced to rubble.
</P>
<P>
   Italy and Japan led the way in making movies with a tragic sense
of life. American audiences, for the moment non-complacent, were
dazzled by the stark production values of Italian neo-realism, with
its location shooting and (sometimes) non-professional actors, and
began acquiring a taste for humanistic realism, poverty,
black-and-white photography and unhappy endings. At home, American
studios took note of the newly pessimistic mood by producing film
noir _ largely a postwar genre made by European emigre directors.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, sex was also a major attraction of foreign films. Not
only could foreign directors get away with more, not having to
answer to the Hollywood production code; they also took for granted
such facts of life as extramarital affairs, homosexuality,
prostitution and so on. This gritty realism was all very
titillating: adult movie houses marketed art films like Bergman's
``Monika'' as if they were soft-core pornography. In those years,
America still looked to Europe for its sophistication, aesthetic
and sexual.
</P>
<P>
   How to explain the sea change that has occurred since? With the
triumph of popular culture over high culture, Americans, global
exporters of the winner, pop culture, no longer feel the same
longing for what the Old World knows.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, our movies have caught up sexually with the
rest of the world, for better or worse.
</P>
<P>
   Another changing factor has been the role of film festivals.
There were fewer in the postwar era, and the results counted more.
A victory at Cannes or Venice created almost unbearable suspense
about the winner's American release date.
</P>
<P>
   Compare with the present: if ``Rosetta'' or L'Humanite'' or
``Beau Travail,'' all recent festival award-winners from directors
with promising track records, had been released around 1962, I am
sure these stunning films would have been more talked about and
successful at the box office. As it is, each came and went rather
quietly.
</P>
<P>
   Let's face it: American audiences have become more resistant to
reading subtitles, while American independents have learned from
foreign film classics to make homegrown art movies. Hollywood has
done a good job of capturing an increasing market share worldwide,
stifling the local product and discouraging the distribution of
foreign films stateside.
</P>
<P>
   It must also be admitted that European cinema has sharply
declined since its postwar heyday _ maybe not as much in France,
but certainly in Italy, Germany, Scandinavia, Eastern Europe. The
fact that Americans seem to identify more with European than Asian
or African cinema may explain why the largely Third World cinematic
titans of our own era, like Abbas Kiarostami, Hou Hsiao-hsien, Wong
Kar-wai and Ousmane Sembene, have failed to become household names
on the order of Fellini, Truffaut or Fassbinder. Or maybe it's that
the whole machinery of promoting film directors as auteurs, demigod
celebrities, seems to have slipped into lower gear: even a hot
European filmmaker like Lars von Trier can no longer command the
name recognition of Ingmar Bergman. (Leaving aside the fact that
he's not as good as Bergman.)
</P>
<P>
   The golden age of foreign film coincided, not surprisingly, with
the zenith of the art house. Hollywood studios' stranglehold on big
theater bookings had prompted small, independent theater owners to
switch to a foreign product. Art houses grew nationally from 12 in
1945 to more than 550 in 1960.
</P>
<P>
   Every medium-sized city had one. New York boasted over a dozen
first-run, single-film art houses, most memorably the Little
Carnegie, the Fifth Avenue Cinema, the 68th Street Playhouse, the
Plaza, the Fine Arts. As art movies became hip, so did their
venues: with espresso machines and stools in the lobbies, they were
the forerunners of coffee bars, great places to pick up (or imagine
picking up) someone attractive. In retrospect, these art houses may
have been as important for their urbane architecture and interior
design as their promotion of cinema.
</P>
<P>
   Alongside these first-run theaters, somewhat rattier in
appearance but equally important, were the repertory houses _ the
Thalia, the New Yorker and the Bleecker Street Cinema in New York,
the Brattle in Cambridge, the Telegraph in Berkeley. These were our
film schools. You could catch up with double-bills of classics all
summer long at the Thalia, or cut classes and watch two ``forgotten
films'' at the New Yorker, shuttling the Upper West Side corridor
between 89th and 95th Streets.
</P>
<P>
   When I was a teen-ager I was attracted to film (and jazz, for
that matter) in part because there was only about 50 years of
history to keep in one's head. I could sit through some of the
duller silent classics mentioned in Arthur Knight's paperback
history of movies, ``The Liveliest Art,'' knowing that such dues
were finite. But cinema has now celebrated its 100th anniversary,
and at 100 years the narrative of the canon begins to fragment. No
longer do Pabst and Murnau seem to glide so effortlessly into
Welles and Wyler.
</P>
<P>
   Or there are newer, more truncated canons: the young men in a
college film course I teach are keenly aware of sci-fi pedigrees,
from ``2001'' through ``Blade Runner'' to ``The Matrix,'' or of
Quentin Tarantino's debt to John Woo and David Lynch, but they've
never seen a Godard, much less heard about ``Wild Strawberries'' or
``Diary of a Country Priest.''
</P>
<P>
   Video rentals spelled the demise of the repertory houses. With
everything on tape (or, it was assumed, soon to be), audiences no
longer felt the urgency to catch something old because it might not
show again. ``The Bicycle Thief'' and ``Ugetsu'' began to seem like
passe monuments, Old Master paintings in museums one might revisit
any time. A curious thing happened: the drive for novelty brought
the peripheral genres, the larky impulse rentals, to the center,
while marginalizing the classics. Visit a hip video store today and
you will find film noir, Hong Kong action pictures and ``outlaw''
directors (like Samuel Fuller, Sam Peckinpah and Ed Wood) featured
prominently, while the more unambiguously towering cinematic
masterworks are either unavailable or shunted to a back-room side
shelf.
</P>
<P>
   Film Forum's redoubtable programmer, Bruce Goldstein, who
curated the current series with Michael Sayers, is on a mission to
change all that. Interestingly, Goldstein himself did his part to
nurture film noir, pre-code, sci-fi, and campy ``worst'' movies
into commercially viable genres.
</P>
<P>
   It was partly, he explains, that one had to package something
unusual to attract the press, which meant abandoning the
tried-and-true repertory. ``But because we did all these weird
series,'' he adds, ``we'd lost sight of the classics. It's time to
get back to basics.''
</P>
<P>
   You can't get any more basic than ``The Golden Age of the
Foreign Film'': besides the aforementioned titles, its lineup
includes such unassailable classics as ``Rashomon,'' ``Seven
Samurai,'' ``L'Avventura,'' ``Contempt,'' ``La Dolce Vita,''
``Tokyo Story,'' ``Rocco and his Brothers,'' ``Beauty and the
Beast,'' ``Ashes and Diamonds,'' ``The 400 Blows,'' ``Los
Olvidados,' ``The Golden Coach'' and the Apu trilogy.
</P>
<P>
   One might quibble with the omission of Rohmer, Becker, Rivette,
Resnais, the Russians and the British, but of course such a series
has to be highly selective. The list does include a number of
crossover hits of debatable quality: the over-ripe ``Black
Orpheus,'' the likable but cheesy ``Never on Sunday,'' the
over-calculating ``Wages of Fear.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Other art house favorites included in the list, like ``Woman in
the Dunes'' or ``Repulsion,'' seem now more like clever tours de
force rather than full-blown masterworks.
</P>
<P>
   There is no attempt to lure the jaded cineaste with obscure
films like those that might turn up at the Museum of Modern Art.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, museums, which have been heroically
shouldering the bulk of the movie classics repertory, can perhaps
adopt a more scholarly stance. Film Forum (though technically also
``nonprofit'') is a self-sustaining movie theater and has to be
cannier about pulling in an audience.
</P>
<P>
   Precisely the charm of this current series, then, is that it is
so definitely meat and potatoes, with no surprises, no revisionist
intents. Its very emphasis on foreign film's greatest hits helps to
recapture more sharply the cultural moment. Some of the pairings
are particularly deft: Truffaut's underrated ``Soft Skin'' with
Claude Chabrol's nifty ``Bonnes Femmes.'' Goldstein, ever
respectful of history, says, ``I see it almost as an homage to the
Thalia and the New Yorker, and the kind of double bills they did.''
</P>
<P>
   One thing has gotten better from the golden age of repertory:
print quality. In the 1945-65 era, film buffs took what they could
get, often scratched or washed-out dupes of pirated prints in 16
millimeter. Today's audiences are more exacting on that score, in
addition to which the copyright laws have changed, making
respectable pirating more difficult. Meanwhile, a handful of
influential programmers (most notably Goldstein) have been able to
persuade studios to strike new 35-millimeter prints. Distributors
like Kino International, Milestone Film and Video, Interama, Strand
and Rialto Pictures have done their part by rereleasing
theatrically a stream of classics, many of which are included in
this series.
</P>
<P>
   A whole new generation raised on video will thus be able to see
these magnificent films as they were intended, projected on a big,
enveloping screen in crisp visual detail. Older viewers like myself
can revisit their favorites, savoring the satisfaction of taste
confirmed or the piquancy of disappointment. Either way, we may
someday look back with gratitude at Film Forum's repertory
operation as a golden age unto itself.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-08-00 2119EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
