<HEADER>
A6180 &Cx1f; tta-z
u s BC-OLY-SWIMSUITS-2TAKES(     08-08 1020
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SWIMSUITS-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. SWIMMERS TO DON HIGH-TECH BODY SUITS AT OLYMPIC TRIALS 
</HEADLINE>
   By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ When the Olympic trials begin here on Wednesday,
American swimmers will make as much news for what they are wearing
as for what records they may set in preparation for the 2000 Summer
Games next month in Sydney, Australia.
</P>
<P>
   A bodysuit, including a long-sleeved design that fits athletes
from neck to toe, has revolutionized the sport by reducing drag as
swimmers slice through the water. A flurry of records set by Inge
de Bruijn of the Netherlands and Ian Thorpe of Australia have put
others on notice that the suits give an edge to elite swimmers. At
least 11 world records have been set internationally since the new
suits were approved this year for international competition.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the 1,306 competitors at Indianapolis are expected to
wear some version of the suits at the Olympic trials, as are a
great majority of the medal hopefuls in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   The new suits are said to increase speed by up to 3 percent,
which can make the difference between a gold medal and fourth place
in a sport in which races are decided by hundredths of a second.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the top American swimmers have welcomed the suit as an
inevitable advance in technology that has brought the hinged-blade
to speed-skating, aerodynamic bikes to cycling, the flexibility of
fiber glass to the pole vault and graphite rackets to tennis.
</P>
<P>
   In her attempt to win five gold medals at the Summer Games, the
sprinter Marion Jones has been experimenting with a hooded,
full-length bodysuit to counter the effects of the wind and cool
temperatures expected in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   The most widely used model of the suit here is made by Speedo,
the official supplier of the U.S. national swim team. It is called
the Fastskin suit, which mimics shark skin in that it contains
tiny, v-shaped ridges that allow water to pass over the swimmer
more efficiently. The super-stretch fabric also compresses a
swimmer's muscles, reducing vibration in the tissue and therefore
reducing the buildup of lactic acid that causes fatigue.
</P>
<P>
   Swimmers also say the suit lifts them higher in the water and
helps them retain speed and form when they begin to tire. There are
five versions of the body suit available. Some swimmers prefer
suits that only cover their torsos, some men prefer only trunks
that extend to their thighs or toes, and some male and female
swimmers are wearing the neck-to-toe version without sleeves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like it's a power suit when I put it on; I feel like a
superhero a little,'' said Tom Malchow, who set a world record in
the 200-meter butterfly in June in a body suit. ``I was hoping they
would put a Superman or Batman logo on the front.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone approves of the suit. Alexander Popov of Russia is
one of only a handful of top swimmers who do not wear a bodysuit,
yet he shattered the world record in the 50-meter freestyle in June
and said he would continue to wear the same briefs that brought him
two gold medals in the sprints at the 1996 Atlanta Olympics. Gary
Hall Jr., who finished second twice to Popov in Atlanta, agreed
with his rival.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a gimmick,'' Hall said. ``It's an attempt by the swimsuit
manufacturers to make everyone believe that the suit makes the
swimmer, not that the swimmer makes the suit.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Opposition to the suits comes on several fronts. First,
swimming's world governing body, known by its initials as FINA, has
approved use of the suit even though its bylaws prohibit any device
that enhances an athlete's ``speed, buoyancy or endurance'' in
competition. John Coates, president of the Australian Olympic
Committee, has accused FINA of misinterpreting its own rules in
allowing the body suits, which clearly aid in speed and lift in the
water.
</P>
<P>
   Also, not every athlete has had equal access to the suits, or
has been able to have one custom-fitted. The U.S. swimming
federation initially banned the suits from the trials, saying they
would be unfair because not every athlete could get them. The
federation quickly backed down last month when a swimsuit
manufacturer filed a grievance with the U.S. Olympic Committee.
Every swimmer at the trials who wants a body suit is supposed to
have one provided free of charge (for consumers, Speedo expects the
full-length, long-sleeve suit to retail for $250 this fall). It was
clear Tuesday, however, that some swimmers were experimenting with
the suits for the first time with the trials only a day away.
</P>
<P>
   ``If people haven't worn them before coming here, it could be
dizzying trying to figure out which style to wear,'' said John
Collins, who coaches the renowned Badger Swim Club in Larchmont,
N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Some observers also believe that the suits will only increase
the anonymity of the swimmers, who are already hidden in the water
when they compete, their heads covered in swim caps.
</P>
<P>
   But the cat is out of the technological bag, so to speak, and
any swimmer who does not wear one in Sydney risks being left behind
in the chase for medals.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The new suits are hardly the first innovation in swimwear.
Bodyhugging Lycra suits appeared in the mid-1970s, and more than 75
percent of the medalists at the 1996 Atlanta Games were a version
of the Speedo ``Aquablade'' model, sleeveless suits that covered
women from neck to knee and men from waist to knee.
</P>
<P>
   Of the approximately 100 suits that another sportswear company,
Nike, has given away here at the trials, 95 have been a version of
the bodysuit, said Carrie Bates, a sports marketing manager for the
company and an Olympic champion swimmer in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll never stop the evolution of technology,'' said Bates,
who won three gold medals at the 1984 Los Angeles Games. She
disagreed with Hall's assessment that the suits were a gimmick.
``This is about helping the swimmers find what they are most
comfortable and confident with,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   A number of swimmers have complained that the swimming
federation's vacillation has caused confusion and interrupted
training with the suits. But most swimmers seem pleased to have a
chance to compete in the suit before the Olympic Games, where they
will be prevalent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pleased with the decision,'' said Jenny Thompson, who has
won five Olympic gold medals in the swimming relays. ``We should be
practicing what's going to be the norm in Sydney.''
</P>
<P>
   Amy Van Dyken, who became the only American woman ever to win
four swim gold medals in one Olympics at the Atlanta Games, pointed
out that she won the 50-meter freestyle and the 100-meter butterfly
by a combined total of four hundredths of a second.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not going to turn a swimmer like my mom into an Olympic
gold medalist,'' Van Dyken said. ``But in hundredths of a second,
it could make a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Lenny Krayzelburg, a world-record holder in the 100- and
200-meter backstroke, said he would wear a version of the Fastskin
suit that extended from his waist to his knees because he sensed a
loss of feel for the water in the suits that covered his entire
legs, chest and arms. Some breaststrokers said they felt
constrained by the new suits when they perform their
outward-kicking stroke.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like putting on panty hose but 10 times worse,'' said
Kristy Kowal, a favorite in the 100-meter and 200-meter
breaststroke.
</P>
<P>
   Still, most elite swimmers will squeeze themselves into some
form of the body suit here and in Sydney. Some are already
anticipating the next advancements for the 2004 Summer Games in
Athens.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a couple of years, I don't know if they're going to have
gills built into the suits, but that would be kind of cool,'' Van
Dyken said.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-08-00 2120EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000808.0340 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 21:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6182 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-GORE-LIEBERMAN-ART-2N     08-08 1409
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-LIEBERMAN-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NASHVILLE, Tenn.: other American.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Despite sweltering 97-degree heat that left Gore's drenched
shirt stuck to his back, the Democratic team got exactly the images
of family and rectitude that it wanted out of Tuesday's event. The
Gores and Liebermans, who have socialized together for years,
appeared buoyant and affectionate as they strode in unison down a
runway and onto the podium.
</P>
<P>
   Together, the two couples and their children, as well as the two
candidates' elderly mothers, created an attractive family tableau.
Lieberman, who Democrats hope will help separate Gore from
President Clinton's moral lapses, attested to Gore's devotion to
his wife and children and described the vice president as ``a man
of family and faith.''
</P>
<P>
   Tipper Gore spoke warmly of Lieberman's wife, Hadassah, and the
two candidates, having removed their jackets, exchanged a mighty
bear hug after Gore introduced his running mate. Lieberman, clearly
having the time of his life, smiled giddily and pumped his fists as
the crowd chanted ``Joe, Joe, Joe'' and waved newly minted
``Gore-Lieberman'' placards.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman, who spoke for 20 minutes, twice as long as Gore,
described the surreality of the last 24 hours as ``a magical
mystery tour.'' In his prayer, he thanked God for ``bringing me to
this extraordinary moment in my life'' and thanked Gore ``for
making this miracle possible for me and breaking this barrier for
the rest of America forever.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You know,'' he added, ``there are some people who might
actually call Al's selection of me an act of chutzpah.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Lieberman spoke touchingly of her parents, both of whom
survived the Holocaust, and said she was moved to be speaking at a
memorial that commemorates ``the American heroes, the soldiers who
actually liberated my mother in Dachau and Auschwitz (in fact, the
War Memorial, with its limestone Doric columns, was built in 1925
to honor the 3,400 Tennesseans who died in World War I, according
to the Tennessee Historical Commission).
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether you and your family immigrated from Europe, Africa,
Mexico, Latin America or Asia, I am standing here for you,'' Mrs.
Lieberman said. ``This person is our country. This land is your
land and anything is possible for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's speeches continued a pattern in the 2000 campaign, in
which Democrats and Republicans seem to be appropriating each
other's language. Gore's reference to tearing down walls echoed
President Ronald Reagan's memorable demand to Mikhail S. Gorbachev,
the Soviet leader, to tear down the Berlin Wall. That phrase, in
turn, showed up in Gov. George W. Bush's acceptance speech at the
Republican convention last week.
</P>
<P>
   And Lieberman on Tuesday quoted Gov. George W. Bush's father,
who asked in his 1988 campaign, ``If you have to change horses in
midstream, doesn't it make sense to get on the one that's going in
the right direction?''
</P>
<P>
   Joe Andrew, the co-chair of the Democratic National Committee,
said after the speeches that the new Democratic ticket was being
received enthusiastically, even by liberals who might disagree with
Lieberman's centrist politics. ``What brings them back is the sense
that we're going to win with this ticket,'' he said. ``While the
Republicans had this illusion of inclusion convention, all about
photo ops, Al Gore is all about real opportunity.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Before and after Tuesday's event, Lieberman, 58, spent time
meeting campaign aides, receiving briefings on Gore's positions,
working on the speech he will deliver at next week's Democratic
convention in Los Angeles, and preparing for a multi-state campaign
swing that begins on Wednesday with a visit to Gore's hometown of
Carthage, Tenn., and to Stamford in Lieberman's home state.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, the Republican nominee, said in a statement on Tuesday
that he respected Lieberman ``for his convictions, his strong
faith, and his record on Social Security, missile defense, and
reforming our public schools.'' Those were pointed references to
past positions taken by Lieberman _ in support of allowing workers
to invest a portion of their payroll taxes in the private markets,
deploying an expensive space-based missile defense system, and
establishing pilot programs allowing parents to use federal
vouchers to pay private school tuition _ that are opposed by Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``This selection,'' Bush continued, ``now presents the Vice
President with an interesting test of whether he will continue
attacking positions his running mate shares, or whether he will
lift up our nation by elevating the tone of his presidential
campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore campaign officials on Tuesday distributed quotations and
writings by Lieberman, including an unpublished article written in
June, suggesting that he had moved away from his support for the
partial privatization of Social Security because it posed
unacceptable risks for retirees.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman, sounding more like a Tennessean than a son of
Connecticut, used his speech on Tuesday to shoot down the Bush
campaign's suggestion that he had more in common with Bush than
with Gore. ``With all due respect,'' he said, ``I think that's like
saying that the veterinarian and the taxidermist are in the same
business because either way you get your dog back.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Gore on Tuesday took pains to emphasize the
positions on which he and Lieberman agreed. ``He believes, as I
do,'' Gore said, ``that every family has a right to clean air and
clean water. He believes, as I do, in that the earth is the Lord's
and the fullness thereof.'' Gore continued: ``He believes, as I do,
in an America that frees itself forever from the dominance of big
oil and foreign oil.''
</P>
<P>
   Together, he said repeatedly, he and Lieberman had fought for
welfare reform, for fiscal discipline and balanced budgets, for
putting more police on the streets, for providing health care for
uninsured children, for campaign finance reform and for a strong
national defense. He pointed out that both men ``broke with our own
party to cast two lonely Democratic votes in support of the Persian
Gulf War.''
</P>
<P>
   Drawing attention to Lieberman's religion once again, Gore said,
``Joe and I come from different regions and different religious
faiths. But we believe in a common set of ideals.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither Gore nor Lieberman mentioned President Clinton in their
remarks on Tuesday, though Lieberman said the Democratic ticket
would ``help renew the moral center of this nation.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman has long been considered one of the most moral voices
in the Senate, and Democratic strategists believe it is beneficial
that he was one of the first in his party to strongly and publicly
denounce Clinton's sexual relationship with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with Gore on Monday, parts of which were
broadcast on Tuesday, NBC News anchor Tom Brokaw read Gore portions
of a September 1998 speech by Lieberman in which the senator
labeled Clinton's behavior inappropriate, immoral and harmful. He
then asked Gore whether he agreed with Lieberman ``when he said
that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I did,'' Gore responded, ``and said so at the time and I think
most Americans agreed with that. I think that most Americans want
to talk about the future of our country and want to focus on the
choices that we have to make in this election and I think honestly,
Tom, that most people are ready to move on.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, he said, would play an active role in his campaign. But
he added: ``I am running this campaign on my own with my own
message and vision and I welcome his help in support of that
message and I expect I'll receive it.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Gore has never condemned Clinton with words approaching
Lieberman's. He initially defended Clinton, saying he believed the
president's denials of improper conduct. After Clinton admitted in
August 1998 that he had been deceptive, Gore said he was proud that
the president ``has had the courage to acknowledge mistakes'' and
said he was honored ``to work with this great president.''
</P>
<P>
   Several days after Lieberman made his remarks on the Senate
floor, Gore said of Clinton that ``he himself has said what he did
was wrong.'' About a month later he gave his own opinion that
``what the president did was wrong.'' His strongest comments came
in a June 1999 interview: ``What he did was inexcusable and,
particularly as a father, I felt that it was terribly wrong,
obviously.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
