<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE  

</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sales at Cisco Systems Increase 61 Percent in Quarter
</P>
<P>
   Cisco Systems reported a 61 percent gain in sales for its fiscal
fourth quarter, as the company continued to be the leading supplier
of the necessary hardware for the Internet. It was the company's
10th consecutive quarter of accelerating year-over-year revenue
growth.
</P>
<P>
   Bridgestone Said to Weigh Recall
</P>
<P>
   Bridgestone said it would hold a news conference today in
Washington amid speculation that it is preparing to recall millions
of tires after dozens of safety complaints and at least 21 fatal
accidents that are being investigated by government regulators.
</P>
<P>
   United Cancels 200 More Flights
</P>
<P>
   United Airlines canceled more than 200 flights around the
country, disrupting service for thousands of passengers for the
fourth consecutive day. The cancellations follow a disastrous
weekend in which United, the world's largest airline, was racked by
delays and forced to cancel about 600 flights, or about 15 percent
of its weekend service.
</P>
<P>
   FirstEnergy to Acquire GPU
</P>
<P>
   FirstEnergy, an Ohio-based utility company, agreed to acquire
GPU of Morristown, N.J., for $4.5 billion in cash and stock. The
acquisition would make FirstEnergy the sixth-largest energy concern
in the United States, based on customers served. Its increased size
and scale would also give it the potential to produce and
distribute electricity more efficiently, industry analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   Poor Face Choices on Energy Costs
</P>
<P>
   Millions of low-income Americans remain untouched by the
flourishing economy and, as a result, unprotected from the effects
of rising fuel and utility prices. Those prices inflict painful
choices _ especially in cities without adequate public
transportation and in small towns and suburbs where long distances
make driving a necessity.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki Signs Con Edison Bill
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George Pataki of New York, putting the blame for a February
nuclear accident squarely on Consolidated Edison, signed a bill
forcing the company to repay customers more than $100 million it
has collected in expenses from the accident, and prohibiting it
from collecting tens of millions more.
</P>
<P>
   Hyundai Profit Spur Call for Spin-Off
</P>
<P>
   Hyundai Group, South Korea's largest conglomerate, reported
record profits in its automotive business, an unexpected piece of
good news from a company known more lately for its heavy debts.
Hyundai creditors seized on the news to demand that the parent
company hasten its promised restructuring and separate the auto
business from Hyundai's unhealthy subsidiaries.
</P>
<P>
   2 Dial Executives Resign
</P>
<P>
   Dial, the maker of Dial soap and Armour canned meats, warning
that it would miss earnings expectations for the third time this
year, announced that its two top executives had resigned.
</P>
<P>
   Reality on the Yellow Brick Road
</P>
<P>
   Warner LeRoy grew up on the back lot of the Warner Brothers
studio and was on all the movie sets, most memorably the day a
scene was being filmed from ``The Wizard of Oz.'' He tells that
story and others as he traces his life from Hollywood to boarding
school in Switzerland with a roommate who is now the Aga Khan, to
drama classes at Stanford, and to milestones in the theater,
restaurant and amusement park industries in New York and vicinity.
</P>
<P>
   Dow Rises 109 Points; Nasdaq Falls
</P>
<P>
   Blue-chip stocks moved higher for the seventh straight session
as tame inflation data lured investors back to interest
rate-sensitive shares, like retailers. The Dow rose 109.88 points,
or 1 percent, to 10,976.89. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index
was up 3.48 points, or 0.2 percent, to 1,482.80. The Nasdaq shed
14.44 points, or 0.4 percent, to 3,848.55.
</P>
</TEXT>
