<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 21:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6185 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e BC-HOLLOWMAN-REVIEW-AZR &LR;      08-08 0615
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLLOWMAN-REVIEW-AZR </SLUG>
  
 BC-HOLLOWMAN-REVIEW-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    `HOLLOW MAN' NEEDS A SOLID PLOT(a) 
 &HT;    (RESENDING FOR THOSE WHO MAY HAVE MISSED THIS)(a) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By BILL MULLER(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Invisible Man was never like this.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of Claude Rains simply disappearing as he unwraps his
bandages, (beginitalic)Hollow Man (enditalic)features fantastic
transformation sequences as bodies dissolve before our very eyes.
</P>
<P>
   In a special-effects showcase, skin melts away, replaced by bone
and sinew. Muscles gradually disappear until there's only a
skeleton. Finally, the bones seem to disintegrate, and there's
nothing left.
</P>
<P>
   If you think that's something, you should see it in reverse.
</P>
<P>
   And in (beginitalic)Hollow Man(enditalic), you do. The
disappearing and reappearing trick is trotted out several times,
and it never fails to impress. We've come a long way from Lon
Chaney Jr. turning into a werewolf.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, those old horror movies had substance and style,
which (beginitalic)Hollow Man (enditalic)clearly lacks. While the
special effects and a wisecracking Kevin Bacon are enough to carry
the first 90 minutes, the movie unravels in the final act.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the film devolves into something akin to
(beginitalic)Alien:(enditalic) a monster on the loose with our
brave crew trying to find it and survive in the process. It's also
quite the gore fest, with gallons of blood and mangled corpses
everywhere. Not to mention explosions - lots of explosions.
</P>
<P>
   Though (beginitalic)Hollow Man (enditalic)would have worked much
better as an understated thriller, director Paul Verhoeven just
couldn't resist returning to his blood-soaked
(beginitalic)RoboCop-Total Recall (enditalic)roots.
</P>
<P>
   That's too bad because the movie starts out with promise as we
meet Sebastian Caine (Bacon), a cocky, egotistical researcher who
has developed an invisibility serum. Caine, who is working with the
military - invisible soldiers being a pretty formidable weapon -
first tests his serum on animals but becomes convinced it will work
on humans.
</P>
<P>
   Bacon does a nice job developing the character, who takes an
almost boyish glee in his work while being reckless at the same
time. He also lightens the tone with good comic timing.
</P>
<P>
   Like brave researchers before him, Sebastian decides to test the
invisibility serum on himself, with the help of his lovely
assistant, Linda McKay (Elisabeth Shue), and granite-jawed
researcher Matthew Kensington (Josh Brolin). Naturally, Linda is
Sebastian's old flame, and she's now dating Matthew behind his
back.
</P>
<P>
   From there, it's the old good-news, bad-news scenario. It's
pretty easy to make Sebastian disappear. But making him reappear
proves a little tougher.
</P>
<P>
   With Sebastian invisible, the movie rolls out the inventive
special effects, adding clever touches throughout. The audience can
have fun counting the ways to spot the invisible man, at least for
a few seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Sebastian is not the nicest guy, so he ultimately becomes the
world's most scientifically advanced peeping Tom, and worse.
Gradually, the whole thing begins to work on his mind, with
somewhat unfortunate results.
</P>
<P>
   Being invisible has other drawbacks, especially for an audience.
Ultimately, Verhoeven must have realized that the viewers need to
see Sebastian for part of the time, so he replaced Rains' bandages
with a crude latex mask.
</P>
<P>
   When Sebastian removes his sunglasses, he's literally
empty-headed.
</P>
<P>
   And there's no better way to describe (beginitalic)Hollow
Man(enditalic).
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Reach Muller at bill.muller(a)arizonarepublic.com or (602)
444-8651.
</P>
</TEXT>
