<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 21:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6191 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-FBN-FALCONS-NEWHOME08     08-08 1088
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-NEWHOME0809 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Falcons ready to move into new Flowery Brance facility
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Greenville, S.C. - Where once there were dirt floors, the
Atlanta Falcons on Thursday will tread gold.
</P>
<P>
   Well, not exactly.
</P>
<P>
   But when the team moves into its new facility in Flowery Branch,
coach Dan Reeves and his team will make a quantum leap not only
from their humble 22-year-old facility in Suwanee, but from Reeves'
first visit with the organization 23 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   In 1977, when he was offensive coordinator with the Cowboys,
Reeves interviewed to be head coach.
</P>
<P>
   He did not like what he saw in the bowels of old Atlanta-Fulton
County Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest shock was the weight room was on a dirt floor,''
Reeves said. ``And when the Braves were (playing) in there, the
Falcons had to go practice in a nearby park.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, the Falcons won't have to go anywhere to practice, even in
lousy weather.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, the team would bus from its 28,000-square foot
facility in Suwanee to the Georgia Dome _ if it was available _ for
late-season practices when weather was an issue.
</P>
<P>
   But the new $18 million facility, which is still being built,
will have a covered field in a 92,000-square foot building. That's
in addition to a 75,000-square foot building that will be team
headquarters, and three outdoor fields.
</P>
<P>
   Wide receiver Terance Mathis, entering his seventh season with
the Falcons, can hardly believe it.
</P>
<P>
   Before, meeting rooms, rehabilitation stations, departments,
cafeterias, etc. were spread out over three buildings and six
trailers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having everything under one roof is great,'' he said. ``You
never have to worry about bundling up, or walking in the rain. I'm
happy to be around to see it. It's been talked about for years.''
</P>
<P>
   Team president Taylor Smith and Reeves began talking of this
when Reeves was hired in '97.
</P>
<P>
   There was hiccup this time last year when it looked like the new
facility would end up in Stone Mountain Park.
</P>
<P>
   But various financial reasons and the possibility of the
organization one day owning rather than leasing its new property
shifted the focus to the sleepy town off I-985, near Gainesville.
</P>
<P>
   This facility won't be sleepy.
</P>
<P>
   Where defensive staffers used to cram into coordinator Rich
Brooks' office for meetings, now, every position will have a
meeting room of its own.
</P>
<P>
   And instead of the team-wide meetings that used to be so
uncomfortable in that trailer on the hill, there will be a 128-seat
auditorium where every player, coach, video man and scout will have
a table of his own
</P>
<P>
   Don't even get strength and conditioning coach Al Miller
started.
</P>
<P>
   Half the high schools in Georgia have a bigger, better and less
cramped weight room than what he's had.
</P>
<P>
   It was great in '78, when the Falcons moved into the Suwanee
facility, but the NFL and especially and each team's support
staffs, have grown in leaps and bounds since.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, the local team catches up.
</P>
<P>
   Where once there were two bench presses, there will be at least
eight.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be about three times as big,'' Miller said. ``We
can handle everybody. You won't have five or six people waiting at
one station. It shortens their workout time, and helps the
conditioning factor because they can get through there faster.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be nice. It's going to be a health club.''
</P>
<P>
   Left tackle Bob Whitfield, of course, offered a different
opinion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Man, it's all the way out in Flowery Branch,'' he said,
souring on his commute. ``Unless Taylor has that helicopter ready
for me, that's a beast.''
</P>
<P>
   The team president just happened to walk up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, Bob, you're going to love it,'' Smith said. ``They got a,
`Cold plunge.'''
</P>
<P>
   That's a large, cold whirlpool for cooling down in after hot
practices.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, well that sounds nice,'' Whitfield said, arm around Smith.
``Can you put a beer tap in there, too?''
</P>
<P>
   That's not going to happen.
</P>
<P>
   But there will be a soda fountain in the media work room, and
press conferences will be just around the corner and down the hall
from the media work room.
</P>
<P>
   At Suwanee, there was no media work room, just a small, dingy,
dark room in the old Falcon Inn motel.
</P>
<P>
   Press conferences were in a trailer. The media relations office
was in another trailer, marketing in another trailer, some rehab
equipment in another trailer, and so on.
</P>
<P>
   ``For press conferences, for example, we'll have track lighting,
which will be nice for TV,'' said Aaron Salkin, director of public
relations. ``We're going to have a research/archives room. And each
writer will have a work station.''
</P>
<P>
   Vice president of corporate development and former linebacker
Tommy Nobis _ who used to work out under the old stadium _ was the
point man in researching other NFL training facilities, and worked
closely with architects.
</P>
<P>
   Executive vice president administrations Jim Hay has overseen
construction.
</P>
<P>
   ClayCo, a St. Louis-based contractor that built the Rams'
facility, is pulling this off so fast heads are spinning, although
the team can not yet handle fans because of ongoing construction of
parking lots and the indoor facility.
</P>
<P>
   ``In those old defensive meetings, it was almost a joke. Those
guys were sitting in each other's laps,'' Nobis said. ``Now, that
cold pool will be like jumping into a lake in Wisconsin in the
winter. The Swim-X is a rehab-type pool that gives you a current.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody looking at new facilities would say the Rams' is the
nicest now. I'm prejudiced, but I think this is going to be
nicer.''
</P>
<P>
   Equipment manager Brian Boigner will have about three times more
storage space, and sliding shelves and closets.
</P>
<P>
   The training room will nearly triple itself.
</P>
<P>
   Video director Tom Atcheson's about to step up in class, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll be going to all digital video, and each coach will have
one installed in his office,'' he said. ``Instead of having to
scroll through it, when they want play No. 47, they can just go
straight to it. And I'll have about three times more room.'' Reeves
is convinced it will be a home capable of helping attract free
agents, even though it's about 50 miles from Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``Moving into the new facility is like moving into a new house.
It kind of lifts everybody's spirit,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be nice where . . . everybody else in the NFL
will be looking up at us.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
