<SLUG> BC-DRUG-CERTIFICATION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. DRUG CHIEF VOICES CONFIDENCE IN MEXICO'S EFFORTS 
</HEADLINE>
   By GINGER THOMPSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ In one of his last official visits here as the
U.S. director of drug policy, Gen. Barry R. McCaffrey praised the
transition team assembled by President-elect Vicente Fox and said
he shared Fox's opposition to the American drug certification
program.
</P>
<P>
   But McCaffrey, who has long expressed misgivings about the
program, said at a news briefing that there was ``zero'' chance
Congress would end it in the near future.
</P>
<P>
   At most, he said, the program might die a natural death as the
Organization of American States drew up plans next year for a
multinational drug evaluation process that would open all member
governments' drug programs to scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   ``I actually believe,'' McCaffrey said, ``that the certification
process is slowly disappearing under the evidence that
multinational cooperation better serves the interests of the
American people than confrontation.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the program, created by Congress in the 1980s, the State
Department evaluates other countries' drug interdiction efforts and
can impose economic sanctions on countries that do receive
certification. Most Latin American governments view the program as
interventionist and lopsided because it does not allow for scrutiny
of American efforts to combat drug consumption.
</P>
<P>
   McCaffrey, who arrived here on Monday for meetings with
officials like Fox's chief security and law enforcement advisers,
praised the president-elect for seeking greater cooperation among
countries in the fight against drugs. And he said he was confident
that Mexico's efforts would not be weakened by Fox's plans to
gradually limit the role of the military.
</P>
<P>
   McCaffrey has long praised the Mexican military as a crucial
element of the battle because of its successes in destroying
marijuana crops and in confiscating shipments of drugs traveling
through Mexico on the way to the United States. At least 60 percent
of all cocaine that enters the United States is widely thought to
pass through Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``My judgment is that President-elect Fox and this team that we
are working with are pragmatists,'' McCaffrey told reporters.
``They are determined to go down in history as Mexican patriots. I
cannot believe they will do anything that doesn't make sense to
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have got large new visions,'' he said, ``and what we are
going to do is listen to what they say and be supportive of their
emerging strategies.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon after his election on July 2, Fox announced plans to
reorganize the Mexican justice system to resemble U.S. agencies. At
the same time, he announced plans to lobby Washington to end the
drug certification program. This will be among the topics to be
discussed this month when Fox travels to the United States to meet
with President Clinton, Vice President Al Gore and the Republican
presidential candidate, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   A member of Fox's transition team said that even though ending
certification seemed unlikely, Mexico was determined to stop it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
