u p BC-DEMS-VEEP-HNS &LR;      08-08 1057
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEMS-VEEP-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIEBERMAN SAYS DEMS WON'T CEDE MORALITY ISSUES 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE, Tenn. _ Sen. Joseph Lieberman, an observant Orthodox
Jew, wove in references to scripture, God and faith Tuesday as he
addressed a Nashville crowd after he was introduced as Democratic
presidential candidate Al Gore's running mate.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman, the first Jew to run on a major party presidential
ticket, praised Vice President Gore for a bold historical move.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know there are some people who might call Al's selection
of me an act of chutzpah,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman also made it clear that the Democrats will not cede
morality and character issues to the Republicans. The two will
claim their party's nomination for president and vice president at
the Democratic National convention next week in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Gore introduced Lieberman during a noon rally at the War
Memorial Plaza in downtown Nashville.
</P>
<P>
   Both Gore and Lieberman drew parallels between their ticket and
that of John F. Kennedy, who in 1960 became the first and only
Roman Catholic to be elected president.
</P>
<P>
   ``Next week when our party meets in Los Angeles we will recall
the last time we met there, at the convention where we nominated
John F. Kennedy,'' said Gore. ``That year, we voted with out hearts
to tear down a mighty wall of division. We made history. And when
we nominate Joe Lieberman for vice president we will do it again.
We will tear down an old wall of division once again.''
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign, hoping to blunt Republican nominee George W.
Bush's bounce in the polls after last week's successful GOP
convention, has been elated at the initial reaction to the
selection of Lieberman, a two-term Connecticut senator who grabbed
Americans' attention in 1998 by scolding President Clinton for his
affair with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Pundits and even some Republicans praised the centrist Democrat,
who has broken with his party on a number of issues, including his
support of private school vouchers. One overnight poll by Gallup
USA found Gore had almost erased the double-digit gap with Bush.
</P>
<P>
   While Lieberman never mentioned Clinton, he alluded to both the
pluses and minuses of the current administration.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the economic boom of the two Clinton terms,
Lieberman dismissed Bush's claim during his convention speech in
Philadelphia that the last eight years have been squandered.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today the same people who let this nation drift are trying to
convince us that the past eight years have been squandered,'' he
said. ``But if you're one of the 22 million people who got a new
job during the past eight years, they haven't been squandered.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman also disputed claims by the Bush aides that he and the
Texas governor have similar political philosophies.
</P>
<P>
   ``With all due respect, I think that's a little bit like saying
that the veterinarian and the taxidermist are in the same business,
because either way you get your dog back,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Lieberman also tried to show that he and Gore would set a
different moral tone than Clinton. To make his point that the Gores
shared his ethical standards, he referred to Tipper Gore's
controversial campaign in the 1980s to put warning labels on rock
albums containing profanity and sexually suggestive lyrics.
</P>
<P>
   ``And we must work, and we will work _ Al and Tipper, Hadassah
(his wife) and I _ to help renew the moral center of this nation so
that families can be stronger, children safer and parents empowered
to pass to their children their faith and moral values,'' he said.
``As Tipper Gore said so well, when it was difficult to say, let's
stand with parents who are trying to raise PG kids in an X-rated
society.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman also spoke of himself as the embodiment of the
American dream, the son of a baker who worked long hours to send
his three children to college.
</P>
<P>
   The senator made numerous references to his faith, at one point
citing a passage from Chronicles in the Old Testament. He appeared
to offer a brief prayer, ``Dear Lord, I thank you for bringing me
to this extraordinary moment of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   He was joined on stage by his wife, who noted that both of her
parents were World War II Holocaust survivors. Looking at the
majestic war memorial, she said that it was American soldiers who
liberated her mother from the concentration camps.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I stand before you deeply, sincerely thankful that I am an
American,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The extended Lieberman family was also present, including three
of their four children, and a granddaughter who is named Tennessee
because her mother grew up in a small town in the state.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the sweltering heat that forced Lieberman at one point
to borrow a towel to wipe his brow, the candidates and their
families were clearly buoyed by the enthusiastic reaction of a
crowd estimated at 3,000.
</P>
<P>
   In his remarks, Gore skipped over various areas where he and
Lieberman have disagreed over the years and instead emphasized that
they have shared a common philosophy that focuses on fiscal
discipline, a strong defense, welfare reform, and environmental
protection.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said both men backed campaign finance reform.
</P>
<P>
   However, Lieberman was one of the few Democrats on a Senate
committee investigating Democratic abuses during the 1996
presidential campaign that voiced criticism of the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Gore also touched on the character issue. ``Joe Lieberman has
the experience and integrity,'' he said. ``He has the courage and
the commitment. And for all his public life, Joe Lieberman has
stood for working families.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush used a statement complimenting Lieberman to take a shot at
Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``I respect Senator Lieberman for his convictions, his strong
faith, and his record on Social Security, missile defense and
reforming our public schools,'' Bush said. ``I hope he will run a
positive campaign and that the vice president will use this
opportunity to change his tone to that of Senator Lieberman's
level. This selection now presents the vice president with an
interesting test of whether he will continue attacking positions
his running mate shares, or whether he will lift up our nation by
elevating the tone of his presidential campaign.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXEND OF STORY $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
