<SLUG> BC-SPACE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARGO CAPSULE DOCKS WITH SPACE STATION 
 
 

</HEADLINE>
 STATION-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARK CARREAU 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ An unmanned Russian Progress cargo capsule filled with
vital life support equipment such as a toilet, vacuum cleaner and
other supplies docked Tuesday with the soon-to-be-inhabited,
U.S.-led international space station.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the gear is destined for installation aboard the large
new Russian crew module that arrived on July 25, furnishing the
slowly developing orbital outpost with its first living and working
quarters for future resident astronauts.
</P>
<P>
   With the smaller Progress in pursuit, the two spacecraft linked
at 3:13 p.m. CDT, as they coasted more than 220 miles over Central
Asia. Though supervised by ground teams in suburban Moscow, the
operation was closely monitored at the station's mission control
facility at the Johnson Space Center in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Launched Sunday from Kazakhstan, the 23-foot-long cargo capsule
delivered more than 1,300 pounds of equipment. They included oxygen
generation and carbon dioxide removal systems to supply and recycle
breathing air aboard the station, a Russian space toilet, laptop
computers, food, clothing and communications gear.
</P>
<P>
   Coupled with last month's much-delayed addition of the large
Russian crew module called Zvezda, Tuesday's linkup sets the stage
for a steep acceleration in U.S. station construction activity,
including plans for nine NASA space shuttle assembly missions
within the next year.
</P>
<P>
   Russian economic problems delayed the arrival of the
43-foot-long crew module by 27 months.
</P>
<P>
   The Progress and its cargo will remain undisturbed until the
shuttle Atlantis reaches the station in early September with a U.S.
and Russian crew. During a five-day stay, the visiting shuttle crew
plans to unload the Progress and begin the task of installing the
Russian life support equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Their efforts will prepare the slowly developing station for the
arrival of its first resident crew in early November aboard a
Russian Soyuz capsule.
</P>
<P>
   American commander Bill Shepherd and cosmonauts Yuri Gidzenko
and Sergei Krikalev have trained to complete the activation of the
life support equipment early in their four-month stay. Like the
others to follow, their expedition will be punctuated by the
arrival of space shuttle crews with large new station components.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are starting to embark on a set of activities that is
probably as complex as anything we've ever done in the space
business, including landing on the moon,'' Ron Dittemore, NASA
shuttle program director, said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   NASA plans to follow its September shuttle visit to the station
with major assembly flights in October, November and January. The
October flight will add an external foundation to the station for
the American solar-power generator that will follow on the November
mission. The electricity generated by the new solar array power
module will be needed by the large U.S. laboratory module slated to
follow on another shuttle in January.
</P>
<P>
   More flights will follow next year to equip the laboratory with
research gear and to add an airlock to the station, easing the many
spacewalks that will be needed future construction.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, the station's 16-nation partnership hopes to complete
the assembly by 2006.
</P>
<P>
   When finished, the orbital outpost will sprawl to the size of a
pair of football fields placed side-by-side and house seven-member
crews.
</P>
<P>
   Rotating crews will be assigned a range of physics, biology and
medical experiments aboard a half-dozen laboratory modules. Station
residents will also keep tabs on changes in the Earth's environment
and test hardware that could be used for future human expeditions
to the moon and Mars. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXEND OF STORY &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
