<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 21:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6203 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-NY-VERIZON-(TRIMS)-NY     08-08 0889
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-VERIZON-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK CITY AREA IS FRONT LINE OF VERIZON STRIKE 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also VERIZON-STRIKE, VERIZON-NORTHPOINT) 
 By THOMAS J. LUECK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Call it a New York state of mind.
</P>
<P>
   Three days into the strike by more than 86,000 employees of the
nation's largest local telephone company, spanning the region from
Maine to Virginia, the most strident and sometimes violent front
lines of the walkout have been in New York City and its suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, the company, Verizon Communications, said it had
reported 455 strike-related incidents of assault, harassment and
vandalism to the police in 12 states and the District of Columbia _
with more than half of them in New York state.
</P>
<P>
   The first two strike-related arrests were made in New York on
Tuesday. And Tuesday evening, New York State Supreme Court Judge
Louis York, in Manhattan, granted the company's request for a
temporary restraining order, effective through next Monday, that
bars picketers from preventing managers or replacement workers from
entering their offices or carrying out work assignments.
</P>
<P>
   The flare-ups, ranging from egg throwing to arson, have come
amid a scorching spell of heat and humidity that descended on the
New York metropolitan area on Sunday, shortening tempers just as
the strike began.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The weather may help explain why the city, which lately has
prided itself on a steep drop in crime, was rocked on Sunday night
by a wave of violence, including 20 shootings and four murders,
that had nothing to do with strike,
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   But experts say outbreaks along picket lines and evidence of
strike-related vandalism in New York point to broader,
farther-reaching factors in the nation's largest city and
communications capital, where a rapid technological, new-economy
shift into nonunionized wireless and Internet communications jobs
is running head on into a long tradition of union activism.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the place where the unions will have their impact,''
said Mitchell Moss, a professor of urban studies and
telecommunications expert at New York University. ``The density of
the city means that a small disruption can have an enormous
effect,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night, the company declined to estimate how many of
several thousand residential phone lines in New York City were
still out of service because of vandalism that had occurred since
the strike began early Sunday. Union leaders have denied member
involvement in any network vandalism.
</P>
<P>
   Moss said the unionized Verizon workers, many of them schooled
in strike tactics through years of employment at AT&AMP;T and Nynex
(which merged with Verizon's predecessor, Bell Atlantic, in 1997),
hold a particularly potent weapon in New York because of their
knowledge of the intricacies the city's telecommunications wiring _
and because of the wide publicity they are assured if the network
is disrupted.
</P>
<P>
   ``They know the infrastructure because they built it,'' he said.
``And since this is the media capital of the world, you get more
sympathy from other union workers than you would anywhere else.''
</P>
<P>
   That logic was apparently not lost Tuesday on a striking Verizon
worker, who gave his name only as Jerry, and who was involved in a
confrontation outside a Verizon maintenance garage on King Street
in the Soho section of Manhattan. Accounts varied, but the incident
resulted in a maintenance truck being battered and stuck under a
electronic gate that witnesses said had been lowered by strikers,
who had access to the gate's remote control box. A nonunion Verizon
contractor, who was in the truck, was not injured. No arrests were
made.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every now and then, it gets tense,'' said Jerry, a member of
the Communication Workers of America. ``But we know that a large
majority of jobs in this industry will go wireless, and it is only
the union that can give us a future.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Besides winning the court injunction, the company responded to
union violence by increasing a $10,000 reward it began offering on
Sunday for information leading to convictions for strike-related
vandalism. The new bounty is $25,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``We certainly have evidence the our management workers have
experienced abuse from the pickets, sometimes dangerously so,''
said Eric Rabe, a Verizon spokesman. Similar injunctions had been
issued by state courts in Pennsylvania and Rhode Island on Monday,
the company said.
</P>
<P>
   In one of Tuesday's arrests in New York, a picketing worker was
charged with disorderly conduct outside Verizon's Manhattan
headquarters at Avenue of the Americas and 42nd Street, after
police said he refused to remain behind a barricade.
</P>
<P>
   In the other incident, police said a striking worker was charged
with petty larceny after removing lug nuts from the wheels of a
Verizon maintenance truck on West 15th Street.
</P>
<P>
   Verizon said Tuesday that it had received reports of 143
incidents of vandalism or harassment involving its employees or
equipment within New York City since the strike began, and believed
at least 115 may have involved criminal activity.
</P>
<P>
   But a CWA spokeswoman in Washington, Candice Johnson, said
Verizon might be exaggerating the disruption caused by the strike. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
