<HEADER>
A6207 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-OLY-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     08-08 0995
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WELL-SUITED FOR SPEED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; INDIANAPOLIS _ If you believe what you've heard the past few
months, there will be no fast swimmers at the U.S. Olympic Trials,
just fast swimsuits.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody is talking about the androgynous, neck-to-ankle
bodysuit that is either revolutionary or revolting, depending on
whom y who think it's cheating.
</P>
<P>
   Me? I wondered what all the fuss was about. I mean, when was the
last time you heard somebody say Tiger Woods' equipment is what
makes him a great golfer?
</P>
<P>
   But as the tales of the bodysuit's magical powers spread far and
wide, my curiosity kicked in. A former competitive swimmer, I
decided to find out first hand what the big deal was. I called Stu
Isaac, the vice president of Speedo, and kindly asked him if I
could test one of his company's Fastsuits.
</P>
<P>
   To my immense relief, he didn't giggle. He shipped me an itsy,
bitsy bodysuit and after I finished laughing, I tried it on, then
tried it out.
</P>
<P>
   It was the same model American Tom Malchow wore when he set the
world record in the 200-meter butterfly earlier this summer. Dutch
sprinter Inga de Bruijn has broken eight world records in it since
May. Clearly, you're not going to put on a suit called a Fastskin
and expect to go slow. So it was with me. I wasn't disappointed,
but I'm also not about to quit my day job.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the expense _ with a retail price of $240, it is not
suited for the masses _ the main problem I see with the suit is
getting to the starting blocks on time.
</P>
<P>
   My advice to the swimmers who will be wearing the bodysuit for
the first time as the Olympic Trials get under way today is the sa
have for people traveling L.A.'s freeways: Allow plenty of time for
unexpected snarls.
</P>
<P>
   Isaac persuaded me to wear a size better suited for Calista
Flockhart. My torso felt like Wayne Gretzky's toes in those
two-sizes-too-small skates he always favored.
</P>
<P>
   It took me 3 minutes of aerobic activity to squeeze into the
sleeveless version of the Fastskin suit (there also are
full-sleeved and half-leg versions). When I later told this to a
women's college coach, she dryly replied that I must have had too
large a size then because her swimmers require anywhere from 10 to
15 minutes to wiggle into their bodysuits. The team record, I was
further informed, is 8 minutes, 23 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, it's not an article of clothing designed with fashion
runway shows in mind.
</P>
<P>
   When I walked onto the pool deck, people stopped and stared at
me as if to say, uh, lady, you missed the turn for the beach.
</P>
<P>
   From afar, it did look like I was wearing a surfer's wetsuit.
But up close you can plainly see the difference; the Fastskin suit,
a blend of polyester, lycra and polyurethane, has V-shaped ridges
that are supposed to lessen drag by directing water away from the
body.
</P>
<P>
   I was about to be the judge of that.
</P>
<P>
   Not being one to jump to conclusions, I DIVED in the pool. To my
surprise, I popped up to the surface like a cork. It was
intoxicating to flit across the pool like a skipping stone.
</P>
<P>
   The coaches I've talked to say the bodysuit is ideal for the
lean swimmer and the not-so-lean alike; it makes the swimmer with
very little bodyfat more buoyant _ thereby cutting down on the
water's resistance _ and acts as a corset that makes everyone else
more streamlined.
</P>
<P>
   All I know is I hadn't ridden that high in the water since being
weaned from my water wings at the age of 2. To paraphrase Dennis
Miller, if I had been any higher, I would have had to submit a
urine sample.
</P>
<P>
   Not to say the hydrodynamics of swimming are never going to be
the same, but I imagine the starter at Sydney, before commanding
the swimmers to take their marks, will be instructed to remind
them, ``In the event of a musculature power failure, your suit can
be used as a flotation device.''
</P>
<P>
   The rules established by the sport's international governing
body (FINA) forbid the use of ``any device that may aid (a
swimmer's) speed, buoyancy or endurance during a competition.''
</P>
<P>
   FINA recently ruled the suits do not enhance performance. To
which I say, yes, and androstenedione had absolutely nothing to do
with Mark McGwire's home-run offensive in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   My times in the suit won't have Jenny Thompson or Dara Torres
quaking in their sweats. But I did go half-a-second faster for a
25-yard sprint than what I consistently clock in my tried-and-true
lycra skinsuit. To swim in the bodysuit is to appreciate how a
golfer must feel when he swings one of Callaway's ERC forged
titanium drivers or a cyclist when he's racing down the Alps on an
aluminum feather.
</P>
<P>
   If the bodysuit violates FINA's rules, then I would argue, so do
goggles. After all, they've clearly aided endurance over the years
by enabling swimmers to log lots of mileage in chemically treated
pools without worrying about their eyes swelling shut.
</P>
<P>
   Time doesn't stand still, so why should sporting equipment? At
its best, technology is a tailwind that carries sportsmen and
sportswomen past the old, familiar horizons and into uncharted
territories.
</P>
<P>
   After a cursory check to see which way the wind is blowing, FINA
green-lighted the bodysuits for use next month at the Olympics in
Sydney, which is why a lot of swimmers will be wearing them at the
Trials.
</P>
<P>
   The hope here is FINA doesn't give in to a well-meaning minority
who are painting bodysuits with much the same brush as steroids.
Yes, they both enhance performance. But I have yet to hear of the
bodysuit giving anybody acute acne or irrevocable organ damage.
</P>
<P>
   A little chafing around the shoulders and armpits, maybe, but
that's it.
</P>
<P>
   Anybody really interested in preserving the purity of sport
ought to stop worrying about the dragless suit and do something
about designer drugs. I don't need to try those to know they make
you go faster.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
