<HEADLINE>
PBS SHOW AIDS ENTREPRENEUR IN HUNT FOR VENTURE CAPITAL 
</HEADLINE>
   By PETER SINTON  
 c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Move over Regis Philbin, Alex Trebek and Pat
Sajak. Public television programs also are handing out big bucks.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the PBS-syndicated show ``MoneyHunt'' announced the
winner of its ``Wow! What a Great Idea'' contest for entrepreneurs,
becoming the first TV show to award venture capital.
</P>
<P>
   CampusEngine.com, a Sacramento (Calif.) County startup that
works with college newspapers to expand their Web sites and help
businesses reach the coveted college student market online,
received $100,000. In the process, it beat out more than 2,000
companies.
</P>
<P>
   CampusEngine Chief Executive Officer Jack Crawford started the
company in Folsom, Calif., in October to help college newspapers
build their Web sites into full-fledged Internet portals where
students can communicate and businesses can pay to advertise.
</P>
<P>
   Crawford, 33, decided to become an entrepreneur after studying
accounting at Arizona State University and working for Coopers &AMP;
Lybrand. ``I realized I didn't want to do people's taxes for the
rest of my life and wanted to get involved in technology,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   He decided to focus on the college market because it is ``the
most well-connected and Web-savvy market.'' Crawford wanted to
partner with college newspapers rather than having to spend
millions of dollars to establish a brand name on each campus. He
figured that colleges would appreciate help in building their
online communities and that businesses would be interested in
finding a quicker, easier way to pitch their products and service
to many colleges without visiting each one.
</P>
<P>
   He was right. CampusEngine already has partnered with 71 college
newspapers with about 1.4 million students, including more than a
third of the 100 largest colleges. It expects to serve and share
advertising and promotion revenues with 150 campuses by the end of
the year. In California, customers include the University of
California at Davis, the University of San Francisco and California
State University at Chico.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we created `MoneyHunt,' our goal was to foster the
entrepreneurial spirit and highlight the best and the brightest of
the new business ideas being developed across the country,'' said
Miles Spencer, co-founder and host of the show, which is in its
third year.
</P>
<P>
   In its hunt for the worthiest company, ``MoneyHunt'' played host
to events in 14 cities. At the Golden State Venture Capital
Conference in Sacramento in March, CampusEngine beat out about 20
competitors.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of GROW09 (63880 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  Finally, in the ``MoneyHunt'' episode that premiered on the Web
site ( &LR; www.moneyhunt.com &LR; ) last Wednesday, Crawford faced off
against James Alexander of Mibrary.com, a New York startup.
</P>
<P>
   Spencer said he and several other judges were looking for three
things: ``a great idea simply expressed, the opportunity to create
a break-away product and an entrepreneur the camera loves.''
</P>
<P>
   After deftly answering questions and presenting his vision for
CampusEngine.com, Crawford won $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are thrilled to win this competition and about the
confidence of people who see thousands of business plans,''
Crawford said. In addition to the investment from ``MoneyHunt,''
CampusEngine has raised $1.5 million in the Sacramento area from
Deep River Ventures, Granite Bay Ventures and Sierra Angels.
</P>
<P>
   But Crawford's money hunt is not over. He expects to land
another $10 million from VC firms and media companies in the next
month.
</P>
<P>
   MORE ON GRANTS: In response to last week's story about
government technology grants available to entrepreneurs, former
NASA Ames Research Center manager Bob La Mere wrote to recommend
two local community colleges that provide training sessions on the
Small Business Innovative Research (SBIR) process.
</P>
<P>
   One is the Center for Applied Competitive Technologies at DeAnza
College in Cupertino, Calif. It provides manufacturing assistance
to small businesses and typically plays host to SBIR process
training in Sunnyvale each year.
</P>
<P>
   The other is the West Valley College California Procurement
Training &AMP; Assistance Center in Saratoga, Calif.
( &LR; www.westvalley.edu/ &LR;   &LR; wvc/calptac &LR; ). Sue Coates, director of the
center, says the center offers $20 workshops and private consulting
``at free or nearly free rates.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Grow a Business appears every Wednesday. Send small-business tips,
comments and questions to entrepreneurs(at)sfgate.com, or to Peter
Sinton, Grow a Business column, 901 Mission St., San Francisco, CA
94103.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
COL. 2 of GROW09 (63880 ) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   END OF STORY  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
