 PERSONALS: If You're Rich, He's Your Man 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file.) &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By LEAH GARCHIK &QC;  &LR; 
 &UR; c.2000, San Francisco Chronicle &LR;  &QC; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Noting that ``66 major corporations have already donated more than
$50,000 to both  &UR; Bush &LR;  and  &UR; Gore &LR; ,'' Billionairesforbushorgore.com
is planning a Million Billionaire March. The site, pointed out to
Personals by  &UR; Howard Pearlstein &LR; , includes the accompanying photo
of the candidate.
</P>
<P>
   -- What's it like to be aboard &UR; George W. &LR; 's plane? Brill's
Content describes Los Angeles Times reporter  &UR; Esther Schrader &LR; 
onboard, seeing ``Bush talking excitedly with a group of
reporters.''
</P>
<P>
   ``With pen poised and tape recorded in hand, Schrader made a
hurried dash up the aisle of the plane.'' An aide calmed her down,
signaling her to put the tape recorder away. ``Nothing newsworthy
here. Waving his arms excitedly, Bush was explaining which of his
family pets had been named after which players in the Texas Rangers
farm system.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; FAR &AMP; NEAR &LR;
</P>
<P>
   -- Nature boy  &UR; Michael Eisner &LR; , who owns three adjacent lots in
Malibu, wants to build a private elevator to the beach, says the
New York Daily News, but would first need permission from the
California Coasting Commission and the Malibu planning department.
</P>
<P>
   -- The correct way to say it, says  &UR; Howard Becker &LR; , is pee-YAN-o
PLAYer.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; TO THINE OWN SELF BE BORING &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MSNBC's  &UR; Jeannette Walls &LR;  says that  &UR; Michelle Pfeiffer &LR; , who's
been making the promotional rounds for her new movie, ``What Lies
Beneath,'' is giving magazine editors a hard time. Whether this is
intentional is open to discussion.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's all this bargaining and finagling to get her,'' said
one editor, ``and then she says absolutely nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what she's like in real life,'' said another,
``but in interviews, she is the most boring person alive. It's a
good thing she photographs well or we'd have absolutely no story.''
</P>
<P>
   The minority view is admiring: ``It's a finely honed skill among
certain stars,'' said a third editor, ``to get tons of publicity
without revealing a thing about yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; FAUNA &AMP; FAUNA &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Department of Agriculture's latest count, mandated by
the Animal Welfare Act, says in 1998 there were 1,213,814 animals
being used in laboratories. But Lingua Franca, forwarded to
Personals by  &UR; Patrick Walsh &LR; , points out that the list of animals _
including 206,243 hamsters, 27,381 sheep and 142,963 ``other''
animals _ does not include rats, mice or birds, which the
government considers ``lower species.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``other animals'' category includes ferrets, woodchucks,
armadillos, chinchillas, horses, spotted hyenas and opossums, and
Lingua Franca, which focuses on scholarly issues, apparently thinks
the ``lower species'' designation is semantic hair-splitting.
</P>
<P>
   P.S. &UR; Larry Dossey &LR; , author of ``Reinventing Medicine,'' reports
that 52 percent of male pet owners ``confess to having sung to or
danced with their dogs,'' says the Earth Island Journal.
</P>
<P>
   P.P.S. &UR; Alan Porter &LR;  of San Rafael bought an anti-deer garden
spray called Not Tonight Deer.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
WHO SAID WHAT
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``Whether he likes it or not (and I suspect he does), his true &LR; 
 &UR; metier will continue to be eccentrics _ men reserved, blinkered, &LR; 
 &UR; shut off from their fellows, and obsessed. Within such minority &LR; 
 &UR; men there is a hidden glee, an inward fanatical glow; and in &LR; 
 &UR; their souls Guinness is at ease.'' &LR;
</P>
<P>
   -- Critic  &UR; Kenneth Tynan &LR;  in a profile of  &UR; Alec Guinness &LR;  that
first ran in Harper's Bazaar in 1952 and was sent to Personals by
 &UR; Georgia Seibert &LR; . The New York Post says that  &UR; Mike Nichols &LR;  is
planning a remake of ``Kind Hearts and Coronets'' starring  &UR; Robin &LR; 
 &UR; Williams &LR;  in all the parts played by Guinness in the original.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
