<HEADER>
A6214 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-LIEBERMAN-FAMILY-NYT     08-08 0522
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIEBERMAN-FAMILY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MRS. LIEBERMAN, CHILD OF HOLOCAUST SURVIVORS, NO LONGER WORKING IN
QUIET 
</HEADLINE>
  By DAVID M. HERSZENHORN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   STAMFORD, Conn. _ The selection of her husband as Vice President
Al Gore's running mate thrust Hadassah Lieberman onto the national
stage Tuesday and into the type of highly public role she has
worked hard to avoid as a political spouse.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Lieberman, 52, has held several part-time jobs in
Washington since her husband, Joseph Lieberman, was elected to the
United States Senate in 1988. But her friends and former colleagues
say that her first commitment has always been raising to their
daughter, Hana, who is 12.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Lieberman, the former Hadassah Freilich, worked for the
National Research Council promoting education programs and for
APCO, a public relations firm. She has also done freelance public
relations and health care consulting.
</P>
<P>
   In general, Mrs. Lieberman has preferred to work quietly for
charitable causes rather than to actively promote any political
agenda.
</P>
<P>
   At the rally introducing Mr. Lieberman in Nashville on Tuesday,
Gore's wife, Tipper, spoke of Mrs. Lieberman as the daughter of
Nazi concentration-camp survivors, something that friends say is at
the core of how Mrs. Lieberman views herself and the world. ``I
think her background as a survivor's daughter has given her a
humanity that a lot of people don't have,'' said Mindy Weisel, a
friend.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Mrs. Lieberman is on the board of the Auschwitz
Jewish Center Foundation, which is building a visitors' center near
the concentration camp in Poland and has supported the American
Committee for Shaare-Zedek Medical Center in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   The Liebermans, who were married in 1983, may seem to have a
1950s style of life, preferring quiet dinners at home to the buzz
of the political social scene, but their family is a decidedly
modern American one, extended exponentially by divorce and
re-marriage even as it has remained rooted in traditional Jewish
observance across four generations.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman's first marriage to Betty Haas, a psychiatrist, ended
in divorce in 1981. They have two children, a son, Matt, 32, who
teaches English in New Haven, and a daughter, Rebecca, 31, who
lives in New York City and works for the Children's Aid Society.
Matt and his wife, April, have two daughters, Willy and Tennessee,
whose name provided fodder for Gore at Tuesday's rally in
Nashville.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Lieberman is also divorced, from Gordon Tucker, a rabbi in
White Plains, N.Y., who is a former dean of the Jewish Theological
Seminary in New York City. They have a son, Ethan, who is now
studying to become a rabbi.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the children, grandchildren and ex-spouses, Mr.
Lieberman's mother, Marcia, still lives in Stamford, where he grew
up, and Mrs. Lieberman's mother, Ella Freilich, a Holocaust
survivor, lives in Riverdale, the Bronx, where she watched her
daughter on television Tuesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't slept in two days already, just answering
congratulations,'' Freilich said. ``I haven't eaten today. I am
just sitting and crying.''
</P>
</TEXT>
