<HEADLINE>
SELES OUT OF TOURNEY BECAUSE OF SORE ARM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICH HAMMOND  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; MANHATTAN BEACH, Calif. _ The estyle.com Classic lost one of
its top attractions Tuesday morning when third-seeded Monica Seles
withdrew from the tournament, citing a strained left forearm.
</P>
<P>
   Seles said that she injured her arm in practice last Thursday,
three days before she lost to Venus Williams in the final of the
Acura Classic.
</P>
<P>
   ``It all started last week in San Diego with blisters on my left
hand that limited my practice,'' said Seles, who is expected to
continue playing next week in Montreal. ``Due to the blisters, I
was forced to adjust my grip, which caused the strain in my
forearm.''
</P>
<P>
   Seles' place in the second round was taken by American Kristina
Brandi, who lost in the final round of qualifying on Monday. Brandi
will face Russia's Elena Dementieva in the second round.
</P>
<P>
   __ Tough times: It's been a difficult week for Nathalie Tauziat,
who was eliminated from the tournament Tuesday, one day after she
learned that her appeal to join France's Olympic team had been
denied.
</P>
<P>
   Tauziat, the author of a recently published book about life on
the women's tour, has become a polarized figure and the object of
much ire on the circuit. She claims that politics, not performance,
led to her being overlooked during Olympic selections.
</P>
<P>
   The French Tennis Federation denied Tauziat's appeal, and the
player now plans to take her case to the International Tennis
Federation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't really shocked,'' Tauziat said. ``France is very
political and they never change a decision when they make it.''
</P>
<P>
   Tauziat, 32, is considering retiring at the end of the year and
is ranked No. 8 in the world, highest among Frenchwomen.
</P>
<P>
   __ Here comes the bride: Arantxa Sanchez-Vicario of Spain
defeated her doubles partner, Barbara Schett of Austria, 6-4, 6-1
in her first match following her marriage last month.
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez-Vicario, whose wedding made front-page news in Spanish
newspapers, had not played since Wimbledon. She lost the first
three games of the first set against Schett but won 12 of the final
14 games and looked sharp.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes it's not how you start, it's how you finish,''
Sanchez-Vicario said. ``This was the first match after a long break
for me. I even got to spend a few days with my husband.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez-Vicario, who will turn 29 in December, is at a crucial
point in her career. She is capable of playing high-level tennis,
as she proved by reaching the semifinals of the French Open earlier
this year, but she has slipped from the short list of the world's
elite.
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez-Vicario said her marriage will not impact her future in
tennis, but the future is clearly on her mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as I feel strong and ready to play my best, I'll be
out there,'' Sanchez-Vicario said. ``When I don't feel motivated
anymore, then I will leave.''
</P>
</TEXT>
