<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECO-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUSTAINABLE-WOOD PRODUCTS GROWING INTO BIG BUSINESS 
</HEADLINE>
   By GLEN MARTIN  
 c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Sustainable wood products _ anything made from
trees logged in a manner certified as environmentally sound _ have
been in fashion during the past few years, comparable to the
interest in heirloom tomatoes or hemp linen.
</P>
<P>
   No longer. Sustainable wood is now big business, and it marks a
melding of commercial timber production and rigorous environmental
standards that could change the way forests are managed and homes
are built.
</P>
<P>
   The movement says you can have your cake and eat it too _ or at
least, have plywood, wood-frame homes and wooden furniture as well
as healthy, biologically diverse commercial forests.
</P>
<P>
   Leading the trend is Home Depot, the biggest retail purveyor of
construction materials in the country. It agreed last year to phase
out the sale of products made from trees logged in an
environmentally dubious fashion.
</P>
<P>
   The behemoth retailer was recently joined in its
sustainable-wood pledge by Kaufman and Broad, one of the country's
biggest home builders.
</P>
<P>
   And yesterday, Lowe's Home Improvement Warehouse, another
do-it-yourself megastore chain, upped the ante. The company
instituted an immediate ban on lumber from the threatened Great
Bear Rainforest in British Columbia. It also said it will phase out
wood products from other endangered forests and give strong
preference to buying environmentally certified wood.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really taking off,'' said Kate Heaton, a senior forestry
specialist with the National Resources Defense Council, an
environmental lobbying and litigation group. ``A couple of years
ago, it wasn't clear whether it would take hold. Now we know it's
here to stay.''
</P>
<P>
   Sustainable wood has caught the fancy of some important players
_ most notably corporate retailers.
</P>
<P>
   After months of protests in front of its stores, Home Depot said
last year that it would phase out products from endangered forest
ecosystems by 2002 and give preference to wood products certified
by the Forest Stewardship Council.
</P>
<P>
   ``That had tremendous impact,'' said Heaton. ``If there was one
event that really gave the movement serious credibility, that was
it. Now, we're seeing a lot of big corporations jumping on board.''
</P>
<P>
   Kimberly Woodbury, the manager of environmental programs for
Home Depot, said the company was not driven to its decision by the
protests.
</P>
<P>
   Woodbury said company executives began talking with
certified-wood proponents in 1993 and joined the Certified Forest
Products Council in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a sound business decision for a variety of
reasons,'' said Woodbury. ``Certification is an excellent tool
retailers can use to demonstrate corporate social commitment and
educate our customers about the importance of sustainable wood
sources. We're finding that customers may not shop specifically for
the (certified) logo, but it increases their satisfaction with the
products.''
</P>
<P>
   Environmentally certified wood is certainly enjoying a vogue in
the Bay Area, if an exhibit at San Francisco International Airport
is any indication.
</P>
<P>
   This week, the world's largest sustainable-wood veneer wall _ a
whopping 670 by 38 feet _ was displayed at the airport's new
international terminal along with a collection of products made
from eco-friendly lumber.
</P>
<P>
   The foremost certification group is the Forest Stewardship
Council, an organization founded in 1993 and based in Oaxaca,
Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``They appoint the certifying organizations which do the actual
work of evaluating timber operations,'' said Heaton. ``So far,
there are nine certifiers worldwide, two in the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of ECO09 () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  One of the U.S. certifiers is Scientific Certification Systems,
based in Oakland. The other, a Vermont group called SmartWood,
maintains a partnership with another California organization, the
Institute for Sustainable Forestry in Willits, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Certification is now occurring in both equatorial tropical
forests and temperate coastal forests such as those found in
Northern California and the Pacific Northwest, said Peter Nowack,
the director of marketing and communications for the Certified
Forest Products Council, a nonprofit group that disseminates
information on environmentally certified forestry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ultimately, boreal forests (located in interior regions at
extreme northern or southern latitudes) will be included in the
process as well,'' said Nowack.
</P>
<P>
   Achieving certification is not particularly easy.
</P>
<P>
   The stewardship council applies 10 principles and 52 criteria in
its evaluations, said Nowack, ``but they all focus on three basic
areas. The first determines if forest management is environmentally
responsible; the second determines if it is socially responsible to
the people who live and work in the forest; and the third looks at
the long-term economic viability of the management plans.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, 50 million acres of commercial timberland have been
certified by the council worldwide, with 6 million of that total
located in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   That may seem like a lot _ but it's the merest fraction of the
world's commercial woodlands.
</P>
<P>
   Timber industry giant Sierra Pacific Industries, for example,
owns 1.5 million acres of commercial forest in California alone _
fully 1 percent of the state's surface area.
</P>
<P>
   While many retailers and public-works boosters are charmed by
environmentally certified forestry, the same can't necessarily be
said of U.S. timber producers, many of whom note they are already
adhering to some of the strictest environmental standards in the
world.
</P>
<P>
   ``The California forestry practices rules are already extremely
tough,'' said Tim Feller, a district manager for Sierra Pacific
Industries. ``It's gotten to the point that it's very difficult for
us to compete with international producers who face far less in the
way of environmental restrictions, such as Russia, New Zealand,
South American countries and Canada. Last year wasn't a very
profitable one for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Feller said Sierra Pacific subscribes to the Sustainable
Forestry Initiative, a kind of timber and paper industry analogue
to the Forest Stewardship Council.
</P>
<P>
   While the initiative's requirements don't involve certification
and aren't as rigorous as those of the stewardship council, Feller
maintained it promotes healthy woodlands.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a rubber stamp,'' Feller said. ``I'm aware of six
companies that have already been booted out because they couldn't
meet the standards. Your records are reviewed, and there's
on-the-ground inspections to make sure archaeology sites,
watersheds and wildlife are protected, and there's good utilization
of all the harvested wood.''
</P>
<P>
   The stewardship council and the forestry initiative are ``two
different cars taking the same road,'' said Feller. ``Maybe one's
faster and one's slower, but they're both headed to the same
place.''
</P>
<P>
   Nowack, however, takes issue with that metaphor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sierra Pacific is typical of the forest products industry, in
that they're resistant to the principles of the Forest Stewardship
Council,'' he said. ``The timber industry is still very powerful,
and they're certainly exerting their influence. On the other hand,
the more consumer and corporate demand there is for (certified
forestry) products, the more we get the industry's attention.''
</P>
<P>
   Nowack said while there is no longer any danger of sustainable
forestry fading away, big questions remain about the actual
definition of the practice.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 2 of ECO09 () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  ``It comes down to whose standards will prevail,'' he said,
``those of the stewardship council or those of the timber industry.
One will ultimately become the gold standard, though we may
eventually see some kind of tiered system.''
</P>
<P>
   Right now, said Woodbury, the biggest priority is getting more
certified wood into the pipeline.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of progress has been made, but only about 5 percent of
the wood fiber on the market is from certified sources,'' she said.
``We have to keep our noses to the grindstone and get more tangible
certified products into the stores.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail Glen Martin at martingl(at)sfgate.com.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 3 of ECO09 () &QL;
</P>
<P>
   END OF STORY  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
