<SLUG> BC-NBCI-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 S.F.'S NBC INTERNET SLASHING STAFF BY 170  &HT;     By VERNE KOPYTOFF  
 c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ NBC Internet, the San Francisco online media
firm, said yesterday that it is cutting 170 jobs, nearly 20 percent
of its staff, in an effort to reduce costs.
</P>
<P>
   The layoffs will affect workers in all departments, according to
Robert Silverman, a spokesman for NBC Internet, one of the Bay
Area's biggest Internet firms. A majority of the layoffs will be at
the company's San Francisco headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   NBC Internet's job reductions come amid workforce retrenchments
across the Internet industry. The company's cuts are among the
largest this year.
</P>
<P>
   The layoffs follow a quarter in which NBC Internet warned that
it would report bigger-than-expected losses and suffered a dramatic
decline in its stock price, which is now nearly 90 percent off its
high at the beginning of the year. In June, the company implemented
a hiring freeze instead of continuing the rapid growth it had
forecast for the rest of the year.
</P>
<P>
   NBC Internet's stock price was unchanged yesterday at $11. Its
shares are down nearly 90 percent from its January high of $106.13.
News of the layoffs came after the market closed.
</P>
<P>
   The firings will reduce NBC Internet's workforce from 850 to 680
by the end of the year. An unknown number of other workers will be
reassigned.
</P>
<P>
   ``NBC Internet is not a player yet,'' said David Card, an
analyst with Jupiter Communications, a market research firm. ``They
are not one of the big three portals and they haven't
differentiated themselves well.''
</P>
<P>
   In June, NBC Internet, which is 40 percent owned by General
Electric's NBC, was the ninth-most-popular Web property, according
to Media Metrix, the online ratings service. It trails far behind
competing Web portals such as Yahoo, Microsoft and Lycos.
</P>
<P>
   Card questioned NBC Internet's efforts to create a large catalog
of television programs for viewers to watch on their personal
computers. He said such programming, aimed at users who have
high-speed connections that allow better video quality, has a very
limited audience.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, NBC Internet has suffered an identity crisis with
its disparate Web sites, including Xoom.com, a Web page building
service, and Snap.com, an Internet portal. The company is trying to
address the confusion by combining those sites under the portal
NBCi.com. this fall.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of NBCI09 (109085 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  NBC Internet recently acquired Flyswat.com, an online links
service, GlobalBrain.net, a search service, and Allbusiness.com, a
portal for small businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Silverman, the NBC Internet spokesman, said the job cuts will
make the company more competitive while maintaining its health. He
said that the firm is healthy, with nearly $357 million in cash.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail Verne Kopytoff at verne(at)sfgate.com.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
COL. 2 of NBCI09 (109085 ) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   END OF STORY  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
