<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SWIMPRE-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN A WORD, THEY'D LOVE THIRD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ Track and field athletes in this country feel
sorry for themselves because the top three finishers at the Olympic
selection meet qualify for the Summer Games and everybody else goes
home, no matter how fast they've run in the past or how far they've
thrown.
</P>
<P>
   Sorry, but they're not going to get much sympathy from their
swimming brethren. The process by which the U.S. swimming team for
next month's Sydney Olympics will be chosen over the next eight
days is so cruel it makes track and field's look kind.
</P>
<P>
   Only the top two finishers in each individual event earn an
Olympic berth (swimmers lost a third Olympic entry in each event in
1984 when synchronized swimming was added to the aquatics program).
</P>
<P>
   The loneliest number? It's the number 3. Just ask former
Stanford star Jenny Thompson, who was pegged to win as many as
seven gold medals at the 1996 Summer Games.
</P>
<P>
   That was before the sprinter traveled to the Trials, came down
with insomnia and sleepwalked through the meet, finishing no higher
than third in any of her four individual events. She made it to
Atlanta but in a diminished role, as a member of three relays.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the Olympic Trials, first and second are equal in my
mind,'' Thompson said earlier this week. ``If you're third, it's
just as good as last.''
</P>
<P>
   Thompson put off retirement to make amends for 1996 and again
will contend for an Olympic berth in as many as four individual
events and three relays starting today at the Indiana
University-Purdue University Natatorium.
</P>
<P>
   She'll require 12 races to qualify in her four individual
events; for the first time in the history of the Trials, semifinal
heats have been added to all events shorter than 400 meters,
meaning a swimmer will need three strong swims spread out over two
days to qualify for the Olympics (before it was two races,
contested on the same day).
</P>
<P>
   Thompson will lead a women's sprint brigade _ call it the Space
Cowgirls _ that is challenging both the record books and age-old
assumptions. Thompson, Dara Torres, Amy Van Dyken and Angel Martino
have 120 years and 20 Olympic medals among them. They are at the
front line of an ongoing war waged to make swimming lucrative
enough to pursue as a career and not just a means of paying for
college.
</P>
<P>
   Torres, 33, a graduate of the Westlake School, is swimming
faster than she ever has and so is the 27-year-old Thompson. Every
tie they race, they raise the ceiling on women's competitive
careers.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it wouldn't be swimming without a head-turning
performance by a precocious teen. In 1992 it was Anita Nall; in
1996, Irvine's Amanda Beard. This year the chlorine queen of the
teen set could be 14-year-old backstroker Diana MacManus or
16-year-old breaststroker Megan Quann.
</P>
<P>
   The leading man of these Trials is expected to be Lenny
Krayzelburg of Studio City and USC. Krayzelburg, 24, was a surprise
fifth-place finisher in the 200-meter backstroke at the 1996
Trials. Four years later he is the world-record holder in the 100
and 200 backstrokes and, hence, the overwhelming favorite in both
events.
</P>
<P>
   Krayzelburg might not be an Olympic Trials winner yet, but he
already has his breakfast of champions picked out. Starting next
week his image will grace boxes of Kellogg's Crispix cereal.
</P>
<P>
   Hovering in the wings is 17-year-old Aaron Peirsol of Irvine,
who would love to be a cereal killer. He might look to Tom Malchow
for some pointers; in 1996 Malchow shaved four seconds off his best
time in the 200-meter butterfly and won the Trials, displacing from
the Olympic team former world record holder Melvin Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   In 1972 Kurt Krumpholz broke the world record in the 400
freestyle in the heats and then finished out of the top three in
the final and didn't make the Olympic team. So it's not just
posturing when Krayzelburg and Malchow, who broke the world record
in the 200 butterfly in June, profess to be on edge just like the
meet's other 1,307 participants.
</P>
<P>
   ``This meet's unpredictable,'' said Malchow, who graduated from
Michigan last year. ``That's the beauty of sports.''
</P>
<P>
   It's also what makes this meet a beast.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-08-00 2228EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000808.0366 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 22:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6220 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-PUC-SFCHRON &LR;      08-08 1095
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUC-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 REGULATOR CALLS FOR STRICTER OVERSIGHT OF LONG-DISTANCE INDUSTRY  &HT;     By TODD WALLACK 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ California's top utility regulator admitted
yesterday that her agency has done a poor job of reining in abuses
by long-distance telephone companies and vowed to beef up oversight
of the industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need better rules because the rules we have don't work,''
said Loretta Lynch, who became president of the Public Utilities
Commission in March.
</P>
<P>
   Lynch said that the state agency doesn't do enough to identify
and follow up on patterns of abuse by long-distance carriers and
that current regulations have too many loopholes. She also said the
PUC doesn't do enough to resolve customer problems once they
contact the PUC.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to do a whole lot better because we are not doing very
well right now,'' Lynch said, responding to a Chronicle special
report on telecommunications troubles published yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   The report found that customer complaints against long-distance
telephone companies doubled from 1997 to 1999, based on an analysis
of 125,000 grievances filed with the PUC. The articles revealed how
long-distance companies take advantage of loopholes in the rules to
hide many fees.
</P>
<P>
   According to an internal PUC survey, first reported by The
Chronicle yesterday, 4 out of 10 customers who filed a written
grievance with the agency said they were disappointed with how the
PUC handled the complaint. Critics say the PUC would have found
even more frustrated consumers had it also polled people who filed
complaints by telephone. Lynch said she was appalled to learn the
survey was so narrowly focused.
</P>
<P>
   But Lynch said changes in PUC enforcement are already in the
works. Fellow Commissioner Carl Wood has proposed a
telecommunications ``Bill of Rights,'' which would require
companies to clearly spell out all fees and requirements to
consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Lynch added that she hopes to find a new consumer services chief
who can more aggressively enforce current rules. She said she
demoted William Schulte, the current chief, and his key deputy
partly because the agency is doing a subpar job of handling
complaints.
</P>
<P>
   PUC Commissioner Henry Duque said he is also concerned about the
complaint process.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a lot of room for improvement,'' Duque said. He said
he frequently hears from people who have filed complaints via
telephone ``and nothing has happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Chris Witteman, an attorney with the Greenlining Institute, a
San Francisco consumer watchdog group, said The Chronicle's stories
point out that the PUC isn't doing enough to crack down on
companies after spotting a pattern of complaints.
</P>
<P>
   ``We continue to have serious doubts about the commitment of the
PUC to consumer protection,'' Witteman said. ``Many, many
misleading advertisements and hidden charges go unchallenged.''
</P>
<P>
   State lawmakers had mixed reaction to the stories.
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Richard Mountjoy, R-Monrovia, said he hears similar
complaints about all state agencies. Mountjoy says his staffers
spend much of their time helping constituents cut through red tape.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say the same would hold true of any government
bureaucracy that tends to move rather slowly,'' said Mountjoy, vice
chair of the Senate committee on Energy, Utilities and
Communications. But if state lawmakers receives a flood of
complaints about the PUC, he said legislators ``will probably call
the PUC on the carpet.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of PUC09 (21106 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  Assemblyman Anthony Pescetti, R-Rancho Cordova, vice chairman of
the state Assembly committee on Utilities and Commerce, said he
could empathize with consumers based on his own problems with
long-distance companies. One firm, Global Crossing, sent him a bill
even though he never signed up for the service.
</P>
<P>
   But Pescetti said he believes the PUC is already in the process
of adopting tougher rules through the Bill of Rights proposal. He
said he doesn't think the legislature should pass additional laws
unless the PUC asks for an ``assist.''
</P>
<P>
   Assemblyman Roderick Wright, D-Los Angeles, chairman of the
Assembly utilities committee, also said he believes the PUC is on
the right track.
</P>
<P>
   He pointed out, for instance, that the PUC and Attorney General
Bill Lockyer teamed up last month to sue WorldCom, the long
distance company that received the most complaints last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we need to change the laws, we can do so,'' Wright said.
``But it's too early right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Wright also noted that slamming, or switching customers' service
without permission, and cramming unauthorized charges onto
customers' bills are already illegal. The PUC, he said, is simply
trying to ``catch up'' with the surge of complaints.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday, both the PUC and The Chronicle received an increase
in calls and e-mail from customers who had problems with their
telephone bills.
</P>
<P>
   Vera Pearce in San Francisco said she was stunned to find a $31
charge for a three-minute collect call from Portland, Ore., though
she distinctly remembers refusing the call. ``That's $600 an
hour,'' she said. ``I have never heard of such a thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Hector Flamenco of San Francisco said his bills soared because
of hidden fees after he signed up for service with NOS
Communications of Las Vegas. The Chronicle highlighted NOS in one
of its articles.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a nightmare,'' Flamenco said. ``I finally got rid of
them.''
</P>
<P>
   NOS did not return a call seeking comment. But WorldCom and AT&AMP;T
empathized they are working hard to reduce complaints.
</P>
<P>
   WorldCom, which merged with MCI two years ago, said it now
requires sales representatives to sign a written code of conduct,
gives telemarketers financial incentives to avoid slamming or other
misconduct and randomly monitors calls. So far this year,
complaints to the PUC about the company are down 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The story was very comprehensive in describing the current
situation,'' said WorldCom spokeswoman Leland Prince, ``but the
piece that was missing in our mind was all of the improvements we
are making.''
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T spokeswoman Jane Young also pointed out that the company
recently ranked No. 1 in a recent JD Powers and Associates study on
high-volume customers, though it didn't score nearly as well among
customers who make fewer calls.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of the situations you've mentioned in your series . . .
show us that we still have work to do.'' she said. ``We are
addressing that.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail Todd Wallack at todd(at)sfgate.com.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
COL. 2 of PUC09 (21106 ) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   END OF STORY  &QL;
</P>
