A6222 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      08-08 0465
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAMPAIGN NEWS AND NOTES 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MAKING UP FOR THE PAST
</P>
<P>
   In a step toward atoning for what many Democrats agree was one
of their party's biggest political blunders, the party has invited
the sons of the late Robert P. Casey to speak at next week's
convention in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Casey, the former governor of Pennsylvania, had asked to speak
at the 1992 Democratic convention in New York and deliver a report
opposing the party's platform, which called ``reproductive choice''
a ``fundamental right.'' But the nominees _ Bill Clinton and Al
Gore _ wanted the convention to send a message of unity for
abortion rights, and Casey was barred from speaking.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with the approval of Gore, this year's nominee, the party
has invited two of Casey's sons _ Robert P. Casey Jr., who is
facing re-election as Pennsylvania's auditor general, and Patrick
Casey, a candidate for Congress from Scranton _ to participate in a
video tribute to their father at the convention.
</P>
<P>
   GORE WINS UAW BACKING
</P>
<P>
   The United Auto Workers announced Tuesday that it would endorse
Vice President Al Gore for president, ending its feud with him over
trade and giving him a boost in Michigan and other industrial
Midwestern states.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic officials said Gore and the union president, Stephen
P. Yokich, who had flirted with Ralph Nader, the Green Party
candidate, had spoken in recent months in an effort to iron out
differences over trade and environmental issues. Among other
things, the union succeeded in adding language to the platform
saying that Gore would push for more fuel-efficient cars ``in a way
that preserves and creates jobs for American workers, and delivers
products that consumers want to buy.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore will travel to Michigan, which has 450,000 current and
retired U.A.W. members, on Friday to accept the endorsement.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GOP FIRES BACK
</P>
<P>
   The Republican Party has begun running its first attack ad, a
30-second commercial accusing Vice President Al Gore of hypocrisy
on environmental issues. The spot claims that Gore has been
distorting Gov. George W. Bush's environmental record in Texas,
and, citing a recent biography, reports that Gore ``has allowed
mining companies to mine zinc from his property'' in Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   Republican officials are spending $3.7 million to run their new
spot in 17 states: Arkansas, Florida, Georgia, Iowa, Illinois,
Kentucky, Louisiana, Maine, Maryland, Michigan, Missouri, New
Mexico, Ohio, Oregon, Pennsylvania, Washington and Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   WEDNESDAY'S SCHEDULES
</P>
<P>
   GEORGE W. BUSH _ Oxnard, Calif.; San Luis Obispo, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   DICK CHENEY _ St. Louis; Grand Rapids, Mich.; Columbus, Ohio
</P>
<P>
   AL GORE, JOSEPH LIEBERMAN _ Carthage, Tenn.; Stamford, Conn.
</P>
</TEXT>
