<SLUG> BC-WEST-FIRES-CLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON VISITS WILDFIRE FRONT LINES 
</HEADLINE>
  (With WEST-FIRES) 
 By MARC LACEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BURGDORF JUNCTION, Idaho _ From above, the scene resembled a war
zone: pillars of smoke, flashes of fire and vast expanses of
charred remains.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a big plume of smoke over there,'' said President
Clinton, who surveyed the devastation of the Burgdorf Junction
fire, one of hundreds sweeping across the West, from his
helicopter, Marine One, yesterday morning. ``It looks like a bomb
going off.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton visited the front lines of the fire, which has raced
through 25,000 acres and become one of the largest blazes ravaging
the Western states, to rally firefighters engaged in what amounts
to a military-style operation. Their weapons are chain saws,
helicopters loaded with water buckets and pulaskis, the combination
ax and hoe used to dig containment trenches through the combustible
trees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wanted to get in the plane this morning and fly out
here to say thanks,'' said Clinton, who shared a bag lunch with the
firefighters in a mess hall in the woods.
</P>
<P>
   Supporting the professional firefighters are 500 Army troops
from the Fourth Infantry Division at Fort Hood, who have traded in
their self-propelled howitzers for axes and are relying heavily on
their military training.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is as dangerous as it gets,'' said Lt. Col. Darryl A.
Williams, a former military aide to the president who now leads
soldiers here. ``No one is shooting at us, but the fire is a worthy
adversary.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton announced the release of $150 million in emergency funds
to continue the fight. But the money will go quickly. The cost of
the firefighting effort is more than $10 million a day.
</P>
<P>
   Sam Wilbanks of the United States Forest Service spent a recent
night on the front lines of the Burgdorf Junction fire, which was
started on July 9.
</P>
<P>
   After long days of digging ditches in the thin mountain air,
firefighters often camp within sight of the enemy. Wilbanks said
they rolled out their bedding on the rocky terrain and did
something that seems odd under the circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lit a little fire to stay warm,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-08-00 2235EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
