<SLUG> BC-CISCO-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CISCO SALES RISE 61 PERCENT IN FOURTH QUARTER 
</HEADLINE>
  By LAWRENCE M. FISHER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Cisco Systems Inc. on Tuesday reported a 61
percent gain in sales for its fiscal fourth quarter, as the company
continued to be the leading supplier of the necessary hardware for
the build-up of the Internet. It was the company's 10th consecutive
quarter of accelerating year-over-year revenue growth.
</P>
<P>
   Excluding acquisition-related charges, Cisco earnings exceeded
analysts' published estimates by a penny a share.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, Cisco said its No. 2 executive, Donald J. Listwin,
was resigning to lead an unnamed company, in which Cisco is a
minority shareholder. Listwin, whose title was executive vice
president, is leaving after 10 years with the company, where he was
responsible for Cisco's New World business strategy and led its
service provider and consumer businesses as well as corporate
marketing.
</P>
<P>
   Cisco reported its results after the close of the market. Cisco
shares closed at $65.50, down 75 cents, in Nasdaq trading.
</P>
<P>
   For the quarter ended July 29, Cisco reported earnings of $796
million, or 11 cents a diluted share, up 32 percent compared with
$605 million, or 8 cents per share, for the period a year ago.
Sales rose 61 percent to $5.72 billion, compared with $3.56 billion
in the fourth quarter of fiscal 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Cisco said its pro forma net income, which excludes the effects
of acquisition charges, payroll tax on stock option exercises and
net gains realized on minority investments, was $1.20 billion, or
16 cents a diluted share, for the fourth quarter of fiscal 2000,
compared with $710 million, or 10 cents per share, for the fourth
quarter of fiscal 1999, increases of 69 percent and 60 percent,
respectively. Analysts had expected Cisco to earn 15 cents a share,
according to First Call.
</P>
<P>
   ``The quarter, as expected, looks very strong,'' said Greg
Geiling, an analyst with J.P. Morgan. Revenue growth of 61 percent
year over year, and 16 percent over the immediately previous
quarter, ``are tremendous numbers for a company this size,'' he
said. ``And it looks like very balanced growth across all the
business lines, which is just what you like to see.''
</P>
<P>
   During the quarter, Cisco completed the acquisitions of
Atlantech Technologies Ltd., JetCell Inc., PentaCom Ltd., Qeyton
Systems and Seagull Semiconductor Ltd. for a combined purchase
price, including assumed liabilities, of approximately $1.39
billion, and took one-time charges of $461 million, or
approximately 6 cents per share, on an after-tax basis, as
write-offs of purchased in-process research and development.
Additionally, Cisco completed the acquisitions of ArrowPoint
Communications Inc., the InfoGear Technology Corp. and SightPath
Inc., which were accounted for as poolings of interests.
</P>
<P>
   ``We predicted five years ago that we were in the midst of a
second Industrial Revolution that would determine the prosperity of
companies, countries, and individuals. Today, the Internet
continues to drive the strongest U.S. economy in history,'' John
Chambers, Cisco's president and chief executive, said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see no indications in the marketplace that the radical
Internet business transformation in practices like customer
service, supply-chain management, employee training, empowerment,
and e-commerce that is taking place around the world today is
slowing _ in fact, we believe it is accelerating globally,''
Chambers said.
</P>
<P>
   But Chambers also said that Cisco is experiencing some of the
problems that come with explosive growth. Particularly in new
product areas, the company has been constrained by shortages of key
components, and is taking steps to increase order volume with its
major suppliers. Lead times on its own products reached what
Chambers called ``an undesirable peak'' in June, but he added that
he expected improvements in manufacturing management to return
these times to normal by the end of the calendar year.
</P>
<P>
   For the year, Cisco reported earnings of $2.67 billion or 36
cents a diluted share, compared with $2.02 billion, or 29 cents a
share for fiscal 1999. Sales rose 55 percent to $18.93 billion,
compared with $12.17 billion for fiscal 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Cisco's pro forma net income was $3.91 billion, or 53 cents a
diluted share, for fiscal 2000, compared with pro forma net income
of $2.52 billion or 36 cents a share for fiscal 1999, increases of
56 percent and 47 percent, respectively.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
