<HEADER>
A6225 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-POLICE-SAFIR-ART-N     08-08 0610
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-POLICE-SAFIR-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAFIR FORMALLY RESIGNS; PLAUDITS AND CRITICISM FOLLOW 
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: Photo NYT18 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By C.J. CHIVERS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Police Commissioner Howard Safir formally announced
his resignation Tuesday, relinquishing command of the largest
police department in the nation to work as a salaried consultant
for ChoicePoint Inc., a corporate investigations firm in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The commissioner said his final day at 1 Police Plaza would be
Aug. 18, ending nearly four and a half years as one of the city's
most prominent officials.
</P>
<P>
   Safir, who has supervised the New York Police Department during
a period when crime declined markedly but relations between the
police and many minority residents seemed to sour, appeared with
his wife, Carol, in a ceremonial chamber in City Hall.
</P>
<P>
   He suggested that his legacy was apparent on the city's streets,
in what he described as the professionalism of police officers and
their success in rolling back crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they have done for this city is not only evident in the
fact that we are not only the No. 1 tourist destination in the
United States, but also evident in every neighborhood _ whether
it's Brooklyn or Queens or Staten Island or the Bronx _ where crime
is the lowest it has been in three decades,'' Safir said.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, who leaves office in 16 months, would
not discuss whom he might select to replace Safir.
</P>
<P>
   Even as the City Hall ceremony for Safir was ending Tuesday,
other city officials and Safir's critics were calling news
conferences of their own, at which they offered a starkly different
interpretation of the commissioner's record.
</P>
<P>
   City Council Speaker Peter Vallone said Safir had lost his way
by focusing too much on the statistical measures of police
productivity instead of on the impact some of his policies had in
the city's neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was an overemphasis on statistics,'' Vallone said. ``The
next commissioner should be concerned about numbers and about
people.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Al Sharpton said Safir's legacy was one of tolerating
violent officers and encouraging aggressive tactics, a combination
that sometimes ended in tragedy, as in the station house torture of
Abner Louima and the deaths of four unarmed black men _ the most
highly publicized being Amadou Diallo and Patrick Dorismond _ who
were fatally shot by the police during one 13-month period.
</P>
<P>
   ``He presided over some of the worst, most graphic police
brutality cases in memory,'' Sharpton said. ``His leaving will not
cause any regret at all in our community.''
</P>
<P>
   Consistent with past form, Safir seemed unfazed by his critics,
and even eager to dismiss them. As he left City Hall, where aides
of Mark Green, the public advocate, were distributing fliers
announcing a news conference at which Green later criticized him,
Safir was asked for his feelings. He said, ``Mark Green is a joke,
he has always been a joke, and he continues to be a joke.''
</P>
<P>
   Safir, 58, announced in May that he was suffering from prostate
cancer. But he said Tuesday that his illness was treatable and that
his health had no bearing on his decision to resign.
</P>
<P>
   ChoicePoint, a publicly traded corporation with 4,000 employees
in 22 cities, provides various forms of intelligence to government
and corporate clients, including results of employees' drug tests
and background screening of potential vendors. It is one of the
country's largest pre-employment screeners, with gross revenues of
$430 million last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-08-00 2239EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000808.0372 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 22:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6228 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-GORE-SELECTION-1STLD-     08-08 1186
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-SELECTION-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN SELECTING A NO. 2, NO DETAIL TOO SMALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: SUBS 5th graf, George Mitchell ..., with Gore campaign
rejecting Graham because of diary entries, deletes redundant
Dukakis material lower down; tightens elsewhere, subs overline.) 
 (ART ADV: Photo NYT15 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By DAVID BARSTOW with KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE, Tenn. _ In the days before Gov. George W. Bush
announced his selection of Dick Cheney as his running mate, Vice
President Al Gore and his advisers sensed an unexpected
opportunity. Aboard Air Force II and in Gore's campaign
headquarters here, there was a consensus that Bush and his aides
had bungled their selection process, that the Republicans had come
across as leak-prone, rushed and uncharacteristically amateurish.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign swiftly set out to exploit this perceived
weakness by trying to turn the running mate selection process
itself into a political weapon. With lock-step discipline, Gore's
spokesmen derided Bush for conducting his search ``like a
fraternity rush.'' They presented Gore's selection process as
dignified, orderly, pander-free and, above all else, private.
</P>
<P>
   But the strict secrecy imposed by the Gore campaign shielded
from public view an intensely political, highly competitive and
sometimes frenetic selection process.
</P>
<P>
   Again and again, Gore's selection process was shaped by gritty
political concerns that had little bearing on what he had
repeatedly described as his single most important criterion for a
running mate _ someone possessed of the experience and ability to
assume the presidency if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   George Mitchell, the former Senate majority leader, for example,
never made it to the short list, at least in part because of his
work as a lobbyist for the tobacco industry, people involved in the
selection process said. Sen. Evan Bayh of Indiana faced opposition
from groups that support abortion rights and gave his assent to a
campaign aimed at countering criticism over his voting record on
abortion, but faded nonetheless. Sen. Bob Graham of Florida was
hurt by his habit of filling diaries with mundane aspects of his
day, a practice some in the Gore campaign worried would be viewed
as eccentric.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Democratic officials said, Bush's repeated
efforts to tarnish Gore with resurrected memories of President
Clinton's affair with a White House intern elevated the standing of
Gore's eventual choice, Sen. Joseph Lieberman, the first Democrat
to condemn Clinton's affair from the Senate floor.
</P>
<P>
   The enforced secrecy _ potential running mates were warned not
to divulge details about their contacts with the Gore vetting teams
_ also served to obscure lobbying efforts by a select group of
well-connected political professionals. Several of Gore's campaign
consultants had also worked for those on his list of potential vice
presidents, and these men and women fought hard for their favored
picks. One adviser, Bob Shrum, has worked with several of the
potential candidates but argued for one of them, Sen. John Edwards
of North Carolina. Another adviser, Michael Whouley, argued for his
former boss, Sen. John Kerry of Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Only last week, Al From, president of the Democratic Leadership
Council and an influential voice among moderate Democrats, lobbied
both Gore and his campaign chairman, William Daley, on behalf of
Lieberman, who is the chairman of the council.
</P>
<P>
   As with any presidential candidate, the choice of running mate
is an important and telling decision. Gore's aides argued that the
way he went about picking Lieberman illustrated several of the vice
president's strengths, most notably his meticulous, rigorous
preparation before arriving at major decisions. Gore, they said,
has raised vetting to new levels of thoroughness and inclusiveness.
</P>
<P>
   Although Gore announced in April that former Secretary of State
Warren Christopher would lead his selection team, Gore actually
began to organize his selection process months before. His vetting
teams were led by such veteran lawyers as Charles F.C. Ruff, the
former White House counsel who defended Clinton during his
impeachment trial. The team that vetted Lieberman, led by Jamie
Gorelick, a former deputy attorney general, went so far as to
review the more than 800 legal opinions that Lieberman rendered
when he was attorney general of Connecticut from 1983 to 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Sheldon Cohen, a former IRS commissioner, was drafted to review
tax returns. Gore also instructed Christopher to consult freely and
frequently with an informal group that consisted of Labor Secretary
Alexis M. Herman, former Housing Secretary Henry Cisneros, Sen. Jay
Rockefeller of West Virginia and Gen. John M. Shalikashvili, the
former chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``I gained added respect for his values and judgment,''
Christopher said when asked in an interview what he had learned
about Gore during the search process. ``I found he went about the
process seriously and conscientiously.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans drew different lessons from Gore's method of picking
a running mate. While praising Lieberman as a man of integrity,
they said that Gore's selection process underscored what they
described as his penchant for tactical ruthlessness and a tendency
to shade the truth for political gain.
</P>
<P>
   Ari Fleischer, a spokesman for Bush, dismissed the notion that
the Gore decision-making process was more orderly and dignified
than Bush's process. He said that much of what Gore did, including
his mention of a ``wild card'' candidate, was theater designed for
public consumption. He said that the important difference between
the two campaigns was that the Bush campaign had greeted the choice
of Lieberman graciously, while the Gore campaign had attacked
Cheney.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're missing the whole big picture on where the public is
about attacking everything,'' Fleischer said.
</P>
<P>
   One Democratic lawyer who has guided potential running mates
through both Gore's vetting routine and Clinton's in 1992
complained that this year's process was at times ``delayed and
disorganized.'' Just five days before his self-imposed deadline,
Gore said that he had narrowed his list to six. Yet one finalist,
House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt of Missouri, had not been
vetted _ a task that had taken lawyers weeks of painstaking work
for other finalists.
</P>
<P>
   Such was the sophistication of Gore's selection stagecraft that
even leaks were orchestrated for maximum effect. Eager to win over
women, Gore had emphasized that several women were under strong
consideration. Last week, as interest was peaking over Gore's
progress, his campaign let it be known that one of his finalists
was Gov. Jeanne Shaheen of New Hampshire, even though she had
already said she would turn down the job, and even though one
person involved in Gore's screening process said that she had not
been under serious consideration for some time.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, before a single primary or caucus had been contested,
Gore had already started thinking about running mates. By October
his campaign chairman at the time, Tony Coelho, had contacted
Christopher and asked him to start thinking about how to organize a
search.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher, 74, was a logical choice. A man who exudes tact and
discretion, Christopher had led Clinton's search in 1992, and
Clinton's selection of Gore was widely regarded as a turning point
in the campaign. But Christopher was well aware of the perils of
the selection process. A hasty vetting job in 1984 left Walter
Mondale's campaign bogged down for weeks with questions about the
finances of his running mate, Geraldine Ferraro.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody who tries to do this has to read the history and see
the mistakes that were made and try to avoid them,'' Christopher
said. Those lessons, aides said, were central to one of Gore's
primary search objectives _ finding a running mate who could get
off to a fast, clean start, unlike Cheney, for example, who spent
his first week defending his conservative voting record in
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Starting in February, Christopher and Gore began to construct
what Christopher came to call his ``People to Consult List,'' a
roster of senior Democrats that ultimately would grow to 70 names.
The list included nearly a dozen women, 18 members of minority
groups and representatives of several special interest groups. Most
were on the list simply because Gore wanted their advice. But 25 of
the names, including Lieberman's, were considered as potential
running mates.
</P>
<P>
   According to Coelho, the Gore campaign made an overture to Colin
Powell, just as the Clinton campaign had done in 1992. ``He was
indirectly approached to see if he would ever consider a
vice-presidential spot on any ticket,'' he said. But the general
rebuffed the overture and the matter was dropped.
</P>
<P>
   Even as Gore's spokesmen insisted that there was no long list,
no short list, no list at all, Christopher embarked on a series of
interviews to help Gore pare down their list. As a first step, a
team of young Washington lawyers prepared memorandums on the public
careers of the 25 possible candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher visited Lieberman in his Senate office on May 1. In
an interview the next month, Lieberman described his session as
``an out-of-body experience'' for a politician who had once been
too embarrassed to openly admit his ambition to be a senator. That
day, as he faced his old friend _ he calls him Chris _ Lieberman
found himself suddenly confronting the dizzying possibility of
occupying the nation's second highest office.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Chris came here it was the first moment it had any
reality to it,'' he said. ``Somebody said to me: `This is like the
ministry. You're called to the ministry, you don't seek it.'''
</P>
<P>
   By early June, as word of Christopher sightings spread across
Capitol Hill, and as one politician after another coyly confirmed
that yes, they had in fact spoken with him, the speculation was
such that no fewer than 30 Democrats had been named in various news
media reports as under active consideration.
</P>
<P>
   But by that point, Gore had already settled on about a
half-dozen names. He told Christopher to go ahead with full vetting
on this group, which included Lieberman, Shaheen, Edwards,
Gephardt, Bayh and Kerry, Democratic officials said. But even
before the vetting was in full swing, there were indications that
Lieberman was the leader of the pack.
</P>
<P>
   On June 15, the day Daley replaced Coelho as campaign chairman,
his first substantial conversation with Gore quickly turned to the
question of running mates. ``He said, `Joe is really close, he's
really great, what do you think?''' Daley recalled. ``Then he went
into the other candidates, but he was the first one he named.''
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign set about assembling five to seven vetting
teams, each led by a senior lawyer working with a more junior
lawyer. Other lawyers were added as needed to the teams, all of
which reported to James Hamilton, a lawyer with long experience
examining the lives of troubled Washington figures.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton has represented Vince Foster, the deputy White House
counsel who later committed suicide; Dennis DiConcini, the former
senator from Arizona implicated in the Keating Five scandal; and
David Durenberger, the former Minnesota senator who also faced an
ethics inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher gives him perhaps his highest form of praise: ``He
is very discreet.''
</P>
<P>
   The vetters, who like Christopher worked as unpaid volunteers,
gathered boxes of records from each of the finalists _ every vote
ever cast, every press release ever issued, transcripts of
speeches, videotapes of political debates, books they have written,
school transcripts, a lifetime of financial and medical records.
</P>
<P>
   None of the five who made it to the vetting round were
eliminated on the basis of some shocking revelation that emerged
from the records that were handed over to the various vetting
teams. ``The vetting process produces pluses and minuses, but there
was no show stopper,'' Christopher said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the pluses and minuses mattered greatly, and the vetting
process itself, along with the rumor-mill speculation surrounding
it, produced some ugly moments of competition, rivalry and sheer
political spectacle.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   One such instance came in recent weeks. Kerry, a popular and
seasoned politician, was attractive to Gore for many reasons, not
the least of which was that he is a decorated Vietnam war veteran.
But in recent weeks rumors raced through political circles in
Washington and beyond about Kerry's dating habits when he was
divorced years ago. It was a troubling development that took on
added significance given the emphasis at the Republican National
Convention on restoring ``honor and decency'' to the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Gore campaign aides said the rumors had no bearing on the
selection, but on Monday, Kerry told The Boston Globe that Gore's
vetters inquired about that time of his life. ``They asked a couple
of questions from the period when I was single, and I gave them an
explanation,'' he said. ``Three-quarters of the stories that were
written when I was single were not accurate.''
</P>
<P>
   Christopher's queries to special interest groups turned up a
problem for Bayh on one of the touchstone issues of the Democratic
Party _ abortion rights. In early May, Christopher left a telephone
message for Alice Germond, the acting president of the National
Abortion and Reproductive Rights Action League, a group that
closely monitors voting records on abortion issues. When Germond
saw the message, she immediately recognized the purpose of his call
and assembled the abortion voting records of potential running
mates.
</P>
<P>
   When she came to Bayh, she expressed concern about his vote to
ban a late-term abortion procedure that opponents call ``partial
birth abortion.'' Worse yet for Bayh, she and an official from the
National Organization of Women were quoted in a Baltimore Sun
article that suggested that Bayh's ``problematic'' stance on
abortion might make it difficult to mobilize votes from women who
support abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Germond said that her only intent was to
provide unbiased information about the abortion records of every
potential running mate. Even so, Bayh's supporters were furious at
the abortion league and NOW.
</P>
<P>
   ``I assumed they were trying to push Feinstein,'' said Ann
DeLaney, Bayh's former campaign manager, referring to Sen. Dianne
Feinstein of California, one of the women who was mentioned as a
possible vice presidential candidate. ``I was outraged,'' DeLaney
said.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after the Sun story appeared, DeLaney expressed her
anger to Bayh as they went jogging one evening. She said she
discussed her desire to write a letter accusing NARAL and NOW of
distorting what she described as his firm record in favor of
abortion rights. He did not discourage her, she said. Sure enough,
her letter soon appeared in news stories that described how Indiana
women were rallying in defense of Bayh's record on abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Bayh soon found his chances being downgraded in
stories quoting Democratic officials. Meanwhile, Edwards'
background as a trial lawyer who had won millions for consumers
injured by corporate negligence made him an easy fit for Gore's
populist message about taking on major oil and drug companies. And
every time Gore and his spokesmen described Cheney as part of the
Republican ``old guard,'' Edwards' stock appeared to inch higher.
</P>
<P>
   But again, Gore's screening machinery turned up a steady
drumbeat of concern about his relative lack of political experience
as a first-term senator.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those were questions that were asked during the process,''
Edwards readily acknowledged on Monday. ``They're perfectly
reasonable questions.'' The questions only grew louder with the
selection of Cheney, a man with decades of experience at the
highest levels of government.
</P>
<P>
   On Air Force II on July 24, the day before Bush announced his
selection of Cheney, Gore told reporters that Bush's pick probably
would not have an impact on his selection. But behind the scenes,
advisers believed that Cheney's experience had to be accounted for,
and that dynamic favored Lieberman, 58.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the gravitas level, he matches up,'' Christopher said.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Lieberman advocates such as From were making
the argument to the highest levels of the campaign that with
Lieberman's ``seal of approval,'' it would be difficult for Bush to
continue to tar Gore with the president's personal scandal.
</P>
<P>
   But for all the thoroughness of the Gore screening process, his
vetters never did fully explore the possible impact of the largest
question mark over Lieberman _ how voters would react to an
Orthodox Jew on a national ticket. A number of people on
Christopher's consultation list had repeatedly raised Lieberman's
religion as a possible problem. But Gore, who has been criticized
by Republicans for being excessively guided by polls, issued orders
that no steps were to be taken to gauge public reaction to
Lieberman's religion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gore said, 'That's not part of me. That's not part of my
thinking. I exclude that,''' Christopher recalled.
</P>
<P>
   What they did, do, though, was explore dozens of hypothetical
situations to test how Lieberman would respond to potential
conflicts between his observance of the Sabbath and the duties of a
vice president, said Gorelick, who vetted Leiberman, said in an
interview Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had definitely thought through them in the context of the
public life he has led to date,'' she said. ``He has had to vote on
the Sabbath, go to critical meetings on the Sabbath, has had to be
away from home on the Sabbath and he has thought through those
issues.''
</P>
<P>
   By late July, Gore had conducted one-on-one interviews with all
of his finalists except Gephardt. There were no moments akin to
1992, when Clinton interviewed Gore well into the early morning.
Lieberman's interview, conducted at Gore's residence at the Naval
Observatory, lasted about an hour, the same amount of time Gore
spent with the others.
</P>
<P>
   But it clearly went well.
</P>
<P>
   Herman, the labor secretary, spoke with Gore after the interview
with Lieberman. She described Gore's response more as one of
affirmation rather than revelation. ``You had this sense of, `Boy,
was I right about this guy.'''
</P>
<P>
   Going into Sunday's decisive meetings in the vice president's
10th floor suite at the Loews Vanderbilt Plaza Hotel in Nashville,
aides got a definite sense that Gore had just about settled on
Lieberman but wanted one more ``gut check'' before making the
decision final. His questions were more pointed than probing, as if
he were attempting to test his political and personal judgments
against the range of opinions in the room.
</P>
<P>
   Not long before Gore told aides of his decision, he called his
oldest daughter, Karenna Gore Schiff, who was in her apartment in
New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``He goes on a personal instinct for this sort of thing,'' she
said. ``And I always knew he would.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
