<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 22:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6234 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-OBIT-TRUMP-NYT &LR;      08-08 0236
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-TRUMP-NYT </SLUG>
  
 MARY MacLEOD TRUMP, 88, PHILANTHROPIST  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mary MacLeod Trump, a philanthropist who supported
charities near her home in Queens, and elsewhere, died Aug. 7 at 88
at Long Island Jewish Medical Center, her family said.
</P>
<P>
   Trump was born Mary MacLeod on the Isle of Lewis in Scotland on
May 10, 1912. On a visit to New York City in the 1930s, she met
Fred C. Trump. They married in 1936 and settled in the Jamaica
Estates section of Queens, and Fred Trump went on to become one of
the city's biggest developers.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Trump was the mainstay of the Women's Auxiliary of Jamaica
Hospital and of the Jamaica Day Nursery. The Trumps were also
active in the Salvation Army, the Boy Scouts of America and the
Lighthouse for the Blind, among others. A pavilion at Jamaica
Hospital Medical Center bears their name. They also gave buildings
to the National Kidney Foundation of New York/New Jersey and to
Community Mainstreaming Associates of Great Neck, N.Y., which
provides homes for the disabled.
</P>
<P>
   Fred C. Trump died last year. Mary Trump is survived by four
children: Donald, the developer and casino operator; Robert, the
president of his father's property management company; Maryanne, a
federal judge on the 3rd Circuit Court of Appeals; Elizabeth, an
executive with Chase Manhattan Bank; eight grandchildren; and four
great-grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-08-00 2248EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000808.0377 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 22:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6235 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKW-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT     08-08 0767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SHOT HEARD ROUND THE LEAGUE
</HEADLINE>
 By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The old pro may never do anything as spectacular in
the rest of her career, but Teresa Weatherspoon will always have
The Shot.
</P>
<P>
   It was not a dunk, not a drive of brute force, but a desperate
running heave from midcourt that would bank in, yes, off the glass
to prolong the finals for another game.
</P>
<P>
   It reverberates a year later, showing up on every highlight and
advertisement for the Women's National Basketball Association:
</P>
<P>
   Flutie throwing the Hail Mary. Mr. October hitting his third of
the night. Jordan, flapping his tongue, faking somebody out of the
building. The big-game signature for an entire sport.
</P>
<P>
   A year later, Weatherspoon, now 34, took another shot to her
fragile nose Tuesday night while making seven assists and six
steals as the Liberty beat Cleveland, 57-44, to capture the
home-court advantage for the first two rounds of the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Spoon is our most valuable player,'' reiterated the steady Sue
Wicks after the game.
</P>
<P>
   Weatherspoon did her best to ratchet up the energy for the
18,663 fans. The ambience in Madison Square Garden is still sweet
and spontaneous for this evolving league _ attracting female fans,
family types, new faces. There was a woman with a bandanna over her
shaven head, and a tattoo, and assorted necklaces, in Woody Allen's
seat. The league is settling in for a long run with these
enthusiastic players who sign autographs and acknowledge their
fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``It might just be the woman way,'' Weatherspoon said with a
smile.
</P>
<P>
   At 6 p.m. she was as gentle as an alto in the church choir, but
she promised she would not look that way an hour later, after her
own version of meditation. Weatherspoon's feisty game face is
hardly the female version of the grim glare Bernard King used to
screw on in the Lincoln Tunnel before arriving at the Garden.
</P>
<P>
   ``I go into my own little world,'' she said. ``We're not just
basketball players, we're entertainers. The high-fives, the facial
looks, they're part of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Weatherspoon has been around. After leaving the basketball
bastion of Louisiana Tech, she played seven years in Como and then
Busto Arsizio outside Milan, Italy, loving the intensity.
</P>
<P>
   She played for the United States in Seoul in 1988, helping to
win a gold medal, and she played in Barcelona in 1992, losing in
the semifinals to the last remnants of the Soviet Union and saying
later, ``This will leave a scar for the rest of our lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Able to come home in 1997, Weatherspoon has seen the league
jump-start with unimagined average attendances of 9,669 the first
year, 10,869 the second, 10,207 the third, and down to 8,988 this
year, hurt in part by the early start because of the impending
Summer Games in Australia.
</P>
<P>
   Last year Weatherspoon knew the worst and the best of feelings.
Before the season, she learned that her 19-year-old nephew, Anthony
Weatherspoon, had died in a crash. She was very close to him,
giving him advice that children resist from their own parents.
After he was gone, whenever she did something special, she would
point a forefinger to the rafters: that one was for Anthony.
</P>
<P>
   Her best moment came in Houston during the quickie
two-of-three-game finals. Having lost the opener, the Liberty was
in danger of going out with 2.4 seconds left when Weatherspoon took
a pass, made two dribbles and heaved the ball with .4 seconds
remaining. (They worked on it every day at the end of practice, she
said later.) The ball slammed off the backboard and through the net
and Weatherspoon remembered to raise her forefinger. For Anthony.
Then she swooned to the floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some day I'd like to be sitting next to Jerry West and talk
about it,'' Weatherspoon said Tuesday night, referring to West's
classic 60-foot shot that tied the third game of the 1970 finals
against the Knicks, although the Knicks went on to win that game.
</P>
<P>
   The Liberty lost the third and deciding game but The Shot
endures _ as marketable as any player the league has developed,
even the 12 stars going to the Summer Games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never gave it a thought,'' Weatherspoon said of Australia.
``I've had my day. It was great.''
</P>
<P>
   She is a Liberty now. She broke her nose last week but will not
be hindered by a mask, or even thinking about the dangers of diving
for a loose ball. Weatherspoon is one of the very few players who
have stuck it out with the same team, four years into this
fledgling league.
</P>
<P>
   With any luck, this league will long outlast her, and The Shot
will live on.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-08-00 2249EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000808.0378 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 22:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6236 &Cx1f; tad-z
b i BC-MEXICO-MCCAFFREY-0809     08-08 0786
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-MCCAFFREY-0809-2NDLD-CO </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDs: in 3rd graf, corrects to read ' participated in meetings
between U.S. and Mexican officials Monday and Tuesday.'
 &HT;    U.S. DRUG CZAR SEES 'POSITIVE' TRANSITION OF POWER AMONG MEXICAN
JUSTICE OFFICIALS
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By SUSAN FERRISS 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Before heading to drug-plagued Colombia, U.S. drug
czar Gen. Barry McCaffrey stopped in Mexico Monday and Tuesday and
praised what appears to be an open transition of power here after
71 years of one-party presidential rule.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a pretty positive atmosphere,'' McCaffrey told U.S.
correspondents here, after meeting with Mexican President Ernesto
Zedillo, justice officials and members of Mexican President-elect
Vicente Fox's transition team.
</P>
<P>
   McCaffrey, who frequently has visited Mexico as the White
House's director of National Drug Control Policy, said Fox's
representatives participated in meetings between U.S. and Mexican
officials Monday and Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Fox defeated Mexico's ruling Institutional
Revolutionary Party, the PRI, and will take office on Dec. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly the PRI was shocked by its defeat, but I sensed an
enormous goodwill and respect for Mr. Fox,'' McCaffrey said.
``There is a completely open transition process going on.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox has pledged to clean up corruption in Mexico, a country that
is the transit point for up to 60 percent of the South American
cocaine sold in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The maverick politician has suggested that he will dramatically
revamp Mexican police agencies and the Attorney General's office
here. Because one party has controlled Mexico's presidency for
seven decades, speculation is rampant over how smoothly this can be
accomplished and how organized crime groups will react.
</P>
<P>
   ``The transition team we've been exposed to is pragmatic and
looking for creative new solutions,'' McCaffrey said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are determined to go down in history as Mexican
patriots,'' he added. ``I cannot believe they will do anything that
doesn't make sense to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox will reportedly review the role of the Mexican military in
the future and whether troops should be used for police work.
Currently, the Mexican military is involved in eradication of
drugs, interdiction, and intelligence and law enforcement work.
</P>
<P>
   McCaffrey praised the record of Mexico's Navy, which has been
working effectively with United States officials over the last year
to detect and seize drug shipments off the Pacific coast.
</P>
<P>
   But he declined to comment on whether Mexico should continue to
use the military in the war on drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm positive of one thing. The United States should not have a
hand in any way in shaping how . . . foreign nations in the
hemisphere organize themselves internally to confront these
issues,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   McCaffrey did say, however, that Mexican and U.S. officials will
recommend that Fox and whoever wins the U.S. presidency in November
should try to preserve the agreements for cooperation on drugs that
have been established under Zedillo and Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Fox has already said he would like the United States to get rid
of the current annual ``certification'' of countries, in which
Congress judges countries for their drug-fighting records. Mexico
has repeatedly come under attack for corruption and other failures.
</P>
<P>
   McCaffrey has long agreed with Fox's proposal, but doesn't
believe Congress is willing to scrap certification.
</P>
<P>
   He said nations in this hemisphere would discuss an alternative
system for grading each other on the drug war when they meet for
the Summit of the Americas in April 2001 in Quebec.
</P>
<P>
   McCaffrey meets in Miami Wednesday with officials from the U.S.
Army's Southern Command, before heading to Cartegena, Colombia to
talk about the U.S.'s $1.3 billion anti-drug aid package to
Colombia.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton will visit Colombia on Aug. 30 to show
support. Colombia is a cocaine-producing country overwhelmed by
violent traffickers and rebels that control about 40 percent of the
nation's territory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Colombia is in a risky position,'' he said. ``We're committed
to standing with them. Hopefully the region will also, along with
the Europeans and the Japanese. He (President Andres Pastrana) has
to solve several problems at the same time: an economy in the
dumps; a peace process that's going nowhere; and a drug production
problem that's skyrocketing.''
</P>
<P>
   Susan Ferriss' E-mail address is: susanf(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   For more information see:
</P>
<P>
   www.whitehousedrugpolicy.gov
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
