<SLUG> BC-REFORM </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEROT LOYALISTS VOTE TO DISQUALIFY BUCHANAN 
 

</HEADLINE>
 PARTY-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONG BEACH, Calif. _ Reform Party officials loyal to party
founder Ross Perot muscled their way out of a Long Beach meeting
room, then reconvened nearby and voted to disqualify Pat Buchanan
as a candidate for the party's presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time Buchanan backers appeared to lock up control of
the Reform Party and clear the way for nominating him later this
week as their standard-bearer in the November general election.
</P>
<P>
   The Perot loyalists, out-maneuvered by Buchanan-backers at a
fractious closed-door meeting of the Reform Party national
committee, forced their way past security guards who had been
ordered to block the exits.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is idiotic,'' said Paul Truax, a Dallas businessman and
Texas Reform Party founder who was among the dozens who shoved and
bellowed their way out of the Buchanan meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've won,'' Bay Buchanan, Pat's sister and campaign manager
declared, saying the walkout signaled that efforts had failed to
block Perot supporters from taking over the party. ``It's over
now.``
</P>
<P>
   Bay Buchanan dismissed the Perot loyalists' decision to
disqualify her brother's candidacy. ``This is basically a sad and
pathetic group of individuals who have lost and are unwilling to
give up power,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Long Beach police were summoned by several Perot loyalists who
claimed they were assaulted as they tried to leave the meeting
room.
</P>
<P>
   James Bourassa of Scottsdale, Ariz., who had red marks on his
neck, told police he was grabbed from behind during the melee.
``They were trying to lock the doors and didn't want us to leave,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The session the loyalists abandoned was chaired by Gerry Moan,
interim party chairman and Buchanan ally who controls the party's
finances. He dismissed the Perot-faction's chances of convincing
anyone their convention is legitimate. ``Yay for them,'' Moan said.
``It's not gonna be recognized.''
</P>
<P>
   At issue is control of the party and the $12.6 million in
federal campaign funds the party nominee can use in the fall
presidential race. The money, which must be awarded by the Federal
Election Commission, was earmarked for the Reform Party after
Perot, the Dallas billionaire, received almost 9 percent of the
popular vote in his 1996 presidential bid.
</P>
<P>
   Since his defeat, Perot has had little to do with the
organization. Earlier this year he turned away supporters who saw
him as their only chance to keep the Reform Party out of the hands
of Buchanan, who quit the Republican Party last year after failing
in his third try for the GOP presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Fearing that Buchanan would use the Reform Party to push his
social conservative agenda, party officials mounted an 11th hour
effort to block his nomination, then recruited John Hagelin as an
alternative candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Hagelin is a founder of the Natural Law Party and physics
professor at Maharishi University of Management in Iowa. Hagelin
will appear on the general election ballot in some states as the
Natural Law Party nominee.
</P>
<P>
   Sometime today, Perot loyalists _ led by former Reform Party
chairman Russ Verney and Truax _ were to announce a lawsuit seeking
to block Buchanan from gaining access to the federal campaign
money.
</P>
<P>
   After Verney, Truax and their allies left the Buchanan-dominated
meeting, a vote was taken by the conservative commentator's
supporters to reject a recommendation from the party's executive
committee that he should be disqualified from the party primary.
</P>
<P>
   The primary, which is being conducted by mail-in ballots and
email, began July 5 and ends today. A two-thirds vote by the
convention would be required to overturn the primary results. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXEND OF STORY $$$
</P>
