<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS' ELLIS PARTICIPATES IN FIRST DRILLS SINCE BREAKING LEG LAST
SEASON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS, Texas _ Cowboys defensive end Greg Ellis
practiced yesterday for the first time since suffering a
career-threatening leg fracture roughly eight months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Ellis, who broke the tibia and fibula in his left leg against
the Philadelphia Eagles on Dec. 12 and underwent surgery to have a
titanium rod inserted in his leg that night, stopped short of
promising to be in the lineup when the Cowboys open the season
against the Eagles on Sept. 3.
</P>
<P>
   However, he said the opener is his goal and yesterday's return
was the first step.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, it doesn't mean I will be there for opening day,'' Ellis
said. ``I don't know how the leg will react to a live shot or
somebody kicking it. I think it will be fine. The trainers think
it's going to be fine. There are no guarantees. This is the first
step toward finding out.''
</P>
<P>
   Ellis, who has spent much of training camp working out with
Cowboys conditioning coaches, didn't practice as well as he would
like. However, he said he was thrilled to be practicing again.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was exciting to be out there,'' Ellis said. ``It felt like
more than a regular practice to me. It was tough not being out
there with my teammates. Now I'm back. That was a big step, and
it's rewarding.''
</P>
<P>
   Though cautious, Cowboys defensive coordinator Mike Zimmer was
equally pleased. He said Ellis' presence is crucial to the
defense's success. Ellis led the team last year with 7 1/2 sacks,
despite missing the final three games.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot will be determined by how he feels tomorrow and the next
day,'' Zimmer said. ``But he's a heck of football player. We need
him.'' Roster moves While the Cowboys welcomed two newly signed
players, tight end Rickey Brady and safety Hurley Tarver, to
training camp yesterday, they said good bye to three others.
</P>
<P>
   Running back Chrys Chukwuma, linebacker Bernard Russ and tight
end Brian Roche were released by the team.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys coach Dave Campo said the impressive play of rookie
linebackers Orantes Grant and Corey Atkins made Russ expendable.
Roche was deemed too one-dimensional. The Cowboys have a
pass-catching tight end in Jackie Harris but need someone who can
block. Roche was not physical enough.
</P>
<P>
   Campo said the Cowboys hope Brady can give them what they want.
However, they also plan on using a backup offensive lineman as a
blocking tight end. The Cowboys have three open roster spots but
are in no rush to fill them. The Cowboys will scan the waiver wire
to see who best fits their needs. Justin's job in jeopardy
Third-string quarterback Paul Justin's penchant for turnovers has
put his job on notice, Dave Campo said yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Justin was already a long shot the make the roster because of
his $500,000 salary. His six turnovers in two preseason games have
put him in a deeper hole with the Cowboys, who have stopped making
excuses for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to be concerned about him,'' Campo said. ``If he was
pressing before, he's got to press again. He's got to make some
plays.'' Garmon still impressing Dave Campo said that former Haltom
High School standout Kelvin Garmon has been the biggest surprise in
camp. Garmon, who has started at left guard in Larry Allen's
absence the past two games, will get a look at right guard now that
Allen has returned.
</P>
<P>
   Campo wouldn't go so far as to say that Garmon will compete with
Jorge Diaz for the starting spot. However, the Cowboys have been so
impressed with Garmon that they have switched Tony Hutson, who was
supposed to battle Diaz for the starting guard spot, to tackle.
Briefly Cowboys running back Emmitt Smith left practice yesterday
with a strained right calf. It is not believed to be serious, but
expect Smith to be miss his third consecutive preseason game Sunday
against the Oakland Raiders.
</P>
<P>
   Cornerback Kevin Smith missed practice yesterday for personal
reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Second-round pick Dwayne Goodrich, off to a disappointingly slow
start, will be set back even further after suffering a strained
hamstring.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
