<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-WILEY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-BUCKEYE'S BIG HIT GETS NOTICE OF COWBOYS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RAY BUCK 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS, Texas _ Michael Wiley remains humble and modest
in spite of being something of a movie star this week.
</P>
<P>
   He earned the respect of his peers and his coaches with a
knock-down block on an Atlanta Falcons linebacker Saturday night at
the Tokyo Dome, a hit heard literally 'round the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy crumbled,'' Cowboys running back coach Clarence
Shelmon said. ``Everyone in the \Roffensive\S meeting started
hollering, `Ooh! Wow!' Believe me, players in this league ``know''
a good hit when they see one.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta linebacker Chris Draft _ two inches taller and 20 pounds
heavier than the 5-foot-11, 189-pound Wiley _ blitzed on a pass
play and tried to bull-rush the former Ohio State running back.
</P>
<P>
   ``\RWiley\S looked like Emmitt Smith, circa 1992 ... I mean, he
stoned the guy,'' Cowboys coach Dave Campo said. ``It was one of
the best licks of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Wiley, a rookie fifth-round draft pick whose star keeps rising,
also has shown flashes of being an explosive kickoff return man,
something that he hadn't done full time since his sophomore year
with the Buckeyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shoot, hopefully, I can be the kickoff-return specialist
here,'' Wiley said yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Emmitt \RSmith\S and Chris \RWarren\S here, I probably
won't see much playing time. I'm learning to be more patient as a
runner. ... The older guys tell me, `Don't race to the hole. Relax
a little bit and let everything happen for you.'''
</P>
<P>
   Through two preseason games, Wiley leads all Cowboys rushers (59
yards on 15 carries) and all kickoff returners (seven for 25.0
yards per return). He also is the Cowboys' best pass protector at
his position not named Emmitt Smith, Shelmon said.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a small guy, Wiley is one of the toughest guys I've ever
been around,'' the assistant coach said. ``I saw it on videotapes
of Ohio State games, but you never know if it transfers until the
guy gets to this league.''
</P>
<P>
   Wiley is in a three-way battle with two undrafted free agents,
Michael Black and Troy Hambrick, to make the team as the third
running back behind Smith, the NFL's leading active rusher, and
Warren, the incumbent third-down specialist.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be hard to choose between Black and Wiley right
now,'' Shelmon said. ``They both make defenders miss. They're
terrific blockers. They run pass routes real well. They both have
done extremely well on special teams. It would be really hard to
separate them right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Wiley and the 5-11, 206-pound Black, who spent the past two
seasons on Seattle's practice squad, have been joined by Hambrick,
who was moved from fullback to running back after Chrys Chukwuma
was waived yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Chukwuma had one of the Cowboys' three fumbles Saturday night.
Turnovers and penalties are two areas for which Campo has close to
zero tolerance.
</P>
<P>
   Wiley also fumbled when he was stripped of the ball Saturday at
the end of a 49-yard kickoff return.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not concerned with that one ... that was a learning
experience,'' Campo said. ``Both \Rspecial teams coach\S Joe
Avezzano and I walked up to him after it happened _ not at the same
time _ and said the same thing: `They strip in this league,
Michael.'''
</P>
<P>
   They strip the ball in the Big Ten, too. Wiley can't _ and won't
_ use that as an excuse, saying instead, ``I think I just got
excited. I thought I was breaking into the clear with nobody around
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Black is the Cowboys' second-leading rusher with 32 yards on 10
carries. Warren (27 on seven carries) has scored the team's only
touchdown this preseason.
</P>
<P>
   Hambrick, younger brother of Cowboys strongside linebacker
Darren Hambrick, has shown just enough promise at fullback to merit
a look at tailback.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hasn't been the blocker that you'd like to see at
\Rfullback\S ... and rightly so, because he hasn't played there
before,'' Shelmon said. ``But he has shown a lot of talent for a
big man \R6-1, 235\S.''
</P>
<P>
   Hambrick rushed for 1,189 yards and scored 18 touchdowns last
season at Division II Savannah (Ga.) State, and certainly would be
a strong candidate for the practice squad if he doesn't make the
53-man roster. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
