<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 23:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6346 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-ACCOUNTING-MARKETPLAC     08-08 0819
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ACCOUNTING-MARKETPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: AFTER ANDERSEN WAR, ACCOUNTANTS THINK HARD ABOUT
CONSULTING 
</HEADLINE>
   By REED ABELSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Now that the Andersens are finally splitsville, are accountants
going to forsake everything but the single life, limiting
themselves to poring over a company's books and offering tax
advice?
</P>
<P>
   Not if they can help it.
</P>
<P>
   A day after an arbitrator freed Andersen Consulting from Arthur
Andersen, the tax and auditing firm, attention shifted to some of
the other accounting and consulting marriages that are on the
rocks. Though the world's largest accounting firms are eager to
sell their existing consulting businesses for a variety of reasons,
they will probably continue to offer a wide array of services _
unless regulators place new limits on them.
</P>
<P>
   In the long run, ``all the public accounting firms will be in
consulting,'' predicted Robert K. Elliott, the chairman of the
American Institute of Certified Public Accountants and a partner
with KPMG.
</P>
<P>
   Consulting has fueled much of the firms' growth over the last
decade or so, said Jon McKenna, the executive editor of the Public
Accounting Report. ``It would be foolish to sell off a goose that
golden,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The international arbitrator brought in to settle the bitter
Andersen dispute, which had dragged on for three years, essentially
gave Andersen Consulting its freedom for a paltry $1 billion,
although Arthur Andersen got the right to the Andersen name.
</P>
<P>
   But the other firms moving toward split-ups expect to get a lot
more than $1 billion given the high valuations on the consulting
businesses. Ernst &AMP; Young sold its consulting unit earlier this
year to Cap Gemini SA for some $11 billion, and KPMG plans to spin
off the bulk of its consulting operations in an initial public
offering that could raise nearly $3 billion. PricewaterhouseCoopers
is also considering divesting itself of its consulting unit by the
end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Selling at least a part of the business to another company or
the public makes sense, according to Elliott. ``I think it's driven
by the economics,'' he said. Some firms are worried about the
retirement needs of their partners, while others simply want to put
the cash to other uses, offering stock to the partners or investing
more in the traditional accounting side of the firm.
</P>
<P>
   If money is why these firms are getting out, money may be the
reason these firms get back into consulting, even after they sell
off a large stake in their existing businesses. Arthur Andersen,
for example, started another consulting business even after it
decided to part ways with Andersen Consulting. ``There's a natural
desire to have consulting in one of these firms,'' said Kenneth A.
Merchant, the dean of accounting at the University of Southern
California.
</P>
<P>
   What might change is the type of consulting these firms do. They
may move away from management or information technology consulting
to other areas that are either in demand or somehow related to
their expertise in giving outsiders faith in the numbers and
representations that companies make. ``The challenge is what does
business assurance mean,'' said Rocco J. Maggiotto, the global
leader of markets and strategy for PricewaterhouseCoopers.
</P>
<P>
   There is also some anxiety among these firms that the Securities
and Exchange Commission might eventually give them little choice in
the matter. Arthur Levitt, the chairman of the SEC, has expressed
concern over the perception that auditor independence has been
hindered by consulting services offered by the same firm, a
perception strengthened when companies like Pinnacle Holdings and
its auditor come under investigation for questions of independence,
as happened Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   While accounting firms are already prohibited from offering some
of those services, the SEC is proposing to bar companies from using
the same firm to provide both internal and outside audits and using
a firm that provides information services consulting to them as
their auditor.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Levitt does not prevail, or reaches a compromise that
allows many of the consulting services to still be offered, the
need to reassure investors and clients of their independence may
force firms to stay away from certain businesses. ``Whether Levitt
is there or not, they've opened the box up,'' said Tom Rodenhauser,
an analyst with Consulting Information Services, who expects the
relationship between accountants and consultants to fundamentally
change to avoid potential conflicts of interest.
</P>
<P>
   After the firms rid themselves of their consulting units and
become smaller, there is also the possibility of further
consolidation, even as the firms once known as the Big Eight have
shrunk to the Big Five. Without the consulting unit, Arthur
Andersen has become a much smaller player, and Ernst and KPMG had
once expressed interest in combining.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-08-00 2310EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
