<HEADER>
A6348 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-OBIT-MEYER-NYT &LR;      08-08 1204
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-MEYER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICHAEL MEYER, 79, IBSEN AND STRINDBERG TRANSLATOR AND SCHOLAR 
</HEADLINE>
   By MEL GUSSOW   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Michael Meyer, whose translations of the plays of Ibsen and
Strindberg are performed throughout the English-speaking world and
who wrote monumental biographies of both Scandinavian playwrights,
died Aug. 3. He was 79 and lived in London.
</P>
<P>
   Meyer was himself a playwright and teacher but found his primary
artistic calling as a conduit to Ibsen and Strindberg. Although in
a sense he was shadowed by them, he opened doors to their art for
generations of theatergoers.
</P>
<P>
   He did not seem to feel that his work as a translator and a
biographer was a lesser occupation, but it was, in his mind, a kind
of self-annihilation. He said, ``The most difficult thing, if the
translator is a writer himself, is to keep himself out of it, to
resist leaving his thumbprint.'' He applied a similar principle to
the writing of biography. His objective was to be complete but
``never upstage the subject.''
</P>
<P>
   In his pantheon, first came Ibsen, a giant of the theater who
justly deserved Meyer's ``Ibsen: A Biography,'' an 865-page tome of
great gravitas. Meyer belonged to the all-inclusive school of
biographers, writing books that would stand by themselves and would
also be sources for future biographers. In ``Ibsen'' he offered
endless facts about the playwright's life in and outside the
theater and laundry lists of his income.
</P>
<P>
   But behind those details was a portrait of a genius, a book that
since its publication in 1971 has remained an essential study of a
founding father of modern theater.
</P>
<P>
   In his book Meyer credits Ibsen with breaking down social
barriers that had previously bound theater and with eradicating
artificialities of plot.
</P>
<P>
   He concludes, ``Ibsen's enduring greatness as a dramatist is due
not to his technical innovations, but to the depth and subtlety of
his understanding of human character (especially feminine
character), and, which is rarer, of human relationships.''
</P>
<P>
   Writing in The New York Times Book Review, Rolf Fjelde, himself
a prolific translator of Ibsen plays, said this was the ``most
complete Ibsen biography to date.'' While criticizing prolixity as
the chief defect of the book, he said that the author ``abundantly
reminds us of the contradictory, variously colorful, prosaic and at
times moving outer record of Ibsen the man.''
</P>
<P>
   After ``Ibsen,'' it seemed natural that Meyer would move on to
``Strindberg,'' but for some time he avoided that biography while
concentrating on his translations. Eventually he acceded to the
wishes of publishers and devoted himself to the Swedish playwright,
just as he had to his Norwegian counterpart and rival.
</P>
<P>
   His reasons for hesitating over Strindberg were clear. Meyer was
Jewish, and he was offended by the playwright's prejudices. He said
that the characteristics he most disliked in people ``would be
headed by racism, hysteria, self-pity, malice and vengefulness, and
Strindberg possessed all these in full measure.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he would have preferred to write about a sympathetic
subject, he ``decided that however miserable Strindberg made
others, I would keep my antipathy to myself.''
</P>
<P>
   In his biography, Meyer describes Strindberg as a pioneer in
``the depiction of men and women driven by love, hatred, jealousy
or a mixture of all three to that nightmare border country where
hysteria abuts on madness.'' He says Strindberg was someone who
``explored those dark corners of the human soul which most of us
seal off like poisoned wells; he was unbalanced, but so were most
explorers of that country _ Swift, Melville, Dostoyevsky, Kafka.''
</P>
<P>
   In his translations of Ibsen and Strindberg, Meyer held fast to
one of his cardinal rules: he stripped away archaisms, but he did
not modernize the dialogue. By keeping the language in context, he
was able to secure a longer life for his translations. They outlive
the vernacular and the topical, retaining their classical
dimension.
</P>
<P>
   Because Meyer was himself a playwright, they are eminently
playable, and they have been acted by the most important English
actors, including Laurence Olivier, Peggy Ashcroft, Anthony Hopkins
and Vanessa Redgrave.
</P>
<P>
   For such an expert, Meyer was a latecomer to his profession. He
was born in London and studied at Oxford University. During World
War II, he was at first a conscientious objector, then served three
years as a civilian with the British Bomber Command. From 1947 to
1950 he was a lecturer in English literature at Uppsala University
in Sweden, where he learned Swedish.
</P>
<P>
   In Sweden he wrote a novel and, later, several plays: ``The
Ortolan'' was staged at Oxford with Maggie Smith, then at the
beginning of her career. It was Meyer's translation of Frans G.
Bengtsson's novel ``The Long Ships'' that brought him to the
attention of the BBC, which commissioned him to translate Ibsen's
``Little Eyolf'' for radio.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, he knew only rudimentary Norwegian, but he soon
learned the language and wrote television versions of ``The Lady
from the Sea'' and ``John Gabriel Borkman,'' which starred Olivier,
Irene Worth and Pamela Brown.
</P>
<P>
   He was then asked to translate all 16 of Ibsen's major plays,
and also to write a biography of the playwright. The work on Ibsen
overlapped with his translations of 18 Strindberg plays. As he
said, ``Translating plays suddenly became a way of life for me.''
</P>
<P>
   The 651-page Strindberg biography was published in 1985. With
characteristic specificity, Meyer said that each biography took him
five and a quarter years to write.
</P>
<P>
   In his review of ``Strindberg'' in The New York Times, John
Gross said: ``Michael Meyer proves as admirable a guide to this
problematic genius as anyone could ask . . . as the foremost
English translator of Strindberg, he brings to bear the authority
both of a scholar and a man of the theater.''
</P>
<P>
   The Strindberg was dedicated to Graham Greene, whom Meyer met
during the war. ``Later we traveled together,'' he said. ``We sat
on either end of our veranda in Tahiti, I translating `The Ghost
Sonata' while he wrote `A Burnt-Out Case.''' Later in his memoir,
``Words Through a Windowpane,'' he wrote about Greene, George
Orwell, Arthur Koestler, Ralph Richardson and other literary and
theatrical friends.
</P>
<P>
   Meyer is survived by a daughter, Nora.
</P>
<P>
   Although he wrote on other subjects, he seemed obsessed with the
two towering Scandinavians. He wrote a play about Ibsen in his
later years and a play about Strindberg from boyhood to death. In
1991 in ``A Meeting in Rome,'' he brought the two of them together
in a play about an imaginary encounter between the artists who had
so dominated his own life.
</P>
<P>
   As Meyer writes in ``Ibsen,'' the two almost met in Italy in the
spring of 1884, but Strindberg was held back by bad weather. If
these two extraordinary men had met, Meyer conjectures, ``they
might have got on rather well, for Strindberg, when his black mood
was not on him, was a tremendous charmer, and he was the kind of
emotional individualist . . . Ibsen found stimulating. And when
Ibsen liked someone and put his own charm forward, there were few
who could resist him.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
