<SLUG> BC-DIAL-RESIGN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXECUTIVES RESIGN AS DIAL EARNINGS FALTER 
</HEADLINE>
   By GREG WINTER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Dial Corp., which makes Dial soap and Armour
canned meats, said on Tuesday that its top two executives had
resigned and it warned that it would miss earnings expectations for
the third time this year.
</P>
<P>
   Malcolm Jozoff, the chairman, president and chief executive
since 1996, who ushered the company through three years of rapid
growth before it stalled this year, was succeeded by Herbert M.
Baum, 63, the president of Hasbro Inc. and a Dial board member
since 1997. Susan J. Riley, the executive vice president and chief
financial officer for the last three years, also stepped down and
was succeeded by the company controller, Jack Tierney.
</P>
<P>
   The overhaul comes after a troubled first half for the company,
based in Scottsdale, Ariz. Its stock price has tumbled recently to
its lowest level since Dial spun off its travel services in 1996.
It decided at that time to focus exclusively on consumer brands
like Purex detergent, Breck shampoo and Renuzit air freshener.
</P>
<P>
   Twice before, first in March and again in June, Dial warned
investors that languishing sales, inventory backlogs and price cuts
by competitors would drive earnings down as much as 30 percent for
the year. In response, analysts, some of whom expected Dial to earn
$1.30 a share in 2000, lowered their forecasts 77 cents a share, a
34 percent drop from the profit last year.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's announcement made it clear that analysts will have to
revise their estimates yet again and are awaiting a conference call
with Baum in the coming weeks before setting new projections.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Dial fell 87.5 cents on Tuesday, to $11.9375.
</P>
<P>
   When Jozoff took control of Dial in 1996, he introduced new
products, cast off other unprofitable ones and cut prices on core
brands to make them more competitive. The move led to a turnaround,
jump-starting the company from minimal to roughly 15 percent growth
a year.
</P>
<P>
   To sustain that pace, Dial began a series of acquisitions, from
Sarah Michaels in 1998 to Freeman Cosmetics last year. This year,
the company bought Coast soap from Procter &AMP; Gamble and joined
forces with Henkel, a German chemical company, to introduce a
premium line of its Purex brand.
</P>
<P>
   But the performance of its recent acquisitions has been
lackluster, company officials acknowledge. And, after a banner year
for Amour canned meats, the company raised its prices, but
competitors did not follow suit. Over all, Dial's sales have
slumped more than 5 percent this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
