u f BC-BRIDGESTONE-RECALL-NY     08-08 0420
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRIDGESTONE-RECALL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRIDGESTONE SAID TO PLAN BIG RECALL OF TIRES 
</HEADLINE>
   By MILT FREUDENHEIM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bridgestone Corp. said Tuesday that it would hold a news
conference Wednesday in Washington, after a meeting of company
representatives and regulators who have been investigating dozens
of safety complaints and at least 21 fatal accidents involving
sport utility vehicle and pickup truck tires.
</P>
<P>
   Reuters and The Associated Press reported Tuesday that the
company's Firestone division would announce a recall of millions of
the tires used on SUVs and light trucks, which are used by several
auto companies. The tire models listed in the reports were the ATX,
ATX II and Wilderness AT.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of Firestone and Ford Motor met Tuesday with
officials of the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration to
discuss its investigation of the tires.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the complaints involved the Ford Explorer, an agency
official said. Martin Inglis, Ford's vice president for North
American automotive operations, said his company had ``had a team
working for 10 or 11 days around the clock'' to identify the extent
of the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Firestone has been the main tire supplier to Ford since the days
of both companies' founders, Henry Ford and Harvey Firestone, and
the families have been linked through marriage.
</P>
<P>
   Ford has repeatedly said the last week that it would continue to
use Firestone tires. Discount Tire, Montgomery Ward and Sears,
Roebuck have stopped selling the tires because of safety concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Fields, a Bridgestone spokesman, said it would announce
Wednesday ``additional steps that we are going to take to address
this issue.'' The company declined to comment on the reports that
it planned a recall.
</P>
<P>
   Inglis noted that unlike warranties on other auto parts, those
on tires are issued by tire makers, and recalls are the
responsibility of the tire maker, not the automaker.
</P>
<P>
   Scott F. Merlis, an analyst with Wasserstein Perella Securities,
said the tire defects were primarily a customer relations problem
for Firestone, which he said ``had to move fast to contain broader
damage to the company's overall brand.''
</P>
<P>
   Consumer lawsuits have been filed since 1996 contending that the
tires contributed to fatal accidents _ especially during hot
weather in the South.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the safety agency, which is part of the
Transportation Department, said the government had not drawn any
conclusions about the safety of the tires.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
