<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-BURNHILL-NYT </SLUG>
  
 DR. MICHAEL BuRNHILL, 72; LED IN WOMEN'S CARE  
 By WOLFGANG SAXON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dr. Michael Seth Burnhill, a leader in women's health care,
family planning and reproductive health, died Aug. 4 in New
Brunswick, N.J. He was 72 and lived in Belle Mead, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   He was attending to patients in his Belle Mead office earlier
that day when he suffered an aortic dissection, or tear, and
collapsed, his family said. He died at Robert Wood Johnson
Hospital, where he had worked until last year.
</P>
<P>
   Burnhill had been the vice president for medical affairs of the
national Planned Parenthood Federation of America since 1995. He
joined the organization in 1972, as medical director of Planned
Parenthood of New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Trained as an obstetrician-gynecologist, he became known in the
profession in the 1960s when he joined his father, Dr. Charles
Birnberg, in developing an early intrauterine device, or IUD. Known
as the Birnberg Bow, it was a widely used contraceptive.
</P>
<P>
   Burnhill, a native of Brooklyn, graduated magna cum laude from
Syracuse University in 1949 and received his medical degree at the
University of Vermont in 1953. He completed his specialized
training at Mount Sinai Hospital in New York in 1960 and received a
doctorate of medical science, obstetrics-gynecology, at State
University of New York Downstate Medical Center in 1972.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1960s he was affiliated with several hospitals in
Brooklyn, as well as with New York Hospital, George Washington
University Hospital and Johns Hopkins Hospital and School of
Medicine. He joined the staff of Robert Wood Johnson Medical School
and University Hospital as a professor of obstetrics and gynecology
and senior attending physician in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   Burnhill, who was divorced, is survived by a daughter, Lauren A.
Burnhill of Miami; a son, David A., of Rockville, Md.; and a
sister, Marian Mintzer of Fort Lauderdale, Fla.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
