<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-LEHTINEN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JERE LEHTINEN, STARS AGREE ON FOUR-YEAR CONTRACT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF CAPLAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Stars avoided the first of two arbitration cases yesterday
when they agreed to terms with right winger Jere Lehtinen.
</P>
<P>
   Lehtinen, 27, agreed to a four-year deal for an undisclosed
amount, thereby canceling a scheduled arbitration hearing tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   Lehtinen, who is spending the off-season at his home in Finland,
earned $1.5 million last season and was expected to seek a raise
through arbitration that would double his salary.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is one of the premier defensive forwards in the league, and
we look forward to his future contributions,'' Stars general
manager Bob Gainey said.
</P>
<P>
   Lehtinen, a two-time Selke Trophy winner as the league's top
defensive forward, is a player whom coach Ken Hitchcock refers to
as a team catalyst. Lehtinen struggled through an injury-plagued
1999-2000 season, his fifth with the Stars. Stars management could
have used that to their advantage in a hearing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that either party was uncomfortable with the
idea of going to arbitration and portraying their case in the
open,'' Gainey said. ``But, when there is a settlement made, it is
usually because there's room in there for both parties to agree.''
</P>
<P>
   A broken ankle kept Lehtinen out of all but 17 regular-season
games last season, and he missed the opening two rounds of the
playoffs. He had one goal among six points in 13 playoff games.
</P>
<P>
   Only forward Blake Sloan remains unsigned. Sloan's arbitration
hearing is on course for Saturday in Toronto. The Stars have not
been forced to an arbitration hearing in franchise history, but
Gainey said it appears the club could be headed that way with
Sloan.
</P>
<P>
   Sloan, who made $357,000 last season, wants a one-way contract.
In his two seasons with the Stars, he was under a two-way contract,
meaning his salary would be drastically reduced if he were sent
down to the team's minor-league affiliate.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Gainey said he will restart negotiations with unrestricted
free agents next week. The Stars remain interested in signing a
defenseman, likely Dave Manson. The Stars also are interested in a
forward and have talked with Ted Donato and Claude Lemieux.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-08-00 2320EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
