u p BC-MRS-CLINTON-LIEBERMAN     08-08 1001
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MRS-CLINTON-LIEBERMAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MRS. CLINTON MOVES TO MAKE LIEBERMAN WORK FOR HER, TOO 
</HEADLINE>
  By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hillary Rodham Clinton moved on Tuesday to turn Sen. Joseph
Lieberman's presence on the national ticket to her political
advantage, saying she wanted him to campaign by her side this fall.
</P>
<P>
   She predicted that Lieberman's presence on the New York ballot
would increase turnout among Jewish voters and lift her own Senate
candidacy, an assertion that was immediately disputed by Rep. Rick
Lazio, her Republican opponent.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton discussed having Lieberman come to New York during a
congratulatory conversation with the Connecticut senator on the day
that Vice President Al Gore formally announced that he had chosen
Lieberman to be the first Jew to run on a major-party ticket for
national office.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, whose aides have been worried about her relative lack
of support among Jewish voters in New York, described Gore's
decision as a welcome development for Clinton's candidacy, in terms
of increasing her support among Democrats in general and Jewish
voters in particular.
</P>
<P>
   ``As people get to meet him, they're going to come away just
impressed and really energized by this choice,'' the first lady
said in a radio interview in Albany. ``And I think here in New
York, it's going to drive up the vice president's numbers, which
will be great for the ticket and for you know, the popular vote. I
think it's going to be really a good decision across the board. So
I expect it will help in New York, but I suspect it's going to help
around the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazio's campaign manager, Bill Dal Col, disputed Clinton's
analysis, asserting that developments in the presidential race
would have no bearing on the high-profile contest between Lazio and
Clinton. Nonetheless, in a suggestion of some concern in Lazio's
camp, the candidate took a break from a closed fund-raising tour in
California to chastise Clinton for her remarks and note several
issues on which she disagreed with Lieberman, including his support
for school vouchers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hillary Clinton is many things, but she's no Joe Lieberman,''
Lazio said in Thousand Oaks, Calif., according to a transcript of
his remarks provided by his press office. ``If Clinton thinks
Senator Lieberman can drag her across the finish line in New York,
she's sorely mistaken. She's desperate to make this race about
anything other than our records.''
</P>
<P>
   The cross-country exchange on Tuesday suggested the extent to
which a decision made by Gore to help his own presidential race had
captured the attention of both candidates in the race for Senate in
New York.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has had difficulty winning the level of support among
Jewish voters that Democratic candidates typically draw in New
York, so the Lieberman selection could prove fruitful for her.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, Sen. Charles Schumer, running against Alfonse D'Amato,
drew 75 percent of the Jewish vote, according to a survey of voters
leaving the polls. Jewish voters made up 12 percent of the
electorate that year.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Clinton appears be drawing closer to 60 percent.
Analysts say that she probably needs 65 percent to win the
election.
</P>
<P>
   A campaign aide to Clinton predicted that the Lieberman
development could add two full percentage points to her showing on
Election Day, a margin that could make the difference in what most
polls show as an extremely close race.
</P>
<P>
   Edward Koch, the former New York City mayor and one of Clinton's
most important Jewish supporters, said Jewish support was now
``going to pour out here in the city and across the state.''
</P>
<P>
   Schumer also asserted that Clinton would benefit. ``It excites
people about the ticket, both Jewish and non-Jewish,'' Schumer said
in an interview. ``And that is good for Hillary Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman's selection almost certainly erases any chance that
George W. Bush will invest much time or money in New York. Some
Republicans have been worried that Lazio would be unable to swim
against the tide of a large victory by Gore in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, several factors suggest that Lieberman's selection
may not provide as much help to Clinton as she would like. For one,
Jews already vote in large numbers, particularly in a presidential
race, so the actual increase in turnout may not be as large as her
supporters suggested. And even Clinton's associates acknowledged
that animosity toward the first lady means that Jewish voters who
turn out for Gore could leave the voting booth without casting a
vote for Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce J. Teitelbaum, who has extensive ties to the Orthodox
Jewish community and served as Rudolph Giuliani's campaign manager
in the Senate race, said that the Lieberman selection posed at best
an opportunity for Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lieberman's presence will attract more Jews to the polls in
November, but she needs to seize the opportunity to get Jews to
vote for her, and I don't think she will,'' Teitelbaum said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton quickly moved to demonstrate how she intended to use
Lieberman to her advantage, campaigning in Orthodox communities in
Rockland County on Tuesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   She told an audience of schoolgirls in New Square that Lieberman
``has been my friend for 30 years,'' and said his selection showed
how committed Gore and the Democratic Party were to Jewish voters.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio's aides sought to undercut Clinton on Tuesday by noting
areas in which the two Democrats disagreed, and added that
Lieberman had taken the floor of the Senate to denounce President
Clinton for his involvement with Monica Lewinsky. The first lady
evinced no concern about either issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I consider both of us to be sort of mainstream centrist New
Democrats,'' she said in her Albany radio interview. ``We don't
agree 100 percent on all the issues.''
</P>
<P>
   As to what Lieberman said about her husband, she said: ``You
know, the president said he agreed with him. And I think people are
going to find a lot to like about Joe Lieberman.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
