<SLUG> BC-NBC-INTERNET-LAYOFFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NBC'S INTERNET UNIT TO LAY OFF 20 PERCENT OF ITS EMPLOYEES 
</HEADLINE>
   By SAUL HANSELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NBC Internet, the online affiliate of the NBC television
network, said Tuesday that it would lay off 170 people, some 20
percent of its total workforce of 850.
</P>
<P>
   About 100 employees were told Tuesday they had been laid off,
and the remaining positions will be eliminated by the end of the
year, either through attrition, additional layoffs, or because
certain units may be sold.
</P>
<P>
   NBCi, as the company is called, is a publicly traded company
that is 39 percent owned by NBC, a unit of General Electric. Its
shares have fallen by 85 percent this year. Tuesday, they closed
unchanged at $11.
</P>
<P>
   With ad sales slowing and the markets less forgiving, the
company decided to tighten its belt, said William J. Lansing, the
company's chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   ``In an easier money time, you invest in business models that
have returns down the road,'' he said. ``In the environment we are
in today, the Street wants to see results now and you have to be
very disciplined.''
</P>
<P>
   NBCi had expected to break even in the middle of 2002, but the
layoffs and other cost cutting will allow it to show profits
sooner, Lansing said, though he declined to say when.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our intent is not to lose money indefinitely,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the quarter ended June 30, NBCi lost $151.9 million on sales
of $30.5 million. That loss was higher than analysts had expected
because of a slow-down in ad revenue, especially from Internet
companies.
</P>
<P>
   The company was formed last November as a result of the merger
of Snap, an Internet portal site that NBC controlled, and Xoom, a
publicly traded site that focused on direct marketing. The company
also included several other operations that had been started by NBC
as well as several acquisitions, including Allbusiness.com, a
service aimed at small companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``This business was formed through the merger of many
businesses, and we have to now figure out how those pieces fit
together,'' Lansing said.
</P>
<P>
   Two months ago, the company announced that it would eliminate
Snap, Xoom and its other brand names and introduce a single new
service this fall under the NBCi.com brand.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet units of other broadcast companies have also been
cutting back. CBS's relatively small in-house Internet unit laid
off several dozen people this summer. And Walt Disney Internet Co.,
which runs the GO.com portal, is scaling back its ambition to focus
on entertainment and travel.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
