<SLUG> BC-UNITED-FLIGHTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNITED AIRLINES CANCELS MORE FLIGHTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Air Line Pilots Association is correct) 
 By DAVID BARBOZA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ United Airlines canceled more than 200 flights
nationwide on Tuesday, disrupting service for thousands of
passengers for the fourth consecutive day.
</P>
<P>
   The cancellations came after a disastrous weekend in which
United, the world's largest airline, was racked by delays and
canceled about 600 flights, or about 15 percent of its weekend
service, because of what the company said was inclement weather in
the East and Midwest and a continuing pilot shortage.
</P>
<P>
   The difficulties of the last week come as airline delays in the
United States are on the rise and United is promoting itself as an
official sponsor of the Democratic National Convention, which
begins next week in Los Angeles. United has been hurt worse by
delays than other carriers. Its flights arrived on time 57 percent
of the time in May, the last month for which statistics are
available, and it has had a record number of cancellations.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Rono Dutta, the president of the UAL Corp., the
parent of United, issued an apology to passengers, saying the
airline deeply regretted the ``pain and suffering'' the delays and
cancellations had caused.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Brathwaite, a United spokesman, said on Tuesday that the
company was continuing to negotiate with representatives of the
airline's 10,000 pilots, many of whom have refused to work overtime
since their contract expired in April.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether United's troubles could affect service to the
convention, Brathwaite said: ``I really couldn't say. We're going
to do the best we can.''
</P>
<P>
   Since United's contract with its pilots expired, the airline has
been plagued by a shortage of pilots willing to work overtime. And
after its contract with its maintenance workers expired in July,
United executives have complained about a rise in maintenance
delays.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, several weeks ago, the company announced that it
would reduce its schedule of flights by about 3 percent to try to
ensure it had enough pilots.
</P>
<P>
   United, which schedules about 2,400 flights a day, has been
reducing its flight schedule since May.
</P>
<P>
   Herb Hunter, a United pilot and a member of the Air Line Pilots
Association, which represents United, said yesterday that weather
was a chief cause of the weekend troubles. But he also said United
failed to hire enough pilots.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've said all along that we've had staffing problems coming
into the summer,'' he said. ``But I applaud the company for cutting
back some flights.''
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street analysts say the contract negotiations and weekend
cancellations have made things particularly ugly at United.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been a lingering issue at United going back to
April,'' said Samuel C. Buttrick, who follows United for
PaineWebber. ``And unfortunately this comes under the broad
headline of `labor negotiations.'''
</P>
<P>
   The cancellations and reductions in flights, Buttrick said, are
going cost somewhere between $120 million and $150 million in
pretax profits in the third quarter. Wall Street analysts are
worried that United's contract disputes could hurt UAL, which
announced in May that it would acquire US Airways for $4.3
billion. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
