<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-FRIARS-DISPUTE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WALK IN THE WOODS BRINGS A DEAL NEARER ON FRIARS' PROPERTY 
</HEADLINE>
   By COREY KILGANNON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A dispute between a friary and the federal government over an
18-acre parcel of forest in Garrison, N.Y., is on its way to
resolution after the parties were brought together to discuss their
differences on a hike.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department has agreed not to take legal action
forcing the Franciscan Friars of the Atonement to sell the rights
to 18 acres next to its Graymoor Spiritual Life Center, the group's
world headquarters, established in 1898.
</P>
<P>
   In 1984, the National Park Service bought an easement on 58
acres of the 400-acre Graymoor property for a stretch of the
Appalachian Trail. The trail runs through the property, which is
home to 45 friars, 86 nuns and various ministries, including a
homeless shelter.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1985, the Park Service, which oversees the 2,144-mile
trail, has been trying to buy another easement, on 18 acres
adjacent to the trail, for ``buffer land.'' But the friars have
refused to sell, maintaining that giving up rights to the land
would endanger the future of their ministry.
</P>
<P>
   In June, the Park Service asked the Justice Department to order
the friars to sell the 18 acres by eminent domain, a legal
procedure that allows governments to take land for the public good
at its market value.
</P>
<P>
   But on Monday, Sen. Charles Schumer and Rep. Sue W. Kelly, both
Democrats, brought the two sides together to discuss the issue over
a hike on the wooded trail at Graymoor.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides agreed to meet on Aug. 23 to draw up a legal
arrangement, which would protect the land against development and
make it accessible to the friars and the government.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Arthur M. Johnson, minister general of Graymoor, said
the friars and the Park Service would meet ``with no attorneys
present.'' He said he looked forward to working out a solution
without the fear of eminent domain proceedings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
