<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CONED-ACCIDENT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATAKI SIGNS BILL REQUIRING CON ED REBATE 
</HEADLINE>
  By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Putting the blame for a February nuclear accident
squarely on Consolidated Edison, Gov. George Pataki signed a bill
Tuesday requiring the company to repay customers more than $100
million collected to pay expenses from the accident and prohibiting
it from collecting tens of millions more.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's decision to sign the bill, which could cost the
utility about $200 million, stunned nearly everyone involved in the
dispute, and came after attempts by the Pataki administration to
reach a negotiated settlement with the company had failed.
</P>
<P>
   It is by far the largest rate rollback the state has ever
imposed on a utility for its own misdeeds, more than double the
previous record of $82 million, in a case against Con Edison in the
early 1980s. The governor's office said that for the average
residential customer, it would mean a $14 credit in New York City,
and $21 in Westchester County. The administration plans to have the
company apply the credits to September electric bills.
</P>
<P>
   But Con Edison promised to sue the state to void the law,
although company officials would not say on what grounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``In passing unlawful legislation, the state sends a message to
all of its citizens and corporations that politics overrides sound
public policy,'' said Joseph P. Petta, a company spokesman. ``We
are confident that the court will recognize that this bill is
unconstitutional.''
</P>
<P>
   Pataki signed the bill on the last day he had to act on it,
after the failure of weeks of talks between Con Edison and the
state's Public Service Commission, which is appointed and
controlled by the governor.
</P>
<P>
   ``This bill was the only mechanism for immediate, meaningful
rate relief, for putting money back in people's pockets,'' said
Assemblyman Richard L. Brodsky, the Westchester County Democrat who
played a leading role in attacking Con Edison and demanding
redress.
</P>
<P>
   The bill reached the governor's desk at the height of summer
power demand, and at a time when rates have spiked because of power
shortages around the Northeast. New York and other states are
breaking up the old utility monopolies, forcing companies like Con
Edison to sell most of their power plants and buy power on the open
market, subjecting them to price fluctuations as supply and demand
vary.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki, a Republican, has sought repeatedly, through tax cuts,
regulatory mandates and other steps, to lower the price of
electricity in New York, which has some of the nation's highest
rates. But Democrats and some consumer advocates have attributed
the recent price increases to his administration's handling of
restructuring, and Pataki's decision to sign the bill could help
mute such complaints.
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 15, cracked pipes in a steam generator allowed a small
amount of radioactive gas to escape from the Indian Point 2 nuclear
reactor alongside the Hudson River in Buchanan, 35 miles north of
Manhattan. The accident forced Con Edison to shut down the plant,
and it is likely to remain closed for months, the Nuclear
Regulatory Commission having rejected the company's repair plans as
insufficient.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-08-00 2328EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
