<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-SOCCER-REPORT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MLS NEEDS TO DEVELOP ITS DEVELOPMENT PLAN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BLANE BACHELOR 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Late in its fifth season, Major League Soccer, by the standards
of the other professional sports leagues in America, is still an
infant.
</P>
<P>
   Its sport is still foreign to many casual U.S. fans, and MLS
doesn't chart its progress in giant leaps and bounds, but in baby
steps.
</P>
<P>
   One of the developments that league higher-ups have been hyping
all season is the influx of young players. The league views rookies
_ including D.C. United's Bobby Convey, Chicago's DaMarcus Beasley,
Colorado's Seth Trembly _ as teen-agers today, superstars tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   But maybe in that view, MLS wants to walk before it can crawl.
</P>
<P>
   The league's system for developing such young talent _ called
Project-40 _ is, at best, confusing, at worst, inexplicable.
Launched in 1997, the program is a joint venture with the U.S.
Soccer Federation designed to develop young players and provide a
talent base for the United States' national teams.
</P>
<P>
   Each MLS team is awarded two or three of Project-40 players, who
train with their MLS squads during the week and play with their
P-40 teams on weekends. Once coaches feel the players can
contribute regularly in MLS, the players graduate from the program.
</P>
<P>
   At least that's the public-relations version of the system. In
reality, what sounds like a mutually beneficial relationship offers
MLS coaches little chance to witness P-40 players in game action
and forces young players to bounce back and forth between squads.
</P>
<P>
   ``Personally, I feel it's a very imperfect situation because
they don't resemble a team,'' Colorado Rapids coach Glenn ``Mooch''
Myernick said. ``They don't know from game to game who they'll be
alongside, and there is no training in it. A big part of
development in any player is knowing the nature of competition that
they are in on a regular basis.''
</P>
<P>
   That's not to say P-40 has been a complete bust. The Burn's
Sergi Daniv, the Chicago Fire's Josh Wolff and Beasley, and
United's Ben Olsen and Convey are a few examples of players who
flourished in the system and are now contributing _ and
contributing well _ to their MLS teams.
</P>
<P>
   But the system needs some fine-tuning. As more and more players
opt for MLS instead of college, the league can pat itself on the
back for attracting them, but it better be able to use that other
hand to steer the young talent into a system that will facilitate
growth of the players and the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we need to be careful with it,'' Myernick said. ``In
the traditional soccer nations, the 16- or 17-year-old kids come
into a pro club, and there is an awful lot of foundation work and
groundwork that has to be done before he gets to the first team.
We're missing a number of developmental stages in our current
system. We have to be careful about it.''
</P>
<P>
   With those few missing pieces _ perhaps a reserve team for each
MLS squad _ maybe the 5-year-old league will be able to put itself
against the wall, pull out the measuring stick and find that it is
finally growing taller, catching up with its big-brother leagues
across the globe.
</P>
<P>
   Burn should reconsider playing in Cup, Dir says The Burn has a
very serious agenda for the next month: making the Major League
Soccer playoffs, and becoming one of four MLS teams to do so all
five seasons.
</P>
<P>
   That makes it difficult for the Burn to focus on other
objectives that might take away from that goal.
</P>
<P>
   But that's exactly the difficulty tonight, as the Burn heads to
Naperville, Ill., for a Lamar Hunt U.S. Open Cup quarterfinal game
against the Chicago Fire at 6:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The scheduling presents Burn coach Dave Dir with several
concerns. This is the second consecutive Open Cup match in which
the Burn is on the road. Dir said he did not understand why the
Burn was forced to travel to Illinois because the Fire's next MLS
game is Aug. 16, when it plays the Burn at the Cotton Bowl. The
Fire played its most recent game at home during the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The Burn, on the other hand, has played four of its past give
games on the road, including a U.S. Open Cup match in Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do it for the good of the game, but we have to re-evaluate
what we get out of this,'' Dir said. ``Clearly, \Rorganizers\S have
political considerations, and it's almost comical when we're
playing a game here when Chicago was at home this weekend and
doesn't play for 10 days. Nothing makes sense of it.'' The Burn
also has lost two players during U.S. Open Cup games, midfielder
Paul Broome (lacerated right thigh) and midfielder Angel Rivillo
(knee sprain). Dir also pointed out that the U.S. Soccer Federation
and the Fire are both based in Chicago. Federation officials were
not available for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Dir emphasized the importance of the U.S. Open Cup for the Burn,
which won the title in 1997, but said he planned to meet with Burn
general manager Andy Swift to discuss Dallas' future involvement.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big thing about the Cup is that we're real proud to have
won it, but it will take some serious thinking about whether we
want to go back,'' Dir said. ``It will be hard to leave, but we're
getting to the point now that the scheduling is becoming more of a
detriment to the team.'' \Nsubheds:Direct kicks Division heating up
The ``Division of Death'' moniker that many soccer analysts gave to
the Central Division looks like a pretty fair assessment, with
about a month left in the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   Only seven points separate the teams tied for first, Tampa Bay
and Chicago with 41 points, and the last-place Burn, which has 34.
Columbus is third with 35.
</P>
<P>
   The Burn could tighten the race, especially with four of its
final six games at the Cotton Bowl, where it is 8-2-2 this season.
</P>
<P>
   The heat generated between the Burn and the Fire last year in
one of the best playoff series in MLS history should ignite again
tonight. The two teams meet in a U.S. Open Cup quarterfinal match,
and have two more MLS regular-season games. \Nsubheds:Beat-up Burn
Reminiscent of its 1998 season, the Burn seem to be limping into
the final stretch.
</P>
<P>
   The Burn is missing four key players, with defender Ricardo
Iribarren and midfielder Ted Eck the newest additions to the
injured list. Eck strained a ligament in his left foot, and
Iribarren has a cracked rib. Also out are midfielders Sergi Daniv
(fractured left ankle) and Paul Broome (right-thigh contusion).
\Nsubheds:New training site During the off-season, the Burn plans
to move its training to Blue Sky Sports Center in The Colony. For
the past four seasons, the Burn has trained at Greenhill School in
North Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Blue Sky Sports Center, 7801 Main St., is on about 90 acres and
includes a 40,000-square-foot soccer facility. The Burn plans to
move in Nov. 1, and the facility's grand opening is scheduled for
Dec. 1. \Nsubheds:Throw-ins Chicago Fire forward Ante Razov was
selected MLS Player of the Week after he scored three goals,
including the game-winners in each of the Fire's victories. Razov,
who has scored three goals with the U.S. National Team this year,
has been MLS Player of the Week three times this season. Burn
defender Jorge Rodriguez is among eight players recently fined by
the MLS disciplinary committee. Rodriguez was fined $250 for
serious foul play for the caution he received late in last week's
victory against New England.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
