<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS APPARENTLY WON'T FACE MARTINEZ, CLEMENS IN HOMESTAND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ The Rangers seem destined to miss Pedro Martinez and
Roger Clemens on the next homestand. Both pitched last night, but,
unless their managers change their minds, neither is expected to
pitch against the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Yankees' Clemens is scheduled to pitch again on his
normal four days' rest and would pitch Sunday against the Anaheim
Angels. Martinez, who normally pitches on four days' rest, is
getting an extra day because the Boston Red Sox don't play
tomorrow. So manager Jimy Williams is holding him back to pitch
Monday against the Tampa Bay Devil Rays. The Rangers play Friday
through Sunday against Boston and Monday through Aug. 16 against
New York.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez's next start after Monday's should be against the
Rangers a week from Saturday at Fenway Park. Clemens, if the
Yankees' rotation holds true, should pitch against the Rangers on
Aug. 23 at Yankee Stadium. \Nsubheds:Davis being skipped Manager
Johnny Oates, taking advantage of tomorrow's day off, is skipping
left-handed pitcher Doug Davis in the rotation so he can help take
some of the workload off Mike Venafro in the bullpen. Venafro has
been the Rangers' only left-hander in the bullpen, and Oates became
concerned when he was needed in four of the first five games on the
road, throwing a total of 82 pitches.
</P>
<P>
   Davis is scheduled to work out of the bullpen through Friday or
Saturday then re-enter the rotation to pitch against the New York
Yankees on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've worked Venafro hard,'' Oates said. ``Davis will still
get nine consecutive starts after this; the tradeoff is giving
Venafro some time off.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis entered the rotation when Darren Oliver went on the
disabled list with weakness and fatigue in his left shoulder.
Oliver is pitching on a medical-rehabilitation assignment for
Triple-A Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   By shuffling his rotation, Oates is setting up Matt Perisho,
Davis and Ryan Glynn to start in next week's three-game series
against the Yankees at The Ballpark in Arlington. \Nsubheds:Greer
celebrates 1,000th hit Rusty Greer's double Monday night was the
1,000th hit of his career, coming in his 878th major-league game.
That's the fastest any Rangers player has reached the 1,000-hit
level. Ivan Rodriguez and Ruben Sierra both did it 914 games, and
Juan Gonzalez did it in 915.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice,'' Greer said. ``When I first came up, they said I'd
be here a couple of weeks. I wasn't expecting to get 100 hits. It's
a little bitter-sweet, getting it and losing the game, but it's
something I can be proud of.'' \Nsubheds:No more contract talks
General manager Doug Melvin said yesterday he will wait until after
the season to reopen contract talks with outfielder Rusty Greer and
reliever Tim Crabtree. He had discussions with their agents earlier
this season but tabled them when the Rangers started struggling.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers have options on both players for next season, Greer
at $4.5 million and Crabtree at $1 million. The Rangers don't have
to make a decision on those until after the season, but, barring
major injury, both options are expected to be picked up.
\Nsubheds:Munro injury concern Right-handed pitcher Peter Munro,
who was acquired yesterday from the Blue Jays, comes with some
risk. He was 1-1 with a 5.96 earned-run average in nine games with
the Blue Jays before going on the disabled list June 16 with a
strained right elbow.
</P>
<P>
   After three medical-rehab starts, Munro was optioned to Triple-A
Syracuse and has pitched much better, going 3-2 with a 1.40 ERA. He
pitched six shutout innings in his most recent start.
\Nsubheds:Minor leagues The Rangers released Oklahoma first baseman
Shawn Gallagher, who was the Rangers' Minor League Player of the
Year in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma outfielder Rich Butler has been placed on the disabled
list with a hamstring injury. Mike Zywica has been promoted from
Double-A Tulsa to replace him.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers have signed outfielder Henry Barrios to a contract
with Tulsa. He was hitting .328 with Schaumburg (Ill.) in the
independent Northern League.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
