<DOCNO> NYT20000808.0400 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 23:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6388 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a LOWE'SCHAINTOSTOPSELLING     08-08 1252
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 LOWE'S CHAIN TO STOP SELLING LUMBER FROM ENDANGERED FORESTS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 ByKATHY MULADY AND ISAAC BAKER  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Following an emerging trend in environmental awareness, Lowe's
home improvement retail chain announced plans Tuesday to stop
selling lumber and other wood products from endangered forests and
to begin immediately phasing out products from the Great Bear Rain
Forest in British Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   The move reflects a social awareness by consumers and their
interest in buying sustainable and Earth-friendly products,
according to researchers.
</P>
<P>
   Some 60 percent of Americans would like to buy and use
sustainable products but want businesses to make it easy for them,
according to one study. And businesses are beginning to take
notice.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Kauffman, Lowe's senior vice president in charge of
merchandising, said the company has been working with
environmentalists and scientists for nine months to begin forming a
policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been a difficult but refreshing process. This is not
a destination but a journey,'' Kauffman said in a conference call
Tuesday to discuss the company's new policy.
</P>
<P>
   The Lowe's chain is considering whether to ban wood products
from some forests in the Pacific Northwest and the Southeast, but
would not say what areas specifically may be targeted.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope our approach as willing partners will allow Lowe's to
take a leadership role,'' Kauffman said. ``We hope customers will
appreciate our commitment and give us positive feedback with their
checkbooks,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   There were no specifics as to how the move might affect the cost
of lumber at stores.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists applauded the announcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very significant decision,'' said Nigel Sizer, director
of forest policy for the World Resources Institute in Washington,
D.C. ``Their size and their buying power indicates that their new
policy could have a big impact.''
</P>
<P>
   Sizer said his group is mapping the world's endangered forests.
He said Lowe's has agreed to stop buying products from forests once
they are designated at risk.
</P>
<P>
   Lowe's, which recently bought Seattle-based Eagle Hardware and
Garden, is the second-largest home improvement retail chain in the
nation. The company is based in Wilkesboro, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Ray, executive vice president of American Lives, a market
research firm specializing in consumer choices, said Lowe's is
taking the right steps.
</P>
<P>
   Ray, who interviewed more than 2,000 people nationwide for a
study sponsored by the federal Environmental Protection Agency,
said the overwhelming majority of Americans want to be
environmentally responsible, but feel the subject is too technical.
</P>
<P>
   ``A huge portion want to be involved, but they feel
disempowered,'' Ray said. ``They appreciate it when someone like
Lowe's comes in and says, `We are going to take care of it for you
and make it easy.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Ray estimates there is a ready audience of about 50 million
adults who are eager for companies to make it easy for them to buy
Earth-friendly products.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to see a lot more of this as other businesses
catch on,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lowe's is the second national hardware retailer to limit its
sales of wood from endangered forests. Home Depot made a similar
announcement a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Home Depot, the nation's largest hardware
retailer, based in Atlanta, Ga., said company President Arthur
Blank plans to mark the one-year anniversary of their announcement
by issuing a report card on their efforts of the past year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Home Depot encouraged the home improvement industry a year ago
to follow its lead to develop a global environmentally responsible
wood-purchasing policy. We welcome those who want to join us in
this pursuit,'' spokesman Chuck Sifuentes said.
</P>
<P>
   Home Depot promised to eliminate wood from endangered forests
from their stores by the end of 2002, particularly certain lauan,
redwood and cedar products, and give preference to ``certified''
wood.
</P>
<P>
   To carry the certified label, a supplier's wood must be tracked
from the forest, through manufacturing and distribution, to the
customer and must ensure a balance of social, economic and
environmental factors. The Forest Stewardship Council, an
international organization, is the most widely used for such
certification.
</P>
<P>
   Lowe's also has agreed to give preference to FSC certified wood
and lumber products.
</P>
<P>
   But Robert Bernhardt Jr., a spokesman for the Western Wood
Products Association in Portland, Ore., said many questions still
remain before a uniform certification system can be implemented.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who defines what is good (wood) and what is not good, what is
endangered and what is not endangered?'' he asked. ``There is no
standard definition for that, so that's part of the problem in
developing an overall plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a trend toward that (certification), but as far as
consumers, are they willing to pay the cost is still a question.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the biggest owners of forest land _ the state of
Washington _ may consider seeking certification for some of its
wood products. Washington Lands Commissioner Jennifer Belcher has
raised that possibility as the state is in the process of gauging
logging practices on more than a million acres of state lands west
of the Cascade Mountains.
</P>
<P>
   Lowe's issued an immediate ban on products from the Great Bear
Rain Forest of British Columbia, the largest intact stand of
centuries-old temperate rain forest stretching along the Pacific
Coast to Alaska. Great Bear holds one-quarter of the temperate rain
forest remaining in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Lowe's executives said the retailer already has eliminated ramin
dowels from Indonesia from its inventory and converted to a
domestic poplar species. Ramin, a light-colored hardwood, is native
to Borneo and is often used for furniture, dowels and tool handles.
</P>
<P>
   Other products made of endangered woods will be phased out
gradually.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to be pulling products from our shelves; that
makes little sense,'' said Lowe's Kauffman. ``They are already
fabricated and manufactured; it would only be symbolic to remove
them from the shelves, and it would be a shame to have them end up
in a Dumpster somewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Lowe's does about $4 billion in sales of lumber and wood
products each year. Kauffman said about a half-percent of the
company's total wood sales are of products from the Great Bear Rain
Forest.
</P>
<P>
   The Environmental Investigation Agency, based in Washington,
D.C., called Lowe's commitment ``ground-breaking wood policy aimed
at protecting the world's threatened forests by ending the sale of
wood from such forests.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an undeniable trend,'' said Michael Brune of the Rain
Forest Action Network. ``Major wood buyers are responding to the
needs of their customers who are saying `no more.' What will result
is a massive shift in these logging companies. I think it will send
shock waves through the logging industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Brune applauded Lowe's policy as more specific than Home
Depot's, because it names regions where it plans take action to
protect threatened forests. Those areas include British Columbia,
Indonesia and the southeastern United States.
</P>
<P>
   Lowe's did not offer a specific time frame for completion of its
plan, however. On Tuesday, Lowe's also announced formation of a
Healthy Forests Advisory Board, which will help the company
implement its new policy and advise it on general forestry issues.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-08-00 2333EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
