<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 23:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6399 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BBO-GONZALEZ-COLUMN-T     08-08 0630
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-GONZALEZ-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OVERALL HOME-RUN PACE SHOWS NO SIGNS OF ABATING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is supposed to be the season of the burly slugger, the
juiced baseball, the bandbox ballpark. This is supposed to be the
season where no home-run record is safe.
</P>
<P>
   But a quick check of the league leaders reveals no pulse-raising
totals, no jaw-dropping numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Going into last night's games, Gary Sheffield and Sammy Sosa
topped the National League with 35 homers each, and are on pace to
hit 51. Barry Bonds has 34, and is on track for 50. Blue Jays
teammates Tony Batista and Carlos Delgado led] the American League
with 33 each, a pace that would yield 47 at the end of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Fifty homers or so is nothing to be ashamed of, to be sure. Babe
Ruth only hit 50 or more in a season four times in his 22-year
career. Hank Aaron, the all-time record holder, never hit more than
47. Before '96, there had been only 12 50-homer seasons in the AL
and only seven in the NL.
</P>
<P>
   Still, considering that in the past three seasons Mark McGwire
hit 65, 70 and 58, that Sammy Sosa hit 63 and 66 the past two
seasons, and that Ken Griffey Jr. hit 56 in both '97 and '98, a
mere 50 or so seems kind of puny.
</P>
<P>
   What happened to all those guys with the big biceps swatting
rock-hard balls out of tiny stadiums?
</P>
<P>
   Actually, nothing. The leaders' totals only seem puny compared
with the exploits of McGwire and Sosa the past couple of years.
Overall, home run totals continue to climb.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thirty-five now, that's a lot of home runs,'' said David
Vincent, co-editor of ``The Home Run Encyclopedia'' and the homer
guru for the Society for American Baseball Research. ``It just
doesn't seem like it. It's sort of a strange situation in that
you've got the leaders like that, but you've got the grand total
way up.''
</P>
<P>
   No one is challenging the single-season record for the first
time in three years, but for the third time in three seasons, the
overall home-run totals are headed toward record territory.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more of what we've seen a lot of the last few years,
which is some of these guys who you wouldn't think of as home-run
hitters are hitting more,'' Vincent said.
</P>
<P>
   In '98, when McGwire stunned the baseball world by hitting 70
homers, there were a record 5,064 homers hit. That record fell in
'99, when batters hit a collective 5,528. The numbers are even
greater this season. There were 4,097 homers hit in the first 1,662
games, putting hitters on pace for 5,990. Batters hit an average of
2.28 homers per game in '99. This year, the average is up to 2.47.
Batters averaged a homer for every 30.23 at-bats last year. This
season, they're doing it every 28.02 at-bats, an all-time record
pace.
</P>
<P>
   League totals aren't as compelling as individual numbers, of
course. The total number of homers hit in 2000 will not be the
answer to some future trivia question. Even though no one is likely
to approach 60 this season, it should have been expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have been very surprised if we would have continued
that 65 pace,'' Vincent said. ``Those numbers are way out of scope.
I'm not at all surprised we've backed off of that. The three guys
that have been up at the top, McGwire's hurt, Sosa doesn't have
anybody's coattails to ride and Griffey's been in a funk all
year.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, home runs continue to rise, even without major
contributions from the Big Three. What's the significance, other
than a confirmation of the various juiced ball-muscular
player-small ballpark theories?
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else, it serves as a reminder that even in this era
of unprecedented home-run totals, those McGwire-Sosa home-run duels
the past couple of years truly were special.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-08-00 2354EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
