<HEADER>
A6401 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BBA-RANGERS-YOUTH-TEX     08-08 0535
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-YOUTH-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS ADD ANOTHER YOUNG PITCHER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ The Rangers haven't undergone a complete overhaul,
but, thanks to the Toronto Blue Jays, they have added a couple of
young pitchers. That might prove beneficial when the Rangers start
talking trades in the off-season.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers completed the Dave Martinez trade yesterday by
acquiring right-hander Peter Munro from the Blue Jays. Munro, 25,
was 4-3 with a 2.48 earned-run average in 10 starts for Triple-A
Syracuse and was 1-1 with a 5.96 ERA for the Blue Jays, including
0-1 with a 4.80 ERA in three starts. He's being sent to Triple-A
Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's young and he has a good arm,'' Rangers general manager
Doug Melvin said. ``He just turned 25 \Ron June 14\S. He's just one
of those guys you want to give a chance to and see what happens.''
</P>
<P>
   That also is the reason the Rangers picked up 25-year-old
right-handed reliever Darwin Cubillan, along with minor-league
shortstop Mike Young, from the Blue Jays for pitcher Esteban Loaiza
on July 19. Cubillan pitched 13 scoreless innings for Triple-A
Oklahoma before being brought up to the majors Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to see him pitch,'' said Rangers manager Johnny
Oates, who plans to use Cubillan in long and middle relief. ``He's
got a pretty good arm and pretty good stuff. He was off to a good
start at Oklahoma City. We'll see what he can do. Again, we'll try
to put him in the right spot to succeed.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers would like to find out about their young players
because they're in a rare position of having some depth at key
positions. They have four young starters who have major-league
experience _ Matt Perisho (25), Doug Davis (24), Ryan Glynn (25)
and Munro _ and five hard-throwing right-handed relievers _ Tim
Crabtree (30), Jeff Zimmerman (28), Francisco Cordero (22),
Jonathan Johnson (26) and Cubillan.
</P>
<P>
   Combine that with an extra young outfielder _ they have Ruben
Mateo (21), Gabe Kapler (24) and Ricky Ledee (26) to go along with
veteran Rusty Greer _ plus some room with their payroll, and the
Rangers could be in position to trade young players for an impact
player in the off-season.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers haven't been in that position in a while. That's why
they couldn't get Roger Clemens from the Blue Jays before the 1999
season or make a run at Mike Hampton when the Houston Astros
unloaded him last off-season.
</P>
<P>
   But now they can get involved if, for example, the Arizona
Diamondbacks decide they can't afford Curt Schilling for a full
season, if the Chicago White Sox decide they can't sign James
Baldwin (a free agent after 2001) or if the Seattle Mariners need
to trade a pitcher so they can afford to re-sign Alex Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   That could prove to be a more economical route for the Rangers
than throwing millions at one of the top available free agents:
Hampton, Clemens, Mike Mussina and Denny Neagle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, we're just trying as many good young pitchers as we
can,'' Melvin said. ``With pitching, you never know when a guy
might find it. This just gives us some depth.''
</P>
<P>
   And some options they haven't had lately.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-08-00 2355EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
